1. d4( { In one of the  next variations , we will take a closer look at the first moves and different move orders. At this point of the introduction, it makes sense to focus on the main move order which is typically beginning with }1.d4 { and   }2.c4 { . } )
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6{ The starting position of the Slav opening. }
3. Nf3{ Here and on the fourth move, White has various developing possibilities - I only needed two sample moves to show the basic setup of the Grünfeld Slav! }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6( { This position characterizes the structure of the Grünfeld Slav. Black combines the solidity of the Slav opening - see the position after   }2...c6 { - with dynamic plans of the Grünfeld Indian }{ (GID) }{ .    The Grünfeld Indian is an independent, extremely popular opening, usually achieved via the move order   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 { . }{ You can immediately see the similarities to our setup! The only difference is the move ... c7 - c6 .     Why is it so important?    In the main variations of the Grünfeld Indian, it is extremely typical that White is able to take over the entire center. Among others, but not exclusively, with the simple move order }4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e4 { .    }{ Well, the Grünfeld Indian wouldn't be so popular if that made the black position objectively bad. But this early abandonment of the center is certainly not to everyone's taste, and Black needs to know precise move orders in many variations to put sufficient pressure on the white center.     This sometimes makes the move orders extremely forcing and - combined with the fact that the well-known opening theory is so widely analyzed - can sometimes make preparation relatively easy for the white player - especially if a weaker player with White is satisfied with a draw.    By playing our setup, we not only make it harder for White to take the center so early in the opening, but we also avoid the mountain of known theory. Although both the Grünfeld Indian Defense and the Slav opening are generally among the most theorized openings around, our Grünfeld Slav has a fairly niche existence in the existing opening theory.     When I decided to create this course, here and began to research existing literature, I could find neither a book nor a Chessable course that addressed the opening from the black side. Quite a curiosity!    I will explain the reasons  elsewhere  in this chapter. For us, however, this means several things:     We are more familiar with the opening than our opponents    - Even if our opponents can prepare, it is difficult for them to find material. }{ Most opening courses treat the opening so stepmotherly that we usually have them out prepared by move 8 }{ .    - We can draw on ideas from two of the most respected openings! }{    - As you'll see in a moment, you can play the opening not only against   }1.d4 { , but also against many other first moves - especially }1.c4 { and }1.Nf3 { . A big plus!    For years, I've considered the Grünfeld Slav one of the most underrated openings around, and when I got the chance to create a Chessable course, the topic was chosen for me pretty quickly.    I hope you come to the same conclusion after studying the course! Have a lot of fun with the opening! } )
