{ Christoph, wait! Isn't the opening called the Schlechter Slav?     It actually is! It is named after the Austrian Carl Schlechter, who almost became world champion with it against Emmanuel Lasker in 1910 - or maybe not?!     Schlechter didn't play the Grünfeld Slav as one of his main openings. Besides this game, I could only find one other in which he chose our setup. But he played it in one of the most historic games in chess history!     In 1910, World Champion Lasker had agreed to play a 10-game match against Schlechter. After 9 games, Schlechter was (surprisingly) leading 5:4 and Lasker could not win a single game. One more draw and our namesake might have become World Champion.     There are many myths about this game. Both players made many mistakes and played some strange moves - maybe the nerves?     Some people claim that such a short match could not possibly be to determine the World Champion.     Others say that Schlechter needed to win the match with two points to win the title. So maybe it was Schlechter who needed the full point despite his lead? Maybe these questions will never be answered - or at least these theories will most likely stick around forever.    Unfortunately the game didn't end well for our hero. After a completely crazy game, Lasker prevailed and kept his title.    Even though this is really not an interesting game from an opening perspective, a course about the Schlechter Slav wouldn't be complete without it so I included it. I added some annotations to some interesting positions but the game is mainly interesting because of its meaning for chess history.    Clicking through the game, my first assessment is that Lasker clearly went more bonkers than Schlechter. Just look at his aggressive moves in the early middlegame! Or his insistence later on avoiding the queen exchange when he already had the chance to wind up in very advantageous endgames!     But I'm not a chess historian, so my opinion is certainly worth no more than any other. }1. d4
