{ [ How bad is the Grünfeld Slav?] }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6( { This question comes up almost automatically as soon as a book or a course is published on an opening that is not regularly encountered at the very highest level. Although I'm definitely a bit biased, I'll answer the question honestly to the best of my knowledge.    For one thing, there is no such thing as  the  Grünfeld Slav. If we take the position after   }3.Nf3 Nf6 { as a basis and look at the main white moves, we will see that against some of them, our Schlechter setup is not only possible but an absolute main variation. For example against }4.g3 { , the move }4...g6 { leads to variations that we share with the Fianchetto Grünfeld Indian.    These days, many GID players answer   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 { with }3...c6 { and practice has shown that this is arguably Black's most reliable variation.    So here, the opening has a very good reputation! } )( { Even better might be the variation }4.Qc2 g6 { . As I will explain in the Introduction of Schlechter's Dream -  see here  - our move is here the absolute main line and certainly one of the reasons why the early queen move is not more popular than it is. } )( { What about other moves, for example, the two main moves }4.e3 { or }4.Nc3? {    Well, according to a lot of players, here, the opening doesn't have the best reputation. But, from my point of view, there is a very clear main (and avoidable) reason for this: the opening is often played unnecessarily poorly! I first noticed this when I had to prepare with White against the Schlechter Slav myself. In the database, you can see many games in which Black plays the opening apparently on autopilot.    The solidity of the opening is exploited to play }4...g6 { , }-- 5...Bg7 { , }-- 6...O-O { without a second thought. Then the light squared bishop is developed to the first available square, often with }-- 7...Bg4 { , where Black frequently gives up the bishop pair. Then the knight is developed with }-- 8...Nbd7 { and often this setup is rounded off with moves like }-- ...e6 { or }...a6 { .    So in many games, Black simply ignores any activity in the center. Of course, if Black plays like this, White has no reason to make any concessions and can choose a setup of his choice against it. For example, }5.Bf4 { or }5.Bg5 { , }-- 6.e3 { , }-- 7.Be2 { , }-- 8.O-O { , }-- 9.h3 { after which White can typically claim various advantages:    }{ 1. the more active c-pawn    2. the immediate consequence of which is that the white  Nc3  is better placed than the black  Nd7 .    3. often, White still wins the bishop pair.    4. and in particular it is said: the bishop on  g7  is simply badly positioned! All he does is look at a pawn on  d4  that is insanely stable due to his crony on  e3 .    'Solid, but passive' is often the summary.    'Why the hell would Black play that way?' was pretty much my main thought when I had to take a closer look at the opening from White's point of view for my preparation a few years ago.    Even without being particularly deep into the material at that point, I saw that the opening had much more potential than playing it so passively. The engine had shown hidden resources for Black in pretty much every variation I considered for White.     I think you can use this 'solid, but passive' way of playing as a nice 'safety net' if you really get surprised in one variation. (It is a thousand times better than getting mated in a sharp opening if you misremember just one important move there.)    Nevertheless, this is not the way that we usually play the position. As you will see in this course, Black has a lot of dynamic possibilities to play actively in the center! Besides some typical Schlechter ideas, we will see many ideas from other Slav variations, for example ... dxc4  , but we will also see a lot of ideas from the Grünfeld Indian Defense.    An important point is the role of the pawn moves ... c6 - c5  and ... e7 - e5 .     ['The Butcher']These pawn breaks }{ (= pawn moves that attack the opponent's pawns) }{ will be seen a lot in this course and I'll probably sound like a cracked record pretty soon, so often will I emphasize the importance of these breaks! Once we have achieved one of these breaks, the black bishop on  g7  usually becomes a monster in an instant!     Either because the long diagonal is opened up or because after a pawn exchange on  d4  suddenly a pawn remains on this square which no longer enjoys any pawn protection. Suddenly the bishop on  g7  would be an insanely well-positioned piece that puts constant pressure on a weak pawn on  d4 .    For more on the plans, see  Manoeuvres and Plans .    It is precisely because of these dynamic possibilities that I consider the name 'Grünfeld Slav' much more fitting for this repertoire than 'Schlechter Slav' since it expresses its dynamics. Nevertheless, I will use both names equally in this repertoire.    Whenever a fianchettoed bishop is playing a particularly important role in an opening, it is not unusual to emphasize this fact by giving it a nickname. For example, most people know what a 'dragon bishop' is and how important it is in the Sicilian Dragon.     To honour our bishop on  g7 , I called it the  'butcher' , which, on the one hand, is quite fitting regarding its activity once it is activated but it is also based on a German pun since 'Schlechter' sounds like 'Schlächter' which is the German word for 'butcher'.    [Conclusion]To return to the initial question: in the theory so far, these dynamic approaches have been largely ignored, with the result that the entire opening is completely underestimated in my view.     It is true that much of the appeal of the opening is the great practical aspect - you can play the setup against many white systems, opponents are less prepared for it, your position is solid and without weaknesses. } )( { Probably, White can achieve a '⩲' with perfect preparation and machine-aided calculation - I don't want to make you false promises there -, but it is much harder to achieve than theory often makes you believe. And even in the critical variations with }4.e3 { or }4.Nc3 { , Black has many improvements and novelties over the only variations that are often mentioned in theory - and this course gives them to you!    } )
