1. d4( { This first move is played most of the time when people enter the Slav universe. White immediately puts a pawn into the center. Hardly a bad idea. Nevertheless, as promised, you can also implement our repertoire against other first moves by White     A)  }1.c4 { The English opening. For us it is advisable to play }1...c6 { . We should get a pawn to  d5  as soon as possible to limit White's options in the center. In general, White has two possibilities     A1)  }2.e4 { is the radical move order to disturb us from our Slav plans. We will get a position that is more typical for the Caro-Kann. We will still play }2...d5 { . In these lines, the center is more dynamic than in our regular Slav lines because several files can open up immediately. Nevertheless, this so-called Panov Variation shouldn't frighten anyone who wants to pick up the Slav against the English. It isn't even that popular among  1.e4  players (who could reach this position via   }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 { ) because there are well-known antidotes for Black these days.     A2)  The second possibility is pretty much everything else! If White plays another developing move such as   }2.Nc3 { , }2.Nf3 { , }2.g3 { , etc..., we will get very Schlechterlike positions after }2...d5 { General rule: You should go ... d7 - d5  as soon as possible. In many of your games, your opponents will play  d2 - d4  rather sooner than later and transpose to our  1.d4  lines. Variations where White postpones the d-pawn advance can be found  here . } )( {  B)  }1.Nf3 { gives us more liberties. Both moves that control the  e4 -square can very likely transpose to the Schlechter. }{ My main recommendation is }1...d5 { - I think nothing should be more natural for us than to put the d-pawn in the center. Nevertheless, }1...Nf6 { is also possible without any drawbacks. }{ Whenever White plays  c4 , we will respond with ... c7 - c6  . There are only very few setups where White can play without either  d2 - d4  or  c2 - c4 . They can be found  here . }{    }( {  C)  I promised you a complete  1.d4 / 1.c4 / 1.Nf3  repertoire and that's what you shall get! But our setup is even better than that! Unfortunately, I had to set the frame of this project somewhere - and  1.d4 / 1.c4 / 1.Nf3  seemed to be a good size - but this repertoire should make it very easy for you to build a repertoire against moves like   }1.b3 { , }1.b4 { , }1.g3 { , }1.d3 { or }1.e3 { as well. If you respond to these moves with }1...d5 { , it's not unlikely that your opponent will transpose to variations from our repertoire with an early  d2 - d4  ,  c2 - c4  or  Ng1 - f3  . The only independent attempts would probably be transitions to the Bird opening, for example, with }2.f4 { , or some very crooked setups like a colour-reversed Hippo ( }2.g3 -- Bg2 -- b3 -- Bb2 -- d3 -- Nd2 -- Ne2 { is what it looks like), but that shouldn't be much of a theoretical or practical problem, considering how often you encounter these moves in tournaments. } )( {  D)  Against   }1.Nc3 { I would honestly always make my repertoire dependent on what my repertoire is against }1.e4 { . A Sicilian player should probably consider   }1...c5 { . French or Caro players can play }1...d5 { and respond to }2.e4 { with }2...e6 { or }2...c6 { .    An  1...e5  player (against  1.e4 ) can play   }1...Nf6 { to transpose after }2.e4 e5 { . (The immediate   }1...e5 { allows a few tricks starting with }2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 { .)    Nevertheless, if you play   }1...Nf6 { or }1...d5 { against the knight move, with this repertoire you already have a weapon if your opponent plays }2.d4 { -  see here ! } ) )
1. d5( { This is the most normal move in the world for 99% of all Slav players. For conclusiveness' sake, let's just mention that }1...Nf6!? 2.c4 c6 { will most likely also end in Slav variations. I don't think that you achieve anything with this move order trickery. You might even be forced to play very non-Slav positions after }3.Bf4!? { To be fair, this is not a great move but a general rule - not only in this course but for most Slav repertoires - is to take on  c4  if White develops their bishop to  f4 . Here, this is not possible. Those who play this weird move order usually respond with the very odd }3...Qb6 { . I can only repeat myself. I don't think your life becomes easier by playing this move order. } )
2. c4( { When I read my first chess books more than 15 years ago, }2.c4 { was some kind of automatic move. Some players played the move }2.Nf3 { first and }-- 3.c4 { only at move three, but it was still the same setup.    }{ That still has some implications for how we talk about our openings. A lot of authors write things like 'I recommend the Grünfeld against 1.d4' or 'Against 1.d4, I play the Queens' Gambit declined'.     What they really mean is that they play those openings against White's combination of  d2 - d4  and  c2 - c4 . For many years now, the so-called 'Queen's pawn openings' - that means White plays  1.d4  but does not play  c2 - c4  anytime soon - gained extreme popularity. }{ At the amateur level online, the London System }2.Bf4 { might be even more popular now than }2.c4 { .    }{ Let me make one thing clear: If our opponent plays without  c2 - c4 , there is no real reason for us to play  2...c6 . It is not a horrible move, but in a lot of cases, we can play much more active with the c-pawn and play ... c7 - c5 . }2...c6 { is a move that we mainly play as a reaction to White's threat to go  c4xd5 . Without this threat, we have much more liberties. } )( {  A)  }2.Nf3 { is a flexible move. I would recommend just playing }2...Nf6 { . It is part of our setup and if White plays }3.c4 { , we can still go }3...c6 { .    If White plays   }3.e3 { or }3.g3 { , we can continue to offer White the Schlechter Slav with }3...g6 { . Whenever White plays  c2 - c4 , we play  ...c7 - c6 . There is not really much else that White can try to achieve - and if they try to postpone the c-pawn break, it is often Black who can get active with his and play  ...c7 - c5  under good circumstances. Those lines can be found  here . } )( {  B)  }2.Bf4 { The London System. This is a good example of why we shouldn't play }2...c6 { on auto-pilot. }{ If White doesn't attack  d5 , we don't have to protect it! Instead, it is often Black who can play actively with ... c7 - c5 . In this repertoire, I recommend the move order }2...Nf6 { , followed by }-- ...e6 { and }-- ...c5 { . This might not be the first line that comes to mind if you think about a setup similar to the Grünfeld Slav but after checking out the Introduction to the London chapter, this will become clearer. } )
2. c6( {  'Only a fool makes a threat he is not prepared to carry out'     Jaime 'Fookin' Lannister – Game of Thrones    I can't think of a better quote to describe the move }2...c6 { . I like to think that people first get attracted to the Slav for one of two reasons.     1)  They see games where Black can develop their pieces undistracted - for example like in a London reversed with }-- 3...Nf6 { , }-- 4...Bf5 { , }-- 5...e6 { , }-- 6...Bd6 { , }-- 7...Nbd7 { , }-- 8...O-O { and just love the simplicity of this setup.    }{  2)  They see bloody double-edged games where Black takes on  c4  and protects the pawn with claws and teeth and immediately fall in love with the dynamic possibilities.     The two approaches could not be further apart! But one simple truth is: You can't cover a whole Slav repertoire with just one of these approaches alone. This might be pretty obvious for the second type - for example, an early  e2 - e3  destroys all pawn-grabbing intentions on  c4  - but is less obvious for the first approach. } )( { One of the reasons why we play the move }2...c6 { in the first place is to force some kind of concession from White. If we compare our Slav defence for a second with its sibling the Queen's Gambit Declined }2...e6 { - which doesn't create any threat - and have a look at the database, we will see that White's dream setup often looks like this: }3.Nc3 { , }-- 4.Nf3 { , }-- 5.Bf4 { , }-- 6.e3 { , }-- 7.Bd3 { , }-- 8.O-O { .    This is obviously a little bit simplified but you see that White would love to get a setup where the knights are on their most influential squares, no bishop is locked in, and - in most lines - White has no big incentive to take on  d5 . In the Slav, we should have no intentions to give White all that!    }{ The pure existence of most lines against the Slav are based on the belief that White needs to do something about the  c4 -pawn. Either by protecting it or by exchanging on  d5 . In amateur games, it happens frequently that White leaves the  c4 -pawn hanging and Black simply ignores it.     At the risk of sounding a bit too direct: It doesn't make much sense to learn the existing theory against such good but conceding moves, and at the same time just let the opponent have their way when they try to push their dream setup through without any concessions.     You don't have to grab the pawn at the first opportunity and, as you will see in this course, there are some easy rules that you can follow, but it's just something important to keep in mind.     Long story short: If you are a dirty pawn grabber, you shouldn't have any doubts about playing the Slav anyways. But even if you see yourself more as a slow starter who prefers healthy development, you have to be ready to do it once in a while! } )
3. Nf3( { If our opponent knows that they can expect the Grünfeld Slav, this is by far the most flexible move order. There is not a single critical line in our repertoire, where White plays without this move against a Schlechter setup. Sidelines without this move can be found  here .    Against most other moves, we would also play  ...g6.  The biggest exceptions are moves that develop White's dark-squared bishop - typically either to  f4  or  g5.  After those moves, White would be ready to continue with  e3  and would be close to achieving their dream setup. So after }3.Bf4 { , we will go }3...dxc4! { . } )( 3.cxd5 { is the Exchange variation which can either transpose to a combination of the Schlechter Slav and the Exchange ='Schlexchange' -  starting here  - (I couldn't come up with a dumber name) but there are also some independent lines where we should step back from our Schlechter setup -  see here . } )
3. Nf6{ In this position, White has several moves that have been played hundreds or thousands of times at the highest level. }( { A lot of White players are not willing to leave the pawn on  c4  hanging any longer and play moves to protect it - like }4.e3 { , }4.Nbd2 { , }4.Qb3 { or }4.Qc2 { . Goal achieved, White made a concession.    }4.g3 { is a tricky move for our repertoire. Why?    On the one hand, it is not a super popular choice in this very position because Black has several options that promise him decent counterplay. One of these decent options is our standard move }4...g6 { . The 'problem' with this move is that it leads to the fianchetto variation in the Grünfeld Indian - and via this move order it is one of the most debated variations at the top level! } )
4. Nc3( 4.Nc3 { is often seen as the most critical move as it is the most natural development move White has without making a concession. It is actually fairly logical to respond with }4...dxc4 { - the very theoretical 'Classical Slav' - but besides the fact that this leads to positions that have nothing to do with our Grünfeld Slav, there is also no need to take immediately. White is still two moves ( }5.Bf4 { or }5.Bg5 { , followed by }-- 6.e3 { ) away from getting the desired position without concessions so we can simply keep developing for now. } )
4. g6( { If you're willing to play this position, then you're part of the 'Badass Grünfeld Slav Club'!    Against other fourth moves, I think you can play the Grünfeld Slav - even in the variations where a lot of theory exists - very well with the knowledge of general plans alone, which makes the opening a perfect backup Slav if you are already a Slav player with other variations in your repertoire.    Against }4.Nc3 { , (so far!) only a few players are willing to initiate the Grünfeld Slav with }4...g6 { . One reason is certainly that you need more precise knowledge if White continues to aim for their dream setup - for example with }5.Bf4 { or }5.Bg5 { .    But the main reason for the unpopularity - nowadays - is probably the variation }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Bf4 { .    }{ While the exchange on  d5  is often in principle a 'concession' - after all, White had the more active c-pawn and the black knight gets the square  c6  - the exchange of the c-pawn ensures that Black can never play the 'Grünfeld break' ... c5  to revive the 'butcher' on  g7 . White simply hopes for a 'boring' position where Black has a misplaced bishop on  g7 .     This is by far the variation I've covered in the most detail in this course because here we should know most precisely how to create dynamic counter chances.     Nevertheless, I'm not sure that this variation promises White more than calmer  e2 - e3  lines. And precisely because we're aiming for somewhat more chaotic realms here, where we're the experts 99.9% of the time }{ (no White repertoire deals with these variations) }{ , it is possible to have a lot of fun in these variations from the black side! } )
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "What to avoid | Artemiev, Vladislav vs. Ponkratov, Pavel, Warsaw 2021"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

{ There is one scenario that you must avoid at all costs as a Grünfeld Slav player:     That your butcher on  g7  actually becomes as bad as it is often said to be.     This risk exists mainly in the Schlexchange variations, where White exchanges on  d5 . Without the c-pawn we can't play ... c5  - and if ... e5  is also not possible, the pawn break which is in general the more difficult one to achieve anyway, then our buddy on  g7  is quickly taken out of the game.     White would love to play a symmetrical pawn structure, where the passive bishop is the only imbalance when all the white pieces are otherwise on good squares.    Sample games that are supposed to illustrate that a game is lost mainly because a piece  doesn't  do something feels like trying to prove that something  doesn't  exist. It's difficult to find hard proof.     Nevertheless, I think the following game shows quite well what can happen in such a scenario. }1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. cxd5{ Stopping all ... c5 -breaks in the future. }
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ White is playing the critical line that is often cited as White's best option against the Grünfeld Slav. White wants to develop all minor pieces to good squares. Note that White also takes  e5  under control. }
6. Bg7( { One of my rules in this course is that in Exchange structures, }6...Nc6 { is a more flexible move than ... Bg7  . } )
7. e3( 7.h3!? { is also good. } )
7. O-O( 7...Nh5 { is a move that we will see regularly in this course but here, this cannot be recommended. }8.Bxb8 Rxb8 9.Qa4+± { just wins the  a7 -pawn and the  h5 -knight is terrible. } )
8. Be2
8. Nc6
9. h3{ This stops all ... Nh5 -ideas to win the bishop pair. From now on, Black has problems creating inbalances. }
9. Ne4( { A typical move in the Grünfeld Slav. Black would love to play   }10...Nxc3 { and give White a backwards pawn on  c3 . Those structures are usually okay. But White can stop this. } )
10. Rc1{ White keeps the structure symmetrical. Now, he can always recapture on  c3  with the rook. }
10. Bf5
11. O-O
11. Rc8
12. Qb3{ White just has a very annoying advantage here. With perfect defense, Black might make a draw but the only imbalance in this position is the activity of the minor pieces - and even an optimist such as myself can see little good in the  g7 -bishop here. Black has no counterplay while White has different ideas to create some pressure on the queenside. }
12. Na5( 12...Qd7 { is apparently better but it doesn't change anything about the nature of the position. } )
13. Qb4
13. Nxc3
14. Rxc3
14. Rxc3
15. Qxc3{ All those exchanges didn't reduce White's pressure. We could even say that every exchange makes Black's position worse as the relevance of a badly placed pieced increases with every exchange. }
15. Nc6( { The engine already suggest the pretty desparate pawn sacrifice }15...Nc4!? { to win the bishop pair. Besides the fact that White can simply take, White could even consider to continue his campaign of avoiding all imbalances with }16.b3± { . } )
16. Qb3{ This keeps the pressure against  b7  and  d5 . }( 16.b4!? { is another logical move to make progress. With just one open file, usually pawn play is important to fight for inroads in Black's camp. } )
16. Na5( { Once again, }16...Qd7 { might have been the better call. But we are already only discussing if White is just much better or much much better. } )
17. Qb4{ It's not so easy for Black to untangle his pieces as the  a5 -knight needs protection. }
17. Qb6{ This might even be the best move but the resulting endgame is horrible. }
18. Qxb6
18. axb6
19. Rc1{ White plays very simple positional chess. Now,  20.Rc7  is a big threat. }
19. Ra8{ Black goes for active counterplay but White is obviously much faster. }( 19...Rc8 20.Rxc8+ Bxc8 21.Bc7+- { is the easiest way to pick up the queenside. } )
20. Rc7
20. Bf8{ Finally, the butcher is doing something. But protecting a stupid pawn is a very sad activity... }
21. Nd2{ Black's pieces are passive and White is only looking for the perfect moment to find the decisive breakthrough. }
21. f6( 21...Nc6 22.g4 { , followed by  23.a3  would also lead to total domination. } )
22. a3
22. Bc8{ Black is running out of ideas. }
23. Bb5{ White just keeps improving.  b2 - b4  is in the air. }
23. Kf7
24. e4( { At some point, White has to increase the pressure. The engine prefers the manoeuvre }24.Nb1 -- Nc3 -- Na4 { to go }{ for the  b6 -pawn. There is really not much that Black can do about it. } )
24. dxe4{ This loses by force. }( 24...Be6 { holds on for a little bit longer but Black is already lost. } )
25. d5{ The e-pawn doesn't run away.  d5 - d6  is an annoying idea, but mainly  b2 - b4  is a threat to win the knight on  a5 . }
25. Bf5
26. g4{ Forcing Black's bishop back. }
26. g5{ This doesn't help. }
27. Be3
27. Bg6
28. b4{ The knight is trapped. }
28. Nc6
29. dxc6
29. bxc6
30. Bxc6
30. Rxa3
31. Bd5+
