[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "My Approach"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. --{ The introduction is already quite long. Nevertheless, I think it is time well spent to briefly describe the goals with which such a large project is approached:     1)  I want to show that the opening is very playable and objectively definitely better than its reputation. This requires a minimum of analysis, especially in the 'critical variations' often recommended by theory. On the other hand, many of our novelties often start well before move 10.     Doing a thorough analysis in completely unexplored positions often felt like a walk in the dark. You can't cover every move imaginable. Having a hundred trainables for a position that has never been reached in practice would probably be practical for very few. :)     I've assembled the variations to the best of my ability using engines, databases, and my own rusty head, in order to give a good representation of both White's critical approaches and our own plans, but certainly, there is still quite a lot to be discovered in the opening!     2)  You've heard it a lot: effective opening learning is less about memorising moves and more about understanding the ideas. I agree with that 100%!     Therefore, you will find that     a)  I like sample variations that illustrate what happens in the early middlegame. Some variations are certainly a few moves longer than those of other authors, but that usually means that I still found those very moves particularly instructive! I hope you see it the same way!     b)  I have significantly more variations in the clickables than other courses. In critical main variations that a player armed with engine preparation could use against us, I have refrained from doing so. But in many other chapters, I firmly believe that positional understanding is best gained by seeing different ideas at one glance in comparison to each other rather than having them unrelated in different trainables.      3)  Often enough one hears authors complaining about how difficult it is nowadays to avoid drawish positions in every variation. It is interesting that we even hear this complaint from authors who create White courses with the absolute main - and arguably best - openings!     A Black repertoire, of course, has an even more difficult time and many Black courses resign themselves to the fate of not being able to avoid draws. It is not always possible to completely avoid somewhat boring positions, but I had two goals:     a)  I tried (successfully) to avoid every single move repetition - and some trainables are only about how to avoid draws when the opponent tries to provoke such a repetition early on.     b)  If our opponent tries to flatten the game, I have chosen the variation that is most eager to create imbalances. }
