1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6{ The starting position of the Slav defence. }
3. Nc3{ This is one of White's main continuations. In most cases, this move transposes to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Bg5{ When White develops their dark-squared bishop - typically to  f4  or  g5  - this is usually an indication that we should take on  c4  and try to hold onto it. White's idea to play  Bxf6  is no reason for us not to do it! }( { If White got one more move and could play   }5.e3 { , they would get an improved version of the  e3 -setups -  starting here . } )
4. dxc4( { We don't have to be afraid of }5.Bxf6 { . This would just give up the bishop pair and after }...exf6 { it would even accelerate Black's development. } )
5. a4{ White tries to prevent ... b7 - b5 . A very typical move, but here this is only a temporary success. }
5. Qb6{ I like this move. Black provokes White to go  Qd2  and afterwards, Black continues with ... Qa5 . Without the  a1 -rook being protected, Black is ready to go ... b7 - b5 . }
6. Qd2
6. Qa5{ Black is ready to protect the  c4 -pawn with ... b7 - b5 . }
7. e4
7. b5{ Black has the idea to go ... b4  and ... Nxe4 . }
8. Bxf6
8. exf6
9. Nf3
9. b4{ This, followed by ... c4 - c3 , disturbs White's queenside and activates Black's. }
10. Nd1( 10.Nb1 c3 11.bxc3 bxc3 { is similar. } )
10. c3{ Using White's uncoordinated pieces to fight for the initiative. }
11. bxc3
11. bxc3
12. Qc2( 12.Nxc3 Bb4! 13.Rc1 Nd7! { , followed by }-- 14...Nb6 { gives Black a lot of pressure. } )
12. Bb4{ Black is currently the  c3 -pawn up and White has problems winning this pawn back under good circumstances. Black has targets himself like the  a4 -pawn or the central pawns after ... O-O  and ... Re8 . }{  See variation in course  }
