2. c6{ The starting position of the Slav defence. }
3. Nc3{ This is one of White's main continuations. In most cases, this move transposes to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Bf4{ Another move to develop the dark-squared bishop before playing  e2 - e3 . But you already know the antidote. }
4. dxc4{ As usual, we just take on  c4  if White develops their bishop to  f4 . }
5. e4{ Putting the pawn on  e4  is always double-edged. On the one hand, it grabs space. On the other hand, the pawn can also be a target as Black will certainly play ... b5  and then ... b4  is always in the air. }
5. b5{ Business as usual - we protect the pawn. }
