1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. Bf4{ There are some small differences if White sacrifices the  c4 -pawn with the knight already on  f3 .     White is one move closer to castling and controls the  e5 -square, so there will not be that many variations where Black can try to play the Uno reverse card and start to be the one who goes for the attack  like in this example .     On the other hand, this move doesn't change much about the fact that Black has an extra pawn on the queenside and should try to keep it! }
4. dxc4{ A standard reply by now! }
5. a4{ White wants to fight against ... b7 - b5 , but Black can currently still play it in response to a move like  e3  and Black is also in time to prepare ... Bb4  as a response to  Nc3 . }
5. e6
6. Nc3
6. Bb4( { White has no convincing way to disrupt Black's setup.    }6...Nd5 7.Bg5 { is an additional resource in White's play with the knight on  f3  - doesn't change the fact that it is most likely also slightly better for Black. }{  See variation in course  } )
