3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the Queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4{ This is White's main move in this line. However, if Black plays these positions dynamically, we can have a lot of fun! }( { The position resembles lines from the  Bf4 -Grünfeld (for example,   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bf4 { ). In those lines, Black does often get counterplay with a quick }...c5 { .    }{ We'll do the same here! It may sound strange to aim for these variations when you have already invested a tempo for ... c7 - c6 , but for this, White has played the move  4.Qc2,  placing the queen on a much more vulnerable square than  d1 ! } )
5. Bg7{ Continuing development for now. }
6. cxd5{ If White wants to take on  d5  in this  4.Qc2  line - which usually just leads to a bad Exchange variation anyway - they should do it before playing  Bc1 - f4 . The reason is that the Grünfeld recapture ... Nxd5  gains a lot of strength now!     If we can play this move with tempo, the 'tempo loss' of ... c7 - c6  is at least equalized and as White's setup is often not particularly directed against a Grünfeld setup, Black can often hope to get a strong initiative going. }
6. Bf5{ With the queen on  c2 , it makes sense to include this move. White cannot easily push for  e2 - e4  afterwards. }
7. Qb3{ The most logical square. White attacks  b7 . }
7. Nxd5{ In response, we attack the bishop on  f4 . The pawn on  b7  is poisoned. }
8. Bg3( { Better than taking on  b7 . }8.Qxb7? Nxf4! 9.Qxa8 Qb6! { , followed by }-- ...O-O { and a random knight move trap the queen! } )
8. Qb6( { This might look innocent at first glance but if White allows the queen exchange under the wrong circumstances, Black might just storm White's queenside.    }8...O-O { is another }{ typical move in these situations. White does not really want to take the pawn on  b7  while being so underdeveloped. } )
9. Nbd2{ White should develop the knight to make sure that they can recapture on  b3  with something else than the a-pawn. }
9. Qxb3{ This gives Black a pleasant endgame. }
10. Nxb3
10. Nd7{ Controlling  c5  and  e5  so that White cannot go  Nb3 - c5  or  Bf4 - e5 .     In the next moves, Black can go ... a7 - a5 - a4  to get rid of the knight on  b3  when Black can potentially also play ... c5 . Black has a nice position. }{     See variation in course  }
