[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the Queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4{ This is White's main move in this line. However, if Black plays these positions dynamically, we can have a lot of fun! }( { The position resembles lines from the  Bf4 -Grünfeld (for example,   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bf4 { ). In those lines, Black does often get counterplay with a quick }...c5 { .    }{ We'll do the same here! It may sound strange to aim for these variations when you have already invested a tempo for ... c7 - c6 , but for this, White has played the move  4.Qc2,  placing the queen on a much more vulnerable square than  d1 ! } )
5. Bg7{ Continuing development for now. }
6. e3
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main move. }
7. c5{ A very principled move. The same position, with White's queen on  d1  instead of on  c2 , is one possible position in the Grünfeld (and is completely playable for Black). Here, we have an improved version as the queen on  c2  is pretty misplaced and can be attacked with some developing moves (... Bf5 , ... Na6 - b4 ). }
8. dxc5{ This is the typical reaction in these positions. White temporarily wins a pawn and Black at least has to spend a few tempi to win it back. }
8. Qa5{ The typical square for the queen. Not only do we attack  c5 , but there is also a lot of pressure against  c3 . }
9. Rd1
9. Ne4( { Equality is not Black's biggest problem in this line. Black could also achieve this with moves like }9...Bf5 { or }9...dxc4 { .    Creating as many imbalances as possible was the bigger task for yours truly. However, I am happy with the move }9...Ne4 { . }{ Objectively, this is also equal, but by creating a pawn weakness on  c3 , we'll take a nice first step to give us targets to play against. } )
10. cxd5{ Taking as many pawns as possible. }
10. Nxc3( 10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 Nxc3 { seems also playable. I just like to keep the dark-squared bishop. } )
11. bxc3
11. Nd7{ The typical move to win back the  c5 -pawn. The knight will be superbly placed on  c5 . }( 11...Bxc3+?! 12.Nd2 { makes it hard for Black to win back the  c5 -pawn without making too many concessions. For example }12...Qxc5? 13.Rc1 Bxd2+ 14.Qxd2+- { forces us to exchange all our good pieces and we would remain with an underdeveloped queenside mess while White has the two bishops and a strong d-pawn. } )
12. Nd4{ A good move to block the long diagonal and to not allow ... Bf5  after we have recaptured the pawn with ... Nxc5 . We still have good ways to get access to White's weaknesses. }
12. Nxc5
13. Be2( 13.Bc4 { Supporting the d-pawn but it is only helping in the short term. }13...Bg4 { comes with tempo and provokes some weaknesses. After }14.f3 { , we'll just go }14...Bd7 { while a move like   }14.Rc1 { allows us to just play }14...Rac8 { with ideas like }-- ...Na4 { . } )
13. Na4{ A typical square to attack  c3 . }
14. Rd3
14. Bd7{ Black protects  a4  and is now ready to play ... Qxd5  as well as ... Rac8 . }{     See variation in course  }
