[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Variation. Many players consider the resulting positions boring but I am extremely happy with the lines that I came up with in this course to create imbalances! }
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order in the  full chapter . The main line can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { .    General rule in the Exchange Slav: We play  ...Nf6  before  ...Nc6 . } )
5. Bg5{ A rare move because Black has a convincing antidote. Nevertheless, the move has its supporters.  Most notably, GM Anton Korobov likes to play this line in short time controls - White is planning to take on  f6  and spoil Black's pawn structure. }
5. Ne4{ We will learn in this course that this knight jump is a typical response to White's  Bc1 - g5  move. }( { The fact that Black can even play this move here when White has no knight on  f3  that gets attacked after }6.Nxe4 dxe4 { , makes this position even more instructive.    }{ Black is attacking the bishop on  g5  but we also have the idea to either take on  c3  and force White to the  bxc3 -pawn structure or we can just increase the pressure with ... Qa5 .    White should definitely take it - otherwise, the last move would have been very pointless. } )
6. Nxe4
6. dxe4( { White's main problem is that it is impossible to play }7.e3 { because of }7...Qa5+ { . This makes it slightly uncomfortable to develop the pieces for White. A very typical tactic! } )
7. a3{ Believe it or not, this is White's main move. Taking control over the  b4 -square stops all ideas connected with ... Bb4 + - but it is one additional tempo that White wastes in the opening. }
7. h6( { This move forces White to find a good square for the bishop. As we will see this is not so easy.  To be fair, Black has plenty of good options like }7...Qd5 { , }7...Qb6 { or }7...g6 { as well. } )
8. Bh4{ After this move, White's bishop will not help in the defence of the queenside. }
8. Qb6{ A nice move to exploit this fact. White has some problems defending the  b2 -pawn. }
9. Qc2{ This move, counter-attacking the  c8 -bishop, is White's best option. }( 9.Qd2 { keeps the b and d-pawn protected but allows Black the strong }9...e5! { White has to play a slightly worse position after }10.e3 exd4 { with a weak isolated pawn because }10.dxe5? Nc6 { can become very wrong very quickly for White. }{ Black will pick up the  e5 -pawn later and the queen on  d2  helps Black develop their initiative with the ... Rd8  tempo. } )
9. Nc6
10. e3
10. e5{ With a great position for Black. White can neither take on  e5  nor on  e4  because of  11...Qa5  and so Black gets this explosive position for free. }{     See variation in course  }
