[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange Nc3/Bf4/e3  #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Variation. Many players consider the resulting positions boring but I am extremely happy with the lines that I came up with in this course to create imbalances! }
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order in the  full chapter . The main line can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { .    General rule in the Exchange Slav: We play  ...Nf6  before  ...Nc6 . } )
5. Bf4{ The main move. White just develops the bishop to a safe square and will play  e2 - e3  and most likely  Ng1 - f3  next with very solid development. The resulting setup is in most cases what White is aiming for when they play the Exchange variation! }
5. Nc6{ Another general rule: ... Nc6  is more flexible in the Exchange structures than ... g6  or ... Bg7 . If you are not sure which move to make, play the knight. You will see examples of this in a second. }
6. e3( { The independent move order }6.Nf3 g6 { transposes to the Schlexchange (=Schlechter+Exchange) chapter. } )( { Unfortunately, we cannot really enter 'Schlechter territory' now with   }6...g6 { under good circumstances. That means we have to find a more mainline solution. } )
6. Bg4( { Unfortunately, I don't think it is advisable to play the Schlechter move }6...g6 { in this concrete move order. }{ As you will see in the 'Schlexchange' chapters -  see here  - the moves ... Ne4  and ... Nh5  are important resources there. Without White's knight committed to  f3 , they are much less likely to work. So we need another variation against this specific move order.     The good thing is that this is really the  only  position - if White wants to develop with  Nc3 ,  Nf3 ,  Bf4 ,  e3  - where transpositions to the Schlexchange don't work and so we can choose the most aggressive setup without caring if it works against other move orders as well! }{    I chose the move }6...Bg4 { for different reasons.     1)  It is only the fourth most popular move in this position. That means White players might not be as familiar with this move as with the alternatives }6...Bf5 { , }6...a6 { or }6...e6 { .     2)  If White responds with the most critical move   }7.f3 { , the position will be really imbalanced. Ideal to play for a win!     3)  The move has the best score - pretty much 50%. } )
7. f3{ This is White's sharpest move. After the move  f2 - f3 , White should follow it up with aggressive moves on the kingside like  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4 .     Otherwise, the pawn on  f3  would serve no purpose and White would have just weakened their king and taken away the  f3 -square for the knight for no reason. }
7. Bd7( { We should go back into safety with this bishop. Playing }7...Bh5?! { would play into White's cards as the bishop allows  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4 - h5  with tempo. } )
8. Bd3{ The most popular move. For White's aggressive intentions, the bishop clearly belongs to  d3 . }( { White can also start with }8.g4 { but Black's setup remains the same; ... e6 , ... Be7 , ... Rc8  and at some point, White should put the bishop on  d3 . } )
8. e6{ This is not only a simple developing move, it also prepares ... Nh5  to win the bishop pair - the bishop no longer has the  g5 -square. White should definitely do something about it. }( { After }9.Nge2 Nh5! { , for example, Black would already be slightly better. } )
9. g4{ This is White's main line. White stops ... Nh5  and also prepares a pawn storm on the kingside. }
9. Be7{ For now, Black just develops normally. }
10. Nge2{ The most flexible move order. The knight always belongs on  e2 . }
10. O-O{ It looks risky to castle into White's pawn storm but there are some points to it.     A very important aspect is the manoeuvre ... Ne8 - d6 . This manoeuvre can be executed in different versions.     If White pushes  h2 - h4 , we can often go ... h5 , threaten to take on  g4 , and if White pushes  g4 - g5 , we can just play ... Ne8  and ... g6  with a pretty safe kingside and we can start our own counterplay on the queenside.     If White postpones  h2 - h4 , ... h5  is not nearly as good. White can keep the tension with  h2 - h3  and the structure stays flexible. }
11. Kf2( { More flexible than }11.h4 { which would allow a timely }...h5 { when White has nothing better than to close the kingside with }g5 { . } )( { Now, Black cannot play   }11...h5 { because White can keep the tension with }12.h3 { . So let's see what Black does in such a scenario. } )
11. Rc8( { This is a flexible move to start. The immediate }11...Ne8 { is also possible. } )
12. Rc1( { Let's look at this move as a sample line as it transposes to an existing correspondence game. The following manoeuvre can also be played against other typical moves like }12.Kg2 { or }12.a3 { .    }12.h4 { would once again allow }12...h5! { . } )
12. Ne8{ Even if we are not forced with  g4 - g5 , the ... Ne8 - d6  manoeuvre makes a lot of sense.      d6  is just a good square for the knight, it can no longer be hit with tempo and Black also gains flexibility for their kingside pawns. }
13. h4
13. Nd6( { Just continuing with the manoeuvre. ( }13...Bxh4+ 14.Kg2 { might be possible for Black but it is very risky to open the h-hile for White. Usually, it is not necessary to take this somewhat poisoned pawn.)    Let's stop the trainable here, but let me show you one more idea from the high-level correspondence game Garbar - Stephensson, 2018.      }14.a3 a6 { Both sides just make some useful moves on the queenside. A clear sign that there is no great attack in the position despite White's advanced pawns. }15.g5!? { A try to make progress on the kingside. }15...f6! { A cool reaction. Even though White acted as the aggressor, it is far from clear if opening the kingside is really advantageous for White. White's king might also be the one under fire if some files open up.    In the game, White had no interest in finding out which king would be safer in such a scenario and forced Black to keep the files closed with }16.Qc2 f5 { . The game ended later in a draw in  Garbar, A. - Stephenson, M. ICCF email 2018 . }{  See variation in course  } )
