5. cxd5
6. Qb3{ This is a reasonable move. White puts pressure on the  d5 -pawn so Black cannot execute typical manoeuvres like ... Ne4  or ... Nh5  if White develops their dark-squared bishop. }
6. Nc6{ Following the rule that in the Exchange variations, it is more flexible to play ... Nc6  instead of ... Bg7 . This variation is one of the main reasons why I created this rule. It might be important to have the resource ... Nc6 - a5  at the right moment. }( 6...Bg7?! 7.Bg5 { is what White would like to play. With the pressure against  d5 , Black cannot play }...Ne4 { . } )
7. Bg5( { White would love to see Black play a passive move like }7...e6 { but Black has a more active response - thanks to  6...Nc6! . } )
7. Na5{ This solves all of Black's problems. }
8. Qa4+{ It looks pretty stupid to give Black ... Bd7  with tempo, but White's idea is actually that this blocks the d-file so that Black's queen has less influence there. Why this is important can be seen in the next few moves. }
8. Bd7
9. Qd1{ The safest square. }
9. Ne4{ Of course, we still go for this move. }
10. Nxe4( { This was White's plan. Otherwise, Black could play   }10...Nxc3 { and would have gotten all the moves ... Nc6 , ... Na5  and ... Nd7  with tempo that we usually play anyways in this structure. } )( 10.Nxd5? Nxg5 11.Nxg5 e6! { loses a piece as both knights are hanging. } )
10. dxe4
11. Ne5
11. Nc6{ A strong reply. }( { We are threatening   }12...Nxe5 13.dxe5 Qa5+ { . White's only principled move is now taking the bishop. Still, after   }12.Nxd7 Qxd7 { , Black has pressure against  d4  and can soon plan with ... e7 - e5 ! } ){  See variation in course  }
