5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's main move. White simply wants to develop their pieces in a symmetrical structure, claiming that there is no reason why the bishop on  g7  should be a good piece. Indeed, it is up to us to create imbalances very soon! }
6. Nc6{ For now, we are following our rule... It is actually important that the bishop stays on  f8  for now.     This right here is arguably the most important position in the course! First of all, because this variation is one of White's most popular setups. But also, because we have to create imbalances at all costs and we might miss our chance to do so if we play our next moves on autopilot! }( { The general rule is:    If White plays the natural }7.e3 { , we'll go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )( { If White anticipates this and plays }7.h3 { , we go }7...Ne4 { and take on  c3 ! There are more moves that White can play and we will look at them as well, of course. But if you remember these two key moves, you should be equipped for 95% of your games in this variation. } )
7. h3{ This anticipates ... Nh5  by giving a square on  h2 . So we have to go for the second move that creates counterplay. }
7. Ne4{ Planning to take on  c3  to slightly weaken White's structure. }
8. Rc1{ White cannot really avoid the structure with  bxc3 . If they want to recapture on  c3  with queen or rook, they run into tactics with ... e7 - e5 . }
8. Nxc3
9. Rxc3( 9.bxc3 { is playable but proves the  Rc1 -move quite pointless. } )
