11. Na5{ Black takes control over the  c4 -square that stops White from playing  c3 - c4 . }( { Another typical way to play these positions is }11...b6 { , followed by ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  and potentially ... Na5  slightly later. } )( { However, I prefer the positions with the immediate }11...Na5 { . Black typically has a decent position if we develop our light-squared bishop and start to gang up on the c-file with our major pieces against the  c3 -pawn.   }{ To avoid this, White might try to play aggressively on the kingside with ideas like  h2 - h4 - h5 . In some positions, it is important to have ... Bg4  in response to  h3 - h4 .     Also, by developing our light-squared bishop to  e6 , it plays a role in stabilising the kingside pawns. A role it doesn't have on  b7 . }{     See variation in course  } )
