6. Bf4{ This is White's main move. White simply wants to develop their pieces in a symmetrical structure, claiming that there is no reason why the bishop on  g7  should be a good piece. Indeed, it is up to us to create imbalances very soon! }
6. Nc6{ For now, we are following our rule... It is actually important that the bishop stays on  f8  for now.     This right here is arguably the most important position in the course! First of all, because this variation is one of White's most popular setups. But also, because we have to create imbalances at all costs and we might miss our chance to do so if we play our next moves on autopilot! }( { The general rule is:    If White plays the natural }7.e3 { , we'll go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )( { If White anticipates this and plays }7.h3 { , we go }7...Ne4 { and take on  c3 ! There are more moves that White can play and we will look at them as well, of course. But if you remember these two key moves, you should be equipped for 95% of your games in this variation. } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Bg5{ This is one try for White to keep the bishop pair. }
8. h6( { We have to play this move at some point. We can also start with }8...Bg7 { .    However, White can respond with }9.Bh4!? { which somehow forces Black to transpose to the mainline with }9...h6 { . The problem is that a normal-looking move like }9...O-O { is answered with }10.Qb3! { and Black has some problems keeping both the  d5  and the  b7 -pawn defended! } )
9. Bh4
9. Bg7{ It is still Black's main idea to go  g5  and gain the bishop pair. We also need an answer for  Qb3 . }( 9...g5?! { is a typical move but we need our bishop on  g7 ! Here, White has a strong response. }10.Ne5! { is just better for White.    }{ If we save our knight from  h5 , White can just respond with  11.Bg3  and we have lost a lot of time and weakened our kingside without succeeding in winning our bishop pair. }10...Nxe5 { is the only try to justify Black's last move but this knight will be missed soon. After }11.dxe5 { , Black has no good reply. More or less all logical moves run into a well-timed  Bb5+ .    For example,  A)  }11...d4 12.Qxh5 dxc3 13.Bb5+! Bd7 14.e6! { would be a painful end to the game    or  B)    }11...gxh4 12.Bb5+! { Even stronger than taking on  h5 . }12...Bd7 13.e6! { Once again this motif! }13...Bxb5 14.Qxh5 Rh7 15.Nxb5 Qa5+ 16.Nc3+- { Material is equal but Black's king is never going to survive in this position. } )
10. Rc1( { Let's use this as a sample move to illustrate Black's general follow-up as well as some dynamic possibilities!    }10.Rc1 { is more flexible move than }10.Be2 { . Both, because the rook always belongs on the c-file in the Exchange structure anyway }{ but also because White's queen will be able to take on  h5  if White goes for some knight discoveries. } )
10. g5{ Now, we can go for the bishop! }
11. Ne5( { Knight discoveries like this move or }11.Nd2 { are something to look out for but if we know how to handle them, they shouldn't do us too much harm.    }{ This move would have just lost a pawn after  10.Be2  as White cannot regain a pawn on  h4  if they recapture on  h5  with the bishop. Here, it is a serious option. However, we already know the typical motifs to disturb White! }11.Bg3 { is not a big deal. Black can just play }11...Nxg3 12.hxg3 e6 { , followed by ... Bd7 , ... Qe7 , ... O-O . Black can play on both sides of the board in the resulting position. } )
11. Nxe5( { I think this move is more ambitious than the also playable }11...Bxe5! 12.Qxh5 Bxd4 13.exd4 gxh4 14.Qxh4 { which is about equal. } )
12. dxe5( 12.Qxh5?? Bg4! { is not advisable for White. } )
12. d4{ A typical way to create a lot of action in the center. }
13. Qxd4
13. O-O{ If White exchanges queens, we will just win back the pawn on  e5 . Otherwise, we will get a nice initiative with ... Qa5 , ... Bf5 , ... Rd8 . }( {  A)  }13...gxh4? 14.Qxh4! { is not advisable for Black. The knight will be lost under bad circumstances. } )( {  B)  }13...Qxd4 14.exd4 gxh4 { is playable but it is not winning a piece. }15.Nd5! { is threatening a big check on  c7  and }15...O-O 16.Be2 { wins back the knight on  h5  as well. Apparently, }16...Nf6! { is still equal with the goal of at least eliminating the restricting  e5 -pawn but there is no need to test this evaluation. }{     See variation in course  } )
