6. Bf4{ This is White's main move. White simply wants to develop their pieces in a symmetrical structure, claiming that there is no reason why the bishop on  g7  should be a good piece. Indeed, it is up to us to create imbalances very soon! }
6. Nc6{ For now, we are following our rule... It is actually important that the bishop stays on  f8  for now.     This right here is arguably the most important position in the course! First of all, because this variation is one of White's most popular setups. But also, because we have to create imbalances at all costs and we might miss our chance to do so if we play our next moves on autopilot! }( { The general rule is:    If White plays the natural }7.e3 { , we'll go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )( { If White anticipates this and plays }7.h3 { , we go }7...Ne4 { and take on  c3 ! There are more moves that White can play and we will look at them as well, of course. But if you remember these two key moves, you should be equipped for 95% of your games in this variation. } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Be5{ This is White's most serious option. }
8. f6( 8...Nxe5? { is bad here for several reasons. The typical response is }9.dxe5 { with an attack against  d5  and Black also has to worry about ideas with  g2 - g4  or  Bb5+/ Qa4 + . }{ Concretely, even }9.Nxe5 { is annoying with ideas like  Bb5+/Qa4+ . } )
9. Bg3
9. e6{ Black stabilises their pawns.     It is important not to hurry with ... Bg7  because when White plays  Bg3 - h4  to save their bishop, we might run into tactics connected with  g2 - g4 .     Overall, the main difference of this  8.Be5 -variation compared to  8.Bg3  is the provoked move ... f6 .     In a later middlegame, the move ... f6  to take control over the  e5 -square and potentially prepare ... e5  might be useful. However, this is usually only a good idea if Black has a decent development and White has no way to punish Black for the weaknesses that go hand in hand with this pawn advance.  What weaknesses are those? Well, I guess the honest answer is: Black's whole kingside pawn structure.  So there are some things to consider in this line:     - If we take on  g3  prematurely, White might use the open h-hile for pressure against  h7  and  g6      - We have to be more careful about the  a2 - g8  diagonal - White has more incentive to play an early  e3 - e4  to get more open files and easier access to Black's pawns. Especially the pawn on  e6  is a natural target if White gets an open e-file     All this sounds a little bit scary but don't panic! The main implication is that we should not take on  g3  on autopilot and that we should have this  e3 - e4  break in mind when we decide which move order to choose.  To take right away on  g3  is a little bit risky with the open h-file, the weakened kingside structure and Black not being developed yet: }( 9...Nxg3?! 10.hxg3 { and the desirable }10...Bg7 { runs into immediate problems after }11.Qc2! { with the threat of  12.Rxh7 . }11...O-O 12.Nxd5! { doesn't help either. Black has better moves on move 10 - like   }10...Be6 { - but all those moves don't really solve Black's problems. } )
10. Bd3{ This is clearly the most critical continuation. The bishop pressures the kingside which discourages us from taking on  g3 . Also, this bishop prepares  e3 - e4 . }
10. Bd7{ A good move against the immediate  e3 - e4 . The bishop just stabilizes the  c6 -knight but more concretely, Black can play ... Nb4  without allowing any checks along the  a4 - e8  diagonal and the bishop is also ready to stabilize the light squares from  c6  after that. }( {  A)  }10...Bg7?! 11.Bh4! { is a typical motif.  g2-g4  will be a problem. } )( {  B)  }10...Nxg3?! 11.hxg3 Bg7? 12.Rxh7! { is a typical tactic to exploit it if Black opens the h-file too soon. } )
11. e4
11. Nb4{ Going for the bishop and protecting  d5 . Black will be reasonably stable on the light squares. }{     See variation in course  }
