1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ The combination of  Nc3  and  Nf3  is often considered to be White's most critical move order against the Grünfeld Slav. White has made no concession so far regarding the  c4 -pawn. }
4. g6( { If you play }4...g6 { even against this critical setup, you can proudly call yourself a member of the highly exclusive 'Diehard Grünfeld Slav Club'. White has many options to choose from.    They can still play }5.e3 { or }5.g3 { and transpose to other  e3 - starting here  or  g3 -setups -  starting here .    But White can also choose one of the independent options:     A)  }5.cxd5 { -  starting here 
     B)  }5.Bf4 { -  starting here 
     C)  }5.h3 { -  see here 
     D)  }5.Bg5 { -  starting here 
     E)  }5.Qb3 { -  starting here  } )
5. Bf4{ This is one of White's most popular moves on amateur level but I don't consider it a particularly good one. I think just taking on  c4  gives Black a good position. }
5. dxc4( { The principled move.    Whenever White develops their dark-squared bishop without caring about the  c4 -pawn, it is a good sign that we should take it.    }5...Bg7 { is playable but in my opinion not a very practical move. After }6.e3 { , White will have all their pieces on good squares and to avoid a slightly worse position, Black should play rather dynamically with ... O-O , ... Qa5  and ... c6 - c5  which would require the learning of unnecessarily concrete lines. } )
6. a4{ A typical move to stop ... b7 - b5 . }
6. Nd5( { Immediately making use of White's misplaced bishop on  f4 . A typical motif! The knight can just exchange itself on  c3  to play  ...b5  but sometimes, it can even be annoying on  b4 !    }6...Bg7 7.e4! { promises White some advantage. } )
7. Be5{ Typically the most annoying move. White wants to provoke ... f7 - f6  which is not a move that Black wants to play here. }
7. f6
8. Bg3
8. Qa5{ This puts pressure on  c3  and stops White from  a4 - a5  if Black puts a knight on  b6 .     In this variation it makes sense to take on  c3  with the knight, so that the queen on  a5  has something to keep an eye on, and put the  b8 -knight on  b6 . }
9. Qd2{ The most natural move to protect  c3 . }( {  A)  }9.Rc1 { The rook is not particularly well placed on the c-file and White's  a4 -pawn might become a little bit loose as  Nb8 - d7 - b6  is part of Black's setup anyways. }9...Nd7 10.e3 N7b6∓ { and White has to deal with ideas like ... Nxc3  and taking on  a4 . } )( {  B)  }9.e4 { was played once to only answer }9...Nxc3 { with }10.Qd2 { . However, this doesn't look too impressive. }10...Be6 { looks simple enough but we can also play more forcing with the immediate }10...Bh6!? 11.Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12.bxc3 Be6=∞ { . White has some compensation but this is clearly one of the more innocuous versions of the pawn sacrifice. } )
9. Nxc3{ Black is not forced to take right away, but it is part of our setup anyways. }
10. bxc3
10. Nd7{ The knight can come to  b6  to protect the  c4 -pawn. }( 10...Bh6 11.e3 { is not effective here. } )
11. e4{ Not the only move but the most aggressive one! It allows me to show you one tactical detail that helps us develop. }( 11.e3 { doesn't allow it, but here, we can just protect the pawn with }11...Nb6 { . } )
11. Bh6{ This simply wins a tempo against White's queen. White cannot take it because the queen needs to protect  c3 . }{  See variation in course  }
