     D)  }5.Bg5 { -  starting here 
     E)  }5.Qb3 { -  starting here  } )
5. Qb3{ In the sideline chapters, we will discuss many lines with an early  Qb3 . This variation is the most critical version.     White protects the  c4 -pawn which is a useful thing to do, but there is also a more concrete reason to this move. With the additional piece attacking  d5 , White can opt for setups with  Bg5  and Black doesn't have the typical - dynamic! - response ... Ne4 . }
5. dxc4{ Reacting in Grünfeld Style!     Black will continue with ... b5  to start typical counterplay on the queenside. }( 5...Bg7 { allows }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5 { and Black cannot play dynamically with }7...Ne4 { , because  d5  would be hanging. This is exactly the kind of position that we should avoid! } )
6. Qxc4
6. b5( { I think this immediate  ...b5  is the most precise move order.    }6...Bg7 { would indeed be a position from the Grünfeld. It is also playable, but White gets the possibility to win the center immediately with }7.e4 { . Let's not go down this rabbit hole.  As Black's main counterplay in these lines is still connected with  ...b7-b5  ideas, I think it is the most principled move to play it before White can get a second pawn in the center. } )
7. Qd3{ This is in general not considered to be a particularly good square. Black is not even forced to go for ... b5 - b4  here, but can also play in a calmer fashion. }
7. b4( { Still, let's go with the early  ...b4 . This is most consistent with our lines after   }7.Qb3 { . } )( { Starting with }7...Bg7 { and }-- 8...O-O { is a very playable alternative. With White's queen not on  b3 , Black can play ... b4  at any given time.  Nevertheless, I like the resulting position after  8...b4 . They also have the advantage of stopping White's  e2 - e4  move. } )
8. Ne4{ If White wants to go for  Ne4  in reply to ... b5 - b4 , they should play it with the queen on  d3  instead of  b3 . }( { In the line   }7.Qb3 Be6 8.Qc2 b4 9.Ne4 Nxe4 { , Black gets in ... Be6  for free. }{    If White wants to react to  ...b5-b4  with  Nc3-a4  (which is more critical to stop Black from playing  ...c6-c5 ), White should have played   }7.Qb3 { to give as much support as possible to the queenside. } )
8. Nxe4{ An easy move. White's queen is more vulnerable on  e4  than on  d3 . }
9. Qxe4
9. Bg7{ We have a typical situation. White would love to develop as fast as possible and fix the pawn on  c6  as a weakness.  However, if we get our breaks in - mainly ... c5  but maybe even ... e5  - we will be doing fine immediately and our space-grabbing queenside pawns might give us the slightly more pleasant position. White's pieces are not on really good squares right now and especially the queen on  e4  can be easily attacked with tempo. }
10. e3
10. a5{ This is a nice multi-purpose move. Black protects  b4 , wins some space on the queenside and prepares ... Ba6 . }( { A move like }10...O-O { is also playable but playing }10...a5 { is just very useful.    }{ In variations where White plays  Nc3 - a4  instead of  Ne4 , these ... a5  moves are often too slow, because White has realistic hopes of creating a blockade on the  c5 -square.  However, without the knight on  a4 , we usually have no problems getting our queenside rolling. }{     See variation in course  } )
