[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ The combination of  Nc3  and  Nf3  is often considered to be White's most critical move order against the Grünfeld Slav. White has made no concession so far regarding the  c4 -pawn. }
4. g6( { If you play }4...g6 { even against this critical setup, you can proudly call yourself a member of the highly exclusive 'Diehard Grünfeld Slav Club'. White has many options to choose from.    They can still play }5.e3 { or }5.g3 { and transpose to other  e3 - starting here  or  g3 -setups -  starting here .    But White can also choose one of the independent options:     A)  }5.cxd5 { -  starting here 
     B)  }5.Bf4 { -  starting here 
     C)  }5.h3 { -  see here 
     D)  }5.Bg5 { -  starting here 
     E)  }5.Qb3 { -  starting here  } )
5. Qb3{ In the sideline chapters, we will discuss many lines with an early  Qb3 . This variation is the most critical version.     White protects the  c4 -pawn which is a useful thing to do, but there is also a more concrete reason to this move. With the additional piece attacking  d5 , White can opt for setups with  Bg5  and Black doesn't have the typical - dynamic! - response ... Ne4 . }
5. dxc4{ Reacting in Grünfeld Style!     Black will continue with ... b5  to start typical counterplay on the queenside. }( 5...Bg7 { allows }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5 { and Black cannot play dynamically with }7...Ne4 { , because  d5  would be hanging. This is exactly the kind of position that we should avoid! } )
6. Qxc4
6. b5( { I think this immediate  ...b5  is the most precise move order.    }6...Bg7 { would indeed be a position from the Grünfeld. It is also playable, but White gets the possibility to win the center immediately with }7.e4 { . Let's not go down this rabbit hole.  As Black's main counterplay in these lines is still connected with  ...b7-b5  ideas, I think it is the most principled move to play it before White can get a second pawn in the center. } )
7. Qb3{ This is the best square for White's queen. Both  d3  and  b3  are squares where the queen can be attacked later on, but from  b3  (or later  c2 ) it stabilizes a knight on  a4 , so moves like ... Qa5  will not be with tempo. }
7. Be6{ It makes a lot of sense to drive the queen away from  b3 . Otherwise, it is harder for us to play with ...  b4 . }( 7...Bg7 8.e4 { enters the same Grünfeld variation we could have reached with   }6...Bg7 { . White should be able to be slightly better here. }{ Compared to the  variations  with the queen on  d3 , Black has a harder time mobilising the queenside if we don’t use our chance now! } )
8. Qc2( { The most logical square. White keeps an eye on the  e4 -square and would be ready to answer a move like   }8...Bg7 { with }9.e4 { .    }{ Also White keeps an eye on the  c5 -square that has been weakened by Black's last moves.  The drawback is that ... Bf5  can come with tempo. } )
8. b4{ Fighting for the  e4 -square. We want to play ... Bf5  without being hit with  e2 - e4 . }
9. Na4{ This is White's most ambitious move. They keep control over the  c5 -square.  In these variations, Black really shouldn't waste any tempi because White can realistically fix our pawn weaknesses on the queenside. }
9. Bf5{ This was the idea. White cannot play  e2 - e4  easily. }
10. Qb3
10. Bg7{ Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn for dynamic counterplay. }( {  A)  }10...Qa5? 11.Bd2+- { doesn't help. } )( {  B) Too slow is once again }10...a5?! { . White just gets a positional advantage with natural developing moves, followed by creating pressure on the c-file. }11.Bg5 Ne4 12.Bf4 Bg7 13.e3 O-O 14.Bd3 Nd7 15.Qc2+- { is a logical sequence. } )
11. Qxb4{ White should take on  b4  sooner or later. Black's usual next moves are ... O-O  and ... Nbd7  against most of White's setup so White is free to take the pawn one or two moves later but usually Black just gets a good position if White doesn't grab it. }
11. O-O{ Black just develops as fast as possible in exchange for the pawn. }( 11...Nbd7 { is also possible. } )
12. e3{ White should develop as fast as possible and this is the most solid way to do it. }
12. Nbd7{ Black just develops naturally. Soon, ... e5  or ... c5  will be playable. }
13. Be2
13. Nd5{ White is a pawn up, has the better structure and is ready to castle.  However, for the moment we are attacking the queen and we are ready to go ... e7 - e5  whenever we want. }( { In the main course, I analyse different moves here for White     A)    }14.Qd2 { , not leaving the queen on the queenside     B)  }14.Qc4 { , the most central square, however, the queen can be attacked afterwards     C)  }14.Qa3 { , not blocking any pieces, but very far offside.    In this Quickstarter, I just want to show Black's main idea: } )
14. Qd2{ A safe square for the queen but obviously blocking White's  c1 -bishop. }
14. e5{ This is our typical counter-strike in this line. }
15. dxe5
15. Nxe5{ White is up a pawn but all of Black's pieces are active. We have nice compensation.     See variation in course  }
