[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Hikaru's Followers e3 & b3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. e3( 4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a safe move to protect the  c4 -pawn. The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    }{ And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure.    A rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
4. g6
5. b3{ Let's start our journey through the  e3 -setups with a white queenside fianchetto. After locking in the  c1 -bishop, this doesn't look like an illogical idea! }( { The following lines have often been reached in games by Hikaru Nakamura who got to this position by playing his infamous   }1.Nf3 { & }-- 2.b3 { move order. I think that is not too surprising.    If you start with a   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 { move order, the move   }5.b3 { doesn't necessarily look like a particularly flexible approach.    }{ However, someone who faces the Schlechter setup via a  1.Nf3  move order - like Hikaru - will often realize that there is objectively just nothing better to do than to grab the center with  d2 - d4  in the next moves and transpose to our lines. } )
5. Bg7{ Following the rule that we go ... Bg7  & ... O-O  against all setups with an early  e2 - e3 . }
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ White stays flexible with the development of the  f1 -bishop but Black can easily equalise with our typical Grünfeld break. }
7. c5{ This is the easiest solution. Black is planning to take on  d4 , creating a pawn weakness on that square.     If White takes on  c5 , the knight on  c3  can become a target for ideas like .... Ne4  or ... Qa5 . }
8. Be2{ This is the most popular move - not that we have many predecessors - and leads to positions that have been reached by different GMs via different move orders. }
8. Nc6{ Taking on  d4  is our typical plan, but ideally, we'll do it if White has to recapture with a pawn. That is why we increase the pressure first. }( { The immediate }8...cxd4 { is also fine but it allows }9.Nxd4 { . } )
9. O-O( 9.dxc5 { is playable for White but if White wants to take the pawn, it is much more useful to do it one move earlier. All the typical moves }9...Qa5 { , }9...Ne4 { , }9...dxc4 { are working well for Black. } )
9. cxd4{ Only now, Black takes. }
10. Nxd4{ Exchanging an additional pair of knights is a double-edged decision. }( { White avoids the pressure after }10.exd4 Bg4 { but in the resulting pawn structure, White usually relies on active piece play in exchange for their slightly vulnerable pawns.  Exchanging minor pieces is in general nothing Black should complain about. } )
10. Nxd4{ Forcing White to move their e-pawn to  d4 . }
11. exd4( 11.Qxd4? Ne4 12.Qd3 { is the only move to keep the  c3 -knight protected. }( { ( }12.Qxg7+ { is fancy but White only gets two minor pieces for the queen: }12...Kxg7 13.Nxe4+ f6-+ { ) } )12...Bf5! { threatens horrible discoveries: ... Nxf2 , ... Ng3 , and mainly ... Nxc3  are in the air. White will simply lose material. }{    For example }13.g4 Nxf2!-+ { . } )
11. b6{ A typical setup. Black makes it harder for White to push  c4 - c5  and simply plans ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  to then start pressurizing White's pawns. }
12. Bf3{ This is one advantage for White after the exchange of knights: The bishop can go to  f3 , pinning the  d5 -pawn. However, this is only a short-term issue. Sooner or later Black will unpin the pawn and be ready to take on  c4 . }
12. Bb7
13. Re1
13. e6{ Taking away all the pressure from the  e7 -pawn and also stabilizing the  d5 -pawn. Black will play something like ... Qd7  to unpin the  d5 -pawn, play ... Rc8 , take on  c4  and just concentrate all the piece power against White's hanging pawns on  c4  and  d4 .    A nice illustration is the model game  Kosic - Velimirovic , where we can see Black's plan in action. }{     See variation in course  }
