9. O-O{ The normal move. }
9. Nd7( { For the moment, Black just develops their pieces naturally.    In the main chapter, we will look at different approaches White can try:     1)  Taking the knight with  Nd2xe4      2)  Going for  Nf3-h4      3)  Trying to trap the bishop with }10.h3 { and  g2-g4  ideas.    Here, let's just quickly show our setup against White's most aggressive idea. } )
10. h3{ These ideas with  h2 - h3  should be taken seriously but usually, we only have to remember the following standard move. }
10. h5{ Stopping all  g4 -ideas. After this, Black can continue with normal development. }
11. a4{ Let's just see a sample line of how Black can build up on the kingside. }
11. e6{ The normal move. Black stabilises  d5  and opens up the way for the queen. }
12. b4{ White just keeps advancing on the queenside. }
12. Ndf6{ Stabilising the  e4 -knight while simply bringing this knight to the kingside as well. }
13. b5
13. g5( { Not forced.    Black can also simply play }13...Re8 { or something similar but these aggressive ideas on the kingside are what make this line so fun to play. }{ We just want to open up the kingside with ... g4 . }{     See variation in course  } )
