4. e3( 4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a safe move to protect the  c4 -pawn. The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    }{ And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure.    A rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
4. g6
5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has its followers. This position can also be reached via   }4.Nbd2 g6 5.e3 { .    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4  followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is obviously a very logical move and the most consistent move across our repertoire, }{ following the rule to fight all  e2 - e3  setups with ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first. } )
6. Be2{ A flexible move. White just develops quickly and can later decide if they want to expand with  b2 - b4  or do something different instead. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Bf5{ If White has nothing concrete against it, I think this setup with ... Bf5  leads to pretty active counterplay. The control over the  b1 - h7  diagonal is often annoying for White as this move also supports ... Ne4 . }( { Against this move, White's most critical try is }8.b4 { . } )( { To stop this, some players on the black side prefer to start with }7...a5 { . However, I don't think it is necessary to spend a tempo on that move.  If White expands on the queenside in this fashion, we will get typical counterplay as in the  6.b4 -lines. } )( { Let me just mention that the moves }7...b6 { or }7...e6 { come to mind to get similar positions to the ones in the  Chinese Recipe chapter  (with the knight on  c3  instead of on  d2 ). The big difference is that against both these moves, White can play }8.b4! { under good circumstances.  The typical counterplay we will see in  this line  is not available. } )
8. b4( { This is the only critical line White can play.    }8.b3 { is a typical move, aiming for a fianchetto. These fianchetto lines are discussed in more detail in  this chapter . } )
8. a5{ Forcing White to clarify the situation. Against White's ideas to expand on the queenside, it is important to strike back! }
9. b5{ Typically, this is the only logical follow-up. }
9. dxc4{ Taking on  c4  (and then  b5 ) is something that we will see more often in the main chapter to create some dynamics on the queenside. }( 9...cxb5 { is a very solid alternative. }10.cxb5 Qd6! { Stopping  Bc1 - a3 . Black shouldn't have too much to worry about here. } )
10. Bxc4
10. cxb5
11. Bxb5
11. Na6{ A nice move. The knight can go to  c7  to attack the  b5 -bishop but it might also jump to  b4  and threaten to invade via the light squares. }{     See variation in course  }
