4. e3( 4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a safe move to protect the  c4 -pawn. The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    }{ And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure.    A rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
4. g6
5. Bd3{ We'll use this move order to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice starts with }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { here. }{ Due to our rule to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about White's move order anyway. } )
5. Bg7
6. O-O( { The moves }6.O-O { and }6.Nc3 { can easily transpose to each other. However, there are some instances where White has some independent ideas.  Especially in the lines where White combines any of these moves with an early  h2-h3 , there are some big differences. }{ Short version:  If White delays castling, we shouldn't go for ... Bf5  because White can exchange and start an attack on the g-file. However, with  Nc3  played instead, Black can create dynamic play with ... dxc4  followed by ... b5  and the knight on  c3  might reduce White's options since the move ... b5 - b4  will come with tempo. } )
6. O-O{ As usual, we just castle first before doing anything else. }
7. h3{ White stops ... Bg4 . }( 7.Nc3 { transposes to the  Champion's Choice . } )
7. Bf5{ This is an old idea in the Schlechter Slav and people used to play it in very different positions and under much worse circumstances.     This here is a good version of the move.  With White already castled, Black doesn't have to worry about any ideas with  g2 - g4  and the move  h3  is overall just so innocuous that White won't be able to create pressure anywhere on the board. }
8. Bxf5( { This is obviously the critical variation. Otherwise, Black can just play   }8...Bxd3 { or }8...e6!? { . } )
8. gxf5{ This structure is very reliable for Black. We create a nice outpost on  e4  and can make use of the g-file with ... Kh8  and ... Rg8 , while White doesn't gain anything concrete in exchange.  The doubled pawns are definitely not weak (Black will play ... e6 ). White can rely on 'general' statements that Black's king should not be totally safe with the open g-file or that doubled pawns are supposed to be less flexible than undoubled pawns, but it is hard to create a plan based on these factors.     Since the structure is so closed, there are dozens of different setups White can choose. The following line should be seen more as a sample variation on how to coordinate the pieces as Black. }
9. cxd5{ Exchanging on  d5  solves the problem of the currently hanging pawn on  c4  but it allows us to develop our  b8 -knight to  c6 . }
9. cxd5{ There is currently really not much dynamism in the center, so Black can be optimistic about creating strong counterplay on the kingside. }
10. Nc3
10. Nc6{ This is usually the best square if available. }
11. Bd2
11. Kh8{ Black's play is pretty straightforward. We just put our pieces where they pressurize White's kingside. This move prepares ... Rg8 . }
12. Ne1{ A typical move for White in this structure. White makes their f-pawn mobile and from  d3 , the knight will control a lot of important squares. }
12. Rg8
13. Nd3
13. e6{ Black just stabilizes their structure. }
14. Ne2{ A typical move to bring this knight to the kingside. }
14. Bf8{ The bishop wasn't doing too much on  g7  anymore. From  d6 , it will be much better placed to put pressure on the kingside. }
15. Rc1
15. Bd6
16. Be1
16. Qf8{ Slowly but surely, Black's army assembles on the kingside. More or less any move that brings Black's pieces closer to the attack, are useful moves.  In this regard, ... Qh6 , ... Ne7 - g6 , ... Rg7 , ... Rag8  all look like logical moves to follow up with. }{     See variation in course  }
