1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. e3( 4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a safe move to protect the  c4 -pawn. The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    }{ And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure.    A rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. h3{ White's main move to get the bishop pair immediately. }
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. Rd1{ This is the main move. White overprotects the  d4 -pawn, this might help if they want to go for  e3 - e4 . But it is also an important move to fight against Black's breaks with ... c5  and ... e5 . }
10. Nbd7{ Typical: Black wants to play ... e6 - e5 . In the best case without allowing  c4xd5 . }
11. Qe2( { This is more reasonable than immediate action with }11.e4 { . }{ White anticipates ... e6 - e5  and avoids all kinds of forks. Nevertheless, the following continuation illustrates how annoying Black's threats to go for the typical pawn breaks can be for White! } )
11. Re8{ The typical setup for Black. }( { Black is ready to go   }12...e5 { now as the in-between move }13.cxd5 { is asking for trouble on the e-file after }13...exd4! { . } )
12. Qc2{ Believe it or not, this is the most popular move in the given position. The queen is still looking for a square where it cannot be harassed. As we have seen, even on  e2  the queen is not totally safe as the e-file does often open up via ... e6 - e5 . }( 12.b3 { or }12.Bd2 { run into }12...e5! { With the threat }-- 13...exd4 { , White has nothing better than to take on  e5 . }13.dxe5 Nxe5 { Black will win back the bishop pair. For example, }14.cxd5 Nxd3 15.Qxd3 Nxd5 16.Nxd5 Qxd5! ( { ( }16...cxd5?! 17.Bc3 { neutralizes the  g7 -bishop.) } )17.Qxd5 cxd5= { with an equal endgame.    If you want to keep more tension, you can also play }12...a6 { or }12...Rc8 { and keep the structure flexible. But from a theoretical point }12...e5 { is enough to equalise. } )
12. Rc8{ A nice move. With the queen on  c2 , it becomes immediately more attractive to go for the ... c6 - c5  break - especially if White destabilizes their structure with  b2 - b3 . }
13. Qb3{ This was played by GM Ivanov and Legend Salo Flohr. However, spending yet another move with the queen doesn't help White if Black soon opens up the center, either with ... c5  or ... e5 . }( 13.b3 { allows all kinds of breaks.     A)  }13...e5 { is pretty straightforward. }14.dxe5 Nxe5 { Black can move the queen next - to  e7 ,  c7  or  e5  - and then play ... dxc4  to weaken White's structure. }{     B)  }13...a6!? { followed by ... c5  is also possible. }{     C)  However, don't play }13...c5?! { when }14.Nb5! { might become annoying. } )
13. Qc7{ Protects  b7  and finishes the development. Now Black will break in the center on the next move. }
14. Bd2
14. c5{ With a decent position for Black in  Ivanov-Furhoff , a model game the Black player won despite being outrated by 250 points! }{     See variation in course  }
