1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. e3( 4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a safe move to protect the  c4 -pawn. The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    }{ And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure.    A rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2{ This variation is one of White's absolute main lines. Sam Shankland, Christof Sielecki and Daniel Barrish all give this move as their recommendation in their white repertoires. }
6. O-O
7. O-O{ In this position, Black has played a lot of different moves. I'll go with the rather rare move 7... b6  in this repertoire.  The reasons why I neglected other, more popular, moves can be found  here . }
7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. Bd2{ This is a pretty non-concrete move. Let's use it to show Black's main setup. }
8. e6{ A strong move. From here on, Black will always be ready to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn and keep the game imbalanced. }
9. Rc1{ This is White's usual follow-up when they play  8.Bd2 . }
9. Bb7{ The next moves are easy: ... Nbd7 , maybe ... Qe7 , but - most importantly - ... c5 ! }
10. b4{ This move is typical but combined with the general innocuous setup White has, Black can just develop normally. }
10. Nbd7{ Black is ready to go ... c5 . }
11. Qb3( { White tries to be smart by putting the queen on the b-file so that }11....c5 { runs into }12.bxc5 { and the bishop on  b7  is a problem. But Black has an easy solution. } )
11. dxc4{ We can just take on  c4  first. }
12. Bxc4
12. c5( { And now we achieved our favourite break. }13.bxc5 { is no longer attractive because of }13...Bxf3 { . }{     See variation in course  } )
