13. Rxa5{ Black is ready to push ... c5 . There is not much White can do to stop it. }( 13...Qxa5? 14.Bd2 { is problematic. White is increasing the pressure on  b4 . Especially }-- 15.a3 { is an annoying threat. } )
14. a3{ The best move according to the engine. White is still trying to pressurize Black's queenside. }( 14.Bd2 c5 { is very ineffective here for White. Obviously, }15.a3 { is not a threat here, as we could just take with }15...Rxa3 { . } )
14. Qd6{ Black has different moves. ... Qd6  stabilizes  b4  and once again prepares ... c5 . }( 14...c5 15.Rb1 { is the engine justification. The pin along the b-file forces }15...Na6 { . After }16.axb4 cxb4 { , we will get a similar position as in our main line, though under slightly worse circumstances. } )
15. Qd2
15. c5( { A good moment to strike back in the center. Let me show you some ideas in the clickables.     A)  }16.Bb2 { is a natural developing move but we can just take on  d4 . After }16...cxd4 { , we can play  ...e5  if White recaptures with a piece, and after }17.exd4 { , we are not even forced to defend the  b4 -pawn passively. Instead, we can go }17...Bf5! { to exchange White's dominant bishop. After }18.Bxf5 Rxf5 19.axb4 { , we will win the pawn back with }19...Nc6 { , }{ followed by ... Rb5  and ... Rfb8  . } )( {  B)  }16.Rb1 { is another move. After }16...Na6 { , we have to protect the  b4 -pawn. Typical is the pawn structure after }17.axb4 cxb4⇆ { . White has the extra pawn in the center, we the passed pawn on the b-file. In the next moves, we should give it support with ... Be6  and ... Rb8 . We should regroup our knight from  a6  - A route via  c7  to land on  d5  or  b5  looks logical - and we should always watch out for a good moment to break with ... e5  to include our bishop in the game and break White's restricting pawn structure. }{     See variation in course  } )
