[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "g3 Sidelines: 7.Nc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. g3( { You will see that I cover the  g3 -lines in quite some detail despite }4.g3 { not being one of the most popular moves in the database. There are two main reasons for that:     1)  You won't encounter the following lines only via the Slav move order but they can also be reached with other first moves. You can reach this position via the Reti   }1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 { , the English   }1.c4 c6 2.g3 { , maybe even against   }1.d4 { players who like to postpone pushing their c-pawn and play }1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . So overall, you can play our lines even against many flexible White players!     2)  The second reason is that we have to share the theory of these lines with many King's Indian and Grünfeld players, which are in their nature much more theoretical openings than our Grünfeld Slav. For example after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 { , the move }3.g3 { became increasingly popular on all levels and I don't expect the trend to stop anytime soon. It is often considered one of White's easiest setups and when you look at the lines with modern engines, you get the feeling that 90 % of the variations Black players used to play against this move, lead to really good positions for White if they know what they are doing.    There are not many setups the engines like. However, on the top of the list is }3...c6 { , followed by }-- 4...d5 { - transposing to our setup - and it became pretty much the main setup for KID and GID players against the fianchetto. On one hand, this means that you can have a lot of trust in the objective value of the following positions. On the other hand, it means that this is pretty much the most theoretical position in the whole course!    }{ Nevertheless, don't be discouraged: As an author, I felt obliged to give a very comprehensive view of White's tries, but as a player, a lot of this information is more of a 'nice to know'. This is certainly not one of the chapters where you risk being much worse if you develop naturally.      Rule for the  g3 -chapters: You start with 4... g6 , 5... Bg7 , 6... O-O  against everything.  } )
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O{ In the main chapters, we will discuss move orders where White postpones casting wherever necessary, but usually this here can be seen as the main tabiya of the  g3 -variations. Both sides made their most flexible moves without committing to anything. However, now is the time when White has to decide what to do with the  c4 -pawn. }
7. Nc3{ Even though I recommend kingside development first against the fianchetto setups, this doesn't mean that White can leave the  c4 -pawn hanging infinitely! On move 7, White should typically make sure that the pawn is no longer hanging. }( 7.Nc3 { is the most popular move on Lichess but not even top-4 in the master's database. That is not surprising: This move is a pawn sacrifice and White typically struggles a little bit to win it back. } )
7. dxc4{ Black can just take the pawn! It's White's job to prove that they have enough compensation. }
8. Ne5{ An attempt to regain the pawn on  c4  immediately. However, I couldn't find any strong player who has played this move more than once.  Black has very VERY convincing antidotes. }
8. Ng4{ This is a very clever move to keep the pawn. If White takes on  c4 , they'll lose the  d4 -pawn. And exchanging the knights is certainly also not in White's interest. }( 8...Be6 { is also good. } )
9. Nxg4{ One of White's main moves, but things feel already wrong. The exchange of knights is certainly in Black's favour who is a pawn up. }
9. Bxg4{ Now, the  d4 -pawn is hanging which limits White's options. }
10. d5{ This active move makes it at least possible for White to create counterplay. }( 10.h3 { also has been played a few times but Black just stabilizes with }10...Be6 { . }{  d4  is still hanging and Black will just develop with ... Qd7 , ... Na6  , ... Rfd8 . } )
10. Qc8{ A nice move which makes it very hard for White to regain the pawn. }
11. Bg5
11. Re8{ Black is ready to go ... Bh3  to exchange White's light-squared bishop. But Black's main trump is obviously the extra pawn! }{     See variation in course  }
