4. g3( { You will see that I cover the  g3 -lines in quite some detail despite }4.g3 { not being one of the most popular moves in the database. There are two main reasons for that:     1)  You won't encounter the following lines only via the Slav move order but they can also be reached with other first moves. You can reach this position via the Reti   }1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 { , the English   }1.c4 c6 2.g3 { , maybe even against   }1.d4 { players who like to postpone pushing their c-pawn and play }1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . So overall, you can play our lines even against many flexible White players!     2)  The second reason is that we have to share the theory of these lines with many King's Indian and Grünfeld players, which are in their nature much more theoretical openings than our Grünfeld Slav. For example after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 { , the move }3.g3 { became increasingly popular on all levels and I don't expect the trend to stop anytime soon. It is often considered one of White's easiest setups and when you look at the lines with modern engines, you get the feeling that 90 % of the variations Black players used to play against this move, lead to really good positions for White if they know what they are doing.    There are not many setups the engines like. However, on the top of the list is }3...c6 { , followed by }-- 4...d5 { - transposing to our setup - and it became pretty much the main setup for KID and GID players against the fianchetto. On one hand, this means that you can have a lot of trust in the objective value of the following positions. On the other hand, it means that this is pretty much the most theoretical position in the whole course!    }{ Nevertheless, don't be discouraged: As an author, I felt obliged to give a very comprehensive view of White's tries, but as a player, a lot of this information is more of a 'nice to know'. This is certainly not one of the chapters where you risk being much worse if you develop naturally.      Rule for the  g3 -chapters: You start with 4... g6 , 5... Bg7 , 6... O-O  against everything.  } )
4. g6
5. cxd5{ The Exchange variation can even be played in the  g3  setups. Even though these symmetrical positions can generally be seen as a little bit drawish, I think I found some nice lines to create imbalances for Black.     As you will see, there are different plans on how to create active play in these positions and - from an objective point of view -, we can be very happy that our knight has the  c6 -square.    Arguably the main idea to create imbalances in this line is by playing  Nf3 - e5 /... Nf6 - e4  and taking on  c6 / c3  to change the pawn structure.     One side creates a potentially weak pawn in the opponent's camp, the other side gets more influence in the center.    Luckily for us, practice has shown that the resulting positions are equally playable for both sides, so we can either play this manoeuvre ourselves, or just welcome our opponent to take our knight on  c6  if they put their knight on  e5 !    Because of this, most of the time, you can just follow up in autopilot mode with ... Nc6  and ... Bf5 . }
5. cxd5
6. Bg2( { White cannot really play without this move. White can also start with }6.Nc3 { or }6.Ne5 { but  Bg2  will be part of White's setup anyways.  With Black, }{ we just continue with   }6...Bg7 { and }-- 7...O-O { against all moves. } )
6. Bg7{ Our set-up in this line is very easy. We play ... O-O , ... Nc6  and ... Bf5  - usually in this move order.  The main approach for White is to play  Nf3 - e5  and take on  c6 . This creates an obvious imbalance in the pawn structure. But we'll also look at the lines where White keeps the structure symmetrical. }
7. O-O( { We will have this as main move order for White even though most of the positions could also be reached via }7.Nc3 { . }7.Ne5 O-O { has no independent meaning. } )
7. O-O{ Castling, ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 ! That is the typical setup. }
8. Nc3
8. Nc6{ We are still following our development scheme. This position can be seen as the main tabiya for the  c4xd5  approach within the Fianchetto universe. }
9. Bf4( { If White wants to play without  Nf3-e5 , this is the most popular move.    }9.Bg5 { doesn't make nearly as much sense as }9...Ne4! { is more or less just the win of a tempo. } )
9. Bf5{ Following our general setup. }
10. Rc1( { Besides }10.Ne5 { , which leads to a position like the next trainable, this is the only move that has been played quite a number of times. }{ On amateur level, this move is even more popular than the knight move to  e5 . } )
10. Qb6{ Becoming active on the queenside. }
11. Na4
11. Qa6{ A reasonably active square for the queen, looking at the a-file and towards  e2 . Not the most exciting position in the world but easy equality with all pieces on the board.    We have many ways to make progress from here: Using the outpost on  e4  (with knight or bishop) ... h6  & ... g5 , centralising the rooks. }( 11...Qb5 { is also a typical square but here White can play }12.Rc5 { with tempo. }{     See variation in course  } )
