7. Qb6{ This is the main move and I think for a reason! Offering a queen trade does not look like a particularly ambitious option and White risks a worse position if they fall into the trap of simplifying too early.     Besides this 'trap', Black is preparing ... Rd8  (which might also look like a somewhat mysterious move), but one of the ideas is that it allows Black to recapture on  d5  with pieces instead of the  c6 -pawn, avoiding a symmetrical position. }
8. Nc3( { This is White's logical follow-up, using the fact that this active square is available for the knight without any pawn sacrifices. }8.Rd1 Rd8 9.Nc3 { transposes to the main line. } )
8. Rd8{ It makes sense to keep an eye on the  d5 -pawn. White had no direct threat, but this move keeps the tension and doesn't allow White to play  9.Qxb6  and  10.cxd5  with a symmetrical pawn structure longer than absolutely necessary. Black is ready to recapture on  d5  twice with pieces.  In this position, White players played a lot of different moves. One of the reasons why this variation is so popular at the highest level is the existence of many hidden subtleties in different move orders that make it hard for Black to play the next moves on autopilot.  I will give you different ideas on how to play the resulting positions. Guidelines for this repertoire:  - We want to provoke  c4 - c5  in many positions     - often we achieve this by playing ... Be6 . Once we have achieved this goal, the structure is much more defined and the tension in the center is reduced. Black's typical source of counterplay in the resulting structure is the plan to go ... e7 - e5 .     - Besides ... e5 , Black has no clear pawn breaks that are advantageous for him. In closed positions without pawn breaks, we have two ways to improve our position:      1)  Bringing our pieces to better squares.     2)  Winning space with our pawns. If the queens come off, we should keep the plan in mind to expand with our pawns on the kingside. The strength of this plan can be seen in the model game Osmak vs Muzychuk -  see here . }
9. Qxb6{ Even with  8.Nc3  and ... Rd8  included, this is not advisable for White. }
9. axb6
10. cxd5
10. Nxd5
11. Nxd5
11. Rxd5{ This is the idea of 8... Rd8 . The resulting position is known to be slightly better for Black. A young MVL showed some nice manoeuvres from this position. }
12. Rd1{ Against other moves plays Black in the same way. }
12. Be6
13. a3
13. Rb5{ White's queenside is under quite some pressure. }{     See variation in course  }
