1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. g3( { You will see that I cover the  g3 -lines in quite some detail despite }4.g3 { not being one of the most popular moves in the database. There are two main reasons for that:     1)  You won't encounter the following lines only via the Slav move order but they can also be reached with other first moves. You can reach this position via the Reti   }1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 { , the English   }1.c4 c6 2.g3 { , maybe even against   }1.d4 { players who like to postpone pushing their c-pawn and play }1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . So overall, you can play our lines even against many flexible White players!     2)  The second reason is that we have to share the theory of these lines with many King's Indian and Grünfeld players, which are in their nature much more theoretical openings than our Grünfeld Slav. For example after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 { , the move }3.g3 { became increasingly popular on all levels and I don't expect the trend to stop anytime soon. It is often considered one of White's easiest setups and when you look at the lines with modern engines, you get the feeling that 90 % of the variations Black players used to play against this move, lead to really good positions for White if they know what they are doing.    There are not many setups the engines like. However, on the top of the list is }3...c6 { , followed by }-- 4...d5 { - transposing to our setup - and it became pretty much the main setup for KID and GID players against the fianchetto. On one hand, this means that you can have a lot of trust in the objective value of the following positions. On the other hand, it means that this is pretty much the most theoretical position in the whole course!    }{ Nevertheless, don't be discouraged: As an author, I felt obliged to give a very comprehensive view of White's tries, but as a player, a lot of this information is more of a 'nice to know'. This is certainly not one of the chapters where you risk being much worse if you develop naturally.      Rule for the  g3 -chapters: You start with 4... g6 , 5... Bg7 , 6... O-O  against everything.  } )
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O{ In the main chapters, we will discuss move orders where White postpones casting wherever necessary, but usually this here can be seen as the main tabiya of the  g3 -variations. Both sides made their most flexible moves without committing to anything. However, now is the time when White has to decide what to do with the  c4 -pawn. }
7. Qb3{ Even in the  g3 -variations, the move  Qb3  is a main option for White. White protects the pawn on  c4  - so they will be able to develop their  b1 -knight to  c3  - and puts the typical pressure on the  b7  and  d5 -pawns. }
7. Qb6{ This is the main move and I think for a reason! Offering a queen trade does not look like a particularly ambitious option and White risks a worse position if they fall into the trap of simplifying too early.     Besides this 'trap', Black is preparing ... Rd8  (which might also look like a somewhat mysterious move), but one of the ideas is that it allows Black to recapture on  d5  with pieces instead of the  c6 -pawn, avoiding a symmetrical position. }
8. Nc3( { This is White's logical follow-up, using the fact that this active square is available for the knight without any pawn sacrifices. }8.Rd1 Rd8 9.Nc3 { transposes to the main line. } )
8. Rd8{ It makes sense to keep an eye on the  d5 -pawn. White had no direct threat, but this move keeps the tension and doesn't allow White to play  9.Qxb6  and  10.cxd5  with a symmetrical pawn structure longer than absolutely necessary. Black is ready to recapture on  d5  twice with pieces.  In this position, White players played a lot of different moves. One of the reasons why this variation is so popular at the highest level is the existence of many hidden subtleties in different move orders that make it hard for Black to play the next moves on autopilot.  I will give you different ideas on how to play the resulting positions. Guidelines for this repertoire:  - We want to provoke  c4 - c5  in many positions     - often we achieve this by playing ... Be6 . Once we have achieved this goal, the structure is much more defined and the tension in the center is reduced. Black's typical source of counterplay in the resulting structure is the plan to go ... e7 - e5 .     - Besides ... e5 , Black has no clear pawn breaks that are advantageous for him. In closed positions without pawn breaks, we have two ways to improve our position:      1)  Bringing our pieces to better squares.     2)  Winning space with our pawns. If the queens come off, we should keep the plan in mind to expand with our pawns on the kingside. The strength of this plan can be seen in the model game Osmak vs Muzychuk -  see here . }
9. Rd1{ This is White's main move. White simply strengthens their d-pawn. }
9. Be6( { This is a sideline but White players failed to show anything against it. Most players go for }10.c5 { , but this is hardly threatening. } )( 9...Bf5 { is the main line. Black is threatening  ...Qxb3  and  ...Bc2 , so White usually goes for }10.Ne1 { . }{ Here, Black can go for the same plan (just with the knight on  e1  instead of on  f3 ) by playing }10...Be6 { . }{ The plans remain very similar. Overall, the knight looks more passive on  e1  but if it jumps to  d3  and potentially  c5 , things might not be so clear. } )
10. c5{ The most popular move. Even though I don't think that it is particularly critical. }
10. Qxb3( { This is the normal reaction. In some positions, it is possible to keep the queens on with }10...Qa6?! { , but 'playable' is the best-case scenario and often it is just asking for trouble, like here with }11.Bf1! { . } )
11. axb3
11. Nbd7( { A typical move is }11...Na6 { to control the  b4 -square and block the a-file. However, I don't think that we need the knight here and we can instead develop our pieces towards the center and the kingside where we want to start our counterplay. } )
12. b4
12. a6{ The queenside play has stopped for now. In the next moves, we will start our counterplay on the other side of the board. The typical ways to do this are by either preparing ... e7 - e5  or by winning more space with our kingside pawns. }( { A typical way how the game could continue is }13.h3 h6 14.g4 g5 { . So far, both sides have tried their best to win as much space as possible with their pawns. In the next moves, Black coordinates the pieces on the kingside and once their pieces are ideally placed, they will look for the most promising pawn break on the kingside. }15.Nh2 Nf8 16.Nf1 N6h7 17.Ng3 Ng6 18.f3 Nh4 19.Be3 Nf8 20.Na4 f5! { and Black took over the initiative in  Kolehmainen, K. - Delgado Ramirez, N., ICCF email 2019 . }{     See variation in course  } )
