1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3{ Most chapters will begin with this move order. Against the Grünfeld Slav, the  f3 -square is clearly the best square for the knight so this is White's most flexible move order. }
3. Nf6
4. g3( { You will see that I cover the  g3 -lines in quite some detail despite }4.g3 { not being one of the most popular moves in the database. There are two main reasons for that:     1)  You won't encounter the following lines only via the Slav move order but they can also be reached with other first moves. You can reach this position via the Reti   }1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 { , the English   }1.c4 c6 2.g3 { , maybe even against   }1.d4 { players who like to postpone pushing their c-pawn and play }1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . So overall, you can play our lines even against many flexible White players!     2)  The second reason is that we have to share the theory of these lines with many King's Indian and Grünfeld players, which are in their nature much more theoretical openings than our Grünfeld Slav. For example after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 { , the move }3.g3 { became increasingly popular on all levels and I don't expect the trend to stop anytime soon. It is often considered one of White's easiest setups and when you look at the lines with modern engines, you get the feeling that 90 % of the variations Black players used to play against this move, lead to really good positions for White if they know what they are doing.    There are not many setups the engines like. However, on the top of the list is }3...c6 { , followed by }-- 4...d5 { - transposing to our setup - and it became pretty much the main setup for KID and GID players against the fianchetto. On one hand, this means that you can have a lot of trust in the objective value of the following positions. On the other hand, it means that this is pretty much the most theoretical position in the whole course!    }{ Nevertheless, don't be discouraged: As an author, I felt obliged to give a very comprehensive view of White's tries, but as a player, a lot of this information is more of a 'nice to know'. This is certainly not one of the chapters where you risk being much worse if you develop naturally.      Rule for the  g3 -chapters: You start with 4... g6 , 5... Bg7 , 6... O-O  against everything.  } )
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O{ In the main chapters, we will discuss move orders where White postpones casting wherever necessary, but usually this here can be seen as the main tabiya of the  g3 -variations. Both sides made their most flexible moves without committing to anything. However, now is the time when White has to decide what to do with the  c4 -pawn. }
7. Nbd2( { We will discuss this move and }7.b3 { in the same  main chapter . In my opinion, th knight move is just less flexible than starting with }7.b3 { . }{ In those lines, White is often happy to have the knight on  b1 , for example, to stop Black's a-pawn with  Nb1 - c3 . }{ After }7.Nbd2 { , White has some independent options but they really cannot convince. } )
7. a5( { This will transpose in most cases to  the lines  after   }7.b3 { . } )
8. e3{ This slow move stabilizing the center has been played by some Grandmasters. I guess you can claim that there is no big idea behind the move itself.  However, the fact that White hasn't developed their queenside yet (and it won't become easier once Black has pushed ... a4 ) is often a sign that White wants to ignore the queenside altogether in the next few moves and build up their position on the kingside to its maximum instead.     Typical follow-ups for White in this regard are  Ne5  and  f2 - f4 . If provoked, White might even expand further with  g2 - g4 . This is the reason why I don't recommend ... Bf5  against this sideline - White might be happy to see it if they have aggressive kingside intentions. }( { The immediate }8.Ne5 { is sometimes played with similar intentions. However, this is even less flexible. Both }8...Nbd7 { as well as }8...a4 { followed by }-- 9...Nbd7 { are very much in the spirit of our setup. } )
8. a4{ For now, there is no reason why we should stop our plan of expanding on the queenside. }
9. Ne5{ A logical follow-up of White's last move but not very flexible. }
9. Nbd7{ This is a simple solution. }( {   }10...Nxe5 11.dxe5 Ng4 { is a legitimate threat and exchanging the knights on  d7  would be horrible after the precious time that White used to bring the knight to the 'active'  e5 -square. } )
10. Nd3( { This is White's best move but Black is already better. }10.f4?! { was once played by Mamedyarov in a blitz game. A nice moment to point out that White's setup is made for a slow build-up, not for a dynamic fight with an open center.    In this regard, }10...c5! { is a nice reminder that we are always looking for good moments to play these Grünfeld motifs. } )
10. Nb6{ A strong move. Black puts pressure on the  c4 -pawn and White has no good way to solve the tension. }( { Maybe }11.cxd5 cxd5 { is the best way to handle the damage control but that looks like an Exchange variation gone wrong. } )
11. c5
11. Bf5{ Developing the bishop and attacking the knight. We will play 12... Nbd7  on the next move and all our pieces are on good squares while White struggles with a very passive queenside coordination. Note that the bishop will now be pretty safe on  f5  because there is no knight on  e5  that could potentially support  g3 - g4 . }{     See variation in course  }
