1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3{ As mentioned in the Introduction, there was a time when anything besides a quick  c2 - c4  was seen as highly innocuous by many players. I can imagine that many of these purists might go one step further and even see the move  2.Nc3  as some kind of insult. }( { By blocking the c-pawn, White voluntarily gives one of the two pawn breaks in the center away and the second one -  e2-e4  - is much harder to accomplish. There is no queen behind the e-pawn to support it and while  f2-f3  is a typical idea in these Veresov lines, it is also much more weakening than for example, in the mirrored structures after   }1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 { the move }c3 { . } )( { With the increasing popularity of the 'Jobava London' with   }3.Bf4 { , all these 'abstract' arguments became much less important, even though you still see players who describe the move  2.Nc3  as 'anti-positional' once in a while. } )
2. Nf6{ The most natural move. We simply develop and stop  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bg5( { Before the Jobava London }3.Bf4 { became popular, }3.Bg5 { was the move White players typically chose on move 3 if they played the Veresov. It was never particularly popular, but was still played once in a while as a surprise weapon. }{ White plays with the idea to take on  f6  to spoil Black's structure and is often ready to castle long quite early to get a sharp position. }( { Getting in a quick  e2-e4  - sometimes by means of a pawn sacrifice - is an idea that is often seen.  When I was young, I learned that   }3...Nbd7 { was Black's best move to stop the doubled pawns on the f-file while also not allowing  e2-e4 . These days, theory figured out that   }4.Bxf6 { is not even something to be afraid of if it creates the doubled pawns. Even provoking this with   }3...h6 { is now a respectable answer. I haven't seen  3.Bg5  in a while and I have the feeling, it went pretty much extinct (at least that is my impression). }3...Nbd7 { might still be objectively the best move but it is also the most theoretical one.  As this line is so rare these days, I will go with something more practical for the very few instances that you'll ever meet this line. } ) )
3. c6{ This is one of Black's easier responses. In lines where White plays  Bxf6  , it is usually a good setup for Black to play ... exf6  and then go for control of the light squares with ... f5 , ... g6 , ... c6 . }( { As Black is often provoking this these days by spending a tempo on }3...h6 { ,  4.Bxf6  is even more unattractive when Black plays a move that's part of this typical setup instead of the tempo loss!    Besides that, Black is also preparing ... Qb6 , since White has no ideal moves to protect  b2 . ... Qa5  and ... b5  might also come in quite handy if White goes for long-castling. }{    Overall, I think }3...c6 { takes away a lot of fun ideas White usually hopes for in this variation. } )
4. Bxf6( { This exchange is not even particularly threatening if Black spends a tempo provoking it with   }3...h6 { . Here, this is pretty much just a gifted bishop pair. } )
4. exf6{ The easy way to recapture. Our kingside structure stays intact and we might get some activity along the e-file. }
5. e3( { On titled player level pretty much exclusively played. }5.e4 { was often seen on amateur level, but the opening of the center should just benefit Black. Something like }5...dxe4 6.Nxe4 f5⩱ { is certainly very good for Black.      }5...Qb6!? { might also be strong to throw White off balance. } )
5. f5{ Black's next moves are always the same: ... g6 , ... Bd6 , ... Nd7 , ... O-O  and only then do we think about our following plans.  Potentially, we can expand on both sides of the board. A sample line: }
6. Bd3
6. g6
7. Nf3
7. Nd7
8. O-O
8. Bd6{ We just follow our standard setup. }
9. Ne2{ A typical move. Without any action in the center, White has to prepare  c2 - c4  to get any open files. }
9. O-O{ Black has good development, the two bishops and nice control over the center. If White does nothing forcing, we can just step by step improve our pieces.  ... Nf6 , ... Qe7 , ... Kg7 , maybe ... b6 , ... Bb7  look like normal moves to slowly improve the pieces. Besides that, we can consider expanding with either ... h5  on the kingside or ... a5 - a4  on the queenside. }
10. c4
10. dxc4{ The standard reply to remember. We have no intention to let White give us an IQP on  d5 . }( { After }11.Bxc4 { , we can already consider }11...b5!? { to start an expansion on the queenside but also to prepare ... Bb7  and potentially ... c5 . With our bishops, we have every reason to play aggressively in the center to open up files! }{     See variation in course  } )
