2. Nf6{ The most natural move. We simply develop and stop  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bf4{ This is the modern Jobava-London. White often plays these lines very aggressively. }
3. e6( { The same move that we play against the normal London but here it is connected to different ideas. If we can, we would like to continue with   }4...Bb4 { and }-- ...c5 { when we pretty much play a French Winawer (   }1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.e5 c5 { ) without the space disadvantage! } )
4. Nb5{ This move is the clear mainline nowadays. White stops the pin with ... Bb4 . }
4. Bb4+{ This check looks slightly random but the bishop won't be that bad on  a5 .     In the future, the bishop can go to  c7  where it opposes White's  f4 -bishop, prepares ... e5  and can even become an attacking piece if White cannot exchange it! By provoking  c2 - c3 , White will be forced to retreat with the knight to  a3  where it usually goes the whole way back to  b1  to get developed to the 'normal London square'  d2 . Nevertheless, this is so slow that it shouldn't really worry us. }( 4...Na6 { is the main alternative to protect  c7 . Here, there are also a lot of new territories to explore. As White's knight has the option to return to  c3  later - instead of  a3  - and with Black's knight stuck on the queenside for a while, White has time to build up on the kingside. }{    For example after }5.e3 Be7 { White can play the immediate }6.h4!? { or }6.g4!? { but even a slow build-up on the kingside with  Ng1 - f3 - e5 ,  Bf1 - d3 ,  Qf3  can become dangerous. Nothing horrible but I think the bishop check is easier. } )
5. c3
5. Ba5{ This was the idea. The bishop protects  c7 . }
6. e3{ This is White's most popular move - simple development. }
6. a6{ It is usually a good idea to kick the knight back to  a3  as fast as possible. }( 6...O-O { is also possible but for example }6...Qe7?! 7.a4! { is already very annoying. }7...a6 8.b4 Bxb4 9.Nxc7+  )
7. Na3{ Now, White's knight is pretty misplaced and it usually even retreats to  b1 , as  c2  is also a square without future. }
7. O-O( { A flexible move even though we can also start with }7...Qe7 { . The threat of }-- 8...Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 Qxa3 { usually provokes }8.Nb1 { . } )
8. Nf3{ The most natural move, even though putting this knight here allows the following ... Nh5 . }
8. Qe7( { With the threat   }9...Bxc3+ { . }{ This move usually provokes  Na3 - b1  and the inclusion of ... Qe7  and  Nb1  is usually a good thing for Black. } )
9. Nb1
9. Nh5{ Going for the bishop pair. }
10. Bg5( {  A)  }10.Be5 f6 11.Bg3 { gives Black plenty of good options. We can play }11...Nxg3 { but we can also play it safe with }11...g6 { . } )( {  B)  }10.Bg3?! { is even worse as Black's kingside is more stable after }10...Nxg3 11.hxg3 { . Now, }11...g6 { secures the kingside and after that, we can play for ... e5  or ... c5 . } )
10. f6
11. Bh4
11. g5{ Once again we use aggressive means to win the bishop pair. }
12. g4{ This was played in the Correspondence game Cirulis - Nichols, 2021. But this kind of exchange shouldn't frighten Black. }( {  A)  The natural }12.Bg3 { allows Black dynamic counterplay in the center. }12...Nc6 { preparing  ...e5 . }13.Nbd2 g4 { is not the only move, but misplacing the knight first is a typical idea. }14.Nh4 { and here we can go for immediate action with }14...e5!? { , but it is also possible to start with the more flexible }14...f5 { that protects  g4  and still allows ... e5  but also ... f4  in the future. } )( {  B)  }12.Nfd2 { doesn't achieve anything. }12...Ng7 13.Bg3 Nc6!⩱ { . Black is getting ready for ... e5 . } )
12. gxh4
13. gxh5
