1. c4
1. c6
2. e4( { As I promised in the introduction, you can also aim for the Schlechter Slav against   }1.Nf3 { and }1.c4 { . In most cases, White will sooner or later put their d-pawn on  d4  and transpose to variations of other chapters. Nevertheless, we can't force our opponent to move the d-pawn two squares forward! In many cases, Black will still get positions very similar to the Schlechter Slav.    The biggest exception will be discussed here: Even though we as Slav players should do our best to get a pawn to  d5  as quickly as possible - and I, therefore, recommend }1...c6 { against  1.c4  - White has the opportunity to put their e-pawn in the center undisturbed with }2.e4 { .    This leads to a position mostly achieved via the Caro-Kann Defense in the  1.e4  cosmos   }1.e4 c6 2.c4 { .    }{ Tendentially, few English players have any interest in crossing over into these waters - especially since even  1.e4  players have mostly lost their interest in this variation by now. Neither engines nor statistics are particularly impressed, and Black players now have several reliable setups that have withstood the test of time }{ (and engines) }{ .    So this is definitely nothing that should stop us from playing the Slav against  1.c4 . } )
2. d5
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. exd5( { Very typical for the whole variation is that White gets an isolani on the d-file, since their c- and e-pawns are exchanged early. Next, we will talk about   }3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { , after which the IQP is still very likely, but the pawn structure is a bit more flexible.    Here, we talk about capturing twice on  d5 . }{ Why should White play 4.exd5 when the other option is more flexible? In principle, there are two reasons:    - White hopes to keep the  d5 -pawn on the board.    - White hopes that holding back  d2 - d4  will give them additional options. It is typical for the side with the IQP to try to compensate for the pawn weakness through active, often concrete play. And although the move  d2 - d4  fits the general development scheme, White is sometimes quite happy to have saved this move in order to be able to put direct pressure on the black position with raiding attacks like  Bc4  &  Qb3  or  Bb5 +,  Qa4 ,  Ne5 .     Important:  We do not play }{   }4...Qxd5? { because this would only allow White to gain some tempi in the opening. Instead, we play }4...Nf6! { in order to be able to take with the knight on  d5 . If White wants to keep the pawn on  d5 , they should then play }5.Bb5+ { or }5.Qa4+ { to force a black piece to  d7 . Especially after the queen's check, White has countless attempts to cling to the pawn on  d5 , though Black should not have major problems with the pawn in any variation. } )
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place their pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn (IQP) position. } )
5. Nc3{ If White wants to develop naturally instead of going for the defence of the  d5 -pawn, this is the most flexible move. }( { Other moves like }5.Nf3 Nxd5 { should just transpose. } )
5. Nxd5{ Some players like to delay the capture on  d5  to not allow any tempo moves against the  d5 -knight before Black is fully developed. Against the main line Panov - where White has spent a tempo on  d2 - d4  - this works pretty well, but here, White could use this tempo for more concrete ideas to hold on to the  d5 -pawn. }( 5...g6 6.Bc4 Bg7 7.Nf3 O-O 8.Qb3 { is the kind of position to illustrate the point. I am not even 100 % sure if this is the most critical move order, but Black has some problems winning the  d5 -pawn and I am not convinced that Black can really solve all opening problems here. } )
6. Nf3( { The main move, as it is the most flexible one. White cannot really play without it. }6.d4 { transposes to the Panov main line-  see here . } )
6. Nc6{ I chose this for our repertoire because it is the most flexible developing move. }( { I considered }6...g6!? { , as it is also a move that could lead to a position with similarities to other variations from our repertoire. However, I decided against it, because White's main attempts against it can become extremely concrete. }7.Qb3 Nb6 8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Ne5!? { is the main response, but there are also alternatives along the way. I think, in this chapter, we have already seen enough very concrete stuff! } )( { After }6...Nc6 { , there are two independent tries.     1)  The main move is }7.Bb5 { .     2)  A rarer guest is }7.Bc4 { .    The move }7.d4 { would transpose to our main line  Panov chapter . } )
7. Bb5{ White tries to put some pressure on  c6 . Moves like  Qa4  or  Ne5  are very typical to follow it up. These days, there are different good moves that are considered to be very decent for Black. }
7. g6{ A relatively rare move but still approved by many GMs who played it. Black claims that the bishop on  g7  will be very nicely placed - either it attacks White's d-pawn after  d2 - d4  or it simply controls the long diagonal - and doesn't care about White's idea to put pressure on  c6 . }
8. Qa4{ This is White's typical follow-up. Increasing the pressure against  c6  is the most principled move after  7.Bb5 . }( 8.Ne5 { is a less ideal version to put pressure on  c6 . After }8...Qd6 { , the counter-threat against  e5  allows Black to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  very soon, which will resolve all the pressure against  c6 . } )
8. Qd6( { Black can also go for the pawn sacrifice }8...Nb6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { . With the bishop pair in a pretty open position and the lead in development, this gives Black great practical compensation. } )( { However, I think Black just equalises with absolutely no problems after }8...Qd6 { and the number of lines to remember should also be smaller. } )
9. O-O
9. Bg7{ Black is ready to castle and this usually solves all our problems - if we ever had any. }
10. Re1{ Not an important theoretical move but let's just use it to explain some pretty important aspects of this kind of position and why Black is never afraid if White goes for the  e7 -pawn with their underdeveloped setup. }
10. O-O{ We can just develop naturally. }( 10...Bd7 { is also possible when White usually switches to the }11.Qh4 { plan. }{ The bishop on  d7  is usually most actively placed on  f5  against this approach. } )
11. Nxd5{ This is winning a pawn for White but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid. }( {  A)  Interestingly enough, }11.d4?! { is already a positional mistake. White can no longer go for the  Qh4 -plan and after the strong }11...Bd7! { , White cannot even spoil Black's pawn structure anymore with }12.Bxc6 { . White will just suffer in the resulting middlegame because of the long-term weakness of the  d4 -pawn. } )( {  B)  }11.Bxc6 bxc6 { leads to a typical situation. Both sides have one pawn weakness - White on the d-file, Black on  c6  - but Black has the bishop pair. This alone should be reason enough, why we don't have any problems. Black can just develop with ... Bf5 , put the rooks on the b- and d-file, and has a nice position.  Also an important idea is ... c5  to trade off the two weaknesses.     In the resulting positions, Black is often better, because the bishops will be extremely happy about the fact that the center is now open. } )
11. Qxd5
12. Bxc6{ The principled follow-up. }
12. bxc6{ It is typical to keep the queens on the board. }( { Nevertheless, Black would also have compensation after }12...Qxc6 13.Qxc6 bxc6 14.Rxe7 { . Something like }14...Be6 { to attack  a2  and possibly go ... Bd5 , followed by ... a5 - a4 , ... Rfb8  looks like great compensation in the endgame. } )
13. Rxe7
13. Bf5{ This is one natural way to play for compensation. Black just develops and cuts through the light squares.  ... Be4  looks like a nice potential follow-up. But let's just mention that Black does also have other ways to prove compensation. }( {  A)  }13...c5 { is a good move to keep White restricted by controlling the  d4 -square. (The control over  b4  might also be useful though.) } )( {  B)  }13...a5 { is a typical move to win space on the queenside. Black might continue with developing the light-squared bishop, followed by ... Rfb8 , ... Rb4  and a lot of pressure on the queenside. } )( {  C)  Even }13...g5!? 14.d3 g4 { is approved by the engine. Black misplaces the  f3 -knight and with the lack of development, White has no convincing way to punish Black for this kingside weakness.  So let's just summarize that there are usually all kinds of ways to justify sacrificing the  e7 -pawn - even if is not this exact position. }{     See variation in course  } )
