1. c4
1. c6
2. e4( { As I promised in the introduction, you can also aim for the Schlechter Slav against   }1.Nf3 { and }1.c4 { . In most cases, White will sooner or later put their d-pawn on  d4  and transpose to variations of other chapters. Nevertheless, we can't force our opponent to move the d-pawn two squares forward! In many cases, Black will still get positions very similar to the Schlechter Slav.    The biggest exception will be discussed here: Even though we as Slav players should do our best to get a pawn to  d5  as quickly as possible - and I, therefore, recommend }1...c6 { against  1.c4  - White has the opportunity to put their e-pawn in the center undisturbed with }2.e4 { .    This leads to a position mostly achieved via the Caro-Kann Defense in the  1.e4  cosmos   }1.e4 c6 2.c4 { .    }{ Tendentially, few English players have any interest in crossing over into these waters - especially since even  1.e4  players have mostly lost their interest in this variation by now. Neither engines nor statistics are particularly impressed, and Black players now have several reliable setups that have withstood the test of time }{ (and engines) }{ .    So this is definitely nothing that should stop us from playing the Slav against  1.c4 . } )
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it.  I also tried to avoid a lot of theory in the mainline by choosing a variation that just recently became popular but has been already approved by strong GMs. } )
4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Nf3{ This is White's main move. They just develop and stay flexible with the structure in the center. }
6. a6{ Not a new move but one that only became popular recently. Black just stops all ideas with  Bf1 - b5  which is one of White's main tries to put pressure on Black's position.  So far, it has given Black very decent results. }( {  A)  }6...g6 { would be logical for our repertoire but White has the very concrete }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 { . Now, }8...e6 { weakens the dark-squares and }8...Nxc3 9.Bc4! { is the start of a heavily debated variation that seems to be slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }6...Bg4 { is holding up nicely theoretically. The main line is a really forcing variation that leads to an endgame where Black still needs to know nuances to hold the balance. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3!? { It is very typical that White has to play concretely to not end in a slightly worse IQP position. }8...Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+! { is a nice in-between check to force Black's king to  e7 . }12...Ke7 13.Qxb5 { with an endgame that Black should hold.    Black has alternatives along the way but those are usually considered at least slightly better for White. } )
7. cxd5{ This is White's most popular move but Black had no big problems in practice. }
7. Nxd5
