8. Be6( { A key move. Black stabilizes  d5  and has the threat of   }9...Nxc3 10.bxc3 Bxc4 { . } )
9. Bb3{ This is a move that is mostly played automatically. White had to address Black's threat and this is the most solid move. }( {  A)  }9.Qe2 { has been played but after }9...Rc8 { White has to go }10.Bb3 { anyways, when Black's move should be more useful than White's. } )( {  B)  }9.Qb3?? { just loses material here, as Black has control over the  b5 -square. }9...Na5! 10.Qa4+ { . With Black's pawn on  a7  instead of  a6 , this would be okay for White. Here, we can just play }10...b5! { . } )
9. Na5( { Going for the light-squared bishop. }9...Nxc3 10.bxc3 Bxb3 11.axb3 e6 { is a solid alternative that has also been played with decent results for Black. } )
10. Ng5{ Once again this idea to undermine the  e6 -bishop. }
10. Qd7{ Black's score with this move is so far (June 2022) 5/5 against strong opposition, so no reason to deviate. If White takes on  e6 , we recapture with check which gives us enough time to save our  d5 -knight. }
11. Nxe6( { White should take the bishop. }11.O-O?! { was played in three games but Black can now save their bishop with }11...Nxb3! { . Black is slightly better both after     A)  }12.axb3 Bg4 { , as well as after...     B)  }12.Qxb3 Nxc3 13.Qxc3 Bd5⩱ { . } )
11. Qxe6+
