2. d5
3. g3( { If White plays   }1.c4 { and neither wants to play a Panov nor transpose to }1.d4 { lines, I think the Reti double fianchetto is the most dangerous independent try. } )
3. Nf6
4. Bg2
4. g6{ We just play our standard moves. }
5. b3{ White goes for the double fianchetto.  With White's d-pawn on  d4 , Black had the simple manoeuvre ... Bf5  and eventually ... Ne4  to find good squares for the pieces. As long as White's pawn can come to  d3 , this option is much less attractive. }
5. Bg7
6. Bb2
6. O-O{ We follow the same rules as in other  g3 -lines: ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first! }
7. O-O{ White has different move orders to reach this position.    While other variations in the  main chapter  are more of a 'nice to know', this version of the double fianchetto is not without venom. Black is fine but we shouldn't act carelessly. }( 7.d3 { is much less flexible than  7.O-O . It makes sense to keep the d-pawn flexible to discourage Black from preparing  ...e5 . We can simply play }7...a5 { when things will most likely transpose to  this variation , but it is also a valid idea to save the tempo on the a-pawn move and start with the immediate }7...Re8 { , followed by ... Nbd7  . } )
