1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. g3{ The Reti-Opening. White just builds their house on the kingside with  Bg2  and  O-O  and keeps a lot of flexibility.     There are not that many independent move orders starting with  1.Nf3  that don't transpose to other lines.    White can still transpose to the main lines with a quick  c2 - c4  and/or  d2 - d4 , but they can also play a reversed King's Indian with  d2 - d3 , or even play something completely different such as a double fianchetto with  b3  and  Bb2 . }
2. Nf6( 2...g6 { is a clever variation. This move order has the advantage that }3.Bg2 Bg7 { is now preparing  ...e7-e5 . For many White players, this is reason enough to play }4.d4 { when }4...Nf6 { will lead to positions from our  1.d4 part .    Nevertheless, if White just ignores it and plays   }4.O-O { , I think it is much more consistent with the rest of the repertoire to continue with }4...Nf6 { instead of }4...e5 { . }{ So, the 'threat' of ... e5  would be some kind of bluff.     In this regard, it doesn't make a big difference for us and the move order 2... Nf6  feels more consistent with other lines. } )
3. Bg2
3. g6
4. O-O{ The most flexible move. }
4. Bg7
5. d3{ This move indicates that White wants to play a 'King's Indian Attack'. They stay flexible with their pawns and prepare either  e2 - e4  or  c2 - c4 . }( { At this point in the course, we have pretty much looked at all other moves via transposition. }5.d4 { transposes to  these lines , }5.c4 c6 { to  those , }5.b3 {  here . } )
5. O-O
6. Nbd2{ In the King's Indian, Black players have tested pretty much every halfway reasonable setup against the fianchetto variation over the decades. Here, White is playing these setups with an extra tempo which gives them even more liberties.  It is impossible to look at all possibilities but let's look at White's most principled way of playing by preparing  e2 - e4 . One factor in this position - and one reason why the fianchetto variation in the King's Indian is so popular - is that it is very easy to play some moves. After ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... e5 , Black simply has more space and has many moves to improve the position bit by bit (... h6 , ... Qc7 , ... Be6 , putting the rooks on  d8  and  e8 ). }
6. c5{ Grabbing space with the c-pawn is a very principled reaction if White doesn't force us to play ... c6 . I think this option is very much in the spirit of the other lines. }
7. e4{ White's main move, finally putting a pawn in the center. }
7. Nc6{ We just keep developing. }
8. Re1{ White has other moves as well but this is the best move suited against our setup with ... e5 . White wants to create pressure against the  e5 -pawn as soon as possible. }( { Against other moves, such as }8.c3 { , we can also simply play }8...e5 { . } )
8. e5{ Taking as much space in the center as possible. }
9. exd5
9. Nxd5
10. Nc4
10. f6{ The modern main move to protect the  e5 -pawn. }( 10...Re8 { used to be more popular, but }11.Ng5! { is slightly annoying with ideas connected with  Nxf7  and  Qf3 . Black is objectively fine, but we will be provoked to play some ugly moves here as well. } )( { After }10...f6 { , White has achieved the maximum they can hope for in this line.  At least they forced us to spend a tempo with the f-pawn, which is not really a move we would like to play. Nevertheless, Black has a nice space advantage as a long-term factor and White has no easy way to exploit Black's newly created weakness.  In the next few moves, we will simply play ... Be6 , ... Qd7 , ... Rad8  with a nice position. }{     See variation in course  } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "Grabbing the Pawn!"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/2p2np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[Result "*"]

5. Bf4
{ I think every Slav player - not only us who worship the Schlechter - should follow one rule:     We have to grab the  c4 -pawn in some situations!     I know that many Slav players play the opening because they appreciate a solid center and don't really want to do anything in the opening but develop their pieces. I am also not the kind of player who likes to grab pawns in the opening.    However, the idea ... dxc4  is just too important to ignore! }( { One of our ideas behind   }2...c6 { is to provoke some kind of concession from White. Letting them get away without one is, just in general, a mistake.    }{ Especially, if White develops their dark-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain, it is usually a good signal for us to take the pawn.    If White could continue with  e2 - e3 , they would have an improved version of the  e3 -setups as they have no bishop locked in on  c1 ! } )5. dxc4{ After all the introduction, this is the logical move here. }
6. e3{ This is White's most successful move in practice. At this point, however, I show the move mainly because the following manoeuvre should also be part of our bag of ideas.    The theory can be found  here . }
6. Be6{ Black should definitely defend the  c4 -pawn - otherwise 5... dxc4  wouldn't have made a lot of sense - and this is the most stubborn way to do so. }( 6...b5?! { is the other standard way of protecting the pawn. In this concrete position, White can win back the pawn and has chances for an advantage with their better central control: }7.a4 b4 8.Nb1 Ba6 9.Qc2⩲ { with a slight advantage. } )
7. Ng5{ A standard move to attack our bishop on  e6  and win the pawn on  c4 . Remember the following manoeuvre! }
7. Bd5{ The bishop avoids being captured by the knight but isn't it in danger? }
8. e4{ White doesn't win a piece! Black can also attack one of White's minors. }
8. h6{ A typical counter-attack. If White retreats,  e4  is simply hanging. }
9. exd5{ Typically forced. }
9. hxg5
10. dxc6( { A smart move. Black cannot play }10...gxf4 { because }11.cxb7 { wins the rook on  a8 . } )
10. Nxc6{ Black still has his extra pawn and pressure against  d4 . White has compensation in the form of the bishop pair, but Black has solved all opening problems. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "Starting a Queenside Initiative"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2p2np1/3p4/2PP4/1QN1PN2/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 7"]
[Result "*"]

7. Be2
{ We don't take on  c4  exclusively if it wins a pawn. We shouldn't do it for no reason - if White trades a center pawn of Black's for a non-center pawn of their own, it's in principle a good trade for them. Sometimes, however, taking on  c4  can be the start of a queenside initiative. Here we see a good example. }7. dxc4{ A very nice decision to create counterplay on the queenside. }
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ Black must continue energetically to justify their last move. But now they can spread out with tempo on the queenside. }
9. Be2
9. a5{ Black simply wins space on the queenside and gets the options to play ... b5 - b4  or ... a5 - a4 . }
10. O-O
10. Bf5{ A nice move, stopping  e3 - e4 .     Why is Black's queenside play here such a good option?      1)  First of all, a lot of moves come with tempo. White's light-squared bishop had already moved before we took on  c4  but even if we decide to advance even further - either with ...  a4  or ... b4 , both these moves would win additional time.      2)  But another important factor can be seen if we think about White's options. I would say there are two main ideas about how White might exploit our last moves.      A)  White can prove that their majority in the center can be used to restrict Black's active play or (even better) the pawns can be used to steamroll Black in the center.      B)  White can prove that Black's queenside structure is vulnerable. Especially, the  c6 -pawn might come to mind as a backwards pawn that is on an open file. However, neither of these options looks dangerous.     Black's control over the  e4 -square makes it extremely hard to achieve  e3 - e4 , not only but also because  Nf3 - h4  can be answered with ... Be6  and with tempo.     Plan B looks very far away as well. The  c3 -knight is blocking the c-file, and the  c1 -bishop is still blocking this square for one of White's rooks. It will take a while before White could ever dream of pressure along the c-file - and in the meantime, Black will have done something with his initiative.     See the model game  Drozdovskij - Motylev  for the remaining moves. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "The ...c5-break: Creating Weaknesses #1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nppbp/2p2np1/3p4/2PP1B2/4PN2/PPQN1PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 8"]
[Result "*"]

8. Be2
{ The first examples of this chapter were basics for every Slav player - no matter if Grünfeld Slav or any other. But now we come to probably the most important plan of this repertoire: the plan of how to turn the  g7 -bishop into the 'butcher'! }8. c5{ Black just plans to take on  d4  and give White an IQP. Recapturing with the knight does not work because Black has ... e5 .     So far the  g7 -bishop on  d4  has only bitten on granite. But now the d-pawn either exchanges completely - in which case the long diagonal is open - or White takes again with the e-pawn, after which the resulting pawn on  d4 , however, no longer has any pawn protection. }( { The pawn structure is strongly reminiscent of a colours-reversed Tarrasch variation of the Queen's Gambit   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 { . What is considered the best setup? You guessed it:  g3  &  Bg2  . } )
9. cxd5{ If White wants to avoid ... cxd4 , they have to do something themselves in the center.     This move is at least better than taking on  c5 . }( 9.dxc5?! Nxc5 10.cxd5 { It is smart to take now on  d5 . We have to recapture with the queen to protect the  c5 -knight. }10...Qxd5 { Still, this position is pretty horrible for White. Our pieces are just much more active and ... Bf5  is coming as well. } )( 9.O-O { might be the best move but Black just plays }9...cxd4 10.exd4 dxc4 { followed by ... Nb6 - d5  and just developing all pieces towards  d4 . This is a typical, very comfortable version of an IQP for Black in the Schlechter. }{    I chose this concrete variation for this chapter because it shows a very radical idea of how the  g7 -bishop can play a role in the fight against the white pawn structure. } )
9. Nxd5{ Attacking  f4 . }
10. Bg3( { White should save the bishop but Black has an instructive response. }10.dxc5 { doesn't win a pawn and so it is just giving away the bishop pair for free. }10...Nxf4! 11.exf4 Qc7 { with the double attack against  c5  and  f4 , Black wins back the pawn. } )
10. cxd4{ Black goes for the 'Isolated Queen's Pawn'('IQP') structure! Remember the acronym! I will use it regularly in this course. }
11. Nxd4{ Errm, Christoph, there is no isolated pawn on  d4 ... }
11. Bxd4{ Sometimes, we are even ready to give away our Grünfeld bishop! The resulting position gives us an easy plan evolving around White's weaknesses on the d-file. }
12. exd4
12. N7f6{ Black will just continue with ... Bf5 /... Be6 , ... Rc8 , something like ... Qd7  and ... Rfd8 , with an easy game.     It is true, that we would love to have our bishop on  g7  in this structure but you can't have everything in life. At least, White has a hard time 'punishing' Black's absence of the dark-squared bishop with a kingside attack, well, because none of White's pieces is really directed towards Black's kingside. }{    The black plan in IQP structures is relatively simple.    Step 1: Keep the square in front of the IQP under control to prevent the advance of the pawn.    Step 2: Once the pawn is under control, regroup the pieces so that they attack the pawn. The IQP is a long-term pawn weakness, which means that especially endgames become very pleasant from now on. Especially major piece endgames are considered to be extremely advantageous. Our own pieces have a simple active plan while the opponent can ideally only defend passively. }
