[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "The ...c5-break: Creating Weaknesses #2"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/n1p2np1/3p4/2PP4/3BPN2/PPQ2PPP/RNB2RK1 w - - 0 8"]
[Result "*"]

8. a3( { This is one of my favourite trainables in the whole course. Here we see an instructive variation on how to create counterplay against a structure related to the IQP - the hanging pawns.    White should prevent  8...Nb4  but this is just another tempo that White wastes in the opening.    }8.Nc3? Nb4 9.Qd1 Nxd3 10.Qxd3 { should be slightly better for Black with the two bishops. }10...Bf5 { looks logical but }10...Bg4 11.Ne5 Bf5 { also looks like a good start. } )
8. c5{ Going for the typical break in this line. }
9. b3{ This is White's most popular move in this position. White understands Black's plan to go ... cxd4  and is indeed ready to recapture with the e-pawn to keep more influence in the center. However, they have no interest in getting an isolated pawn after ... dxc4 . With this move, White wants to recapture on both  c4  and  d4  with pawns. }
9. cxd4{ Taking on  d4  and  c4  for very concrete reasons. }
10. exd4{ Positionally, White might claim that the knight on  a6  is horribly misplaced for this structure as it is extremely far away from pressuring White's center pawns.     If the knight were on  c6 , it would be on its ideal square. If White hadn't played  b2 - b3 , Black could take on  c4  and block the IQP with ... Na6 - c7 - d5 , for example. Here it is more tricky to breathe life into the knight. But Black has a very concrete idea in mind. }
10. dxc4
11. bxc4{ This is the so-called 'Hanging Pawns' structure. White doesn't have one vulnerable pawn in the center but two of them! However, both pawns combined control a whole lot of squares.    Our plan is similar to the last example. As long as we align our pieces to attack the hanging pawns, we usually don't do much wrong.    Blocking the pawns is a little more difficult than in an IQP structure, but not impossible. The main thing to keep in mind is that the two pawns are strongest as long as they are adjacent. If one of the two pawns moves forward, weaknesses inevitably arise. The next move - although supported by tactics - is mainly a strong positional move. }
11. e5{ A beautiful move! White can take the pawn in different ways but White's pawn structure gets damaged no matter what and Black's knight gets the  c5 -square. If you can undermine White's pawns in this fashion, their structure will become more vulnerable. A similar motif is ... b7 - b5  in these structures even though this move is obviously extremely far away from working in this concrete position.     More details can be found  here . }
