[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "...c5: Pawn Sacs!"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/p3ppbp/1pp3p1/3p4/P1PPn3/2N1PN2/1P2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9"]
[Result "*"]

9. Nxe4
9. dxe4{ I started the line before the ... c5  break happens to show you that the move ... Ne4  , which we will discuss as a typical move in a moment, harmonizes very well with this break.     Either the knight supports the pawn break directly or White exchanges the knight. In that case, we drive the influential knight from  f3  to a more passive square, which is often a sign that we should now counterattack in the center. }
10. Nd2( 10.Ng5 c5 { is similar but gives White fewer options. If White doesn't take on }e4 { eventually, their knight will look pretty awkward on  g5 . } )
10. c5{ Black immediately uses the chance to play the ... c5 -break. Despite losing a pawn, it opens up the  g7 -bishop and completely paralyzes White's queenside. }
11. dxc5{ A greedy move. Let's have a look to see what happens if White just grabs the pawn and hopes to get away with it. }
11. Na6{ Black gives White a free hand on which pawn to take but with White's bad pieces on the last two rows and the powerful  g7 -bishop, Black will always have compensation. }( 11...bxc5 12.Nxe4 { wasn't Black's idea. } )
12. cxb6{ Let's take this as a sample line. This wins a second pawn but Black develops even faster. }( 12.Nxe4 Bb7 { will give similar compensation. But the theory regarding this variation will be discussed later in the theory chapter -  starting here . } )
12. Qxb6( { White is a pawn up but the butcher on  g7  is a monster and Black is putting a lot of pressure on White's weakened structure.  b2  is weak, the  c1 -bishop cannot move, White has no active moves. In such a situation, you'll have great compensation for the pawn. }13.Nxe4 { would even win a second pawn without solving White's problems on the queenside.     Here , you can find more details. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
