[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "The ...e5-break"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/4ppbp/2p1bnp1/p7/Np1P4/4PN2/PP1B1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 12"]
[Result "*"]

12. Bd3
{ We've talked a lot about the ... c5  pawn break. But there's another one that does virtually the same thing: the break ... e7 - e5 !     It's perhaps not so common in the theory chapters, because Black needs more preparatory moves before he can enforce it, but nevertheless, it's extremely important!     As a rule, it can be played with the same ideas. In some variations White may allow us to play ... e5 - e4 , which can sometimes be very attractive, because it gains a lot of space, drives the knight away from  f3  and sometimes can even be the start of a king attack! Nevertheless, simply taking out on  d4  to open the diagonal or give the opponent a weaker pawn on  d4  is a simple, common plan. }12. Bg4{ A very instructive move! White has the  c5 -square nicely under control so it will be hard to push ... c6 - c5 . However, after this bishop move, Black is ready to break the center with the e-pawn!    This plan is so important for the black position that we are even willing to move an already developed piece a second time in order to prepare the counterattack maximally effectively. On  e6 , the bishop has only blocked the advance. By pinning the  f3 -knight, White suddenly can't do much against ... e7 - e5  and Black gets active counterplay. }
13. h3( { White has nothing better. }13.O-O e5! { makes it even easier to create counterplay. } )
13. Bxf3
14. Qxf3
14. e5{ With a typical counter strike. Let me show you one nuance: }
15. dxe5( { This move looks strong at first glance because   }15...Qxd3 16.exf6 { wins a pawn - at least temporarily.    But Black has a much better move. } )
15. Nbd7( { Black will just recapture on  e5  with the knight.    The tactical point is that   }16.exf6 Ne5! { prepares to take on  d3  with check, so that Black will be able to take on  f6  afterwards.     See in theory chapter  } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "...e6 - Slow and Steady"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2p2np1/3p4/2PP4/1QN1PN2/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 7"]
[Result "*"]

7. Bd2
{ Sometimes it's not so easy to play the move ... c6 - c5  early under good circumstances. Sometimes simply because our center is under too much pressure for it or White can just take the pawn.     But there is one plan that is especially common against the calmer of the  e3 -setups: Black stabilizes the  d5 -pawn by playing ... e6 .     After that, we are always ready to capture out with the e-pawn on  d5 , which prevents symmetry in the centre and keeps our c-pawn on the board.     This c-pawn is then often used after ... b6  and other preparing moves like ... Bb7 , ... Nbd7 , .... Qe7 , ... Rac8 , ... Rfd8 , only to play the ... c5  lever after sufficient preparation. }7. e6{ By the way, this is the setup I also recommend against the variation that is recommended in most repertoires from White's perspective in the  e3 -universe: The direct  Nc3  &  Be2 .  See here  for more information. }
8. Bd3{ This is the better square for this bishop than  e2 . White keeps an eye on  e4  which stops ... Ne4  and allows  e3 - e4  in some positions. }
8. b6{ A logical follow-up. There is a reason why we postpone ... Nbd7  in this concrete variation as we will see on the next move. }
9. O-O
9. c5{ Here, we can play the ... c5 -break without any further preparation.     It's not a universal rule, but it's something you can use as a guide:     The more white pieces blocking the d-file, the easier it is to get ... c5  through. Often problems along the d-file are a reason why White gets some pressure when Black plays the break prematurely. A rook on  d1  can sometimes be quite annoying.     But here White has blocked the d-file with two pieces, which is in principle a good sign that the move ... c6 - c5  works immediately. However, this guideline is just a useful helper but a horribly master.    As soon as we play the ... c5  move, the position inevitably becomes more concrete, because more dynamics arise in the centre. Therefore, concrete consideration should be given to each of these decisions. }( { Note that if White goes   }10.dxc5 { , it is a typical position to go }10...Na6 { , sacrificing a pawn but getting a lot of tempi with ... Nc5  coming. I don't want to analyse this any deeper as }10...bxc5 { is an equally satisfying reply. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "...e6 - A Weird Carlsbad?"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/pp3pbp/2p1pnp1/3p4/2PP4/2NBPQ1P/PP3PP1/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 10"]
[Result "*"]

10. cxd5
{ A valid question after the move ... e6  is naturally what happens if White takes on  d5  anyways. }10. exd5( { Now that this option is possible, we should prefer it over the move }11...cxd5 { .    }{ The resulting pawn structure with the pawns on  d4 / d5  and the half-open c-file for White and the half-open e-file for Black, is called 'Carlsbad Structure'. In the  1.d4 -universe, it is mainly connected to the Exchange variation of the Queen Gambit declined }{ - (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 exd5 { ). The main difference compared to the positions in our course is the placement of the dark-squared bishops. Typically, White would love to have their bishop outside of the pawn chain (for example with }5.Bg5 { ), }{ so having the bishop stuck on  c1  is not ideal for White. However, our butcher on  g7  also doesn't impress much with the  ...e7 - e5  break gone and the uncertainty if we can really play  ...c6 - c5  eventually.    The fact that both dark-squared bishops are not too active for now should at least not be to Black's disadvantage! In the regular Carlsbad positions, White's dark-squared bishop is a pretty influential piece and exchanging it is typically not a bad idea.    White's typical plan in this structure is the 'minority attack'  b2 - b4 - b5 . If White achieves this, they typically create a weakness in Black's camp. With White's bishop on  c1 , they might also hope to activate this poor piece with  Bc1 - a3  eventually.    The following antidote is the most important resource against White's plan in this course, but please note that depending on the position, there might be other good possibilities as well. (For example, answering  b4 - b5  with ... c6 - c5  as a general idea shouldn't surprise you after the first examples of this chapter.) } )
11. b4{ The typical plan. White wants to play  b4 - b5  and take on  c6 . Either, Black get a backward pawn on  c6  or the  d5 -pawn gets isolated. }
11. a6{ A good inclusion. White needs at least two more moves before they will be able to play  b4 - b5 . }
12. a4{ The typical follow-up. }
12. Nbd7{ Black develops naturally and is now ready to go ... b7 - b5 ! If we achieve this, we have stopped White's main plan and their dark-squared bishop will be extremely bad. }( { The immediate }12...b5? { does not work because of }13.axb5 { when our  a6 -pawn is pinned. } )
13. Bd2( { Let's use this move to illustrate Black's main defensive idea. The only move that White could consider to stop it is the aggressive }13.b5!? { . It works tactically because of }13...axb5 14.Ba3 { The only justification of the last move. White unpins the  a4 -pawn with tempo. }( { ( }14.axb5 Rxa1-+ { is of course not possible. ) } )14...Re8 15.axb5 { If White is able to continue with  16.bxc6 , they will have a small advantage with easy play against the pawn. However, Black has a very dynamic answer as White is not fully coordinated. }15...c5! { Black is ready to play ... cxd4 . } )
13. b5{ Remember this idea! All of a sudden, White has no clear path forward and the dark-squared bishop is trapped behind their pawns. White can open the a-file but this is typically not too dangerous and White has no additional pawn breaks on the queenside to increase the pressure. We might consider ... Nd7 - b6 - c4  next to jump to the  c4 -outpost, but our main idea behind the last move is stopping White's own plan! In the next moves, we will typically start playing in the center or on the kingside. Note that this plan is also valid if Black's b-pawn would be on  b6  instead of on  b7  in the initial position.    A model game that shows Black's active possibilities in this structure is  Wang - Bu  in the model game section. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "Regrouping the Butcher"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p2n1pbp/2p3p1/3npb2/N2P4/4PN2/PP1QBPPP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 15"]
[Result "*"]

15. O-O
{ First, let's look at this example to see in which situations Black can use his e-pawn to play ... e5 - e4 . In this variation, Black has already burned a few bridges because he has sacrificed a pawn. Now we have to play hardball and find something concrete! }( { Opening up the position with }15...exd4 { cannot be the solution because }16.Nxd4 { attacks  c6  and  f5 . }{ But by pushing the e-pawn to  e4 , we can start a kingside attack. } )15. e4{ This is some kind of dream position for Black. The typical scenario is that Black combines this pawn advance with a kingside attack.    Black needs some moves to coordinate their pieces toward White's king but given enough time, Black will create serious threats. Because of Black's space advantage on the kingside, White cannot manoeuvre their own pieces towards the kingside.    This leaves White only with the chance to counter in the center or on the queenside before Black starts a mating attack. But if we look at the passive white pieces, we should be pretty optimistic that Black should come first. }
16. Ne1{ What a miserable knight. }
{ Let us look at this position from the perspective of the butcher: Black has played one of the typical pawn breaks with ... e7 - e5 , which is supposed to invigorate the bishop - but since Black has moved on with the pawn to  e4 , the pawn on  d4  is still a bulwark, supported by the pawn on  e3 .     What about the other pawn break? ... c5  is still possible, but difficult to implement. Not only does White have the square under control right now, but we would also undermine our knight on  d5 .    If you come to the conclusion in a position that you can no longer help the butcher with any of the typical pawn levers, there is no shame in simply regrouping it.     Here we have a nice example of that: since Black likes to combine the pawn on  e4  with a kingside attack, the bishop is not doing much on  g7  right now anyway. Time to lead it to greener pastures. }16. Re8{ The typical square for the rook. It supports the pawn on  e4 , making it hard for White to play  f2 - f3 . The rook might also join the attack via  e6  or maybe even  e5 ! But there is also something else that it prepares... }
17. b3{ A sample move, trying to develop the  c1 -bishop. }
17. Bf8{ Occupying the  a3 - f8  diagonal before White can do so. The bishop will be nicely placed on  d6  to pressurize White's kingside. On the next move, Black can play ... Qg5 , ... Bd6  and create an attack. }
