[Round "?"]
[White "1) Manoeuvres and Plans"]
[Black "A Misplaced Knight?! ...Ne4!"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[Result "*"]

6. Bg5
{ In this example, we will see a move that may not really be a plan or a manoeuvre but is so common in this course that I wanted to put it in this chapter anyway: The move ... Ne4 .     In fact, we'll see more moves with this knight in this chapter. In principle, of course,  f6  is not a bad square for the knight. After all, it controls several central squares. Nevertheless - the knight blocks our butcher on  g7 .     Therefore, it is a typical idea - often only after the opening - to regroup this knight. In fact, in this course, we will see every possible move the knight can make - including ... Ne8 , ... Ng8  and ... Nh7 !     Nevertheless, ... Ne4  is by far the most common move and you should remember this move, especially as a signal move on White's move  Bc1 - g5 !    Reasons why  e4  is so often a good square for the knight:    - It is well-positioned in the center. If White captures it, we often expel the good knight from  f3 .    - Sometimes, it threatens to win the bishop pair. This can be seen here with the white bishop on  g5 , but it is also true for a white bishop on  d2 .    - We exert pressure on  c3  and can either reinforce it, for example with ... Qa5 , or we take on  c3  and give the opponent a backward pawn on  c3 , which later serves us as a target along the c-file.    - Not here, but in many situations, the knight supports ... c6 - c5 . }6. Ne4{ Especially against White's last bishop move, this is a standard reply. }
7. Bf4{ The bishop has to go somewhere. }
7. Nxc3{ As the c-file is already opened, the simply plan to just take on  c3  and build up on the c-file later on, is quite logical. }
8. bxc3
8. Nc6{ One rule from the theoretical chapters: In the Schlexchange variations, it is often more flexible to play ... Nc6  before ... Bg7  even though this here is not one of the positions where it makes a big difference.     In the next moves, we will develop with ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first and then play ... Na5  to fix the weak square on  c4 . In the long run, we will build our rooks up on the c-file. }
