9. a3
{ The last example might have been a little bit obvious. But the ... Ne4  manoeuvre can also simply be used to provoke some imbalances. }9. Ne4( { Obviously, this is not the most critical variation in the course and Black is fine after other moves such as }9...Bf5 { or }9...Bg4 { as well.    But if we want to play for a win, it makes sense to know how to imbalance the game slowly but surely. } )( {  A)  After }9...Ne4 { , we are ready to play }-- 10...Nxc3 { when White gets a backward pawn on  c3  (and we simply destroy the symmetry). } )( {  B)   If White plays }10.Bd2 { , we can at least win the bishop pair with }10...Nxd2 { . } )( {  C)  And if White takes with }10.Nxe4 dxe4 11.Nd2 { , we can at least create a lot of dynamic in the center with }11...e5! { . } )
