6. a4
{ Another typical move that we'll see several times in this course, is Black's knight jump to  d5 . This typically happens in lines where Black grabs the pawn on  c4 .    The knight on  d5  does several things:    - Sometimes, it attacks a bishop on  f4     - We increase the pressure on  c3 . We can follow it up with ... Qa5 , but it is also simply enough to just play ... Nxc3 . Often, the  c3 -pawn is a weakness afterwards and by exchanging White's knight, we can also play ... b7 - b5  to stabilize the  c4 -pawn.    - Especially with White's pawn on  a4  - a typical scenario in ... dxc4 -lines -, Black might also put their knight on the  b4 -square. It is hard for White to drive the knight away from that square and often enough, the knight might invade via the  d3 - or  c2 -square. }6. Nd5( { Immediately making use of White's misplaced bishop on  f4 .    }6...Bg7 7.e4! { promises White some advantage. } )
