7. e3
{ One idea we'll come across again and again in this course is to grab the bishop pair with the move ... Nh5 .     In the given position - one of the most important in this repertoire - it is extremely important to create imbalances.     Once you have become comfortable with the emerging positions in this main variation, you will not find it difficult to play this idea in other positions as well, often under even much better circumstances. You will encounter this move in many variations where White places his bishop to  f4 , for example, the 'regular' Exchange variation, the London System or the Jobava London. }7. Nh5( { White should typically react with }8.Bg5 { or }8.Be5 { to create some weaknesses in Black's camp. However, if White plays the immediate }8.Bg3 { , Black is usually more than happy with }8...Nxg3 9.hxg3 { . With Black's kingside structure completely intact, there is not much pressure along the h-file and Black wins the bishop pair immediately. Objectively, this might still be close to equality but usually I'd already prefer Black in those situations.    The bishop pair is not too active yet but it certainly is a long-term asset and as chess positions have the tendency to rather open up than close down, I am always very happy with our future prospects in these situations. } )
