[Black "...Nxd5 - The Grünfeld Recapture"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nppbp/2p2np1/3p4/2PP4/3BPN2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 8"]
[Result "*"]

8. cxd5
{ Normally, of course, our intention is to retake with the  c6 -pawn on  d5  if White trades there. We do that in - random guess - 95% of the cases. }( { However, it is an important idea that in this Grünfeld Slav course we can, well, also take back the pawn in the Grünfeld way - typically known from lines like   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { .    }{ 'Isn't the move ... c7 - c6  pretty useless then?' I hear you ask. And you are right! Taking with the knight should be taken only in exceptional situations, but here we see a good example.    - White has invested a tempo for  e2 - e3 . So kicking our knight now with  e3 - e4  would also cost White a tempo.    - The white knight on  d2  is quite passive. In closed positions, there is often enough time to regroup badly placed pieces, but after the 'Grünfeld recapture' there is usually a dynamic game in the center, where a passive piece, in general, is a much bigger problem.    - The bishop on  d3  is also not in a good position. Potentially the d-file soon opens up if Black plays ... e5  or ... c5  and there the bishop is just in the way on  d3 .    - Our knight on  d7  is not ideally placed in an Exchange structure - it is clearly better placed on  c6  , but in the emerging Grünfeld structure it is suddenly perfectly placed and supports both ... e5  and ... c5 . } )8. Nxd5{ More information can be found  here . }
