[Black "Countering on the Queenside #1"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2p2np1/3p4/1PPP4/4PN2/P2N1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 0 7"]
[Result "*"]

7. Bb2
{ In many positions in the Schlechter Slav, the question for both sides is often: What is my plan?     Especially in closed positions, many players struggle with this question.     In my experience, the term 'closed position' refers quite well to positions in which neither no or only one pair of pawns has been exchanged. (You won't find this definition in any book, because there are exceptions so don't nail me down on that, but I think in the vast majority of cases the rule applies.)     Well, for our side, we have already learned some plans in this chapter.    One piece of general advice I always like to give in closed positions is: 'If you really don't know what to do, just gain space'.     'Gaining space' often enough means nothing more than rushing forward with your pawns in order to win control over squares, constrict the opponent and give your own pieces more room to move.     Usually, you take the pawns that don't have to protect your king- even though we'll see exceptions from this in this course as well!     "Space" is one of the few things in life where you can take a good example from toddlers who immediately grab every toy around them when another toddler enters the room. Even if you don't know what to do with it, it's better to have it yourself than leave it to the other guy!    Here, we have a typical situation where White is trying to grab space for free on the queenside. Often, this  b2 - b4  move is followed up with  a2 - a4  and eventually  a4 - a5  or  b4 - b5  can be played.    A general rule is: If your opponent tries to grab space for free, don't let them! Instead, hit back immediately! Sometimes it's possible to answer a white expansion with a blow in the centre, for example with ... e7 - e5 , but in many cases, this is not possible and the right way is to counter on the queenside - even if White may look 'optically' superior on that flank!     The following sequence shows very nicely how this can look. }7. a5{ Immediately undermining White's position. }
8. b5{ This is the typical response. }
8. a4{ This gives Black the  a5 -square for their queen and also stops White's a-pawn from supporting their friends on the queenside. Not to mention that White has to think about ... a4 - a3 . }
9. bxc6( { Let's use this as a sample line. More options can be found in the theory section -  see here .    If White doesn't take on  c6  themselves, it is a common idea for Black to play   }9...dxc4 { and 10... cxb5  to open up the queenside. } )
9. Nxc6{ Black goes for quick development and it is interesting to see how fast things can go wrong for White. }
10. Be2{ Let's continue the sample line. This was played by GM Kurajica, but Black can take over the initiative! }
10. dxc4{ Black opens up the center. }
11. Nxc4{ This keeps more control over the  e5 -square. But here Black can quickly make progress on the queenside. }( 11.Bxc4 { makes it easier for Black to get in the  ...e5 . }11...a3! { Forcing the bishop to a more unfortunate square.     A)  }12.Bc1 e5! 13.dxe5 Nd5-+ { White has too many problems along the  a1 - h8  diagonal after Black takes on  e5 . Ideas connected with ... Nc3  can also be annoying for White, especially because that makes it impossible for White to play  Rb1 . }{     B)  }12.Bc3 Nd5! { Black wins at least the bishop pair under very good circumstances. Most likely,  ...e5  will still come. } )
11. b5{ Using the possibility to mobilise the queenside! All of a sudden, it is Black who has the clearly superior position on the queenside. I'll give the analysis from the theory section in the clickables in case you need to be convinced: }( {  A)  Going back is not an option. }12.Ncd2? a3! 13.Bc1 Nd5! {  ...Nc3  is coming as well as, of course, ... e5 . } )( {  B)    }12.Nce5 Nxe5 { is also horrible for White. }{  ... Qa5 +  is coming and Black's pawns will force White in the defense. For example: }13.Nxe5 Qa5+! 14.Kf1 { is just bad as White will never finish their development while Black steamrolls White on the queenside and the center while the endgame after }14.Qd2 Qxd2+ 15.Kxd2 { is just slowly lost. }15...a3! { Forcing the bishop to  c1  because }16.Bc3 Ne4+ { loses material. }16.Bc1 Ne4+ { Driving the king to  e1  has to be a good thing and ... Bxe5  is now also an option. }17.Ke1 Bxe5 18.dxe5 { This endgame is just lost for White as their majority is worth less while Black's majority is far advanced and the  a2 -pawn is a clear target. For example: }18...Nc3 19.Bd2 b4-+ { followed by ... Be6 . -  see here  } )
