8. b4{ A very aggressive option. As seen in the last example, if White grabs so much space on the queenside, we shouldn't let them get away with it easily but instead, we should fight back! }
8. dxc4{ A very concrete approach. Black wants to follow it up with ... b5  and ... a5  to fight against White's advance on the queenside. }( { Playing it slow with a move like }8...e6 { is slightly risky when White advances aggressively on the queenside. I don't think there is a concrete refutation but White has different attractive options like }9.a4!? { . } )
9. Bxc4
9. b5{ Black has to play concretely to justify the last move. }( { Black wants to break White's bind on the  c5 -square but the immediate }9...a5 { runs into problems. White answers with }10.b5! { and Black stays very restricted, mainly because the  ...c5 -break does not work very well without any development supporting it. }10...c5? { runs into several refutations.    }{ One possibility is just to increase the pressure on  c5  and either create a weakness there or force Black to go ... cxd4  when White will happily recapture with the knight and jump to  c6 . }11.Ba3! Nbd7 12.Na4! cxd4 { If Black doesn't take, White will just continue with  dxc5  and  Rc1 . }13.Nxd4 Bb7 14.Nc6+-  )
10. Bd3{ Let's take this as a sample line. This keeps an extra eye on the  b5 -pawn, arguably making it harder to go ... c5  but it also allows  Ne4  if Black attacks the  c3 -knight with ... b5 - b4 . }
10. a5{ This is the idea behind Black's last two moves. Black is now the one with the initiative on the queenside.  See here  for more details. }
