1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { In this chapter, we will discuss some of White's less popular options - either by playing something very unusual on move 3 or by playing something unusual after }3.Nc3 Nf6 { . A lot of these moves are not bad but just very inflexible and can still transpose to variations from other chapters. }{    At this point, Black has not committed himself to a Schlechter setup with ... g7 - g6 . In which variations do you follow up with this move and in which don't you?    There is one easy rule that does not only apply in this chapter but in every chapter:     If your opponent develops their dark-square bishop before you play ... g7 - g6  - for example by playing }4.Bg5 { or }4.Bf4 { , you do something different. In every other case, you can safely enter Schlechter territory.    }{ The reason number one is actually quite simple - and also the explanation why these bishop moves are usually dealt with in a sideline chapter of every Slav course:     Black can simply take on  c4 ! White typically has big problems regaining the pawn and even if they succeed, it is usually at the cost of many concessions!    There is a second reason why you should not follow up with }5...g6 { against those moves. If White responds with }6.e3 { , }{ they might actually reach an improved version of typical  e2 - e3  structures with the bishop outside of the pawn chain. Don't allow that!    One of my rules for every Slav player is: You have to be ready to just take the pawn on  c4 ! I know that many Slav players play the opening because of its solid character and have no interest in an early pawn-grabbing but ... dxc4  is just too important as a resource to ignore it.    And, actually, White's early bishop moves are one of the main reasons why I 'invented' this rule. } )
