2. c6{ This chapter is about lines where White tries to postpone  Nf3  in favour of other moves or tries to play without it altogether. Some of these lines ask for immediate punishment while others have no independent meaning as they simply transpose to other chapters in this course. }
3. Nc3{ This is not a rare move but instead one of White's main continuations. However, White should transpose to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Bg5{ White's idea to play  Bxf6  is no reason for us not to take the pawn! }
4. dxc4( { We don't have to be afraid of }5.Bxf6 { . This would just give up the bishop pair and after }...exf6 { it would even accelerate Black's development. } )
5. e3{ This allows ... b5 . }
5. b5
6. a4
6. Qb6{ If our e-pawn was on  e6 , we would pin White's knight on  c3  with ... Bf8 - b4 . If this is not possible, then ... Qb6  is often the safest way to stabilise the pawn structure.    In the next moves, Black ideally wants to recapture on  f6 . Either with a piece (that keeps their pawn structure completely intact) or with the e-pawn which allows quick development of the dark-squared bishop and still allows Black to castle kingside easily. That means that Black would love to play ... Nbd7  before ... e6 .     There is only one tricky move order for White. }
7. Be2{ White plays with ideas like  Be2 - f3 . Black has to be aware of this option. They cannot play the ideal move order with ... Nbd7  before ... e6 . }
7. Bb7( { Black anticipates White's idea and stabilises on the long diagonal.     A)  }7...e6 8.axb5 cxb5 9.Bf3 Bb7 10.Bxf6 gxf6 11.d5 { promises White good compensation. } )( {  B)  }7...Nbd7?! { Ignoring White's ideas with this move might already be a small mistake. }8.axb5! cxb5 9.Bf3! { , an annoying move! }9...Bb7 ( { ( }9...Rb8?! 10.Bf4! { traps the rook.) } )10.Bxb7 Qxb7 11.Qf3! { and Black can't keep both  a7  and  b5 . } )
8. Nf3
8. e6( 8...Nbd7 9.a5! { is annoying. }{ Black has to watch out for ideas with  a5 - a6 . } )
9. Bxf6{ White should take on  f6  before Black can play ... Nbd7  and avoids the weakening of their structure. }
9. gxf6
10. O-O
10. a6{ White will have some compensation when they break the queenside with  b2 - b3 , but I would always prefer Black in this situation with an extra pawn and bishop pair. }
