1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6{ This chapter is about lines where White tries to postpone  Nf3  in favour of other moves or tries to play without it altogether. Some of these lines ask for immediate punishment while others have no independent meaning as they simply transpose to other chapters in this course. }
3. Nc3{ This is not a rare move but instead one of White's main continuations. However, White should transpose to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Bg5{ White's idea to play  Bxf6  is no reason for us not to take the pawn! }
4. dxc4( { We don't have to be afraid of }5.Bxf6 { . This would just give up the bishop pair and after }...exf6 { it would even accelerate Black's development. } )
5. e4{ This scores horrible for White and the pawn on  e4  can also be vulnerable. }
5. b5{ White should do something about ... b5 - b4 . }
6. e5
6. Nd5
7. a4
7. h6{ Forces the bishop to commit to one diagonal. }
8. Bd2{ This strengthens the knight but is extremely passive. }
8. a5( { White has no play on the kingside, so Black can easily improve their queenside structure to its fullest extent.    }8...e6 9.Qg4 { is also good for Black, but maybe slightly annoying. } )
9. axb5( { This is at least the beginning of a forcing series of moves. It is extremely hard to recommend another alternative.    }9.Nf3 e6∓ { is just a huge extra pawn for Black. } )
9. Nxc3
10. Bxc3( 10.bxc3 cxb5 { leaves White with no breaks on the queenside. } )
10. cxb5
11. b3( { This is a typical idea to break up Black's pawns but it is equally typical to just ignore the idea of   }12.bxc4 !  )
11. e6
12. bxc4
12. b4( { This position resembles the sharp Noteboom variation of the Slav defence:   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 e6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.a4 Bb4 6.e3 b5 7.Bd2 a5 8.axb5 Bxc3 9.Bxc3 cxb5 10.b3 Bb7 11.bxc4 b4 { which is usually considered to be about equal.    }{ But in direct comparison, Black does have the bishop pair here and the  d4 -pawn might be slightly unstable. Overall, Black's position is preferable. } )
13. Bb2
13. Bb7{ Putting the bishop on the long diagonal. }
14. Nf3{ In this structure, the game plans are often quite simple. Black wants to advance their connected passed pawns on the queenside as fast as possible while White is trying to prove that their central majority is the bigger factor.     In this regard, White might hope that they do currently have a nice blockade on the light squares on the queenside but as we will see, this is not the case. }
14. b3{ This is just strong. Black prepares ... Bb4 + and simply plans  a5 - a4 - a3  if White does nothing. }
15. Qxb3{ This is the obvious move against the  a5 - a4 - a3  idea, but Black just plays }
15. Bb4+{ With a strong initiative for Black. White's king will be in the center for quite a while - most likely until it gets checkmated. }
