7. h6{ Forces the bishop to commit to one diagonal. }
8. Bh4{ Now, the bishop cannot defend any longer against the threat on the  a5 - e1  diagonal and this will be a factor in many lines. }
8. g5( { This is too strong to recommend something different.    Still, let me point out that }8...a6 { invites the strong exchange sacrifice }9.axb5 cxb5 10.Nxb5 axb5! 11.Rxa8 Bb7 { and White should most likely reduce the damage by playing }12.Ra7 ( { ( }12.Ra1 g5! 13.Bg3 e6 { and }-- Bb4+ { is coming.) } )12...Qb6 13.Rxb7 Qxb7 14.e6!? { even though this should still be great for Black.    Overall, Black is spoilt for choice in this line. } )
9. Bg3
9. e6( { The easiest move. The position somehow resembles positions from the Anti-Moscov Variation of the Slav   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 dxc4 7.e4 g5 8.Bg3 b5 { , but this is a very good version.    }{ White has no pressure yet and Black can even be the first one to create annoying threats with ... Bb4 . } )
10. Nf3( 10.h4 Bb4 { is similar. } )
10. Bb4{ We can stop here. Usually, Black's biggest problem in these positions is their king who has no completely safe spot somewhere on the board, but their own counterplay with ... Nd7 , ... Bb7 , ... Qb6  and potentially ... O-O-O  and/or ... c5  comes so fast, that this position is borderline winning. }
