9. e4{ A logical move to grab the center but Black's counterplay is fast. }
9. b4{ This looks like a good moment to play this move. Black will develop with tempo in the following moves. Ideas like ... Ba6  or ... c5  are in the air. }
10. Na4
10. Qa5{ wins a tempo against the knight on  a4 . }
11. b3
11. Ba6{ Destroying White's coordination. }
12. Qc2
12. Bxf1
13. Kxf1{ White has a pretty awkward king on  f1 . If we give White some time to coordinate their pieces ( g3 ,  Kg2 ,  Rac1 ,  Rfd1 ), they will be better, but we have no intentions of letting this happen. }
13. c5{ This strike is extremely typical for the Grünfeld. We disrupt White's development and if they take the pawn, we can use the open c-file to build an initiative.     White can take the pawn in different ways but the problems are always similar: White's pieces will be uncoordinated.     I analysed this position a little deeper but as this whole  4.Qb3  line is so rare, let’s stop the trainable lines here. I will give the additional analysis in the clickables. }( {  A)  }14.Nxc5 Rc8! { Pinning the knight on  c5 . In the next moves, Black will try to dislodge the pawn on  d4  that keeps the White position together. }15.Rc1 ( { ( }15.Qe2 Nh5! { Threatening ... Nxf4  as well as ... Rxc5  }16.Be5 Bxe5 17.Nxe5 Nc6 18.Nxc6 Rxc6⇆ { and  ...e5  is coming with nice counterplay.) } )15...Nfd7! { Black is preparing  ...e5  to undermine the  d4 -pawn. There is not much that White can do about it. }16.Qe2 { Relatively the best but it doesn't stop our plan. }16...e5! { ⇆ with decent counterplay for Black.     B)  }14.Bxb8 { This approach to simplifying the position is playable but also promises White no advantage. }14...Raxb8 15.Nxc5 { As in the line  A  with  14. Nxc5  }{ , it is our goal to undermine White's  d4 -pawn. A pretty convincing method is }15...Ng4! { Preparing moves like ... e5  and tactics connected with ... Bxd4  (after for example ... Rfd8 ) but there are even more devilish tricks in the position. }16.h3 { Looks natural but doesn't help White. }16...Ne5! { A stunning move. It's really all about undermining the  c5 -knight. }{     B1)  }17.dxe5 Rfc8! { It is a nuance to use the f-rook so that the other rook can join the action with  ...Rb5  in some lines. }18.Rc1 { White has other moves to give the knight back immediately but those lines are just visually okay for Black. }18...Bh6! { Even stronger than  ...Rb5  that is enough to win back the piece. }19.Nd2 ( { ( }19.Ke2?? { would lose on the spot. }19...Bxc1 20.Rxc1 Rb5! { ) } )19...Qb5+ { improving the queen. }20.Ke1 ( { ( }20.Qc4?? Bxd2-+ { loses a second piece for White as the c5-knight remains pinned.) } )( { ( }20.Kg1 Rd8! { ) } )20...Rd8 { A nice move to increase the pressure. }21.Rd1 Bxd2+! 22.Rxd2 Rdc8⩱ { Black will win back the piece under very pleasant circumstances.     B2)  }17.Nxe5 Bxe5 18.dxe5 Rfc8 { Pinning the knight. }19.Rc1 Rb5⩱ { Black will win all their sacrificed material and remain with the slightly more active pieces. For example after }20.Qe2 Rbxc5 21.Rxc5 Qxc5 22.g3 Qxe5 { White should draw something like this but Black is sitting on the easier side of things.     C)  }14.Qxc5?! Qa6+! { Black will just win the  e4 -pawn and will just be better as their pieces will be better coordinated. }( { (Don't go }14...Qxc5? 15.Nxc5+- { and everything is protected.) } )15.Qc4 { With a king on  f1 , White is happy to exchange queens but it doesn't solve all the problems. }15...Qxc4+ 16.bxc4 Nxe4⩱ { White needs a few more moves to bring their pieces into the game and Black can start to pressurize the central pawns on  c4  and  d4 . } )
