8. O-O( { Black can just develop their pieces and will soon strike back against White's center.    }8...b4 { Black can also play in the same concrete style that I suggest in the chapter  Royal Adventures , but  8...O-O  should be the more natural move. }9.Na4 Bf5 10.Qc4 { Black can already force a repetition with }10...Be6 11.Qc2 Bf5 { but they can also be more ambitious with }10...O-O { . } )
9. e4{ A logical move to grab the center but Black's counterplay is fast. }
9. Qa5{ This looks optically very promising with ideas like ... b4  and ... Ba6 , but White has a lucky way out to escape with a perpetual that we cannot really avoid without taking too many risks. }
10. e5
10. Nd5
11. Bd2{ After this move, it seems there is no good way to avoid the draw. Let me just quickly show you the engine line: }
11. Nb4
12. Qb1
12. Bf5
13. Ne4{ White's setup doesn't look particularly stable but it holds and White is ready to kick Black's pieces out with  14.a3 . }
13. Bh6{ Trying to deflect White's bishop but White can more or less ignore it. }
14. Bc3( 14.Bxh6? Nc2! { is Black's idea. White can play }15.Kd1 { or }15.Ke2 { . In both cases, we can play }15...Bxe4 { and are threatening devastating discoveries. } )
14. Qa4{ Threatening ... Nc2 +. }
15. b3
15. Qa3{ Black has saved their knight on  b4  against  a2 - a3  but White can repeat moves here. }
16. Bb2
16. Qa5
17. Bc3
17. Qa3{ with a draw. }
