2. c6{ This chapter is about lines where White tries to postpone  Nf3  in favour of other moves or tries to play without it altogether. Some of these lines ask for immediate punishment while others have no independent meaning as they simply transpose to other chapters in this course. }
3. Nc3{ This is not a rare move but instead one of White's main continuations. However, White should transpose to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Qb3{ A typical move that we will see in different positions in this course.     In this concrete position, the queen move is really rare. Usually, White plays  Nf3  before this move, so that the  d4 -pawn has extra protection in the lines with ... dxc4 .     Nevertheless, I think it makes sense to cover this move for completeness' sake and to show the spirit of this variation with some sample lines. }
4. g6{ Once again the easiest move for Black is to offer transpositions to more common lines with  Qb3 . }( { White should play }5.Nf3 { (after which Black should still respond with }5...dxc4 { -  see here ) as this knight move is just much more flexible than   }5.Bg5 { or }5.Bf4 { in this position. }{ Not only because it is more flexible but also because the knight move protects  d4 .     Nevertheless, let's look at White's alternatives. } )
5. Bf4
5. dxc4{ This way, we do often create counterplay against the queen on  b3 . On  c4 , her majesty will be exposed and Black can develop quickly with tempo. }
6. Qxc4{ White could have the same position with the move  Nf3  played instead of  Bf4  which looks way more flexible.     This is a good version for Black. }
6. b5{ I think it makes sense to start with ... b5  as this forces the queen to  d3 . Otherwise, the  d4 -pawn hangs. }
7. Qd3
7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. O-O( { Black can just develop their pieces and will soon strike back against White's center.    }8...b4 { Black can also play in the same concrete style that I suggest in the chapter  Royal Adventures , but  8...O-O  should be the more natural move. }9.Na4 Bf5 10.Qc4 { Black can already force a repetition with }10...Be6 11.Qc2 Bf5 { but they can also be more ambitious with }10...O-O { . } )
9. e3{ The solid move but Black will still be able to strike against White's center. }
9. Qa5{ Pinning the knight and preparing ... Bf5  this way. White should definitely not ignore that. }
10. Nd2( { Unpinning the knight. Black has different options here.    }10.Be2 Bf5! 11.Qd2 { The best square to unpin the knight but even this has drawbacks. }11...b4! { and Black will get in ... Ne4  with tempo, followed by ... c5 . } )
10. Nfd7( { I think this is the easiest move. Black prepares  ...e5  and will have good counterplay afterwards.    }10...Bf5!? { is the more tactical alternative. One point is that the automatic }11.e4 { weakens White's  d4 -pawn and Black can just drop back with the bishop and create counterplay against this pawn. }11...Be6 12.Be2 b4! 13.Nd1 Rd8! 14.O-O Nh5! 15.Be3 Bxd4! 16.Bxd4 Nf4 17.Qe3 Nxe2+ 18.Qxe2 Rxd4∓ { is just a sample line to show what happens if White is not careful. } )
