7. Nxe4
7. dxe4
8. e3( { At first glance, this looks like a horrible blunder but for the moment, Black has no concrete winning tactic.    }8.Bd2 { is too passive to promise White anything. }8...Bg7 ( { (Don't fall for }8...Qxd4 9.Bc3! { ) } )9.e3 O-O { Black will play  ...e5  soon and be very happy. White might postpone this with a move such as }10.Bc4! { This fights against }10...e5 { as this would run into }11.Bb4 { .    But besides these 'cheapos', there is not much that White can do to stop it mid-term.   }10...a5 { looks like a good way to start. It is not the only one but I like it. }{ This wins space and takes away the option for White to go  Bb4 .     A sample line could continue }11.Ne2 Nd7 { Black could have also played the immediate ... e5  but the move is not running away and Black tries to win the bishop pair first with ... Nb6 . }12.O-O Nb6 13.Bb5 { Keeping the two bishops. Now, Black can just execute their favourite break. }13...e5! { with decent counterplay. } )
