1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6{ This chapter is about lines where White tries to postpone  Nf3  in favour of other moves or tries to play without it altogether. Some of these lines ask for immediate punishment while others have no independent meaning as they simply transpose to other chapters in this course. }
3. Nc3{ This is not a rare move but instead one of White's main continuations. However, White should transpose to other variations in this course either with a quick  Ng1 - f3  or by taking on  d5 , leading to the  Exchange Variation . }
3. Nf6
4. Bf4{ Another move to develop the dark-squared bishop before playing  e2 - e3 . }
4. dxc4{ As usual, we just take on  c4  if White develops their bishop to  f4 . }
5. e4{ Putting the pawn on  e4  is always double-edged. On the one hand, it grabs space. On the other hand, the pawn can also be a target as Black will certainly play ... b5  and then ... b4  is always in the air. }
5. b5{ Business as usual - we protect the pawn. }
6. a4{ is completely ignoring the problems of White's position. }
6. b4
7. Na2
7. Be6{ Much stronger than taking on  e4  (which is also good by the way). For the moment, the bishop can not be harassed with  Nf3 - g5 , the pawn on  c4  is protected and ... Nxe4  is now a legitimate threat. }
