1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6{ In this chapter, we will talk about the sidelines with an early  3.Nf3  by White.     You will see that in this course, most chapters begin with this early knight move. The reason is simple:     It is typically the most flexible move that White can choose. In most setups, other squares for the knight are typically not that attractive. You don't have to be a Slav expert to understand that the knight has just, in general, more influence on  f3  than on  e2  (or even  h3 ) but especially after all the lines that we have already seen where I did my best to underline the importance of Black's pawn breaks in the Schlechter Slav, it should be absolutely clear why White wants to have their knight on a square where it controls  e5 !    In the next chapters, we will talk about White's main moves in the given position. Here, we will discuss the less popular moves.    Pretty much the same rules that we had in the last chapter, apply: }( { If your opponent develops their dark-squared bishop - for example after }4.Bf4 { -, we should  not  play }4...g6 { but instead just grab the pawn with }4...dxc4 { . }{ Here, the pawn grab works typically even better than in the last chapter, as White has no knight on  c3  that can play its part in preventing ... b7 - b5 . } )
