4. Qa4( { This is much less popular than }4.Qc2 { or }4.Qb3 { and that is for a reason: }{ All moves protect  c4 , but while the other moves claim additional influence over the centre, this move only has the additional idea of pinning the  c6 -pawn and play }{   }5.cxd5 { if Black does nothing about it.      Black can play }4...dxc4 { and go for similar lines like with  Nc3  and ... g6  included, however, this would give White's last move too much sense.     I think we should just transpose to a Semi-Slav where White's queen is pretty bad on  a4  (and White even spent a tempo placing the queen there). } )
4. e6( { Not really in the spirit of the Schlechter Slav, but we have to do something about White's idea to go  5.cxd5  and here, this is just a very good move as the queen has no business on  a4  in these Triangle Slav structures. }4...dxc4 { is playable but it doesn't fit into our repertoire.    I think if we play   }4...g6 { (and not }4...dxc4 { ) against  4.Qb3  and  4.Qc2 , it would be a concession to play   }4...dxc4 { against the (by far) least popular of these queen moves. }{ After }5.Qxc4 { , I wouldn't mind recommending this line if we could transpose to the  Royal Adventures  by playing }5...g6 { when }6.Nc3 { just transposes. Instead, White can play }6.g3 { and we would be forced to learn lines here as well. } )
5. Bg5{ A natural developing move. At least, the  c4 -pawn is now protected. }
5. h6
6. Bxf6{ If White takes, we just go ... Nd7 , ... g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and we will be ready to execute some breaks in the center sooner or later. }
6. Qxf6
7. Nc3
7. Nd7
8. e3
8. g6{ Once our bishop is on  g7  and our king safe on  g8 , we will look for breaks with ... e5  or ... c5 . }
