5. e3{ This slow move is also possible with the queen on  b3 . As usual, we follow the rule that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against all kinds of  e2 - e3  setups. }
5. Bg7
6. Nc3{ The most flexible move. }
6. O-O
7. Bd3( { Developing the light-squared bishop allows Black to take on  c4  under decent circumstances. The same reaction can be played against }7.Be2 { .    This is usually the case if White combines these bishop moves with additional tempo-losing moves. }{ If we replace  Qb3  with  h3 , we would play the same way -  see here . With the queen on  b3 , this variation is even better for Black as the queen is nothing but a target. } )
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ The typical follow-up, gaining space on the queenside. }
9. Be2{ A safe square but overall, White's setup is just very passive. }
9. a5{ Black starts advancing on the queenside. }
10. O-O
10. Bf5{ A nice square for the bishop. Black takes control of the  b1 - h7  diagonal and makes it hard for White to push  e3 - e4 . Also, the queen on  b3  can now only retreat to  d1  if hit with ... a4 .     Look at the model game Drozdovskiy-Motylev -  see here  for a potential continuation. }
