5. Bf4( { A typical follow-up whenever White uses their queen to protect the  c4 -pawn. White uses the fact that the bishop is not blocked by anything (in comparison to   }4.e3 { or }4.Nbd2 { lines, for example). } )
5. a5{ This is a typical idea in these structures with the queen on  b3 . Black will happily use the possibility to expand on the queenside with the tempo ... a5 - a4 .     The pawn on  a4  will be a big asset for Black and, usually, White can not even dream of winning this pawn.     One tactical motif to take note of is that a move like  Nc3xa4  is typically running into ... dxc4  and White cannot recapture as ... b7 - b5  will be an annoying fork. }
6. e3( { We are already on completely new territory and the engines just confirm that Black is getting very good play by advancing on the queenside. So we don't have to look too deeply into these lines.    An important point is that }6.Nc3? { is already a mistake. Black can just play }6...a4! { . }7.Nxa4 { After other moves, Black can just take on  c4 . }7...dxc4! { White cannot recapture on  c4  because of the ... b5  fork, but even if they just drop back with }8.Qd1 { , we can just create a strong pawn mass on the queenside with }8...b5 { . } )
6. a4( { That's the idea. We use the a-pawn to win space on the queenside.    If White now goes back with }7.Qd1 { , we got the space for free as White used the two tempi we had to invest in ... a5  and ... a4  for  Qd1 - b3 - d1  and even if White goes to  c2 , it is not clear if this is not costing even more tempi as Black has moves like ... Bf5  or ... Nb4  with tempo. } )
7. Qc2{ Arguably the most natural move. }
7. Bg7{ Black just goes for quick development. }
8. Nc3( 8.Bxb8? { is not winning the a-pawn because of }8...Bf5 { when Black can recapture on  b8  with the queen. } )
8. O-O{ Black has brought the king to safety and is now ready to strike in Grünfeld fashion against White's center. }
9. Bd3{ It makes sense to secure the queen against ... Bf5  attacks, but with the bishop on  d3 , White is usually running into good versions of the ... c5  move. }
9. c5{ White is not well set up to meet the transition into Grünfeld positions. They just lost too much time. }
10. Bxb8{ Once again, destabilizing the a-pawn is one of White's few tries to justify the previous moves. Also, the knight was very quickly threatening to come to join the fray with ... Nc6 , pressuring  d4  and preparing ... Nb4 . }( 10.dxc5 Na6 { with the two ideas ... Nb4  and ... Nxc5  is working nicely for Black. } )
10. Rxb8
11. Qxa4( { If White wants to take on  a4 , this is the best move to do it.    }11.Nxa4? { is still a mistake because of the typical shot }11...dxc4! { , followed by  ...b5 . } )( 11.O-O { It's not easy to give good advice to White at this point. }11...a3 { A typical pawn push that we can throw into White's position to weaken the dark squares.    }{ Overall, we just have the bishop pair in a position that is about to open up very soon! Black can continue with ... Bg4  or just open the center by taking on  d4  and  c4 . } )
11. Bd7{ This is a strong response. Black wants to open the center soon with ... cxd4  and ... dxc4 .     In the resulting position, we will be able to play ... b5  and put the bishop on  c6 . }
12. Qd1{ This seems to be the best square, overprotecting  d4  while also not staying on the c-file that can easily open up. }( { After }12.Qc2 { , the counterplay is very similar. }12...dxc4 13.Bxc4 b5 { and Black can continue with ... cxd4  and ... b4 . } )
12. dxc4
13. Bxc4
13. b5
14. Bd3
14. Bc6{ With different possibilities for Black.     We can take on  d4  to open the center. We can play ... c4  and ... b4  to create strong queenside pawns. We can even consider ... Nd7  and .... e5  to play for more pawn breaks in the center.     Black has the easier game. }
