1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2
4. g6( { The title of this chapter might need some explanation. 'Schlechter's Dream'?    It actually is! If you are a true believer in the Schlechter - if you aren't yet, hopefully the next 30 chapters will convince you-, there is nothing better that can happen to you than an opponent who plays   }4.Qc2 { .    What is the idea behind White's move? Typically, White wants to annoy two types of Slav players.     1)  Those who simply want to develop with }4...Bf5 { and     2)  those who like nothing more than to grab the pawn with }4...dxc4 { and protect it no matter the cost.    Option 1 is obviously not possible at all and while }4...dxc4 { is one of Black's main moves, it can no longer be combined with pawn-grabbing intentions as White can simply play }5.Qxc4 { . } )( { However, against }4...g6 { , the queen move does not really serve a purpose. Quite the opposite!    }{ All of a sudden, the queen is on a square where ... Bf5  can come with tempo; when we play ... c5  and open the c-file, the queen might be extremely misplaced; in some variations, even ... Nc6 / a6 - b4  can come with tempo. Overall, the optimist in me would even say that the queen is even worse positioned on  c2  than on  d1  - and White has now even invested a tempo to move the queen there! After studying these lines, you will hopefully share my excitement. We will typically get improved versions of other chapters. }( { The move }4...g6 { is actually so convincing that it is the absolute main line even between players who would never enter the Schlechter against other moves, for example after   }4.e3 { or }4.Nc3 { . } ) )
