5. Bg7{ I will go with 5... Bg7  and 6... O-O  as my main recommendation just because it follows the rule that this is what we do against all variations with an early  e2 - e3 ! }( { Honourable mention to the move }5...Bf5 { . Developing this bishop with tempo can hardly be a bad idea! } )
6. Nc3{ Typical for White's setup with an early  e2 - e3 , these lines are full of transpositions.     If you want to see what happens when White combines  Nc3  with  Be2  or  Bd3 , go to the variations with  6.Bd3  -  see here  or  6.Be2  -  see here . }
6. O-O
7. Bd2{ This move has been played in some games by titled players but there is no big point behind it if we just continue in our active Grünfeld style. }
7. c5{ This is apparently a novelty but this break will come very naturally to us after studying this chapter. Black just has very pleasant counterplay and if White takes on  c5 , we will win back the pawn in a few moves. }
8. dxc5
8. Bf5{ Developing with tempo. }
9. Bd3( { Moving the queen makes no big difference. }9.Qb3 Nbd7 { Black will win back the pawn and we are not worried about }b7 { . } )
9. Bxd3
10. Qxd3
10. Na6( 10...Nbd7 { is similar. } )
11. Nxd5{ This move does mainly illustrate that Black's initiative does also survive if the queens come off and so we can just take on  c5 . }
11. Nxc5
12. Nxf6+( { This might not be the most precise move but it shows the idea that not every queen exchange helps White.    }12.Qa3 { is the engine move but Black can just continue naturally. }12...Nxd5 13.Qxc5 Nb6⇆ {  b2  is hanging, ... Rc8  is a threat and ... Qd3  is a move to keep White's king in the center.     Black is very comfortable. } )
12. Bxf6
13. Qxd8
13. Rfxd8{  b2  is still under pressure, ... Nd3 + is a big check. Black will win back the pawn with the better structure. }
