1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. e3( { The main alternative to }5.Bf4 { . However, now we can transpose to advantageous versions of positions from the  e3  chapters -  starting here . } )
5. Bg7{ I will go with 5... Bg7  and 6... O-O  as my main recommendation just because it follows the rule that this is what we do against all variations with an early  e2 - e3 ! }( { Honourable mention to the move }5...Bf5 { . Developing this bishop with tempo can hardly be a bad idea! } )
6. Be2{ Not a particularly popular move. I guess most White players don't like it to allow ... Bf5  after which either light-squared bishop or queen have to move a second time. }
6. O-O{ The most flexible move to start with. }
7. O-O( { Usually, White castles as fast as possible in this variation to minimize Black's counterplay in the center if they go  ...c5 .    }7.Nc3 c5! { is giving Black the same kind of counterplay but with White's king still in the middle. } )
7. c5( { Not the only move but I think the most in the spirit of our repertoire.    }7...Bf5 { is a very solid reply. }8.Qb3 { Black shouldn't have many problems after }8...Qb6 { . } )
8. cxd5( { Let's follow this as the main move as it is the move that has been played in the only two games with this position.    If White takes on  c5 , the pawn will usually be lost sooner or later. For example }8.dxc5 Bf5 { Developing with tempo. }9.Qb3 Nbd7 { White has no good way to protect  c5  and }10.Qxb7?! Nxc5 { is typically giving Black great compensation as White's queenside is completely underdeveloped. } )
8. cxd4{ If White recaptures with the pawn, this would be a pretty poor IQP position. }
9. Nxd4{ The normal move. }
9. Nxd5{ Winning back the pawn. Black has easy equality. }
10. Rd1{ White tries to create some pressure along the d-file. }
10. Qb6( { Getting out of the d-file. The structure is symmetrical but there are some possibilities to create imbalances.    Let's see some possibilities to do so.     A)  If White goes }11.Nc3 { , we'll have an immediate imbalance after taking on  c3 . }11...Nxc3 12.bxc3 { White has compensation in form of the activity along the b-file. Still equal but the symmetry is broken.     B)  }11.Qc4 { was played in  Predke - Ponomariov, Riga 2021  but the queen is vulnerable against  ...Be6  moves. For example }11...e5! 12.Nb3 Nb4! { followed by  13...Be6 .     C)  If White wants to avoid the split pawn structure with something like   }11.Nd2!? { , then Black can offer this imbalance. }11...Nc6 12.Nxc6 Qxc6 { It makes sense to exchange queen as the queen on  b6  was slightly vulnerable against  Nc4 -jumps. }13.Qxc6 bxc6⇆ { Once again, the position is equal in evaluation but no longer symmetrical. }{ Black can try to go for an initiative on the queenside with ... a7 - a5 - a4 , putting a rook on the b-file, ... Be6 . } )
