1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. e3( { The main alternative to }5.Bf4 { . However, now we can transpose to advantageous versions of positions from the  e3  chapters -  starting here . } )
5. Bg7{ I will go with 5... Bg7  and 6... O-O  as my main recommendation just because it follows the rule that this is what we do against all variations with an early  e2 - e3 ! }( { Honourable mention to the move }5...Bf5 { . Developing this bishop with tempo can hardly be a bad idea! } )
6. Bd3{ This is White's main move. Most White players develop the bishop to this square instead of on  e2 , as ... Bf5  can't come with tempo. }
6. O-O
7. O-O( { Castling is more important than other developing moves. However, }7.Nc3 Na6 { is similar. } )
7. Na6{ A nice move. Black still wants to continue with the Grünfeld ... c5  but to threaten ... Nb4  first is a clever move order. }
8. a3( { White should prevent  8...Nb4  but this is just another tempo that White wastes in the opening.    }8.Nc3? Nb4 9.Qd1 Nxd3 10.Qxd3 { should be slightly better for Black with the two bishops. }10...Bf5 { looks logical, but }10...Bg4 11.Ne5 Bf5 { also looks like a good start. } )
8. c5{ Going for the typical Grünfeld pawn break. You see, that this works is very typical for the  4.Qc2 -line. }
9. cxd5{ White wants to create a big center with  e3 - e4  coming. }
9. cxd4( { The typical response, provoking White to get an isolated pawn on  d4 .    }9...Qxd5?! 10.e4! { is White's idea. } )
10. e4{ White should try to keep a strong structure in the center. }
10. e6{ A typical move to destroy White's space taking central pawns. }
11. Bg5( { The best move. By creating the threat of   }12.e5 { , White makes sure that Black cannot take on  d5 . } )( 11.dxe6?! Bxe6⩱ { is what Black wants. } )( 11.d6 { would be a good idea if White could play  12.e5  next - which is also the reason why Black can't take the pawn - but after }11...e5! { , the  d6 -pawn will fall when Black remains with the better central influence. } )
11. h6{ Forcing White to give up the bishop pair. }
12. Bxf6{ White has to take, otherwise  d5  is simply hanging. }( 12.Bh4 g5 13.Bg3 exd5∓  )
12. Qxf6{ Black would simply be better if White has to give up their center. }
13. e5{ The best move. White wants to keep the strong pawns. }
13. Qf4{ Important. By keeping an eye on  e5 , Black makes sure that White can't play  14.d6  . }( 13...Qd8? 14.d6 { for example would be horrible.    Now, we have a very double-edged position. Actually, Black could be a pawn up after something like   }14.Re1 exd5 { . }{ White has compensation but Black should be okay as well. ... Be6  looks natural and ... Na6 - b8 - c6  is a nice manoeuvre to bring the horsie back into the game. } )
