4. g6
5. e3( { The main alternative to }5.Bf4 { . However, now we can transpose to advantageous versions of positions from the  e3  chapters -  starting here . } )
5. Bg7{ I will go with 5... Bg7  and 6... O-O  as my main recommendation just because it follows the rule that this is what we do against all variations with an early  e2 - e3 ! }( { Honourable mention to the move }5...Bf5 { . Developing this bishop with tempo can hardly be a bad idea! } )
6. Bd3{ This is White's main move. Most White players develop the bishop to this square instead of on  e2 , as ... Bf5  can't come with tempo. }
6. O-O
7. O-O( { Castling is more important than other developing moves. However, }7.Nc3 Na6 { is similar. } )
7. Na6{ A nice move. Black still wants to continue with the Grünfeld ... c5  but to threaten ... Nb4  first is a clever move order. }
8. a3( { White should prevent  8...Nb4  but this is just another tempo that White wastes in the opening.    }8.Nc3? Nb4 9.Qd1 Nxd3 10.Qxd3 { should be slightly better for Black with the two bishops. }10...Bf5 { looks logical, but }10...Bg4 11.Ne5 Bf5 { also looks like a good start. } )
8. c5{ Going for the typical Grünfeld pawn break. You see, that this works is very typical for the  4.Qc2 -line. }
9. b3{ This is White's most popular move in this position. White wants to recapture on  d4  with the pawn but doesn't like to end up with an IQP (Isolated pawn on  d4 ). With this move, White prepares to recapture on  c4  with a pawn as well so that the d-pawn won't stay without a neighbour. }
9. cxd4{ Taking on  d4  and  c4  for very concrete reasons. It is a nice line to illustrate some general points. }
10. exd4
10. dxc4
11. bxc4{ Positionally, White might claim that the knight on  a6  is horribly misplaced for this structure, as it is extremely far away from pressuring White's center pawns. But Black has a very concrete idea in mind. }
11. e5{ This move just destroys White's center and gives the knight on  a6  the  c5 -square! White did their best to keep the strong central pawns side by side, but now they are broken up. A very typical positional idea even though it is here connected with some tactics. The remaining moves of this trainable are just to show that everything works out tactically for Black. }
12. dxe5{ Hard to recommend something different. If White just exchanges  d4  against  e5 , Black will do fantastically. }( { For example after: }12.Nxe5 Qxd4 13.Bb2 Qd6∓ { All of Black's pieces will jump to good squares. } )
12. Nc5{ Black plays with some tactics related to White's piece placement on the queenside. Especially the  a1 -rook but also the knight on  b1  can be tactically vulnerable. }
13. Rd1( { White has nothing better, even though Black has nice compensation after just grabbing the bishop pair.     A)  }13.exf6 Bxf6 { is similar.    }{ The double attack against  a1  and  d3  will win back the piece. } )( {  B)  }13.Be2 Bf5 { develops with tempo and Black can just play for activity with ... Nfe4  next or go for the  e5 -pawn with ... Nfd7 . } )
13. Nxd3
14. Rxd3
14. Bf5{ White has to take on  d8  and the hanging pieces on  a1  and  b1  make sure that White cannot take on  f6 . }
15. Rxd8
15. Bxc2( { With the bishop pair, White's bad pieces and the weak structure, Black definitely has enough compensation.    White cannot win material because, for example, }16.Rxf8+ Kxf8 17.exf6 Bxf6 { wins back material on the queenside. } )
