1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. cxd5{ This move shows a lot of respect towards our dynamic options to play ... dxc4  and especially ... c5  at some point. It has been played occasionally by some very strong players, but I don't consider it a good move.     White will constantly get much worse versions of the 'normal' Schlexchange variation -  starting here  - as the queen on  c2  is simply extremely vulnerable and White even spent a tempo placing the queen there. }
5. cxd5
6. Bf4( { This is playable, but White should transpose with  7.Nc3  on the next move to the  main line  }6.Nc3 Nc6 7.Bf4 { . } )
6. Nc6{ A rule for other Schlexchange chapters: ... Nc6  is typically more flexible than ... Bg7  . }
7. e3{ This allows our typical bishop pair grab - something, we will see a lot in this course. }
7. Nh5{ White gets a very bad version of the lines spoken about in the  Schlexchange chapter . The queen move to  c2  doesn't make a lot of sense in this setup. }
8. Bb5
8. Bd7( { The easiest move. Black can also allow the structure after   }9.Bxc6+ bxc6 { but there is really no reason to do it.    Black can be slightly better without any imbalances. } )
9. O-O
9. Nxf4{ Taking the bishop pair. }
10. exf4
10. Bg7{ Black has a very solid position and the pair of bishops is a long-term factor. Black can just finish development with ... O-O , ... Rac8 , ... e6  with an easy game. }
