3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. cxd5{ This move shows a lot of respect towards our dynamic options to play ... dxc4  and especially ... c5  at some point. It has been played occasionally by some very strong players, but I don't consider it a good move.     White will constantly get much worse versions of the 'normal' Schlexchange variation -  starting here  - as the queen on  c2  is simply extremely vulnerable and White even spent a tempo placing the queen there. }
5. cxd5
6. Nc3{ White should definitely play this move now or on the next move. }
6. Nc6{ As we have just seen, we'll typically go ... Nc6  before ... Bg7 . }
7. Bg5{ This ignores the typical dynamic options of the Grünfeld Slav! }
7. Ne4{ A strong move. If White takes on  e4 , then Black will get a massive initiative. If White does not take, Black will have a very favourable version of the variations that we will see in the Exchange chapter. }
8. Nxe4{ Accepting the pawn gives Black a dangerous lead in development. }
8. dxe4
9. Qxe4
9. Bf5
10. Qh4{ The best square to keep some pressure on Black's kingside. }
10. Bg7{ Black just keeps developing. }
11. e4( { White has to move this pawn two squares to develop. }11.e3? { takes away some important escape squares for the bishop. }11...h6 12.Bf4 g5-+ { wins material. } )
11. h6{ An important in-between move. If Black had to retreat with the bishop, White would catch up in development. But 11... h6  is a strong reply. }
12. exf5( { A mistake but the only move where memorization is necessary.    A retreating move such as }12.Be3 { is better but Black can just win the  e4 -pawn. }12...g5 13.Qg3 Bxe4∓ { Material is even and White's king is still under fire. } )
12. hxg5{ After getting rid of White's dark-squared bishop, White can no longer block the ... Qa5  check with  Bd2 . }
13. Qxg5{ White can try to keep the queen in the defence but Black can make sure that White won't keep the control over  d2  for long. }
13. Bh6{ The queen is attacked and Black is getting ready to play ... Qa5 + to keep White's king in the center where it will most likely simply get checkmated. }
