4. g6
5. cxd5{ This move shows a lot of respect towards our dynamic options to play ... dxc4  and especially ... c5  at some point. It has been played occasionally by some very strong players, but I don't consider it a good move.     White will constantly get much worse versions of the 'normal' Schlexchange variation -  starting here  - as the queen on  c2  is simply extremely vulnerable and White even spent a tempo placing the queen there. }
