[White "4) Schlechter's Dream 4.Qc2"]
[Black "5.Bf4 & 6.cxd5 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4
5. Bg7( { I think }5...Bg7 { is a very principled response. Now, the position resembles lines from the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 { ) }{ just with  c7 - c6  and  Qd1 - c2  included.     It is true that ... c7 - c6  is not Black's most useful move, however, the move  Qc2  might even be disadvantageous for White. The queen is just really exposed on that square. } )
6. cxd5{ Usually, White will take on  d5  before playing the move  Bf4 . The reason is that the Grünfeld recapture ... Nxd5  gains a lot of strength!     If we can play this move with tempo, the 'tempo loss' of ... c7 - c6  is at least equalized and as White's setup is often not particularly directed against a Grünfeld setup, Black can often hope to get a strong initiative going. }
6. Bf5{ With the queen on  c2 , it makes sense to include this move. White cannot easily push for  e2 - e4  afterwards. }
7. Qb3{ The most logical square. White attacks  b7 . }
7. Nxd5{ In response, we attack the bishop on  f4 . The pawn on  b7  is poisoned. }
8. Bg3( { Better than taking on  b7 . }8.Qxb7? Nxf4! 9.Qxa8 Qb6! { , followed by }-- ...O-O { and a random knight move trap the queen! } )
8. Qb6( { This might look innocent at first glance but if White allows the queen exchange under the wrong circumstances, Black might just storm White's queenside.    }8...O-O { is another }{ typical move in these situations. White does not really want to take the pawn on  b7  while being so underdeveloped. } )
9. Nbd2{ White should develop the knight to make sure that they can recapture on  b3  with something else than the a-pawn. }
9. Qxb3{ This gives Black a pleasant endgame. }
10. Nxb3
10. Nd7{ Controlling  c5  and  e5  so that White cannot go  Nb3 - c5  or  Bf4 - e5 .     In the next moves, Black can go ... a7 - a5 - a4  to get rid of the knight on  b3  when Black can potentially also play ... c5 . Black has a nice position. }
