[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4
5. Bg7( { I think }5...Bg7 { is a very principled response. Now, the position resembles lines from the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 { ) }{ just with  c7 - c6  and  Qd1 - c2  included.     It is true that ... c7 - c6  is not Black's most useful move, however, the move  Qc2  might even be disadvantageous for White. The queen is just really exposed on that square. } )
6. e3
6. O-O
7. Bd3( { This is White's second most popular move after }7.Nc3 { but it is a serious mistake. I wouldn't give it any trainables when it hadn't been played even by some Grandmasters!    The main problem for White is that Black can play the Grünfeld break }7...c5 { here even better than after  7.Nc3  - and as we will see  here , even there it is working really nice for Black. } )
7. c5{ This is a very strong response. White's setup is not made for dynamics in the center. }
8. O-O( {  A)  }8.dxc5 Nc6 9.O-O { transposes. } )( {  B)  }8.cxd5? Nxd5! { is just bad because Black has ideas with ... Nb4  or just ... Nxf4  . }9.Qxc5 { The only justification that I can think of. }9...Nxf4! 10.exf4 Nc6!-+ { Black will just win back the  d4 -pawn and remain with the better structure, the two bishops and even a lead in development. } )
8. Nc6{ A strong move. Black just develops fast and fights for the initiative but White also shouldn't allow 9... cxd4  when they will remain with a really bad version of an isolated pawn. }( 8...cxd4 9.Nxd4 { is good for Black but at least White avoids the IQP }{ on  d4 . } )
9. dxc5{ The only move that avoids the IQP structure. }
9. Nd7( { This does not only attack  c5 , Black also creates the threat of   }10...Nb4 { , ... Nxd3  and ... Bxb2  as well as }10...e5 { , followed by the fork }-- ...e4 { . } )
10. Be2( { White really doesn't have anything better against Black's threats.     A)  }10.Nc3?! e5 11.cxd5 Nb4-+ { is winning a piece for Black. } )( {  B)  }10.cxd5 Nb4! 11.Qe2 Nxd3 12.Qxd3 Bxb2∓ { will win the exchange for Black. White will not have enough compensation. } )
10. Nxc5{ Black is just much more active in comparison and has ideas to just advance with ... e5  and ... d4 . Not to mention that ... Bf5  will be with tempo. }
11. cxd5{ The only move that might disturb Black's setup. }
11. Qxd5
12. Nc3
12. Qf5{ A very nice move. Black is ready to simplify the position but despite the symmetrical structure, White will face some serious problems.     Black's pieces are more active and especially the  d3 -square can be an inroad into White's camp. Just to give you a sample line: }( 13.Qxf5 Bxf5 14.Rfd1 Rfd8 { Both sides just improve their pieces. }15.Rac1 Nd3!? { and White would already be forced to give up the bishop pair with }16.Bxd3 { . } )
