[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4
5. Bg7( { I think }5...Bg7 { is a very principled response. Now, the position resembles lines from the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 { ) }{ just with  c7 - c6  and  Qd1 - c2  included.     It is true that ... c7 - c6  is not Black's most useful move, however, the move  Qc2  might even be disadvantageous for White. The queen is just really exposed on that square. } )
6. e3
6. O-O
7. Nbd2( { This move is better than }7.Bd3 { because White's position is not so vulnerable to the }...c5 { break - for one move! } )
7. Nbd7{ This is a nice move prepare ... c5 . Black also takes control over the  e5 -square which gives us the option to play ... Nh5  without allowing  Bf4 - e5 . }( 7...c5 { is topical but White can solve the tension slightly better than in other variations. }8.cxd5! Nxd5?! { allows White here to just snack the pawn on  c5  as there is no ... Nb4  threat in the position. }9.Bxb8! Rxb8 10.Qxc5 { and Black doesn't have enough compensation.    }8...cxd4 { is better but White can just play }9.e4! { with a nice center. } )
8. Be2{ This just makes it really easy to play ... c5 . }
8. c5{ Black just plans to take on  d4  and give White an IQP. Recapturing with the knight does not work because Black has ... e5 . }
9. cxd5{ If White wants to avoid ... cxd4 , they have to do something themselves in the center.     This move is at least better than taking on  c5 . }( 9.dxc5?! Nxc5 10.cxd5 { It is smart to take now on  d5 . We have to recapture with the queen to protect the  c5 -knight. }10...Qxd5 { Still, this position is pretty horrible for White. Our pieces are just much more active and ... Bf5  is coming as well. } )( 9.O-O { might be the best move but Black just plays }9...cxd4 10.exd4 dxc4 { , followed by ... Nb6 - d5  and just developing all pieces towards  d4 . This is a typical, very comfortable version of an IQP for Black in the Schlechter. } )
9. Nxd5{ Attacking  f4 . }
10. Bg3( { White should safe the bishop but Black has an instructive response. }10.dxc5 { doesn't win a pawn and so it is just giving away the bishop pair for free. }10...Nxf4! 11.exf4 Qc7 { with the double attack against  c5  and  f4 , Black wins back the pawn. } )
10. cxd4{ Black goes for the IQP structure. }
11. Nxd4
11. Bxd4{ Here we are even ready to give away our Grünfeld bishop! The resulting position gives us an easy plan evolving around White's weaknesses on the d-file. }
12. exd4
12. N7f6{ Black will just continue with ... Bf5 /... Be6 , ... Rc8 , something like ... Qd7  and ... Rfd8 , with an easy game.     It is true, that we would love to have our bishop on  g7  in this structure but you can't have everything in life. At least, White has a hard time 'punishing' Black's absence of the dark-squared bishop with a kingside attack, well, because none of White's pieces is really directed towards Black's kingside. }
