3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4
5. Bg7( { I think }5...Bg7 { is a very principled response. Now, the position resembles lines from the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 { ) }{ just with  c7 - c6  and  Qd1 - c2  included.     It is true that ... c7 - c6  is not Black's most useful move, however, the move  Qc2  might even be disadvantageous for White. The queen is just really exposed on that square. } )
6. e3
6. O-O
7. Nbd2( { This move is better than }7.Bd3 { because White's position is not so vulnerable to the }...c5 { break - for one move! } )
7. Nbd7{ This is a nice move prepare ... c5 . Black also takes control over the  e5 -square which gives us the option to play ... Nh5  without allowing  Bf4 - e5 . }( 7...c5 { is topical but White can solve the tension slightly better than in other variations. }8.cxd5! Nxd5?! { allows White here to just snack the pawn on  c5  as there is no ... Nb4  threat in the position. }9.Bxb8! Rxb8 10.Qxc5 { and Black doesn't have enough compensation.    }8...cxd4 { is better but White can just play }9.e4! { with a nice center. } )
8. Rc1{ With this move, White tries to keep an eye on the c-file as much as possible. }
8. Nh5{ Grabbing the bishop is working very nicely here. }
9. Bg5{ A typical move is to escape via  g5  but we have equally typical responses. }
9. h6
10. Bh4
10. c5( { A good moment to strike in the center even though Black could also go for the dark-squared bishop. }10...g5!? 11.Bg3 g4 { Misplacing the knight first before going  ...e5 . }12.Nh4 { The best square, looking towards  f5 . }12...e5! { In the resulting, dynamic position, Black's bishop pair - at some point, we take on  g3  - should give us the easier game. } )
11. dxc5( { Let's choose this as trainable because here, Black can use a tactic worth remembering.    }11.cxd5 cxd4! { is working well for Black. }12.Nxd4 Bxd4! 13.exd4 Nb6 { is a motif we have seen earlier which works well for Black while }12.e4 Nb6 { gives Black many breaks to disrupt White's center like }-- ...e6 { or }...f5 { . } )
11. Nxc5
12. cxd5( { Doesn't this just win a pawn?   }12...Qxd5?? 13.Qxc5 { doesn't work for Black - but we have a fantastic resource. } )
12. Bf5{ This is based on some nice tactics. }
13. Bxe7{ The only move to stay in the game. White forces Black's queen to  e7 . }( 13.Qxc5? Rc8! { loses the rook on  c1 . } )( 13.e4? { also doesn't work. }Nxe4! 14.Nxe4 Rc8 { White's queen is overloaded with the protection of  c1  and  e4  and so Black will win back their piece while remaining with the attack. } )
13. Qxe7
14. Qxc5{ Now, we can't play ... Rac8  because  e7  is hanging. }
14. Qf6( { Black just keeps the queens on the board and even though White is two pawns up, Black is doing great with ideas like  ...Rac8 .    To be honest, White also simply has problems keeping their pawns on the board, especially because White should prioritize bringing the king to safety.    Let's not go any deeper in the line as a trainable as it is very unlikely that anyone will ever encounter this exact position. But let's just see two potential follow-ups to illustrate the previous points.     A)    }15.Qd4 { Logical to block the long diagonal and avoid the  ...Rac8  threat. }15...Rac8! { White's problem on the c-file even continues with reduced material. }16.Rxc8 Rxc8 17.Qxf6 Nxf6 { and Black will win back the d5-pawn and have easily enough compensation for one pawn. }18.Bc4 b5! { is not possible.    }15...Qxd4 { Ruining White's structure and winning the d5-pawn immediately afterwards is also an idea. }16.Nxd4 Bxd4 17.exd4 Rfe8+ { , followed by  ...Nf4 .     B)    }15.Nc4 { looks like a very loose way of protecting  b2  and blocking the c-file but it seems possible. }15...Rfc8! { It is a nice subtlety to use the f-rook as the other rook might be active on  a8  (or  b8 ) after ... a6  and ... b5  . }16.Qb4 { White has to leave the queen on a square where she controls the  ...b5  move. }16...b5! { Still! Black gets a lot of open files on the queenside. }17.Qxb5 Rab8! 18.Qa5 Rxb2! { and Black has massive compensation for the pawn. }19.Be2 Qe7! { with the idea to go }-- ...Nf4 { .    The engine gives zeros but there is certainly a lot of life in the position! } )
