8. dxc5{ This is the typical reaction in these positions. White temporarily wins a pawn and Black at least has to spend a few tempi to win it back. }
8. Qa5{ The typical square for the queen. Not only do we attack  c5 , but there is also a lot of pressure against  c3 . }
9. Rc1{ This is a very solid move. In this whole variation, we will see many lines where Black creates pressure against  c3  so White just overprotects the point. }
9. Bf5( { Black has different ideas like }9...Na6 { but I think this is the trickiest move for White to face. } )
10. Qb3{ This allows typical counterplay. }
10. Ne4( { A typical move, increasing the pressure on  c3 .    }10...Nbd7 { is also okay. Let's look at different lines to show Black's dynamic ideas. White's uncastled king really gives Black a lot of room for creativity. } )
11. Nd4{ is a typical move to block the long diagonal but here Black can take over the initiative. }
11. e5
12. Nxf5{ Forced. }
12. gxf5
13. Bg3
13. d4{ White doesn't lose a piece but they have to spend time preventing it while Black just opens up the centre and attacks the poor fellow on  e1 . }
14. Qb5( { This way, White can save the piece but Black's initiative is just starting.    }14.Qa4 Qd8 { with similar motifs. } )
14. Qd8
15. Nd5( { After }15.Nxe4 fxe4 { , Black will just steamroll White with their center pawns. } )
15. f4{ Fantastic chess. Black just give all their pawns away to open the central files against White's king. }
16. f3( { A clever try not to open the e-file. }16.exf4 exf4 { followed by ... Re8  with a massive attack. } )
16. dxe3{ A sweet response. Black stays with strong pawns and the  g3 -bishop stays trapped. }
17. fxe4
17. Nc6{ Black will take on  g3  whenever we want but we also have other trumps like the juicy  d4 -square. }
