1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2( { This is one of the few moves where our Schlechter response }4...g6 { is indeed the most popular move. }{ The reason is simple: ... g6  prepares ... Bf5  which makes the queen's placement on  c2  pretty awkward. } )
4. g6
5. Bf4
5. Bg7( { I think }5...Bg7 { is a very principled response. Now, the position resembles lines from the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 { ) }{ just with  c7 - c6  and  Qd1 - c2  included.     It is true that ... c7 - c6  is not Black's most useful move, however, the move  Qc2  might even be disadvantageous for White. The queen is just really exposed on that square. } )
6. e3
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main move. }
7. c5{ A very principled move. The same position, with White's queen on  d1  instead of on  c2 , is one possible position in the Grünfeld (and is completely playable for Black). Here, we have an improved version as the queen on  c2  is pretty misplaced and can be attacked with some developing moves (... Bf5 , ... Na6 - b4 ). }
8. dxc5{ This is the typical reaction in these positions. White temporarily wins a pawn and Black at least has to spend a few tempi to win it back. }
8. Qa5{ The typical square for the queen. Not only do we attack  c5 , but there is also a lot of pressure against  c3 . }
9. Rc1{ This is a very solid move. In this whole variation, we will see many lines where Black creates pressure against  c3  so White just overprotects the point. }
9. Bf5( { Black has different ideas like }9...Na6 { but I think this is the trickiest move for White to face. } )
10. Qb3{ This allows typical counterplay. }
10. Ne4( { A typical move, increasing the pressure on  c3 .    }10...Nbd7 { is also okay. Let's look at different lines to show Black's dynamic ideas. White's uncastled king really gives Black a lot of room for creativity. } )
11. Be5{ is a typical move but here also too slow. }
11. Bxe5( { Black shouldn't take without a concrete idea in mind but here, we have a nice justification.    }11...Nxc5 { does also give Black a slightly more pleasant position. } )
12. Nxe5
12. Nc6{ A very nice follow-up. Black develops with tempo against the knight on  e5  and if White takes, then the b-file is ready for Black to invade. }
13. Nxc6{ White cannot really afford to lose more time by moving back with the knight. }
13. bxc6{ White is only one pawn up and  c5  is already hanging. ... Rab8  is coming. }
14. cxd5{ This is relatively best, trying to remain up material. }
14. Rab8{ Using the b-file to the fullest extent. }
15. Qa4( { White should try to exchange queens and this is the better way to do it.    }15.Qa3? Qxa3 16.bxa3 Nxc3 17.Rxc3 Rb1+!-+ { , followed by  ...cxd5  makes it really hard for White to ever develop their kingside - and it is only a matter of time when Black will win back more of White's pawns. } )
15. Qxc5( { Black keeps up the pressure and White has problems untangling. White also cannot easily exchange queens.    For example, }16.Qc4 Qa5 17.Qa4 Qb6 { is a nice queen dance when White cannot take on  e4  because }18.Nxe4? Qxb2 { has a double threat for Black in form of }-- ...Qxc1 { and }...Rb4 { .    Black will win back the material and the attack is too strong. } )
