7. Nc3{ This is the main move. }
7. c5{ A very principled move. The same position, with White's queen on  d1  instead of on  c2 , is one possible position in the Grünfeld (and is completely playable for Black). Here, we have an improved version as the queen on  c2  is pretty misplaced and can be attacked with some developing moves (... Bf5 , ... Na6 - b4 ). }
8. dxc5{ This is the typical reaction in these positions. White temporarily wins a pawn and Black at least has to spend a few tempi to win it back. }
8. Qa5{ The typical square for the queen. Not only do we attack  c5 , but there is also a lot of pressure against  c3 . }
9. Qa4{ This is a move that has been played a few times but to me, this just looks like a move made out of fear of some tactics against the knight on  c3 .     White cannot hope for more than a simplified position where rather Black is better. }
9. Qxc5
10. Qb5( { Believe it or not, this is the main move. Reducing the pressure is really all White can hope for in this position.     A)  The 'active' }10.b4 { was played twice in practice but White doesn't gain anything from this b-pawn adventure. }10...Qc6 { The  a1-h8  diagonal looks menacing. }11.b5 Qc5 { White has the same position with the pawn on  b2 . Now, the long diagonal is just more threatening than before. } )( {  B)  }10.cxd5 { If White takes on  d5 , this is usually in Black's favour. The  g7 -bishop opens up. }10...Nxd5 11.Nxd5 Qxd5 12.Bc4 Qc6 { The pawn structure is simplified but the pressure against  b2  can become very annoying for White. } )
10. Qxb5{ We don't mind exchanging queens. Black should have a little bit of pressure in the resulting endgame. }
11. Nxb5( { This is the usual way to recapture. White threatens  12.Nc7 .    }11.cxb5!? { was played in some games, trying to restrict the knight on  b8 . A creative idea but not particularly good. After }11...Nbd7 { , }{ Black can just develop the knight to  b6  or  c5 , followed by natural developing moves like ... Bf5  and centralising the rooks.     White just weakened their pawn structure as Black does now have a healthy pawn majority in the center while White's pawns on the queenside will be much harder to push. } )
11. Na6{ Defending against the threat!     With best play, White should reach a draw but the practice has shown that it is not so easy. Black will just develop naturally with ... Bd7 / f5 / g4 , ... Rac8 , ... Rfd8  and waits for a good moment to open up the dark-squared bishop on  g7  or jump at the opponent with ... Nb4  or ... Nc5 .     How easy things can go wrong for White shows the line: }( 12.Be2?! dxc4! 13.Bxc4 Nd7! { and White has problems defending the  b2 -pawn. }14.Rb1?! Nb6! { with the double attack ... Nxc4  and ... Bf5 . }15.Bd3?! { Only makes matters worse. }15...Nb4!-+ { and White has problems defending their queenside.    Obviously, this was a bad line from White's perspective but it just shows how easily Black's queenside pressure can manifest into something concrete. } )
