9. Ne4( { Equality is not Black's biggest problem in this line. Black could also achieve this with moves like }9...Bf5 { or }9...dxc4 { .    Creating as many imbalances as possible was the bigger task for yours truly. However, I am happy with the move }9...Ne4 { . }{ Objectively, this is also equal, but by creating a pawn weakness on  c3 , we'll take a nice first step to give us targets to play against. } )
10. cxd5{ Taking as many pawns as possible. }
10. Nxc3( 10...Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 Nxc3 { seems also playable. I just like to keep the dark-squared bishop. } )
11. bxc3
11. Nd7{ The typical move to win back the  c5 -pawn. The knight will be superbly placed on  c5 . }( 11...Bxc3+?! 12.Nd2 { makes it hard for Black to win back the  c5 -pawn without making too many concessions. For example }12...Qxc5? 13.Rc1 Bxd2+ 14.Qxd2+- { forces us to exchange all our good pieces and we would remain with an underdeveloped queenside mess while White has the two bishops and a strong d-pawn. } )
{ Why it is so important not to allow ... Bf5  can be seen if White just ignores it. }12. Be2
12. Nxc5
13. Be5( { Neutralizing the dark-squared bishop is usually a good idea for White. However, stopping  ...Bf5  is more important.     A)  }13.O-O?! Bf5 { and White loses  a2  or  c3  under bad circumstances. } )( {  B)  }13.Nd4 { would transpose to the  last trainable  of this chapter. } )
13. Bf5
14. Qb2( { This seems to be the best square because White does at least get the queens off. }14.Qc1 Ne4 { doesn't save the  c3 -pawn. } )
14. Na4{ A typical square to attack  c3  and here it even comes with tempo. }
15. Qb4
15. Qxb4{ It is very typical for this line that Black's compensation is still very strong with the queens off. }
16. cxb4
16. Nc3{ Often, we win a pawn on this square but even without it, this is a nice outpost. The knight attacks  a2 ,  d1 ,  d5  and  e2 . }
17. Rd2( { White protects everything. }17.Bxg7 Kxg7 { doesn't change too much. } )
17. a5{ Black tries to open the queenside as much as possible. Black is much better because White is completely tied down.     They cannot take on  c3  because this would pin the  d2 -rook. }( { White cannot castle because of ideas with }18.O-O Nxe2+ Rxe2 Bd3 { while Black can always just try to win the d-pawn with ... Rfd8  or just invade via the c-file. } )
