[White "5) Exchange Variation 3.cxd5"]
[Black "Introduction Exchange Variation"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5( { This is the Exchange Variation or 'boring crap' as some people call it. The structure is symmetrical, that's true, but that doesn't mean that game is necessarily becoming boring!    I think especially as Grünfeld Slav players, we don't have to worry too much about the game being exciting. I did my best to choose weapons that create as many imbalances as possible. And let's put modesty aside, I'm pretty happy with the variations I've put together!     Which variations will we cover in this chapter?     Here, we'll only cover variations that are 'typical' for the move order   }3.cxd5 cxd5 { . This includes some weird early sidelines like }4.Bg5 { -  starting here  - or }4.Nc3 Nf6 5.f3 { -  see here . }{ Besides those variations, White usually chooses this move order to develop their dark-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain to  f4  - here, there is no pawn on  c4  that we can grab - and then just develop with  Nb1 - c3 ,  e2 - e3 ,  Ng1 - f3 .    Luckily for us, there are not that many move orders that have some independent meaning: Especially lines where White combines an early  Nb1 - c3  and  Ng1 - f3  are prone to transposing to other chapters. } )( {  A)  }4.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 g6 { leads to the next chapter, the  'Schlexchange' . } )( {  B)  The same applies to the move order }4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Bf4 Nc6 5.Nf3 g6 { that also transposes to one of our Schlexchange chapters - like  this  } )( {  C)  }4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bf4 Nc6 6.e3 { is known to be a very innocuous move order -  see here  } )( {  D)  Overall, this leaves us with only one really critical move order: White postponing  Ng1-f3 . After, for example, }4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Bf4 Nc6 6.e3 { , I will explain later why opting for a Schlechter with }6...g6 { might not be the wisest of decisions. However, because this is the only real position with independent meaning we can cherry-pick the most aggressive of Black's options in the given positions. I'll make a case for the aggressive }6...Bg4!? { that can lead to very entertaining positions as you will see.    }{ Rules for this chapter:      1.  We play ... Ng8 - f6  typically before ... Nb8 - c6 . The reason is simplicity, as we might reach the same positions via other move orders where our knight is already committed to  f6 . }{ For example   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { would also lead to the Exchange variation.    }{  2.  In the Exchange variations, the move ... Nc6  is typically more flexible than ... g6  or ... Bg7 . I might choose one of the latter moves over ... Nc6  if it immediately transposes to a variation that we have to learn via other move orders anyway, but usually, you do nothing wrong if you start with the knight move.    Setups that we will not discuss in this chapter are:    - The exchange variations with  g2-g3     - The exchange variations with  e2-e3  } )
