[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Exchange Variation 3.cxd5"]
[Black "6.Bb5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Bf4( { This move, followed by  5.e3 , is indeed the most popular move order for White. In our repertoire, there is no big difference and the game will most likely transpose to lines that we reach via the }4.Nc3 { move order. } )
4. Nf6( { In this position, it doesn't matter if we start with }4...Nf6 { or }{ . We play both moves as soon as we can so they usually transpose. } )
5. e3{ The typical follow-up. }
5. Nc6
6. Bb5( { A not-so-common move. }6.Nf3 { or }6.Nc3 { transpose to variations we'll reach via the  4.Nc3 / 4.Nf3  move orders.   }{ White puts some pressure on  c6  and is ready to give away the bishop pair on that square to leave Black with a pawn weakness. In some positions,  Nf3 - e5  and  Qd1 - a4  can be ideas to increase the pressure towards  d7 . } )
6. e6{ I believe this is both a very practical response and that it fits nicely to the lines from the Schlechter Exchange chapter. With White's bishop on  b5 , it is useful to have the option of ... Bd7 . So developing the light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain might play into White's cards.  More concretely, we want to play a quick ... Be7  to prepare ... Nh5  without running into the  Bf4 - g5  response.     The resulting positions will have a close resemblance to lines from the  Schlexchange chapter . }
7. Nc3( { The most popular move even though White can also start with }7.Nf3 { . } )
7. Be7{ Black is getting ready to play ... Nh5  after  8.Nf3  by taking away White's options to play  Bf4 - g5  afterwards. }
8. h3{ If White wants to stop ... Nh5 , this is a very typical reaction. However, with such a move White will have no chances for an opening advantage. }
8. O-O{ Black just develops naturally. }
9. Nf3{ Now, White can play this move without any issues. }
9. Ne4{ An interesting move to create imbalances. Black wants to take on  c3 . }
10. O-O{ The most natural move. White just finishes their development. }
10. Nxc3{ That was the idea. }
11. bxc3
11. Na5{ A typical move. Black controls the  c4 -square and would love to use this square as an outpost. }
12. Bd3{ The bishop on  b5  no longer has a purpose. Black will play ... Bd7  anyways and the last thing White wants to do is exchange their light-squared bishop.  Typically in this structure, White wants to keep as many pieces as possible on the board because, in the endgame, the  c3 -pawn will be a long-term weakness. Usually, White goes for dynamic chess and tries to decide the game in the middlegame. }
12. Bd7{ Black's play is pretty straightforward. We play ...  Rc8  to make use of the half-open c-file.  ... Bc6  is a nice move because, after that, White has a harder time playing  e3 - e4  without exchanging light-squared bishops - which would be clearly in Black's favour. After that, Black can play ... Bd6  to offer the exchange of dark-squared bishops. }
13. Qc2{ This is White's most critical move. White asks some questions on the kingside by attacking  h7 . After other moves, Black would just continue with the simple plan just mentioned. }
13. h6( { There is nothing inherently wrong with }13...g6 { . Pawn-structure-wise, this is something we will see in many other variations. Concretely, White might try to exploit our dark-squared weaknesses with }14.Bh6 { - our butcher is not on its usual square! } )( 13...h6 { is safer. } )
14. Rfe1( 14.e4 dxe4 15.Bxe4 Bc6! { is currently not leading anywhere. Exchanging light-squared bishops is what Black wants. } )
14. Bc6{ The safest move to stop  e3 - e4 . }( 14...Rc8 { is also playable but White can push }15.e4 { . Stockfish justifies Black's last move with the extremely concrete computer line }15...Bb4! 16.Bd2 dxe4 17.Rxe4 f5! { followed by ... Bd6  and ...  Nc4  when it appears that Black is fine.     However, it is easier simply not to allow all of this. } )
15. Ne5{ Bringing the knight to this nice outpost. White should still try to build their pieces up on the kingside. }
15. Rc8( { The typical setup. White has different attacking ideas.  A logical follow-up would be }16.Qe2 { to bring the queen into the attack via  g4  or  h5 . Ideas with  Bxh6  might be in the air soon. Black however has enough defensive resources.  The main thing we have to do is avoid scenarios where White can simply assemble their pieces on the kingside while our pieces are stuck on the other side of the board. We want to challenge White's attacking pieces!     In this regard, ... Bd6  is a typical move to be ready to either exchange the knight on  e5  or the bishop on  f4 . If White brings their queen over to the kingside, we should make sure that her majesty doesn't feel too safe there.  ... f5  is an important resource against a queen landing on  g4 . The f-pawn move does weaken our position but it also shuts down the bishop on  d3  and allows us to defend our kingside along the 7th rank. The light-squared holes can be defended with ... Be8  - a move that also takes away the  h5 -square from White's queen.  Long story short - we shouldn't get mated and our counterplay on the queenside will come sooner or later. } )
