1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Bf4( { This move, followed by  5.e3 , is indeed the most popular move order for White. In our repertoire, there is no big difference and the game will most likely transpose to lines that we reach via the }4.Nc3 { move order. } )
4. Nf6( { In this position, it doesn't matter if we start with }4...Nf6 { or }{ . We play both moves as soon as we can so they usually transpose. } )
5. e3{ The typical follow-up. }
5. Nc6
6. Bb5( { A not-so-common move. }6.Nf3 { or }6.Nc3 { transpose to variations we'll reach via the  4.Nc3 / 4.Nf3  move orders.   }{ White puts some pressure on  c6  and is ready to give away the bishop pair on that square to leave Black with a pawn weakness. In some positions,  Nf3 - e5  and  Qd1 - a4  can be ideas to increase the pressure towards  d7 . } )
6. e6{ I believe this is both a very practical response and that it fits nicely to the lines from the Schlechter Exchange chapter. With White's bishop on  b5 , it is useful to have the option of ... Bd7 . So developing the light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain might play into White's cards.  More concretely, we want to play a quick ... Be7  to prepare ... Nh5  without running into the  Bf4 - g5  response.     The resulting positions will have a close resemblance to lines from the  Schlexchange chapter . }
7. Nc3( { The most popular move even though White can also start with }7.Nf3 { . } )
7. Be7{ Black is getting ready to play ... Nh5  after  8.Nf3  by taking away White's options to play  Bf4 - g5  afterwards. }
8. h3{ If White wants to stop ... Nh5 , this is a very typical reaction. However, with such a move White will have no chances for an opening advantage. }
8. O-O{ Black just develops naturally. }
9. Nf3{ Now, White can play this move without any issues. }
9. Ne4{ An interesting move to create imbalances. Black wants to take on  c3 . }
10. Bd3{ A clever move. White anticipates that the bishop will no longer be useful on  b5  in the structures after .... Nxc3  and  bxc3  and immediately brings it to its best square.  Not castling themselves also has the advantage that White can easier attack with g- and h-pawn. }
10. Nxc3{ That was the idea. }
11. bxc3
11. Bd6( { Against White's move order, we have to play carefully.    For example }11...Na5 { is risky as it removes one more piece from the kingside. }12.Qc2 { forces some weakness on the kingside and it seems White always gets a strong initiative. For example }12...h6 13.g4! { followed by  g4 - g5  can be very risky.     With  11...Bd6  , Black is starting to exchange some pieces. It is true that our dark-squared bishop is our 'good bishop' in this structure with the  d5 - e6 - f7 -pawn chain but because of the  c3 -weakness, we will be happy with most endgames and the structure can easily change anyway - either because we play ... e6 - e5  or because White feels like changing the structure with  e3 - e4  or  c3 - c4 . } )
12. O-O{ White should just develop. As we will see, ... Bxf4  is not really something that White should stop.      The attacking plan against 11... Na5  doesn't really work here. }( 12.Qc2 h6 13.g4?! { Black is much better set-up to counter attack in the center. For example }13...f6! { is a strong reply.  g4 - g5  is stopped and ... e5  is in the air. } )
12. Qc7( { Spending a tempo to make sure that we get the bishop exchange under our circumstances.    }12...Bxf4 13.exf4 { is also playable, but White gets the half-open e-file immediately and might use it to build up on the kingside:  Re1 ,  h3 - h4 - h5 ,  Ne5 . The pawn on  f4  is not really a weakness. } )
13. Bxd6( { Protecting  f4  with something like }13.Qd2 { doesn't make a lot of sense here. }{ Black will just continue with ...  b6 , ... Bb7 , ... Rac8  in typical fashion.  White cannot really do anything active with their pieces here. } )
13. Qxd6{ A typical situation: If White plays slow, Black will just play ... b6 , ... Bb7  and put rooks on the c.-file.  Despite having the 'bad bishop', we have a very easy plan and I am not sure if White can claim the same. So White should aim to find something dynamic. }
14. Qe2{ White is planning  e3 - e4  and  Qxe4  with mating threats against  h7 . After other moves, Black can just develop with the ... b6 , ... Bb7  plan. }( { The immediate }14.e4 dxe4 15.Bxe4 b6 { followed by ... Bb7  (or even .... Ba6 ) is just fine for Black. } )( { Playing for the  c3-c4  break with something like }14.Rc1 { is also possible. However, Black doesn't mind that change of structure as well. }14...b6 15.c4 dxc4 16.Rxc4 { White is ready to create some pressure along the c-file. However, with the 2 vs. 1 majority on the queenside, we are not too unhappy. }16...Ne7! { Black prepares to fight back along the c-file. }( { ( }16...Bb7 17.Qa4! Rfc8 18.Rfc1 { might give White some pressure because the knight on  c6  cannot move for now - after the exchange of rooks, there would be  Qe8+ .) } ) )
14. e5{ An idea to keep in mind. Black strikes first in the center.  With an open center, White won't be able to create attacking chances. }( 14...b6?! 15.e4! { is what White is hoping for. }15...dxe4 16.Qxe4 { with an attack against Black's king. For example, }16...g6 17.Qh4! { → with the threat of }-- 18.Ng5 { . } )
