1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Bg5{ A funny-looking move. The bishop doesn't attack anything right now but it pins the e-pawn and if Black goes ... Nf6 , White will take and spoil Black's pawn structure.  However, this line is not critical and Black has good ways to prove that the bishop on  g5  is rather a target than a useful piece. }
4. f6{ Not the only good move but very tempting. In this repertoire, we will have many positions where we play ... f6 .     This is one of our better versions. }
5. Bf4{ Here, the bishop is just very vulnerable. }
5. Nc6{ Black prepares ... e5 . }
6. Nf3{ White prevents it. }
6. g5{ A shocker move, but in these exchange variations, we will see it frequently that one side can attack with the kingside pawns without a care in the world. Because the center is so closed, this is often a very appropriate idea - like here!     Indeed, this move leads to positions that we will later in the chapter see with the black colour! In these lines, we play ... Bg4  to provoke  f2 - f3  and to justify it, White should continue aggressively with  g2 - g4 . Here, we got both pawn moves with tempo instead of one so we equalized the minus tempo that we have from being Black and are all of a sudden playing more or less a White opening!     Even though I am convinced that Black can equalize in those lines, it is still a pleasant opening outcome for Black to have a position after 6 moves that some players usually strive for with White! }
7. Bg3{ The bishop might indeed become a target on  g3 .     ... Nh6 - f5 , ... h5  are typical ideas. }
7. g4{ Concretely, this is an even better move. The knight has no good squares. }
8. Nh4{ On  h4  it stops ... h5 - h4  but the knight itself can be a target. }
8. e5{ Black can just take the center. }
9. e3{ White tries to stabilize but Black can increase the pressure. }
9. f5( { A very strong move. Black is threatening   }10...Be7 { as well as }10...f4 { .    It is hard for White to find a move. } )
