4. Nf3( { To play the Exchange Slav with an early  Nf3  is possible but there are barely any lines that would not transpose to lines from the }4.Nc3 { move order. } )
4. Nf6( { The typical reply because we could also reach this position via the move order   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { . } )
5. Bf4( { The only move that could lead to independent positions.     A)  }5.Nc3 g6 { transposes to the  Schlechter Exchange  chapter.     B)    }5.Bg5 Ne4 { makes no sense for White. } )
5. Nc6
6. e3{ This is the only independent move order. However, postponing  Nb1 - c3  is not only unnecessary, Black also has objectively better options than in other lines. }( 6.Nc3 g6 { does once again transpose to our  Schlechter Exchange variation . } )
6. Nh5{ I think this is the best fitting move for our repertoire. We will mainly play the mainline from our Schlechter Exchange chapter but without the moves  Nb1 - c3  and ... g7 - g6  included.  In some of those variations, Black played an early ... g5  to hunt White's bishop down. Allowing Black the same ideas without having played ... g6  earlier can lead to the same positions but with a full extra tempo for Black.  But even if White plays a setup where Black usually doesn't play ... g5 , there is simply no scenario where omitting the moves  Nc3  and ... g6  is beneficial for White. }( { For conclusiveness' sake, let's just point out that the move }7...Qb6 { is also quite annoying for White. } )
7. Be5{ This is the only critical move - even though it is not as effective as with Blacks  g7 -pawn on  g6 ! }( {  A)  }7.Bg5 h6 8.Bh4 g5 { would exactly be the kind of variation where Black is a full tempo up compared to Schlechter Exchange variations -  see here . } )( {  B)  }7.Bg3 { is never critical even with  Nc3  and ... g6  included. }{ So Black can even play }Nxg3 8.hxg3 g6!? { which will transpose to those lines. If Black wants to play more subtle, we can also play }8...e6 { or }8...Bd7 { first. } )
7. f6{ We can just copy our antidote from the  sister variation . }
8. Bg3
8. e6{ An easy move, trying to get an improved version of the sister variation. In that variation, Black does often play ... Be7  instead of ... Bg7 . }( { So we could consider playing }8...g6 { which would most likely transpose but that move serves no great purpose for now.  Here, we can just start with ... Be7 , ... Bd7 , ... O-O  before deciding if we really want to touch our g-pawn. } )
