[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order. The main line -  starting here  - can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { . } )
5. Bg5{ A rare move because Black has a convincing antidote. Nevertheless, the move has its supporters.  Most notably, GM Anton Korobov likes to play this line in short time controls - White is planning to take on  f6  and spoil Black's pawn structure. }
5. Ne4{ Even here this move is playable. Black is attacking the bishop on  g5  but we also have the idea to either take on  c3  and force White to the  bxc3 -pawn structure or we can just increase the pressure with ... Qa5 .     White should definitely take it - otherwise, the last move would have been very pointless. }
6. Nxe4
6. dxe4( { White's main problem is that it is impossible to play }7.e3 { because of }7...Qa5+ { . This makes it slightly uncomfortable to develop the pieces for White. } )
7. a3{ Believe it or not, this is White's main move. Taking control over the  b4 -square stops all ideas connected with ... Bb4 + - but it is one additional tempo that White wastes in the opening. }
7. h6( { This move forces White to find a good square for the bishop. As we will see this is not so easy.  To be fair, Black has plenty of good options like }7...Qd5 { , }7...Qb6 { or }7...g6 { as well. } )
8. Bd2{ This is an odd-looking pawn sacrifice but it might be White's best move objectively. Nevertheless, I have the feeling that White can barely hope for more than winning back the sacrificed pawn. }
8. Qxd4( { Black should accept the challenge. White hopes for a slow position like }8...Nc6?! 9.e3 { when White consolidates with the slightly better structure. } )
9. Qc2{ This is White's best move. The queen protects  b2  and by keeping an eye on the  e4 -pawn - currently White is also attacking  c8  - Black has no great squares for their queen after the coming  e2 - e3 . }( 9.e3? Qxb2 { doesn't promise White nearly enough compensation. } )
9. Nd7{ The best square for the knight. Once White has played  e2 - e3 , they will have holes on  b3  and  d3 . The knight would be placed ideally on  c5  to occupy both squares. }
10. e3
10. Qb6{ The computer claims that White can equalise with best play. Nevertheless, Black's play is just so much easier:  ... Nc5 , ... Bf5 , ... e6 , invading on either  b3  or  d3 . }( 11.Qxe4 Qxb2 { is also slightly better for Black. } )
