1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order. The main line -  starting here  - can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { . } )
5. f3{ This move with the aggressive idea to go  e2 - e4  is completely different from most variations from the exchange variation. The problem is that 5.f3 does also weaken the dark squares in White's camp and Black has a nice way to exploit this. }
5. Qb6{ Very annoying for White. Black starts to fight for the  g1 - a7  diagonal. }
6. e4( { This is White's main move and the critical response. Nevertheless, White might regret his opening against a decently prepared Black player.    IM Hauge played the modest }6.e3 { twice to avoid the problems of the main line. However, the move  f3  just doesn't make a lot of sense here.  Black should be more than fine no matter what. }6...Nc6 7.Bd3 e5! { might be the most aggressive (and best) way to punish White. } )
6. dxe4
7. fxe4
7. e5{ This is Black's idea. Suddenly, White's dark squares feel horribly weak. }
8. Bb5+{ This is White's main try to justify the aggressive opening choice. I think Black is slightly better but at least we have to avoid some pitfalls. }( {  A)  }8.dxe5 { is not good as White will lose the pawn back after }8...Ng4 { and Black remains with the better structure. } )( {  B)  }8.Nf3 exd4 { followed by ... Bc5  is also just asking for trouble on the dark squares. } )
8. Nc6{ A strong response. It looks risky to put the knight in the pin but the tactics don't work for White. }( 8...Bd7 { is also possible but much riskier. }9.dxe5 Bxb5 10.exf6 { and Black has to find some very computerlike moves ( }10...Bc4! { ) to survive. } )
9. d5{ The only move. White is attacking the pinned knight.     How can Black avoid losing a piece? }
9. Bb4( { A strong reply. By counter-pinning the  c3 -knight, Black threatens   }10...Qxb5 { and }10...Nxe4 { . } )
10. Qd3( { White has to keep the tension. Once Black stabilizes, White will suffer from their overextended position.     A)  }10.Ba4? Nxe4! { doesn't work for White.  c3  is hanging, there is a small mate on  f2  - nothing White should allow. } )( {  B)  }10.Qe2?! { is similar to  10.Qd3  but not quite as good. Black can just copy the recipe against it. }10...a6! 11.Ba4 Qa5! { ∓ Black is threatening }-- 12...Qxa4 { but we are also ready for }12...b5 { to unpin the knight. } )
10. a6{ Forcing the bishop to  a4  where it has less support. }
11. Ba4
11. Qa5{ Playing with the same tactics as before. Black is threatening ... Qxa4  and we can also go .... b5  if necessary. }
12. Bd1{ The only safe square for the bishop if Black plays ...  Nd4  next. }( { Something like }12.Bd2 { allows Black a comfortable position. The easiest way is the simple }12...Bxc3 { removing the defender of the  a4 -bishop. }13.Bxc6+ bxc6 14.Bxc3 { when Black should be slightly better after more or less any of the queen moves }14...Qb5 { , }14...Qa4 { or }14...Qb6 { . } )
12. Nd4{ It is still a complicated position but I would prefer Black. White has many holes in their position.  ... Bd7  and ... Bb5  seems to be a nice manoeuvre for Black to start the invasion. }
13. Nge2( 13.Bd2 { is the second most popular move but we can play in the same style: }13...Bd7 { , followed by ... Bb5 . } )
13. Bd7{ Preparing ... Bb5 . With best play, White seems to hold but Black has easy play. }( { The game could continue }14.O-O O-O ( { ( The immediate }14...Bb5? 15.Qg3! { is surprisingly annoying.) } )15.a3 Bb5! { White has to take. }16.Nxb5 Qxb5 17.Qxb5 axb5 18.Nxd4 Bc5! { and in the endgame, Black should be slightly pressing.  e4  is hanging,  b2  is weak once we have played ... Bxd4  and ... b4  is in the air. } )
