[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order. The main line -  starting here  - can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { . } )
5. Bf4{ The main move. White just develops the bishop to a safe square and will play  e2 - e3  and most likely  Nf3  next with very solid development. }
5. Nc6
6. e3( { The independent move order. }6.Nf3 g6 { transposes to the Schlechter Exchange chapter. This variation is arguably the most important one in this chapter.  Unfortunately, we cannot really enter 'Schlechter territory' with   }6...g6 { under good circumstances. That means we have to find a more mainline solution. } )
6. Bg4( { I choose the move }6...Bg4 { for different reasons.     1)  It is only the fourth most popular move in this position. That means White players might not be as familiar with this move as with the alternatives }6...Bf5 { , }6...a6 { or }6...e6 { .     2)  If White responds with the most critical move   }7.f3 { , the position will be really imbalanced. Ideal to play for a win!     3)  The move has the best score - pretty much 50%. } )
7. f3{ This is White's sharpest move. After the move  f2 - f3 , White should follow it up with aggressive moves on the kingside like  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4 .     Otherwise, the pawn on  f3  would serve no purpose and White would have just weakened their king and taken away the  f3 -square for the knight without any compensation. }
7. Bd7( { We should go back into safety with this bishop. Playing }7...Bh5?! { would play into White's cards as the bishop allows  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4 - h5  with tempo. } )
8. Bd3{ The most popular move. For White's aggressive intentions, the bishop clearly belongs to  d3 . }( { White can also start with }8.g4 { but Black's setup remains the same; ... e6 , ... Be7 , ... Rc8  and at some point, White should put the bishop on  d3 . } )
8. e6{ This is not only a simple developing move, it also prepares ... Nh5  to win the bishop pair - the bishop no longer has the  g5 -square. White should definitely do something about it. }( { After }9.Nge2 Nh5! { , for example, Black would already be slightly better. } )
9. Bg3{ This move has been played a number of times to address the ... Nh5  idea. The bishop would now be ready to drop back to  f2 .     The main drawback is that Black can just start their queenside counterplay very easily. }
9. Be7{ First we develop. With White's bishop on  g3 , we can also safely castle as White has no pawn storm on the kingside. }
10. Nge2{ White's typical follow-up. }
10. O-O( { Black can also start with the queenside play immediately with moves like }10...a6 { or }10...Rc8 { but as White has no kingside attack, we can play as we should do in most opening variations by castling early. } )
11. O-O
11. a6( 11...Rc8 { is also possible. } )
12. Rc1
12. b5{ Black's queenside play is pretty easy. ... Rc8 , ... Na5 - c4 , ... b4 , maybe including the a-pawn or playing ... Bb5 .     White has some slow plans like pushing  e3 - e4  or building a battery towards  h7  with something like  Bb1 ,  Qd3 ,  Nf4 - h5  but Black's queenside play should be enough to counter these plans. }
