9. Bg5{ This move, with the idea to play  f3 - f4  to reach some kind of Stonewall formation has been played by Morozevich and Nepomniachtchi.     Nepo's opponent, Jordan van Foreest found a nice antidote that we can copy. }
9. Be7{ Simple development for now. Black prepares to castle. }
10. f4{ The main move connected with  9.Bg5 . }( { White could also play similar to our last trainable with }10.Nge2 { . Black's plan would here be the same. Castling and then start a queenside initiative. For example }10...O-O 11.O-O Rc8 { , followed by ... a6 , ... b5 , ... Na5 .     The typical stuff! } )
10. O-O
11. Nf3
11. Ne8{ A very nice move. The knight is heading towards  d6  where it controls many central squares.  Equally important is the fact that Black gets more flexibility on the kingside to play moves like ... f6  to take away the  e5  and  g5 -squares and to just get more control in general about the kingside where White would usually love to attack in the Stonewall.     Check out the short but sweet model game Nepomniachtchi - van Foreest -  see here . }
