[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { We will choose this as White's main move order. The main line -  starting here  - can also be reached via }4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf6( { We have to play this position anyways. Another move order to reach it is   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { . } )
5. Bf4{ The main move. White just develops the bishop to a safe square and will play  e2 - e3  and most likely  Nf3  next with very solid development. }
5. Nc6
6. e3( { The independent move order. }6.Nf3 g6 { transposes to the Schlechter Exchange chapter. This variation is arguably the most important one in this chapter.  Unfortunately, we cannot really enter 'Schlechter territory' with   }6...g6 { under good circumstances. That means we have to find a more mainline solution. } )
6. Bg4( { I choose the move }6...Bg4 { for different reasons.     1)  It is only the fourth most popular move in this position. That means White players might not be as familiar with this move as with the alternatives }6...Bf5 { , }6...a6 { or }6...e6 { .     2)  If White responds with the most critical move   }7.f3 { , the position will be really imbalanced. Ideal to play for a win!     3)  The move has the best score - pretty much 50%. } )
7. Nf3{ This is the move that White can choose if they want to keep the game as balanced as possible. No pawn storm on the kingside - just symmetrical development. }( { If we talk about boring chess, we might also talk about the move }7.Be2 { which really has no other purpose than to exchange one pair of minor pieces. However, this is not an exchange that Black is particularly unhappy about.  The light-squared bishop is technically White's 'good bishop' in this structure because all their central pawns are on dark squares so exchanging this piece has some clear drawbacks. The light squares just get much weaker and there are many games that have solely been won in this structure because Black could make good use of the resulting light-squared weaknesses.  Especially  c4  can become a nice outpost. After some development, moves like ... Rc8  and ... Na5 - c4  are extremely typical.  Let's not talk White's position worse than it is - that Black exchanges their own 'good' bishop with ... Bd6  is also not completely ridiculous - but Black would get a very easy plan very early on in the opening. } )
7. Rc8( { A slightly unusual move but only because Black's most natural move doesn't work perfectly here.    }7...e6?! 8.Qb3! { asks some unpleasant questions. }{ That the  g4 -bishop has no way back to  d7  can become crucial. For example }8...Na5? 9.Qa4+! { is just lost because White comes with moves like  Nf3 - e5  or  Nc3 - b5 . } )
8. Be2{ This is a solid move but White is obviously not overly ambitious. }
8. e6{ Black is just completely fine. I don't want to prolong the trainable unnecessarily if Black has a good position no matter what.  I think there are two different approaches in general if you want to win such a position with Black.      1)  You just enjoy that you have equalised comfortably on move 8, with all pieces on the board and you just develop in a way that as many pieces as possible stay on the board: ... Be7 , ... O-O . You just trust the complexity of the game that chances will appear in the future      2)  You just actively create imbalances - usually my approach in this repertoire. In this regard, it is possible to go for a bishop vs. knight imbalance by playing ... Bxf3  and then ... Bd6  to cut White's bishop pair in half. }( { A typical continuation for the second approach would be: }9.O-O Bxf3!? 10.Bxf3 Bd6 { If White tries to avoid imbalances with }11.Bg5 { , Black can just play }11...h6 { and continue to expand with their pawn on the kingside. Either after }12.Bh4 g5 { or }12.Bxf6 Qxf6 { with aggressive ideas like ... h5 - h4  or ... g5 - g4 . } )
