7. Na5{ A typical response to White's queen move. We protect  b7 , attack the queen and the knight is also looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qa4+{ This is White's most popular move. White wants to misplace Black's pieces but that costs time. }
8. Bd7{ Attacking White's queen with tempo is the best way to parry White's check. }
9. Bb5( { This position could also be reached via the move order   }8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Qa4 { . It has been played by dozen of grandmasters who were looking for a slight initiative in this position.    However, Black shouldn't have too many problems neutralizing it and positionally Black is doing very fine when the light-squared bishops come off. } )
9. e6{ A nice move to stabilise Black's structure. }
10. Bg5( { By pinning the knight on  f6 , White is threatening   }11.Bxd7+ { (or }11.Bxf6 { followed by taking on  d7 ). }{ Black couldn't recapture on  d7  with the queen as the knight on  a4  would lose its protection.     But we can easily parry the threat and it is not clear if the bishop is really better on  g5  than on  f4 . } )
10. Nc6{ A nice move to consolidate. On the next move, we play ... a6  going for the bishop pair. }
11. Nf3( { This is the most natural move.    GM Simen Adgestein once played }11.Qd1 { to get the queen out of the bishop's diagonal but there is no big point behind it. }{ Black could just develop naturally with ... Be7 , ...  Rc8 , ... O-O . } )
11. a6{ That's usually enough to win the bishop pair. }
12. Bxc6( { This is the typical move even though Black has no problems.    }12.Be2 { was once played by an International Master but Black can barely do anything wrong there. Even the aggressive }12...h6 13.Bh4 g5!? 14.Bg3 Nh5 { is fully justified - with the kind of position that is typical for our  Schlexchange chapter . } )
12. Bxc6{ Black is doing really fine. We should just ignore the bishop on  g5  - even if White takes on  f6  and we have to recapture with the g-pawn, our bishop pair will easily compensate for the slightly weakened structure.  With this in mind, ... Bd6  and then ... Qc7  seem to be a good way to unpin the  f6 -knight. }
