6. e3( { The independent move order. }6.Nf3 g6 { transposes to the Schlechter Exchange chapter. This variation is arguably the most important one in this chapter.  Unfortunately, we cannot really enter 'Schlechter territory' with   }6...g6 { under good circumstances. That means we have to find a more mainline solution. } )
6. Bg4( { I choose the move }6...Bg4 { for different reasons.     1)  It is only the fourth most popular move in this position. That means White players might not be as familiar with this move as with the alternatives }6...Bf5 { , }6...a6 { or }6...e6 { .     2)  If White responds with the most critical move   }7.f3 { , the position will be really imbalanced. Ideal to play for a win!     3)  The move has the best score - pretty much 50%. } )
7. Qb3( { Besides }7.f3 { , the most aggressive move. However, Black's side has a decent reputation. } )
7. Na5{ A typical response to White's queen move. We protect  b7 , attack the queen and the knight is also looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qa4+{ This is White's most popular move. White wants to misplace Black's pieces but that costs time. }
8. Bd7{ Attacking White's queen with tempo is the best way to parry White's check. }
9. Bb5( { This position could also be reached via the move order   }8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Qa4 { . It has been played by dozen of grandmasters who were looking for a slight initiative in this position.    However, Black shouldn't have too many problems neutralizing it and positionally Black is doing very fine when the light-squared bishops come off. } )
9. e6{ A nice move to stabilise Black's structure. }
10. Bxd7+{ This immediate capture is not particularly good but it has been played a number of times on all levels so I think it deserves its own trainables. However, White is mainly playing for tricks. }
10. Nxd7{ We have to take with the knight not to lose the  a5 -knight. }
11. e4{ was played in two games. The idea to open up the position while Black's king is in the center is logical.  But Black doesn't have to fulfil White's wishes.      This move was played by the GMs Shirov and Petrosian. Black is getting ready for ... Nb6  which will solve all problems. }
11. Nc6( 11...dxe4 { is possible but White can try to start an attack with }12.d5! { . } )
12. exd5{ The most logical move, still trying to open the center. }
12. Nb6( { With this double attack, Black wins back the pawn with a decent position.    Even the immediate }12...exd5 { seems possible. If White takes on  d5 , Black will regain the pawn quickly. }13.Nxd5 Nb6! 14.Nxb6 axb6! { Because White has to save their queen, Black wins the  d4 -pawn next. } )
13. Qb3
13. exd5{ Black can just continue with ... Be7  or ... Bb4 . followed by ... O-O . The position is symmetrical but we have the better bishop. }
