7. Na5{ A typical response to White's queen move. We protect  b7 , attack the queen and the knight is also looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qa4+{ This is White's most popular move. White wants to misplace Black's pieces but that costs time. }
8. Bd7{ Attacking White's queen with tempo is the best way to parry White's check. }
9. Bb5( { This position could also be reached via the move order   }8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Qa4 { . It has been played by dozen of grandmasters who were looking for a slight initiative in this position.    However, Black shouldn't have too many problems neutralizing it and positionally Black is doing very fine when the light-squared bishops come off. } )
9. e6{ A nice move to stabilise Black's structure. }
10. Bxd7+{ This immediate capture is not particularly good but it has been played a number of times on all levels so I think it deserves its own trainables. However, White is mainly playing for tricks. }
10. Nxd7{ We have to take with the knight not to lose the  a5 -knight. }
11. Nb5( { This move has been played by a number of titled players but it just forces Black to play a really strong reply. The threat   }12.Nc7+ { forces Black to protect that square. } )( 11.Nf3 { has been played more often but if we just play }11...a6 { , we will transpose to the  10.Nf3 a6 - variation . } )
11. Rc8{ Kind of an obvious move. White cannot really take on  a7  and if that's not possible, we can just play ... a6  next.  White's whole sequence would be proven extremely pointless. }
12. Nxa7{ This is a mistake but it is the only continuation where Black has to know their precise response. White takes a pawn and is also attacking the  c8 -rook. }( {  A)  }12.Nd6+?! { looks tempting but Black can easily get rid of White's annoying pieces. }12...Bxd6 13.Bxd6 { The bishop looks nice but we have }13...Nc4! { Black is attacking  d6  and  b2 . If White drops back with }14.Ba3 { , we could simply just take but we also have more ambitious options like }14...Rb8 { , followed by ... b5 , ... a5  and ... b4 . } )( {  B)  }12.Bd6? a6 { loses material because }13.Bxf8 axb5 { comes with tempo. } )( {  C)  The best move seems to be }12.Ne2 { but that just allows us to play }12...a6 { and White's knight has nothing better than to go back. } )
12. Rc4{ Nice! Black saves the rook, drives away the queen and can try to catch the knight on  a7 . }
13. Qd1( { The trickiest move. }13.Qb5 Rb4 { just wins back the pawn while White's knight is still stranded on  a7 . }14.Qd3 Rxb2-+ {  ... Bb4 +  and ... Qb6  are coming. } )
13. Qb6{ The knight on  a7  is running out on squares even though Black has to be precise because White can try to drive away the  c4 -rook away from the c-file. }
14. b3{ White's only chance is to force this rook to an unfortunate square. Without the rook on the c-file, White would have  Na7 - c8 . }
14. Bb4+{ It is important to include this check but as White now has to run with their king, this is also just a pretty obvious move. }
15. Kf1{ The best square for the king, leaving the  e2 -square open for the  g1 -knight. }
15. Rc3{ The only square on the c-file. }
16. Ne2{ White is still trying to get rid of the rook. }
16. Qa6{ An important last move. By pinning the  e2 -knight, Black is getting ready to castle and then we can finally go for the  a7 -knight. ... Rd3 , maybe followed by ... Rd2  can also come in quite handy very soon. Black should just be winning with precise play. }( 16...Qxa7? { would be a grave mistake because }17.Nxc3 Bxc3 18.Rc1!+- { wins material for White. }{ The  c3 -bishop cannot move because of  Rc8 +. } )
