7. Qb3( { Besides }7.f3 { , the most aggressive move. However, Black's side has a decent reputation. } )
7. Na5{ A typical response to White's queen move. We protect  b7 , attack the queen and the knight is also looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qa4+{ This is White's most popular move. White wants to misplace Black's pieces but that costs time. }
8. Bd7{ Attacking White's queen with tempo is the best way to parry White's check. }
9. Bb5( { This position could also be reached via the move order   }8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Qa4 { . It has been played by dozen of grandmasters who were looking for a slight initiative in this position.    However, Black shouldn't have too many problems neutralizing it and positionally Black is doing very fine when the light-squared bishops come off. } )
9. e6{ A nice move to stabilise Black's structure. }
10. Nf3{ This is the main move. White just develops and accepts the fact that the light-squared bishops will be exchanged. }
10. a6{ Forcing White to take on  d7 . }
11. Bxd7+
11. Nxd7
12. O-O{ White is playing for quick development. In most cases, White's idea is just to be the first one to control the c-file but also  e3 - e4  to blast open the center is an idea if Black develops their kingside too slow. }
12. Be7( { The safest continuation.     A)  Some players like to start with }12...b5 { to drive White's queen to the  d1 -square when White cannot go  Rf1 - c1  immediately. The drawback is that White has the extra pawn break  a2 - a4 . This is all not the end of the world but I prefer not to give White additional options as long as they have the lead in development. } )( {  B)  }12...Rc8 { is another possible move to fight for the c-file as fast as possible but here it becomes extremely attractive to play }13.e4!? { . } )
13. Rfc1{ Usually, White prefers this rook. The rook on  a1  might indeed be useful if White ever wants to play with  a2 - a4  - which might be the case after a potential ... b7 - b5 .     Be careful! This is not only a good positional move but it is also creating a threat! }
13. Nc6{ Stopping all Shenanigans on the c-file. Now, Black is finally ready to castle, play ... Qb6  or ... Qa5 , then ... Rfc8  with easy development. }( { Don't go }13...O-O ? { because of }14.Nxd5 exd5 15.Bc7+- { . } )( { After }13...Nc6 { , Rapport played twice with White }14.Qb3 { . However, Black can just answer with }14...Qb6 { and has a harmonious piece setup. } )
