6. e3( { The independent move order. }6.Nf3 g6 { transposes to the Schlechter Exchange chapter. This variation is arguably the most important one in this chapter.  Unfortunately, we cannot really enter 'Schlechter territory' with   }6...g6 { under good circumstances. That means we have to find a more mainline solution. } )
6. Bg4( { I choose the move }6...Bg4 { for different reasons.     1)  It is only the fourth most popular move in this position. That means White players might not be as familiar with this move as with the alternatives }6...Bf5 { , }6...a6 { or }6...e6 { .     2)  If White responds with the most critical move   }7.f3 { , the position will be really imbalanced. Ideal to play for a win!     3)  The move has the best score - pretty much 50%. } )
7. Qb3( { Besides }7.f3 { , the most aggressive move. However, Black's side has a decent reputation. } )
7. Na5{ A typical response to White's queen move. We protect  b7 , attack the queen and the knight is also looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qa4+{ This is White's most popular move. White wants to misplace Black's pieces but that costs time. }
8. Bd7{ Attacking White's queen with tempo is the best way to parry White's check. }
9. Qc2{ The main move. White's last manoeuvre was about forcing Black's light-squared bishop to  d7  where it is arguably more passive.  But White has lost some time and the knight on  a5  might indeed be pretty useful. }
9. e6{ Solid development. }
10. Bd3( { This is played more often than }10.Nf3 { . However, usually, those moves transpose into each other after }10...Rc8 11.Bd3 { . } )
10. Rc8{ White's setup is just asking Black to make use of the c-file and the  c4 -square. In this regard, ... Rc8  is the most flexible move. }
11. Nf3( { The most popular move by far.    }11.Nge2 { overprotects  c3 , but Black just gets easy play with }11...b5 { , followed by ... Nc4 , ... Be7 , ... O-O  . } )
11. Bb4{ This move is the most in the spirit of our repertoire. Black plans to take on  c3  to give White a permanent weakness on the c-file. }
12. O-O{ White usually keeps developing. }
12. Nh5( { Not the main move but even played by Caruana. The main line is the simple }12...O-O { .    Nevertheless, the motifs of this  ...Nh5  move are typical for this repertoire and this here is certainly a decent version of the move. } )
13. Bg5( { This is the sharpest move White has - especially if they continue with   }13...f6 Bxh7!? { . } )
13. f6
14. Bh4{ This move allows Black to grab the initiative. }
14. g5{ The idea of Black's play is to grab the bishop pair, so this move is the logical follow-up. }
15. Bg3( { This leads to a position that has been tested a few times in GM games. No one else than Anand showed us how to play these positions.    }15.g4 gxh4 16.gxh5 { might be objectively the best option for White but it looks to me that Black has the much easier play. Black has the bishop pair, White's king is already on the open kingside and even Black's h-pawn might become useful.  Check out the model game Nozicka - Korkus, Correspondence 2020 -  see here . Black found a nice way to bring their king to the queenside and he even proved that the 'weak  h4 -pawn' can play a role in our attack. } )
15. g4( { Grabbing space on the kingside. }15...Nxg3 { first is also possible. } )
16. Nh4{ This is the best square. The knight builds a blockade on the  h4 -square and is also on the kingside with the hope for some kingside attack. }
16. Nxg3( { At some point, we have to grab the bishop pair. The immediate }16...f5?! { allows }17.Be5 { . } )
17. fxg3( { This is the typical way to recapture.    }17.hxg3 f5⩱ { is safer for White but it also offers less active possibility. The kingside is maybe not technically closed, but it is very hard for White to open it under good circumstances- sacrifices on  f5  don't work and  f2 - f3  can not easily be played under good circumstances.  However, Black has the bishop pair and is also the side who can easier make progress on the queenside. ... b5  or ... Nc4  come easily. } )
17. f5{ Closing down the kingside while White's structure is destroyed and Black has easy counterplay on the queenside. In the model game Nguyen - Anand, 2014 -  see here , White found nothing better than the desperate sacrifice on  f5  which is something that shouldn't have worked. }
