12. Nh5( { Not the main move but even played by Caruana. The main line is the simple }12...O-O { .    Nevertheless, the motifs of this  ...Nh5  move are typical for this repertoire and this here is certainly a decent version of the move. } )
13. Bg5( { This is the sharpest move White has - especially if they continue with   }13...f6 Bxh7!? { . } )
13. f6
14. Bxh7{ This is the sharpest option but Black's play is reasonably forced and we can follow the rule just to take every attacking piece until White is only left with the queen on the kingside! }
14. fxg5{ This is a novelty to keep more life in the position. Black can also play the exact same 5 moves with the exchange on  c3  included - and different correspondence games have proven that Black is absolutely fine with best play.  However, when it comes to winning chances, it might be reasonable to keep the bishop pair on the board. Especially because the  c3 -knight is currently not a dangerous attacking piece that needs to be eliminated. }( 14...Bxc3 15.bxc3 fxg5 16.Qg6+ Kf8 17.Qxh5 Be8 18.Qg4 Rxh7 19.Nxg5 Rh6 20.Nxe6+ Rxe6 21.Qxe6 { is what happened in 5 reasonably strong correspondence games. In three games, Black drew with }21...Qd7 { , in one with }21...Nc4 { and in the last one, the players already agreed to draw here:) } )
15. Qg6+{ Because both sides have several hanging pieces, the next moves are relatively forced. Currently, White is a piece down so they have to collect the  h5 -knight with this move. }
15. Kf8{ Much safer than  e7 . }
16. Qxh5
