17. Qg4( { The most precise reply.    }17.Qh3? { keeps the bishop protected but White is now in an eternal pin. Black can just slowly but surely attack  h7 . }17...Bxc3 { Taking just reduces White's counterplay. }18.bxc3 Qe7∓ { Protecting  e6  and preparing ... g6 . With a knight on  c3 , White would have  Nc3xd5 , using the pin of the  e6 -pawn. } )
17. Rxh7{ We have to take the bishop. }
18. Nxg5( { White is threatening   }19.Nxh7+ { and }19.Nxe6+ { . The next move is once again forced. } )
18. Rh6
19. Nxe6+
19. Rxe6
20. Qxe6
20. Bf7{ We have a very interesting position. White has 3 pawns and a rook against two minor pieces.  On paper, this is an advantage. However, White's pawns are not playing a huge role yet and also their rooks are not into the game yet.  Black's pieces in comparison can jump to life very quickly. We should continue with ... Rc6 , using the rook to defend and attack along the sixth rank. ... Nc4  comes quickly.     When it comes to the bishop on  b4 , we might take on  c3  in some positions to create a pawn weakness, but also playing ... Bd6  to regroup the bishop towards White's kingside is an idea. }
