[White "6) Schlexchange Introduction & Sidelines"]
[Black "Introduction Schlexchange"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5( { Welcome to the heart of this repertoire! So far, we have mainly mentioned the Grünfeld Slav only in passing or in positions where the move was obviously attractive   }4.Qc2 g6 { -  see here . }{ Now, we will come to the chapters that will make you a diehard Schlechter devotee. Congratulations!     Especially if White plays  Ng1 - f3  and  Nb1 - c3  on move 3 and 4, this is often considered the real test for the Schlechter Slav. White made no concessions so far regarding the  c4 -pawn and has plenty of options to choose from on move 5: } )( {   }5.Bf4 { , }5.Bg5 { , }5.Qb3 { and }5.cxd5 { are White's most independent options.    }{ Especially the last move is often considered to be THE real test of the Schlechter. And that is not illogical: By taking on  d5 , White takes our ... c7 - c5  break from us when we have to be even more careful that our bishop on  g7  will not end up as a bad minor piece. Nevertheless, I believe Black has plenty of resources to choose from to avoid this scenario and create imbalances that give us a fully-fledged game.    I have titled this structure 'Schlexchange' - a mixture of 'Schlechter' and 'Exchange', in order to distinguish it conceptually from other exchange variations.    White typically develops their dark-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain, plays  e2 - e3  and would like to claim that they have the better minor pieces in a position with otherwise not many imbalances. Oh dear, how wrong they are! } )( { The critical line is }6.Bf4 { that we will discuss in the next chapters -  starting here . In this chapter, we will start with the sidelines.    }{ Rules for this chapter:    - ... Nc6  is more flexible in these Exchange structures than ... Bg7     - We want to play ... Ne4  in response to  Bg5 . } )
