6. Bg5( { This provokes the typical response }6...Ne4 { . } )( { As we will see, we will even play this knight jump in lines with }6.Bf4 { -  see here . So, if it is White's idea to move the bishop a second time after this knight move is played, White might just be a tempo down compared to those lines. Overall, this shouldn't be a particularly dangerous move. } )
6. Ne4{ The typical reaction against the bishop on  g5 . }
7. Bh4{ This can be considered White's most logical follow-up. As mentioned, even in lines with  6.Bf4 , Black does often go for the ... Ne4  move.  So losing a tempo this way doesn't look critical. }( { In comparison to the line   }5.Bg5 Ne4 6.Bh4 { -  see here  -, we cannot grab a pawn on  c4 . However, we are nevertheless not unhappy with Black. The exchange on  d5  opens the c-file, so Black can go for the standard counterplay idea to take on  c3  and put pressure along this file. And it is also not clear why the bishop should be better on  h4  than on  f4 . } )
7. Nxc3{ By taking on  c3 , we give White a long-term weakness on  c3 . Building up on the c-file is our main resource of counterplay in this structure. (Don't forget to thank White for opening the c-file.) }
8. bxc3
8. Nc6( { It doesn't really matter if we start with this move or with }8...Bg7 { . After the bishop move, }9.Qa4+ { has been played with good results for White. } )( { It is not particularly scary, but we avoid this move order by starting with }8...Nc6 { . }{ Also,  we are following the general rule that ... Nc6  is more flexible than ... Bg7  in the Exchange structures. } )
9. e3( { White should just continue their development. Here, }9.Qa4 { makes no sense. Black can play the solid }9...Bd7 { , }9...Qa5 { or }9...Qb6 { . This threatens }-- 10...Qb2 { and is just provoking White to spend a tempo preventing this. } )
9. Bg7( { We develop in the same way as after   }7.Bf4 {  see here . }{ With the bishop on  h4 , Black's opening is even safer than with the bishop on  f4  as White cannot go for any  h2 - h4 - h5  ideas easily. } )
10. Bd3{ Let's use this as a sample line. Black's setup is always the same. }
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. Na5{ A good square for the knight, stopping all kinds of  c3 - c4  ideas. Eventually, our rook will land on  c8  when we pressurize the  c3 -pawn and can use  c4  as an outpost for the knight.  When it comes to the development of the  c8 -bishop, the general rule is: If White goes for a kingside attack, it is better to have the bishop on  d7  or  e6  where it can potentially stabilise the kingside.  If White doesn't make moves indicating a kingside attack, I'd usually prefer ... b6  & ... Bb7  where the bishop is ideally placed against all kinds of breaks in the center and also limiting White's play on the b-file.     Even though the  h2 - h4 - h5  attacking plan is slower than with White's bishop on  f4 , it is only one tempo with  Bh4 - g3  that White needs to invest to make it possible. Once again, let me just link you to the  sister variation . If you copy the reaction that I explain there against White's different tries, you will definitely do a good job here as well! }
