6. Qb3{ This is a reasonable move. White puts pressure on the  d5 -pawn so Black cannot execute typical manoeuvres like ... Ne4  or ... Nh5  if White develops their dark-squared bishop. }
6. Nc6{ In the exchange variation, it is more flexible to play ... Nc6  instead of ... Bg7 . This variation is the main variation why I created this rule. It might be important to have the resource ... Nc6 - a5  at the right moment. }( 6...Bg7?! 7.Bg5 { is what White would like to play. With the pressure against  d5 , Black cannot play }...Ne4 { . } )
7. Bf4( { This is less popular than }7.Bg5 { but not necessarily worse. However, Black has the same counterplay. } )
7. Na5{ Winning a tempo against the queen. Looking at the  c4 -square. }
8. Qd1( { This is actually the best square because it is the safest.    For example, }8.Qc2 { is only asking for ... Bf5  or ... Rc8  eventually. Nevertheless, now we have the main variation of the Schlechter exchange just that the knight is on  a5  instead on  b8 . } )( { We could just play }8...Nc6 { , trying to transpose but that would allow White to repeat moves with }9.Qb3 { . Let's go for something else. } )
8. Bg7{ In this 'improved' version of the  Bf4 -exchange, we can actually just play ... Bg7  and castle. }
9. e3
9. O-O{ White has different moves here. As this is just an inferior - and much less popular version - of the regular Schlechter exchange, I don't think that we should go into big details. }( { A general rule is - same as in the  sister variation  with  7.Rc1 , that we either play   }10...Nh5 { next or - if White stops this with   }10.h3 { , we can go }...Qb6 { to create pressure on the queenside. } )
10. h3{ This stops ... Nh5  but Black still can develop active play. }
10. Qb6{ White has to take care of the  b2 -pawn. }( 10...Ne4 11.Rc1 { is not effective here as White can recapture on  c3  with the rook. } )
11. Nb5{ This is the only concrete move. White blocks the b-file and wants to jump into  c7  either with the bishop or the knight. }( 11.Rb1 { allows Black to exchange light-squared bishops with }11...Bf5 12.Bd3 Bxd3 13.Qxd3 Rfc8 { with very easy counterplay on the c-file. } )
11. Ne8{ A very solid move. Black just makes sure that nothing comes to  c7 . Next, we can play ... Bd7  to get rid of the  b5 -knight and take the pawn on  b2 . }( { The game could continue:     A)  }12.Rc1 { This doesn't protect  b2  so we can try to get rid of the  b5 -knight. }12...Bd7! 13.Nc3 ( { (Jumping into  c7  is not leading anywhere. }13.Nc7 Nxc7 14.Bxc7 Qb4+ { , followed by  ...Nc6  is just a very harmonious position for Black as we are better developed.) } )13...Qxb2 { We can go for the exchange of  d5  against  b2 -pawn as White's knight will have no stable squares. }14.Nxd5 e6 { Saving the e-pawn. }15.Nc3 Rc8 { with good counterplay on the queenside. } )( {  B)  }12.Qd2 { This move is now possible as Black doesn't have  ...Nf6-e4  with tempo. }12...Bf5 { The most active square and we might even go to  e4  with the idea to capture the knight.  Also, ... Nc4  is still in the air. }{     B1)  }13.Be2?! { is already quite bad as Black gets their bishop to  d3 . }13...Nc4 14.Bxc4 dxc4 15.Nc3 Bd3 { Black is slightly better as White is unable to castle.     B2)  }13.Nc3 { This anticipates that the knight can become vulnerable on  b5  and was not much to do there anyway. }13...Nf6 { The knight has done its job on  e8 . Next, we can go ... Ne4  and even recapture with the d-pawn to create some imbalances. }{     B3)    }13.Rc1 Be4 { Threatening to take on  f3  and spoil White's structure. }14.Be2?! Nc4! { would once again be a good way to exploit the ... Nc4  resource and the unstable knight on  b5 . } )
