6. Qb3{ This is a reasonable move. White puts pressure on the  d5 -pawn so Black cannot execute typical manoeuvres like ... Ne4  or ... Nh5  if White develops their dark-squared bishop. }
6. Nc6{ In the exchange variation, it is more flexible to play ... Nc6  instead of ... Bg7 . This variation is the main variation why I created this rule. It might be important to have the resource ... Nc6 - a5  at the right moment. }( 6...Bg7?! 7.Bg5 { is what White would like to play. With the pressure against  d5 , Black cannot play }...Ne4 { . } )
7. Bg5( { White would love to see Black play a passive move like }7...e6 { but Black has a more active response - thanks to  6...Nc6! . } )
7. Na5{ This solves all of Black's problems. }
8. Qd1{ We have the starting position of the  6.Bg5 -line just with Black's knight on  a5  instead of on  b8 . Hard to believe that this is to White's advantage. }
8. Ne4{ The same recipe against it. If White moves their bishop, we can just take on  c3  and have an improved version of the lines with the knight on  b8 . The knight often goes to  a5  anyways in those lines! }
9. Nxe4{ This move is here tactically possible and I don't think any moves really make much sense. }
