10. a6( { By preparing  ...b5 ,   }11...f6 { becomes a threat. } )( { The immediate }10...f6? { allows }11.Qa4+ { . } )
11. Bd2( { This is actually the only move that doesn't lose material. White is going out of the   }11...f6 { fork - that would actually also just trap the knight on  e5  - and is threatening   }12.Qa4+ { . } )
11. b5( { Mainly just stopping the queen check on  a4  but that we prepare  ...Bb7  is also not a bad thing. For the moment,   }12...f6 { is also a threat. } )
12. e3{ White's best move. White can play  a2 - a4  next and fight for the  c4 -square for their knight. }( { The immediate }12.a4 { is just less flexible. }12...b4 { closes the queenside and }-- ...f6 { is still a threat. } )
12. f6{ Forcing the issue with this move is a simple way to get a good position but we also see some typical motifs. }( { The main alternative is }12...Bg7!? { when }13.a4 { puts a lot of pressure on our kingside. We can't play }13...b4 { as White can just take and so we have to find some studylike moves. }13...Bxe5! 14.dxe5 O-O ! { Sacrificing the  b5 -pawn. For example, }15.axb5 axb5 16.Bxb5 ( { ( }16.b4 Bg4! { is similar.) } )16...Bg4!! { Fighting for the  b3 -square. }17.Qxg4 Nb3 18.Rd1 Nxd2 19.Rxd2 Qa5⇆ { with ideas like ... Qxb5  and ...  Rfd8  Black seems to have enough counterplay. But yeah, there is no need for this. } )
13. a4
13. b4( { Here, we can close the queenside.    }13...fxe5 14.axb5 { results in problems with the  a5 -knight. } )
14. Nc4
14. e6{ Black has nice control over the light squares and can continue with ... Bb7 , ...  Kf7  with a solid formation. }
