6. Nc6{ In the exchange variation, it is more flexible to play ... Nc6  instead of ... Bg7 . This variation is the main variation why I created this rule. It might be important to have the resource ... Nc6 - a5  at the right moment. }( 6...Bg7?! 7.Bg5 { is what White would like to play. With the pressure against  d5 , Black cannot play }...Ne4 { . } )
7. Bg5( { White would love to see Black play a passive move like }7...e6 { but Black has a more active response - thanks to  6...Nc6! . } )
7. Na5{ This solves all of Black's problems. }
8. Qa4+{ It looks pretty stupid to give Black ... Bd7  with tempo, but White's idea is actually that this blocks the d-file so that Black's queen has less influence there. Why this is important can be seen in the next few moves. }
8. Bd7
9. Qd1{ The safest square. }
9. Ne4( { Of course, we still go for this move.    In our model game  Fedoseev - Kempinski , Black played }9...Nc4 { and won brilliantly but }10.e4! { would have been a strong response. } )
10. Nxe4( { This was White's plan. Otherwise, Black could play   }10...Nxc3 { and would have gotten all the moves ... Nc6 , ... Na5  and ... Nd7  with tempo that we usually play anyways in this structure. } )( 10.Nxd5? Nxg5 11.Nxg5 e6! { loses a piece as both knights are hanging. } )
10. dxe4
11. Nd2{ That this move is now possible, is the deep idea behind  8.Qa4+ . The  d4 -pawn is not hanging. Nevertheless, Black is so active that it barely matters. }
11. e3{ I really like this move to stop White's development. }( { We have won so many tempi in the opening that we have every reason to be aggressive. }11...Qb6 { with or without  ...h6  and  Bf4  included - has been played quite a while. After }12.e3 { , Black has different options such as taking on  b2  or }12...e5 { . Still, I was not super impressed by the resulting positions. } )( 11...e3 { looks like more fun! } )
12. Bxe3{ White has to take with the bishop but it is now blocking the e-pawn. }( 12.fxe3? { is just horribly in a positional way. We can just develop with }12...Bg7 { and then }-- ...O-O { and eventually  ...e5  can be prepared. } )
12. Bg7{ By increasing the pressure on  d4 , Black makes it hard to move the bishop away from  e2 . If White plays  g2 - g3 , we can play ... Bc6 . If moves the knight from  d2 , we can play ... Nc4 . Black has nice compensation. Just to show some sample lines: }
13. Nf3( {  A)  White can develop the queenside first with }13.Rc1 { , also taking more control over the  c4 -square. I think }13...Be6 { is a nice move to play with the same ideas. }14.g3 { runs into }14...Bd5 { and we can still put a knight on  c4  if White moves their horse away from  d2 . } )( {  B)  }13.g3 Bc6 14.Nf3 { transposes to our sample line. } )
13. Bc6{ A good diagonal for the bishop. We put pressure on the kingside and can also take on  f3  if it wins the d-pawn. }
14. g3{ White has different moves. We can't look at all options but the given variations should give you a good idea about the nature of Black's compensation.     This move plans a quick development with  Bg2  and  O-O . }( 14.Rc1 { keeps the knight on the rim but we can simply develop. }14...O-O { White still can't move the  e3 -bishop without losing the pawn. }15.g3 ( { ( }15.Bd2 Bxf3 16.gxf3 Bxd4 { wins back the pawn.) } )15...Bd5!? { with }-- ...Nc4 { ideas leads to a similar position as in the trainable. } )
14. Nc4{ Now, Black can always take on  e3  to weaken White's structure and win the bishop pair. }
15. Bg2{ White should finish their development.  b2  is not hanging. }
15. Qa5+{ This check leads to a position that is objectively close to equality and Black looks 'visually' even very slightly better so it is hard to resist something different. }( { Still, let me mention that we can also play for positional compensation by taking on  e3 .     A)  For example }15...O-O 16.O-O Nxe3! 17.fxe3 Qa5=∞ { with }-- ...e5 { to follow is also very nice positional compensation. } )( {  B)  }15...Nxe3 16.fxe3 e5!? { is a very creative way to sacrifice another pawn but White's structure will be completely in ruins after }17.dxe5=∞ { Black will most likely just win the  e5 -pawn eventually and will still have the much better structure as compensation for the remaining pawn. } )
16. Bd2
16. Nxd2{ This is now a pretty forcing variation to win back the pawn. }
17. Qxd2
17. Qxd2+
18. Kxd2{ The knight cannot take as it is pinned. }
18. O-O-O{ With the pin along the d-file and the  a8 - h1  diagonal and ... e5  ideas, Black will win the  d4 -pawn back and is arguably just very slightly better coordinated than White even though the game should end in a draw if White defends correctly. }
