6. Nc6( { No over-exaggeration: This here is arguably the most important informational in the whole course!    We have reached the main position of the Schlexchange. After   }6.Bf4 { , Black should not mix up his move order. First of all, we have to follow the rule to play }6...Nc6 { before  6...Bg7  in the Schlexchange. That is the easy part.    However, on the next move, we have to go for imbalances immediately before White gets the chance to avoid those! } )( {  A)  After }7.e3 { - the most natural move - we will go bishop hunting with }7...Nh5! { . In most lines, we will win the bishop pair while White will try to provoke as many weaknesses before doing so. Very exciting positions! } )( {  B)  }7.h3 { is a logical move to prevent this from happening but here, Black can go for the immediate }7...Ne4! { . }{ We simply want to capture on  c3  when White will get a backward pawn that should compensate for our slightly passive bishop on  g7 . }{ Note that White cannot really prevent this because }8.Rc1 { - positionally, it is a good idea to recapture with a piece instead of a pawn - runs into }8...Nxc3 9.Rxc3 e5! { when we have ideas with }-- ...Bb4 { . }{ (A good example why ... Nc6  is more flexible than ... Bg7 .) }( { In two chapters, we will briefly look at White's moves  C)  }7.h4!? { and  D)  }7.Rc1!? { but I think for your start in this variation, }{ it should be enough to remember the moves ... Nh5  and ... Ne4  as ways to create imbalances against option A and B! }( { In this chapter, we will start with }7.h3 { . } ) ) )
