1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4
6. Nc6
7. h3
7. Ne4
8. e3
8. Nxc3{ That was Black's idea. Black creates an imbalance in the pawn structure and will develop their pieces in such a way that they put pressure either on the weak  c3 -pawn or the weak  c4 -square.  White can try to change the structure with  c3 - c4  or  e3 - e4  but in the resulting structures, Black will always have active play. }
9. bxc3
9. Bg7
10. Bd3{ The most natural developing move. White prepares castling and makes it harder for Black to play ... Bf5 . }
10. O-O
11. O-O{ The most flexible move. }
11. Na5{ Black takes control over the  c4 -square that stops White from playing  c3 - c4 . }( { Another typical way to play these positions is }11...b6 { , followed by ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  and potentially ... Na5  slightly later. } )( { However, I prefer the positions with the immediate }11...Na5 { . Black typically has a decent position if we develop our light-squared bishop and start to gang up on the c-file with our major pieces against the  c3 -pawn.   }{ To avoid this, White might try to play aggressively on the kingside with ideas like  h2 - h4 - h5 . In some positions, it is important to have ... Bg4  in response to  h3 - h4 .     Also, by developing our light-squared bishop to  e6 , it plays a role in stabilising the kingside pawns. A role it doesn't have on  b7 . } )
12. Nd2{ White prepares  c3 - c4  and  e3 - e4 . Also,  Nd2 - b3  can be an idea to exchange the knight on  a5  that is currently defending the queenside and has potentially a nice future on  c4 . }( 12.Nd2 { is the most popular move in practice but I believe that this approach is not really threatening. } )
12. b6{ As White's last move is removing one piece from the kingside, White will most likely no longer go for a crazy kingside attack.     In these situations, I prefer the bishop development to  b7  - or  a6 ! }
13. Nb3{ A logical idea. White wants to exchange Black's most influential piece on the queenside. }
13. Nc4{ Immediately going for outpost. Black just wants to continue with ... Bb7  and ... Rc8  but we are also preparing ... e5  in some positions to open up the center. }( 13...Nxb3 14.Qxb3 { followed by  a2 - a4 - a5  gives White a nice initiative on the queenside. } )
14. Bxc4{ White can take the outpost but the bishop pair should always give Black enough counter-chances. }
14. dxc4
15. Nd2{ White attacks the  c4 -pawn but Black can defend it tactically with the most natural move. }
15. Bb7( { Stopping }16.Nxc4? { because of }16...Qd5 { with a double attack against  g2  and  c4 . } )( { Protecting the pawn with }15...b5? { can backfire. }16.a4! { ± and Black has no good move to leave the structure intact.    }{ In the next moves, Black can prepare ... e7 - e5  or try to expand on the queenside with ... b5 , maybe ... Qa5 , ... Rfc8  or ... a5 . } )
