15. Bxc4
15. dxc4
16. Qxc4
16. Rc8{ Black is lining up against  c3 . In the following moves, Black combines ideas against the weak pawn with ... Qd5  motifs to activate the pieces and provoke some weaknesses. }
17. Qa4{ The only try to keep the extra pawn. }( {  A)  }17.Qb4 a5 { is immediately losing material back. White can try to be tricky with }18.Nxa5 { but after }18...Ba6 { , Black wins the exchange. } )( {  B)  }17.Qd3?! { is too passive. }17...Qd5! { threatens mate on  g2 . }18.f3 Qc4! { and Black just wins back the  c3 -pawn as White cannot protect it after }19.Qxc4 Rxc4 20.Rac1 Rfc8⩱ { . Black's bishop pair give us the advantage. } )
17. g5{ A very nice resource. White cannot take the pawn because ...  Qd5  attacks bishop and  g2 . And if White retreats, the  e3 -pawn has less protection which will be important after taking on  c3 .     Let's just mention that Black does also have other ways to prove compensation for the pawn. The important part is just to be aggressive and open many files to give the bishops many diagonals to work with. }( { For example }17...a5 { allows White to protect  c3 . But Black can still get a good game after something like }18.Rac1 Bc6 19.Qa3 a4! { Forcing White's knight to a bad square. }20.Nd2 ( { ( }20.Na1 e5! { is similar.) } )20...e5! { White cannot take on  e5  as  d2  hangs. }21.Bg3 f5!=∞ { with an initiative on the kingside.    Just a sample line, of course, but I think one that nicely illustrates how to play with the bishop pair in this position. } )
18. Bg3
18. Rxc3{ Equalising the material. }
19. Qxa7{ Taking the pawn is the only critical line. }
19. Qd5{ Protecting the bishop, threatening mate on  g2  and provoking a weakness on the kingside. }
20. f3( 20.e4 Qxe4 { is not better. } )
20. Rxe3( { Technically, White can still be a pawn up after }21.Qxb6 { but Black has managed to get a lot of open diagonals and active squares for their pieces. }{ ... Rc8  and ... Re2  are coming,  d4  is weak.  Black has full compensation. } )
