12. Re1{ White has many moves that deserve the attribute 'flexible'. White keeps the option open to play on the kingside - which can be dangerous if we develop our bishop to  b7  - but also keeps ideas to play on the queenside or in the center.  12.Re1  is one of these moves.  White is just making a useful move that might prepare  e3 - e4  in the future but also just waits for what Black will be doing. We cannot look at every possible move for White but the following lines do hopefully give you a good general idea of how to play these positions. }
12. Be6{ When White plays flexible, I prefer to develop the bishop to  e6  or  d7  so that it can stabilise the kingside if needed.     On  e6 , it anticipates better White's breaks  c3 - c4  or  e3 - e4  and sometimes we can also aim for ... Qd7  and ... Bf5 , exchanging the light-squared bishops. }( 12...Bd7 { allows }13.e4 { under decent circumstances as Black has no immediate control over  c4  and  d5 . Nevertheless, something like }13...dxe4 14.Bxe4 Rc8 { does also look playable.    At least White has to play very energetic to prove something here! }15.Ne5! { ⩲ creates some pressure because }15...Rxc3?! 16.Bd2± { can become awkward. } )
13. Rb1{ The most useful move, immediately pressuring the b-file.     With the bishop on  e6 , Black should not play ... b6  on autopilot because the light squares can be weak. }
13. Qd7{ A typical move to connect the rooks and prepare ... Bf5  to exchange the light-squared bishops. }( 13...Rc8 { is also logical but I don't like the fact that ... Qd7  next would allow White to play  Bb5  when we have nothing better than to go back to  d8 . }{ For example }14.Qc2 Qd7 15.Bb5 Qd8 { . To be honest, White has nothing better than to repeat with }16.Bd3 { - otherwise, Black might play   }16...Bf5 { - but if we want to avoid every repetition, we have to deviate somewhere. } )
14. Nd2( { A logical move. White prepares  c3-c4  and  e3-e4  but mainly   }15.Nb3 { is some kind of threat because it attacks  a5 , threatens }-- 16.Nc5 { and taking on  b3  would give White pressure along the b-file. } )( {  A)  }14.Bb5 { is theoretically still playable but I don't see the point here. We can go }14...Qc8 { and the bishop is just worse on  b5 . } )( {  B)  }14.Ng5 { doesn't make much sense. Black can play }14...Bf5! { which was one of the main ideas behind  ...Qd7  anyways. White's only justification could be }15.e4! { which leads to  this trainable  after }15...dxe4 16.Nxe4 { . } )
14. Bf5{ I wanted to include this idea to exchange light-squared bishops in one of the trainables. Nevertheless, Black does also have other options. }( 14...a6!? { Anticipating White's idea to create pressure along the b-file by preparing  ...b5 . If White continues with }15.Nb3 { , then }Nxb3 16.Qxb3 b5! { takes away all queenside pressure. } )
15. Bxf5{ Positionally speaking, Black should be really happy with this exchange. White's light squares become more vulnerable. }
15. Qxf5
16. Rb5{ This gives some tactical ideas with the attack against  a5  and the option to go  c3 - c4  but it is not really scary. }
16. b6{ Stabilising the queenside. }
17. c4{ The only move to create some pressure. }
17. Qd3{ The kind of move that proves the vulnerability of the light squares. }
18. Rxd5
18. Rfc8( { Even more precise than taking on  c4  right away. The pawn cannot be protected anyways and Black gains some options such as }19.Rd7 Kf8 { . } )
