11. Na5{ Black takes control over the  c4 -square that stops White from playing  c3 - c4 . }( { Another typical way to play these positions is }11...b6 { , followed by ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  and potentially ... Na5  slightly later. } )( { However, I prefer the positions with the immediate }11...Na5 { . Black typically has a decent position if we develop our light-squared bishop and start to gang up on the c-file with our major pieces against the  c3 -pawn.   }{ To avoid this, White might try to play aggressively on the kingside with ideas like  h2 - h4 - h5 . In some positions, it is important to have ... Bg4  in response to  h3 - h4 .     Also, by developing our light-squared bishop to  e6 , it plays a role in stabilising the kingside pawns. A role it doesn't have on  b7 . } )
12. Qc2( { A move similar to }12.Qe2 { . White stays flexible and waits for Black's response. } )
12. Be6{ After analysing back and forth, I decided that it is worth starting with this move. Black gets the idea ... Qd7  and ... Bf5  which should for now be enough reason to distract White from their ambitions on the kingside.  Once White has spent some tempi on moves that don't make much sense for any kingside ambitions, the bishop might indeed go back to  d7  where it gives Black usually more active options. }( 12...Bd7!? { Usually the best square against the flexible approaches. The bishop is still close to the kingside but also controls critical queenside squares such as  a4  or  b5  which can be useful if Black wants to play ... b5  at some point. Without the bishop on  e6 , it is also easier for Black to go for ... e7 - e5 . }13.h4!? { was the main reason why I refrained from recommending it. I am convinced Black is objectively fine but in so many positions ... Bg4  seems to be a necessity against this attack - and with the  f3 -knight unpinned, it is hard to avoid repetitions if White responds with  Ne5  or  Nh2 . } )
13. Rab1{ Playing the rook to  b1  does only stop Black's idea temporarily. }
13. Qd7{ Following the plan. }
14. Qb2{ This move is mainly based on some tactics. White hopes for double-attacks against  a5  and  e7  or against  a5  and  d5 . But if Black is careful, this is not a big deal. }
14. b6{ This weakens the light squares but protecting the  a5 -knight takes away White's tactical ideas. I think the alternatives are weaker. For example: }( {  A)  }14...Rfc8?! 15.Ng5! Bf5 16.Bxf5 Qxf5 ( { (or }16...gxf5 17.Qb5 { ) } )17.Qb5 b6 18.g4! { is a very computerlike idea to win a pawn but it should be reason enough for us not to go for this. }18...Qf6 19.Qxd5±  )( {  B)  }14...Bf5?! 15.Bxf5 Qxf5 ( { ( }15...gxf5 16.Qb5 { is also very annoying.) } )16.Qb4 { winning the  e7 -pawn. } )( { After }14...b6 { , Black's next move is ... Bf5 , followed by ... Nc4 , taking control of the light squares. } )
