14. Rfc8{ A nice move. We cannot play ... Bf5  in a version that also exchanges queens.  And as long as the queens are on the board, the structure with ... gxf5  is playable but risky - we should make sure that we have as much counterplay as possible on the other side of the board so that White cannot simply checkmate us on the kingside.     With this move, we also prepare ... Nc4 . }( { The immediate }14...Bf5 15.Bxf5! { is not ideal for Black. }15...Qxf5 18.Qxf5 gxf5 19.Rb5 { wins a pawn and }15...gxf5 { gives White attacking ideas like  Nh4 ,  Kh1 ,  Rg1 ,  g4 . } )
15. Nd2{ Let's take this as a sample move. White takes control over  c4  and is also setting up the idea  Nb3  with the typical problems to protect  a5  and  c5 . }( 15.Ng5 Bf5! 16.Bxf5 gxf5⇆ { is similar. } )
15. Bf5{ A nice move, underlying that the resulting structure is okay if White's pieces are not ideally set up to start a kingside attack. }
16. Bxf5
16. gxf5{ With a very double-edged position. Black can continue with ... e6 , ... Nc4 , ...  Kh8 , ... Rg8 . }
