11. Na5{ Black takes control over the  c4 -square that stops White from playing  c3 - c4 . }( { Another typical way to play these positions is }11...b6 { , followed by ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  and potentially ... Na5  slightly later. } )( { However, I prefer the positions with the immediate }11...Na5 { . Black typically has a decent position if we develop our light-squared bishop and start to gang up on the c-file with our major pieces against the  c3 -pawn.   }{ To avoid this, White might try to play aggressively on the kingside with ideas like  h2 - h4 - h5 . In some positions, it is important to have ... Bg4  in response to  h3 - h4 .     Also, by developing our light-squared bishop to  e6 , it plays a role in stabilising the kingside pawns. A role it doesn't have on  b7 . } )
12. Qc2( { A move similar to }12.Qe2 { . White stays flexible and waits for Black's response. } )
12. Be6{ After analysing back and forth, I decided that it is worth starting with this move. Black gets the idea ... Qd7  and ... Bf5  which should for now be enough reason to distract White from their ambitions on the kingside.  Once White has spent some tempi on moves that don't make much sense for any kingside ambitions, the bishop might indeed go back to  d7  where it gives Black usually more active options. }( 12...Bd7!? { Usually the best square against the flexible approaches. The bishop is still close to the kingside but also controls critical queenside squares such as  a4  or  b5  which can be useful if Black wants to play ... b5  at some point. Without the bishop on  e6 , it is also easier for Black to go for ... e7 - e5 . }13.h4!? { was the main reason why I refrained from recommending it. I am convinced Black is objectively fine but in so many positions ... Bg4  seems to be a necessity against this attack - and with the  f3 -knight unpinned, it is hard to avoid repetitions if White responds with  Ne5  or  Nh2 . } )
13. Rfc1{ This innocuous-looking move does actually stop Black's idea to go ... Qd7 . }
13. Rc8{ Black should just continue with this logical developing move that does also take  c4  once more under control. }( { After }13...Qd7?! { , }14.Nd2! { is a strong response. White has the typical idea }-- 15.Nb3! { which threatens  a5  and }-- 16.Nc5 { while we also don't want to exchange on  b3 .    If we follow our plan   }14...Bf5 15.Bxf5 Qxf5 16.Qxf5 gxf5 { , then }17.c4! { ± is well-timed. }{ White gets rid of the hole on  c4  and starts to open up the queenside while Black has no clear counterplay. } )
14. Rab1( { A logical move to continue pressuring the queenside. }14.h4 Qd7! { would now be once again very comfortable for Black as White can neither prevent }-- ...Bf5 { nor break the control over the  c4 -square. } )
14. Bd7{ A manoeuvre to remember. Just two moves after ... Be6 , we move the bishop back to  d7 . This simply is the better square for this bishop.  White's two last moves didn't really do anything for a potential kingside attack while the tempo loss is not too critical if White mainly tries to play on the queenside - our structure there is so solid that White cannot really make good use of this tempo anyways. }
15. h4{ We had the bishop on  e6  to answer this move with ... Qd7 . It is logical to try it now. It is White's most aggressive option. }
15. b6{ If White builds up on the kingside, we have to make sure that we can challenge White's pieces on their attacking outposts. By taking care of the hanging  b7 -pawn, we are getting ready to play ... Nc4  to stop  Nf3 - e5 . }
16. h5( { The most principled continuation.     A)  }16.Ba6?! Bf5!⩱ { is just good for Black. } )( {  B)  }16.Ne5 Nc4⇆ { is also in time. } )
16. Nc4{ Bringing the knight to its ideal square, stopping all  Ne5 -ideas. Next, Black can consider playing ... Re8  and ... e5  himself to create counterplay. }( { The immediate }16...Re8? { can only serve as an example of why we should take White's kingside play seriously. }17.Ne5! { Now, the knight can jump to its outpost. The best move now seems to be to play }17...Bxe5 { to get rid of this knight when Black's kingside is still shaky. }17...Nc4?! { now comes too late. }18.hxg6 { (Because of the in-between check on  h7 , Black cannot take on  e5  - neither now nor on the next move.) }18...hxg6 19.Bxg6! fxg6 20.Qxg6+- { White has ideas with }-- 21.Bh6 { and Black's king has no shelter. } )
