12. Bd7( { Staying flexible with the bishop, not buying it that White wants to play on the queenside only.     A)  }12...Be6 { can lead to concrete problems on the b-file. }13.Nd2 { Preparing  Nd2-b3 . For example }13...Rc8 14.Nb3! { can lead to some pressure. }14...Rxc3 15.Nc5!⩲ { does not only attack  b7  and  e6  but also threatens }-- 16.Qd2 { to trap the rook. And after }14...Nxb3 15.Qxb3 { , White does also have some kind of ideal version to execute pressure along the b-file. } )( {  B)  }12...b6 { As  12.Rb1  is a move that implies some play on the queenside, I think it is logical to continue with ...  b6  and ... Bb7 . I think this is also fully playable. The main problem is that White can play a lot of flexible waiting moves such as }13.Rc1 { , }13.Re1 { , }13.Qc2 { , }13.Qe2 { , wait for }...Bb7 { , and then start with }14.h4 { . Black's defensive resources are intact as far as I can say but covering all these moves in detail would significantly increase the number of trainables. } )( 12...Bd7 { is easier. } )
