7. h4( { In this chapter, we will have a quick look at the odd-looking move }7.h4!? { . Grandmaster and chess entertainer Simon Williams who uses his h-pawn "Harry" at any given opportunity against his opponent's fianchetto setups, would certainly approve of this move.    White gives their bishop a square on  h2  and makes  ...Nf6-h5  less attractive, very much in the same spirit as }7.h3 { but much more aggressive. White might get the possibility to play  h4-h5  but weakens their kingside in the long run and a bishop on  g4  will be much more annoying.    This move will transpose to one of the sidelines against the Grünfeld-Indian. After   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.h4!? { , the move }5...c6 { stabilizes the  d5 -pawn and stops  h4 - h5  because if that - we could simply take the pawn with the knight.  This line shouldn't frighten us but as it has been reached - via transposition - in different super GM games, I decided to include it. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Schlexchange meets Harry - 7.h4!?"]
[Black "9.Be2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4
6. Nc6
7. h4
7. Bg7{ Developing the kingside is Black's most flexible way to continue the development. }
8. e3
8. O-O( { White's main move here is }9.Qb3 { but let's look at the other options first to understand why. } )
9. Be2{ A normal developing move like this will allow Black to bring their bishop to  g4 . }
9. Bg4{ The ideal square, weakened by White's  h2 - h4 -move. }
10. Qb3( { This might still be White's best move but it is already less desirable than one move earlier.     A)  }10.Ne5 Bxe2 11.Qxe2 Rc8 { Black has absolutely no problems and it is absolutely not clear why White should be happy about the move  h2 - h4  in this position.    To see how things can quickly go downhill here for White, check out the model game Martin Carmona - Wagner -  see here . } )( {  B)  }10.O-O Rc8 { is similar. We have a decent exchange structure but why exactly is the pawn on  h4 ? } )
10. Qd7{ Black can play this simple move to keep everything harmoniously defended. }
11. Ne5( { The only forcing option. After normal developing moves like }11.O-O { , we'll get a good position by simply developing ourselves }11...Rfc8= { . } )
11. Nxe5
12. dxe5( { This gives the game some dynamics. }12.Bxe5 Bxe2 13.Nxe2 Rfc8 { is just one of these exchange structures where the pawn on  h4  looks more than a problem than a good thing. } )
12. Ne4{ Black can occupy this nice outpost. If White wants to grab a pawn, things will be very double-edged. }
13. Bxg4( { One of White's different options.     A)  }13.Qxd5 Nxc3 14.Qxd7 Bxd7 15.bxc3 Rac8=∞ { leads to typical, good compensation for the pawn.     B)    }13.Nxd5? { is a huge mistake. }13...Bxe2 14.Kxe2 Qg4+ { and White either drops the  g2 -pawn or runs into }15.Kf1 Nd2+-+ {     C)  After   }13.f3 { , we can just take on  c3 . }13...Nxc3 14.Qxc3 Bf5!? { ⇆ }{ Inviting White to weaken their kingside even more with  g2 - g4 . Next, we just put a rook on  c8  and start counterplay via the c-file. } )
13. Qxg4
14. Qxd5( { There is nothing better.     A)  }14.Nxe4 dxe4 { is a very decent position for Black.     B)  }14.Nxd5? { This can win a pawn but after invading on  g2 , White's king is in horrible shape. }14...Qxg2 15.Nxe7+ Kh8-+ { The only way to hang on to the material is }16.Rf1 { but after }16...Rad8 { the king is stuck in the center. } )
14. Nxc3
15. bxc3
15. b6{ Saving the b-pawn. With ... Rac8  and ... Rfd8  coming, we have once again the typical compensation. }
