6. Nc6
7. h4
7. Bg7{ Developing the kingside is Black's most flexible way to continue the development. }
8. e3
8. O-O( { White's main move here is }9.Qb3 { but let's look at the other options first to understand why. } )
9. Ne5{ Stopping ... Bg4 , maybe hoping to get an attacking position. }
9. Nxe5{ This is a very reliable solution. By exchanging some pieces, Black makes sure that White cannot build up any kind of attack on the kingside.  And even if the position looks simplified, the position is more complex than it seems. }
10. dxe5{ This recapture would be good if it would win the  d5 -pawn but it doesn't. The pawn can easily be more of a target than an asset. }
10. Ne4{ The most active square. }
11. h5{ This is a typical move but White won't be able to combine this with any kind of kingside attack. }
11. Nxc3{ A very ambitious move. Stopping all kinds of ideas to go  Nxe4   dxe4  and exchange queens. }( { Simple development with, for example, }11...Bf5 { is also possible. Black really has no problems. } )
12. bxc3
12. Qb6( { Activating the queen. }12...Qa5 { is similar. } )
13. h6{ Pushing the pawn to  h6  instead of taking on  g6  is one of Alpha Zero's favourite ideas. Here, it is not too impressive. }
13. Bh8{ Black will just continue with ... Be6 , ... Rac8  and put pressure on White's pawns. Eventually, we might think about ... f6  to open up our bishop. }
