7. Bg7{ Developing the kingside is Black's most flexible way to continue the development. }
8. e3
8. O-O( { White's main move here is }9.Qb3 { but let's look at the other options first to understand why. } )
9. Ne5{ Stopping ... Bg4 , maybe hoping to get an attacking position. }
9. Nxe5{ This is a very reliable solution. By exchanging some pieces, Black makes sure that White cannot build up any kind of attack on the kingside.  And even if the position looks simplified, the position is more complex than it seems. }
10. dxe5{ This recapture would be good if it would win the  d5 -pawn but it doesn't. The pawn can easily be more of a target than an asset. }
10. Ne4{ The most active square. }
11. Nxd5( { Taking the pawn cannot be recommended.     A)  }11.Qxd5?! { is slightly better but Black can just play the 'easy moves'. }11...Nxc3 12.Qxd8 Rxd8 13.bxc3 Be6 { Black will follow up with ... Rac8  and will have no problems regaining the pawn. ... Rc5  to prepare ... Rfc8  or 'rovering' along the 5th rank makes a lot of sense. Once the pawn is lost, White simply has the slightly weaker structure. } )( {  B)  }11.Nxe4 dxe4 { is playable but despite reaching a pretty symmetrical structure, it rather helps Black. The  e5 -pawn is more vulnerable than  e4  and Black will also be the one who takes over the d-file eventually with ... Qa5 + and ... Rd8  ideas. } )
11. Be6{ A precise move. White has nothing better than going back to  c3 . }( 11...Qa5+? 12.b4! { works for White. } )
12. Nc3( 12.Nb4? { is a weird square just to avoid the weakened pawn structure after  12.Nc3 . }12...Qa5-+ { is just }{ winning.  b4  is hanging, we can always recapture on  e5  and ... Rfd8  will come quickly to bring the last pieces into the game. } )
12. Nxc3( { White is in a tough situation.     A)    }13.Qxd8 Rfxd8 14.bxc3 Rac8 { leads to a horrible endgame despite the extra pawn - that one will fall soon and     B)    }13.bxc3 Qa5 { will give Black a strong initiative against all the weak white pawns. } )
