7. h4
7. Bg7{ Developing the kingside is Black's most flexible way to continue the development. }
8. e3
8. O-O( { White's main move here is }9.Qb3 { but let's look at the other options first to understand why. } )
9. Ne5{ Stopping ... Bg4 , maybe hoping to get an attacking position. }
9. Nxe5{ This is a very reliable solution. By exchanging some pieces, Black makes sure that White cannot build up any kind of attack on the kingside.  And even if the position looks simplified, the position is more complex than it seems. }
10. Bxe5{ This is pretty much exclusively played. }
10. Ne4( { A strong move to clarify the situation.    }10...Bf5 11.Bxf6 Bxf6 12.g4! { might actually give White good attacking chances and a rather passive move like   }10...Be6 { allows }11.Bd3 { when Black has some problems creating counterplay. } )
11. Bxg7( { White should take the bishop. }11.Nxe4 { gives Black the chance to simply play }11...dxe4 { , offering to transpose but we can also play the slightly stronger }11...Bxe5! { .    If the knight retreats, we will retreat as well and have won the bishop pair while }12.dxe5 dxe4 { is not as easy as it seems.  ...Qa5+  is a threat and overall,  e5  is just an easy target. The queen exchange is clearly the best option. }13.Qxd8 Rxd8 { Still, White has to be really careful. ... Rd5  is an option, ... Bg4  can be annoying to stop White from fighting for the d-file. }14.Bc4! { looks like the right way for White to keep the balance but for example }14.Rd1? Rxd1+ 15.Kxd1 Be6! { ∓ }{ with pressure against  a2  and ... Rd8 - d5  ideas would already be costing a pawn. } )
11. Kxg7{ The position looks simplified but there is still a game to be played. Because Black has the idea ... Nxc3 , most white players took on  e4  in this position but as you can see in the model games, this doesn't make it easy.  Grischuk has 2/2 in this position - one game was classical -, but the most impressive game I found was Egresi - Antal -  see here  where Black achieved a convincing victory. }
