8. O-O( { White's main move here is }9.Qb3 { but let's look at the other options first to understand why. } )
9. Qb3{ This is White's main move. By putting pressure on  b7 , White wants to make it hard for Black to develop the light-squared bishop. }
9. Na5( { I think it is hard to play without this move and by playing it immediately, we receive more information about where White wants to put their queen. Typically, White decides between }10.Qa3 { or }10.Qb4 { to keep control over the center and also the attack against }a5 { might play a role. } )( {  A)  }9...a6 { is another fighting move and can easily transpose to our lines as we will play  ...a6  in most cases anyways. } )( {  B)  }9...Re8!? { is also a similar move that is so far holding up quite nicely in practice (2 out of 3). We are preparing ... e5  but as we will see, this move does also work nicely in combination with ... Na5  as a queen on  a3  and especially  b4 , can be a target for tactics with ... Bf8  to either play ... e5  or simply trap the queen!     By starting with the rook move, Black keeps more control over  e5  but on the other side, White hasn't yet committed the queen to either  a3  or  b4  so it is not clear if Black's subtle ... Bf8  idea will be important at all. Also, as 9... Re8  is less forcing, there are more potential move orders. Nevertheless, this move can easily transpose to our recommended lines as }10.Be2 { is the most critical move order. White wants to play }-- 11.Ne5 { next when neither }...Ng4 { nor }...Nh5 { are possible and the pawn sacrifice with }...Nd7 { is also less attractive as White is one move closer to castling.    }10.Ne5 { This knight jump immediately played happened only once. Here, Black has different good solutions.     B1)  }10...Nd7!? { I think the easiest solution is to just challenge the knight right away. }11.Nxd7 { White has nothing better than to take. }11...Bxd7 { Black is ready to open the center with ...  e5  but even playing it slow with ... e6  looks definitely like a decent exchange structure. }{     B2)  }10...Ng4 11.Nxg4 Bxg4 12.Qxd5 e5!? { is similar while     B3)  }10...Nh5!? { is also working - and an important resource in general - but here leading to unnecessarily complicated variations. }11.Bh2 Bxe5! 12.dxe5 d4! 13.Rd1 Be6 14.Qxb7 dxc3 15.Rxd8 Rexd8 16.bxc3 Rab8 17.Qxc6 Rb1+ 18.Ke2 Rb2+ 19.Ke1 Rb1+ { with perpetual check is just one of the variations that describe the craziness. } )
10. Qb4{ This is generally considered the less ambitious move as White is pretty much offering a repetition. However, if we want to play on, this might be even trickier to face as the queen is more influential on  b4  than on  a3 . }
10. a6{ This is just a useful move to stop all  Nc3 - b5  or  Bf1 - b5  ideas. Eventually, the move might be also useful to play ... b5 . }( 10...Nc6 11.Qb3 { happened in several games to make a quick draw. White could deviate with   }11.Qa3 { but without the queen on  b3 , we can just develop with }11...Bg4 { and have zero problems.  In a practical game, it might be smart to repeat the moves once and maybe provoke White to play an inferior move if they want to keep the game going as well. However,  10...a6  is the more ambitious move. } )( { The immediate }10...Re8 { is also playable with similar ideas to the ones that we will see. White has some extra options to use the  b5 -square such as }11.Bb5 Nc6 12.Bxc6 bxc6 { but to be fair, this doesn't look like a problem at all. }{ The bishop pair and White's slightly vulnerable setup should compensate for the weakness on  c6 . } )
11. Rc1{ In my opinion, this is White's most critical move as it prepares some subtle tactics. It can be combined with  Bf4 - c7  ideas but if we are aware of that, we can keep it easily under control. }
11. Re8{ This move, followed by ... Bf8  eventually is one of Black's main resources against the queen on  b4 . }
12. Bd3{ If White just develops, we can execute the standard plan. }
12. Bf8{ With the rook on  c1 , we should play ... Bf8  immediately. }( 12...Bd7?! { is sometimes a good inclusion but here - very subtle - White's rook on }c1 { can make it hard for Black to create queenside counterplay after }13.Ne5! Bf8 14.Ne2! e6 15.Qd2 { This is slightly problematic.     A)  }15...Rc8? 16.Bg5! { Ideas if  Bxf6 ,  Nxd7  and  Qxa5  are just overloading Black's queen and }{     B)    }15...Bb5? 16.Nxf7 Kxf7 17.Bc7 { does also win material. } )
13. Qa4{ Usually the move to play if Black doesn't start with ... Bd7 . }( 13.Ne5 { blocks  ...e5  but Black can challenge the knight immediately with }13...Ng4 { or }13...Nd7 { . }{ If White exchanges the knights, we would be threatening ... e5  once again. } )
13. Bd7{ Developing with tempo and driving the queen to a worse square. }
14. Qc2{ The best move even though the queen is vulnerable here against ...  Na5 - c6 - b4  or ... Rc8 . White plays with the idea to play  h4 - h5  next. }( 14.Qd1 Bg4 { doesn't give White any aggressive options. } )
14. Nc6{ The last precise move. We are threatening ... Nb4  but we also take control over  e5  to prepare ... Bg4  without running into  Nf3 - e5 . }( 14...Rc8? 15.h5! { is all of a sudden dangerous. }15...Nxh5 16.Rxh5! gxh5 17.Bxh7++- { is starting a devastating attack on the kingside. } )
15. a3
15. Bg4( { Stopping  h4-h5 . If White plays }16.Ne5 { , we can simply take and after }16.Nh2 { a very principled reaction is }16...e5 { to open up the center. } )
