9. Na5( { I think it is hard to play without this move and by playing it immediately, we receive more information about where White wants to put their queen. Typically, White decides between }10.Qa3 { or }10.Qb4 { to keep control over the center and also the attack against }a5 { might play a role. } )( {  A)  }9...a6 { is another fighting move and can easily transpose to our lines as we will play  ...a6  in most cases anyways. } )( {  B)  }9...Re8!? { is also a similar move that is so far holding up quite nicely in practice (2 out of 3). We are preparing ... e5  but as we will see, this move does also work nicely in combination with ... Na5  as a queen on  a3  and especially  b4 , can be a target for tactics with ... Bf8  to either play ... e5  or simply trap the queen!     By starting with the rook move, Black keeps more control over  e5  but on the other side, White hasn't yet committed the queen to either  a3  or  b4  so it is not clear if Black's subtle ... Bf8  idea will be important at all. Also, as 9... Re8  is less forcing, there are more potential move orders. Nevertheless, this move can easily transpose to our recommended lines as }10.Be2 { is the most critical move order. White wants to play }-- 11.Ne5 { next when neither }...Ng4 { nor }...Nh5 { are possible and the pawn sacrifice with }...Nd7 { is also less attractive as White is one move closer to castling.    }10.Ne5 { This knight jump immediately played happened only once. Here, Black has different good solutions.     B1)  }10...Nd7!? { I think the easiest solution is to just challenge the knight right away. }11.Nxd7 { White has nothing better than to take. }11...Bxd7 { Black is ready to open the center with ...  e5  but even playing it slow with ... e6  looks definitely like a decent exchange structure. }{     B2)  }10...Ng4 11.Nxg4 Bxg4 12.Qxd5 e5!? { is similar while     B3)  }10...Nh5!? { is also working - and an important resource in general - but here leading to unnecessarily complicated variations. }11.Bh2 Bxe5! 12.dxe5 d4! 13.Rd1 Be6 14.Qxb7 dxc3 15.Rxd8 Rexd8 16.bxc3 Rab8 17.Qxc6 Rb1+ 18.Ke2 Rb2+ 19.Ke1 Rb1+ { with perpetual check is just one of the variations that describe the craziness. } )
10. Qa3( { This is the main move for White as it doesn't allow the repetition with }10.Qb4 Nc6 { . }{ But the queen is controlling fewer squares on  a3  and this makes our task here much easier. Especially the move ... Nc4  can be accomplished easily. } )
10. Bf5{ A very reliable move. Black wants to jump to  c4  with the knight but only after White has made a move with their bishop. }( { The immediate }10...Nc4 { is making use of the fact that the queen doesn't control the  c4 -square. This entertaining move was played in Fedoseev - Carlsen, Wijk 2019. }{    Both after }11.Bxc4 dxc4 { as well as after   }11.Qb4 a5!? { , the game gets nicely imbalances. However, I didn't like that White can play   }11.Qb3 { when it seems Black cannot really avoid the repetition with }11...Na5 { . } )
11. Be2{ This is White's main move but it gives Black a decent version of the  10...Nc4 -line as White has already moved their light-squared bishop. }
11. Nc4( { Creating imbalances. }11...Ne4 12.Nxe4 Bxe4 { would be a more solid way of handling the position. } )
12. Qb3( { Played in the only game I found with this position.     A)  }12.Qb4 Qb6 { would be pretty much the same just with fewer options for White as their queen is not protected. } )( {  B)  }12.Bxc4 dxc4 { gives Black a decent position with bishop pair and queenside majority. This is literally the  10...Nc4   11.Bxc4   dxc4 -variation being a full tempo up. After }13.O-O { , we can just play }13...a6 { to prepare  ...b5  or go }13...Re8 { to prepare }-- ...Nd5 { . } )
12. Qb6( { Black is threatening to play   }13...Nxb2 { . } )( { In Xu - Areshenko, Sharjah 2017, White simplified with }13.Bxc4 dxc4 14.Qxb6 axb6⇆ { but Black found a nice plan with ... Ra5  to prepare ... b5  and the advance of the queenside pawns. Black got good winning chances in that game. } )
