[White "9) Schlexchange Bishop Hunt - 7.e3"]
[Black "Introduction 7.e3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4
6. Nc6
7. e3
7. Nh5( { This position after }7...Nh5 { is one of those you'll regularly get as a Grünfeld Slav player.   }5.cxd5 { is often an indication that our opponents know you at least a little bit about the Schlechter Slav, and the moves   }6.Bf4 { and   }7.e3 { are quickly played on autopilot after that.    Objectively, this may be one of the most critical variations against the Schlechter setup, but I haven't found anything totally convincing for White, and even if improvements for White exist somewhere, they are in an extremely unbalanced position type in which we are permanently the side more familiar with the ideas and plans. } )( { With our move }7...Nh5! { we go for the white bishop pair with all our might. If White gives it to us voluntarily with }8.Bg3 { , I would already objectively prefer the black position minimally, but even if White plays one of the correct moves }5.Bg5 { or   }5.Be5 { , I think only Black has fun with the position for the time being, who determines the positional character and - after studying this chapter - knows all the typical motifs that can get White into trouble very quickly.    This is really one of the chapters I would recommend you to study carefully. Black has many aggressive ideas and move sequence subtleties to make the most of his position.    Rules for this chapter:    - Go for this bishop pair!    - Study this chapter carefully! } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Schlexchange Bishop Hunt - 7.e3"]
[Black "8.Bg5 & 10.Be2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nb8 - c6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bf8 - g7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move  …Nc6-a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 .     Now, White has to make a decision. Their ideal setup contains  e3  (to finish development) and  h3  (mainly to have the  h2 -square for the bishop). If White can reach this setup, they should indeed be able to claim a small edge. However, there is no ideal move order for White to do this without allowing Black to create dynamic imbalances. }( { The main rule is: If White goes }7.h3 { , we go }...Ne4 { to take on  c3 . } )( { If White plays }7.e3 { , we go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Bg5
8. h6( { We have to play this move at some point. We can also start with }8...Bg7 { .    However, White can respond with }9.Bh4!? { which somehow forces Black to transpose to the mainline with }9...h6 { . The problem is that a normal-looking move like }9...O-O { is answered with }10.Qb3! { and Black has some problems keeping both the  d5  and the  b7 -pawn defended! } )
9. Bh4
9. Bg7{ It is still Black's main idea to go  g5  and gain the bishop pair. We also need an answer for  Qb3 . }( 9...g5?! { is a typical move but we need our bishop on  g7 ! Here, White has a strong response. }10.Ne5! { is just better for White.    }{ If we save our knight from  h5 , White can just respond with  11.Bg3  and we have lost a lot of time and weakened our kingside without succeeding in winning our bishop pair. }10...Nxe5 { is the only try to justify Black's last move but this knight will be missed soon. After }11.dxe5 { , Black has no good reply. More or less all logical moves run into a well-timed  Bb5+ .    For example,     A)  }11...d4 12.Qxh5 dxc3 13.Bb5+! Bd7 14.e6! { would be a painful end to the game.     B)    }11...gxh4 12.Bb5+! { Even stronger than taking on  h5 . }12...Bd7 13.e6! { Once again this motif! }13...Bxb5 14.Qxh5 Rh7 15.Nxb5 Qa5+ 16.Nc3+- { Material is equal but Black's king is never going to survive in this position. } )
10. Be2{ This isn't a particularly threatening move. Black can just execute their main idea which is to ... g5  and grab the bishop pair. }
10. g5
11. Nd2{ It is always worth a thought to answer ... g5  with a counter-attack against  h5 . As it is not our intention to drop back with the knight, we have to go for the exchange  Nh5  vs.  Bh4 .     However, it is important to do it under the most dynamic circumstances! Let's use this trainable to show some nice ideas! }( 11.Bg3 { is a solid move but Black has no problems. }11...Nxg3 12.hxg3 e6 { With a solid position for Black.    }{ We will just finish our development with something like ...  O-O , ... Bd7 , ... Qe7  and once all our pieces are out, we can decide whether we want to play on the queenside with ... Rc8 , ... a6 , ... b5  or if we advance on the kingside with ... f5 , ... g4 , ... h5 .     These positions can become very interesting! } )
11. e5( { A very nice move order subtlety!     A)  }11...gxh4 12.Bxh5 e5!? { is similar but White can take on  e5  under slightly better circumstances. } )( {  B)  }11...Nf4!? { is a nice idea to spoil White's pawn structure as well! }12.exf4 gxh4 { and Black has a decent position with the pressure against  d4 . } )
12. dxe5( 12.Bxh5 exd4! { is a nice in-between move before taking on  h4 . Black opens the e-file and creates a weakness on  d4  if White recaptures. } )
12. d4( { Black just opens up the center and wants to win the  f4 -square for their knight after }13.exd4?! Nf4! { . Usually, these dynamics work very well for Black! } )
