3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nb8 - c6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bf8 - g7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move  …Nc6-a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 .     Now, White has to make a decision. Their ideal setup contains  e3  (to finish development) and  h3  (mainly to have the  h2 -square for the bishop). If White can reach this setup, they should indeed be able to claim a small edge. However, there is no ideal move order for White to do this without allowing Black to create dynamic imbalances. }( { The main rule is: If White goes }7.h3 { , we go }...Ne4 { to take on  c3 . } )( { If White plays }7.e3 { , we go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Bg5
8. h6( { We have to play this move at some point. We can also start with }8...Bg7 { .    However, White can respond with }9.Bh4!? { which somehow forces Black to transpose to the mainline with }9...h6 { . The problem is that a normal-looking move like }9...O-O { is answered with }10.Qb3! { and Black has some problems keeping both the  d5  and the  b7 -pawn defended! } )
9. Bh4
9. Bg7{ It is still Black's main idea to go  g5  and gain the bishop pair. We also need an answer for  Qb3 . }( 9...g5?! { is a typical move but we need our bishop on  g7 ! Here, White has a strong response. }10.Ne5! { is just better for White.    }{ If we save our knight from  h5 , White can just respond with  11.Bg3  and we have lost a lot of time and weakened our kingside without succeeding in winning our bishop pair. }10...Nxe5 { is the only try to justify Black's last move but this knight will be missed soon. After }11.dxe5 { , Black has no good reply. More or less all logical moves run into a well-timed  Bb5+ .    For example,     A)  }11...d4 12.Qxh5 dxc3 13.Bb5+! Bd7 14.e6! { would be a painful end to the game.     B)    }11...gxh4 12.Bb5+! { Even stronger than taking on  h5 . }12...Bd7 13.e6! { Once again this motif! }13...Bxb5 14.Qxh5 Rh7 15.Nxb5 Qa5+ 16.Nc3+- { Material is equal but Black's king is never going to survive in this position. } )
10. Bb5( { This is finally a move that disturbs our plan to play }10...g5 { . By pinning the knight, White can play }11.Ne5 { under much better circumstances. } )
10. O-O{ Unpins the  c6 -knight and makes it possible to play ... g5  next. }( 10...g5?! 11.Ne5! { is once again slightly better for White. We have no  ...Nxe5 ! }11...Bxe5 12.Qxh5 { White is better after }12...Bf6 13.Bg3 { as well as after   }12...Bxd4 13.exd4 gxh4 14.Qxh4± { . } )
11. O-O( { The most normal move. }11.Rc1 { leads to a variation from the  7.Rc1 move order . } )
11. g5{ Now, Black is ready to go after the bishop! }
12. Ne1{ A move that we'll not see very often. The idea is similar to a lot of  Nf3 - d2 -variations. Luckily, we can just copy the counter recipe. }( 12.Nd2 e5! { would also be the line here. } )
12. e5{ Once again, we can go ... e5  and ... exd4  before taking on  h4 . }
13. Qxh5{ The start of a pretty long, forcing variation. }
13. exd4{ I'll go with this move here as well as taking on  d4  before taking on  h4  is what we usually do in most lines of this repertoire. }( { Nevertheless, }13...gxh4!? { is also playable here. Black will get their pieces to decent squares.    For example, }14.dxe5 Nxe5 { already threatens }-- ...Bg4 { . White has to spend a tempo against this and Black can just finish the development with ... a6 , ... Be6  and can potentially play ... Qg5  to get rid of White's queen or can play actively with ... Nc4 . } )
14. Bxg5( { Taking a pawn. }14.exd4 gxh4 { is just a good version for Black as  d4  is under pressure. } )
14. Qxg5{ We are happy to exchange queens as our king is weaker than White's. }
15. Qxg5
15. hxg5
16. Nxd5{ If White does not continue to be greedy, Black is just fine with their active pieces. }
16. dxe3{ Ruining White's structure. }
17. fxe3( { Forced if White has any ambitions. }17.Nxe3 Bxb2 { allows Black to get their pawn back immediately. } )
17. Rd8( { Don't go }17...Bxb2? 18.Rb1 { and Black will lose material. }18...Bg7 19.Bxc6! bxc6 20.Nc7 { wins the exchange and   }18...Be5 19.Nf3 { doesn't help.    }{ Black should rely on their activity instead of taking on  b2  immediately. Black has enough compensation with White's weak  e3  and  b2 -pawns and ideas to enter with ... Rd2 .     Just to give some sample lines: } )( {  A)    }18.Nf6+ Bxf6 19.Rxf6 Kg7 20.Rf2 Ne5 { and Black's active pieces compensate for the pawn. } )( {  B)    }18.Bxc6 bxc6 19.Ne7+ Kf8 20.Nxc6 ( { ( }20.Nxc8 Raxc8 { also promises Black active piece play.) } )20...Re8 { Black will win back one pawn and with such mighty bishops, they will have decent compensation. } )
