10. Bb5( { This is finally a move that disturbs our plan to play }10...g5 { . By pinning the knight, White can play }11.Ne5 { under much better circumstances. } )
10. O-O{ Unpins the  c6 -knight and makes it possible to play ... g5  next. }( 10...g5?! 11.Ne5! { is once again slightly better for White. We have no  ...Nxe5 ! }11...Bxe5 12.Qxh5 { White is better after }12...Bf6 13.Bg3 { as well as after   }12...Bxd4 13.exd4 gxh4 14.Qxh4± { . } )
11. O-O( { The most normal move. }11.Rc1 { leads to a variation from the  7.Rc1 move order . } )
11. g5{ Now, Black is ready to go after the bishop! }
12. Bxc6{ If White wants to go for the  Ne5  idea, they have to take on  c6  first. }
12. bxc6
13. Ne5{ The logical follow-up. }
13. Bxe5{ Forced as White was attacking  h5  and  c6  both. White can now take both on  e5  or on  h5 . }
14. Qxh5
14. Bg7{ Saving  h6  and the bishop. }
15. Bg3{ An interesting position. White has the better pawn structure but Black has the bishop pair and some ambitious options to win space at the whole board. }
15. f6{ A nice move. Black prepares ... e5  and also ... Qe8  will be a nice move.  Without queens on the board, Black has a very easy time expanding on the kingside. Let's just use a sample line to see how the game can proceed. }
16. Na4{ The most direct move to fix the weakness on  c6 . White will just continue with putting a rook on  c1 . }
16. Qe8{ Protecting  c6  and preparing ... h5 . }
17. Qxe8{ The endgame will offer equal chances. The bishops compensate for the weakness on  c6 . }
17. Rxe8{ Let me show an instructive sample line. }
18. Rfc1
18. e5{ This shows a nice resource in these positions. Often Black doesn't even have to protect  c6  as it is tactically defended with ideas along the  a4 - e8  diagonal. }
19. Rxc6{ White can take the pawn but has to leave the active c-file to protect the knight. }( 19.dxe5 { avoids getting a weakness on  d4  but Black's pawns will become extremely mobile and in combination with the bishop pair, this promises very good compensation. }19...fxe5 20.Rxc6 Bf5! { Black is fully developed and ready to go ... d4 . Black is definitely okay in such scenarios. } )
19. Bd7
20. Ra6
20. exd4{ Creating a weakness on  d4 . }
21. exd4
21. f5{ Bringing the bishop on  g7  to life. White has to give their extra pawn back. }
22. Be5
22. Bxe5
23. dxe5
23. Bxa4
24. Rxa4
24. Rxe5{ With an equal endgame. }
