6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nb8 - c6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bf8 - g7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move  …Nc6-a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 .     Now, White has to make a decision. Their ideal setup contains  e3  (to finish development) and  h3  (mainly to have the  h2 -square for the bishop). If White can reach this setup, they should indeed be able to claim a small edge. However, there is no ideal move order for White to do this without allowing Black to create dynamic imbalances. }( { The main rule is: If White goes }7.h3 { , we go }...Ne4 { to take on  c3 . } )( { If White plays }7.e3 { , we go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Bg5
8. h6( { We have to play this move at some point. We can also start with }8...Bg7 { .    However, White can respond with }9.Bh4!? { which somehow forces Black to transpose to the mainline with }9...h6 { . The problem is that a normal-looking move like }9...O-O { is answered with }10.Qb3! { and Black has some problems keeping both the  d5  and the  b7 -pawn defended! } )
9. Bh4
9. Bg7{ It is still Black's main idea to go  g5  and gain the bishop pair. We also need an answer for  Qb3 . }( 9...g5?! { is a typical move but we need our bishop on  g7 ! Here, White has a strong response. }10.Ne5! { is just better for White.    }{ If we save our knight from  h5 , White can just respond with  11.Bg3  and we have lost a lot of time and weakened our kingside without succeeding in winning our bishop pair. }10...Nxe5 { is the only try to justify Black's last move but this knight will be missed soon. After }11.dxe5 { , Black has no good reply. More or less all logical moves run into a well-timed  Bb5+ .    For example,     A)  }11...d4 12.Qxh5 dxc3 13.Bb5+! Bd7 14.e6! { would be a painful end to the game.     B)    }11...gxh4 12.Bb5+! { Even stronger than taking on  h5 . }12...Bd7 13.e6! { Once again this motif! }13...Bxb5 14.Qxh5 Rh7 15.Nxb5 Qa5+ 16.Nc3+- { Material is equal but Black's king is never going to survive in this position. } )
10. Nd2{ This is a solid move. White tries to avoid the chaos combined with ... g5  by keeping an eye on the  h5 -knight. }
10. O-O{ The most flexible move. }
11. Rc1( { If White wants to play without  f2-f4 , this move is more flexible than }11.Be2 { or }11.Bd3 { . That the rook belongs to  c1  is much more certain than the positioning of White's light-squared bishop.    }11.Be2 Bf6! 12.Bxf6 Nxf6 { should transpose to  11.Rc1 . The rook belongs on the c-file. } )
11. Bf6{ A motif to remember. With White taking so much dynamic out of the game, our butcher might very likely not get the dynamic it requires, so it makes sense to exchange it. }
12. Bxf6
12. Nxf6{ White is left with the - on paper - better light-squared bishop. Nevertheless, our position is really solid and we have no really bad pieces.  Overall, I think Black's position is very playable. }
13. Bd3{ This is a normal-looking square for the bishop but Black's options to play dynamically in the center are becoming more attractive - this is not only true for this line! If Black plays their pawn breaks ... e5  (or ... c5  in other lines), White's bishop is often just in the way of its own pieces on the d-file.     So, I think a logical response is to strike immediately. }
13. e5{ A nice moment to become active. }
14. dxe5{ What else? }
14. Nxe5{ Black has active pieces,  d3  is hanging, ... d5 - d4  is an important idea to get rid of the IQP. White only has one decent move. }
15. Nb3( 15.Nf3? { is not a good idea. }15...Nxf3+! 16.Qxf3 d4! { and White even gets into immediate trouble. For example: }17.exd4 Re8+! 18.Ne2 Qa5+! { when White's king is under attack. } )
15. Bg4{ It is conventional knowledge that the side who plays with an Isolated Queen's Pawn, is not supposed to exchange minor pieces.     However concretely, exchanging the light-squared bishops is not a bad idea as our bishop had no concrete purpose and in the resulting position our knights should have decent prospects of using the outposts on  e4  and  c4  that our IQP provides. }
16. Be2
16. Bxe2
17. Nxe2( 17.Qxe2 Ne4! { allows making immediate use of the  e4 -square. }{ A solid idea for Black is to continue with ...  Rc8  and threaten to spoil White's pawn structure as well. } )
17. Qd6{ Black has their fair share of dynamics in this position and their knights can jump to  e4 ,  c4 , sometimes  g4 , while our rooks will have a lot of influence on the central files ( e8  and  d8  are the typical squares even though it is also possible to put a rook on  c8  as exchanging rooks is okay in this structure.)     I think just exchanging knights should generally be avoided as we need those horsies to create some dynamic counter-chances. }
