10. Be2{ is not in the spirit of White's setup. It doesn't put any pressure on Black's structure, so Black can even ignore all my warnings from the last move and just take on  g3 . }
10. Nxg3( { I would love to wait with this move and play }10...Bg7 { first, leaving the h-hile closed as long as possible. But White can play }11.Bh4! { with the annoying threat of  g2 - g4  as our knight has no squares.     So, if we want to develop our bishop to  g7 , we should take on  g3  first. } )
11. hxg3
11. Bg7( { With bishop (or queen) on the  b1 - h7  diagonal, White would have the typical tactic   }12.Rxh7 Rxh7 12.Bxg6+ { .    }{ Here, the game can easily transpose to positions that can also occur in variations where White did not voluntarily provoke the ... f6  move. }{ The only independent option is White going for  e3-e4  but this usually only works if Black reduces the pressure towards  d4  as a mistimed  e4  can be answered with ... dxe4   Nxe4   f5 ! with a double attack against }{  d4  and  e4 . } )
12. O-O
12. O-O
13. Re1{ White is anticipating that Black plays a move like ... Qe7  or ... Bd7 , so that Black has less pressure along the d-file and White can play  e3 - e4 . }( {  A)  }13.Rc1 { can transpose to more positional lines but doesn't really fit in the  e3 - e4  plan. The rook might even be hit with  ... Bg7 -h6  at some point. } )( {  B)  A mistimed }13.e4?! { does always run into }...dxe4 14.Nxe4 f5! { and Black wins the  d4 -pawn. } )
13. Bd7{ This allows White to execute their idea to go  e3 - e4 . I want to use the opportunity to show a typical pawn sacrifice. }( { But if you are not happy with my suggestion, let me just say that Black can also continue the 'waiting game' with moves like }13...a6 { (useful to avoid  Bb5  and  Nb5  in some variations), followed by ...  Kh8 , ... Qd6 , potentially advancing on the kingside with ... f5  and ... g5 . } )
14. e4{ Otherwise, Black will play 14... Be8  and White can no longer push the e-pawn. }
14. Be8{ If Black can play ... Bf7  next, we are completely solid. }( 14...dxe4?! { does no longer work as }d4 { is not hanging after }15.Nxe4 f5 { . White will get pressure along the e-file after }16.Nc5 { . } )
15. exd5{ This is winning a pawn but Black gets enough compensation. }
15. exd5
16. Qb3{ with the double attack against  b7  and  d5 . Why is this okay for Black?     Well, if White takes on  d5 , we will have a position with an open center and all of a sudden we have some monster bishops on  f7  and  g7  that put pressure on White's queenside. Combined with the weakness of the  d4 -pawn, this gives Black enough active opportunities. }
16. Rb8{ Black has no intentions to give the  b7 -pawn. We want rather lose the  d5 -pawn as this was the pawn that blocked our light-squared bishop. }
17. Qxd5+{ White is not forced to take but it is the most interesting variation - and other moves are also not promising for White. }
17. Qxd5
18. Nxd5
18. Bf7{ Where it belongs! }
19. Ne3( 19.Nc3 Rfd8 { is similar. } )
19. Rfd8{ , followed by ... f5 , ... Rbc8 , maybe ... Nb4 . It is annoying for White to save the  a2 -pawn without committing to moves like  a3  or  b3  that weaken the queenside even more. Black is just fine. }
