1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nb8 - c6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bf8 - g7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move  …Nc6-a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 .     Now, White has to make a decision. Their ideal setup contains  e3  (to finish development) and  h3  (mainly to have the  h2 -square for the bishop). If White can reach this setup, they should indeed be able to claim a small edge. However, there is no ideal move order for White to do this without allowing Black to create dynamic imbalances. }( { The main rule is: If White goes }7.h3 { , we go }...Ne4 { to take on  c3 . } )( { If White plays }7.e3 { , we go for the bishop pair with }7...Nh5 { . } )
7. e3
7. Nh5( { A really important move in our setup. After }7...Bg7 8.h3! { it is too late for }8...Ne4 { as Black cannot create real imbalances after }9.Rc1 { . } )
8. Be5{ This is White's most serious option. }
8. f6( 8...Nxe5? { is bad here for several reasons. The typical response is }9.dxe5 { with an attack against  d5  and Black also has to worry about ideas with  g2 - g4  or  Bb5+/ Qa4 + . }{ Concretely, even }9.Nxe5 { is annoying with ideas like  Bb5+/Qa4+ . } )
9. Bg3
9. e6{ Black stabilises their pawns.     It is important not to hurry with  Bg7  because when White plays  Bg3 - h4  to save their bishop, we might run into tactics connected with  g2 - g4 . Overall, the main difference of this  8.Be5 -variation is the provoked move ... f6 .     We have already seen a lot of positions where Black willingly played the move ... f6  to take control over the  e5 -square and potentially prepare ... e5 . However, this is usually only a good idea if Black has a decent development and White has no way to punish Black for the weaknesses that go hand in hand with this pawn advance.  What weaknesses are those? Well, I guess the honest answer is: Black's whole kingside pawn structure.  So there are some things to consider in this line:     - If we take on  g3  prematurely, White might use the open h-hile for pressure against  h7  and  g6      - We have to be more careful about the  a2 - g8  diagonal - White has more incentive to play an early  e3 - e4  to get more open files and easier access to Black's pawns. Especially the pawn on  e6  is a natural target if White gets an open e-file     All this sounds a little bit scary but don't panic! The main implication is that we should not take on  g3  on autopilot and that we should have this  e3 - e4  break in mind when we decide which move order to choose.  To take right away on  g3  is a little bit risky with the open h-file, the weakened kingside structure and Black not being developed yet: }( 9...Nxg3?! 10.hxg3 { and the desirable }10...Bg7 { runs into immediate problems after }11.Qc2! { with the threat of  12.Rxh7 . }11...O-O 12.Nxd5! { doesn't help either. Black has better moves on move 10 - like   }10...Be6 { - but all those moves don't really solve Black's problems. } )
10. Bd3{ This is clearly the most critical continuation. The bishop pressures the kingside which discourages us from taking on  g3 . Also, this bishop prepares  e3 - e4 . }
10. Bd7{ A good move against the immediate  e3 - e4 . The bishop just stabilizes the  c6 -knight but more concretely, Black can play ... Nb4  without allowing any checks along the  a4 - e8  diagonal and the bishop is also ready to stabilize the light squares from  c6  after that. }( {  A)  }10...Bg7?! 11.Bh4! { is the typical  g2-g4  problem. } )( {  B)  }10...Nxg3?! 11.hxg3 Bg7? 12.Rxh7! { is a typical tactic to exploit it if Black opens the h-file too soon. } )
11. O-O{ This is White's more flexible move. }
11. Be7{ I think this is Black's most solid move. One important defensive idea behind this move is that  e3 - e4  will be answered ... dxe4 , followed by ... f5 . This might force some concessions from our opponents. If we take on  g3  right now, we lose this defensive resource because ... f5 - f4  is no longer a threat to trap the  g3 -bishop. }( 11...Bg7? 12.Bd6! { should not be played. } )
12. e4{ The most direct approach. However, Black's defensive plan is the same, more or less no matter the exact move order. }
12. dxe4
13. Bxe4{ The better way to recapture as White is ready to open the position further with  d4 - d5 . }
13. f5( { That is an important move.   }14...fxe4 { is equally a threat as }14...f4 { , trapping the other bishop, so White is forced to give away their light-squared bishop. } )
14. Bxc6
14. Bxc6{ Black has nice control over the light squares and ... f4  is still a threat. }
15. Be5{ The best move. }
15. O-O{ Saving the rook with castling! Black's next moves are easy. We'll go ...  Qd7 , put our rooks in the center (c8 and  d8  look most active but maybe we put one on  e8  to stabilize  e6 ), we'll regroup our knight from  h5  back to  f6  where it also controls the light squares in the center.  Black is very solid. }
