11. Be7{ I think this is Black's most solid move. One important defensive idea behind this move is that  e3 - e4  will be answered ... dxe4 , followed by ... f5 . This might force some concessions from our opponents. If we take on  g3  right now, we lose this defensive resource because ... f5 - f4  is no longer a threat to trap the  g3 -bishop. }( 11...Bg7? 12.Bd6! { should not be played. } )
12. Rc1{ Let's look at a more flexible move order for White. Black's next moves are usually ... O-O  and ... Rc8  if White delays  e3 - e4  - those moves always make sense in Black's position. }
12. O-O
13. Re1{ White plays some flexible moves, keeping the option  e3 - e4  open while not committing to it. White might also play slow on the queenside with  a3 ,  Na4  and  b4 . }
13. Rc8
14. a3{ Another flexible move.  Let's just mention that Black's reaction to the  e4  move is so far still the same: }( 14.e4 dxe4! 15.Bxe4 f5 16.Bxc6 Bxc6 { followed by all the possible moves that take control over the  d5 -square. } )
14. Be8{ Always a nice manoeuvre. In most cases, the bishop gets just transferred to  f7  where it stabilizes Black's whole pawn structure (and sometimes prepares .... e5  this way).     But Black might also combine this move with more creative manoeuvres (... Rf7 , ... Bf8 , ... Rfc7  is an instructive manoeuvre that I saw more than once while preparing this course even though this should only work if White plays their position extreeeemely slow. }
15. Na4{ At some point, White needs to commit to one plan. This is a typical move to play on the queenside by preparing  Nc5 . }( { If White goes }15.e4 { we can still go for the standard manoeuvre }15...dxe4 16.Bxe4 f5!  )
15. Bf7{ This is the typical follow-up. }
16. Nc5{ White wants to provoke weaknesses on the queenside but Black doesn't need to worry too much. }
16. b6{ It is a typical manoeuvre that White spends two tempi just to provoke ... b6 . }
17. Na4{ Usually, it is considered White's best option to just go back to  a4 . }
17. Na5{ And Black can start their own counterplay on the queenside. A typical outpost is the  c4 -square.  At some point, we'll take on  g3  and - if  c4  is not available- , we might also play the interesting manoeuvre... Na5 - b7 - d6  as this is often considered the best square for the knight in these structures. }
