6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nc6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bg7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move ... Nc6 - a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 . }
7. Rc1( { This is a pretty smart move. If White comes to the conclusion that both }7.e3 Nh5 { and   }7.h3 Ne4 { are good for Black, this is a logical move.   }{ Not only is  c1  the most natural square for the rook anyways in the Exchange structure, but more concretely, White is also preparing to recapture on  c3  with the rook, if Black goes ... Ne4 . } )( { As we have seen, this doesn't work out in the move order }7.h3 Ne4 8.Rc1 Nxc3 { because }9.Rxc3 { allows }...e5! { with }-- ...Bb4 { ideas.    But if White just changes the move order, this is a very serious idea. } )
7. Bg7( 7...Nh5 { might also be possible but besides all the typical moves ( Bg5 ,  Be5 ,  Bg3 ), White can also play }8.Bd2 { .    }{ This might be playable for Black, but White would have won a tempo compared to other lines with  e2 - e3  and  cxd5  - see  this chapter  - as Black should play ... Nh5 - f6  soon when they wasted two tempi with their knight ( f6 - h5 - f6 ) while White's bishop moves improved its position ( c1 - f4 - d2 ). } )
8. e3
8. O-O{ A nice flexible waiting move. ... Nh5  is an important idea but the inclusion of  Rc1  and  Bg7  compared to lines  7.e3  might indeed be useful for White.  In some lines, Black likes to postpone taking the bishop on  g3  if White can make immediate use of the open h-file. But without the  g7 -square available, Black has to worry about their knight - for comparison's sake  see here . }
9. Bb5{ A positional move. White might consider taking on  c6 , creating a pawn weakness on the c-file and putting pressure on that pawn. }
9. Nh5( { Still, White doesn't stop }...Nh5 { , so we go for it! White has the typical tries }10.Bg5 { and }10.Be5 { . } )
10. Bg5
10. h6{ The typical reaction. We hunt down the bishop. }
11. Bh4
11. g5{ Business as usual for us in this variation. }
12. Bxc6{ White played  9.Bb5  to create a weakness on  c6 . This is a good moment to do it. If they wait any longer, Black might be able to stop it. }( { After }12.Bg3 Nxg3 13.hxg3 Qd6 { , }{ Black is able to recapture on  c6  with the queen. } )
12. bxc6
13. Ne5{ This is the critical line. White attacks the knight on  h5 , also  c6  is under attack. Black is forced to take on  e5 . }
13. Bxe5
14. Qxh5{ This is the best move for White. }
14. Bg7{ Forced. }
15. Bg3{ Interestingly, we could reach this position via the  7.e3  move order, just that White would have most likely played  O-O  instead of  Rc1  to evacuate the king.     Here, Black can play even more dynamically to activate their pieces. }
15. c5{ Breaking up the center. }
16. h4( { It seems White has a slim path to equality, starting with this move.    }16.dxc5?! d4! { This is always an important resource in Black's play. }17.exd4 ( { ( }17.Rd1?! dxc3! { is a queen that Black is more than ready to sacrifice. With minor piece + rook for the queen, it is barely a sacrifice and Black will either remain with a massive passed pawn on }b2 { or White has to take on }c3 { after }18.Rxd8 Rxd8 { . White's king is in grave danger.) } )17...Qxd4∓ { is terrible for White because }-- ...Bg4 { is a threat and that means that their king will remain in the center. } )
16. cxd4
17. exd4
17. g4{ Closing down the kingside before taking on  d4 . }
18. Be5{ Let's look from here on at a sample line that illustrates some nice points. }
18. f6{ Black has no intention to exchange the dark-squared bishop. }
19. Bf4{ Attacking  h6 . }
19. e5{ Black just ignores the attack against  h6  and goes for immediate counterplay in the center. That's the spirit of how you play when you have the two bishops and the opponent's king is in the center! }
