1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nc6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bg7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move ... Nc6 - a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 . }
7. Rc1( { This is a pretty smart move. If White comes to the conclusion that both }7.e3 Nh5 { and   }7.h3 Ne4 { are good for Black, this is a logical move.   }{ Not only is  c1  the most natural square for the rook anyways in the Exchange structure, but more concretely, White is also preparing to recapture on  c3  with the rook, if Black goes ... Ne4 . } )( { As we have seen, this doesn't work out in the move order }7.h3 Ne4 8.Rc1 Nxc3 { because }9.Rxc3 { allows }...e5! { with }-- ...Bb4 { ideas.    But if White just changes the move order, this is a very serious idea. } )
7. Bg7( 7...Nh5 { might also be possible but besides all the typical moves ( Bg5 ,  Be5 ,  Bg3 ), White can also play }8.Bd2 { .    }{ This might be playable for Black, but White would have won a tempo compared to other lines with  e2 - e3  and  cxd5  - see  this chapter  - as Black should play ... Nh5 - f6  soon when they wasted two tempi with their knight ( f6 - h5 - f6 ) while White's bishop moves improved its position ( c1 - f4 - d2 ). } )
8. e3
8. O-O{ A nice flexible waiting move. ... Nh5  is an important idea but the inclusion of  Rc1  and  Bg7  compared to lines  7.e3  might indeed be useful for White.  In some lines, Black likes to postpone taking the bishop on  g3  if White can make immediate use of the open h-file. But without the  g7 -square available, Black has to worry about their knight - for comparison's sake  see here . }
9. Be2( { This looks rather passive but is better than }9.Bd3 { if White plans to answer ... }Nh5 { with }Be5 { . White will have less trouble with the pawn on  e5  in comparison. Check out these lines starting  here  to see the problems of  9.Bd3 . } )
9. Nh5{ If White doesn't save the bishop with  9.h3  , this is always the response. }
10. Be5( { This doesn't look like a good version to go }10.Bg5 { . Black can just grab the bishop with ... h6 , ... g5  and ... Nxg3 . White did not make anything serious wrong but Black will get a decent version of the  7.e3 -variation. }10...h6 11.Bh4 g5 12.Bg3 Nxg3  )
10. f6( { The typical reaction. }10...Nxe5? 11.dxe5± { doesn't work here for Black as  d5  is already hanging and so Black is simply not in time to create counterplay against the  e5 -pawn. } )
11. Bg3
11. Nxg3{ Grabbing the bishop pair. }
12. hxg3
12. Be6{ A nice move. Often this bishop is nicely placed on  f7  where it overprotects the kingside and the  d5 -pawn.  Sometimes the additional control over  c4  might be useful. Overall, I think these positions are equally balanced.  White should definitely try to use their better-developed pieces to find something concrete - either by creating (and exploiting) weaknesses on the queenside or by going for an early  e3 - e4  to open the position while Black is not fully coordinated.     However, I think Black's position is solid enough that we should survive both approaches and always have the long-term advantage of the two bishops. }
13. Qb3{ Another move that White might play to provoke some weaknesses on the queenside. Also,  e3 - e4  is an idea as it pins the pawn on  d5 . }
13. Na5{ A nice move. Black protects  b7 , attacks  b3  and unpins the  d5 -pawn this way. }( 13...Rb8 { is also playable but it allows }14.e4 { which is not necessary. } )
14. Qb4{ Not the only square, but Black's setup is similar anyways: ... Bf7 , ...  Rb8  (to protect  b7 ), ... Nc6  to go back to the center and later on, Black might go for the ... e5 -advance. }
14. Bf7
15. O-O
15. Rb8
16. Rfd1{ White makes useful moves to centralize their pieces and discourage Black from playing ... e5 . }
16. Nc6{ We have a typical situation. White looks slightly more active but they don't really have a clear plan while Black has different ideas to improve their positions.     Besides the ... e5  idea - that White should have under decent control at the moment- , Black can also just play some positional moves like ... e6  or ... a6  that improve the position, ... Re8 , ... Bf8  might be a manoeuvre to activate the dark-squared bishop, and at some point, Black might even be able to start a kingside expansion with ... g5  and ... h5 . }
