7. Bg7( 7...Nh5 { might also be possible but besides all the typical moves ( Bg5 ,  Be5 ,  Bg3 ), White can also play }8.Bd2 { .    }{ This might be playable for Black, but White would have won a tempo compared to other lines with  e2 - e3  and  cxd5  - see  this chapter  - as Black should play ... Nh5 - f6  soon when they wasted two tempi with their knight ( f6 - h5 - f6 ) while White's bishop moves improved its position ( c1 - f4 - d2 ). } )
8. e3
8. O-O{ A nice flexible waiting move. ... Nh5  is an important idea but the inclusion of  Rc1  and  Bg7  compared to lines  7.e3  might indeed be useful for White.  In some lines, Black likes to postpone taking the bishop on  g3  if White can make immediate use of the open h-file. But without the  g7 -square available, Black has to worry about their knight - for comparison's sake  see here . }
9. Bd3{ Usually, this is a good square for the bishop in the lines where Black plays ... Nh5  and White answers with  Be5 . However, with Black already castled, this is absolutely no problem. }
9. Nh5{ Black can just grab the bishops under good circumstances. }
10. Be5{ This is often a principled approach versus ... Nh5  but here it is not really working. }
10. Nxe5{ Black can just take. White's pawn on  e5  will be nothing but weak. }
11. dxe5
11. Bg4{ With the king still on  e8 , White might have annoying moves like  Qa4 + or  Bb5 +. Here, however, White has no tricks and just big problems with the  e5 -pawn. }
12. Be2{ This is the only move not to lose a pawn. }
12. e6{ Black just protects the  d5 -pawn. }
13. h3{ This is once again forced. It might look weird to force Black to take on  f3  as the resulting position is more than decent for Black. However, White doesn't really have a choice at this point. }( { A slow move like }13.O-O ? { can be answered with }13...Qb8! { ∓ }{ when White will lose the  e5 -pawn without any compensation. } )
13. Bxf3
14. Bxf3
14. Bxe5{ White can now win back the pawn by taking on  h5  but Black will be dominant with the strong dark-squared bishop. }
15. Bxh5
15. gxh5
16. Qxh5
16. Bg7{ Black is slightly better because they have the much better minor piece. White really has no convincing plan to use Black's slightly weakened king's position. }
