1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nc6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bg7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move ... Nc6 - a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 . }
7. Rc1( { This is a pretty smart move. If White comes to the conclusion that both }7.e3 Nh5 { and   }7.h3 Ne4 { are good for Black, this is a logical move.   }{ Not only is  c1  the most natural square for the rook anyways in the Exchange structure, but more concretely, White is also preparing to recapture on  c3  with the rook, if Black goes ... Ne4 . } )( { As we have seen, this doesn't work out in the move order }7.h3 Ne4 8.Rc1 Nxc3 { because }9.Rxc3 { allows }...e5! { with }-- ...Bb4 { ideas.    But if White just changes the move order, this is a very serious idea. } )
7. Bg7( 7...Nh5 { might also be possible but besides all the typical moves ( Bg5 ,  Be5 ,  Bg3 ), White can also play }8.Bd2 { .    }{ This might be playable for Black, but White would have won a tempo compared to other lines with  e2 - e3  and  cxd5  - see  this chapter  - as Black should play ... Nh5 - f6  soon when they wasted two tempi with their knight ( f6 - h5 - f6 ) while White's bishop moves improved its position ( c1 - f4 - d2 ). } )
8. e3
8. O-O{ A nice flexible waiting move. ... Nh5  is an important idea but the inclusion of  Rc1  and  Bg7  compared to lines  7.e3  might indeed be useful for White.  In some lines, Black likes to postpone taking the bishop on  g3  if White can make immediate use of the open h-file. But without the  g7 -square available, Black has to worry about their knight - for comparison's sake  see here . }
9. Bd3{ Usually, this is a good square for the bishop in the lines where Black plays ... Nh5  and White answers with  Be5 . However, with Black already castled, this is absolutely no problem. }
9. Nh5{ Black can just grab the bishops under good circumstances. }
10. Bg5{ This is the best move in the given situation. }
10. h6{ The inclusion of ... h6  and  Bh4  is something that Black should be happy with. Here, it is not so much about following it up with ... g5  - generally a nice idea but it doesn't work tactically - but instead it is a nice move to prepare ...  Bg7 - f6 . To exchange this bishop is now a good idea as it might become a very passive piece with the central pawn structure as fixed as it is now.  Without the ... h6 -move, White might answer  Bg7 - f6  with  Bh6 . It is not necessary to allow that. }
11. Bh4
11. Bg4{ If Black plans to exchange the dark-squared bishop with ... Bf6 , it makes sense to also give away the light-squared bishop. Otherwise, White might reach a position where they can play against a bad bishop on  c8 . }( { Kids, don't go }11...g5?? 12.Nxg5 hxg5 13.Qxh5 gxh4 14.Qh7# { . } )
12. O-O( { White has a lot of different moves that lead to similar positions like }12.h3 Bxf3 13.Qxf3 Bf6 14.Bxf6 Nxf6 { . } )
12. Bf6{ A nice positional idea. The butcher wasn't particularly active, so we exchange it against the bishop on  h4 . }
13. Bxf6( { After all those moves to keep the bishop alive, it doesn't look too threatening to see }13.Bg3 { .    }{ Black will at some point take on  g3  and enjoy the bishop pair. Black's kingside is much more stable than in other lines and White lost some time so this would be a great version. } )
13. Nxf6{ Not the most exciting position in the world but Black is fine and there is always the imbalance bishop vs. knight if Black takes on  f3 . }
