[White "10) Subtle Schlexchange - 7.Rc1"]
[Black "9.h3 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. g6
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Bf4{ This is White's most popular move by far. }
6. Nc6{ Remember this: In the exchange variation, ... Nc6  is often the more flexible move than ... Bg7 .     In some lines, it is just useful to have the move ... Nc6 - a5  as an answer to  Qb3 , and also in more general terms, we have better control over  d4  and  e5 . }
7. Rc1( { This is a pretty smart move. If White comes to the conclusion that both }7.e3 Nh5 { and   }7.h3 Ne4 { are good for Black, this is a logical move.   }{ Not only is  c1  the most natural square for the rook anyways in the Exchange structure, but more concretely, White is also preparing to recapture on  c3  with the rook, if Black goes ... Ne4 . } )( { As we have seen, this doesn't work out in the move order }7.h3 Ne4 8.Rc1 Nxc3 { because }9.Rxc3 { allows }...e5! { with }-- ...Bb4 { ideas.    But if White just changes the move order, this is a very serious idea. } )
7. Bg7( 7...Nh5 { might also be possible but besides all the typical moves ( Bg5 ,  Be5 ,  Bg3 ), White can also play }8.Bd2 { .    }{ This might be playable for Black, but White would have won a tempo compared to other lines with  e2 - e3  and  cxd5  - see  this chapter  - as Black should play ... Nh5 - f6  soon when they wasted two tempi with their knight ( f6 - h5 - f6 ) while White's bishop moves improved its position ( c1 - f4 - d2 ). } )
8. e3
8. O-O{ A nice flexible waiting move. ... Nh5  is an important idea but the inclusion of  Rc1  and  Bg7  compared to lines  7.e3  might indeed be useful for White.  In some lines, Black likes to postpone taking the bishop on  g3  if White can make immediate use of the open h-file. But without the  g7 -square available, Black has to worry about their knight - for comparison's sake  see here . }
9. h3{ White has made all the right moves. They have a nice setup against all ideas with ... Nh5  and ... Ne4 , so how can Black create imbalances? }
9. Qb6{ A strong move. The attack against  b2  forces White so some concessions. }
10. Bb5( { The only real try for White. }10.Nb5 Qa5+ { doesn't make a whole lot of sense. } )
10. Ne4{ We have to disturb White's piece coordination before White can just consolidate. Black is just threatening to remove the defender of the  b5 -bishop by playing ... Ne4xc3 .     White should now protect the bishop on  b5  and has different ways to do so. }( { Playing }11.Bxc6 bxc6 { is not very principled as White just gives away the bishop pair,  b2  is still hanging and Black has even ideas to keep the white king in the center with ... Ba6 . } )
11. Qb3{ This move does not only protect  b5  but is also attacking the  d5 -pawn. However, as we will see, Black doesn't have to worry too much about this attack. }
11. Nxc3( { We should take now as   }12.Nxd5 { was a threat. } )
12. bxc3{ Taking with the pawn is possible but gives Black the typical counterplay along the c-file and the weak  c4 -square. }
12. Na5{ Coming with tempo and useful as we are controlling  c4 . }
13. Qa4{ White has to protect the  b5 -bishop and this seems to be the best square even if it is also not ideal as a future ... b7 - b5  will be with tempo. }
13. a6{ Driving the bishop away and preparing ... b5 . }
14. Bd3
14. Qd8{ A very nice prophylactic move. The queen was standing in the way of ... b5  which is the move Black will play on the next move.  We'll reach a nice pawn structure on the queenside. }
