9. h3{ White has made all the right moves. They have a nice setup against all ideas with ... Nh5  and ... Ne4 , so how can Black create imbalances? }
9. Qb6{ A strong move. The attack against  b2  forces White so some concessions. }
10. Bb5( { The only real try for White. }10.Nb5 Qa5+ { doesn't make a whole lot of sense. } )
10. Ne4{ We have to disturb White's piece coordination before White can just consolidate. Black is just threatening to remove the defender of the  b5 -bishop by playing ... Ne4xc3 .     White should now protect the bishop on  b5  and has different ways to do so. }( { Playing }11.Bxc6 bxc6 { is not very principled as White just gives away the bishop pair,  b2  is still hanging and Black has even ideas to keep the white king in the center with ... Ba6 . } )
11. Qb3{ This move does not only protect  b5  but is also attacking the  d5 -pawn. However, as we will see, Black doesn't have to worry too much about this attack. }
11. Nxc3( { We should take now as   }12.Nxd5 { was a threat. } )
12. Rxc3{ The solid move for White. It just doesn't promise anything. }
12. Bd7{ Taking on  c3 , followed by playing ... Bd7  is our typical against more or less all of White's moves that protect  b5 . Now, we can always recapture on  c6  with the bishop. Also, we have discoveries against the bishop on  b5 . }
13. Qxd5{ I think this is the only move worth its own trainable even though Black has different ways to get a good position. }( 13.O-O ? Na5! { would just win material for Black. } )( { If White just spends a tempo on the threat against  b5 , we will just play a timely  ...a6  and get a decent version of the exchange structure. e.g. }13.a4 Rfc8 14.O-O a6 { If White takes on  c6 , we will at least have the bishop pair to play with. }15.Bc4 Qxb3 16.Bxb3 e6= { with not the most exciting position of this course but Black is definitely okay.    }{ Typical moves are ... f6  to take away the  e5 -square and regroup the bishop on  g7  with ... Bf8 . At some point, Black might play ... b5  to open the queenside. } )
13. Rad8{ Let's go with the positional compensation. We just protect the bishop on  d7 . }( { Now,   }14...Nb4 { is a threat with a double attack against }b5 { and }d5 { . White is behind in development and has to make some concessions to avoid the loss of material. } )( { The crazy }13...Nxd4!? { is playable as well but it is the kind of move where you should be an engine to really understand what's going on. }{ A lot of pieces on  d4 ,  d7  and  b5  are hanging, also discoveries against  c3  are possible. Not really what I want to include in this kind of rather strategical repertoire. Let's just say, that here we would be forced to play variations like }14.Bxd7 Nxf3+ 15.gxf3 Bxc3+ 16.bxc3 Qb1+ 17.Ke2 Qxh1 { with 'obvious equality':) } )
14. Bxc6{ White should include the moves  a4  and ... a6  before taking on  c6 . It doesn't look like a big difference but now Black can take on  b2  under much better circumstances. }
14. Qxb2
15. Bxd7{ If White saves their rook, we will just recapture on  c6  and remain with a slightly better position. }
15. Qxc3+
16. Ke2{ White has two pieces for the rook, so not that much of a material advantage. Nevertheless, if they bring out the rook on  h1  and hide the king on the kingside, White will just be better.  But Black has ways to attack the white king before it can consolidate. The first thing is to fight for ... Qc4 + when White's king will be forced to an even more unfortunate square. }( 16.Kf1?! { allows similar motives just that it is much harder to include the  h1 -rook into the game and a check on the back rank will always force White to go passive with  Nf3 - e1 . }16...e6! {     A)  }17.Qxb7 { This seems to be the best move but Black immediately wins back material because of  ...Rb8  and  ...Rb1+  ideas. }17...e5! 18.Bxe5 Bxe5 19.g4! { and White can answer }...Rb8 { and  ...Rb1+  with }Kg2 { . Nevertheless, Black is now equal in material and their pieces are very active.     B)  }17.Qb5? Qc1+! 18.Ne1 Bxd4! { is a nice way to activate the bishop form  g7 . ... Bc3  is a threat and }19.exd4 Qxf4 { is just horrible for White as their pieces are still on weird squares and more pawns are falling. } )
16. e6{ A strong move. We attack the queen which only has a limited amount of squares available as it needs to defend  d7 . We will be able to force White to take on  b7  when we will get in ... Qc4 + and ... Rb8 , when Black's pieces really come to life. }
17. Qb5( 17.Qxb7 Qc4+ { is similar. } )
17. a6
18. Qxb7
18. Qc4+{ Driving the king away from  e2 , where it is not too far away from hiding in the kingside. }
19. Kd2
19. e5{ Black would love to play ... Rb8  which was not possible until now as the bishop from  f4  was controlling that square. But now, Black will be ready to activate their rooks, no matter how White reacts. }( {  A)  }20.Rc1? { would be one of the moves that White could play here, had they included  14.a4 a6  before taking on  c6 . However, with the move on  a2  instead of  a4 , Black can save their own queen with checks. }20...Qxa2+ 21.Rc2 Qa5+! { and Black just wins the bishop on  f4 . } )( {  B)  }20.Bxe5 Bxe5 21.Nxe5 Qxa2+ { followed by  ...Rb8 . } )( {  C)  }20.Nxe5 Qxa2+ 21.Kd3 Rb8 { followed by ...  Rb3 +.  f2  is also hanging. This last variation seems to be holdable for White with best play but I am absolutely sure that Black has all the fun with the opponent's king on  e4 ! } )
