1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Bf4( { The title of this chapter might be a little bit unfair. Nevertheless, when I see the move }5.Bf4 { , I immediately think of a player who expects a 'passive' Schlechter player and doesn't even expect dynamic counterplay in the center in the next moves - or that the  c4 -pawn could simply hang!    Especially at amateur level, the bishop move is extremely popular at this point - and in older opening books, you actually saw the move recommended from time to time. Today's engines show you in a few seconds that the move is not particularly promising, and even though certainly not everything in the emerging variations has been exhausted, I would not advise any player to use this move.    In fact, the variation }5.h3!? dxc4 { leads to very similar but comparatively much-improved pawn sacrifice variations for White. So if you need an insider's tip from the white point of view, I can only recommend the  next chapter . } )( { My recommendation in this position is to just grab the pawn with   }5...dxc4 { . This fits nicely with other  Bf4 -lines in this course and is objectively, in my opinion, the best move.    A quick comment about the move }5...Bg7 { : Even though I don't think it's the best move, it shouldn't be underestimated. White players typically rely on the fact that Black is only getting a bad version of the  Bf4  Grünfeld (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bf4 { ), }{ because Black typically plays ... c7 - c5  in one move there.     That may or may not be true - for me, it was honestly reason enough from the start to prefer to analyze 5... dxc4  more closely, but the matter is not that clear. Black can combine the ... c5  idea with other resources (... Qa5 , ... Be6 !?, ... Ne4  ) and I would be very surprised if you couldn't build a repertoire around it as well. Still, capturing the  c4 -pawn is the easier move. } )
