4. g6
5. Bf4( { Here, Black does have the choice between }5...dxc4 { and }5...Bg7 { . I think taking the pawn is objectively the better move and more consistent with other variations of this course. } )
5. dxc4( { The principled move.    Whenever White develops their dark-squared bishop without caring about the  c4 -pawn, it is a good sign that we should take it.    }5...Bg7 { is playable but in my opinion not a very practical move. After }6.e3 { , White will have all their pieces on good squares and to avoid a slightly worse position, Black should play rather dynamically with ... O-O , ... Qa5  and ... c6 - c5  which would require the learning of unnecessary concrete lines. } )
6. a4
6. Nd5( { Immediately making use of White's misplaced bishop on  f4 .    }6...Bg7 7.e4! { promises White some advantage. } )
7. Bd2{ This weird move has been played a few times in practice. However, it is really harmless. }
7. Bg7{ This is a very easy way of playing. The position resembles some Grünfeld lines, but Black has an extra pawn on  c4  that they have every intention to hold for the moment! }
8. e3( { This puts even less pressure on Black than }8.e4 { . } )
8. Nxc3
9. Bxc3( 9.bxc3?! b5∓ { with the pawn on  e3 , White has an even harder time creating a kingside initiative as compensation. } )
9. Be6( { Black can be reasonably happy. }10.Ng5 { is not a problem.  Let's use the rest of the trainable to show why! } )
10. Ng5{ After other moves, Black will just play ... O-O  and eventually ... b5 . }
10. Bd5
11. e4{ The only logical follow-up but objectively this doesn't help. }
11. h6
12. exd5
12. hxg5
13. dxc6
13. Nxc6{ Black is still their extra pawn up and even ahead in development. }
