10. d5( 10.b3 { is a typical move in these kinds of situations to undermine Black's pawn chain. However, White also destabilizes their own position - the bishop on  c3  is no longer protected and the  d4 -pawn pinned. Even if White wins back one of Black's pawns, it is at a high cost as White's center will be under a lot of pressure.    The most precise move seems to be }10...Bg4! { to start asking questions as soon as possible. White can win back the pawn with }11.axb5 cxb5 12.bxc4 { , but after }12...Nc6! { , the  d4 -pawn is under huge pressure.     A)  }13.cxb5?! Nxd4! { is already much better for Black as }14.Bxd4 Bxf3! { works tactically. After }15.Qxf3 Qxd4 { , Black has a big initiative with White's king in the center.     B)    }13.e5 { is a sad necessity to reduce the pressure against  d4 . However, Black has different good moves. The engines want to go with the immediate }13...b4!? { , }{ followed by ... O-O  and ... a5 . }{ That is definitely a decent version of a Noteboom structure (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nc3 e6 4.Nf3 dxc4 5.a4 Bb4 6.e3 b5 7.Bd2 a5 8.axb5 Bxc3 9.Bxc3 cxb5 10.b3 Bb7 11.bxc4 b4 { ) }{ as White's pawns are not only arguably harder to mobilize, but they are also quite vulnerable once Black plays something like ... Qd7  and ... Rfd8 . }{    From a human perspective, I also like the idea of keeping the b-pawn flexible.   }13...Rc8!? { seems to be a good move to do so, while keeping the pressure against  c4  and  d4 . }14.cxb5 Nxe5! 15.dxe5 Qxd1+ 16.Rxd1 Rxc3 { gives Black a very nice endgame with the bishop pair and the weak pawn on  e5 . And after the better   }14.Be2 bxc4 { , Black is for the moment a nice pawn up and can use the  d5 -square as an outpost eventually with ... Qd5  or ... Be6 - d5 . }15.Bxc4? Nxe5! { is of course not possible. } )
10. Bxc3+
11. bxc3{ White is not really threatening anything here, but at least they can simplify in some drawish endings. }
11. Qa5{ This looks like a logical move for Black. White should be able to equalise with precise play - still not really an opening success for White! }
12. Qd4{ Winning a tempo for White by attacking  h8 . }
12. O-O
13. Be2
13. cxd5{ White was about to castle and play  axb5 , so we should force the issue. }
14. O-O( 14.exd5 Nd7 15.O-O bxa4 { transposes to the trainable. } )
14. bxa4{ Just taking everything. }
15. exd5
15. Nd7
16. Bxc4
16. Qc5{ Black has a decent endgame. They might just continue with ... Bb7 , putting a rook on the c-file and pressurize White's c-pawn. }
