8. Qa5{ This puts pressure on  c3  and stops White from  a4 - a5  if Black puts a knight on  b6 .     In this variation it makes sense to take on  c3  with the knight, so that the queen on  a5  has something to keep an eye on, and put the  b8 -knight on  b6 . }
9. Qd2{ The most natural move to protect  c3 . }( {  A)  }9.Rc1 { The rook is not particularly well placed on the c-file and White's  a4 -pawn might become a little bit loose as  Nb8 - d7 - b6  is part of Black's setup anyways. }9...Nd7 10.e3 N7b6∓ { and White has to deal with ideas like ... Nxc3  and taking on  a4 . } )( {  B)  }9.e4 { was played once to only answer }9...Nxc3 { with }10.Qd2 { . However, this doesn't look too impressive. }10...Be6 { looks simple enough but we can also play more forcing with the immediate }10...Bh6!? 11.Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12.bxc3 Be6=∞ { . White has some compensation but this is clearly one of the more innocuous versions of the pawn sacrifice. } )
9. Nxc3{ Black is not forced to take right away, but it is part of our setup anyways. }
10. bxc3
10. Nd7{ The knight can come to  b6  to protect the  c4 -pawn. }( 10...Bh6 11.e3 { is not effective here. } )
11. e4{ This grabs space but now we can develop with tempo. }
11. Bh6{ White cannot take it because the queen needs to protect  c3 . }
12. Qc2{ Clearly, the best square to protect  a4  and  e4 . }( 12.Qb2? Nb6 { is only giving Black more possibilities to take the  a4 -pawn. For example after }13.Nd2?! Be6 { , we are already threatening to take on  a4 . }14.Be2? Nxa4! 15.Qxb7 { doesn't work because of }15...Bxd2+ 16.Kxd2 Qxc3+ 17.Kd1 Nb2+-+ { . } )
12. Nb6{ Stabilising the  c4 -pawn. }
13. Nd2( { Black has different possibilities. We can go for the immediate }13...f5 { but we can also develop greedily. } )
13. Be6{ Hanging on to the pawn and waiting for a better moment to create counterplay. }( { Nevertheless, }13...f5 { is also possible. We have the ideas }-- ...f4 { - the main threat - as well as }...Bxd2 { and  ...fxe4  . } )
14. Be2( 14.Bc7 { stops the next move of the text but is not very effective here. }14...Bxd2+ 15.Qxd2 Rc8 { If White takes on  b6 , we'll go ... axb6  and potentially ... b5  and if the bishop retreats, we can just take on  a4 . } )
14. O-O-O{ Our king is pretty safe on the queenside for now and after ... Rhf8 , we might still play ... f5 . }
