15. Qc1( { White shouldn't go }15.Qb2? Nxa4! { -+ } )( { Exchanging on  b6  first gives White more liberties with their queen but Black can play  ...b5  next. For example }15.Bxb6 axb6 16.Qb2 b5 { when Black is extremely solid. } )
15. Kd7{ A very unusual move but after some analysis, I came to the conclusion that it is actually a smart idea to drive the  c7 -bishop away with the king. It is not so easy to open the center for White and by the time they achieve it, our king should already be back in safety. }( 15...Rc8?! 16.Bxb6 axb6?! { doesn't work because after }17.Bxc4± { , we have no }...b5 { to create counterplay. } )
16. Bxb6{ Taking on  b6  is the more critical line. }
16. axb6{ White can now take on  c4 , but we are ready to get active on the queenside. }
17. Bxc4( { After other moves, such as }17.O-O { , we also play }17...b5 { . } )
17. b5{ Using the pin of the a-pawn. }
18. Bb3{ Protecting the  a4 -pawn. }
18. b4{ Threatening ... bxc3 . }
19. cxb4{ This is the option to keep the game more open. But it is not clear which side can take advantage of this. }
19. Qxb4+( { This doesn't win a piece for Black because White can protect the bishop with }20.Nd2 { . } )
