1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Bf4( { Here, Black does have the choice between }5...dxc4 { and }5...Bg7 { . I think taking the pawn is objectively the better move and more consistent with other variations of this course. } )
5. dxc4( { The principled move.    Whenever White develops their dark-squared bishop without caring about the  c4 -pawn, it is a good sign that we should take it.    }5...Bg7 { is playable but in my opinion not a very practical move. After }6.e3 { , White will have all their pieces on good squares and to avoid a slightly worse position, Black should play rather dynamically with ... O-O , ... Qa5  and ... c6 - c5  which would require the learning of unnecessary concrete lines. } )
6. e3{ This is White's most successful move but I don't think that Black should have too many worries. }
6. Be6{ Black should definitely defend the  c4 -pawn - otherwise 5... dxc4  wouldn't have made a lot of sense - and this is the most stubborn way to do so. }( 6...b5?! { After this, White can win back the pawn and has chances for an advantage with their better central control: }7.a4 b4 8.Nb1 Ba6 9.Qc2⩲ { with a slight advantage. } )
7. Ng5{ This is the most forcing variation. }
7. Bd5{ The bishop avoids being captured by the knight but isn't it in danger? }
8. e4{ White doesn't win a piece! Black can also attack one of White's minors. }
8. h6
9. exd5
9. hxg5
10. dxc6( { A smart move. Black cannot play }10...gxf4 { because }11.cxb7 { wins the rook on  a8 . } )
10. Nxc6{ White has to decide whether they want to exchange the  d4 -pawn against the  g5 -pawn (by taking on  g5 ) or whether they just defend  d4  with  11.Be3  . }
11. Bxg5{ Also here, Black has more than one playable move. }
11. Qa5{ A entertaining way to play the position. White is still behind in development and Black puts a lot of pressure on the white position. }( { The straight-forward }11...Nxd4 12.Bxc4 Bg7 { looks definitely reasonable.     A)  }13.Be3 { is most likely the best, but Black should be fine after both }13...Nf5 { or }13...e5 { .     B)    }13.O-O?? Qc7! { and White loses because of the double-attack against  c4  and  h2 . } )
12. d5( { White is threatening   }13.Bxf6 { and }-- 14.dxc6 { . But Black has an elegant solution to the problem. } )
12. Bg7
13. dxc6( 13.Bxf6?! Bxf6 { and the pressure against the  c3  makes it impossible for White to take on  c6 . }14.dxc6? Bxc3+ 15.bxc3 Qxc3+ 16.Ke2 Rd8-+ { White's king will never survive this. } )
13. Qxg5
14. cxb7{ White grabs a pawn for now, but this is really all they can do. }
14. Rb8
15. Qa4+
15. Nd7( { Black has a massive initiative.   }16...Bxc3 { , followed by  ... Qe5+  is an idea, but Black can also just continue to bring their pieces into the game.   ...Rh8-h4  looks like a nice manoeuvre to include the rook. } )
