[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. h3( { This move looks pretty random (and has barely ever been played). In my first draft for this course, I didn't even have the move }5.h3 { as a sideline on my agenda. It wasn't until most of the other chapters were already done and I went looking for holes in my repertoire that I encountered this move, which was surprisingly highly rated by the engine. Does }5.h3 { have a deeper point?    }{ It has! As we have seen in the chapters about the Exchange variation -  see here  -, Black does often prefer the move ... Nc6  over the move ... Bg7  in those lines.  So by playing another move that is part of their setup, White just wants to delay  cxd5  for one move. }{ If Black plays   }5...Bg7 { , White will just play }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bf4 { and has move-ordered us in a variation we usually don't want to play. }7...Ne4 8.Rc1! { just stops Black's plan to create imbalances. }{    When I realized that, I briefly panicked as I understood that this innocuous-looking move is a serious line.    How can we avoid being move-ordered?    I think the best solution is actually to take on  c4 . I have to admit, taking on  c4  is now not as strong as after }{   }5.Bf4 { , as Black doesn't have the   }6...Nd5 {  move  }{ with tempo which is an important resource in the  Bf4-lines .     Nevertheless, I consider it the lesser of both evils. Despite its rare character, we have to take  5.h3  seriously if we ever encounter it over the board.    Rules for this chapter:    - Take the pawn    - There are many similarities between this chapter and  5.Bf4  } )
