[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) The tricky 5.h3!?"]
[Black "7.e4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. h3
5. dxc4( { I think Black should take the pawn.    }5...Bg7 { looks like an automatic move but after }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bf4 { we are move ordered into a position that I usually don't recommend. As explained in the chapter about the  Schlexchange Slav , it is important to play ... Nc6  before ... Bg7 . } )
6. a4( { This is White's idea. They try to play an improved version of the line   }5.Bf4 dxc4 6.a4 { because the standard reply }6...Nd5 { is not coming with tempo -  see here . } )
6. Nd5{ This move seems to be more or less necessary. Black should make it as hard as possible for White to regain the pawn on  c4 . This move prepares ideas with ... b6 , sometimes ... Nb6 , and it opens up the bishop on  g7 . }
7. e4
7. Nxc3
8. bxc3
8. b5{ A typical situation. White has an impressive center, we have the extra pawn.  As usual, it is White who has to prove something in these situations. }
9. h4{ If White continues with slow moves like  Be2  and  Be3 , Black will just develop their pieces with ...  Bg7 , ... O-O , ... Nd7  and ... Bb7  with no problems. }
9. h5{ Here, this is a reliable choice to stop White's h-pawn. }
10. Be2
10. Bg7
11. Ng5( { There is nothing concrete to show if White makes a simple developing move like }11.Be3 { . Black will just continue developing with no problems.    }{ This knight move seems to be the only move that can pose some problems for Black. All of a sudden, White has ideas like  f2 - f4  or even  g2 - g4  to gain momentum on the kingside and open up files. If Black castles, there might be even ideas connected with  Bxh5 !. Black has to be precise. } )
11. e5{ A principled and strong counter. White just decentralises their knight to start an attack on the flank, so Black strikes back in the center! }
12. Be3{ After this move, Black can develop counterplay in the center. }
12. exd4
13. Bxd4
13. Bxd4
14. cxd4{ with a messy position with different possibilities. I like a creative idea to bring Black's rook into the game. }
14. a6{ Stabilizes the structure and plans ... Ra7  when the rook can be used on the seventh rank. Both for attacking purposes like ... Rd7 , but also in the defence this rook can be quite useful. }
