17. Kxd1
17. Bxe4{ Taking the  e4 -pawn with tempo. Let me show you some more moves to understand the position better: }( 18.Ra1 { The best square for the rook. Black has different ideas to bring their pieces into the game. The most forcing move seems to be the best. }18...a6! { Trying to liquidate the queenside when White will remain with weaker pawn structure. }19.b6! { Keeping the b-pawn alive. }19...Nd7 { Attacking the weak  b6 -pawn. White only has one real move. }20.Nd2! { Winning a tempo against the bishop on  e4  and preparing to take on  c4 . }20...Bxg2!? { I think Black should just grab the  g2 -pawn. White might win the pawn on  g6 , but every move that White does on the kingside gives us time to coordinate our pieces and deal with the annoying b-pawn. }( { ( }20...Bd5 21.Nxc4 Bf8! { is similar and also playable. I just think taking on  g2  is the better version.) } )21.Rg1 Bd5 22.Nxc4 Bf8! { An important move. The bishop was not well placed on  g7  and now we take control over the important  d6 -square and the whole  a3 - f8  diagonal.  Black has ideas like ... Bc5 , ... Rc8 , ... Kf7  to bring their pieces to good squares. }{    }22...Bxc4 23.Bxc4 Nxb6 { is also possible. White will win back one of their pawns after }24.Bd3 { and have some compensation for the other one because their pieces are so active. Nevertheless, Black should be fine with best defence. }24...Bh6 { seems like a good way to start to exchange one of White's bishops. } )
