9. h5{ Here, this is a reliable choice to stop White's h-pawn. }
10. Be2
10. Bg7
11. Ng5( { There is nothing concrete to show if White makes a simple developing move like }11.Be3 { . Black will just continue developing with no problems.    }{ This knight move seems to be the only move that can pose some problems for Black. All of a sudden, White has ideas like  f2 - f4  or even  g2 - g4  to gain momentum on the kingside and open up files. If Black castles, there might be even ideas connected with  Bxh5 !. Black has to be precise. } )
11. e5{ A principled and strong counter. White just decentralises their knight to start an attack on the flank, so Black strikes back in the center! }
12. d5{ White should keep the center closed in order to minimize counterplay. }
12. f6{ Black has to go for this move to drive away the knight. }( { A move like }12...cxd5?! { looks very natural to create counterplay in the center. Unfortunately, the engine proves that White has convincing ways to punish Black's lack of development. A sample line could be }13.exd5 Bb7 14.axb5 Qxd5 15.Qxd5! { White can even trade queens. }15...Bxd5 16.Be3+- { when the  a7 -pawn will fall and White's passer should be decisive. } )
13. Nf3
13. Bb7( { If Black gets one more move, for example after the otherwise logical }14.Ba3 { , Black will play }14...a6 { and remain with an extra pawn and a reasonably solid position. } )( { White should instead try to win this pawn back. They can do this by playing }14.Rb1 { or the immediate }14.dxc6 { . } )
14. dxc6
14. Qxd1+{ Ruining White's right to castle instead of allowing White to so. }
15. Kxd1{ White should take with the king to keep pressure on the  c4 -pawn. }
15. Bxc6
16. axb5
16. Bxb5{ White can win back the  c4 -pawn but Black will finish their development in the meantime. }
17. Nd2
17. Nd7{ White can take on  c4 , but Black will bring their rooks into the game in the meantime. Black should be pretty solid. Note that the butcher is not well placed currently with the pawns on  f6  and  e5  and should be regrouped via  h6  or  f8 . }
