5. dxc4( { I think Black should take the pawn.    }5...Bg7 { looks like an automatic move but after }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bf4 { we are move ordered into a position that I usually don't recommend. As explained in the chapter about the  Schlexchange Slav , it is important to play ... Nc6  before ... Bg7 . } )
6. a4( { This is White's idea. They try to play an improved version of the line   }5.Bf4 dxc4 6.a4 { because the standard reply }6...Nd5 { is not coming with tempo -  see here . } )
6. Nd5{ This move seems to be more or less necessary. Black should make it as hard as possible for White to regain the pawn on  c4 . This move prepares ideas with ... b6 , sometimes ... Nb6 , and it opens up the bishop on  g7 . }
7. a5{ A serious move. White just continues to fight against ... b5 . If Black is not able to hang on to the pawn on  c4 , White will just be comfortably better with their strong center pawns. }
7. Nb4{ Black has to rely on some tactics to keep the pawn on  c4 . With ... b5  off the table, for now, it becomes more important that Black can protect the  c4 -pawn with ... Be6 . }( { White's typical response to this is  Nf3-g5  but with the knight on  b4 , this is not working because of the tactical shot }8.Ng5 Qxd4 Qxd4 Nc2+ { . } )( { A move like }7...Bg7?! { allows White to win back the pawn comfortably after something like }8.e4 Nxc3 9.bxc3 Be6 10.Qa4± { . } )
8. e4
8. Be6{ A very interesting position. Black's pieces are slightly cramped because of White's strong center pawns.  However, I believe that Black will have a very decent position if White shows nothing concrete and let Black just develop with ... Bg7 , ... O-O , ... N8a6 , followed by improving the major pieces and/or possibly playing ... b5 . (If taking en passant with  axb6  can just be answered with ... axb6 , there is not much to worry about.) So White should go for something concrete.     The best idea seems to be a well-timed  Ng5  to win the bishop pair (Black will usually answer with ... Qd7 ) and to prepare  d4 - d5  to separate the  c4 -pawn from the protector on  e6 .     White's problem is that it takes time to go for this plan under good circumstances. }
9. Be2{ White has to develop first before being able to play  Ng5 . }( 9.Ng5 Qxd4! { is the typical response to a mistimed  Ng5 . } )
9. Bg7
10. Be3
10. O-O
11. O-O( { The time is still not ready for }11.Ng5 Bxd4! 12.Bxd4 Qxd4 { and White lost the important  d4 -pawn. } )
11. N8a6{ Now, Black is ready to play ... b5  to give the  c4 -pawn more support. }
12. Ng5{ With the king evacuated, White is finally able to play this move. But Black is already nicely developed. }( 12.Qd2 b5! 13.axb6 axb6 14.Ng5 Qd7 { transposes to this variation with  12.Ng5  . } )
12. Qd7{ The typical response to  Ng5 . }
13. Nxe6{ Usually, this doesn't run away and only really makes sense if White wants to follow up with something concrete. }
13. Qxe6
14. e5{ This is a completely different approach. White is trying to restrict Black's pieces and prepares  Nc3 - e4 . There is also the annoying idea to go  Be2 - g4 . }
14. f6{ Immediately breaking the bind! }( { Just don't be passive with a move like }14...Nc7? { because }15.Bg4 { is very annoying. Black is forced to go for }15...f5 16.exf6 Qxf6 17.Ne4!± { and White's active piece play promises him very easy play. } )
15. exf6
15. exf6( { Even }15...Bxf6 { seems playable but this move keeps the pawn structure intact and Black might even flirt with the idea to go ... f5  and ... f4 . } )
