1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. h3
5. dxc4( { I think Black should take the pawn.    }5...Bg7 { looks like an automatic move but after }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bf4 { we are move ordered into a position that I usually don't recommend. As explained in the chapter about the  Schlexchange Slav , it is important to play ... Nc6  before ... Bg7 . } )
6. a4( { This is White's idea. They try to play an improved version of the line   }5.Bf4 dxc4 6.a4 { because the standard reply }6...Nd5 { is not coming with tempo -  see here . } )
6. Nd5{ This move seems to be more or less necessary. Black should make it as hard as possible for White to regain the pawn on  c4 . This move prepares ideas with ... b6 , sometimes ... Nb6 , and it opens up the bishop on  g7 . }
7. h4{ Now that the  f6 -knight has left the kingside, it makes sense to use the h-pawn aggressively. But it is a double-edged story because White weakens their own kingside and all variations where White castles short are becoming quite a bit riskier.  Also ...  Bg4  is a move that can be annoying at some point. Nevertheless, this might be White's most critical move order. }
7. c5{ This is a very principled reaction to White's flank attack - we strike in the center. The lines can be really wild. }
8. e3{ This innocuous-looking move might be White's best choice. They stabilize their center and play  h4 - h5  next. }
8. cxd4{ Black opens up the center. }
9. Qxd4{ By far the best move. White is attacking  h8  and  d5 . }( {  A)  }9.exd4 Be6 { makes it tricky to regain the pawn. }10.Ng5 Nxc3 { is definitely okay for Black. If White recaptures on  c3 , we play ... Bd5 . } )( {  B)  }9.Nxd4 Nxc3 10.bxc3 e5⩱ { with a queen exchange is definitely also taking away all attacking options for White. } )
9. Nb4{ This is Black's tactical justification. ...  Nc2  is a threat that can hardly be stopped under good circumstances.  White has to find a series of very computerlike moves if they don't want to be worse. }
10. Qxd8+( { Necessary. }10.Qxh8 Nc2+ 11.Ke2 Qd3# { would be mate! } )
10. Kxd8
11. Bxc4{ Yes, this sacrifices a whole rook but everything else is easily fine for Black. }( {  A)  For example }11.Rb1 Nd3+ 12.Bxd3 cxd3 {  d3  is weak but we are a pawn up and have the bishop pair. } )( {  B)  Attacking  f7  is much better for Black. }11.Ng5 Nc2+! 12.Kd2 { The best square. If White goes to  d1 , it can surprisingly be a problem that the king doesn't protect  c3  }( { ( }12.Kd1 Nxa1 13.Nxf7+ Ke8 14.Bxc4 Bg7! { works here. }15.Nxh8 Bxh8 { Here, White can neither play }b3 { nor }b4 { to trap the knight which gives Black more time to save it.) } )12...Nxa1 13.Nxf7+ Ke8 14.Bxc4 ( { ( }14.Nxh8 Be6! { ) } )14...Rg8 ( { ( }14...Bg7 15.Nxh8 Bxh8 16.b4!⩱ { is here possible.) } )15.Nd6+ { This wins back the exchange but Black remains better. }15...exd6 16.Bxg8 Nd7∓ { A complicated position but Black is still a knight up and Black can use the time that White needs to trap it for their own counterplay: ... Nf6 , ... Bf5 , ...  Rc8 . } )
11. Nc2+{ Black has to accept the challenge. }
12. Ke2{ The best square. White doesn't block any piece on  e2 . }
12. Nxa1{ Black is a whole rook up for now. }
13. Ng5{ White's only chance to regain enough material. }( 13.Ne5? { would be a mistake. Black can reply with the strong }13...Be6! 14.Bxe6 ( { ( }14.Nxf7+ Bxf7 15.Bxf7 { is better but White will never have enough compensation even when they finally trap the knight in the corner.) } )14...fxe6 15.Nf7+ Ke8 16.Nxh8 Nb3-+ { Black's knight escapes while White's knight will be trapped with ... Bg7  . } )
13. Bg7{ This is the easiest move to stop the madness. Now, things become relatively straightforward. }( 13...Bg4+ 14.f3 Be6 { continues the madness.     A)  }15.Bxe6? fxe6 16.Nf7+ Ke8 17.Nxh8 Nb3-+ { would lose for White as their knight is trapped.     B)  }15.Nxe6+ { is possible. Black will stay an exchange up but White has some compensation after picking up  a1 . To be fair, it is hard to understand everything. }15...fxe6 16.Bd2 Nc2 17.Rc1=∞ { If Black simply develops, we have a position with compensation but I find it quite shocking that }17...Nb4? 18.Bxe6! { is apparently simply losing for Black. Please ask your engine why...     C)  }15.Rd1+ { is the other possible move for White. }15...Ke8 16.Nd5 { The threat of  17.Nc7#  forces the following sequence. }16...Bxd5 17.Bxd5 { Now, there is a mate threat on  f7  so }17...e6! 18.Bxb7 { White will win the rook on  a8  and now it is Black to play for compensation. For example }18...Nb3 19.Bxa8 Bb4!=∞ { when White has some problems getting their pieces out. } )
14. Nxf7+
14. Ke8
15. Nxh8
15. Bxh8{ White will win back the knight on  a1  and material will be even. }
16. Bd2
16. Nc2{ We don't give the knight voluntarily. }
17. Nd5{ The best move to threaten  Nc7 + and control the  b4 -square. }
17. Be5{ Black protects  c7 . }
18. Kd3{ White has different ways to trap the knight but this seems to be the most precise way. By playing 18.Kd3, White controls the  d4 -square. This allows White to answer ... e6  with  Nf4 ! }( { For example }18.Bb3 e6 { is easy for Black. }19.f4! { The only resource to get an equal position. }( { ( }19.Nf4? Bxf4! 20.exf4? Nd4+-+ { just blunders everything) } )19...exd5 20.fxe5 Bg4+ { Misplacing White's king slightly before we play  ..Bf5 . }21.Kf2 Bf5= { Black can win the knight on  c2 , but ... Nc6 , ... Kd7 , ... Ke6  will also pick up  e5 . } )
18. Nxe3{ Winning at least one pawn against the knight. }( 18...e6?! 19.Nf4!± { doesn't achieve anything here and only blocks the  c8 -bishop. } )
19. Kxe3
19. Nc6{ Black will get their pieces out with ... Bf5  and ... Rd8  with an acceptable endgame. }
