5. dxc4( { I think Black should take the pawn.    }5...Bg7 { looks like an automatic move but after }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bf4 { we are move ordered into a position that I usually don't recommend. As explained in the chapter about the  Schlexchange Slav , it is important to play ... Nc6  before ... Bg7 . } )
6. a4( { This is White's idea. They try to play an improved version of the line   }5.Bf4 dxc4 6.a4 { because the standard reply }6...Nd5 { is not coming with tempo -  see here . } )
6. Nd5{ This move seems to be more or less necessary. Black should make it as hard as possible for White to regain the pawn on  c4 . This move prepares ideas with ... b6 , sometimes ... Nb6 , and it opens up the bishop on  g7 . }
7. h4{ Now that the  f6 -knight has left the kingside, it makes sense to use the h-pawn aggressively. But it is a double-edged story because White weakens their own kingside and all variations where White castles short are becoming quite a bit riskier.  Also ...  Bg4  is a move that can be annoying at some point. Nevertheless, this might be White's most critical move order. }
7. h5{ ... h7 - h5  is not a reaction that you should play on autopilot as it gives away the  g5 -square and just weakens the kingside in general. However, often this is the right reaction to stop all of White's immediate ways to start an initiative while we are still underdeveloped. }
8. a5( { If we compare this position to the position after   }7.a5 { -  see here -, White might think that the inclusion of the h-pawn moves is beneficial for White because Black's kingside is softer making it easier for White to develop a kingside initiative.    However, I think Black can get a decent version of the regular Exchange Grünfeld after the simple   }8...Bg7 { . } )
8. Bg7
9. e4
9. Nxc3
10. bxc3
10. c5{ This is always the key move in these Exchange Grünfeld structures. Why is this a pleasant version?     Usually, the strategic fight in these variations evolves around the pawns on the  a1 - h8  diagonal- mainly about the  d4 -pawn. If Black can create pressure, we usually have easy counterplay.     Here, White lost quite some time with their pawns on the rim, especially the h-pawn moves can also be a slight weakness and with the weak  g4 -square, Black can often play ... Bg4  to increase the pressure on the d-pawn even more. }
11. Bxc4
11. cxd4{ Black is not forced to take and would like to increase the pressure first. }( {  A)  Just the very concrete line }11...O-O 12.Ne5! { seems to be slightly annoying because taking on  e5  doesn't solve all of Black's problems. }12...Bxe5 13.dxe5⩲ { Without the c-pawns, Black could create counterplay on the c-file with }...Qc7 { but here it might be a little bit tricky to do so. } )( {  B)  }11...Nc6 { is part of the general plan of creating pressure against  d4 , but }12.d5! { is a very typical reply. White is ready to leave the  c3 -pawn hanging but Black cannot really take it. }12...Bxc3+ 13.Bd2 { leads to a position where Black has won a pawn but will lose even more tempi because of the hanging  c6 -knight. }13...Bxa1 14.Qxa1 { does not work as  h8  and  c6  are both hanging. } )
12. cxd4
12. O-O{ Black can continue with ... Bg4  and ... Nc6  with nice pressure against White's pawns. }
