15. Qc2( { The strongest move. White unpins and is threatening   }16.Qxg6 { . } )( 15.Qd3 { allows }15...Bxf3 16.gxf3 e6 { Here, the same moves as after  15.Qc2  doesn't really give White anything. }17.Bb4 Re8 18.Bb5 Nd7 { White has no clear follow-up and Black is ready to strike back with ... a5 , ... Bf8  or ... e5 . We are currently slightly tied down but once we untangle, we have some trumps with the outside a-pawn, the weak  h4 -pawn and the not completely safe white king. } )
15. Qc8{ Trying to use White's weird line-up on the c-file and also allowing to reduce the pressure with ... Be6 . }( 15...Bxf3?! 16.gxf3 e6?! { doesn't work here. }( { ( }16...Qd6 { is better but White still gets pressure after }17.Rg1± { ) } )17.Bb4 Re8 18.Bb5 Nd7 19.Ba5 Qe7 20.Qc7+- { is too much pressure to handle. } )
16. Bb4( { The most active move to deal with the threat against the bishop.    }16.Nd2 Be6 { is similar. }17.Ra4!? { is a smart way to fight for the c-file but even the 'cooperating' }17...Bxc4 18.Rxc4 Qb7 19.O-O Nd7 { looks okay for Black. } )
16. Be6
