4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Bg5( 5.Bg5 { is one of the most popular lines on the amateur level. It is actually the most popular move in the given position on Lichess and it is not even close! (Statistically, this move happens in every third game.)    In titled player databases, things look quite different. Usually, the move is ranked far behind }5.e3 { , }5.cxd5 { and }5.Bf4 { . The main reason for this is that }5.Bg5 { allows two typical ways to initiate counterplay. My recommendation is }5...Ne4 { . We have already seen this move many times in this course and especially against the move  Bc1 - g5  this move can be called a 'standard reaction'.    The other alternative that comes to mind is the move }5...dxc4 { . This is the move I recommend against   }5.Bf4 { -  see here  and }5.h3 { -  see here . } )( { In those chapters, however, I believe that taking  c4  is the only principled response. Here we have a different one with   }5...Ne4 { , and since I prefer to recommend positional moves over pawn-grabbing in case of doubt, it wasn't difficult for me to choose the knight move.    If you want an objective reason against }5...dxc4 { , I can only tell you that }6.a4 { is the critical move. Our response against  5.Bf4  and  5.h3  - }6...Nd5 { - }{ can only be played here under worse circumstances, since it neither comes with tempo and  Bc1 - g5  is certainly more useful than  h2 - h3 .     That's no drama, Black can of course simply develop with }6...Bg7 { , but White can hope for a small advantage if they regain the pawn. } )( { After }5...Ne4 { , the game can actually transpose into variations from the Grünfeld Indian.    For example, after }6.Bf4 { - the best move in my opinion - we reach the same position as after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bg5 Ne4 6.Bf4 { . Here, the move }6...c6 { is only a sideline, but it has been played by strong Grandmasters, including Maxime Vachier-Lagrave.    Rules for this line:    - After   }8.Bh4 { , we can actually just grab the pawn with }8...Nxc3 9.bxc3 dxc4 {    - After   }8.Bf4 { , }{ we often create counterplay against  c3  with ... Qa5  and just wait for good moments to play our typical ... e5  and ... c5  breaks. Potentially, with an exchange on  c4  included. } )
