10. Be2{ This is White's main move but these days Black players know how they can get a good position. }
10. Nd7{ Against the alternatives, we had to play ... a6  to prevent concrete threats. Here, we have better moves. }( { The idea behind  10...Nd7  is to play   }11...Nb6 { and force White's a-pawn to make a decision. } )
11. Nd2( { White's best move. White is trying to play with concrete tactics.    }11.O-O Nb6 { allows Black's plan under much better circumstances. After }12.a5 Nd5∓ { , Black attacks  c3  and can answer  e3 - e4  conceptually with ... Nf4 . In the next moves, we can just play ... Bf5  to make sure that White won't push their e-pawn anytime soon. } )
11. Nb6{ Still, we can play this move. }
12. Bf3( { A very concrete idea to attack  c6  and also threaten   }13.axb5 { . } )( 12.axb5 cxb5 { is what Black is hoping for. If we can play  ...Bb7 , we have the long diagonal and }13.Bf3 Nd5∓ { is just a very safe extra pawn. } )
12. Nxa4{ This is a very instructive exchange sacrifice. Black will get the two bishops and a strong queenside majority. }( { The simple }12...Nd5 { has been played in practice several times, with good results for Black as well. } )
13. Bxc6+{ The critical move is of course to take the exchange. }
13. Bd7
14. Bxa8
14. Qxa8{ With a double attack against  g2  and  c3 . If Black takes one of these pawns, there is no doubt that Black has a winning advantage as the material is mathematically even but Black has the strongly connected pawns on the queenside. One move keeps White in the game. }
15. Qf3{ After the exchange of queens, the  a7 -pawn will be unprotected which makes it less desirable to take on  a7 . }
15. Qxf3{ Not the only move but a simple choice. Even though Black does only have one pawn for the exchange, the endgame is very comfortable with the strong queenside pawns and the pressure against  c3 . }
16. Nxf3
16. f6{ A precise move to control the  e5 -square, even preparing ... e5  but also just simply allowing us to castle without losing the  e7 -pawn. }( 16...Bc6 { with the idea to control the  e4 -square and play ... Kd7  is also possible. Still, Black should play ... f6  in the future anyway to increase the pressure with ... e5  eventually. }( { (However, don't play }16...Nxc3?! 17.Rxa7 { that activates White's rook.) } ){ A logical continuation is }17.Kd2 O-O 18.Bg3 e5! { stopping the manoeuvre  Bg3 - c7  that would make it hard to push the a-pawn.  In the next moves, we will improve our position - ... Rd8 , ... Bf5 , ... Bh6 , ... Kf7 , ... a5  when eventually we can take on  d4  to open the position. At the very least, Black has full compensation. } )
