13. Nb6{ Black is controlling all of White's pawn breaks for now. Next, we can play ... Bc4  and fight for the  c4 -square as an outpost for the knight.  Let me show you some possible continuations in the clickables. }( {  A)  }14.Rfc1 Bc4 { is Black's main idea to land the knight on  c4 . } )( {  B)  }14.Ne5 { is trying to control the  c4 -square but Black has a nice solution: }14...Bxe5!? { looks slightly risky, but White will lose the bishop pair immediately. }15.Bxe5 ( { ( }15.dxe5?! Qd5 16.Rfd1 Qc5 { and Black has great control.) } )15...Bc4! { exchanging light-squared bishops when we have nice control over the light squares. } )( {  C)  }14.Nd2 { is another way of controlling  c4  but really passive. }14...Rc8! { and Black is ready to push  ...c5  next. }15.Nb3 { to stop this allows either }15...Bc4 { or }15...Na4!? { , which once again prepares }-- ...c5 { . Getting active with   }15.c4? { would only backfire: }15...bxc4 16.Nxc4 c5!∓ { when White is in pins all over the place. } )( {  D)  }14.h4 Bg4! { is still a very good way of stopping the h-pawn. } )
