5. Qb3( { You may be surprised to see this queen move not in the sidelines chapter, where we have seen so many other queen excursions to  b3 . The reason is that this is the most critical version of the queen move and Black should not react too naive.    If Black is not careful and simply plays }5...Bg7 { , they may be unpleasantly surprised by }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5! { . Since White has attacked the  d5 -pawn twice, Black cannot react with }7...Ne4 { and has to make a passive move to parry the threat against the  d5 -pawn. } )( { To avoid this scenario, I recommend the very interesting idea }5...dxc4 6.Qxc4 b5! { . This idea is known from variations in the Grünfeld Indian (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Qb3 dxc4 6.Qxc4 { and now for example }6...a6 { , followed by }-- ...b5 { ).    }{ In both variations, Black tries to gain space on the queenside with tempo and at some point to get rid of the backward pawn on the c-file with a well-timed ... c5 .    The disadvantage compared to the GID variation: We have used up a tempo for ... c6     The advantage of our variation: White does not get a giant centre built up with  e2 - e4 , which typically happens in the Grünfeld-Indian variation.    All in all, very dynamic positions arise, in which the player who is better acquainted with the subtleties probably has the better chances. }{    The position can also arise via the move sequence   }4.Qb3 g6 3.Nc3 { .    }{ Rules for the Variation:    - ... c5  is the main pawn break    - If White does not react to ... b5 - b4  with  Nc3 - a4 , we usually have no great problems achieving this lever.    - If, on the other hand, White responds with  Nc3 - a4 , White has good chances of securing the  c5 -square. In this case it is particularly important to play energetically, to push our development forward even with pawn sacrifices and often to create counterplay in the centre with ... e7 - e5 . } )
