1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Qb3{ In the sidelines, we saw many lines with an early  Qb3 . This variation is the most critical version.     White protects the  c4 -pawn which is a useful thing to do, but there is also a more concrete reason to this move. With the additional piece attacking  d5 , White can opt for setups with  Bg5  and Black doesn't have the typical - dynamic! - response ... Ne4 . }
5. dxc4{ Reacting in some Grünfeld Style.     Black will continue with ... b5  to start typical counterplay on the queenside. }( 5...Bg7 { allows }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5 { and Black cannot play dynamic with }7...Ne4 { because  d5  would be hanging. This is exactly the kind of position that we should avoid! } )
6. Qxc4
6. b5( { I think this immediate  ...b5  is the most precise move order.    }6...Bg7 { would indeed be a position from the Grünfeld. It is also playable, but White gets the possibility to win the center immediately with }7.e4 { . Let's not go down this rabbit hole.  As Black's main counterplay in these lines is still connected with  ...b7-b5  ideas, I think it is the most principled move to play it before White can get a second pawn in the center. } )
7. Qd3{ This is in general not considered to be a particularly good square. Black is not forced here to go for  b5 - b4 , but can also play in a calmer fashion. }
7. b4( { Still, let's go with the early  ...b4 . This is most consistent with our lines after   }7.Qb3 { . } )( { Starting with }7...Bg7 { and }-- 8...O-O { is a very playable alternative. With White's queen not on  b3 , Black can play ... b4  at any given time.  Nevertheless, I like the resulting position after  7...b4 . They also have the advantage of stopping White's  e2 - e4  move. } )
8. Ne4{ If White wants to go for  Ne4  as answer to ... b5 - b4 , they should play it with the queen on  d3  instead of on  b3 . Otherwise Black gets in ... Be6  for free. }( 8.Na4 Bf5 { transposes to lines that we discuss via the  7.Qb3  move order -  see here . } )
8. Nxe4{ An easy move. White's queen is more vulnerable on  e4  than on  d3 . }
9. Qxe4
9. Bg7{ We have a typical situation. White would love to develop as fast as possible and fix the pawn on  c6  as a weakness.  However, if we get our breaks in - mainly ... c5  but maybe even ... e5  - we will be doing fine immediately and our space-grabbing queenside pawns might give us the slightly more pleasant position. White's pieces are not on really good squares right now and especially the queen on  e4  can be easily attacked with tempo. }
10. e3{ This is a normal-looking move. But Black can just get a good position with some standard moves. }
10. a5{ This is a nice multi-purpose move. Black protects  b4 , wins some space on the queenside and prepares ... Ba6 . }( { A move like }10...O-O { is also playable but playing }10...a5 { is just very useful.    }{ In variations where White plays  Nc3 - a4  instead of  Ne4 , these ... a5  moves are often too slow, because White has realistic hopes of creating a blockade on the  c5 -square.  However, without the knight on  a4 , we usually have no problems getting our queenside rolling. } )
11. Bc4{ White has different moves but Black's strategic main goal is pretty clear: ... c5 ! }( 11.Bd2 { followed by  Rc1  is a typical idea to get control over the  c5 -square as fast as possible. Let's just make some moves to see why this is not particularly realistic in this specific setup. }{    }11...Bf5 { is not the only move, but winning a tempo against the queen looks logical enough. Now, }12.Qh4!? { is the trickiest move. White plays with ideas to go  e3 - e4  and  Bh6  with a typical attacking setup. However, it is interesting that Black can even spend one more tempo to stop this idea, and is still in time to get ... c5  in. }{    }12...h6! { and now,  e3 - e4  can be answered with ... g5  when White can't keep the  e4 -pawn protected. }13.Rc1 { is part of the positional plan to fight against  ...c5 . }13...Qd6 { and Black just plays ... Nd7 , ... Rc8 , ... O-O  and ... c5 . For example: }14.Be2 Nd7 15.O-O Rc8 16.Rfd1 g5 17.Qg3 O-O 18.b3 c5 { with a good position for Black. } )
11. O-O( { A flexible move. The immediate }11...Ba6 { is similar. } )
12. O-O
12. Ba6{ Black is not forced to exchange these bishops but White's bishop was very active and after taking on  a6 , Black's rook protects the  c6 -pawn so it will be easier for us to play ...  Nd7 . }
13. Bxa6( 13.Qc2 { allows the typical move }13...c5! { . White can take the pawn but it will only be a matter of time until Black wins the pawn back. }14.dxc5 Bxc4 15.Qxc4 Nd7 { , followed by }-- ...Rc8 { . } )
13. Rxa6{ via weird transpositions, we reached a position from Bacrot-Kamsky where Black was even slightly better after some moves. White cannot stop ... c5 . }( { That game went }14.Bd2 c5! 15.Rac1 Re6 16.Qh4 Bf6 17.Qh6 cxd4 18.exd4 Nc6⩱ { and Black had the slightly more comfortable position in Bacrot, E. -Kamsky, G., Thessaloniki 2013. } )
