10. h4{ Modern chess, ladies and gentlemen! This is the computer way of playing this position.     I think the easiest way to play this position from the black side is to just stop all the harry nonsense with 10... h5  . The inclusion of the h-pawn moves should generally not be to Black's disadvantage.  Considering that both sides castles kingside, we can conclude that the h-pawn moves weaken both kings but as Black is the side who plays more aggressively/dynamically in this variation, I think we have many scenarios where the inclusion is better for us. The engines mainly seem to have one specific setup in mind where things might indeed be favourable for White. }( {  A)  To understand the inclusion of  h4  and  ...h5 , let's look at the immediate }10.Qc2 { . Here, Black can just start pressuring White's kingside. }10...Bg4! { Threatening ... Bxf3  and taking on  d4 . }11.e3 O-O { Black has plenty of ideas to play this position. We can take on  f3  and spoil White's structure, we can just continue playing ... Nd7  and ... c5 . }12.Be2 { Trying to be solid. }12...Bf5!? { A nice idea. We want to force the white queen away from the control of the  c5 -square and if White plays }13.e4 { , we just drop back to  g4 . }( { ( }13.Qb3 c5 { ) } )13...Bg4 { with a lot of pressure against White's center. } )( { Let's look at some other alternatives and what we can play against those.     B)  }10.Qh4 { A prophylactic move against ... Bf5 . Also, White is preparing  Bh6  with a kingside attack. }10...Qa5! { A clever move to stop  11.Bh6 .     B1)  The tactical point is that }11.Bh6?! { is answered with }11...b3+! 12.Bd2? ( { ( }12.Nd2 { is better but White would just be on the defensive there.) } )12...Qxa2! { and Black breaks through in the queenside.     B2)  }11.Bd2 { White should do something against the idea  11...b3  but this just allows Black to play  ...c5  soon. For example: }11...Nd7 12.a3 c5  )( {  C)  Developing the dark-squared bishop is also too slow to stop Black from playing  ...c5 . For example: }10.Bg5 Bf5 { Winning a tempo against the queen. Black could also play other developing moves. }11.Qh4 { White would love to play  Bh6  but we can stop it with the simple }11...h6! { ⩱ White's pieces are just uncoordinated and Black will soon hit White with  ...c5 . } )
10. h5{ An easy solution. In a lot of positions, the inclusion is just advantageous for Black. }
11. Qc2( { This slightly confusing move is the engine's justification.    If White plays normal moves like }11.e3 { , the h-moves don't make a lot of sense for them. White has no longer the  Qh4  &  Bh6  ideas and Black is more often than White the one who goes for a kingside attack so the weakening of both kings is in our favour. }11...Bf5 { Not the only move but developing pieces with tempo is even more attractive with White's king having no completely safe spot somewhere on the board. }12.Qf4 { The only square. }12...O-O { Black castles and is now ready to play  ...c5  without running into  Bb5+  ideas. }13.Bc4 { White should also try to prove that they are the one attacking. This move flirts with  Ne5  or  Ng5  ideas to pressure Black's kingside. }( { ( }13.Be2 { just allows }13...c5 14.e4 Bg4 { and White's center is collapsing.) } )13...Nd7 { Protecting  e5 . }( { ( }13...c5?! 14.e4 Bg4 15.Ne5! { gives White some pressure.) } )14.O-O Nb6!? { An ambitious move. Black postpones .... c5  for a moment to stop White's pressure along the  a2 - g8  diagonal and claims that Black's queenside is flexible enough to be mobilized afterwards. }( { ( }14...c5?! 15.e4 Bg4 16.Ng5± { with  f3 -ideas and pressure against  f7  is not what we want. }{ ) } )( { ( }14...Qb8!?⇆ { is an easy move to exchange queens. In the resulting position, Black will have no problems playing  ...c5 .) } )15.Bb3 Nd5! 16.Qg3 a5!⇆ { Black can advance with ... a4  and we also have the option to play ... c5  at some point - maybe even after ... Nd5 - f6 - e4 . White simply has no real control over the important queenside squares. } )
11. O-O( { Here, Black should just develop normally.    With the h-pawn moves included, the move }11...Bg4?! { isn't so great anymore. White can use the somewhat stable outpost on  g5  for the knight. }12.e3 { Protecting the  d4 -pawn first. }12...O-O ( { (Taking on  f3  also isn't ideal for Black. White can use the f-pawns to strike with  f3-f4-f5  against Black's kingside. For example: }12...Bxf3 13.gxf3 Nd7 14.Bd2 a5 15.f4 { , followed by }-- 16.f5 { .) } )13.Ng5→ { and White has ideas like  Bc4 ,  f3 ,  e4 . } )
12. Bg5{ Pressuring  e7 , also using that Black cannot play ... h6  anymore. }
12. a5{ Once again this nice multi-purpose move that starts active counterplay on the queenside. }
13. Rd1{ White should still anticipate Black's  c5 -break. }( { The innocuous }13.e3 { allows }13...Bf5! { . White has no great response. }14.Bd3 Bxd3 15.Qxd3 c5! { allows our typical break while   }14.e4 Bg4! { gives Black plenty of counterplay against White's center. } )
13. Be6{ This slightly weird-looking move is my recommendation. Black is not really threatening to take the pawn on  a2  just yet because  b2 - b3  just traps the bishop, but it discourages White from taking on  c6  after Black plays ... Nd7 . }( 13...Bg4 { is a more natural move but I couldn't find a good way to avoid the following repetition. }14.e3 Nd7 15.Be2 Re8 16.Qxc6 { Not a super ambitious move but it looks like Black should take the draw after this with }16...Rc8 17.Qb5 Rc2 18.Rd2 Rc1+ 19.Rd1 { .    }{ There is certainly still a lot to discover but by putting the bishop on  e6 , White can never really take on  c6 . } )
14. e3{ Black's play is very similar, no matter if White plays  e2 - e3  or  e2 - e4 . We'll always go ... Nd7  and prepare the ... c5 -break as well as a potential advance with ... a4 . }( 14.e4 Nd7 15.Bc4 { White should put the bishop on  c4  to neutralise the  e6 -bishop. }( { ( }15.Be2 a4! { threatens }-- ...b3 { and is just an unnecessary problem for White.) } )15...Bg4! { Black gets typical Grünfeld pressure and has the idea to go }-- ...Bxf3 { . } )
14. Nd7
15. Bc4( { Once again,  c4  is the best square for the bishop because }15.Be2 a4! { with }-- ....b3 { ideas is annoying. } )
15. Bf5
16. e4
16. Bg4{ and we transposed to the variation with  14.e4  - see above. Black still has their breaks available while ... Bxf3  is an additional idea and White's king will never be super safe. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Royal Adventures 4.Nc3 g6 5.Qb3"]
[Black "7.Qb3 & 8.Qd1 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Qb3{ In the sidelines, we saw many lines with an early  Qb3 . This variation is the most critical version.     White protects the  c4 -pawn which is a useful thing to do, but there is also a more concrete reason to this move. With the additional piece attacking  d5 , White can opt for setups with  Bg5  and Black doesn't have the typical - dynamic! - response ... Ne4 . }
5. dxc4{ Reacting in some Grünfeld Style.     Black will continue with ... b5  to start typical counterplay on the queenside. }( 5...Bg7 { allows }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5 { and Black cannot play dynamic with }7...Ne4 { because  d5  would be hanging. This is exactly the kind of position that we should avoid! } )
6. Qxc4
6. b5( { I think this immediate  ...b5  is the most precise move order.    }6...Bg7 { would indeed be a position from the Grünfeld. It is also playable, but White gets the possibility to win the center immediately with }7.e4 { . Let's not go down this rabbit hole.  As Black's main counterplay in these lines is still connected with  ...b7-b5  ideas, I think it is the most principled move to play it before White can get a second pawn in the center. } )
7. Qb3{ This is the best square for White's queen. Both  d3  and  b3  are squares where the queen can be attacked later on, but from  b3  (or later  c2 ) it stabilizes a knight on  a4 , so moves like ... Qa5  will not be with tempo. }
7. Be6{ It makes a lot of sense to drive the queen away from  b3 . Otherwise, it is harder for us to play with ...  b4 . }( 7...Bg7 8.e4 { enters the same Grünfeld variation we could have reached with   }6...Bg7 { . White should be able to be slightly better here. }{ Compared to the  variations  with the queen on  d3 , Black has a harder time mobilising the queenside if we don’t use our chance now! } )
8. Qd1{ This whole manoeuvre  Qd1 - b3xc4 - b3 - d1  looks like the kind of opening that Magnus Carlsen uses to troll his opponents in some online bullet events. }( { But as }8.Qc2 { has the clear drawback of being vulnerable to }...Bf5 { moves - which we will often make use of -, this move starts to make some sense. } )
8. b4( { I will once again go for the immediate b-pawn push. As White was not ready to push   }9.e4 { because of }...b4 { , we can make a case that   }8...Bg7 { should be a flexible alternative.  But going for the immediate  ....b4  is most consistent with other lines in this chapter. } )
9. Na4{ White should definitely go for the control of the  c5 -square. }( 9.Nb1 c5! { would be already very good for Black. } )
9. Bg7{ The most flexible move. }
10. Bd2{ This seems to be White's best move. The attack against  b4  gives Black at least one thing to worry about.  If Black protects the pawn with ... a5  (my recommendation), White is at least one move closer to  Rc1  to prevent the ... c5 -break. }( {  A)  }10.g3 { gives Black different possibilities. One idea is just to prepare  ...c5  as fast as possible. There is not much White can do about it.     A1)  }10...O-O 11.Bg2 Na6 12.O-O Rc8 13.Ne5 Bd5 14.a3 c5 { with easy play.     A2)  }10...Qa5 { with the idea to get in  ...b3+  fast is another idea. }11.Bd2 Ne4 { wins the bishop pair while   }11.Bg2 b3+ 12.Nc3 Ne4 { gives Black nice activity. } )( {  B)  }10.e3 { has no independent value. White should follow it up with  Bd2  soon as the bishop has no better square anyway and Black might have better moves than ...  a5  to protect  b4  - maybe even ... c5  - if White postpones this move for too long. For the moment, Black should just continue normally with }10...O-O { . } )
10. a5{ A safe move to deal with the attack against  b4 . Whenever we protect the  b4 -pawn with this pawn move, we need to have the confidence that White will not be in time to stop all our pawn breaks. But with White's queen not on the c-file, we can be pretty optimistic about that. }( { Black can also consider sacrificing the b-pawn for a bigger lead in development and a quick  c5 -break.    For example }10...Ne4!? 11.Bxb4 Nd7 { Black just develops fast and prepares  ...c5 . }12.e3 Rb8 13.Ba3 c5! { With White's king in the center, a lot of open files and  ...Qa5+  ideas, this should be a very playable position. } )
11. e3{ A logical move to continue development. }
11. O-O{ A flexible move. White has a hard time preventing all of Black's breaks.  We are ready to go ... Ne4  which prepares ... c5  and ... e5  at the same time. }
12. Be2{ This is just a bad move as it doesn't stop any of Black's ideas. }
12. Ne4
13. Qc2{ A logical move to fight Black's setup but a little bit too late. }
13. Bd5{ Protecting  e4  but also clearing the way for ... e5 ! }
14. O-O
14. Nd7{ Black is ready to push either ... c5  or ... e5 . }
15. Bd3
15. Nxd2
16. Nxd2
16. e5{ with active play. }
