8. Qc2( { The most logical square. White keeps an eye on the  e4 -square and would be ready to answer a move like   }8...Bg7 { with }9.e4 { .    }{ Also White keeps an eye on the  c5 -square that has been weakened by Black's last moves.  The drawback is that ... Bf5  can come with tempo. } )
8. b4{ Fighting for the  e4 -square. We want to play ... Bf5  without being hit with  e2 - e4 . }
9. Ne4{ It looks natural to develop the knight to the center but Black gets a lot of activity. Also, with no knight on  a4 , Black has to worry much less that White will be able to create a blockade on the  c5 -square. }
9. Nxe4
10. Qxe4
10. Bg7( { Normal development. We have the same position as in the line   }7.Qd3 b4 8.Ne4 { just with the difference that Black's bishop is on  e6  rather than  c8 . This should certainly be advantageous for Black. } )
11. e3{ Normal developing moves like this won't make it hard to prepare an early ... c5 . }( {  A)  }11.Qc2 { seems to be White's best move but it allows a transposition to a position that we have already talked about in the   }7.Qd3 b4 8.Ne4 { variation.   }11...Bg4 { Just one of many good options. ( }11...O-O { is also fine.) ( }11...Bxd4!? { It is a little bit greedy to steal the pawn but Black is objectively fine.) } )( {  B)  }11.g3 { or }11.h4 { are not possible because }11...Bd5 { followed by  ...Bxf3  and  ...Qxd4  }{ wins the  d4 -pawn. White has some compensation, still, it is nothing that we should be worried about. } )
11. a5{ We have seen the strength of this move already in a lot of different variations. }
12. h4( { This is at least one variation where White can try to use the bishop on  e6  to their advantage.   }12...h5 13.Ng5! { is stronger than with the bishop on  c8 . } )
12. Bf5{ Moving the bishop a second time but with our next move, we'll get the queens off the board which makes this whole  12.h4  idea pretty pointless. }
13. Qf4
13. Qd6{ Black is very comfortable. If we take on  f4 , we'll weaken White's structure and if White takes on  d6 , they repair ours.     Pick your poison! }
