[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Royal Adventures 4.Nc3 g6 5.Qb3"]
[Black "Blockade Variation: 7.Qb3/8.Qc2/ 9.Na4 - 10.Qc4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3
4. g6
5. Qb3{ In the sidelines, we saw many lines with an early  Qb3 . This variation is the most critical version.     White protects the  c4 -pawn which is a useful thing to do, but there is also a more concrete reason to this move. With the additional piece attacking  d5 , White can opt for setups with  Bg5  and Black doesn't have the typical - dynamic! - response ... Ne4 . }
5. dxc4{ Reacting in some Grünfeld Style.     Black will continue with ... b5  to start typical counterplay on the queenside. }( 5...Bg7 { allows }6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Bg5 { and Black cannot play dynamic with }7...Ne4 { because  d5  would be hanging. This is exactly the kind of position that we should avoid! } )
6. Qxc4
6. b5( { I think this immediate  ...b5  is the most precise move order.    }6...Bg7 { would indeed be a position from the Grünfeld. It is also playable, but White gets the possibility to win the center immediately with }7.e4 { . Let's not go down this rabbit hole.  As Black's main counterplay in these lines is still connected with  ...b7-b5  ideas, I think it is the most principled move to play it before White can get a second pawn in the center. } )
7. Qb3{ This is the best square for White's queen. Both  d3  and  b3  are squares where the queen can be attacked later on, but from  b3  (or later  c2 ) it stabilizes a knight on  a4 , so moves like ... Qa5  will not be with tempo. }
7. Be6{ It makes a lot of sense to drive the queen away from  b3 . Otherwise, it is harder for us to play with ...  b4 . }( 7...Bg7 8.e4 { enters the same Grünfeld variation we could have reached with   }6...Bg7 { . White should be able to be slightly better here. }{ Compared to the  variations  with the queen on  d3 , Black has a harder time mobilising the queenside if we don’t use our chance now! } )
8. Qc2( { The most logical square. White keeps an eye on the  e4 -square and would be ready to answer a move like   }8...Bg7 { with }9.e4 { .    }{ Also White keeps an eye on the  c5 -square that has been weakened by Black's last moves.  The drawback is that ... Bf5  can come with tempo. } )
8. b4{ Fighting for the  e4 -square. We want to play ... Bf5  without being hit with  e2 - e4 . }
9. Na4{ This is White's most ambitious move. They keep control over the  c5 -square.  In these variations, Black really shouldn't waste any tempi because White can realistically fix our pawn weaknesses on the queenside. }
9. Bf5{ This was the idea. White cannot play  e2 - e4  easily. }
10. Qc4( { I think this move is slightly less flexible than }10.Qb3 { . }{ Both moves attack the  b4 -pawn but from  b3 , the queen does also support the  a4 -knight. } )
10. Bg7{ Black should develop their pieces as fast as possible to create counter chances at the first opportunity. If White grabs the pawn on  b4 , this will give us additional time that we can use to build our initiative. }( {  A)  For example, a move like }10...a5?! { is a bit slow. It protects  b4 , but White can just play it positionally, develop their pieces and fight for the control of the  c5 -square. }11.Bg5 Bg7 12.e3 O-O 13.Bd3 Bxd3 14.Qxd3 Nbd7 15.Rc1± { is a logical way how things can play out if Black just plays normal developing moves instead of creating concrete dynamic counterplay.     Here, White is just much better as ... c6 - c5  is no longer possible and White can just continue with playing against the weakness on  c6 . Black will have a tough time to stop White from playing simple moves like  O-O ,  Rc2  and  Rfc1 . Just a sample line to see how White would usually coordinate their pieces. } )( {  B)  Black can also start with }10...Nbd7 { . }{ Taking on  c6  is not necessarily something White wants as Black develops a nice initiative. } )
11. g3{ Lines with  g3  should better be played with the queen on  b3 . White only runs into more problems with ... Qa5  as the knight is not protected by the queen. }
11. Ne4{ Taking control over the  c5 -square before playing ... Qa5 . }( {  A)  }11...Qa5 12.Nc5 { is not something that we should allow. } )( {  B)  }11...Nbd7 12.Bg2 Qa5 { is a different move order with the same idea of controlling  c5  before going for ... Qa5 . } )
12. Bg2
12. Qa5{ This is a common idea even with the queen on  b3 . Here, this is an even better version. }
13. b3{ A normal-looking move to stabilise the  a4 -knight. }
13. Nd7( { White has to be careful.   }14...Nd6 { is a threat to win White's queen. } )
14. Bb2( { Giving the queen a square on  c1 . }14.O-O ?? Nd6-+ { loses the queen. }15.Qxc6 Rc8  )
14. O-O
15. O-O
15. Nb6{ A typical move to get rid of the knight on  a4  that is restricting our queenside. }
16. Nxb6
16. axb6{ Black has a very active position. }
