13. Ne5{ This is the tactical move to play the position. White attacks  f7 ,  c6  and  e4  and some variations can become quite entertaining. }
13. Be6{ The easiest move. Black defends the threat against  f7  with tempo }
14. Qd3( { The only square for the queen. }14.Qc2?? b3+ { would be a horrible idea. } )
14. Qxa4{ Let's go with this move as the trainable line. It easily solves all of Black's problems. }( { I cannot resist showing you the - computer-like - alternative }14...b3+ 15.Nc3 Nxc3 16.Nxc6! Qxa2! { which is 'obviously equal':) } )
15. b3{ A nice in-between move to keep the queenside more stable. }( {  A)  The immediate }15.Bxe4?! { allows }15...b3! { . White cannot simply lose the queenside because Black's queen will be surprisingly well placed on  a4 . }16.a3? O-O ! { and }-- 17...Rd8 { comes next with the very annoying threats }-- 18...Rxd4 { and }18...Bxe5 { . It is surprisingly hard to find something against these threats. } )( {  B)  }15.Qxe4?! { is not losing by force but Black still gets a very good position with a well-timed  ...b4-b3 . }15...Bd5! { This is not winning a piece but it drives White's queen to the  h3 -square. }16.Qg4! { Threatening mate on  c8 , so Black cannot take the bishop on  g2 . But Black has different ways to implement a well-timed ... b3 . }{     B1)  }16...O-O { This is the safe move. Without White's queen on the third rank, White can never play  b2-b3  because of  ...Bxb3 . }17.O-O b3 { The pressure against  a2  and  d4  gives Black a comfortable game. }{     B2)  }16...f5! { Stopping the mate and forcing the white queen to  h3 . }17.Qh3 b3! { White's pawn structure is once again under pressure. } )
15. Qa5{ Attacking  e5 . }
16. Bxe4{ Finally, White gets their piece back. }
16. Bxe5{ The knight is so dominant on  e5 , pressuring  c6  that we should take it. }
17. dxe5
17. Qxe5{ Black has won a pawn. White has ways to create compensation but nothing more. }
18. Qc2{ White shouldn't waste any time saving the rook on  a1  and should instead attack in Black's camp. This move prepares  Bb2  and attacks the  c6 -pawn. }( {  A)  }18.Rb1?! Bd5! { is just better for Black. } )( {  B)  }18.Qb1 Bd5 19.Bxd5 Qxd5 { is also very decent for Black. } )
18. f5{ This invites an exchange sacrifice for interesting compensation. }( 18...Qxa1 { is a simple move. White wins back the rook on  a8  but Black will remain with a sound position. }19.Bxc6+ Nd7 20.Bxa8 O-O { White has the two bishops, and Black the lead in development. This is certainly playable for both sides. } )
19. Bb2( 19.Bxc6+? { just loses material. }19...Nxc6 20.Qxc6+ Kf7! { -+ }{ Black's rooks are joining the action while White's rooks are only targets. ... Qxa1  and ... Bd5  are in the air. } )
19. Qxe4
20. Qxe4
20. fxe4
21. Bxh8
21. a5{ The idea ... a5 - a4  gives Black a very good piece play for the sacrificed exchange. }
