15. Nd5{ White did a decent job of preventing us from going ... c5 .     With ... Nd5 , we are creating pressure against  d4  and we are also planning to put a knight on  b6 , exchange the  a4 -knight and get some mobility into our queenside. }( 15...Rc8 16.Rfd1 { makes it a little bit tricky to push the c-pawn as Black's queen needs some time to escape the scope of White's rook on the c- and d-file. } )
16. Rfd1{ Let's look at this as a sample line. Overprotecting the center and just centralising the rook. }
16. N7b6
17. Nxb6
17. Nxb6
18. Qb3( 18.Qc5? Na4! { loses. } )
18. Qd5( { A nice move to improve our pawn structure. Either, we'll take on  b3  which gives us options like  ...Bd5  or White takes on  d5  with }19.Qxd5 cxd5 { . }{ In the resulting symmetrical structure, Black definitely has their pluses with the pressure against  d4 , the space advantage on the queenside and maybe some ... Nc4  jumps. } )
