12. Bg2{ The logical follow-up. }
12. Qa5{ This seems to be Black's most precise move order. Black protects  b4 , keeps an eye on  a4  while also preparing ... c5  and looking at ideas like ... Be6  and ... b3 +. }
13. O-O{ The most natural move. }( {  A)  }13.Bd2 { is a typical move to look out for but here Black has no real problems with the  b4 -pawn. }13...Na6! { Protecting the pawn. }14.a3 { This is the typical follow-up of this  Bd2 -idea but here it is only winning the  b4 -pawn under very poor conditions as White's pawns will just be very vulnerable themselves. }14...Ne4! { A nice move, threatening  ...Nxd2  when Black would gain the bishop pair for free. }15.Bxb4 { The only logical move. }15...Qb5 { A nice square for the queen. Black keeps an eye on  b4  and  e2  at the same time. }16.O-O Nxb4 17.axb4 a5! { Black will win back the pawn with a very good position. Both the  b4 - and the  e2 -pawn look juicy. } )( {  B)  }13.a3 { is a funny move. White sacrifices a pawn to open files on the queenside and get access to Black's pawns on  c6  and  a7 . But it is nothing special for White. }13...bxa3+ { Black should take. }14.Bd2 axb2! { An important in-between move. If White would win back the pawn on  a3 , they would get the open files on the queenside for free. }15.Qxb2 Qa6 { Keeping an eye on  e2 . Black will just continue with ... Nbd7 , potentially .... Ne4  and ... c5 . }{ For example }16.Nc5 Qc8 17.O-O Nbd7 { or }17...Ne4 { . Both moves give Black a very reasonable position. } )
13. Qb5{ A nice square for the queen.  e2  is hanging in some lines.  Black's plan is quite easy. Develop with ... Nbd7 , put a rook on  c8  and play ... c5 . If Black manages that, we might arguably be already better as we have more space on the queenside and our pieces are just usually on the better squares.  Let's look at a sample line to see how the game can continue. }
14. Re1{ Let's use this as a trainable. White protects  e2  in the most solid way possible.  Ignoring the  e2 -pawn just gives Black the nice resource to take on  e2  at the right moment. }( {  A)  }14.Bf4 Nbd7 { The most important thing is to develop the pieces! }15.Rac1 { Putting pressure along the c-file is positionally useful but Black can prepare ... c5  while developing and at some point, the hanging  e2  might be taken. }15...Rac8 16.Nc5 { For example this approach, stopping  ... c5  by putting a physical piece in front of the pawn, would be positionally great but Black can just take on  e2 . }( { ( }16.Rfe1 { Protecting  e2  allows once again Black to prepare  ...c5  in time. }16...Be6 17.Qd1 Nd5 { and Black either wins the bishop pair or achieves their favourite break after something like }18.Bd2 c5⇆ { .) } )16...Nxc5 17.Rxc5 Qxe2 { White should still not be worse with the weak  c6 - and  b4 -pawn but Black has annoying ideas like .... Ne4  or ... Nd5 . } )( {  B)  }14.Ne5 { A concrete move, stopping the development of the  b8 -knight by attacking  c6 . But Black can just exchange the knight. }14...Nfd7 { Usually, we don't mind exchanging our  f6 -knight as our bishop on  g7  is much happier with the free view. }15.Nc3 { White can continue this line with some tactical ideas like this but Black will just have a decent position once White's tricks run out. }15...Qb7 { The safest square. Here, White has no tempo moves. }16.a3 { seems to be best but Black just remains with a good structure after something like }16...Nxe5 17.dxe5 Na6 18.axb4 Be6 19.Qa4 Nxb4 { . } )
14. Nbd7{ Black just follows the easy plan: Developing while also preparing ... c5 . }
15. Bd2{ The best move. White develops the bishop with tempo. }
15. a5( { Here, we should spend a tempo protecting the  b4 -pawn. }15...Rab8 { is also an idea in this regard. } )
{ Playing it slow with }16. Rac1{ just allows Black to prepare ... c5 . }
16. Ne4{ Also stopping  Na4 - c5 . The next move is ... Rac8  and then it cannot be long until ... c5  will be played. }
17. Bf4
17. Rac8{ Black is ready to strike back in the center. White has one radical move to continue fighting against ... c5 . }
18. Ne5{ White wants to exchange Black's pieces that prepare ... c5 . But Black can create himself a queenside majority that is also not that bad. }
18. Bxe5{ We would love to keep this bishop on the board but here we have no choice. The resulting queenside majority will justify our decision. }( 18...Nxe5?! 19.dxe5 c5 { Taking with the knight and playing  ...c5  immediately afterwards is what Black wants to do positionally but White has one very annoying concrete move. }20.Rc4! { Black's knight is simply trapped. Black can muddy the waters with }20...Be6 21.Rec1 { but White will be better with two minor pieces versus one rook. } )
19. dxe5
19. Ndc5
20. Nxc5
20. Nxc5{ Black's setup is very stable and in the long run, we will start to run down our queenside pawns down the board! }
