14. Nbd7{ Black just follows the easy plan: Developing while also preparing ... c5 . }
15. Bd2{ The best move. White develops the bishop with tempo. }
15. a5( { Here, we should spend a tempo protecting the  b4 -pawn. }15...Rab8 { is also an idea in this regard. } )
16. Ng5{ The only challenging move. White has to rely on some tactical operations to stop Black from playing ... c5  under good circumstances. }
16. h6{ The most straight-forward response. }
17. e4{ This was White's idea. Otherwise, their last move wouldn't make a lot of sense. }
17. hxg5
18. exf5
18. Qxf5{ Black is currently a pawn up. White has the option to win it back but Black will remain with a very solid structure. }( {  A)  }19.Rxe7 { equalises the material immediately but Black has plenty of play. For exampe: }19...Rae8!? { Offering a second pawn to become active. }20.Rxe8 Rxe8 21.Bxc6 { White is not forced to take the pawn but otherwise Black will be extremely solid on the light squares. }21...Re2 { Attacking  f2  and with ideas like ... Ng4  . }{     B)    }19.Qf3 { Exchanging queens seems to be White's best try. }19...e6 20.Qxf5 gxf5 21.Bxg5 Nd5 { Black has pressure against  d4  and is really solid. We can put our rooks on  b8  and  c8  and can consider going ... N7b6  to break White's blockade on the queenside. } )
