13. Be2
13. Nd5{ This might be the most critical variation in the whole  5.Qb3 -complex. White is a pawn up, has the better structure and is ready to castle.  However, for the moment we are attacking the queen and we are ready to go  e7 - e5  whenever we want. }( { White has different logical moves:     A)    }14.Qd2 { , not leaving the White on the queenside     B)  }14.Qc4 { , the most central square, however, the queen can be attacked afterwards     C)  }14.Qa3 { , not blocking any pieces, but very far offside. } )
14. Qd2{ A safe square for the queen but obviously blocking White's  c1 -bishop. }
14. e5{ This is our typical counter-strike in this line. }
15. dxe5( { Otherwise, Black might consider  ...e4 . For example }15.O-O e4! { is some kind of dream position for Black. The typical scenario is that Black combines this pawn advance with a kingside attack.  Black needs some moves to coordinate their pieces towards White's king but given enough time, Black will create serious threats. Because of Black's space advantage on the kingside, White cannot manoeuvre their own pieces towards the kingside.  This leaves White only with the chance to counter in the center or on the queenside before Black starts a mating attack. But if we look at the passive white pieces, we should be pretty optimistic that Black should come first.  Objectively, this still seems to be holdable for White but in a practical game, Black should be on the easier side of things. }16.Ne1 { What a miserable knight. }16...Re8 { The typical square for the rook. It supports the pawn on  e4 , makes it hard for White to play  f2 - f3 . The rook might also join the attack via  e6  or maybe even  e5 ! }17.b3 { Trying to develop the  c1 -bishop. }17...Bf8! { Occupying the  a3 - f8  diagonal before White can do so. The bishop will be nicely placed on  d6  to pressurize White's kingside. }18.Nc2 Qg5! { Bringing the queen with tempo in the attack as }-- ...Bh3 { is a threat. These attacking positions leave the players a lot of room for creativity.  The main rule is: Direct all your pieces towards White's kingside! } )
15. Nxe5
16. O-O{ The (only?!) advantage of  14.Qd2  over  14.Qc4  is that White is not forced to take on  e5  in this position.     As we will see, the bishop is very useful on  e5 , putting not only pressure against  b2  but also against  h2 . And with the knight still on  f3 , White does also have the idea to go  Nf3 - d4 , forcing Black into the defence of the  c6 -pawn. }( 16.Nd4?! { is a good idea but slightly mistimed. }16...Qg5! { Black creates weaknesses. }16.Nxe5 Bxe5 { looks like our mainline from the  14. Qc4 -variation.    This is just an even better version for Black as White's queen is just blocking White's development. } )
16. Nxf3+{ It is a pity that we have to release the tension but we couldn't continue with 'semi-useful waiting moves'. }( 16...Re8 17.Nd4 { is mildly annoying. } )
17. Bxf3{ White is threatening  e3 - e4  so we should deal with this threat. }
17. Qe7{ Controlling  e4  once more. In the next moves, Black can just put a rook on the b-file and White will continue to struggle to get their pieces into the game. }
18. Qa5{ This seems to be White's best move. The queen on  d2  was just blocking White's pieces and on  a5 , it is controlling the important  c5 -square that White would love to use as an outpost. }( {  A)  }18.Re1 Be4 { is just a worse version for White as the rook is not doing too much on  e1 . } )( {  B)  }18.Qe2 { is another move to improve the queen. But White is not really threatening  e3-e4 . }18...Rab8 { Black can just continue with the regular plan of pressuring the queenside. }19.e4 { The critical move. }19...Rfe8! { Pinning the e-pawn. Maybe the best for White would be to play }20.exd5 Qxe2 21.Bxe2 Rxe2 22.dxc6 Rc8 { with enough compensation for Black.      }20.Re1?! { doesn't work concretely. To be honest, with such a loose unprotected horsey on  a4 , it is not really surprising that Black has tactics saving their pieces. }20...Bxe4 21.Bxe4 Qb4! { White has no solution to the hanging piece on  a4 . } )( {  C)  }18.e4!? Bxe4 19.Re1 { looks like a tactical idea but White really has nothing convincing after }19...f5 { . } )
18. Be4{ This move stops all  e3 - e4  business. I think it is a solid way to keep the pressure. The exchange of light-squared bishops makes White even weaker on the light squares. }( 18...Rab8 { is more according to our plan. However, some lines can be very computer-like. For example: }19.Qc5 { A good positional move. Black should keep the queens on the board while also keeping an eye on  e3-e4 . So }19...Qh4 { is logical. }20.e4!? { This move forces the following sequence. }20...Bxe4 21.g3 { Black does not lose a piece and has a beautiful safe. }21...Bxf3!! 22.gxh4 Rb4! { =∞ White is a queen vs bishop up, but because of the threat }-- ...Rg4+ { , White will have to give most of the material back and Black will remain with very active pieces. } )
19. Bxe4
19. Qxe4{ Now, Black will go back to the plan to create pressure along the b-file. For example: }
20. Bd2
20. Rfb8( { With easy play for Black.    We are currently even threatening   }21....Rb5 22.Qa6 Nc7 { to win White's queen but we are not just playing for cheapos.  The pressure along the b-file should be enough to just win back the  b2 -pawn sooner or later. } )
