7. Be6{ It makes a lot of sense to drive the queen away from  b3 . Otherwise, it is harder for us to play with ...  b4 . }( 7...Bg7 8.e4 { enters the same Grünfeld variation we could have reached with   }6...Bg7 { . White should be able to be slightly better here. }{ Compared to the  variations  with the queen on  d3 , Black has a harder time mobilising the queenside if we don’t use our chance now! } )
8. Qc2( { The most logical square. White keeps an eye on the  e4 -square and would be ready to answer a move like   }8...Bg7 { with }9.e4 { .    }{ Also White keeps an eye on the  c5 -square that has been weakened by Black's last moves.  The drawback is that ... Bf5  can come with tempo. } )
8. b4{ Fighting for the  e4 -square. We want to play ... Bf5  without being hit with  e2 - e4 . }
9. Na4{ This is White's most ambitious move. They keep control over the  c5 -square.  In these variations, Black really shouldn't waste any tempi because White can realistically fix our pawn weaknesses on the queenside. }
9. Bf5{ This was the idea. White cannot play  e2 - e4  easily. }
10. Qb3
10. Bg7{ Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn for dynamic counterplay. }( {  A)  }10...Qa5? 11.Bd2+- { doesn't help. } )( {  B)  Too slow is once again }10...a5?! { . White just gets a positional advantage with natural developing moves, followed by creating pressure on the c-file. }11.Bg5 Ne4 12.Bf4 Bg7 13.e3 O-O 14.Bd3 Nd7 15.Qc2+- { is a logical sequence. } )
11. Qxb4{ White should take on  b4  sooner or later. Black's usual next moves are ... O-O  and ... Nbd7  against most of White's setup so White is free to take the pawn one or two moves later but usually Black just gets a good position if White doesn't grab it. }
11. O-O{ Black just develops as fast as possible in exchange for the pawn. }( 11...Nbd7 { is also possible. } )
12. e3{ White should develop as fast as possible and this is the most solid way to do it. }
12. Nbd7{ Black just develops naturally. Soon, ... e5  or ... c5  will be playable. }
13. Be2
13. Nd5{ This might be the most critical variation in the whole  5.Qb3 -complex. White is a pawn up, has the better structure and is ready to castle.  However, for the moment we are attacking the queen and we are ready to go  e7 - e5  whenever we want. }( { White has different logical moves:     A)    }14.Qd2 { , not leaving the White on the queenside     B)  }14.Qc4 { , the most central square, however, the queen can be attacked afterwards     C)  }14.Qa3 { , not blocking any pieces, but very far offside. } )
14. Qa3{ White keeps control over the  c5 -square - whatever this is worth. But with the queen so far off on the queenside, Black should have different ways to create good counterplay. }
14. Rb8( { I think this is a very strong move. Black does not only have   }15...Nb4 { ideas. } )( { Black still wants to continue with   }15...Re8 { and }-- ...e5 { - and with the rook on  b8 , Black is threatening to trap White's queen with }-- ...Bf8!  )( {  A)  }14...Re8 { can lead to the same position but is slightly less forcing as  ...Nb4  is no threat. } )( {  B)  }14...e5!? { This is our typical break but I just think against this  14.Qa3  move, we can play it under better circumstances. } )
15. O-O( { The most natural move. Now,   }15...Nb4 { isn't really effective. White can just protect  c2  with something like }16.Ne1 { . } )
15. e5{ Our typical pawn break! }
16. dxe5{ The easy (and most likely best) response. }
16. Re8( { Threatening   }17...Bf8 { . This was Black's idea behind  ...Rb8 . } )( 16...Nxe5?! 17.Nd4! { forces Black in the defence. } )
17. e6( { A nice shot. White accepts that the e-pawn is lost and uses it to misplace one of Black's pieces.     A)  }17.Nc3 Nxc3 { , followed by }-- ...Nxe5 { would give Black very active play - no matter how White takes on  c3 . } )( {  B)  }17.Nc5 { This looks like a suicidal move to 'stop' the  ...Bf8  threat. It seems playable but I cannot imagine that some White player plays this. }17...Bf8 18.b4 a5! { White's construction looks ridiculously unstable but it seems White can get away.    For example }19.e4!? axb4 20.Qb2 Bxc5 { White can win their piece back but Black is definitely okay with all of our activity. } )
17. Rxe6( { This move keeps the threat of  ...Bf8 .     A)  The immediate }17...Bf8? 18.exd7! Bxa3 19.dxe8=Q+ Qxe8 20.bxa3 { would give White too much material for the queen. } )( {  B)  However, }17...Bxe6 { is also playable. } )
18. Nc3( { Giving the queen some escape squares on the a-file. }18.Nc5 { is a playable move, not running into }18...Bf8 { because }19.Nxe6! { attacks the queen on  d8 .    Still, Black has easy solutions. }18...Nxc5 19.Qxc5 { and here }19...Nb4 { looks attractive but even the endgame after }19...Qe7 { should give Black plenty of compensation because White's queenside is so vulnerable. } )
18. Bf8{ White's queen doesn't feel safe on a-file and Black just gets very active piece play. }
19. Qxa7{ Black has always good compensation so White can as well take the second pawn. }( { Something like }19.Qa4 Nc5 20.Qd1 Nxc3 21.bxc3 Qa5 { looks also great for Black. } )
19. Nxc3{ Destroying White's structure. }
20. bxc3
20. Nc5( { White has two extra pawns but this can hardly be felt. The queen on  a7  is in quite some trouble and White should look for ways to give some material back to get her majesty out.   }21...Rb7 { is a threat. } )( { The best sequence for White seems to be   }21.Rd1 Rd6 22.Rxd6 Bxd6 { and here, White is already forced to play }23.e4 { after which Black has different ways to take the pawn and when White is only one pawn up and has still problems to solve. } )
