10. Bg7{ Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn for dynamic counterplay. }( {  A)  }10...Qa5? 11.Bd2+- { doesn't help. } )( {  B)  Too slow is once again }10...a5?! { . White just gets a positional advantage with natural developing moves, followed by creating pressure on the c-file. }11.Bg5 Ne4 12.Bf4 Bg7 13.e3 O-O 14.Bd3 Nd7 15.Qc2+- { is a logical sequence. } )
11. Qxb4{ White should take on  b4  sooner or later. Black's usual next moves are ... O-O  and ... Nbd7  against most of White's setup so White is free to take the pawn one or two moves later but usually Black just gets a good position if White doesn't grab it. }
11. O-O{ Black just develops as fast as possible in exchange for the pawn. }( 11...Nbd7 { is also possible. } )
12. e3{ White should develop as fast as possible and this is the most solid way to do it. }
12. Nbd7{ Black just develops naturally. Soon, ... e5  or ... c5  will be playable. }
13. Be2
13. Nd5{ This might be the most critical variation in the whole  5.Qb3 -complex. White is a pawn up, has the better structure and is ready to castle.  However, for the moment we are attacking the queen and we are ready to go  e7 - e5  whenever we want. }( { White has different logical moves:     A)    }14.Qd2 { , not leaving the White on the queenside     B)  }14.Qc4 { , the most central square, however, the queen can be attacked afterwards     C)  }14.Qa3 { , not blocking any pieces, but very far offside. } )
14. Qc4{ This is arguably the most logical move. The queen stays active and is even discouraging us from playing an immediate ... e5 . }
14. Re8{ In this position, we have to prepare ... e7 - e5  first. With the queen on  c4 , we might run into the fork  e3 - e4 . We are on unexplored territory and I expect any human player to just castle in this position.  However, White has other tries that do at least require precise play. }( 14...e5?! { This is not working that great with the queen on  c4 . }15.Nxe5 Nxe5 16.dxe5 Bxe5? 17.e4! { . } )
15. Bd2{ This move keeps an eye on  b4  and allows White to take the  c6 -pawn without running into ... Nb4  issues. Nevertheless, White should have other worries than collecting this pretty weak pawn.  The only good thing about this idea is that  Qxc6  comes with tempo as it attacks the  d5 -knight. }
15. e5
16. Qxc6{ The logical follow-up and the idea behind White's last move. }
16. Ne7{ Saving the knight with tempo. }
17. Qd6{ This keeps contact towards  d4  but not for long. }
17. exd4{ Black wants to open the e-file as long as White's king is on  e1 . }
{ Bringing the king into safety with }18. O-O{ is a nice idea but Black has good possibilities with White's uncoordinated pieces. }
