18. O-O( { White castles to safety and is still a pawn up. However, for this pawn, we have easily enough activity.    }18.Nxd4 { transposes to the  last variation  after }18...Bxd4 19.exd4 Nb6! { . } )
18. dxe3
19. Bxe3
19. Nd5{ Threatening to take on  e3 . }
20. Bg5( { White has no real alternatives.    }20.Bd4? { leaves the kingside dangerously unprotected. }20...Nf4! { White occupies this nice attacking outpost with tempo. White's pieces are all over the place. Black's just winning.    For example: }21.Bc4 Bxd4! 22.Nxd4 Bh3! { is a nice tactical shot. The bishop cannot be taken because of ...  Qg5 + and ... Qg2 #. } )
20. Qb8{ Let's not go deeper than here. White still has their pieces in weird places while Black puts pressure on  e2  and  b2 , and can continue with moves that improve our pieces even further.  ... h6 , ... Nf4 , ....  Qb4 , then activating the  a8 -rook. I think we can enjoy this position. }
