[White "15) Hikaru's Followers e3 & b3"]
[Black "Introduction 4.e3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6{ Welcome to the first chapter with a  e2 - e3  setup! }( {   }4.e3 { is one of White's most popular moves - not only against the Schlechter but against all kinds of Slavs. It is just a save move to protect the  c4 -pawn. }{ Against our repertoire, especially the setup with   }5.Nc3 { and   }6.Be2 { -  see here  - is a popular recommendation by many authors (Shankland, Sielecki, Barrish).    }{ The popularity of these  e3  setups is not too surprising.     They can be played via various move orders }{ - via   }3.e3 { and via }3.Nc3 { and }-- 4.e3 { via   }3.Nf3 { and }-- 4.e3 { .    And also objectively the setup is in no way inferior to the sharper variations. Although the variation looks calm, Black has to play precisely in order not to come under some positional pressure. A good weapon for positional grinders like Magnus!    Those who like positional positions, however, should also be able to get on well with the black position. An interesting fact in my opinion is that famous legend Gata Kamsky doesn't like to play   }4...g6 { against  4.Nc3 , but after his beloved Chebanenko Slav }4...a6 { , if }5.e3 { comes, he likes to answer with }5...g6 { and has been playing this variation for ages.    }{ So he's ready to defend the black side in the  e3  setups, even if he's already committed to the non-mandatory move ... a7 - a6  - against the strongest grandmasters in the world!    If this }{ (slightly disadvantageous) }{ version of the Schlechter is good enough for Gata Kamsky, the 'true Schlechter' is certainly good enough for us!     }{ Rule for all  e3 -variations:    - We play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against anything. This makes us less prone to move order trickery and is also just a very easy rule to build the repertoire on! } )
