[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. b3{ Let's start our journey through the  e3 -setups with a white queenside fianchetto. After locking in the  c1 -bishop, this doesn't look like an illogical idea! }( { The following lines have often been reached in games by Hikaru Nakamura who got to this position by playing his infamous   }1.Nf3 { & }-- 2.b3 { move order. I think that is not too surprising.    If you start with a   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 { move order, the move   }5.b3 { doesn't necessarily look like a particularly flexible approach.    }{ However, someone who faces the Schlechter setup via a  1.Nf3  move order - like Hikaru-, will often realize that there is objectively just nothing better to do than to grab the center with  d2 - d4  in the next moves and transpose to our lines. }{    When I created the lines, I made sure that White couldn't avoid my recommendations by starting with   }1.Nf3 { or }1.c4 { . }{ From an objective point of view, these  b2 - b3  setups are really not threatening and Black has some liberties in choosing their lines - even if you don't follow my exact recommendations. } )
