6. O-O
7. Nbd2{ I think it makes a lot of sense to discuss the setup with  Nbd2  &  b3  rather in this chapter than in the one with  5.Nbd2  -  see here . However, my recommendation against this line is based on a move subtlety from the  Nbd2  move orders.     In the given position, Black has several good moves because White has already committed himself to the rather passive  b2 - b3  &  Bb2 . }( { However, if White plays the move order   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 g6 5.Nbd2 Bg7 6.Be2 O-O 7.O-O { , White still has aggressive options with  b2-b4  on the table that makes the setup with }...e6 { or }...b6 { too slow. That is the reason why I recommend   }7...Bf5 { when }8.b3 { would transpose to the lines discussed here.    So long story short, we have to learn the following }...Bf5 { setup anyways and that's why I recommend it against this move order here as well. For more information check out the lines  starting here . } )
7. Bf5( { This is a very reliable way to develop our pieces. }7...e6!? { or }7...b6!? { could lead to pawn structures similar to our  Be2  main lines.    }{ The fact that White's knight is not on  c3  but on  d2  and that White has already committed himself to  b3  and  Bb2  should be a decent version. }{    Nevertheless, with }7...Bf5 { we transpose to a line that we should learn anyways, so I'll go with this. } )
8. Be2{ The normal move. White wants to develop and this is the only square available for the bishop. }
8. Ne4{ This is the move order I like the most. ... Ne4  is part of our setup anyways and for the moment, we don't commit our other knight to  d7 .     In case White takes on  d5  - which they should not - we can develop the knight to  c6 . }
9. O-O{ The normal move. }
9. Nd7( { For the moment, Black just develops their pieces naturally.    Let's look at three different approaches that White can try:     1)  Taking the knight with  Nd2xe4      2)  Going for  Nf3-h4      3)  Trying to trap the bishop with }10.h3 { and  g2-g4  ideas. } )
10. h3{ These ideas with  h2 - h3  should be taken seriously but usually, we only have to remember the following standard move. }
10. h5{ Stopping all  g4 -ideas. After this, Black can continue with normal development. }
11. a4{ Let's just see a sample line of how Black can build up on the kingside. }
11. e6{ The normal move. Black stabilises  d5  and opens up the way for the queen. }
12. b4{ White just keeps advancing on the queenside. }
12. Ndf6{ Stabilising the  e4 -knight while simply bringing this knight to the kingside as well. }
13. b5
13. g5( { Not forced.    Black can also simply play }13...Re8 { or something similar but these aggressive ideas on the kingside are what makes this line so fun to play. }{ We just want to open up the kingside with ... g4 . } )
