10. Rc1{ If White wants to take on  e4 , they should still include this flexible move. }( { The immediate }10.Nxe4 dxe4 { cannot convince.     A)  }11.Nd2 { White is threatening  g2-g4 . }11...h5! { A typical move in this ... Bf5 -lines. This move does not only secure the bishop against  g2 - g4 , but it can also be the start of an ambitious advance on the kingside! The next move for Black is most likely .... e5  , so it makes sense to play this exchange rather in a situation when Black has already moved the e-pawn once. }{     B)  }11.Nh4 Be6 { also cannot impress. ... g5  is a threat and overall, the  h4 -knight is just misplaced. } )
10. e6{ I like this setup for Black. The bishop on  f5  doesn't have many squares but it is not easy to trap it.  White has no clear plan while Black can slowly but surely build up on the kingside by pushing the h- and g-pawn forward. }
11. Nxe4{ Switching to  h2 - h3  approaches is not critical. }( 11.h3 h5! { This is our standard response. White has nothing concrete. For example, }12.Nh2 { , with the idea  g2-g4 , can either be simply answered with }12...h4 { but sometimes we might even come to the conclusion that  g2-g4  is not even a threat because it weakens White's king as well.    So, in this position, Black can also just play }12...Nxd2 13.Qxd2 Nf6 { and ignore White's ideas. For example, }14.g4 hxg4 15.hxg4 Nxg4 16.Nxg4 Bxg4 17.Bxg4 Qg5! { followed by }-- ...f5 { wins back the piece. } )
