5. Bg7{ Following the rule that we go ... Bg7  & ... O-O  against all setups with an early  e2 - e3 . }
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. Be2{ A slow move that gives Black different decent options. }
7. e6( { Against this move order, I will recommend the same setup that I recommend against the  Be2  mainlines. There is one specific reason why I chose }7...e6 { over other obvious alternatives such as }7...Bf5 { : You cannot be 'move ordered' with  1.c4  or  1.Nf3  move orders! For example in the variation   }1.c4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 Nf6 4.b3 g6 5.Bb2 Bg7 6.Be2 O-O 7.O-O { White can develop naturally without committing to  d2-d4  too early.    }7...Bf5 { might still be playable but loses a lot of its purpose if White can still put their pawn on }d3 { . } )( { However, if we go for a setup with }7...e6 { , followed by ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ...  Nbd7 , White literally has nothing better than to transpose with  d2 - d4  at some point.     For more details, check  this chapter . } )
8. O-O{ Black's setup is very clear.     We'll go ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ... Nbd7 , ... Qe7 , .... Rfd8  and ... Rac8 . After the first moves of this setup, we can already start considering ... c5 . But usually, we will just stick to our setup.  This gives White different move orders to work with. Nevertheless,  8.O-O  is always part of White's setup.     Besides that, the only interesting question is whether White develops the knight from  b1  to  c3  or to  d2 . }
8. b6
9. Nc3( { This move does not transpose to the  Chinese Recipe chapter  with   }8.b3 { because against  those lines , we'll go }8...Ne4 { to avoid setups with  Bc1 - a3 . However, if White's bishop has already committed itself to  b2 , this line is really not threatening. } )
9. Bb7
10. Ne5{ A typical move, trying to install an outpost on  e5  with  f2 - f4 . }
10. Qe7{ Against this idea, it is usually a good idea to create as much dynamic as possible in the center with an early ... c5 . }( { In this regard, }10...Qe7 { is more useful than }10...Nbd7 { as the  b8 -knight might also go to  c6  to put pressure on White's center. } )( 10...c5 { would be logical in that regard but concretely }11.dxc5 bxc5 12.Na4 { seems to give White a lot of pressure against the pawn. } )
11. f4
11. c5
12. Bf3{ A typical move for these situations with so much tension in the center. Both sides try to maximize the pressure. }
12. Rd8( { After White's last move, we had to protect the d-pawn first. The immediate }12...Nc6 13.cxd5± { loses a pawn. } )
13. Qe2
13. Nc6{ Not the only move but quite typical. The knight gets developed to a square where it puts pressure on  d4 . }
14. cxd5{ Usually in those positions, one side gets the so-called hanging pawns. This means - slightly simplified - that one side takes both c- and d-pawn of the opponent and they recapture with b- and e-pawn.  Here, White can decide if they want to play with the hanging pawns or against them. In both cases, these structures are extremely dynamic and ideal to play for the win. For both sides! }( 14.Rad1 { would be a typical move if White rather wants to play with the hanging pawns than against them. Black can keep the tension with }14...Rac8 { but it would be equally typical to just define the structure with }14...cxd4 15.exd4 { and now Black might be the one who takes on  c4  at some point and tries to prove that c- and d-pawn are rather a weakness than an asset. After }15...Rac8 { ,  c6  would be protected and ... dxc4  is a nice idea. } )
14. Nxd5{ Usually, the side with the hanging pawns - which will be us in this case, has no big interest in exchanging minor pieces. The reason is simple:     The hanging pawns are a dynamic asset in the middlegame because they win so much space and sometimes breakthroughs are in the air - see the game  Stupak - Li Chao  - but in the endgame, they can be vulnerable as White can attack them on the open files.     Nevertheless, the particular exchange of the knight on  f6  against one of White's knights is often a good idea as it opens up the butcher. }
15. Nxd5
15. exd5{ This is a very decent version for Black. The pressure against  e5  doesn't even make it easy for White to reach the hanging pawns with  dxc5 , but even if they do it, White does also have a pawn weakness on  e3  that can be a target. }
