7. e6( { Against this move order, I will recommend the same setup that I recommend against the  Be2  mainlines. There is one specific reason why I chose }7...e6 { over other obvious alternatives such as }7...Bf5 { : You cannot be 'move ordered' with  1.c4  or  1.Nf3  move orders! For example in the variation   }1.c4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 Nf6 4.b3 g6 5.Bb2 Bg7 6.Be2 O-O 7.O-O { White can develop naturally without committing to  d2-d4  too early.    }7...Bf5 { might still be playable but loses a lot of its purpose if White can still put their pawn on }d3 { . } )( { However, if we go for a setup with }7...e6 { , followed by ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ...  Nbd7 , White literally has nothing better than to transpose with  d2 - d4  at some point.     For more details, check  this chapter . } )
8. O-O{ Black's setup is very clear.     We'll go ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ... Nbd7 , ... Qe7 , .... Rfd8  and ... Rac8 . After the first moves of this setup, we can already start considering ... c5 . But usually, we will just stick to our setup.  This gives White different move orders to work with. Nevertheless,  8.O-O  is always part of White's setup.     Besides that, the only interesting question is whether White develops the knight from  b1  to  c3  or to  d2 . }
8. b6
9. Nc3( { This move does not transpose to the  Chinese Recipe chapter  with   }8.b3 { because against  those lines , we'll go }8...Ne4 { to avoid setups with  Bc1 - a3 . However, if White's bishop has already committed itself to  b2 , this line is really not threatening. } )
9. Bb7
10. Qc2{ White connects their rooks and controls the  e4 -square.  e3 - e4  might be an idea later on. }( 10.a4 { is typically not a good idea if Black still has the knight on  b8 . After }10...a5 { , Black is ready to go for a quick ... Na6 - b4 . } )
10. Nbd7
11. Rad1{ This is the most popular move on the GM level. White puts their rooks on  d1  and  e1  in anticipation of a quick  e3 - e4  breakthrough. }( { The immediate }11.e4 { is just a much less flexible version of the same idea. }11...dxe4 { Not the only move but equalising immediately. }12.Nxe4 Nxe4 13.Qxe4 Qc7! { Black just prepares  ...c5  and White has no way to stop that. }14.Rad1 c5! { Black is not objectively better yet, but the pressure against White's center is already quite annoying. Black won in  Kavutskiy - Li, 2017 . } )
11. Qe7{ We just continue with our setup. }
12. Rfe1{ This is the most logical follow-up to White's last move. White prepares  e2 - e4 . }( 12.Ne5 { with the idea  f2-f4  is not really threatening when Black is ready to answer with  ...c5  quickly. For example: }12...Rfd8 13.f4 dxc4! { A common motif that we see also in other lines of the course. }14.bxc4 c5 { With typical counterplay in the center. } )
12. Rfd8{ Anticipating White's idea. The rook will be ideally placed on  d8  if White pushes the e-pawn. }
13. e4{ If White plays something different, we will just go ... Rac8  and/or .... c5 . }
13. dxe4
14. Nxe4
14. Nxe4( { The immediate }14...c5 { is also good. } )
15. Qxe4
15. Rab8{ ... c5  will come with tempo with nice counterplay. }
