6. O-O
7. Be2{ A slow move that gives Black different decent options. }
7. e6( { Against this move order, I will recommend the same setup that I recommend against the  Be2  mainlines. There is one specific reason why I chose }7...e6 { over other obvious alternatives such as }7...Bf5 { : You cannot be 'move ordered' with  1.c4  or  1.Nf3  move orders! For example in the variation   }1.c4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.e3 Nf6 4.b3 g6 5.Bb2 Bg7 6.Be2 O-O 7.O-O { White can develop naturally without committing to  d2-d4  too early.    }7...Bf5 { might still be playable but loses a lot of its purpose if White can still put their pawn on }d3 { . } )( { However, if we go for a setup with }7...e6 { , followed by ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ...  Nbd7 , White literally has nothing better than to transpose with  d2 - d4  at some point.     For more details, check  this chapter . } )
8. O-O{ Black's setup is very clear.     We'll go ... b6 , ... Bb7 , ... Nbd7 , ... Qe7 , .... Rfd8  and ... Rac8 . After the first moves of this setup, we can already start considering ... c5 . But usually, we will just stick to our setup.  This gives White different move orders to work with. Nevertheless,  8.O-O  is always part of White's setup.     Besides that, the only interesting question is whether White develops the knight from  b1  to  c3  or to  d2 . }
8. b6
9. Nbd2{ Usually, this move has less influence in the center than  Nc3 . So why develop the knight here?     Well, some players might just randomly decide between  c3  and  d2 , thinking that both are natural squares and that there shouldn't be a huge difference:)     But if White has concrete ideas in mind, it is usually one of the following.      1)  In variations where Black has the typical resource ... dxc4  - like in the  b4  setups - White would be happy to have the possibility to recapture on  c4  with the knight.      2)  White has the option to anticipate Black's ... c6 - c5  idea with  c4 - c5  and stop the c-pawn from moving. With the knight on  c3 , this is more or less never really an idea because the c-pawn cannot be supported along the c-file. }
9. Qe7{ I think this is a smart move order. White's idea of  b3 - b4  was not a threat but it would be one justification for White's last move.  Now, we just control  b4  and force White to choose a different setup. }
10. Qc2{ Black's setup here, compared to lines with the knight on  c3 , differs slightly. Usually, we don't hurry with the move  Ra8 - c8  because White can react with  c4 - c5  and in the resulting position, the rook would just be completely useless on  c8  and even better on  a8 . }
10. Bb7( { Don't go }10...Nbd7? { . White can respond with }11.cxd5 { and Black cannot recapture with the e-pawn as  c6  is hanging and even after }11...cxd5 12.Qc6 { Black's position looks horrible. } )
11. Rac1
11. Nbd7
12. Rfd1
12. Rfc8{ The right rook. Black is still preparing ... c5  but anticipates White's idea to go  c4 - c5 . }( 12...Rac8 13.c5 { might be slightly annoying. Indeed, the best move for Black might be }13...Ra8 { . } )
13. c5{ Not critical but otherwise Black is ready to play ... c5  himself. }
13. bxc5( { Isolating the c-pawn. }13...a5 { is also possible. } )
14. dxc5
14. a5{ Black stops  b3 - b4  and even if White achieves this, Black will be the one deciding when the a-file will be opened. Black has different positional ideas:  ... Ba6  exchanges the 'bad' bishop.     We can try to go for the  c5 -pawn with ... Bf8 .     And we can also consider building up in the center with ... e5 . }
