3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. b3
5. Bg7{ Following the rule that we go ... Bg7  & ... O-O  against all setups with an early  e2 - e3 . }
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ White stays flexible with the development of the  f1 -bishop but Black can easily equalise with one typical Grünfeld break. }
7. c5{ This is the easiest solution. Black is planning to take on  d4 , creating a pawn weakness on that square.     If White takes on  c5 , the knight on  c3  can become a target for ideas like .... Ne4  or ... Qa5 . }
8. dxc5
8. Ne4{ This move puts some pressure on  c3  and also makes sure that we will win back the pawn on  c5  in every situation. }
9. Rc1{ Simply protecting  c3  is not really ambitious but White doesn't really have better options. }( {  A)  }9.Nd4 { This move to block the butcher is not effective here. Black has several decent options like the simple }9...Qa5 { or the highly aggressive }9...Nxc3 10.Bxc3 e5! 11.Nf3 d4! { ↑ when Black is happy to sacrifice one pawn to open up the e-file against White's king. } )( {  B)  }9.Nxe4? Bxb2 { wins material for Black. }10.Rb1? dxe4! { wins a piece for Black. } )
9. dxc4{ Forced because White was threatening to take on  d5 . }
10. Nxe4{ This might win a pawn temporarily but Black gets the bishop pair in exchange and White's extra pawn might also not survive for too long. Both  a2  and  c5  can be targeted in certain variations. }
10. Bxb2
11. Qxd8{ Leaving the queens on the board is risky. }( 11.Rxc4 Qa5+ 12.Nfd2 { This stops }12...Qxa2 { because of }13.Ra4 { but White starts to tie himself up.   }12...Rd8 { should give Black very nice compensation.  a2  is loose but White's main problem is their uncoordinated and passive piece placement. } )
11. Rxd8
12. Rxc4{ White is a pawn up but we have the bishop pair and the king on  e1  is not particularly safe. While White tries to bring that guy to safety, we can develop our queenside and create some counterplay. }( 12.Rc2 { White can also include this intermediate move to take on  c4  with the bishop. But besides the fact that Black can certainly also play }12...Ba3 { or }12...Bg7 { , we also have the clever }12...c3!? { If White takes the pawn, the knight will block the c-file. }13.Nxc3 Ba3 { Black wins back the  c5 -pawn very easily.     }{ If the  c3 -knight moves, Black also has the annoying ... Bb4 + . } )
12. Nc6
13. Be2
13. a5{ A nice move. Black just wins some space and takes control over the  b4 -square.  We are stopping  b3 - b4 , somewhat isolating the  c5 -pawn and - who knows - maybe ... Be6  and ... a4  can be an idea to attack White's vulnerable queenside pawns. }
14. O-O
14. Be6{ Developing with tempo! }
15. Rc2
15. Ba3{ Not the only square for the bishop. }( { Black can also play }15...Bg7 { and claim that the  a1 - h8  diagonal is certainly juicy with no opponents' bishop ever able to challenge this diagonal.     }{ However, after }15...Ba3 { , Black has more concrete options to win the pawn back. ... Nb4  is an idea but moves like ... Bf5  or ... Rac8  (or even ... a4 ) also increase the pressure on White's pawns.  Black has great compensation. } )
