2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and is nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has its followers, especially because some players like to play   }4.Nbd2 { on move }{ 4.    You can see the knight move to  d2  as a restricting move.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or  ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square makes it harder for Black to strike with ... e7 - e5 .  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason.     Despite these 'defensive' reasons, the variations can heat up pretty quickly. Because White has less pressure against our center, it is an extremely attractive possibility for Black to play a quick ... c6 - c5 . Against unprepared opponents, this can quickly give you a good game.    Prepared opponents often avoid this by playing an early  b2 - b4 . This doesn't only win space on the queenside, it also stops our ... c5 -break. However, as mentioned in  Manoeuvres and Plans , we usually quickly strike back on the queenside in those scenarios - often starting with ... a7 - a5 .     Especially if White's kingside is not developed, these positions can quickly become very annoying for White! } )
