3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has been played in quite some games.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is perfectly playable and the most consistent move to the rest of our repertoire. } )
6. Bd3{ The most popular move on amateur level. White simply develops even though Black will have no problems creating counterplay in the center. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Nbd7{ Black prepares ... c5  with typical counterplay. }( { An interesting alternative is }7...c5 { -  see here . } )
8. h3( { The second most popular move after }8.b3 { , but we still play our ... c5  break and White has not really another sensible set-up to develop their queenside besides  9.b3 . } )
8. c5{ That was the plan! }
9. b3
9. b6{ The following moves are a nice standard setup against these rather passive lines in the  5.Nbd2  universe. }
10. Bb2
10. Bb7
11. Qe2
11. Rc8{ A typical setup: Quite often in this course, you see a similar setup but with ... e7 - e6  included. With White's knight passive on  d2 , we can often save this tempo - even though we might still play it later. }
