11. Rc8{ Let's stop the trainable line here. Black just wants to continue with moves like ... e6 , ... Qe7  and ... Rfd8 . If White tries to release the tension in the center by taking on  c5  or  d5 , this will just activate Black's knights. }( { A typical continuation of this scenario is the game Mamedyarov-Gelfand, 2014 which continued }12.Rfd1 e6 13.cxd5 { White immediately takes action in the center, maybe because he had no obvious moves to improve his position while Black would very clearly have useful moves like ... Qe7  or ... Rfd8 . Nevertheless, Black is not unhappy when the center opens up. }13...Nxd5! 14.Ba6 Bxa6 15.Qxa6 { Maybe White was hoping that the attack against  a7  would force us on the defensive but Black can rely on their active piece play. }15...Nb4! 16.Qxa7?! { A greedy move. Maybe it was better to go back with  16.Qe2  when the position should still be equal. }16...Nd3! { This exchanges the dark-squared bishop and gives White some headache on the long diagonal. }17.Rb1 Nxb2 18.Rxb2 cxd4 19.exd4 { And now Black could have reached a great position with }19...Ra8 20.Qb7 Nc5 21.Qc6 Nd3 22.Rbb1 Rxa2∓ {  Mamedyarov, S. - Gelfand, B., Beijing 2014 . } )
