5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has been played in quite some games.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is perfectly playable and the most consistent move to the rest of our repertoire. } )
6. Bd3{ The most popular move on amateur level. White simply develops even though Black will have no problems creating counterplay in the center. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. c5( { This is a way to play the typical Grünfeld move without the preparation of }7...Nbd7 { . If White does not take, Black will just continue with   }8...cxd4 { and can develop their  b8 -knight more active to  c6 . So the only critical move is grabbing the pawn. } )
8. dxc5( { Black can try to safely win back the pawn by starting with }8...a5 { , but I think more in the spirit of this line is to turn it into a real pawn sacrifice variation. } )
8. Na6{ If Black wins back the pawn, they will just have the slightly more active position. So once again, White is somehow forced to be greedy. }
9. Nb3{ Now, Black has no easy way to regain the  c5 -pawn. However, the intention is to open up the queenside and punish White for their lack of development on that side. }( 9.cxd5?! Nxc5 { and Black will win back the pawn on  d5  afterwards. } )
9. b6
10. cxb6
10. axb6{ With a fascinating position. For the moment, White has a solid extra pawn but Black's pieces can quickly jump to life with ... Ne4 , ...  Nb4 /... Nc5 , ... Bb7 /... Be6 . }
