13. Qe2( { A natural move to protect  b5  and connect rooks but Black is already pretty active.    }13.Qb3 { is a logical move to stabilise the queenside and get the rooks into the game but Black can create some pretty stable outposts in the opponent's half. }13...Bc2! { A strong move. }14.Qa3 Nb4 { White has a hard time getting rid of Black's pieces.     A)  }15.Bc3 { might be best even though they have to give up the bishop pair after }15...Nfd5! 13.Rc1 { gives Black easy counterplay after }Rxc1 14.Qxc1 Nb4 { with  a2  hanging and ideas to invade via  d3 .     B)  A slow move like }15.Rfc1 { doesn't do very much and Black can just continue to improve their pieces, for example with }15...Qd5! 16.Bf1 Ne4 17.Nxe4 Bxe4 { . All of a sudden Black has full control over the light squares and threatens }-- ...Bxf3 { and }...Nc2 { . } )
13. Qb6{ Protecting  c6  and also pins the  b2 -bishop. }
14. Rfc1{ Fights for the c-file but Black can use the awkward placement of White's bishops. }( 14.a4 { Stabilizes  b5  but we are immediately ready to invade with our pieces. }14...Rc2! { Followed by ...  Rfc8 , ... Nb4 , ... Ne4 . } )
14. Nc7{ White cannot retreat the  b5 -bishop because  b2  hangs. }
15. Rc5{ The best move. Taking on  b5  right now would give White a dominant rook in the resulting position. }( 15.a4?! { results just in a slightly worse endgame after something like }15...Nxb5 16.Qxb5 Qxb5 17.axb5 Rxc1+ 18.Rxc1 a4 { Black has the two bishops and the long-term asset on the a-file. } )
15. a4{ Not the only move but I think quite an instructive idea. Not only does this move allow us to take on  b5  under better circumstances as the a-pawn will no longer be hanging afterwards, we also stop White's idea to cement the bishop with  a2 - a4 . }( 15...Nxb5 16.Qxb5 Qxb5 17.Rxb5 { gives White some small pressure. } )
