5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has been played in quite some games.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is perfectly playable and the most consistent move to the rest of our repertoire. } )
6. b4{ A typical follow-up of this early  5.Nbd2 . Winning space is usually not a bad idea and this is not the only instance in the course where White goes for this kind of expansion on the queenside.  However, there is some risk involved as an opening on the queenside can horribly backfire for White when being so undeveloped and having the king still in the center. Often, Black does well by seeking immediate counterplay - sometimes in the center but also very often on the queenside! }( 6.b3 O-O 7.Bb2 Bf5 { leads to the fianchetto lines discussed in  this chapter . } )
6. O-O{ The most flexible move - following the rule that we usually castle as fast as possible against  e2 - e3  setups. }( 6...a5 7.b5 a4 { is very much in the style we want to play but at least here White has no bishop on  b2  that can be hit with tempo. Concretely, }8.Ba3 { might be slightly better for White. } )
7. Bb2{ This is the main move. White plays their  b4  move like a calm double fianchetto.  However, very soon, White will be faced with some difficult decisions. }
7. a5{ Immediately undermining White's position. }
8. a3{ This is not in the spirit of the position. With this move, White would accept that their idea of winning space on the queenside was premature and Black can just continue with natural developing moves. The pawn on  b4  can actually become weak as we will see in a second. }
8. Bf5( { Black should just develop quickly after White's innocuous last move. I'll give some analysis in the clickables but I don't consider any of these lines worth trainable.     A)  }9.Be2 { This is the normal follow-up for White. Interestingly enough, White might already be in a little bit of trouble. }9...dxc4! { With the idea to isolate the b-pawn. }10.Nxc4 { One way to recapture. }( { ( }10.Bxc4 b5 { leads to similar positions. }11.Bb3 axb4! 12.axb4 Na6 { It is very awkward to protect the  b4 -pawn.) } )10...axb4! { This is the idea. The  b4 -pawn will be a weakness. }11.axb4 Na6 { This wins the  b4 -pawn. }( { ( }11...Rxa1 12.Qxa1 Na6 { is similar.) } ){  A1)  White should just sacrifice the pawn with }12.O-O Nxb4 { as protecting the pawn makes it even worse for White. For example,     A2)    }12.Qb3 b5! { Fixing the weakness on  b4 . }13.Nce5 Be6 14.Qc3 Nd5 { loses the pawn by force.     A3)    }12.Ba3 Nd5 13.Qb3? Naxb4 { doesn't help.     B)  }9.c5 { is the move that the engines want to play to avoid what comes after  9.Be2 . }{ However, closing the center this way is typically a really sad move because Black has an easy time preparing their ... e5 -break. Here, Black can even combine it with play against the  b4 -pawn. }9...Na6!? { Not really necessary. Black can also just go for ... Nbd7  and ... Ne4  to prepare ... e5 . But still, this is a nice move to tie White to the  b4 -pawn. Black will play ... Ne4  or ... Nd7  to prepare ... e5  but it might also not be completely unrealistic to open up the queenside under good circumstances. For example: }{     B1)  }10.Bc3 { This is asking for }10...Ne4! 11.Nxe4 { White is forced to take. }11...dxe4 12.Nd2 Nc7 { Black's knight will find a nice home on  d5  and Black will break with ... e5  pretty soon. }{     B2)    }10.Qb3 { With the queen on the b-file, it becomes attractive to open up the queenside. }10...b6! 11.Be2 Nd7 { Black is ready to open up the position in different ways. }12.O-O bxc5 13.bxc5? { This allows a tactic. }( { ( }13.dxc5 { is the right recapture even though Black is more comfortable after }13...e5 { .) } )13...Rb8! 14.Qa2 Naxc5! { and White cannot take as  b2  is hanging. } )
