6. b4{ A typical follow-up of this early  5.Nbd2 . Winning space is usually not a bad idea and this is not the only instance in the course where White goes for this kind of expansion on the queenside.  However, there is some risk involved as an opening on the queenside can horribly backfire for White when being so undeveloped and having the king still in the center. Often, Black does well by seeking immediate counterplay - sometimes in the center but also very often on the queenside! }( 6.b3 O-O 7.Bb2 Bf5 { leads to the fianchetto lines discussed in  this chapter . } )
6. O-O{ The most flexible move - following the rule that we usually castle as fast as possible against  e2 - e3  setups. }( 6...a5 7.b5 a4 { is very much in the style we want to play but at least here White has no bishop on  b2  that can be hit with tempo. Concretely, }8.Ba3 { might be slightly better for White. } )
7. Bb2{ This is the main move. White plays their  b4  move like a calm double fianchetto.  However, very soon, White will be faced with some difficult decisions. }
7. a5{ Immediately undermining White's position. }
8. b5{ This is the typical response and the only move played by players above 2400 rating. }( 8.bxa5 Qxa5 { is certainly not what White intends if they play  b2-b4 . Black just got the slightly better pawn structure for free. } )
8. a4{ This gives Black the  a5 -square for their queen and also stops White's a-pawn from supporting their friends on the queenside. Not to mention that White has to think about ... a4 - a3 . }
9. bxc6{ Releasing the tension gives Black very active piece play that can be combined with threats on the queenside. }
9. Nxc6{ Black goes for quick development and it is interesting to see how fast things can go wrong for White. }
10. c5{ A move like this shows how easy Black can develop dangerous dynamic threats. }
10. a3
11. Bc3
11. Ne4{ Black is ready to break with ... e5 . For example: }
12. Nxe4
12. dxe4
13. Nd2
13. e5{ White is way too underdeveloped for a position with such an open center. }
