9. Nxc6{ Black goes for quick development and it is interesting to see how fast things can go wrong for White. }
10. Be2{ This was played by GM Kurajica but Black can take over the initiative. }
10. dxc4{ Black opens up the center. }
11. Nxc4{ This keeps more control over the  e5 -square. But here Black can quickly make progress on the queenside. }( 11.Bxc4 { makes it easier for Black to get in the  ...e5 . }11...a3! { Forcing the bishop to a more unfortunate square.     A)  }12.Bc1 e5! 13.dxe5 Nd5-+ { White has too many problems along the  a1 - h8  diagonal after Black takes on  e5 . Ideas connected with ... Nc3  can also be annoying for White, especially because that makes it impossible for White to play  Rb1 . }{     B)  }12.Bc3 Nd5! { Black wins at least the bishop pair under very good circumstances. Most likely,  ...e5  will still come. } )
11. b5{ Using the possibility to mobilise the queenside. }
12. Nce5( { Going back is not an option. }12.Ncd2? a3! 13.Bc1 Nd5! {  ...Nc3  is coming as well as, of course, ... e5 . } )
12. Nxe5{ Simple enough. White has no good way to recapture. }
13. dxe5{ This leads to a horrible endgame but the alternative is even worse. Now, White is at least able to recapture on  d2  with the knight after the following check. }( 13.Nxe5 Qa5+! 14.Kf1 { is just bad as White will never finish their development while Black steamrolls White on the queenside and the center while the endgame after }14.Qd2 Qxd2+ 15.Kxd2 { is just slowly lost. }15...a3! { Forcing the bishop to  c1  because }16.Bc3 Ne4+ { loses material. }16.Bc1 Ne4+ { Driving the king to  e1  has to be a good thing and ... Bxe5  is now also an option. }17.Ke1 Bxe5 18.dxe5 { This endgame is just lost for White as their majority is worth less while Black's majority is far advanced and the  a2 -pawn is a clear target. For example: }18...Nc3 19.Bd2 b4-+ { followed by ... Be6 . } )
13. Qa5+
14. Qd2
14. Qxd2+
15. Nxd2( 15.Kxd2 Ne4+-+ { once again forced White to destroy their coordination with }16.Ke1 { . Black will just slowly but surely advance on the queenside. } )
15. Nd5{ with a horrible endgame for White. Such an endgame is the dream of every Grünfeld player.     In that opening, it is typical that Black has a 2 vs. 1 majority on the queenside while White has more pawns in the center.  Why is this position such an advantageous version?      1)  Black's majority is very mobile and already very far advanced.      2)  White's structure is much weaker than usual because of the doubled e-pawns.  With one pawn on the d-file, White could create a passed pawn. Here, this is simply not possible. }
