[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has been played in quite some games.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is perfectly playable and the most consistent move to the rest of our repertoire. } )
6. b4{ A typical follow-up of this early  5.Nbd2 . Winning space is usually not a bad idea and this is not the only instance in the course where White goes for this kind of expansion on the queenside.  However, there is some risk involved as an opening on the queenside can horribly backfire for White when being so undeveloped and having the king still in the center. Often, Black does well by seeking immediate counterplay - sometimes in the center but also very often on the queenside! }( 6.b3 O-O 7.Bb2 Bf5 { leads to the fianchetto lines discussed in  this chapter . } )
6. O-O{ The most flexible move - following the rule that we usually castle as fast as possible against  e2 - e3  setups. }( 6...a5 7.b5 a4 { is very much in the style we want to play but at least here White has no bishop on  b2  that can be hit with tempo. Concretely, }8.Ba3 { might be slightly better for White. } )
7. Bb2{ This is the main move. White plays their  b4  move like a calm double fianchetto.  However, very soon, White will be faced with some difficult decisions. }
7. a5{ Immediately undermining White's position. }
8. b5{ This is the typical response and the only move played by players above 2400 rating. }( 8.bxa5 Qxa5 { is certainly not what White intends if they play  b2-b4 . Black just got the slightly better pawn structure for free. } )
8. a4{ This gives Black the  a5 -square for their queen and also stops White's a-pawn from supporting their friends on the queenside. Not to mention that White has to think about ... a4 - a3 . }
9. Ba3{ This is White's main move. We have seen different lines where White got hit with ... a3  so it makes sense to stop this option and also attack  e7 . However, this weird tempo loss is certainly something that we can try to punish! }( { Actually, we now have the position after   }6...a5 7.b5 a4 8.Ba3 { - which I consider very playable for Black - with a full extra tempo for Black! } )
9. Bf5{ Developing the bishop naturally. }
10. bxc6( { This is similar to   }9.bxc6 { -  see here  }{ and the same rules apply: Black should recapture with the knight and rely on active piece play. We want to open up the center and try to punish White for leaving the king on  e1 . } )( 10.Be2?! { is still running into the typical problems with }10...dxc4! 11.Bxc4 cxb5 12.Bxb5 Qa5 { followed by ... Ne4 , ... Rc8 , ... b5 , etc. } )
10. Nxc6
11. Rc1{ This move is needed to create some pressure on the c-file. Otherwise, Black might take on  c4  and go for a quick ... b5 . }( { For example }11.Be2? dxc4 12.Bxc4 Qa5 { is extremely annoying for White. Black will just play  ...b5  next. }13.Rc1 Rac8∓ { doesn't change that. } )
11. Qa5{ Pinning the knight and also preparing  ...dxc4 . }
12. Be2{ White should try to get their king into safety. }
12. dxc4{ Not the only move but the main idea. Black wants to mobilize their queenside. }
13. Rxc4{ This keeps an eye on  c6  so it's harder to play ... b5 . }( 13.Bxc4? Rac8 { leads to the variation we mentioned two moves ago. Black is just much better because  ...b5  is coming. } )
13. Ne4( { Increasing the pressure on  d2  while also threatening   }14...Nc3 { . } )
14. Qc1{ White has no better move to deal with this idea. }
14. Be6{ A very strong retreat. The pawn on  a2  will now lead to some concessions from White. }
15. Rc2
15. Nb4{ This wins the bishop pair. }
16. Bxb4
16. Qxb4{ Black is slightly better here. The two bishops and the typical 2 vs 1 majority on the queenside give us an easy game. The  a2 -pawn is also a liability. }
