5. Nbd2( { Putting the knight on  d2  is not particularly critical and nowhere nearly as popular as }5.Nc3 { , but it has been played in quite some games.    }{ If Black goes for ... dxc4  or something like ... Bg4 , followed by ... Bxf3 , White can recapture with the knight and the control over the  e5 -square might be useful.  Maybe some White players also want to avoid our typical ... Ne4xc3 -maneuver, even though this is a pretty far-fetched reason. } )
5. Bg7( { Black has other options here as well. The engine suggests }5...Bf5 { and Yu Yangyi played }5...a5 { to win some space on the queenside.    However, }5...Bg7 { is perfectly playable and the most consistent move to the rest of our repertoire. } )
6. b4{ A typical follow-up of this early  5.Nbd2 . Winning space is usually not a bad idea and this is not the only instance in the course where White goes for this kind of expansion on the queenside.  However, there is some risk involved as an opening on the queenside can horribly backfire for White when being so undeveloped and having the king still in the center. Often, Black does well by seeking immediate counterplay - sometimes in the center but also very often on the queenside! }( 6.b3 O-O 7.Bb2 Bf5 { leads to the fianchetto lines discussed in  this chapter . } )
6. O-O{ The most flexible move - following the rule that we usually castle as fast as possible against  e2 - e3  setups. }( 6...a5 7.b5 a4 { is very much in the style we want to play but at least here White has no bishop on  b2  that can be hit with tempo. Concretely, }8.Ba3 { might be slightly better for White. } )
7. a4{ I think this move is the best, at least in a sense that Black's counter-attack with ... a5  is no longer creating the same threats as ... a5 - a4  is no longer possible and White also stabilizes on the  b5 -square.     Nevertheless, the last two moves from White completely ignore all rules regarding piece development and Black can typically respond to this with play in the center. }
7. Bg4{ I think every move order that Black can use to prepare ... e5  should lead to very satisfying positions. You will not see many instances in this course where we'll go ... Bg4  if White can recapture on  f3  with the other knight. Here, however, it is not a big deal. }( { As we will see, if White goes for the immediate }8.h3 { , Black will be in good shape to execute their typical breaks ... a5 , ... c5  and ... e5 ! } )( 7...Nbd7 { , followed by  ...e5  is another possibility. To just give a sample line: }8.Be2 e5!? { is possible. Black is certainly fine after something like }9.Nxe5 Nxe5 10.dxe5 Ne4 11.Bb2 Qe7 12.cxd5 cxd5 13.Nxe4 dxe4 14.O-O Bxe5= { . } )
8. Qb3{ This is the most popular move on all levels. White unpins the knight and just puts the queen on an active square where it supports the queenside and also has some influence in the center. }
8. a5{ It makes some sense for Black to provoke  b4 - b5 . After that, ... c5  can be played easily whenever we want. }
9. b5
9. Nbd7{ Black is fully developed and now ready to push in the center. }
10. Bb2{ The move that keeps the most influence in the center. }
10. Rc8{ Not the only move but this rook will be nicely placed here in every scenario. I think we can stop the trainable now and just look at some sample lines. }( {  A)  }11.Be2 { makes it attractive to take on  c4,   because White's bishop has already moved. }11...dxc4 12.Bxc4 ( { ( }12.Nxc4 Be6 { is also unpleasant.) } )12...Nb6! { drives away the bishop from the active  c4 -square. }13.Be2 Be6 { with very active piece play for Black. } )( {  B)  }11.Rc1 c5! { is the typical counter-strike. }12.Be2 { White should keep the tension in the center. }( { ( }12.cxd5?! { opening the center can only be good for Black. }12...cxd4! 13.Nxd4 Rxc1+ 14.Bxc1 Nc5!⩱ { Black will win back the  d5 -pawn with the more pleasant position.) } )12...e6 { stabilising the center. Black should be nicely set up for a position with so much central tension. Our pieces already have a lot of influence in the center. } )
