10. Bd3{ After this move, Black can go for typical aggressive counterplay. }( 10.Be2 { gives Black similar ideas. Just to give some examples:     A)  }10...a5 { with similar counterplay as after  10.Bd3 . }11.b5 { And here, Black can either just play }11...c5 { or }11...cxb5 { when White has no great way to recapture. }12.cxb5 ( { ( }12.axb5 dxc4 13.Bxc4 Qc7 { , followed by  ...Rfc8  and active play in the queenside.) } )12...Nb6 { ,  ...Qc7  and ... Rfc8  are giving Black nice play on the queenside even here. }{     B)  }10...e5 11.dxe5 Ne4 12.Bb2 Qe7 { Black will win back the pawn with no problems. For example, }13.O-O Nxe5 14.Nxe5 Bxe5 { and after the exchange of dark-squared bishops, White might be a little bit soft on the dark squares. Eventually,  ...a5  can create some tension. } )
