6. cxd5{ This variation has been played by some strong Grandmasters like Kozul, Laznicka or Piket. In general, it is a strange line: We play the Slav to force White to make one concession to deal with the hanging c-pawn. And here they give us two of them (exchanging and locking in the  c1 -bishop) voluntarily?    This delayed Exchange variation with the dark-squared bishop locked in on  c1  doesn't promise White anything. Not only that, but it also doesn't make any sense if they don't follow it up with anything concrete. }( { In this case, most players are planning to continue with   }7.Bb5+ { and if Black is not careful, White can often remain with some pressure on the queenside.    But if Black knows their stuff, there is really not that much to be afraid of. } )
