6. cxd5
7. Bd3( { Typically, }7.Bb5+ { is the only ambitious move for White in this  e3 -Exchange Variation. After calmer moves like this one, there is not much Black needs to know.  Both sides have a slightly passive dark-squared bishop now. So, compared to other Exchange Variations, Black has no immediate need to create imbalances to be objectively fine. Nevertheless, a well-timed ... e7 - e5  might be a good way to activate our bishop at the cost of accepting an IQP. } )
7. O-O{ Following the rule to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against all  e3 -setups. }
8. O-O( { The most natural move.    }8.h3 Nc6 9.O-O Bf5 { transposes to the variations  starting here  from the  Bd3  sidelines chapter. } )
8. Bg4{ A good move if we want to keep the option to create some dynamics and play for a quick ... e5 .    Nevertheless, as mentioned, White's setup is so passive that even simplified development such as ... Nc6 , ... Bd7 , ... e6 , ... Rc8  is completely fine. }
9. h3{ The typical move. }( { The rather sharp }9.Qb3 Bxf3 { is discussed in the chapter  Champion's Choice  -  see here . } )
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3
10. Nc6
11. Qe2( { White should play a move that anticipates the  ...e5  idea. Out of those moves, }11.Qe2 { is the most popular one. }{ White just makes sure that ... Nxe5  doesn't come with tempo if Black goes for the e-pawn break. }( {  A)  }11.Rd1 { is similar and can transpose. Here, Black should also simply start with the flexible }11...Re8!? { . } )( {  B)  }11.Bd2 { is the kind of normal developing move that allows the immediate break in the center, as White has no pressure along the d-file. For example, }11...e5! 12.dxe5 Nd7!? { , just to show the idea. }{ ( }12...Nxe5 { is also possible.)     B1)    }13.Qe2 Ndxe5 14.Rad1 d4! { ⇆ is a typical move to get rid of the d-pawn and activate the pieces.     B2)    }13.Qxd5?! Nb6!⩱ { creates some trouble along the d-file.     B3)    }13.Nxd5?? Ndxe5 { just loses. For example, }14.Qe4 f5-+ { when  d5 -is lost. } ) )
11. Re8( { The immediate }11...e5 12.dxe5 Nxe5 13.Rd1 { looks like a decent version for White. }-- 14.Bc2 -- 15.Bb3 { will create quickly pressure against  d5 . } )
12. Rd1{ White doesn't really have an active plan, so it just makes sense to further anticipate Black's active ... e5  idea. }
12. a6( { Black is in no particular hurry to play the  ...e5  break. Stopping this with }13.f4 { might be possible but very double-edged as it also weakens the kingside. } )( 12...a6 { is just a flexible move to prepare  ...b5  and stop  Nb5  - a useful move in case we'll reach an IQP. }12...Qd6 { or }12...Rc8 { are other typical moves.    The immediate }12...e5 13.dxe5 Rxe5!? { seems to be okay with ideas like  ...d5-d4  but I think it is not necessary to give White active ideas such as }14.Bc4!? { . } )
13. Qf1{ Just a sample move to show some more flexible moves for Black's setup.  13.Qf1  makes sense to remove the queen from the e-file. }( { For example after }13.Bd2 e5!? { We can also wait with this move but I want to illustrate one point. }14.dxe5 Rxe5 { Here, Black would be ready to play  ...d4  next. In this regard, }15.Qf1 { might be the best move here as well. } )
13. Qd6{ A nice flexible square for the queen. On the next move, we can go ... e5  and recapture the pawn with her majesty. }( { The immediate }13...e5 14.dxe5 Rxe5 { once again allows }15.Bc4 { . } )
