1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7{ I think it makes sense to use this move order in this chapter to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice is starting with   }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { in this chapter. }{ Because of our rule, that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about the move order that White uses.  Lines, where White combines  Bd3  with an early  Nbd2 , will transpose to lines from the  Nbd2 chapter .    If White plays a quick  b2 - b3 , we will transpose to  Hikaru's Followers .     In the next  chapter , we will discuss the  Bd3 -mainline where White combines this move with  Nb1 - c3  and  O-O  but }{ allows   }7...Bg4 { in the process. With White's bishop already committed to the  d3 -square, this pin is considered a very reliable antidote against it. In this chapter, we will look at possibilities for White to avoid this scenario. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Anti-Champion: Bd3 Sidelines"]
[Black "6.O-O & 7.h3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3{ I think it makes sense to use this move order in this chapter to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice is starting with }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { in this chapter. }{ Because of our rule, that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about the move order that White uses.  Lines, where White combines  Bd3  with an early  Nbd2 , will transpose to lines from the  Nbd2 chapter . } )
5. Bg7
6. O-O( { The moves }6.O-O { and }6.Nc3 { can easily transpose to each other. However, there are some instances where White has some independent ideas.  Especially in the lines where White combines any of these moves with an early  h2-h3 , there are some big differences. }{ Short version:  If White delays castling, we shouldn't go for ... Bf5  because White can exchange and start an attack on the g-file. However, with  Nc3  played instead, Black can create dynamic play with ... dxc4  followed by ... b5  and the knight on  c3  might reduce White's options since the move ... b5 - b4  will come with tempo. } )
6. O-O{ As usual, we just castle first before doing anything else. }
7. h3{ White stops ... Bg4 . }( 7.Nc3 { transposes to the  Champion's Choice . } )
7. Bf5{ This is an old idea in the Schlechter Slav and people used to play in very different positions and under much worse circumstances.     This looks like a good variation to show the different ideas behind this move.  With White already castled, Black doesn't have to worry about any ideas with  g2 - g4  and the move  h3  is so innocuous that White also doesn't get versions where they can create some pressure on the queenside. }
8. Nc3{ It looks slightly weird from the white perspective to spend a tempo ( 7.h3 ) to prevent ... Bg4  and then allow Black to exchange the light-squared bishop via  f5  without gaining the bishop pair or damaging Black's structure. Usually, the simple answer ... Bxd3  is enough for equality in these situations but I want to show a more ambitious approach. }
8. e6{ This move is a little bit risky because Black has to be careful not to get their bishop trapped with  g2 - g4  but there are also a lot of positional advantages. White cannot push  e3 - e4  so easily.  Also, White's queen stays on  d1  which makes it harder to bring their rooks into the game. ( Rd1  is a pretty automatic move in these structures) If White now takes on  f5 , we'll go ...  exf5  and we can potentially build a nice outpost on  e4 . If White really wants to punish us, they have to go for moves like  Be2 , but concretely this doesn't seem to be too dangerous. }
9. cxd5{ This is pretty harmless. Black can just reach a favourable Carlsbad structure with light-squared bishops exchanged. }
9. Bxd3{ A nice reminder that Black can still take on  d3  after having played  8...e6 . That pawn move is always useful. }
10. Qxd3
10. exd5{ Having exchanged light-squared bishop in this structure, is a very nice thing for Black with all of their central pawns on light squares (and the opposite is true for White.) }
11. b4{ The minority attack  b2 - b4 - b5  with the idea to create some weaknesses on the queenside is the only reasonable plan here. }
11. a6{ I think this move fits nice with other lines in our repertoire. Black has no problems to go ... b7 - b5  to stop White from advancing their b-pawn. }
12. a4{ The most logical follow-up. }
12. Qd6{ Bringing the queen to a good square before developing with ... Nbd7 . }( 12...b5? 13.axb5 { is good for White because Black cannot recapture with the a-pawn. } )
13. Bb2( { A clever idea to prepare  b4-b5 .     A)  }13.Ba3 b5! { is the structure that Black wants. White's queenside play is stopped and Black will soon develop their pieces and especially the knights are ready to jump to the light-squared outposts on  e4  and  c4 . } )( {  B)  }13.b5? axb5 { doesn't work for White. Here it is White's unprotected a-rook that poses problems. } )
13. Nbd7{ Now,  a8  is protected and Black is ready to push ... b5 . }( { Don't go }13...Qxb4? 14.Ba3+- { . } )
14. b5{ Otherwise, Black will play ... b5 . }
14. c5{ White should now take on  c5  before Black has the option to play ... c5 - c4 , but in the resulting structure, Black will have decent counterplay with nice outposts on  c4  and  e4 . }
