9. Bxf5
9. exf5{ This is a pawn structure that Black should in general be very happy about. White didn't gain anything from the exchange on  f5  while Black has the open e-file and especially nice control over  e4 . Let's show a sample line. }
10. cxd5{ This seems to be White's best try. White is trying to use the absence of a black e-pawn by increasing the pressure on  d5 . }
10. Nxd5{ Black should not recapture with the pawn on  d5 . That pawn would be isolated and justify White's last moves. }
11. Qb3{ Once again, White has other moves but this is the only move with a concrete idea in mind. White does for the double attack against  b7  and  d5  (which is a positional threat because Black would be forced to remain with an isolated pawn on  d5 . }
11. Nxc3( { The easy solution. }11...Nb6 { is also playable. } )
12. bxc3( 12.Qxb7 { is just a horrible in-between move. Black can even just retreat with the knight. }12...Nd5 13.Qxa8 Qd7-+ { and }-- ...Nb6 { traps the queen. } )
12. Qc7{ with a decent position. Black will play ... Nd7 - f6 - e4 , bring the rooks into the middle and sooner or later ... c5  or ... f4  might be ideas. }
