4. g6
5. Bd3{ I think it makes sense to use this move order in this chapter to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice is starting with }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { in this chapter. }{ Because of our rule, that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about the move order that White uses.  Lines, where White combines  Bd3  with an early  Nbd2 , will transpose to lines from the  Nbd2 chapter . } )
5. Bg7
6. O-O( { The moves }6.O-O { and }6.Nc3 { can easily transpose to each other. However, there are some instances where White has some independent ideas.  Especially in the lines where White combines any of these moves with an early  h2-h3 , there are some big differences. }{ Short version:  If White delays castling, we shouldn't go for ... Bf5  because White can exchange and start an attack on the g-file. However, with  Nc3  played instead, Black can create dynamic play with ... dxc4  followed by ... b5  and the knight on  c3  might reduce White's options since the move ... b5 - b4  will come with tempo. } )
6. O-O{ As usual, we just castle first before doing anything else. }
7. h3{ White stops ... Bg4 . }( 7.Nc3 { transposes to the  Champion's Choice . } )
7. Bf5{ This is an old idea in the Schlechter Slav and people used to play in very different positions and under much worse circumstances.     This looks like a good variation to show the different ideas behind this move.  With White already castled, Black doesn't have to worry about any ideas with  g2 - g4  and the move  h3  is so innocuous that White also doesn't get versions where they can create some pressure on the queenside. }
8. Bxf5
8. gxf5{ This structure is very reliable for Black. They create a nice outpost on  e4  and they can make use of the g-file with ... Kh8  and ... Rg8  while White doesn't gain anything concrete in exchange.  The doubled pawns are definitely not weak (Black will play ... e6 ). White can rely on 'general' statements that Black's king should not be totally safe with the open g-file or that doubled pawns are supposed to be less flexible than undoubled pawns but it is hard to create a plan based on these factors.     Because the structure is so closed, there are dozens of different setups that White can choose.  See the following lines starting from this position more as sample lines on how Black can coordinate their pieces. }
9. Qb3{ Protecting  c4  and pressuring  b7 . On low depths, this is the top engine move. White wants to provoke Black to go ... Qb6 , so that later on, they will be able to expand on the queenside with the  c4 - c5 -tempo.  It is a pretty deep idea but nothing special to worry about. }( { A mistimed }9.c5 { gets usually answered with }9...b6! { . If White is forced to exchange on  b6 , they just give up a lot of central control. }10.b4 { is what White wants to play but once again Black can just undermine White's structure. }10...a5! { and White is no longer able to keep the queenside structure.   }{ This shows why it might be a smart idea to play  c4 - c5  with tempo- this might give White just enough time to stabilize their structure. } )
9. Qb6( 9...Qc7?! { looks logical but }10.Qc2! { is White's idea. White attacks  f5  and  e6  }11.cxd5! { forces Black to recapture with the knight as the  c6 -pawn is pinned. } )
10. Nc3{ Pressuring  d5 . }
10. e6{ Our normal stabilising move. }
11. c5{ Not forced but the only concrete idea to look at. If White plays it slow, Black can just easily finish their development with ... Nbd7  and bring the rooks to the center. }
11. Qc7{ Black should just drop back and is now ready to attack White's structure with  ...b6 . }( 11...Qxb3 12.axb3 { would only strengthen White's structure. } )
12. Qc2{ White in response should make sure that they have  b2 - b4  in response to ... b6 . A very instructive queen dance! }
12. b6
13. b4
13. a5{ The typical way of undermining White's structure. If White would be forced to take on  a5  or on  b6 , Black would just remain with the better structure. White still has to try to stabilize an outpost on  c5 . }
14. Na4{ The logical move to achieve that. }( 14.Bd2 axb4 15.Na4 Nbd7 { is just another move order to reach the same variation. } )
14. Nbd7{ During the next moves, both sides simply fight with all they have over the control of the  c5 -square. }
15. Bd2{ White is threatening to take twice on  b6  and then simply win the a-pawn. So Black has to release the tension now. }( 15.cxb6 { transposes to  16.axb6  after }15...Nxb6 16.Nxb6 Qxb6 17.Bd2 axb4 { . } )
15. axb4
16. cxb6{ This is one way to continue. The ideas, however, are always the same.  Black just wants to continue to fight for the  c5 -square. }
16. Nxb6
17. Nxb6
17. Qxb6
18. Rfb1{ White just plans to win the  b4 -pawn with the bishop and simultaneously control  c5  with this. But Black is just in time with their moves. }
18. Rfc8{ Anticipating  Bxb4  and preparing ... c5 . }
19. Bxb4
19. Ne4{ The most principled move to prepare ...  c5 . }
20. a4{ White has different moves but Black's counterplay looks always similar. This move is the one that poses the most concrete problems as White immediately uses their outside passed pawn. }( 20.Nd2?! c5! { just works for Black. } )
20. Qa6{ Avoiding all discoveries, so ... c5  is now on the table. }
21. Ra2{ Unpinning the d-pawn but Black still has resources to mobilize the c-pawn. }
21. Qc4{ A nice move. White can take on  c4  but Black will be able to push ... c5  afterwards with enough counterplay. }
