14. cxd5
14. exd5( { In the last trainable, we saw my main recommendation }14...cxd5 { which is certainly the more positional way of playing. }{ Nevertheless, ... exd5  is an idea to keep in mind.  With the double isolated f-pawns, Black's position looks a little bit shaky. The exact evaluation of this way of recapturing might obviously depend on several factors and concrete variations but I think it is worth mentioning that the idea itself is worth considering.  Black keeps one more pawn blocking the queenside while Black gets more open files to operate on the kingside and the center. This concrete position should even be a very reasonable version for White as the knight on  e2  stops all ... f5 - f4  ideas and even  Ne2 - g3  might be possible because ... Ne4xg3   f2xg3  might be good for White in some positions with the clear targets on the f-file.  Nevertheless, even this good version for White is playable for Black For example: } )
15. Rc2{ A typical manoeuvring move in these positions if you analyse these positions with an engine. }( { If White plays }15.Ng3 { you have to make sure that you are not forced to take on  g3 . Instead, you should just protect the  f5 -pawn, for example with }15...Qf6 { . } )
15. Bf8{ Once again, I am a fan of this manoeuvre. Sometimes, Black plays the even slower manoeuvre ... Bg7 - f6 - e7 - d6  or  g7 - f6 - d8 - c7  to land the bishop on the long diagonal towards White's kingside.  In these positions, it is usually not about a single tempo. }
16. Ne5{ A good moment for White to occupy the outpost. Black should not take to keep the bishop on  b2  buried. }
16. Qe8{ Leaving the way open for the bishop to go to  d6 . Black's next moves are typical moves to direct the pieces towards the kingside. ... Bd6 , potentially ... Qe7  and ... f6 , ... Rg7 , ... Rag8 . }( { To be honest, in this very concrete position, SF shows a ridiculous computer line with }17.f3 Ng5 18.Kh1 { sacrificing the  e3 -pawn if Black goes }18...f6 { and potentially  ...Qxe3 , which apparently leads to a +0.5 position for White. I don't think that this takes anything away from the ... exd5  move in general! } )
