5. Bd3{ I think it makes sense to use this move order in this chapter to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice is starting with }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { in this chapter. }{ Because of our rule, that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about the move order that White uses.  Lines, where White combines  Bd3  with an early  Nbd2 , will transpose to lines from the  Nbd2 chapter . } )
5. Bg7
6. Nc3
6. O-O
7. h3{ Directed mainly against ideas with ... Bg4  but as long as White hasn't castled, it also prevents Black from playing ... Bf5 . Luckily for us,  h3  is also the loss of a tempo in a dynamic fight so we have every reason to play dynamic moves! }
7. dxc4{ This move, followed by ... b5  and later on ... c5  is a well-known plan from some Slav mainlines. }( { It would also be fair to make the case that the Grünfeld move }7...c5!? { should work nicely against White's slow setup. Most likely, White will just finish development and Black can reach some kind of IQP position. Something like }8.O-O cxd4 9.exd4 dxc4 10.Bxc4 Nc6 { looks definitely playable for Black. } )( { However, the advantage of }7...dxc4 { is that you can also play it against  Be2  instead of  Bd3  as well. } )( 7...Bf5? 8.Bxf5 gxf5 9.g4! { is a strong idea to make use of the move  h2-h3  if White hasn't castled. We shouldn't allow this kind of kingside attack. } )
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ A typical move to win space on the queenside and force the bishop to choose one diagonal. }
9. Bd3{ White takes control over  e4  but if Black is careful, this won't matter and the bishop might indeed be not particularly greatly placed on  d3 . }
9. Bb7{ With the bishop on  d3 , it is much easier to go  e3 - e4 . If the bishop is anywhere else, Black can always play ... b4  and get rid of the only defender. }( 9...Nbd7 10.O-O a6?! 11.e4! { is a move sequence illustrating the purpose of  9.Bd3 . Black can't play  ...b4  and threaten to win  e4 : }11...c5? 12.e5 { makes matters only worse because Black has no good square for the knight and  Bd3-e4  is coming. } )
10. e4
10. c5{ is a typical reaction. With the bishop on  b7 , White once again has to be careful with the  e4 -pawn. }
11. d5{ Relatively best but White is already worse. }( 11.e5 Nfd7 { and White's center will collapse while Black's pieces will be on great squares. } )
11. c4{ We force White's pieces with the next moves to less influential squares and then we'll break open the center! }
12. Bc2
12. b4
13. Na4{ The best square. At least, White has options to play  Na4 - c5 . }
13. e6( { A strong move. White is not well prepared to meet Black's dynamics in the center. For example,     A)  }14.dxe6 Qxd1+ 15.Bxd1 Nxe4 16.exf7 Rxf7 { gives Black massive activity. } )( {  B)  }14.Nc5 { is trickier but not really better. }14...exd5! { works.     B1)  }15.Nxb7?! Qb6 { will just regain the piece. }16.e5 Ne4! { is attacking  f2  as well.     B2)  }15.e5 Ne4 16.Bxe4 dxe4 { allows similar motifs. }17.Qxd8 Rxd8 18.Nxb7 Rd7! { . We have a pretty forcing line but Black is coming out on top. For example, }19.Nc5 exf3 { is forced but good. }20.Nxd7!? Nxd7! { . Black is borderline winning despite being an exchange down. After }21.gxf3 Nxe5 { , }{ we are ready to invade on  f3  or  d3  while White is completely underdeveloped and suffers from their pawn weaknesses. } )
