11. Qc7{ Black just supports the c-pawn and also ... e5  gets prepared. }( 11...c5 12.dxc5 Nxc5 13.Nxb5! { is the tactical idea behind  11.Qc2 . To be honest, even here things are not so clear because Black has very nice piece play after something like }13...Nfe4 { but it is unnecessary to allow it. } )
12. b4{ White has to do something about Black's idea to push ...  c5 . }
12. e5{ Black just executes the other break in the position. Black should be reasonably fine here.  Usually, both plans, to go ... exd4  or to go ... e4  at the right moment, are options to consider. In this specific scenario, it will be hard for Black to push  e5 - e4  under good circumstances simply because Black doesn't get enough control over the  e4 -square.  Even with a rook on  e8 , the pawn will be attacked three times after  Nf3 - d2  and Black neither has ... Bf5  nor  Qe7  to protect it. But even with 'only' the ... exd4  plan in hand, we have enough counterplay. }
13. Bb2{ Let's just look at a sample line to see how the game can develop. This move makes a lot of sense because it increases the pressure towards  e5  and it forces Black to take on  d4  immediately. }( { A move like }13.Rd1 { might have allowed Black to keep the tension a while longer with a move like }13...Bb7 { . } )
13. exd4( { Don't go }13...Bb7?? 14.dxe5 Nxe5 15.Nxe5 Qxe5 16.Nxb5! { . } )
14. Nxd4
14. Bb7{ Black just continues their development. If the  c6 -pawn disappears from the board, most likely because of ... c6 - c5 , the bishop will be nicely placed. }
15. a4{ White should put pressure on  b5  to make it as hard as possible for Black to go ... c5 .  Preventing ... c5  by other means is hardly possible. }( { For example }15.Nb3 Rfc8 16.Rac1 c5= { is very comfortable for Black. } )
15. Rac8{ A good square for the rook. It lines up to prepare ... c5  and annoys the queen on  c2 . }
16. Rfc1{ Still building up on the c-file. }
16. Qb8{ A very nice move to prepare ... c5 . The queen on  c2  feels slightly awkward now opposed to the rook on  c8 . It should be mentioned that Black also has other ways to improve their position even if White can avoid ... c5  in the short-term: ... Rfd8 , ... Ne5 , ... Qd6  might give Black active piece play if White stays passive just to stop the ... c5  move. }
