[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) Anti-Champion: Bd3 Sidelines"]
[Black "6.Nc3 & 7.h3 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3{ I think it makes sense to use this move order in this chapter to cover all of White's setups where they play  Bf1 - d3 . }( { The most popular move order in practice is starting with }5.Nc3 { but as there are also setups where White postpones this knight move, it makes sense to start with }5.Bd3 { in this chapter. }{ Because of our rule, that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  first against all setups with  e2 - e3 , we don't really care about the move order that White uses.  Lines, where White combines  Bd3  with an early  Nbd2 , will transpose to lines from the  Nbd2 chapter . } )
5. Bg7
6. Nc3
6. O-O
7. h3{ Directed mainly against ideas with ... Bg4  but as long as White hasn't castled, it also prevents Black from playing ... Bf5 . Luckily for us,  h3  is also the loss of a tempo in a dynamic fight so we have every reason to play dynamic moves! }
7. dxc4{ This move, followed by ... b5  and later on ... c5  is a well-known plan from some Slav mainlines. }( { It would also be fair to make the case that the Grünfeld move }7...c5!? { should work nicely against White's slow setup. Most likely, White will just finish development and Black can reach some kind of IQP position. Something like }8.O-O cxd4 9.exd4 dxc4 10.Bxc4 Nc6 { looks definitely playable for Black. } )( { However, the advantage of }7...dxc4 { is that you can also play it against  Be2  instead of  Bd3  as well. } )( 7...Bf5? 8.Bxf5 gxf5 9.g4! { is a strong idea to make use of the move  h2-h3  if White hasn't castled. We shouldn't allow this kind of kingside attack. } )
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ A typical move to win space on the queenside and force the bishop to choose one diagonal. }
9. Be2{ I think this is the best move. White doesn't support  e3 - e4  ideas but as Black has a simple antidote against  9.Bd3 , there is nothing White can do about it. }
9. Nbd7
10. O-O
10. a6{ Now, ... c5  is prepared and if White goes  b2 - b4  to stop that, Black can attack White's structure with ... a5 . }
11. b4{ The most direct move to stop ... c5  but it allows ... a5 . }
11. a5
12. bxa5{ Immediately giving up on the blockade on the queenside is usually not a good idea. }
12. Qxa5{ Winning back the pawn and attacking  c3 . }( { The immediate }12...b4 { is similar. } )
13. Bb2{ Relatively best but still very easy for Black. }
13. b4{ White didn't do anything and Black is ready to push ... c5 . }
14. Nb1{ A sad necessity. }
14. c5{ And Black has a very comfortable game. }
