10. a6{ Now, ... c5  is prepared and if White goes  b2 - b4  to stop that, Black can attack White's structure with ... a5 . }
11. b4{ The most direct move to stop ... c5  but it allows ... a5 . }
11. a5
12. Ba3{ Clearly the best move. White wants to keep the blockade of Black's queenside pawns. }( 12.a3 { with the same idea doesn't work. }12...axb4 13.axb4 Rxa1-+ { . } )
12. Re8{ White did a decent job of blocking our queenside but we just continue with the next typical pawn break that we usually have in the Grünfeld Slav. Sooner or later, Black will push ... e5 . }
13. Rc1{ This looks natural but White should better make sure that their queenside construction with  b4  and  Ba3  stays stable. }( 13.Qc2?! e5! { would already be possible.   }{ Here, Black can just increase the pressure towards  b4  until White is forced to release the tension. } )
13. Bf8{ A nice move to prepare both ... e6  and ... e5 . }( 13...e5? { doesn't work yet. }14.dxe5! Nxe5 15.Qxd8! { Black's rook is overloaded protecting  e5  and  d8 . }15...Nxf3+ 16.Bxf3 Rxd8 17.Bxc6 { just loses the whole queenside. } )
14. Qb3{ This is maybe not a super important line but it illustrates how Black is trying to increase the pressure on White's queenside construction. }
14. e6( 14...e5 { , the move I highlighted in the last comments, is also possible here. I just want to use this trainable to illustrate another idea. } )
15. Rfd1{ I guess, we can agree that this is a logical move. }
15. Qe7{ Attacking and pinning the pawn on  b4 ! }
16. Rb1
16. Nd5{ This illustrates another typical move to increase the pressure on  b4 . Now, White is forced to take on  d5  if they don't want to give away the  b4 -pawn. }
17. Nxd5
17. exd5{ Here Black is comfortably better because they still have the pressure on White's queenside and their pawn structure improved massively with the last exchange. }
