11. b4{ The most direct move to stop ... c5  but it allows ... a5 . }
11. a5
12. Ba3{ Clearly the best move. White wants to keep the blockade of Black's queenside pawns. }( 12.a3 { with the same idea doesn't work. }12...axb4 13.axb4 Rxa1-+ { . } )
12. Re8{ White did a decent job of blocking our queenside but we just continue with the next typical pawn break that we usually have in the Grünfeld Slav. Sooner or later, Black will push ... e5 . }
13. Qb3{ This move stabilises  b4  but it also keeps an eye towards  f7 , so Black should be a little bit careful. }
13. a4{ In some regards, it is a pity that we have to play this move here after all these lines we have just seen where Black got good positions by increasing the pressure on the  b4 -pawn. However, now we are able to play ... e5  soon which is obviously also a good idea. }( 13...e5? { is a logical idea but doesn't really work tactically. }14.bxa5 Qxa5 15.Bb4 Qb6 { Well, Black's position is strategically fine but }16.Ng5!+- { is a very embarrassing way of exploiting  f7 . Black simply has no moves to defend it. } )
14. Qc2{ This move doesn't stop Black from playing ... e5 . }
14. e5
15. Rac1{ Let's use this variation to talk about some key things for the ... e5 - e4  idea. }( { If White takes on }e5 { with }15.dxe5 Nxe5 { , it might indeed be useful for Black not to have played  ...Bb7 . (Compare this to the next line.) }{ In this structure, Black will happily develop the bishop rather to  f5  or  e6  than to  b7 . } )
15. e4( { Black could also play }15...exd4 16.Nxd4 Bb7 { with similar structures that we have already seen. }{ Black should be fine. However, I think it is important to also learn some things about this ambitious idea of going ... e4 . } )
16. Nd2{ Attacking  e4 . }
16. Qe7{ Protecting  e4 . What are positional factors in these positions?      1.  Black's pawn on  e4  gives us a great space advantage in the center and on the kingside. Note that White has currently absolutely no defenders on that side of the board. So, even though Black's setup might not look like the most threatening attacking position at first glance - Black has no open files and their pieces are not targeting anything on the kingside yet - this can easily change in the next moves. Black's space advantage makes sure that we can play moves like ... Qg5  or ... Qh4  without being harassed by White's pieces.      2.  The pawn on  h3  makes the attacking prospects even more attractive as this makes White's structure less flexible on that side of the board. White can always consider playing  f2 - f3  in these positions, but because  e3  is so weak in this specific case, this is hardly feasible. So White has to create counterplay on the queenside or the center.   c6  looks like a weak pawn but it is Black's only weakness (if you want to call it like that) and Black has easy moves to protect it (... Bb7 / Bd7 ; ... Rc8 ).     White only has one pawn break to increase the pressure ( d4 - d5 ) and open more files for their pieces. If White plays it slow, Black will just take control over the  d5 -square and after that, White might realise that they have absolutely no way to create any counterplay on that side of the board. }
17. d5{ Absolutely necessary! White exchanges the 'weak' pawn on  c6  but at least creates some dynamics in the center. }( { A slow move like }17.Rfd1 { just allows Black to stop all White's counterplay and then slowly but surely destroy White on the kingside. }17...Nb6! { Controlling  d5 . }18.Bb2 Bf5 { Just developing. }19.a3 Rac8 { Overprotecting the only weak point in Black's camp and on the next moves, Black might just put a knight on  d5  to stop  d4 - d5  altogether and just slowly bring the pieces to the kingside: ... h5 , ... Qg5 , ...  Bh6  (or even ... Bf8 - d6 ). White is overall just strategically lost. } )
17. Nxd5{ It makes sense to take with the knight to open up the bishop on  b7 . }
18. Nxd5
18. cxd5
19. Bxb5( { White created dynamics in the center, so Black cannot simply freely attack on the kingside and rely on the fact that White has no counterplay on the other side. Indeed, White will win a pawn now.    (In this regard,   }20.Bc6 { is the bigger threat than }20.Bxa4 { as the  d5 -pawn gives Black a lot of stability in the center.)     It should be noted that Black even has enough counterplay if White takes on  a4  and creates two connected passers on the queenside. Those two pawns need a looong time before they start creating any real threats and in any case, they don't help White defend against the kingside attack. } )
19. Rb8{ A nice move!  a4  was hanging anyways but the real deal was White's idea to win the  d5 -pawn with the double attack  Bc6 . }
20. Bxa4{ Let's only take a closer look at this move as a sample line because from my perspective it is the most natural way of winning the  a4 -pawn. Other ways include White taking on  a4  with the queen which moves the queen even further away from the action.  In any case, Black's counterplay is based on many typical factors: We would like to play ... Ne5  from where the knight controls many squares, ... Qg5  is a move to create threats on the kingside, ideas with ... Bxh3  are ways in the air and ... d5 - d4  might slightly disrupt White's solid pawn structure.     Also, the  b4 -pawn is just loosely protected by the weird bishop on  a3  and White also has to be careful not to lose the  a2 -pawn with some ... Ra8 -ideas. }( {  A)  }20.Qxa4 { is similar but risky. }20...Rd8! { with the same ideas as in the mainline and here }21.Bxd7 { makes much less sense because }21...Bxd7 { comes here with tempo. With perfect play, White seems to survive but nothing more. } )( {  B)  }20.Bc6 { can here be answered with }20...Bb7 { White can win the  a4 -pawn here as well, but even with light-squared bishops exchanged, Black has full compensation. }21.Bxb7 Rxb7 22.Qxa4 Ne5! -- ...Ra7 { or }...Nd3 { will be annoying. } )
20. Rd8{ Unpinning the knight, so that ... Ne5  can happen. }
21. Bxd7{ White should simplify into a drawish endgame. }( { Something like }21.Rfd1 Ne5 { with ideas like ... Nd3 , ... Qg5 , ... Bxh3  can easily become horrible for White. } )
21. Bxd7
22. Bb2
22. Bxb2
23. Qxb2
23. Qxb4{ With a good position for Black. If White exchanges queens, we can start to attack the poor guy on  a2 . }
