13. a4{ In some regards, it is a pity that we have to play this move here after all these lines we have just seen where Black got good positions by increasing the pressure on the  b4 -pawn. However, now we are able to play ... e5  soon which is obviously also a good idea. }( 13...e5? { is a logical idea but doesn't really work tactically. }14.bxa5 Qxa5 15.Bb4 Qb6 { Well, Black's position is strategically fine but }16.Ng5!+- { is a very embarrassing way of exploiting  f7 . Black simply has no moves to defend it. } )
14. Qd1{ This manoeuvre  Qd1 - b3 - d1  looks bizarre but White provoked ... a4  and here Black has to play ... Bb7  to prepare ... e5  where the bishop is not ideally placed if it is not completely clear that Black can go ... c5  later on. }
14. Bb7{ Protecting the queen on  d8  with the rook on  a8 , so that ... e5  is possible on the next move. }( 14...e5? { doesn't work right away, once again because of the overloaded rook on  e8 . }15.dxe5 Nxe5 16.Qxd8 Nxf3+ 17.Bxf3 Rxd8 18.Bxc6+-  )
15. Ne5{ The most interesting move to look at, simply because it doesn't allow Black to play ... e5 . }( { Something like }15.Rc1 e5! { is just fine. } )
15. e6( { This prepares both   }16...Nd5 { as well as }16...Nxe5 { , followed by  17...Nd5 . }{ White cannot really keep control over  e5  for much longer. } )
16. f4{ The only real try to keep  e5  under control. }
16. Nd5{ If White plants a knight on  e4  and supports it with both the  d4 - and  f4 -pawn, we usually have to exchange it, followed by ... f6 , or we have to play ... f6  without exchanging on  e5  first. This move prepares both and the attack against  c3  and  e3  comes with tempo. }
17. Qd2( { White can also play }17.Qd3 { , Black's plan stays the same. } )( 17.Nxd5?! exd5⩱ { only improves Black's structure and gives White long-term problems along the e-file. } )
17. Nxe5
18. fxe5
18. f6{ Always the move we want to play in these situations. Activating the butcher and breaking up White's pawn structure is always key in these situations! }
19. exf6
19. Bxf6{ Black has a great position and can proceed with ... e5  or ... Bg5 . }
