[White "19) Champion's Choice: Bd3 7...Bg4 Mainline"]
[Black "Introduction 6.Bd3 Mainline"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Bd3
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Bg4( { This developing setup is the most principled setup White can choose in the e3-universe when it comes to center control. White develops both knights to their most active squares as well as the white-squared bishop.    In some ways, this setup not only looks similar to the   }6.Be2 { variation, but even better. Why is the more passive bishop move often recommended by authors nowadays, though?    One answer:   }7...Bg4! {    Although White wins the bishop pair, Black gets very good play. In the main variation }8.h3 Bxf3 9.Qxf3 e6 { , it looks at first sight as if White inevitably simply has a small advantage due to the two bishops in a position with otherwise not very many imbalances.    }{ On closer inspection, however, you realize that White is having trouble finding a plan. An early  e3 - e4 , fails either because the  d4 -pawn hangs or White runs into the casual counter ... e6 - e5 .     On the queenside, White has several options to become active with the pawns, but as we will see, Black stands ready to counter.     Black, on the other hand, usually has the much more active option of playing his levers. Because of the opponent's bishop pair, we should not blindly open the position, but especially the setup }-- 10...Nbd7 { , }-- 11...Re8 { , }-- 12...e5 { is often insanely effective to threaten }-- ...e4 { , give the opponent a pawn weakness with }...exd4 { or activate the pieces after }13.dxe5 Nxe5 { and get the bishop pair back.    In the main variations, White often uses a lot of tempi to invalidate this plan but this gives Black other possibilities to initiate active play.    While in other chapters in this course the right setups for Black were often only discovered over decades, the move   }7...Bg4 { has always been the choice of great players, with good results. On the black side of the variation, you can find - among many other super grandmasters - the names of the World Champions Smyslov, Petrosian, Karpov or Carlsen.    It is a much-discussed variation and White can try different move sequences, so I have covered it in great detail in this chapter. } )
