[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. Qb3{ This is a typical move in the Slav if Black develops their light-squared bishop too early. But when Black can spoil White's pawn structure, this is positionally very risky. }
8. Bxf3{ We should use the possibility to ruin White's kingside structure. }
9. Qxb7{ This is a horrible intermediate move. Black can just save their bishop on  f3  and trap White's queen on  a8  after ... Qd7  and ... Na6 . }
9. dxc4{ I think this is the easiest way. Black gets rid of all in-between moves with  c4xd5 . }( 9...Be4 { also wins. Just to give an example. }10.Bxe4 dxe4 11.Qxa8 Qd7! { Always the key move in this line. }12.d5 { Attacking  c6  avoids the immediate ... Na6  but it doesn't save the game. }12...Rc8! {  ...Na6  is not threatened yet because of  dxc6 , but a move like ... cxd5  is a threat, followed by ... Na6 . There is not much White can do about it. }13.Na4!? { Going for tricks with  Nc5  but White can simply not create a stable setup to get the queen out of the danger zone. }13...cxd5! 14.Nc5 Qc7 { White is losing material. If they try to keep the knight on  c5  with }15.b4 Ng4! { wins the rook on  a1  as Black has a mate threat against  h2 . } )
10. Bxc4( 10.Qxa8? { This move order is even worse because if Black plays }10...Qd7 { , they do not only threaten  ...Na6 , but also  ...Qg4  with mate. }11.Bxc4 Qg4! 12.g3 Qh3-+ { and White gets mated. } )
10. Bd5{ White will be left with very few tricks left once their queen is stuck on  a8 . }
11. Bxd5
11. Nxd5
12. Qxa8
12. Qd7{ The typical move to keep White's queen trapped on  a8 . ... Na6  or ... Nc6  are coming. }
13. Nxd5
13. cxd5{  ...Na6  or ... Nc6  will win White's queen. }
