7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. Qb3{ This is a typical move in the Slav if Black develops their light-squared bishop too early. But when Black can spoil White's pawn structure, this is positionally very risky. }
8. Bxf3{ We should use the possibility to ruin White's kingside structure. }
9. gxf3
9. b6( { Black can also play }9...Qd7 { to keep all the pawns protected. I don't think it makes a huge difference.  In either case, White's doubled f-pawns should be reason enough to have a decent version of this variation. }{ White has slightly more central control with a pawn on  f3  but their weak king should be the bigger factor. } )
10. Rd1{ This was played in the two games I found with this position and - as we will see in the main line - the rook is ideally placed on  d1  as it supports the d-pawn and also makes it harder for Black to accomplish their ... e5  or ... c5  break. }
10. e6{ Black has to play this move to stabilise their center and allow moves like ... Nbd7  or ... Ne8 . }( { We have a position that is similar to the variations after   }8.h3 { but with a decent version for Black as the main difference is that White's f-pawns are doubled - and because of this, the line has barely been played. It should be enough to show a sample line of how the game might continue. } )
11. Bf1{ A decent move to stabilise the kingside. }
11. Ne8( { Black can also play typical moves like }11...Nbd7 { first, }{ but I like the idea to bring the knight to  d6 . This puts pressure on the  c4 -pawn and with the white queen on  b3 , White cannot simply play  b2 - b3 . } )
12. e4{ This move does at least try to prove the pawn on  f3  useful. }( { I think that after a move like }12.f4 Nd6 { Black should be very happy as White does not achieve much by taking on  d5 , but otherwise, Black always has the option to win the bishop pair back by taking on  c4 . } )
12. dxe4
13. Nxe4{ Playing with ideas like  Bg5  to use the piece activity. }( 13.fxe4?! Bxd4 14.Ne2 e5∓ { is pretty solid for Black. } )
13. Nf6( 13...Bxd4? 14.Bg5! { gives White nice compensation. } )
14. Bg5
14. Nbd7{ Black is extremely solid and can unpin their knight on the next move by moving the queen. This should be absolutely fine for Black. }
