1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. cxd5{ If White wants to play an exchange Slav structure, this is the right move order. Once Black has played ... e6 , we will happily play ... exd5 . }
8. cxd5
9. Qb3{ Once again, White can try this typical move as a response to ... Bg4 . But Black can just easily take on  f3  and enjoy their position. }
9. Bxf3
10. Qxb7( 10.gxf3?! Qd7 { makes even less sense than   }8.Qb3 Bxf3 9.gxf3 { as the absence of c-pawns helps Black who can now go   }11...Nc6 { . } )
10. Bxg2
11. Kxg2
11. Nbd7{ White can grab a pawn on  d5 , but their king is open and the pieces are underdeveloped. Black has fantastic compensation. }
12. Nxd5
12. Nc5{ This allows some exchanges but activates Black's pieces efficiently. }( 12...e5 { opening the position is also typical and good. } )
13. dxc5
13. Nxd5( { Some discoveries such as   }14...Nf4+ { or }14...Nxe3+ { are in the air. } )( { White's best move is }14.e4 { when the open king from White and the misplaced pieces should always give enough counterplay. For example }14...Nb4!? { ( }14...Nf6 { to attack  e4  or even }14...Nc7 { seem to be good enough as well.)     A)    }15.Qxb4 Qxd3 { and Black clearly has compensation.     B)    }15.Be2 { keeps the bishops but loses another tempo. E.g. }15...Rb8 16.Qxa7 Nc2 17.Rb1 Qd4! { Black has nice counterplay for the sacrificed pawns. } )
