[White "19) Champion's Choice: Bd3 7...Bg4 Mainline"]
[Black "8.h3 & 10.cxd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. h3{ White's main move to get the bishop pair immediately. }
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. cxd5
10. exd5( { Now that this option is possible, I prefer it over the move }10...cxd5 { . }{ In the resulting imbalanced Carlsbad Structure, Black should be okay with the open e-file and the control over the  e4 -square. White's typical plan in this structure is the minority attack with  b2 - b4 - b5  to create weaknesses on Black's queenside, so let's look at a sample line of how Black can play against this plan. } )
11. b4
11. a6{ A good inclusion. White needs at least two more moves before they will be able to play  b4 - b5 . }
12. a4{ The typical follow-up. }
12. Nbd7{ Black develops naturally and is now also ready to go ... b5 . }
13. b5{ If White wants to play this break, they have to do it now. }( 13.Bd2 { A slow move like this, allows }13...b5! { Black is getting ready to put the knight on  b6  and potentially  c4 . White has no clear path forward. } )
13. axb5
14. Ba3{ The only justification of the last move. White unpins the  a4 -pawn with tempo. }( 14.axb5 Rxa1-+ { is of course not possible. } )
14. Re8
15. axb5( { If White is able to continue with   }16.bxc6 { , they will have a small advantage with easy play against the pawn. However, Black has a very dynamic answer as White is not fully coordinated. } )
15. c5{ Black is ready to play ... cxd4 . }
16. dxc5{ Taking on  c5  is running into concrete problems. }( 16.Bxc5? { is running in similar problems after }16...Rxa1 17.Rxa1 Nxc5 18.dxc5 Ne4! { -+ winning material outright. } )
16. Ne5{ Activating the knight first. }
17. Qe2
17. d4( { Even stronger than }17...Nxd3?! 18.Qxd3 Ne4⇆ { that wins back material with a good position and should also be reason enough for White not to take on  c5 . } )( 17...d4 { just wins material. For example }18.Ne4 Nxd3 ( { ( }18...dxe3 { is also strong.) } )19.Nxf6+? { Bad but the only move that is at least trying to hang on to the material. }19...Bxf6 20.Qxd3 dxe3-+ { The pressure against  a1  and  a3 , combined with ideas like ... e2  and ... Bc3  after an exchange of queens is too much to deal with. } )
