1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. h3{ White's main move to get the bishop pair immediately. }
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. Qe2{ A very flexible move. The queen is slightly vulnerable on  f3  - for example after ... e6 - e5 . }
10. Nbd7( { Now, White should transpose to  10.Rd1  by playing }11.Rd1 { . } )
11. a4{ This line just illustrates how easy Black can get a good position if White does nothing against Black's breaks. }
11. c5( { One of two breaks that work excellently if White does nothing about them.    }11...e5 { works as well.     A)  }12.a5 { If White just ignores the action in the center, Black's typical plan is ... Re8 , ... exd4 , ... Nf8 , ... Ne6  and counterplay against the pawn on  d4 . With our light-squared bishop still on  c8  in this structure, it would make the plan stronger to go ... e4  as the bishop could be an important attacking piece against White's kingside. }12...Re8 { Threatening to take on  d4 . }13.Qc2 exd4 { A typical plan to create a weakness on  d4 . }14.exd4 Nf8!⇆ { The knight goes to  e6 , creating pressure against  d4 . ... Re8 - e7 - d7  is an interesting follow-up to increase the pressure even more. }{     B)    }12.cxd5 { Trying to create a pawn weakness in Black's camp is possible but not too frightening. }12...Nxd5 { Allowing the exchange of knights to open up the  g7 -bishop. }13.Nxd5 cxd5 14.dxe5 Nxe5⇆ { We should never be afraid of this version of an IQP. All our pieces are active, we have pressure against the queenside and we can also prepare  d5-d4  if we want to. } )
12. cxd5
12. Nxd5{ There is nothing wrong to recapture with the pawn but, usually, it is not a bad idea to take with the  f6 -knight first to open the butcher. White can play with or against an isolated pawn but both versions are completely fine for Black. }( { For example:     A)  }13.Bc4 N5b6 14.Bb3 cxd4 15.exd4 Nf6= { and Black has a nice position against White's IQP. We have full control over  d5 . } )( {  B)  }13.Nxd5 exd5 14.dxc5 Nxc5⇆ { when Black has the more active pieces and pressure against White's queenside. } )
