9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. Rd1{ This is the main move. White overprotects the  d4 -pawn, this might help if they want to go for  e3 - e4 . But it is also an important move to fight against Black's breaks with ... c5  and ... e5 . }
10. Nbd7{ Typical: Black wants to play ... e6 - e5 . In the best case without allowing  c4xd5 . }
11. a4{ White just wants to win space on the queenside. If Black plays ... a5  himself, the position on that flank is very much defined. }
11. a5{ In general, it makes a lot of sense for Black to stop White's pawn on  a4  in this structure. Otherwise, White can just play  a4 - a5  and will enjoy a nice space advantage and a flexible structure on the queenside.  Now, White has a hole on  b4  and White might even play a manoeuvre like ... Nd7 - b8 - a6 - b4  to take advantage of it. }
12. b3{ A typical follow-up. White wants to play  Bc1 - a3  which does not only come with tempo but it is also preparing  b3 - b4  - the only way to break open the queenside. }
12. Re8{ A good move, anticipating  Ba3 . }
13. Ba3{ The normal follow-up. }( 13.Rb1 { was played once to prepare it. However, }13...Bf8 { potentially followed by }-- ...Bb4 { makes it very hard for White to achieve the  b3 - b4  break under good circumstances. } )
13. Bf8{ A very nice move. Black is fighting for the  b4 -square and if it leads to the exchange of bishops, we will happily take it. }( 13...Nb8!? { is another interesting move. If the knight reaches  a6 , the queenside will be very hard to crack.  White can try to open up the queenside with a quick  b3-b4  but Black can also try to use the newly opened files for their own play. For example }14.b4!? axb4 15.Bxb4 Na6 { Black can develop active piece play on the queenside. }16.Ba3 Qa5! { Black's pieces can develop with tempo. }17.Rdc1 Nb4 { Another tempo move as White shouldn't give up one of the bishops. }18.Be2 { After so many tempo moves, it shouldn't be too surprising that Black can strike back in the center under good circumstances. }18...e5 { is possible but also }18...dxc4!? 19.Bxc4 Nbd5⇆ { is asking some questions.  c3  is hanging, taking on  d5  improves Black's structure, }20.Bb2 { allows }20...Qb4 { . Black just gets an active position. } )
14. Bb2{ Played in two games by Mamedyarov and Illescas Cordoba. White might claim that by provoking the bishop back to  f8 , Black has a harder time striking back in the center.  However, there are other juicy squares available. }
14. Bb4{ A nice outpost for the bishop. Black can just continue with flexible moves such as ... Rc8  and ... Qe7 . }( {  A)  If White plays }15.Na2 { , we will just go }15...Bd6 { . } )( {  B)  }15.e4 { is still running into }15...e5! { . } )
