10. Nbd7{ Typical: Black wants to play ... e6 - e5 . In the best case without allowing  c4xd5 . }
11. Bf1{ Another prophylactic move to anticipate Black's ... e5  break. }( { In most cases, it can transpose to lines with }11.b3 { or }11.Bd2 { . } )
11. Re8{ Black just follows the normal setup. }
12. Qe2( { Maybe the only real independent try. }12.b3 { and }12.Bd2 { transpose and }12.e4 e5! { does once again work well for Black. For example }13.cxd5 exd4 14.dxc6 Ne5 15.Qe2 Nxc6 { with a very active position. } )
12. a6( { The same setup that we also play against }12.b3 { or }12.Bd2 { . White can - and maybe should - still transpose to those variations. } )
13. Qc2{ This was once played by Seirawan but Black should get a good version of the  11.Qe2  &  12.Qc2 -variation. }( 13.b3 { or }13.Bd2 { transpose to other variations and for example }13.a4 a5!? { should be a decent version of the  11.a4 a5 -variation. }{ True, we lost a tempo by moving our a-pawn twice but White's move in the meantime -  Qe2  and  Bf1  - are not really active moves. } )
13. Rc8{ Black is ready to strike back with ... c5  in the center. }
