14. Bb3{ Anticipating an IQP after ... exd4 . In those structures, Black would love to play ... Nb6  with tempo to put a knight on  d5  next. }( { For example if White starts their queenside play with the immediate }14.b4 { , Black can happily play }14...exd4 15.exd4 Nb6 16.Bb3 Nbd5⇆ { with a decent IQP. } )
14. e4{ This closes the position. In the next moves, Black can try to use the  d5 -square as an outpost and play ... Bg7 - f8 - d6  to bring the bishop on a more active diagonal.  We might even bring the bishop to  c7  and the queen to  d6  if White gives us the time. White doesn't have too many ways to get active.  It makes sense to anticipate  f2 - f3  by playing ... Re7  just to have the possibility to double on the e-file as soon as possible. }( 14...exd4 { is also an idea to play against an IQP but White might be able to keep some pressure. }15.exd4 Nb6 16.Bg5⩲ { It is not so easy to put a blockading knight on  d5  without weakening the kingside with something like ... h6  and ... g5 . } )
