[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) Champion's Choice: Bd3 7...Bg4 Mainline"]
[Black "8.h3 & 10.Rd1: The Overprotecting 11.b3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. h3{ White's main move to get the bishop pair immediately. }
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. Rd1{ This is the main move. White overprotects the  d4 -pawn, this might help if they want to go for  e3 - e4 . But it is also an important move to fight against Black's breaks with ... c5  and ... e5 . }
10. Nbd7{ Typical: Black wants to play ... e6 - e5 . In the best case without allowing  c4xd5 . }
11. b3{ Typically, White wants to develop their bishop to  b2  with this move but it also allows to recapture on  c4  with the pawn if Black ever takes. }
11. Re8{ A good square for the rook. If White goes  cxd5 , our rook will be on the open file immediately and also ... e6 - e5  is supported. }
12. Bf1{ This move is an indication that White has played the move  b2 - b3  mainly to support the  c4 -pawn and is not sure yet if the bishop should be placed on  d2  or  b2 . If you ask me,  b2  looks like the more active square but, for example, if Black wants to play a setup with ... Qa5 , it makes sense to have the option of putting the bishop on  d2  instead. }( { Compared to the line   }11.Bd2 Re8 12.Bf1 { , it is now less attractive to take on  c4  as White can recapture with the pawn.    }{ On the other hand is  12.Bf1  a typical reaction to the move ... Qd8 - e7  to anticipate ... e5 . Here, Black can consider more useful moves than the queen maneuver. } )
12. a6{ The typical, flexible response. }
13. Bd2( { This move is less active than }13.Bb2 { . However, the bishop is also less exposed than on  b2  if Black goes for ... b5  with ideas to open up the b-file. White's setup here, spending a tempo on  b2 - b3  and spending several tempi to place the bishops on  f1  and - usually -  e1 , is claiming that none of Black's breaks does do White really any harm and White will conceptually just ignore Black's counterplay until White has coordinated their pieces.     I would recommend to go for ... e6 - e5 - e4  which uses White's loss in time to grab as much space as possible in the center - especially attractive as White's queen is still on  f3 . } )
13. Bf8{ A nice move to anticipate the structure after ... e6 - e5 - e4 . The bishop won't do much anymore on  g7  and instead  d6  is a nice central square, that also looks towards White's kingside. If White anticipates Black's idea by moving the queen from  f3 , Black also keeps other options like ... Ne4  and ... f5  with some kind of Stonewall.     In those structures, the bishop will also be nicely placed on  d6 . }( { There is not too much wrong with the immediate }13...e5 14.cxd5 e4! 15.Qe2 cxd5 { but Black should play ... Bg7 - f8 - d6  anyway in the next moves. } )( { Let's show a sample line how play could continue after }13...Bf8 { . } )
14. Be1{ A typical move for White after having played  Bc1 - d2 . }
14. Bd6{ Placing the bishop on its ideal square before finally committing to ... e6 - e5 . Now, Black is finally ideally set up to go for the pawn break. }
15. Rac1{ This allows Black's main idea. }
15. e5{ Black will play ... e5 - e4  next when the space advantage in the center compensates for the lack of the bishop pair. }
