15. Qe2{ This moves anticipates ... e5  but it is one more passive move and gives the  e4 -square in Black's hands. We can put a knight on  e4  at some point, play ... f5  and start to play on the kingside.  However, we can also just play flexible and try to play ... e6 - e5  at a good moment. }
15. Qe7{ Black continues to play flexible moves that slightly improve the position bit by bit. }( 15...e5?! 16.cxd5!± { does give White now simply the better structure because we don't have the in-between move  ...e5-e4 . For example }16...cxd5 17.dxe5 { and Black has problems with the  d5 -pawn. } )
16. Rac1{ Not really a move with a concrete plan in mind but let's just use it to illustrate Black's ideas. }
16. h5{ Black grabs space on the kingside which is useful in all kinds of scenarios. }
17. g3{ White wants to put the bishop on  g2  which would stop ... Nf6 - e4  and maybe White could play  e3 - e4  at some point themselves. }( { After other moves such as }17.a4 { Black could play }17...e5! { under much better circumstances than before. We might still get an isolated pawn but our activity on the kingside will compensate for that.    For example }18.cxd5 cxd5 19.dxe5 Qxe5 { and Black is already threatening mate on  h2  and }20.g3 h4! { would put White's kingside under a lot of pressure. } )
17. Ne4{ A nice move. The knight stands dominant on  e4  and Black will support it with ... f5 , followed by an initiative on the kingside. }
