13. Rac1( { The main move. }13.Bf1 { transposes to the last trainable.    This position will be reached if White always plays the most popular moves against our repertoire after  7...Bg4  and it looks quite logical. }{ White placed the bishop actively on  b2  and hasn't spent a tempo yet on the queen on  f3  or the bishop on  d3 . Black should just respond flexible and, as we will see, there are some options to create counterplay on the kingside. } )
13. Qe7( { I give this as main recommendation. Now, Black is threatening   }14...e5 { . Ideally, White wants to have }15.cxd5 { in response and after }15...cxd5 16.dxe5 { White can try to play against the isolated pawn on  d5 . However, Black has }15...e4 { as with the queen on  e7 , we have enough control over the  e4 -square.   }{ If White knows what they are doing, the following moves are usually a lot of manoeuvring. I think it makes sense to play ... h5  next to win some space on the kingside - that is always useful.  After that, we put our  a8 -rook on  c8  or  d8 . Both squares are better than  a8  but where the rook is better placed is not 100% clear to say. If Black wants to play rather for ... c5 , the rook is better on  c8 .     If Black, however, wants to continue with ... e5 , with or without ... dxc4  included, the rook might be better placed on  d8  as the d-file is more likely to open up.  Let me give you some sample lines: } )
14. Bf1( { This move or }14.Qe2 { are usually played to anticipate  ...e5 . } )
14. h5{ Following the general setup. }
15. Rc2{ Let's use this as sample move as it was played in two of three games in the given position. White understands that the position is pretty slow and just gives their rooks more options to navigate on the central files. }
15. Rad8{ With White anticipating Black's ... c5  and ... e5  break, these positions are usually about patience. With the bishop on  f1 , I guess we can make a point that ... c5  might be less likely to achieve as  c4  is nicely overprotected if we try to play on the c-file. }( { Nevertheless, }15...Rac8 { leads to a position played by  Mamedyarov - Caruana  that ended in a draw, so this is certainly also not wrong. } )
16. Qe2
16. Nh7{ A lot of games in this structure were maneuvering games for 30 moves where more or less nothing happened. }( { A typical move is also }16...Nb6 { , trying to provoke White to do something with the c-pawn but White will usually just leave the c-pawn where it is.  However, there are ways to make progress in these positions! I like the idea to just play  ...f5  and reach some kind of Stonewall formation that promises counterplay on the kingside. } )
17. Qe1{ Yep, the top engine move. White cannot really do something active either. }
17. f5{ An ambitious move. Black can try to build up on the kingside.  ... h4 , ... Bh6 , putting knights on  f6  and  g5 , king in the corner and major pieces behind the kingside pawns is a - slightly risky - but completely valid idea. }
