13. Qe7( { I give this as main recommendation. Now, Black is threatening   }14...e5 { . Ideally, White wants to have }15.cxd5 { in response and after }15...cxd5 16.dxe5 { White can try to play against the isolated pawn on  d5 . However, Black has }15...e4 { as with the queen on  e7 , we have enough control over the  e4 -square.   }{ If White knows what they are doing, the following moves are usually a lot of manoeuvring. I think it makes sense to play ... h5  next to win some space on the kingside - that is always useful.  After that, we put our  a8 -rook on  c8  or  d8 . Both squares are better than  a8  but where the rook is better placed is not 100% clear to say. If Black wants to play rather for ... c5 , the rook is better on  c8 .     If Black, however, wants to continue with ... e5 , with or without ... dxc4  included, the rook might be better placed on  d8  as the d-file is more likely to open up.  Let me give you some sample lines: } )
14. Qe2( { Besides }14.Bf1 { , the second typical response. } )
14. h5{ Following the setup. }
15. Bb1{ Let's go with this move here as a sample line because it is a typical manoeuvre that some White players play just to move the bishop out of the way in the center. }
15. Rad8{ The same setup as before. }
16. Rc2{ Let's go with this as main move, It is the engine's top choice. White stays flexible with the rooks. }
16. h4( { A typical move, fixing the kingside pawns.    Striking back in the center should always be considered but White is often exactly hoping for that to get some small pressure.     A)  }16...dxc4 17.bxc4 e5 18.d5! { seems playable for Black but is slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }16...e5?! 17.cxd5 cxd5 18.dxe5⩲ { is giving White the better structure in a decent version. } )
17. Rcd2
17. Bh6{ Activating the bishop and also stopping  e3 - e4  - even though this is rarely a threat in these positions. }
18. a4
18. Nh7{ followed by ... f5  and a similar setup as in the last trainable. }
