[White "19) Champion's Choice: Bd3 7...Bg4 Mainline"]
[Black "8.h3 & 10.Rd1: Queen's Escape 11.Qe2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Bd3
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3{ This is the main line. White shows no interest in fighting against ... Bg4  and claims that the two bishops will be a factor.  However, the resulting positions are considered very well playable for Black, because White's queen on  f3  (after ... Bxf3  and  Qxf3 ) and White's bishop on  d3  are slightly awkwardly placed - often due to ideas connected with ... e6 - e5  after ... Nbd7 . White often spends a lot of tempi in this line moving these two pieces to safer squares. This should give us enough time to gain some positional advantages of our own. }
7. Bg4
8. h3{ White's main move to get the bishop pair immediately. }
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. e6{ That is Black's general idea in this setup. They place their pawns solidly on the light squares. White has the bishops long-term, but Black has a very solid structure.    How good or bad is this position and how do you play it? We have a closed position with not a single open file so far. So, to make progress, pawn play is extremely important. In this regard, White has different ideas to play with their pawns:      1)  White can take on  d5 . This will most likely lead to exchange Slav or Carlsbad structures. In rare cases ... Nxd5  to enter Grünfeld territory might be possible.     2)  White can play  e3 - e4  to open up the center.      3)  White can play on the queenside with  b2 - b4 - b5 .     4)  Risky, but maybe interesting to look at, are positions where White also expands on the kingside with  g2 - g4 . Especially if one side has the bishop pair, they can often get away with 'weakening' their king this way, as the punishment would have to include opening up files at some point, which is exactly what the side with the two bishops wants. }
10. Rd1{ This is the main move. White overprotects the  d4 -pawn, this might help if they want to go for  e3 - e4 . But it is also an important move to fight against Black's breaks with ... c5  and ... e5 . }
10. Nbd7{ Typical: Black wants to play ... e6 - e5 . In the best case without allowing  c4xd5 . }
11. Qe2
11. Re8{ The typical setup for Black. }( { Black is ready to go   }12...e5 { now as the in-between move }13.cxd5 { is asking for trouble on the e-file after }13...exd4! { . } )( { Let's just mention that }11...Qe7 { is less precise. Black has fewer opportunities to respond to }12.e4! { A nice detail is that }12...dxe4 13.Bxe4! { might lead to a small advantage for White. If White recaptures with the knight, Black can at least exchange one pair of minor pieces that should make Black's space disadvantage less important. But after taking with the bishop, Black should not try to simplify. }13...Nxe4?! 14.Nxe4 { is a fantastic idea. White can give up their light-squared bishop, but  c4 - c5  and  Ne4 - d6  is an idea. }14...Nf6?! ( { ( }14...c5?! 15.Bg5 f6 16.Be3+- { is also ugly.) } )15.Bg5 { is winning material. }15...h6 { The only move to get rid of the pin. }16.Nxf6+ Bxf6 17.Bxh6± { with a nice extra pawn. } )
12. e4{ This is still running into the typical response. }
12. e5( 12...dxe4!? { is here also possible. }13.Bxe4!? { This is often the more challenging reply because it often stops simplification. However, here Black can take the bishop. }13...Nxe4 14.Nxe4 { Now,  Nd6  and  Bg5  are typical ideas that are often annoying for Black. But here, we can solve both problems. }14...Nf6! { Preparing to exchange the  e4 -knight while also stopping  Ne4 - d6 . The best move to keep pieces on the board might be }15.Nc3 { with maybe the slightest of pressures. The main try, however, to punish  ...Nd7-f6  is }15.Bg5 { .  16.Qf3  is a threat but Black can concretely play }15...h6! 16.Nxf6+ Bxf6 17.Bxh6 Bxd4! { . This is okay for Black. } )
13. dxe5{ White has nothing better. }
13. dxe4{ This wins back the pawn in the most convincing way. }( 13...Nxe4 14.f4!? { looks very double-edged but the engine evaluates this as better for White. No reason to allow that! } )
14. exf6
14. exd3
15. Qxd3
15. Nxf6{ with an equal position. }
