[White "20) 6.Be2 The Chinese Recipe 7...b6!?"]
[Black "Introduction 6.Be2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O( { This variation with   }6.Be2 { is one of White's absolute main lines. Sam Shankland, Christof Sielecki and Daniel Barrish all give this move as their recommendation in their white repertoires. } )( { My recommendation is the move }7...b6!? { .    }{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (even though not particularly successful).     Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.     This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }{ When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me (see below).     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ...  Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )( { Why not a more popular move? Let's just quickly discuss other options:     A)  }7...Bg4 { , }7...Bf5 { and }7...Nbd7 { are all running in the same idea and can even transpose to exactly the same position! }8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Qb3 { is always an annoying idea. }{ After the bishop moves,  b7  is a problem and ... b7 - b6  would create some light-squared weaknesses and after the knight move, the knight is just misplaced on  d7  as it belongs on  c6  in these Exchange positions. }{ The fact that }9...Nb8!? { or   }9...Bc8!? { might be the best moves after that, tells you all you need to know. } )( {  B)  }7...a6!? { would lead to Kamsky's favourite variation. He has decent success with it but the simple answer }8.a4 { was always enough to discourage me. Either, White plays }-- 9.a5 { next and wins even more space or Black plays   }8...a5 { when the queenside is blocked and White can try to squeeze some boring positions, for example with }9.cxd5 cxd5 10.b3 { . } )( {  C)  }7...dxc4 { is a very interesting move that was actually my choice when I played the Schlechter as a backup weapon a few years ago.    After }8.Bxc4 { , Black typically chooses one of the following two moves:     C1)  I have no big trust in the move }8...b5 { - which is a line that's been played quite a bit. We will get a position similar to  these  but pretty much a full tempo down as White hasn't played  h2 - h3 . One full tempo is quite a lot in these structures as it is often a matter of tempi whether Black can play ... c6 - c5  or if it is White who can win over the control of the  c5 -square. }{     C2)  However, }8...Bg4!? { was always one of my personal favourites. The main line goes }9.h3 Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nbd7 11.Rd1 e5! { This break is Black's main idea. }12.d5! e4!? { with a pawn sacrifice that has been actually been played hundreds of times. Christof Sielecki found nice solutions in the established mainlines but modern engines show actually plenty of new ideas along the line. Certainly interesting stuff as well! } )( {  D)  }7...e6!? { was my initial idea to recommend in this line. The move is similar  7...b6 . Next, we want to play }-- ...b6 { , }-- ...Bb7 { , }-- ...Nbd7 { , }-- ...Qe7 { and }-- ...c5 { . A very easy plan and a very practical choice if it would work every time. However, the line   }8.b3 b6 9.Ba3 Re8 10.Qc2 Nbd7 11.Ne5 { , followed by }-- 12.f4 -- 13.Bf3 { and putting rooks on  c1  and  d1  - Shankland's recommendation - is actually hard to answer. White is creating an ideal setup against ... c6 - c5  and if we can't achieve that, we are in quite a bit of trouble. Nevertheless, if you are not expecting your opponents to know every single sideline of a Lifetime Repertoire, this is certainly a very decent option! }{ Let's just mention that we avoid Shankland's problematic line after   }7...b6 8.b3 { because we can play }8...Ne4! { and don't give White any hopes for a transposition. } )
