7. O-O{ In this position, Black has played a lot of different moves. I'll go with the rather rare move 7... b6  in this repertoire.  The reasons why I neglected other, more popular, moves can be found  here . }
7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. Bd2( { This looks very slow and with no concrete idea in mind. White might try to play  9.cxd5  on the next move and reach the variation }8.cxd5 cxd5 9.Bd2 { without giving Black the option to go }...Ne4 { . Nevertheless, this line is not critical at all, so let's just look at the most important ideas. } )
8. e6{ A strong move. From here on, Black will always be ready to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn and keep the game imbalanced. }
9. Rc1{ This is White's usual follow-up when they play  8.Bd2 . }
9. Bb7{ The main move for Black. }
10. cxd5{ This leads to a typical structure but in a good version for Black. }
10. exd5
11. Ne5{ Otherwise, Black just plays ... Nbd7 , ... Qe7  and ... c5  will come soon. }
11. Ne8{ A nice manoeuvre for the knight. It goes to  d6  where it will have great influence.  Look at the model game Stupak - Li -  see here  - where Black won a brilliancy from this position. }( { ( }11...c5 { is also typical and playable.) } )
