8. cxd5{ If White wants to take on  d5 , it makes sense to do it right away before Black is able to play ... e7 - e6  and is ready to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }
8. cxd5
9. b4{ This does just gain space and restricts Black's queenside quite a bit with a potential  b4 - b5  in the position. }
9. Nc6{ I think it makes a lot of sense to develop this knight before it might be boxed in with  b4 - b5 . White now has to decide whether they want to push  b4 - b5  or not. }
10. b5{ This might be White's most testing continuation as we will see some forcing lines. But it is a double-edged sword.  By playing  b4 - b5  so early, Black gets quick access to the  c4 -square. }
10. Na5{ If Black can just play ... Bb7 , ... Rc8  and ... Nc4 , White might very much regret weakening the  c4 -square by moving their b-pawn. So White should do something rather concrete. }
11. Ne5{ A logical move in all these lines (and it also protects  c4 ), but Black has enough moves to fight for that square. }
11. Bb7{ A logical move in general, but by protecting the  d5 -square, we also prepare ... Nd7  to exchange the knight on  e5 . }
12. Ba3{ Still, clearly the best square for the bishop. }
12. Nd7{ Black is fighting for the  c4 -square and if White does nothing tactical, they will just play ... Rc8 , the knights will be exchanged one way or the other, and then ...  Nc4  follows. }( 12...Rc8 13.Rc1 { might promise White a small advantage. } )
13. Nc6{ This is the start of a very concrete operation and maybe White's best shot at an advantage. }
13. Nxc6
14. Nxd5{ That was the idea.  c6  and  e7  are under attack. }( 14.bxc6? Bxc6 { with an extra pawn for Black was not the idea. } )
14. Na5{ Unfortunately, we are forced to go back to the a-file. }
15. Bxe7{ This leads to a position with rook and two pawns versus knight and bishop. }
15. Qe8( { The engine prefers }15...Qb8 { which leads to similar positions.    Black keeps one additional minor on the board - which is usually what you should do when you play with two minor pieces versus rooks and two pawns - but Black doesn't get such a nice control over the light squares as we do after  15...Qe8 . }16.Bxf8 Bxf8 17.Bf3 { This position would most likely occur to create some pressure. Black isn't in horrible shape but I can imagine you have to be an engine to stop the slow advance of White's central pawns. } )
16. Bxf8
16. Bxd5{ Black is going for a blockade on the light squares. }
17. Bxg7
17. Kxg7{ Let's stop this trainable here. White might objectively be slightly better but we have some clear strategic goals:     - Stopping White from advancing in the center. We might even play ... f5  to control the  e4 -square.     - Besides that, we'll go ... Nf6 . Our queen goes to  e6  where it puts pressure on the  a2 -pawn.     - Our knight on  a5  is a pretty sad piece for now. ... Na5 - b7 - d6  looks like a good manoeuvre to bring the horsie back into the game and to a square where it also controls the  e4 -square.     Once we are coordinated, we might slowly but surely start a kingside attack with ... h5 - h4 - h3 . Typically, the side with the rook and the two pawns doesn't mind exchanging pieces because the additional number of pawns gets especially important in the endgame.  In comparison, we are happy to decide the game in the middle game which usually means that a kingside attack is not that stupid.     Let's just mention that endgames will become much more attractive if we are somehow able to win the  a2 -pawn. }
