9. b4{ This does just gain space and restricts Black's queenside quite a bit with a potential  b4 - b5  in the position. }
9. Nc6{ I think it makes a lot of sense to develop this knight before it might be boxed in with  b4 - b5 . White now has to decide whether they want to push  b4 - b5  or not. }
10. Qb3{ If White doesn't push  b4 - b5 , this seems to be the most flexible move. White keeps an eye on the  d5 -square which makes it hard for Black to regroup the knight from  f6 . }( 10.Ba3 { Aiming for  b4-b5  but keeping some flexibility. }10...a6!? { does not literally stop the b-pawn advance but it takes away much of its strength. Suddenly, the bishop on  a3  is not so greatly placed. } )
10. Bb7( { This move keeps more pieces on the board than }11...Bg4 { . The resulting positions are not super exciting but we have equality by move 11 and all pieces on the board. In the next moves, we can try to provoke White to go  b4 - b5  when we can play ... Na5  and get potential access to the  c4 -square.  We can move our queen out of the way and play ... Rfc8  to have both rooks on the queenside where currently most of the action is happening. ... e6  is a nice move to just stabilise the structure.  An active approach for Black is to go ... Ne4 , inviting White to take the knight and change the structure.     Let's not analyse every single move that White can play here but let's look at a potential direction in which the game could develop. } )( 10...Bg4 11.h3 Bxf3 12.Bxf3 e6 { is an extremely solid alternative. Objectively, Black is definitely okay here as well. } )
11. a4{ This is the most flexible move for White, just winning some space on the queenside. }
11. Ne4( { Not the only move but inviting White to change the structure. }11...a6 { to stop  b4 - b5  is also playable here. } )
12. Bb2{  A)  Taking the  e4 -knight gives Black typical active counterplay with the ... e5 -pawn break. }( 12.Nxe4 dxe4 13.Nd2 e5! { The typical reaction. White cannot allow to open up the center so the best sequence is }14.d5! Ne7 { . }{ Black will win the  d5 -pawn. White will have compensation, still, this line is nothing White should go for. } )( {  B)  }12.Ba3 e5! { is also giving Black massive counterplay.  13.Nxe4  leads to the last variation and }13.dxe5?! Nxe5 { is annoying because Black threatens both the  c3 -knight on the long diagonal but also ... Nd2  is a threat after the exchange of the  f3 - and  e5 -knights. } )( {  C)  Taking the d-pawn is indeed possible but Black has several ways to create nice counterplay. }12.Nxd5 Nxd4 { is one option. }13.Nxe7+ { The only move to keep the extra pawn. }13...Qxe7 14.exd4 Rac8 { Black has massive compensation.  ...Rc3  is coming. }15.Bb2?! { prevents  ...Rc3  but doesn't stop Black from invading. }15...Nd2! { A nice move to win the bishop pair and invade in White's position. }16.Nxd2 Qxe2 { White won't enjoy their extra pawn very much. } )
12. Qd6( { Attacking the  b4 -pawn. We are happy if White goes }13.b5 { . } )
13. Ba3( 13.b5?! Na5 { followed by }-- ...Rfc8 { gives Black great chances to use the  c4 -square. } )
13. Rfc8{ Black has nicely activated their pieces. }
14. Rac1( 14.b5 { is not winning material because }14...Na5 { is a counterattack against White's queen. } )
14. Qd8{ A nice move. The queen did its job on  d6  - it came with tempo and Black could play ... Rfc8  - but now the queen just drops back and Black would love to put the  e4 .knight on the  d6 -square. }
15. Nxe4{ At some point, White should take the knight. }( { Waiting with some moves like }15.Rfd1 e6 16.h3 { allows Black to play }16...Nd6 { where the knight is perfectly placed, controlling both the  c4 - and the  e4 -square. } )
15. dxe4
16. Nd2
16. e6{ Black just stabilizes the structure and can play ... Ne7 - f5 , ... Bd5  slowly improving the pieces. }
