11. b3{ If White plays without  f2 - f4 , Black just develops in the most straightforward fashion: ... Bb7 , ...  Nd7 , maybe followed by ... Nf6 , ... Rc8 , ... Qd7  and ... Rfd8 . Once all the pieces are on good squares, Black can even start thinking about winning space on the kingside with ... h5 - h4  and maybe even ... g5 - g4 .     The following variation is more a sample variation than anything else. }
11. Bb7
12. a4
12. Nd7{ Challenging the knight on  e5 . }
13. Nc4( 13.Nxd7 Qxd7 { would be super pleasant for Black. they can be the first one on the c-file and ... e5  looks like a reasonable move in the next future. } )
