8. Ne5{ Usually, White takes on  d5  before playing  Ne5 . Let's see why. }
8. Bb7
9. f4{ This is White's most direct move order to establish a knight on  e5 . }
9. dxc4{ White is aiming at a very stable structure at a center if they are playing this  Ne5 / f4  setup. That is the reason why they often prefer to take on  d5  first before doing so.  So, in general, it makes a lot of sense for Black to go for a pretty open center with lots of dynamics. }
10. Bxc4
10. e6{ Black just stabilizes the structure by controlling  d5  and  f5  and will continue with preparing the ... c5 -break. }
11. b4{ White can try to use their b-pawn to stop us from ... c5  but this gives us other resources for counterplay like ... a5  or ... Nd5 . }
11. Nbd7{ A flexible move, preparing ... c5 . Let's just see how the game can proceed if White continues to fight against this break. }
12. Rb1( { Stopping }12...c5 { because }13.bxc5 { pins the b-pawn. However, Black has other ways to create counterplay. } )( { Similar is }12.Qb3 { . }12...b5! { A typical move to dislodge the  c4 -bishop, followed by attacking the  b4 -pawn. }13.Be2 a5 { Black gets good counterplay on the queenside. } )
12. Nd5{ A motif to remember. Black attacks  c3  and  b4  while after  Nxd5 , Black can increase their influence in the center. }( { For example }13.Nxd5 exd5 14.Bd3 Nxe5 { We have to get rid of this knight - either by exchanging it and playing ... f6  afterwards or by playing ... f6  immediately. Here, the first option looks safer. }15.dxe5 f6! { with strong counterplay. } )
