8. b3{ A slow move but not without venom. White does not only prepare  Bc1 - b2  but more so  Bc1 - a3  where the bishop is creating some pressure on the  a3 - f8  diagonal. }
8. Ne4{ This move has been played by Bu Xiangzhi and Wang Hao. }( 8...Bb7 9.Ba3 { promises White some pressure, while   }8...e6 { transposes to the variations that made me give up my plans to recommend  7...e6  in this repertoire -  see here  after }9.Ba3 { . } )( { With }8...Ne4 { , Black opens up the bishop on  g7  - which is rarely a bad idea - and just plans to take on  c3  and play ... e6  afterwards.    Then, we will get our desired structure without getting into concrete trouble. } )
9. Bb2( { The logical follow-up. }9.Nxe4 dxe4 10.Nd2 c5 { is just a dream for Black. } )
9. Nxc3
10. Bxc3
10. e6{ Black reaches their typical structure. The plan is usually clear: ... Bb7 , ...  Nd7 , ... Qe7  and ... c5 . Let's look at some lines that just illustrate some positional ideas. }
11. b4{ This looks like White's most direct move. White fights against ... c5  but also simply wins space on the queenside. At some point, White might even consider  c4 - c5  just to stop Black from putting their pawn there! }
11. Ba6{ A nice move. Black puts pressure on  c4  but also anticipates White's idea to go  c4 - c5 .     This change in the pawn structure is much less attractive for White when the light-squared bishops come off as with all their pawns on dark squares, the  Be2  is the 'good bishop' while it is vice versa for Black. }
12. cxd5{ White takes on  d5  and hopes for pressure on the c-file in the resulting position. }
12. exd5( { Going for the imbalance. }12...Bxe2 { is also possible. } )
13. a4
13. Bxe2
14. Qxe2
14. Nd7{ Black's play is very simple: ... Qe7 , ... Rc8 , stabilizing on the queenside and then starting the counterplay in the center and the kingside. }
15. Rac1{ I will just give a sample line. }
15. Rc8
16. h3{ White has several slow moves. Key is that  b4 - b5  will in most cases be answered with ... c5 ! }
16. Qe7{ So far, everything is according to plan. }
17. b5
17. c5{ This usually leads to a position with hanging pawns when White takes on  c5 . They shouldn't allow Black to ... c5 - c4  with a protected passer on the c-file. }
18. Qb2( { A small trick, planning to answer   }18...c4 { with }19.Bb4 { . } )
18. Rfe8{ Now ... c5 - c4  is a positional threat. }
19. dxc5
19. Bxc3
20. Rxc3
20. bxc5{ This hanging pawn positions promise Black active counterplay.     Usually, Black plays in the center or on the kingside, but in this concrete structure with the pawns on  a4 / b5 , it makes also a lot of sense to prepare ... a6  and weaken White's pawn structure. (We should make sure that White cannot answer ... a6  with  b5 - b6  however!) }
