11. Ba6{ A nice move. Black puts pressure on  c4  but also anticipates White's idea to go  c4 - c5 .     This change in the pawn structure is much less attractive for White when the light-squared bishops come off as with all their pawns on dark squares, the  Be2  is the 'good bishop' while it is vice versa for Black. }
12. Qb3( { A reasonable move to keep the structure. }12.b5 Bb7 { is something that Black happily provokes. Black has the easier time playing  ...c5  and }13.bxc6 Nxc6 { only develops the Black pieces. } )
12. Nd7
13. a4{ The most aggressive move on the queenside. Against slower moves, our counterplay looks similar. }
13. Rc8{ Black just continues with normal moves. and ... c5  is already in the air. }
14. Rfd1{ White should take the ... c5 -idea seriously. }( 14.a5?! c5!⩱ { already works for Black. For example: }15.axb6 Bxc4 16.Bxc4 dxc4 17.Qxc4?? cxd4-+  )
14. dxc4{ A very nice move. It is worth remembering that even in the resulting position, Black can still continue to prepare ... c5  and ... e5  with good prospects. }( 14...Qe7? { would be part of our setup but just has a tactical issue. }15.b5 Bb7 16.bxc6 Bxc6 17.Bb4!+- { and White wins material. } )
15. Bxc4
15. Bxc4
16. Qxc4
16. Qe7{ Now the queen can go where she is supposed to be and Black's next move is ... e5 . }
17. Rac1
17. e5{ Black has nothing to complain about. }
