1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O{ In this position, Black has played a lot of different moves. I'll go with the rather rare move 7... b6  in this repertoire.  The reasons why I neglected other, more popular, moves can be found  here . }
7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. b3{ A slow move but not without venom. White does not only prepare  Bc1 - b2  but more so  Bc1 - a3  where the bishop is creating some pressure on the  a3 - f8  diagonal. }
8. Ne4{ This move has been played by Bu Xiangzhi and Wang Hao. }( 8...Bb7 9.Ba3 { promises White some pressure, while   }8...e6 { transposes to the variations that made me give up my plans to recommend  7...e6  in this repertoire -  see here  after }9.Ba3 { . } )( { With }8...Ne4 { , Black opens up the bishop on  g7  - which is rarely a bad idea - and just plans to take on  c3  and play ... e6  afterwards.    Then, we will get our desired structure without getting into concrete trouble. } )
9. Bb2( { The logical follow-up. }9.Nxe4 dxe4 10.Nd2 c5 { is just a dream for Black. } )
9. Nxc3
10. Bxc3
10. e6{ Black reaches their typical structure. The plan is usually clear: ... Bb7 , ...  Nd7 , ... Qe7  and ... c5 . Let's look at some lines that just illustrate some positional ideas. }
11. Qc2{ Another flexible move that keeps the option to continue with  b3 - b4  next. The queen also keeps an eye on  e4  which might be useful if White ever wants to play  e3 - e4 . }
11. Bb7( { A normal move and chosen by Li Chao and Wang Yue. }11...Qe7 { and }11...Nd7 { are also part of our plan. } )
12. b4{ This makes life pretty easy. }
12. dxc4{ Without the pawn on  b3 , White has to recapture with the bishop. The knight on  f3  is not happy about this. }
13. Bxc4
13. c5{ Black can break out immediately. For example: }
14. dxc5
14. Bxc3( { We can also start with }14...Bxf3 { . } )
15. Qxc3
15. Bxf3{ Destroying White's structure. }
16. gxf3
16. bxc5{ The pawn is indirectly protected with ... Qg5 +. With White's weak kingside, Black has a decent game. }
