7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. a4{ This is the move that has been chosen by Carlsen when he was confronted with 7... b6  against Mamedyarov. White just gains space on the queenside and can either push  a4 - a5  at some point or just continue with  b2 - b4 . }( { In that game, Black chose }8...a5 { and even though this is a typical reaction against White's pawn advance, Carlsen showed impressively why this move is not to be recommended. You can find the game  here .    I recommend a pretty dynamic move. } )
8. Ne4{ A move to keep in mind. Black doesn't allow White to expand with  b2 - b4 , they can create imbalances with ... Nxc3  and if White takes on  e4 , Black will win a tempo against the  f3 -knight and can continue with the typical ... c5  and ... e5  breaks. }
9. Nxe4{ Taking on  e4  does usually give us a lot of dynamics because we'll be ready to strike with ... e5  or ... c5  soon. }
9. dxe4
10. Nd2( 10.Ng5 { can transpose after }10...c5 11.Nxe4 { . If White doesn't take, their knight might look pretty awkward on  g5 . } )
10. c5
11. dxc5{ A greedy move. White just grabs a pawn and hopes to get away with it. }
11. Na6{ Black gives White free hand which pawn to take but with White's bad pieces on the last two rows and the powerful  g7 -bishop, Black will always have compensation. }
12. Rb1{ White wants to answer ...  Nxc5  with  b2 - b4 , so Black has to play something different. }
12. bxc5{ The open b-file and d-file will give Black massive compensation. }
13. Nxe4
13. Qb6{ with massive compensation for Black. We will continue with ... Bf5 , ... Rfd8 , ... Rab8  and White's pieces will be horribly cramped. }
