1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O{ In this position, Black has played a lot of different moves. I'll go with the rather rare move 7... b6  in this repertoire.  The reasons why I neglected other, more popular, moves can be found  here . }
7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. a4{ This is the move that has been chosen by Carlsen when he was confronted with 7... b6  against Mamedyarov. White just gains space on the queenside and can either push  a4 - a5  at some point or just continue with  b2 - b4 . }( { In that game, Black chose }8...a5 { and even though this is a typical reaction against White's pawn advance, Carlsen showed impressively why this move is not to be recommended. You can find the game  here .    I recommend a pretty dynamic move. } )
8. Ne4{ A move to keep in mind. Black doesn't allow White to expand with  b2 - b4 , they can create imbalances with ... Nxc3  and if White takes on  e4 , Black will win a tempo against the  f3 -knight and can continue with the typical ... c5  and ... e5  breaks. }
9. Nd2{ This is one of the engine's top moves. White forces Black to make a decision.  If Black takes on  c3 , which is the principled move to weaken White's pawn structure, White's knight supports both  c3 - c4  as well as  e3 - e4  at some point and also  Be2 - f3  is an idea. }
9. Nxc3{ Black weakens White's structure. }
10. bxc3
10. Ba6{ A typical idea in this line. Black increases the pressure on  c4  and even if White takes on  d5 , the bishop is nicely positioned to fight for the  c4 -square. }
11. e4{ This is White's most confrontational move. If White plays it slow, Black will easily equalise with ideas like ... dxc4 , followed by ... c5 . }
11. dxc4{ A solid choice. Black just takes and plays ... c5  with decent counterplay in the center.      I just want to mention that ... e5  is a really typical move in these positions. Usually, these explosive moves work well with our bishop on  g7 .     Here, White has a very concrete way of dealing with this, using the  Be2 - f3  resource to create problems on the long diagonal. }( 11...e5 12.dxe5 Bxe5 13.exd5 cxd5 14.Bf3! { and it will not be easy for Black to get rid of this unpleasant pin. }{ White might continue with  Re1 ,  Nf1 - e3  and increase pressure on  d5 . } )
12. Qc2{ This is a smart idea. White anticipates Black's idea to go ... c5  and protects the  c3 -pawn in order to answer this with  d4 - d5 . }
12. c5( { Black should still strike in the center. }12...b5?! { keeps the pawn but you better don't ask the  a6 -bishop for its opinion. } )
13. d5{ That was the white idea. }
13. e6{ Important! Black has to destroy White's strong center even if it slightly weakens their own pawn structure. }
14. dxe6
14. fxe6
15. Nxc4( { Better than to play }15.Bxc4 { . After }15...Qf6 { , }{ White has to play a passive move to protect  c3 . } )
15. Nc6{ This prepares ... Qf6  without running into  e4 - e5 . }
16. Be3{ White should just develop. }
16. Qf6{ Forcing White to deal with the  c3 -pawn. }
17. Rac1
17. g5{ I like this move. Black fights for space on the kingside and can create their counterplay on that side of the board.  Typical moves are ... Qg6 , maybe ... h5  and ... g4 , ... Bxc4 , followed by ... Ne5  might be an idea. }
