8. Ne4{ A move to keep in mind. Black doesn't allow White to expand with  b2 - b4 , they can create imbalances with ... Nxc3  and if White takes on  e4 , Black will win a tempo against the  f3 -knight and can continue with the typical ... c5  and ... e5  breaks. }
9. a5{ White puts immediate pressure on Black's queenside. }
9. Nxc3
10. bxc3
10. Ba6{ An interesting strategic idea. If White takes on  d5 , Black will enjoy their structure very much with the big hole on  c4  in White's position.  Besides that, Black just wants to finish their development with ... Nd7  and maybe ... Qc7 , at some point Black will be ready to strike back in the center with ... e5  or ... c5 . Maybe with two exchanges on  c4  and potentially with ... b6 - b5  included. }
11. h4{ A principled idea. If White reacts to the pressure against  c4 , Black gets the structures that they is aiming for. With this move, White just ignores the pawn and tries to soften Black's kingside with  h4 - h5  and then most likely  hxg6 . }
11. Qc7{ White's h-pawn advance is not really the start of a massive kingside attack, so we should just develop our pieces. This move is necessary in order to do so.  Black has to stabilize their queenside pawns. }( {  A)  }11...Bxc4?! 12.Bxc4 dxc4 13.axb6± { leaves Black with a horrible structure. } )( {  B)  The immediate }11...Nd7?! { allows the strong exchange sacrifice }12.axb6 axb6 13.Rxa6 Rxa6 14.cxd5 { followed by  dxc6 . } )
12. h5{ White shows a good feeling for symmetry by putting the second outside pawn on the fifth rank. White has some interesting attacking ideas combined with this move like  hxg6 ,  Ng5 ,  f4 ,  Qe1 ,  Qh4  and mate on  h7  :-) However, with principled play in the center, Black shouldn't be too worried. }
12. Nd7{ Black should just develop their pieces as soon as possible. This knight might defend from  f6 . }
13. hxg6{ Let's look at White's most straightforward attacking plan. I think White's setup only makes sense if they continue to play aggressively. }
13. hxg6
14. Ng5{ Currently, White doesn't have too many pieces in the attack, but  f4  and  Qe1 - h4  can change that quickly. }
14. Nf6
15. Qe1{ This is the most flexible move order. Black's defensive ideas can be explained like this:  Black should try to get rid of the annoying  g5 -knight before White's queen lands on  h4 . Black has three moves to do this: ... Ne4 , ... Nh7  and ... Bh6 .     ... Ne4  is the safest option as it doesn't give away the bishop pair and doesn't force Black's king to stand on the h-file for one move. }( { However, the main drawback is that the immediate   }15...Ne4 { allows }16.Nxe4 dxe4 17.f3! { and the kingside opens up. }{ So Black ideally only plays ... Ne4  after White has played  f2 - f4 . With this in mind, Black wants to play the most useful waiting move at their disposal. } )( 15.f4 Ne4! { does minimize all attacking chances. }16.Nxe4 dxe4 { , followed by ... f5  or ... c5 . } )
15. Qd7{ This brings the queen closer to the kingside and especially the control over the  g4 -square can be really useful. }
16. f3{ Trying to prepare  Qh4  without allowing ... Ne4 . }( 16.f4 Ne4 17.Nxe4 dxe4 { is still what Black is hoping for. }{ Black is ready to strike back in the center with ... c5 . } )
16. Nh7{ Black still needs to exchange the strong  g5 -knight. }
17. Nxh7
17. Kxh7( { If Black had played   }15...Nh7 16.Nxh7 Kxh7 17.f4 { , we could have the same position just with the queen on  c7 . Why is this position much better? Black is just more stable on the light squares and has just enough time to go for a blockade. } )
18. f4{ White can also play other moves (after which Black is fine), but this move lets us illustrate the purpose of  15...Qd7 . }
18. f5{ Black stops  f4 - f5  and might just snack the pawn on  c4  on the next move. }( 19.g4 { would be a principled move to open up the kingside but with  f5  so nicely stabilised, Black can go }19...Bxc4 20.Bxc4 dxc4 { and can always }{ recapture on  f5  with the queen. } )
