7. O-O{ In this position, Black has played a lot of different moves. I'll go with the rather rare move 7... b6  in this repertoire.  The reasons why I neglected other, more popular, moves can be found  here . }
7. b6{ This is a very rare move (and maybe the most unconventional move given in this repertoire), but it has been tested by some very strong players, even in classical chess. The most famous player who chose this line was arguably Shakhyar Mamedyarov who played it against none other than Magnus Carlsen (though not particularly successful).    Li Chao is the strongest Grandmaster who played this move several times in classical games.  This move is combined with different ideas. In a lot of games, Black players just followed up with ... Bb7 , they finish their development with moves like ... Nbd7  and after all their pieces are on good squares, Black would push in center with ... c6 - c5  (or ... e7 - e5  in some cases), when the two fianchettoed bishops on  g7  and  b7  might become extremely strong.  In this plan, Black often includes the move ... e7 - e6  just to have the possibility to recapture on  d5  with the e-pawn. }( { When I started this repertoire, it was indeed my intention to start with }7...e6 { and only one very concrete line spoiled the fun for me -  see here .     A different idea is to follow it up with ... Ne4  and ... Nxc3 , weakening White's structure and play ... Ba6 . Black will have pressure against White's  c4 -pawn and if White takes on  d5 , we will have counterplay along the c-file against the pawn on  c3 . } )
8. b4{ A very aggressive option. Typically, if White grabs so much space on the queenside, we shouldn't let them get away with it easily but instead, we should fight back! }
8. dxc4{ A very concrete approach. Black wants to follow it up with ... b5  and ... a5  to fight against White's advance on the queenside. Exactly the right strategy against setups where White advances aggressively on that flank! }( { Playing it slow with a move like }8...e6 { is maybe playable but slightly risky when White has very concrete options on the queenside. I don't think there is a concrete refutation but White has different attractive options like }9.a4!? { . } )
9. Bxc4
9. b5{ Black has to play concretely to justify the last move. }( { Black wants to break White's bind on the  c5 -square but the immediate }9...a5 { runs into problems. White answers with }10.b5! { and Black stays very restricted, mainly because the  ...c5 -break does not work very well without any development supporting it. }10...c5? { runs into several refutations.    }{ One possibility is just to increase the pressure on  c5  and either create a weakness there or force Black to go ... cxd4  when White will happily recapture with the knight and jump to  c6 . }11.Ba3! Nbd7 12.Na4! cxd4 { . If Black doesn't take, White will just continue with  dxc5  and  Rc1 . }13.Nxd4 Bb7 14.Nc6+- { . } )
10. Bd3{ This keeps an extra eye on the  b5 -pawn, arguably making it harder to go ... c5 , but it also allows  Ne4  if Black attacks the  c3 -knight with ... b5 - b4 . }
10. a5{ This is the idea behind Black's last two moves. }
11. bxa5{ White has nothing better than to take this pawn. }
11. b4{ Black can collect the  a5 -pawn next. If we want to play ... c5 , it makes sense to have the b-pawn on  b4  anyways.  On  b5 , it is currently twice under attack, which makes it harder to achieve this break. }( 11...Qxa5 { is another logical and forcing move. Black wins back the pawn and attacks the knight on  c3 . It is not much wrong with it. I just think that it is harder here to create counterplay. }12.Bd2 { is the critical move. }{ Some discoveries are in the air.  While analyzing, I just came to the conclusion that it is much harder to create counterplay here. } )
12. Ne4{ A central square. But after the exchange of knights, there is still no problem achieving ... c5 . }
12. Nxe4{ This opens up the bishop and is also necessary to fight for the  c5 -square. }
13. Bxe4
13. Rxa5{ Black is ready to push ... c5 . There is not much White can do to stop it. }( 13...Qxa5? 14.Bd2 { is problematic. White is increasing the pressure on  b4 . Especially }-- 15.a3 { is an annoying threat. } )
14. a3{ The best move according to the engine. White is still trying to pressurize Black's queenside. }( 14.Bd2 c5 { is very ineffective here for White. Obviously, }15.a3 { is not a threat here, as we could just take with }15...Rxa3 { . } )
14. Qd6{ Black has different moves. ... Qd6  stabilizes  b4  and once again prepares ... c5 . }( 14...c5 15.Rb1 { is the engine justification. The pin along the b-file forces }15...Na6 { . After }16.axb4 cxb4 { , we will get a similar position as in our main line, though under slightly worse circumstances. } )
15. Qd2{ A weird move but pinning the  b4 -pawn is the only try to keep some pressure. }
15. c5( { A good moment to strike back in the center. Let me show you some ideas in the clickables.     A)  }16.Bb2 { is a natural developing move but we can just take on  d4 . After }16...cxd4 { , we can play  ...e5  if White recaptures with a piece, and after }17.exd4 { , we are not even forced to defend the  b4 -pawn passively. Instead, we can go }17...Bf5! { to exchange White's dominant bishop. After }18.Bxf5 Rxf5 19.axb4 { , we will win the pawn back with }19...Nc6 { , }{ followed by ... Rb5  and ... Rfb8  . } )( {  B)  }16.Rb1 { is another move. After }16...Na6 { , we have to protect the  b4 -pawn. Typical is the pawn structure after }17.axb4 cxb4⇆ { . White has the extra pawn in the center, we the passed pawn on the b-file. In the next moves, we should give it support with ... Be6  and ... Rb8 . We should regroup our knight from  a6  - A route via  c7  to land on  d5  or  b5  looks logical - and we should always watch out for a good moment to break with ... e5  to include our bishop in the game and break White's restricting pawn structure. } )
