15. Qa6{ Usually, when our opponent is aiming at positional pressure, we should rather create dynamic counter-chances than trade material. Here, however, this move is justified.  There is a tactical detail that will allow us to push ... c5  because of a pinned  a2 -pawn.     Hard to believe? Let's see! }( 15...Nxd2 16.Nxd2 e5! { is very thematic. However, White might remain with some pressure after }17.dxe5 Qxe5 ( { (or }17...Nd7 18.f4 { ) } )18.Rac1⩲ { . } )
16. Rfc1{ White doesn't help Black take control over  c5  but instead puts the next major piece on the c-file. }( 16.Rac1? { would be the wrong rook because of }16...Qxc4 17.Rxc4 Nxd2 18.Nxd2 Bd3∓ { Black wins the exchange. } )
16. Qxc4{ After this, we will be able to play ... Be6  with tempo. }( 16...Nxd2 17.Nxd2 e5! { is also playable. Here, this is stronger than one move earlier because White cannot even take on  e5 . } )
17. Rxc4( 17.Bxc4?? Rxa4  )
17. Be6{ As we will see, this is an important move to prepare ... c5 . }
18. Rcc1
18. c5( { White cannot take this pawn. }18...Bxb3 19.axb3 c5⇆ { is similar. } )
19. Bxe6( { White has nothing better. White cannot take with the pawn because the  a1 -rook would be hanging and }19.Nxc5 Nxc5 20.Rxc5 Bxb3-+ { loses due to the pin of the  a2 -pawn. } )
19. Rxa4
20. Bb3
20. Ra6{ with decent counterplay in the center. }
