1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2( { or }6.Bd3 { . } )
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. Bg4( { In my introduction to Chapter 20:  'The Chinese Recipe'  I had already written that this variation is an old favourite of mine. By capturing  c4 , Black lures the white bishop away from  e2 , and then directly pins the knight on  f3 .    Black's plan is fairly clear after that:  ...Nbd7  and  ...e5 !    We break open the  h8 - a1  diagonal in typical fashion!    This variation leads to some fun positions. In the main variation }9.h3 Bxf3 10.Qxf3 Nbd7 11.Rd1 e5 12.d5 e4! { Black sacrifices a pawn, but looking at the resulting positions, it is little surprising that Black gets good compensation because the white queenside cannot be developed so easily. Above all, the direct comparison of the dark-squared bishops goes to the butcher!    The fact that Black can play this variation against both a white  Bf1 - e2  and  Bf1 - d3  makes it a good choice if you want to cut a few corners in the  e3  universe - you deal with the two most important setups for White in one go! } )( { Compared to the 'Chinese recipe'   }7...b6 { this variation has been explored much more extensively in theory, but nevertheless, I think I managed to put my own stamp on it and find new ideas (for example with   }13...Ne5!? { and   }17...Qc8!? { in  the main variation ).    Existing Chessable courses (for example Sielecki's LTR) had put this variation under some pressure and at that time, when selecting variations for this repertoire, dissuaded me from giving it as the main recommendation. A few hours of analysis work and novelties later, however, I am convinced: Black is okay! Therefore you can make this 'alternative chapter' your main weapon with a clear conscience.    }{ Rules for this chapter:  We play ... Nbd7 , are ready to take on  f3 , and heat up White (almost always) with ... e5 !      This chapter was added as an update after publication. At the moment there is no video version for it.  } )
