5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. Bg4
9. e4( { This is not a particularly great move, but it shows why White should start with }9.Be2 { if White wants to advance quickly with the e-pawn in the center. } )
9. Bxf3{ This is the simple way to play the position. }( 9...b5!? { is another interesting way to play the position. In fact, Black wins the white d-pawn or e-pawn here because of the possibility  ...b4  in many variations. White gets halfway sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but in any case, Black is objectively okay here too.     A)  }10.Bb3 b4 11.e5!? { is an attempt to sharpen up the position, but }11...bxc3 12.exf6 cxb2 13.Bxb2 Bxf6=∞ { is also one pawn extra for Black for now.     B)  }10.Bd3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 Qxd4=∞ { is another attempt to play for compensation, but for all practical purposes, I'd much rather be Black here. } )
10. gxf3
10. Nh5{ A clever move to first force White into a passive move regarding the  d4 -pawn and at the same time prepare ... e7 - e5 . }
11. Be3
11. e5( { Black has super counterplay with White's weakened kingside. For example:     A)  }12.d5 { is the best move. Again, we can bring our queen to the kingside with }12...Qh4 { or }12...Qf6 { , but we can also exchange out on }d5 { first to be able to develop our knight to }c6 { if necessary.     B)  }12.dxe5? Qh4!∓ { Black leaves the queens on the board! White can't hold the  e5  pawn and White gets into huge dark-squared problems. }13.e6?! Be5-+ { only makes things worse. White is welcome to take on  f7 , but as soon as we break through to  h2 , White will regret their opening badly! } )
