1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. Bg4
9. Be2{ This is Shankland's recommendation. White prepares to take back on  f3  with the bishop, so that his own queen doesn't end up on this somewhat exposed square.  White is banking on the fact that the bishop pair, which will probably be won sooner or later, is a long-term asset to play for, even if the white move doesn't seem particularly ambitious at first.     Moreover, this move allows white to play a quick  e3 - e4  without immediately putting the pawns under pressure. ( See 9.e4 ) }
9. Nbd7{ Typically in this variation Black plays a quick ... e7 - e5  to bring the  g7 -bishop to life. }
10. h3{ A logical move, but as we will see, Black also sometimes voluntarily takes on  f3 . }
10. Bxf3
11. Bxf3
11. e5{ The typical counterattack in the center. }
12. dxe5( { White typically takes on  e5  or plays }12.d5 { . } )
12. Nxe5
13. Be2{ White keeps the bishop pair. }
13. Qxd1( { A relatively concrete approach of playing the position.    The main move so far has been }13...Qe7 { , to keep the queens on the board and with subsequent  ...Rd8  to get some tempi against the white majesty. But White can hope for a small advantage after }14.Bd2 Rad8 15.Qc2 { and now for example }15...Rd7 16.Rfd1 Rfd8 17.Be1⩲ { . Our activity dwindles somewhat after simplifications on the d-file, and if White can free himself with the bishop pair, the endgame will be slightly better for White. } )
14. Rxd1
14. Rfd8{ Black is counting on White still having problems keeping the d-file under control. }
15. Rxd8+{ This is the move where I think we need to play most carefully, so I'll take this as the main variation. }( {  A)  The immediate }15.e4 Rxd1+ { presents White with the choice of immediately giving away the  e4  pawn or, after }16.Bxd1 Nd3 { , tolerating the active knight on  d3 . The second option is clearly better, but nevertheless Black sits at least on the easier side of the balance here as well }{ . }( {  B)  }15.Bd2 Nd3 { also immediately gives us an octopus. } ) )
15. Rxd8
16. e4{ If White now also manages to develop their dark-squared bishop, then everything would be fine. But we have an annoying reply move. }
16. b5( { Very strong. The threat   }17...b4 { forces White to make a few weakening moves. } )( { Let's take a look at some example variations.     A)  }17.Be3 b4 18.Rd1!? { is a fancy idea to fight for the d-file and effectively exchange the  e4  pawn for  a7 . But Black can keep the rooks on the board with }18...Re8!? 19.Na4 Nxe4 { when White has trouble arresting the }a7 { because of  ...Ta8 . White has compensation, but Black can be satisfied. } )( {  B)  }17.a3 Nd3⇆ { now works much better for Black, since the  b7  pawn is no problem if White sacrifices the  b2  pawn. } )( {  C)  }17.f4 Nd3⇆ { is similar. } )( { The immediate   }16...Nd3 { does not stop White from playing }17.Be3 { , since }17...Nxb2 18.Rb1 { is somewhat problematic. Black can keep the white advantage limited with the spectacular }18...Nd5! { which at least stops white from crashing through on  b2  and  b7 , but }19.exd5 ( { ( }19.Rxb2? Nxc3∓ { is the black idea, after which White can't easily pick up the b-pawn. ) } )19...Bxc3 20.Rc1⩲ { probably gives White a small advantage at the end of the day. } )
