4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. Bg4
9. Be2{ This is Shankland's recommendation. White prepares to take back on  f3  with the bishop, so that his own queen doesn't end up on this somewhat exposed square.  White is banking on the fact that the bishop pair, which will probably be won sooner or later, is a long-term asset to play for, even if the white move doesn't seem particularly ambitious at first.     Moreover, this move allows white to play a quick  e3 - e4  without immediately putting the pawns under pressure. ( See 9.e4 ) }
9. Nbd7{ Typically in this variation Black plays a quick ... e7 - e5  to bring the  g7 -bishop to life. }
10. h3{ A logical move, but as we will see, Black also sometimes voluntarily takes on  f3 . }
10. Bxf3
11. Bxf3
11. e5{ The typical counterattack in the center. }
12. d5{ The main move for White. Although it is actually very easy for White to misstep in this variation. }
12. cxd5{ The main move and also my recommendation, since I think the resulting position is easier to play for Black than for White. }( { The engines indicate that }12...e4!? { is a playable alternative, and we will see this idea of  d4-d5  with  ...e5-e4  later in the chapter. The position is close to equality. White may retain a mini advantage after }13.Nxe4 ( { ( }13.Bxe4 Nxe4 14.Nxe4 Nf6 15.Nxf6+ Qxf6=∞ { is another variation. Black gets similar compensation for the sacrificed pawn as we will also see later in this chapter. It is not so easy for White to develop the queenside ) } )13...Nxd5 14.Qc2 { followed by  Bd2  and  Rfd1 . } )
13. Bxd5{ It may not look very natural to give away the light-squared bishop. (Mostly because White often insists on the bishop pair as his main positional advantage in this variation.) But in fact this capture is more or less necessary here. }( 13.Nxd5 e4 { simply gives Black space for nothing and with tempo. As is still often the case in this chapter, we play on the fact that White has problems developing their queenside. An example variation would be: }14.Nxf6+ { White is not forced to take on }f6 { , but doing it in this position at least forces Black to take back with the knight on  f6 . In addition, White must consider how he wants to develop his dark-squared bishop. White cannot play  Bd2  as long as the knight on  d5  is dependent on the queen's cover. }( { ( }14.Be2 { gives Black more possibilities to become active. For example with }14...Nc5!? { .) } )14...Nxf6 15.Be2 Qb6⇆ { followed by  ...Rfd8  and  ...Rac8 . Black has an insanely active position. } )
13. Nc5{ This protects the pawn on  b7 , but also takes control of  e4 , so ... e5 - e4  can be possible here as well. }( { The immediate }13...Nxd5 14.Qxd5⩲ { gives White some pressure. Not only because  b7  hangs, but also because White can continue with  e3 - e4  himself on the next move, which will not please our butcher. } )
14. b4{ This was actually played in two out of three games with this position, but the white players had probably underestimated the dynamics of the bishop. }
14. Nxd5
15. Qxd5( 15.Nxd5 e4! 16.Rb1 Nd3⩱ { is also very unpleasant for White. White has to invest another tempo in their knight on  d5 . } )
15. Qxd5
16. Nxd5
16. e4{ This is simply very unpleasant for white. }
17. Rb1
17. Na4( { Even better than }17...Nd3 { . White has problems with their development and Black quickly gets into the white position via the open lines with the rooks. } )
