9. Be2{ This is Shankland's recommendation. White prepares to take back on  f3  with the bishop, so that his own queen doesn't end up on this somewhat exposed square.  White is banking on the fact that the bishop pair, which will probably be won sooner or later, is a long-term asset to play for, even if the white move doesn't seem particularly ambitious at first.     Moreover, this move allows white to play a quick  e3 - e4  without immediately putting the pawns under pressure. ( See 9.e4 ) }
9. Nbd7{ Typically in this variation Black plays a quick ... e7 - e5  to bring the  g7 -bishop to life. }
10. e4{ This is White's idea in this variation. White prevents ... e4  from being played after ... e5  and wants to solve the problem of the dark-squared bishop. }
10. Bxf3{ The strongest move. Black wants to play ... e7 - e5  quickly, and that's only possible after taking on  f3 . Otherwise White might consider  e4 - e5  themselves. }
11. gxf3{ This kind of recapturing looks rather absurd, but in fact, the move was successfully used three times in 2022 by strong players. The idea is that the immediate  11...e5  doesn't work very well and therefore Black can't easily break out.  However, Black should now have his fair chances even in a slower game, since the weakened white structure compensates for the bishop pair in the long run. }
11. e6{ Here we can switch to a calmer approach with a clear conscience. ... e6  is simply a useful move, controlling the center and creating a square for the queen on  e7 . In fact, this move can also serve to prepare for ... c5 , since White's d-pawn cannot move to  d5  unquestioned. Nevertheless, there are few forced variations here, so the following moves are just a sample variation }( {  A)  }11...e5? 12.dxe5 Nxe5 13.f4 Ned7 14.Be3± { turned out to be quite bad for Black in the game  Malakhov - Feller, France 2022 . All white pieces are now well placed, while the 'bad' double pawns are unattackable for white and gain a bunch of space }{ . }( {  B)  }11...c5 { allows }12.d5 { , but also }12.e5 { followed by a later  d4-d5  can put us quite on the defensive. } ) )
12. Kh1{ A logical move that allows the following idea: }
12. c5{ This is a fairly straightforward approach to solving the problems. }
13. e5{ At least an ambitious attempt to punish Black. }
13. Ne8{ In fact, White actually has to be careful that his center doesn't fall apart! }
14. f4{ Relatively speaking, the best move. }
14. cxd4
15. Qxd4
15. Nb6{ Relatively speaking the best move }{ Again, the move  ...e6  can also pay off, since Black has chances to install an outpost on  d5 . Not only the  b6  knight but also the  e8  knight wants to get there via  c7 . }{ . }
