10. e4{ This is White's idea in this variation. White prevents ... e4  from being played after ... e5  and wants to solve the problem of the dark-squared bishop. }
10. Bxf3{ The strongest move. Black wants to play ... e7 - e5  quickly, and that's only possible after taking on  f3 . Otherwise White might consider  e4 - e5  themselves. }
11. Bxf3{ The natural recapture on  f3 . }
11. e5{ Here we can now play our standard move ... e5  again. }
12. Be3( { This gives the same pawn structure as }12.dxe5 { , however White can try  f2 - f4  there under good circumstances to play with tempo. (And  ...Ne5 - d7  back is a standard manoeuvre as we will see.) So, in the end,  12.Be3  leads to a harmless version of a harmless variation and Black is objectively already minimally more comfortable. } )
12. exd4{ White does not get another opportunity for  d4 - d5 . }
13. Bxd4
13. Re8{ Putting pressure on the  e4 -pawn is a typical motif in this variation, but  ...Bf8 - c5 !? can also be an idea to exchange the very central  d4 -bishop. }
14. g3{ This move was played in the only previous game, so we take this as an sample variation. }
14. Qe7{ A pretty standard way to develop }( {  A)  }14...Bf8!? { The  Bd4  is a dominant piece and  ...Bc5  is a harmonious way to exchange it }{ . }( {  B)  }14...Ne5?! { was played in one previous game, but after }15.Be2! { there is actually no positional improvement for Black, because now  f2-f4  is possible again with tempo. Thank God Schwart realized his mistake here, played }15...Ned7!? { and still won the game as a result!  Korobkov - Shkuran, Evpatoria 2007  } ) )
15. Qe2
15. Nc5
16. Rfe1
16. Ne6{ Again, we expel the bishop from its active square on  d4 . In the next moves we can play on both sides with  ...a5  and  ...h5 , play  ...Rad8  and also regroup the second horse with  ...Ng4  or  ...Nd7 . }
