13. Re8{ Again, Black gets ready to kick the bishop away from  f3  with ... e5 - e4 . }
14. Bg5{ This was played by Aronian and is also the best move according to the computer. }( { The immediate }14.Be3 { can lead to similar positions, but it is a minimally improved version for White if he can provoke the move  ...h6 . Sometimes because the concrete  Qd2  can win a tempo, but - as Sam Shankland taught me in his book 'Small Steps to Giant Improvement' -, the side with a passed pawn in the middlegame rarely wins its game by promoting the pawn directly, but instead by tieing down the opponent's pieces to that pawn followed by a mating attack. In this sense, any weakening of the black kingside is probably useful for White! } )
14. h6{ The bishop is kicked back, after which the knight's captivity is removed. }
15. Be3{ We continue to follow the Aronian game. }( 15.Bh4 { takes away the bishop's ability to act in the center. }15...Qb6 { is now a good move to exploit the fact that the bishop can no longer go to  e3 . But even here }15...Bf8 { is an idea to keep an eye on the d-pawn and perhaps activate it via  c5  towards the kingside. } )
15. Nb6{ Attacking the  d5 -pawn and possibly playing ... Nc4  is another idea I really like. }( 15...e4 { is the standard plan and works reasonably well here as well. }16.Be2 { In  Aronian - Yu, Riga 2019 , 9th game, Black now played the move }16...Nb6 { , but here the move is less strong since the idea  ...Nc4  does not exist. With }17.d6 { White would have gained an advantage. But   }16...Rc8!? { is a reasonable move. which improves the rook, prepares  ...Nc5  and in fact is also simply useful when White plays  d6  and  Nb5 . (Looks crooked, but engines show in many variations that the fork threat on  c7  can be troublesome.) } )
16. d6{ The only chance for advantage. }( {  A)  }16.Qb3 e4! { allows us to win the  d5 -pawn, for example }{ . }( {  B)  }16.Qd3 { is generally a bit slow. }16...Nc8!? { shows another idea behind  ...Nb6 . We can move the knight to the perfect blocking square  d6 . Here we then even immediately threaten the fork  ...e5-e4 . } ) )
16. Nc4{ This move works for black in all variations. Let's take a look at them in the clickables }( {  A)  }17.Bxb7 Rb8 { wins nothing for White. We'll take right on  e3  and then win the  d6 -pawn. } )( {  B)  }17.Bc5 Rc8 { is no real way to save bishop and pawn. }18.Bxa7 Nxd6 { is still the best for White, but at least we have no problems. } )( {  C)  }17.Nb5 { is the best move according to the engine, but }17...Nxe3 18.fxe3 e4 19.Be2 { looks like some achievement to me. The only thing not quite optimal is that the engine insists that Black should play }19...Rf8 { here to address  Nc7 . Not the most active square, but overall Black does look very active with the  g7 -monster, the  e3 -weakness and the possibility of playing some useful moves on the queenside with tempo ( ...a6 ,  ...Qb6 ). } )
