3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4
8. Bxc4
8. Bg4
9. h3{ Traditionally the main move. White immediately secures the bishop pair and subsequently also has the option of playing a quick  Rd1 , which supports both  e3 - e4  and  d4 - d5  - in the case of ... e7 - e5 . }
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3
10. Nbd7{ A quick glance over to the knight on  d7  and our e-pawn knows it's about to jump out of its starting block. }
11. e4{ This move has been played in practice by some strong grandmasters (Shankland, Adams, Fedoseev, Radjabov), but without a rook on  d1  White must be ready to cede the bishop pair immediately. }
11. Nb6{ This is the main move here, winning back the bishop pair due to the double attack against  c4  and  d4 . }( 11...e5!? { actually doesn't score that bad in practice either, but White is objectively slightly better after }12.d5 { . We can't get a quick  ...e5-e4  like in other variations to free our position, and even if we immediately try to put the white center under pressure with the (relatively best@) }12...Nb6 { , we don't have the same chances of active play after }13.Bb3 cxd5 14.exd5⩲ { as, for example, in the similar structure in  this variation . } )
12. Qd3{ Forced if White does not want to lose  d4 . }
12. Nxc4{ We take our chances to capture the bishop pair. }
13. Qxc4
13. b5{ This is objectively the easiest way to play, although it does involve a few simplifications. If you want to leave a few more pieces on the board, you can start with 13... Qd7 , for example, which prepares  ...Rad8  and  ...Rfd8 , but also  ...b5  without losing the  c6 -pawn.     Another idea is 13... Ne8  }{ to manoeuvre the knight to  d6 . After that, we can also develop our queen to  d7  or  b6 , put the  a8  rook in the center, and possibly even try to loosen up the white center with  ... f7 - f5 !? . In these variations, White is visually a little better off with the center pawns, but we are super-solid and White has no clear way forward. }
14. Qxc6{ The only move that can achieve something.  Covering the d-pawn is not recommended. }( {  A)  }14.Qd3?! e5! { is actually already problematic for White. Both the d-pawn and e-pawn are tactical targets. For example, }15.Be3 ( { ( }15.Rd1?! exd4 16.Qxd4 Qxd4 17.Rxd4 Nd5!-+ { is similar, only worse.) } )15...exd4 16.Qxd4 ( { ( }16.Bxd4?? c5-+ { ) } )16...Nd5!∓ { leads to a terrible endgame for White. Either we take on  c3  and play with the better structure, or we take on  e3  and play with a butcher with no equal counterpart. } )( {  B)  }14.Qc5 Qb6 15.Qxb6 { What else? }15...axb6 { is slightly more comfortable for Black. We have pressure on the queenside, but also  e4  and  d4  are a bit shaky }-- 16...b4 { is an immediate threat. } )
14. Qxd4{ White can't win the b-pawn without giving up the  e4 -pawn. }
15. Be3{ The most logical move. }
15. Qc4{ We offer the exchange of queens. In the resulting endgame, our play along the b-file compensates for our slightly weakened structure. }( { The endgame after }15...Qe5 16.f4! Qe6 17.Qxe6 fxe6 18.e5 Nd5 19.Nxd5 exd5 { was reached in  Shankland - Safarli, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 . Black achieved a comfortable draw, but White may have a small objective advantage.  ...g7-g5 ! is an important idea in the position. } )
16. Qxc4
16. bxc4{ In the next move we play  ...Rfb8  with counterplay along the b-file. After that  ... Ne8 -d6  is also an idea here to free our friend on  g7 . }( { White can play against our bishop with }17.e5 Nd7 18.f4 { , but after }18...Rfb8 { White must also passively take care of the  b2  for now, and we can always consider  ...f6  or even  ...g5  to break up the white pawns. } )
