9. h3{ Traditionally the main move. White immediately secures the bishop pair and subsequently also has the option of playing a quick  Rd1 , which supports both  e3 - e4  and  d4 - d5  - in the case of ... e7 - e5 . }
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3
10. Nbd7{ A quick glance over to the knight on  d7  and our e-pawn knows it's about to jump out of its starting block. }
11. Bb3{ A prophylactic move that moves the bishop away from the somewhat vulnerable  c4 -square. As we've seen in other variations, many a time Black can play  ...Nxe5 ,  ...Nb6  or  ...b5  with tempo, which are quite important resources.  However, this move is a bit slow. }
11. e5{ Of course, our standard move here as well. }
12. d5{ Let's consider this the main variation at this point. }( {  A)  }12.Rd1 { leads to  11.Rd1   e5   12.Bb3 . } )( {  B)  }12.dxe5 Nxe5 { isn't a great version of taking out on  e5 . Even if the bishop on  c4  is not attacked with tempo, White is not too happy about the bishop on  b3 , because Black gets good chances to install a pesky knight on  d3 . }{ 13  Qe2   Qd3 ⇆ , followed by  ...Rad8  gives Black a very reasonable position. } )( {  C)  }12.Bd2 exd4 13.exd4 { leads to a reasonable isolation position here. However, besides the typical }13...Nb6 { , }13...Nc5!⇆ { is especially strong to get the bishop pair back. } )
12. e4{ This is also the main move with  Rd1  instead of  Bb3 . This version here is much more harmless for Black. }
13. Nxe4{ The most forcing move }( 13.Qd1 { was played in a previous game, but the white pieces are simply much more passive than in comparable variations. }13...cxd5 14.Nxd5 Nc5⇆ { gives good counterplay, for example. Engines also insist that }13...c5!? { is good here.  Not that often the right move in these positions, but the white pieces are so unimpressive and give so little support to the d-pawn that the black advance on the queenside may well be the bigger positional factor here. } )
13. Nxe4
14. Qxe4
14. Nc5{ Black wins back the d-pawn and remains with nice pressure against the white queenside. }
15. Qc2
15. Nxb3
16. Qxb3
16. Qxd5{ The exchange of queens makes it harder for White to unknot the queenside without losing  b2 . }
17. Qxb7{ Probably a bit greedy, but the alternatives don't impress either. }( 17.Qxd5 cxd5 { is a good endgame for Black despite the isolani. (Feel free to ask the dark-squared bishops if you are unsure.) } )
17. a5{ Black gains some space on the queenside and can immediately continue with  ... a5 -a4  and  ...Rfb8 . The position is in the draw zone, but despite minus pawn, Black probably has the slightly easier game here. }
