11. Rd1{ The main move, covering the center and preparing  e3 - e4  as well as  d4 - d5 . }
11. e5{ Here he comes! }
12. dxe5{ That's just innocuous. }
12. Nxe5{ White cannot take our queen, since we then capture on  f3  with check and win the exchange. }
13. Qe2{ The best sqaure to provide some stability in the center. }
13. Qe7{ Our queen was under attack, but on the next move we'd love to take the  c4 -bishop if White doesn't do anything about it. }
14. Bb3{ Otherwise, we take it. }
14. Rad8{ The easiest way to play the position. The simplest plan is to exchange on  d1 , bring the other rook to  d8  and then hop into the white camp with  ...Nd3 . }( { The manoeuvre }14...Ned7!? { with the idea  ...Nc5  is also possible. For example: }15.e4 ( { ( }15.Bd2 { White can of course leave the e-pawn at the back, but for example after }15...Nc5 16.Bc2 Nfe4⇆ { Black gets the  e4 -square as an outpost and our pieces feel right at home.) } )15...Nc5 16.Bc2 Rfe8⇆ { and Black gets counterplay against the  e4 -pawn. } )
15. e4{ Let's take this as the main move. White wants to develop the black bishop to a more active square than  d2  }( {  A)  }15.Bd2 Nd3 { gives up  d3  immediately. White has nothing better than to give up the bishop pair in any way to get rid of this knight. For example, }16.Be1 Nxe1 { , followed by  ...Nd7  and  ...Nc5  with a very comfortable position for Black }{ . }( {  B)  }15.f4!? { kicks the knight out before we get it in to  d3 , but as we have just seen, }15...Ned7 { followed by  ...Nc5  is not an atypical manoeuvre anyway, and White has now even weakened themselves further here. }16.e4 Nc5 17.e5 { is an attempt to give the position an independent character, but we win back the bishop pair, so this approach is also unconvincing. }17...Nxb3 18.axb3 Rxd1+ 19.Qxd1 Rd8 20.Qe2 Nd5⇆ { is a logical continuation. Soon we will break the pawns with  ...f6 . } ) )
15. Rxd1+
16. Bxd1
16. Rd8{ Black is now ready to  ...Nd3  at any time }
17. Bc2{ An attempt to keep the knight out of the white position. }
17. Qb4{ Not the only move, but so far with 2.5 out of 3 for black. }( { If White now plays }18.f4 { , we can play }18...Nc4 { and in general the queen is very troublesome on  b4  because White also has problems with his development }{ . }( {   }17...c5!? { is another move that the engine likes well. Now, in case of doubt, the  e5 -knight can always return to  c6 , from where the beautiful square  d4  is smiling at it. } ) )
