13. Bd2{ The main move. }( {  A)  }13.dxe5 Nxe5 14.Qe2 Rad8 { leads to the last trainable. } )( {  B)  }13.e4?! { is premature. After }13...exd4 14.Rxd4 Nc5 { all white pieces are on very attackable squares compared to similar variations. Black can already be very ambitious here. If White maintains the bishop pair with }15.Bc2 { , }15...Nfd7 16.Rd1 Ne6 { , for example, gives good chances to use the  d4  square as an outpost. }17.Be3 Rad8⩱ { Black covers  d7 , so  ...Qb4  now becomes possible, but  ...Ndc5  and  ...Nd4  are also very troublesome for White. } )
13. Rad8{ Black continues to be flexible with their pawns. }
14. Rac1{ Let's take this natural move as a sample variation. We have reached a kind of standoff. White has no direct path forward, while Black always has the possibility to change the structure with  ...exd4  or  ...e4 . }( {  A)  The immediate }14.a3 { is more common in practice and can lead over to our Trainable after }14...Rfe8 { , but the engines point out that }14...c5!? { is yet another additional possibility here, virtually forcing White to take  e5  now }{ . }( {  B)  }14.d5 { is typically answered with }14...e4 { after which Black gets active play with the knight squares on  c5  and  e5  }{ . }15.Qe2 { And here we can play both }15...c5 { and }15...cxd5 { to keep our pawn structure intact before moving to our counterplay. } ) )
14. Rfe8
15. a3{ So far played in all games with this position. White prevents ... Qb4  and also gives the bishop a square on  a2 . }( 15.d5 e4 16.Qe2 Ne5!? { would be an interesting additional option for Black here compared to a move before. Getting  ...Nd3  with tempo on the next move would sufficiently compensate for our slightly weakened pawn structure after, say, }17.dxc6 Nd3 18.Rc2 bxc6 { . } )
15. Bh6{ An interesting move. Black is getting ready to take on  d4 , but also wants to halve the white bishop pair at the same time afterwards. }
16. Rc2
