10. Nbd7{ A quick glance over to the knight on  d7  and our e-pawn knows it's about to jump out of its starting block. }
11. Rd1{ The main move, covering the center and preparing  e3 - e4  as well as  d4 - d5 . }
11. e5{ Here he comes! }
12. d5{ White tries to open the position according on their own terms and gain the initiative. But in fact, after Black's next move, it is the second player who gains the initiative - admittedly at the cost of a pawn. }
12. e4{ This is the decisive move in this variation. The e-pawn is ready to sacrifice itself, in return our friend on  g7  thanks him personally for first luring the white d-pawn to  d5 , now disappearing from the long diagonal himself and, last but not least, luring the white knight away from  c3 , after which the pressure against the white queenside ( b2 !) increases immensely.  Had this variation not entered the course after publication, the final sequence of moves would surely have made it into the  'Maneuvers and Plans' , so instructive do I find the black concept here. }
13. Qe2{ If White doesn't take on  e4 , we take on  d5 . At least we have achieved the goal of opening the long diagonal. }
13. cxd5
14. Nxd5
14. Ne5{ A wonderful square for the knight. }( 14...Nb6? 15.Nxb6! Qxb6 16.Bd2 { allows White to develop his queenside.  Bc3  comes next. This is one of the advantages of the  13.Qe2  move order: the rook on  d1  is covered. With the queen on  f4 ,  14...Nb6  is actually the best move. } )
15. Nxf6+{ This has been played in all games with this position so far. }( 15.Nc3 Qe7 { leads to a similar position as in the variation with  13.Qf4 . }{ Here, however, Black has an even simpler version, because White cannot keep the bishop pair well on the board. If White plays  Bb3 , our  e5 -horsie gets the  d3 -outpost. } )
15. Qxf6
16. Bd5{ An attempt to win a pawn, but White would have preferred to do it on move 13. }
16. Qf5{ We are super active and soon have the opportunity to play  ...Nd3 . }
17. Bxb7{ The only attempt to justify the opening. }
17. Rab8
18. Bd5
18. Rfd8{ Black has a lot of pressure on the white position. With best play, White seems to be able to return the extra pawn and reach a drawn endgame, but the black position is much easier to play. }
