10. Nbd7{ A quick glance over to the knight on  d7  and our e-pawn knows it's about to jump out of its starting block. }
11. Rd1{ The main move, covering the center and preparing  e3 - e4  as well as  d4 - d5 . }
11. e5{ Here he comes! }
12. d5{ White tries to open the position according on their own terms and gain the initiative. But in fact, after Black's next move, it is the second player who gains the initiative - admittedly at the cost of a pawn. }
12. e4{ This is the decisive move in this variation. The e-pawn is ready to sacrifice itself, in return our friend on  g7  thanks him personally for first luring the white d-pawn to  d5 , now disappearing from the long diagonal himself and, last but not least, luring the white knight away from  c3 , after which the pressure against the white queenside ( b2 !) increases immensely.  Had this variation not entered the course after publication, the final sequence of moves would surely have made it into the  'Maneuvers and Plans' , so instructive do I find the black concept here. }
13. Nxe4{ White should accept the challenge. }
13. Ne5{ At this point Black has two ways to continue. }( { Besides this knight move there is also }13...Nxe4 14.Qxe4 Nb6 { , which plays for similar compensation if White now holds on to the pawn with }15.Bb3 { . Christof Sielecki, however, recommends }15.Be2 { at this point to simply return the pawn and play on the bishop pair as a long-term advantage. Stockfish agrees with the assessment that this variation is just slightly better for White.    However, in addition to this objective assessment,  13...Ne5  has the advantage that it has been played much less frequently ( 13...Nxe4  more than five times more frequently), so theory has focused less on this move. } )
14. Nxf6+{ Forced, otherwise White would lose a piece. }
14. Bxf6{ We keep the queens on the board, of course. }
15. Qe2( { This move is almost always played. But also after }15.Qe4 { or }15.Qf4 { we would take on  c4 . } )
15. Nxc4
16. Qxc4
16. cxd5
17. Rxd5{ After a long, relatively forced variation we end up in this position, where White has a pawn more, but problems developing their queenside without losing the  b2 -pawn. White should definitely take with the rook on  d5 .  Not only does this move gain tempo against the queen (and any tempo can be useful when it comes to unknotting the queenside). The  d5 -rook can actually also be used usefully along the fifth rank (and often anny Black's queen). }( { After }17.Qxd5 { , }17...Qxd5 18.Rxd5 Rfd8 { is the easiest way to play. In fact, White has only one move that guarantees complete equality and that is }19.e4 Rxd5 20.exd5 Rd8= { which immediately returns the pawn.    Apart from that, }17...Qb6 { is also possible, which is clearly better than after  17.Rxd5 , because no  Rd5-b5  is possible and also  ...Rd8  comes with tempo. } )
17. Qc8( { This is a novelty, with which Black fights directly for the c-file.    At this point there are no previous games, so I'll take a closer look at the six most obvious moves to me: }18.Qxc8 { , }18.Qf4 { , }18.Qd3 { , }18.Qb4 { , }18.Qb5 { and }18.Rc5 { . Since this position is so important for the evaluation of the whole variation, I think it makes sense to spend so much space on it. } )( 17...Qb6 { has almost always been played so far, and keeping the queens on the board while increasing the pressure on  b2  can't be that wrong. Objectively, though, it is no stronger than  17...Qc8  and White players can prepare for it if necessary. (Probably more a theoretical than a practical problem.) }18.e4! { seems to be the best move, when }18...Bxb2 19.Be3⩲ { gives White an initiative that can be quite unpleasant, while   }18...Rac8 19.Qb5 { also demands some precision from Black when playing against a machine-like prepared player.    }18.Rb5 Qa6! { is another much-played variation, but in my view, it promises Black good counterplay. } )
18. Qxc8{ This looks somewhat accommodating. Black is immediately ready to move their rook to  c2 . }
18. Raxc8{ Black has good counterplay, because  ...Rc2  is about to come. If White tries to prevent that with 19.Rd2?! he only gets himself into trouble. 19... Rfd8  is strong because White gets huge problems along the d-file when he trades on  d8 , while -- 20... Rxc1 +! is a nasty threat. }
