17. Qc8( { This is a novelty, with which Black fights directly for the c-file.    At this point there are no previous games, so I'll take a closer look at the six most obvious moves to me: }18.Qxc8 { , }18.Qf4 { , }18.Qd3 { , }18.Qb4 { , }18.Qb5 { and }18.Rc5 { . Since this position is so important for the evaluation of the whole variation, I think it makes sense to spend so much space on it. } )( 17...Qb6 { has almost always been played so far, and keeping the queens on the board while increasing the pressure on  b2  can't be that wrong. Objectively, though, it is no stronger than  17...Qc8  and White players can prepare for it if necessary. (Probably more a theoretical than a practical problem.) }18.e4! { seems to be the best move, when }18...Bxb2 19.Be3⩲ { gives White an initiative that can be quite unpleasant, while   }18...Rac8 19.Qb5 { also demands some precision from Black when playing against a machine-like prepared player.    }18.Rb5 Qa6! { is another much-played variation, but in my view, it promises Black good counterplay. } )
18. Qd3{ A very safe square, with which White controls the d-file, but also keeps an eye on the entry square  c2 . }
18. Re8{ Again, a strong move. Black anticipates that White would like to play  e3 - e4  at some point. }( { Coming in over the d-file would be an idea if White was forced to exchange after }18...Rd8? { , but }19.e4!+- { puts a stop to that and now Black certainly doesn't want to exchange on  d5 . } )
19. e4( {  A)  After, for example, }19.Rb1 { , we also play }19...Qe6 { and if }20.Bd2 { , }20...Rad8⇆ { gives enough counterplay, because now  a2  also tends to be a problem. } )( {  B)  }19.Rd6!? { is a somewhat crooked move to prevent  ...Qe6 , but the rook is simply vulnerable on  d6 . After }19...Be7 { or }19...Be5 { the rook should move back to  d5 . The only minor problem for Black is that  f6  is the best square for the bishop for the moment, because the bishop is both preparing  ...Rad8  and keeping  b2  in view, so after }20.Rd5 { , }20...Bf6 { would actually be the best move.    If you want to avoid this move repetition, there is also   }19...Rd8 { , which now gives Black good counterplay along the d-file again, because White cannot plug the d-file with  e2-e4  and  Rd5 . }20.e4 { is still the best move, but }20...Rxd6 21.Qxd6 Bg7 { gives typical compensation, in which White has difficulty developing the queenside without giving up  b2 . } )
19. Qe6{ This is the black idea. White has problems keeping the  e4 -pawn on the board. }
20. f3{ This is a try, but the dark squares on the white side are not getting better. }
20. Rad8{ Suddenly Black is ready to exchange out on  d5  again. If White takes with the e-pawn we come in on  e1 , if White takes with the queen we play  ... Qb6 +  and  ...Rd8 . White should get his back rank under control with the development of the dark-squared bishop, but this costs the  b2 -pawn. }
