17. Qc8( { This is a novelty, with which Black fights directly for the c-file.    At this point there are no previous games, so I'll take a closer look at the six most obvious moves to me: }18.Qxc8 { , }18.Qf4 { , }18.Qd3 { , }18.Qb4 { , }18.Qb5 { and }18.Rc5 { . Since this position is so important for the evaluation of the whole variation, I think it makes sense to spend so much space on it. } )( 17...Qb6 { has almost always been played so far, and keeping the queens on the board while increasing the pressure on  b2  can't be that wrong. Objectively, though, it is no stronger than  17...Qc8  and White players can prepare for it if necessary. (Probably more a theoretical than a practical problem.) }18.e4! { seems to be the best move, when }18...Bxb2 19.Be3⩲ { gives White an initiative that can be quite unpleasant, while   }18...Rac8 19.Qb5 { also demands some precision from Black when playing against a machine-like prepared player.    }18.Rb5 Qa6! { is another much-played variation, but in my view, it promises Black good counterplay. } )
18. Rc5{ Let's look last at what happens if White continues to chase our queen. }
18. Qd7{ A slightly more active square than  d8 . }
19. e4{ A logical move to develop the bishop. }( {  A)  }19.Rc7?! Qd1+ 20.Qf1 Rfd8⩱ { is not recommended for White. Because of the  ...Be5  skewer, White cannot exchange queens and play  Kh2  and }21.Rxb7?? Qc2-+ { followed by  ...Rd1  is even over immediately }{ . }( {  B)  }19.Rd5 { is possible, but already invites at least a move repetition with }19...Qc8 { . This is the theoretically cleanest solution. If you want to keep the game going, you can play }19...Rac8 { , }19...Rfc8 { or }19...Qe6 { with typical compensation.    Admittedly, this is a bit of a gamble at this point, since White has a slightly easier time developing his queenside than in other variations. The resulting positions remain in the draw range, though often in heavy piece endgames with extra pawns for White if he plays precisely. For example:     B1)  }19...Qe6 20.Bd2! { Here this move works well, as White recovers the  b7 -pawn when White takes on  b2 . }20...Rfe8 21.Rd1 Rac8 { Just a sample variation, though fairly typical. White has managed to get the bishop away from  c1  and therefore has an improved version compared to other variations. However, the position is in the drawing margin because the white queenside pawns are still under pressure.     B2)  }19...Rfc8 20.Rxd7 ( { ( }20.Qb3 { White can also leave the queens on the board. }20...Qe6 21.Bd2! Bxb2!? { wins the pawn back for now, however, }22.Rb1 Be5 23.Rb5! Qxb3 24.axb3! { a clever move order, which due to the double attack against  e5  and  b7  then ends up in a drawn endgame with an extra pawn again. Capturing with the a-pawn somewhat invalidates  ...Rc2  because this is no longer a double attack. }{ ) } )20...Rxc4 21.Rb1 Rc2 { gives Black activity, but White also has a rook on the seventh rank. } ) )
19. Rfc8{ The check on  d1  would still yield nothing. We continue to play simply for compensation along the c-file.  The  f8 -rook is the right rook here, since it doesn't allow  Bh6  with tempo. }
20. Rxc8+{ The check on  d1  would still yield nothing. We continue to play simply for compensation along the c-file. }{ Let's take this as a sample variation }( {  A)  }20.Bh6 Bxb2 { immediately loses the extra pawn here for White }{ . }( {  B)  }20.Qd5 Qe7 { also leads nowhere. White can try to play }21.Be3!? { , hoping to get the  b7  pawn in exchange for  b2 , but that doesn't work either. }21...Bxb2 22.Rb1 Rd8! { This drives the queens away from attacking  b7 , so we can just retreat the bishop right away. }23.Bg5!? ( { ( }23.Qc4 Be5  )( 23.Qb3 Bd4 { wins a tempo against  c5  and saves the pawn.) } )23...Rxd5 24.Bxe7 Rd7= { with an even endgame. } ) )
20. Rxc8
21. Qe2{ The best square from where the queen keeps  c2  and  d3  protected, but also the pawns on  b2  and  e4  remain covered. }( { For example, }21.Qb3 Qd4 { gives Black more concrete counterplay against  e4 . } )
21. Qd4{ A simple human move. Black continues to tie down the  c1 -bishop to  b2  and is ready for ... Re8  or even ... Rc4 , which immediately wins the  e4 -pawn. }( { The engine gives }21...h5!? { as the main move, which stops }22.g4 { and makes }22.Bh6 { less dangerous for our back rank - these are Stockfish's ideas after  21...Qd4  - however none of this is really a big factor. } )
