1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. b4( { This is the main move after }5.Nbd2 Bg7 { -  see here . Here, it is objectively not a particularly critical move. } )
5. Bg7{ I want to follow the rule that we play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against all setups with  e2 - e3 . }( { Still, let me point out that the immediate }5...a5!? { is also very strong. If White plays the automatic }6.b5 { , Black can play }6...cxb5! 7.cxb5 Bf5⩱ { , followed by }-- ...e6 { and even }-- ...Bd6! {    }{ In this exchange structure, we might not necessarily want our bishop on  g7  and White is just overextended.. } )
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. a4{ A typical move to advance and take control of the whole queenside. }( { A natural developing move like }7.Be2 { would give Black different options.     A)  }7...a5!? 8.b5 cxb5 9.cxb5 { is one option with a symmetrical structure and no problems for Black. }9...a4!? { is a typical move to isolate the  b5 -pawn. }{     B)  }7...dxc4! { This is a very energetic way of playing. Black continues with  ...b5  and  ...a5 . For example, }8.Bxc4 b5! 9.Bb3 a5! { when Black gets a nice queenside structure. } )
7. a5{ As usually, I prefer to fight back on the queenside if White advances their pawns so bravely. }
8. b5{ The normal reaction. }
8. cxb5
9. axb5( 9.cxb5 { Leads to an exchange structure that is certainly not worse for Black. }9...Bf5 { is a good way to take control over the  b1 - h7  diagonal. Next, we will play ... Nb8 - d7 - b6 , ... Rc8  and start our play on the c-file. } )
9. dxc4
10. Bxc4
10. Nbd7{ Black will play ... Nb6 , ... Ne4 , ... Bf5  when all our pieces come to good squares. }
