2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. g6
5. Be2{ This move does usually transpose to other chapters once White plays  Nb1 - c3 ,  Nb1 - d2  or even  b2 - b3 . Let's still quickly discuss independent options. }
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. b4{ In these  b4 -variations, we have seen many variations where Whtie got punished if their king was stuck on  e1 . This won't be a problem here. On the other hand, Black's kingside is also fully developed and we can just fight back on the queenside. }
7. dxc4{ The strongest move. }( 7...a5 8.b5 dxc4 9.Bxc4 cxb5 10.Bxb5 { and now either }10...Bd7 { or }10...Ne4 { , followed by }-- ...Nd6 { to fight for the control of the  b5 -square and mobilise our queenside pawns is also extremely typical. } )
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ We have the exact same position with White's knight on  c3  instead of  b1  in the  Chinese Recipe chapter . Even though the knight is slightly vulnerable on that square, it is still by far better to have it developed.  We can play in the same spirit. }
9. Bd3{ The most active square, stopping ... Bf5  and also keeping an eye on  b5 . }( {  A)  }9.Be2 a5 10.bxa5 Qxa5 { is similar just that Black has the extra possibility }...Bf5 { . } )( {  B)  }9.Bb3 { makes Black life even easier. }9...a5 10.bxa5 c5! { is immediately possible as White cannot take on  b5 . If }11.dxc5 { , then }11...Ne4 12.Nd4 Nxc5 { wins back the pawn and  a5  is the next one who bites the dust. } )
9. a5{ The idea behind Black's last moves, White is pretty much forced to take. }
10. bxa5
10. Qxa5
11. Nbd2{ The development of the knight to  d2  looks logical to go to  b3  and control the  c5 -square. }
11. Be6{ Given the circumstances, the best square for the bishop. White's a-pawn is quite vulnerable and Black has nice play on the queenside.  In the sister variation, Black had to be extremely precise to achieve the ... c5  break in time as White has different ideas controlling this square. This is still an important plan but with the extra tempo, Black is under much less pressure and can also play for their piece activity. }
12. Nb3
12. Qc7{ With a balanced position. Black always waits for good moments to play ... e5  or ... c5  but here, we also have the creative idea ... Nbd7 , ... Ra4 , .... Bc4 , ... Rfa8 , activating the pieces and fighting for the control of the light squares. }
