5. Nc3
5. Bg7
6. b4{ This move has been played by famous players like Kasparov, Korchnoi and Aronian. It is the typical idea to expand on the queenside but most players prefer to do it with the knight on  d2  instead. }
6. O-O
7. Bb2{ The typical follow-up of  b2 - b4 . }( 7.a4 Bg4 { is similar. } )
7. Bg4{ A very instructive move. With the knight on  c3  instead of  d2 , Black has the much easier time to fight for ... e7 - e5 . First of all, because the knight is blocking the  b2 -bishop but also because the knight on  f3  cannot be replaced by the other one! }( {  A)  }7...Be6!? { can be played with similar intentions just that Black wants to provoke  c4-c5  first to reduce the pressure against the  d5 -pawn. }8.c5 Bg4!? { Not the only move but very typical. }{ Next, we can go ... Nbd7  and ... e5 . } )( {  B)  }7...a5 { is a typical reaction and also playable here. }8.b5 a4!? { is a typical pawn sacrifice. We have the idea to play  ...a4-a3  and if White plays }9.Nxa4 { , we simply have compensation as our pieces get activated with tempo and White is many moves away from castling. For example, }9...Qa5+ 10.Nc3 Bg4!?=∞ { with the idea to eventually go ... e5  or ... c5 . } )
8. Qb3{ A very ambitious move to allow doubled pawns on the f-file to unpin the knight. This was the move that Kasparov played when he was faced with this position in a simul and he found some followers.  Nevertheless, White's king will never be completely safe and that's a big price to pay. }
8. Bxf3{ Accepting the challenge. }
9. gxf3
9. e6{ A strong move. Now, White can no longer go for the symmetrical exchange structure and taking on  d5  would only open our e-file. }
10. Be2
10. Nbd7{ Normal development but with White's king on  e1 , we can always consider opening up the center with ... e5  and ... c5  - despite the lack of bishop pair. }
11. f4{ This was played in most games to take control over the  e5 -square. }
11. dxc4{ Black is fully developed and now ready to open the position. }
12. Qxc4{ The better move to recapture.  White should keep the defender around their king. }( { After }12.Bxc4 { , there is no clear refutation but Black has many very attractive options. }12...a5!? { is a typical move to attack White's pawns. If White tries to keep it closed with }13.b5 { , we have different good moves.    }13...Ng4 { with the idea  ...Qh4  is a nice idea.    }13...a4!? { to sacrifice a pawn and deflect more of White's pieces from the kingside, is also very strong. } )
12. Nd5{ Black can follow up with ... Qh4  when the  f2 -pawn is a weakness and ... Nxe3  becomes a threat. White's king is dancing around in the center. }
