4. g6( { You have reached the  g3 -section of this course - the last of White's main setups after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 { .    When consulting the databases yourself, you might be surprised why I dedicated 4 chapters. Depending on the database and the concrete position that you use for your search, the move   }4.g3 { will be ranked somewhere between number 3 and number 6 on the list of the most popular moves. There are 2 reasons why I felt I had to cover the  g3 -lines in quite some detail:     1.  You won't encounter the following lines only via the Slav move order but they can also be reached by other first moves. You can reach this position via the Reti   }1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 { , the English   }1.c4 c6 2.g3 { , maybe even against   }1.d4 { players who like to postpone pushing their c-pawn and play }1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . So overall, you can play our lines even against many flexible White players!     2.  The second reason is that we have to share the theory of these lines with many King's Indian and Grünfeld players. For example after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 { , the move }3.g3 { became increasingly popular and I don't expect the trend to stop anytime soon. It is often considered one of White's easiest setups and when you look at the lines with modern engines, you get the feeling that 90% of the variations that Black players used to play against this move, lead to really good positions for White if they know what they are doing. There are not many setups that the engines like. However, on the top of the list is }3...c6 { , followed by }-- 4...d5 { and it became pretty much the main setup for KID and GID players against the fianchetto. On the one hand, this means that you can have a lot of trust in the objective value of the following positions. On the other hand, it means that this is pretty much the most theoretical position in the whole course!    }{ Nevertheless, don't be discouraged: As an author, I felt obliged to give a very comprehensive view on White's tries but as a player, a lot of this information is more of a 'nice to know'. This is certainly not one of the chapters where you risk a passive position if you mix up your move order.          Rules for the  g3 -chapters:    You start with  4...g6 ,  5...Bg7 ,  6...O-O  against everything.     Usually, White plays  Bg2  in the meantime  O-O  as those are equally the most flexible moves for them.     At some point, White needs to think about their  c4 -pawn.     In the next chapters, we will discuss White's main options:     23)   Exchanging on d5      24)   Playing  Qd1 -b3      25)   Playing  b2 - b3 / Nb1 -d2     In this chapter, we will look at the sacrificial lines and rather odd moves to protect the pawn.    } )
