7. Ne5{ In the exchange variation, this is a normal move to immediately use the outpost. Here, the center is not fixed yet and that means that you usually have to be more careful if you move a piece twice in the opening.  Actually, Black can simply get a good position by creating some dynamics. }
7. dxc4{ A very reliable choice, not giving White the option to transpose into some kind of exchange variation with  cxd5  later. }
8. Na3{ Trying to take away on  c4  with a piece that is not already placed actively in the center. However, the knight on  e5  doesn't achieve anything and can easily be exchanged.  Exchanges help Black in this structure as they have less space and so typically more problems finding good squares for their pieces. }
8. Ng4{ Exchanging the first pair of knights. }
9. Naxc4
9. Nxe5
10. Nxe5{ This has been exclusively played in practice. }( 10.dxe5 { has never been played in practice and }10...Be6 { does actually look terrible for White. The engines find a very concrete way to keep the balance but Black is sitting on the easier side of things. }11.Qxd8! Rxd8 12.Na5! b6 13.Bxc6! { White has to give up the bishop to keep Black busy. }( { ( }13.Nxc6? Nxc6 14.Bxc6 Rac8 15.Be4 Bxe5∓ { would just be horrible for White as Black is fully developed and White has problems getting their pieces out.) } )13...Nxc6 14.Nxc6 { Attacking  d8  and  e7 . }14...Rd7 { White is a pawn up but their whole setup is really unstable. Black will just play ... Rc8  and ... Rdc7 . For example: }15.Bf4 Rc8 16.Rfc1 Rdc7 17.Nd4 Rxc1+ 18.Bxc1 { and Black wins their pawn back }18...Bxa2 { is the easiest way to do it. } )
10. Nd7( { Black is planning to exchange the second pair of knights. In the game Sandalakis - Skembris, Kallithea 2009, Black played }10...Be6 { and got a similar position. This game can be seen in the model game section -  see here  - as it shows how easy Black's play in this structure is if some pieces get exchanged.    After }10...Nd7 { , White can respond with }11.Nf3 { to keep }{ pieces on the board but this allows an easy ... e7 - e5  if Black just wants to equalise. In the game  Speelman - Shipov, Hastings 1998 , Black showed that it is not even necessary to strike back in the center immediately - despite the space disadvantage. We have enough good squares for our pieces: ... Qb6 , ... Rd8 , ... Nf6 - e4 , etc. } )
