7. a4{ A move that came to my attention only after publication, but which has become quite fashionable lately. The idea is not so stupid: White wastes no tempo on protecting the  c4 -pawn. }( { If Black takes the pawn with }7...dxc4 { the move  a2 - a4  fits well into the white concept, since Black has a harder time protecting it with ... b5 . However, if Black does not take  c4 , the question is what to play instead. For example, if Black plays the natural }7...Bf5 { , White can simply continue with }8.Nc3 { and White has gotten rid of the worry about the  c4  pawn almost completely without any concession. (Taking the pawn afterwards - for example with }8...dxc4 { - doesn't really convince since White often wins the pawn back after all and can later play  e2 - e4  with tempo.) } )
7. Be6{ This is Stockfish 16's favorite move and it also fits well into the repertoire. Black shows his willingness to take (and keep) the pawn on  c4  - but only on our own terms. }( {  A)  The immediate }7...dxc4 8.Na3 { promises White a slight advantage, as the  c4  pawn falls quickly }{ . }( {  B)  }7...Bf5 8.Nc3 { is, as mentioned, the white idea. Now White has come around to protecting the  c4 -pawn, since }8...dxc4 9.a5 { with ideas like  Qa4  often recovers the pawn after all and allows  e2 - e4  later with tempo } )( {  C)  }7...a5 { is possible to ask White how he actually intends to develop further. But the position seems a bit too static to me here - especially after }8.cxd5 { -, but White has other tries as well and can play solid with }8.Na3 { or in gambit style with }8.Nc3 { . White has several options and slight practical pressure. } ) )
8. Nc3( { The clear main move. White plays similar to the variation   }7.Nc3 { . }{ The insertion of  a2 - a4  and ... Be6  can have advantages for both sides. Both moves are not atypical in positions where Black takes the gambit pawn out, however they also have disadvantages. Black can play ideas with  ...Bg4  only by losing a tempo, while White gives away the  b4 -square, which makes especially the knight manoeuvre  ...Na6 - b4 - d3  a main resource in Black's game. } )( {  A)  }8.Ng5 { makes little sense. We can simply retreat the bishop with }8...Bc8 { , but the easy }8...Bf5 { works as well . }{ Yes, again, White could now avoid spending a tempo on covering the  c4 -pawn, because ... dxc4  would run into  e2 - e4  again. But instead White has their knight standing on  g5  which is now absolutely horribly placed. Black can always gain a quite useful tempo against the knight with ... h6  - but even if we don't attack the knight, it will probably soon return to  f3  voluntarily }{ . }( {  B)  }8.Na3 { anticipates ... dxc4 , but if we don't take on  c4 , the knight doesn't stand very impressively here }{ . }8...Na6 { is only one of several reasonable moves. } )( {  C)  }8.a5!? { is always a halfway reasonable idea in anticipation of ... dxc4 , but it's not really convincing either }{ . }8...dxc4 9.Na3 { isn't possible now, because the  a5 -pawn is hanging. And also otherwise Black has easy play with ideas like  ... Na6 -b4 ,  ...Bd5 , but also  ... Ne8 -d6  to open the  g7 -bishop and keep the pawn for the moment or to counter quite dynamically with an early ... c5 . } ) )
8. dxc4{ If White sacrifices the pawn like this, we should take it now. }
9. e4{ White plays this move here in the vast majority of cases. The big center is supposed to compensate for the missing pawn. }
9. Na6{ In this variation White virtually invites us to play  ...Nb4  and possibly  ...Nd3  - so let's do it! }
10. Qe2( { This is also a common move and in practice the main alternative to }10.h3 { , but usually White still plays  h2 - h3  in the near future. } )
10. Nb4
11. h3{ The main move. White usually can't play without this move. }( {  A)  }11.Be3?! Ng4! { shows one of the reasons. Black wins the  d4 -pawn or the bishop pair. }12.Bg5 ( { ( }12.Bf4 Bxd4!∓ { Here we would simply have an outright extra pawn.) } )12...h6 13.Bd2 Bxd4 14.h3 Ne5 15.Nxd4 Qxd4 16.Bxh6 Rfd8 { Here, White still got the  h6 -pawn plus Black's bishop for the  d4 -pawn, and yet Black is clearly on top. Without the  d4 -pawn, the only white advantage in the position - the big center - has disappeared and Black has wonderful play along the d-file and on the queenside. } )( {  B)  }11.Rd1 { White can also play a few more waiting moves, but it doesn't change our general setup. }11...Nd3⇆ { , followed by  ...Qa5  works pretty well. } )
11. Nd3{ Not the only move, but this knight manoeuvre, followed by  ...Qa5  gives us good play. }
12. Be3
12. Qa5{ We have successfully activated our pieces and White has no easy way to win back the pawn. White has compensation with the strong center, but Black's position is very comfortable. }
