[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Beautiful Symmetry: 4.g3 Schlexchange"]
[Black "Introduction g3-Exchange"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. cxd5
7. cxd5{ Yes, even the  g3 -lines have their exchange variation! The position will be extremely symmetrical but not necessarily for too long. As you will see, there are different plans on how to create active play in these positions and - from an objective point of view -, we can be very happy that our knight has the  c6 -square.    Arguably the main idea to create imbalances in this line is by playing  Nf3 - e5 /... Nf6 - e4  and take on  c6 / c3  to change the pawn structure.     One side creates a potentially weak pawn in the opponent's camp, the other side gets more influence in the center.    Luckily for us, the practice has shown that the resulting positions are equally playable for both sides so we can either play this manoeuvre ourselves but we can also just welcome our opponent to take our knight on  c6  if they put their knight on  e5 !    Rules for this chapter:    - You start with ... g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O     - Most of the time, you can just follow up the autopilot with ... Nc6  and ... Bf5 . }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) Beautiful Symmetry: 4.g3 Schlexchange"]
[Black "7.Nc3 & 8.Qb3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. cxd5{ The exchange variation can even be played in the  g3  setups. Even though these symmetrical positions can generally be seen as a little bit drawish, I think I found some nice lines to create imbalances for Black. }
5. cxd5
6. Bg2( { White cannot really play without this move. White can also start with }6.Nc3 { or }6.Ne5 { but  Bg2  will be part of White's setup anyways.  With Black, }{ we just continue with   }6...Bg7 { and }-- 7...O-O { against all moves. } )
6. Bg7{ Our set-up in this line is very easy. We play ... O-O , ... Nc6  and ... Bf5  - usually in this move order.  The main approach for White is to play  Nf3 - e5  and take on  c6 . This creates an obvious imbalance in the pawn structure. But we'll also look at the lines where White keeps the structure symmetrical. }
7. Nc3( { For White players, there are some subtleties between starting with }7.Nc3 { and }7.O-O { . However, our setup with }...O-O { , ... Nc6  and .... Bf5  is so resilient against different move orders that I had trouble finding any lines starting with  7.Nc3  that don't transpose to  7. O-O !     I chose  7.O-O  as main move order and will discuss only very weird attempts in this  7.Nc3 -variation. } )
7. O-O
8. Qb3{ This move loses a lot of its purpose in this variation. Usually, this move protects a pawn on  c4  to make sure that White has no need to take on  d5 . Also, the pressure against  d5  or  b7  can sometimes play a role.  Well, we cannot play ... Bf5  here but besides that, the queen move doesn't make too much sense. Nevertheless, it is White's most played move that does not transpose to other lines, so let's check it real quick. }
8. Nc6{ Our usual developing scheme. }
9. Bf4{ It is hard to find another useful move to look at. }( 9.Bg5 Ne4!⩱ { is just a good version of our typical knight move.  d4  is weak and dropping back with the bishop from  g5  is just an unnecessary tempo loss for White. } )( 9.O-O { transposes to  this variation . } )
9. Na5{ Not the only move but simple enough. Black just wins a tempo against the queen and the knight might even become active on  c4  afterwards. }
10. Qb4{ I think it is just not possible to justify White's  Qb3  move, so I will not even try it. Wherever the White queen goes, it can be attacked with tempo.  The 'advantage' of  10.Qb4  is that the only move to attack the queen here is ... Nc6  which might lead to a repetition - something we avoid in this repertoire. }
10. Ne4{ A typical move. We centralize the knight, open up the butcher and might take on  c3  if we want. }
11. O-O{ It's hard to recommend another move. }
11. Nc6{ Now, we just go back with the knight. It is not with the idea to go for a repetition, we just want to centralize the knight before we go ... Nxc3 . If White recaptures on  c3  with the queen, we might have legitimate pressure against  d4 . }
12. Qb3( 12.Qb5 a6 13.Qb3 Nxc3 { is similar. } )
12. Nxc3{ Forcing White to make a decision. Either they recapture with the pawn when Black will have the typical pressure along the c-file or White has to recapture with the queen when it might not be particularly safe on the c-file as well and pressure against  d4  is also coming. }
13. Qxc3( { Keeps the symmetry but only Black can be better. }13.bxc3 { allows the standard manoeuvre }13...Na5! { , followed by, for example, ... b6 , ...  Bb7 , ... Rc8  with nice counter chances. } )
13. Bg4{ Threatening to take on  f3  and win the  d4 -pawn. }
14. Rfd1{ White should protect  d4  with a rook. }( 14.e3?! f6!∓ { with the ideas }-- ...g5 { but also just }...e5 { is very hard to deal with for White. } )
14. Rc8{ Black has some nice pressure with the better-coordinated pieces. }
