1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. cxd5{ The exchange variation can even be played in the  g3  setups. Even though these symmetrical positions can generally be seen as a little bit drawish, I think I found some nice lines to create imbalances for Black. }
5. cxd5
6. Bg2( { White cannot really play without this move. White can also start with }6.Nc3 { or }6.Ne5 { but  Bg2  will be part of White's setup anyways.  With Black, }{ we just continue with   }6...Bg7 { and }-- 7...O-O { against all moves. } )
6. Bg7{ Our set-up in this line is very easy. We play ... O-O , ... Nc6  and ... Bf5  - usually in this move order.  The main approach for White is to play  Nf3 - e5  and take on  c6 . This creates an obvious imbalance in the pawn structure. But we'll also look at the lines where White keeps the structure symmetrical. }
7. Nc3( { For White players, there are some subtleties between starting with }7.Nc3 { and }7.O-O { . However, our setup with }...O-O { , ... Nc6  and .... Bf5  is so resilient against different move orders that I had trouble finding any lines starting with  7.Nc3  that don't transpose to  7. O-O !     I chose  7.O-O  as main move order and will discuss only very weird attempts in this  7.Nc3 -variation. } )
7. O-O
8. Ne5( { This move will most likely transpose to lines with   }7.O-O { -  see here  but let's see what happens if White postpones castling. } )
8. Bf5( { We can also start with }8...Nc6 { but let's give White one more chance to transpose with  9.O-O  to the main lines before we allow White to take on  c6 . } )
9. Bf4( { Still postponing castling.    }9.Qb3 { with an attack against  b7  and  d5  can be strongly answered with }9...Nc6! { when White's center is also under a lot of pressure.     A)  }10.Nxc6 bxc6 { leads to a (typical) structure where the queen on  b3  is quite pointless.     B)    }10.e3?! Nxe5 11.dxe5 Ne4 { is just slightly better for Black. The pawns on  e5  and  d5  are both vulnerable, but White also has some problems with their king in the center. For example, }12.Nxd5? Qa5+ { is already very problematic. }13.Nc3 Bxe5 { and White's position is under too much pressure. }12.Qxd5? Nxc3 13.bxc3 Qxd5 14.Bxd5 Bxe5 { simply leads to a horrible structure for White.     C)  The best move for White seems to be   }10.Be3 { when Black has more than one good move. I personally like }10...e6 { most which overprotects  d5  and prepares  ...Nxe5  as well as  ...Nd7 . White's queen on  b3  is not really threatening of they can't take one of our pawns, but }11.Qxb7? Nxe5 12.dxe5 Ng4! { is actually playing with a lot of fire. If White loses the  e5 -pawn, Black is just better and even though White has some tricks to keep the pawn on the board for now, it would only be at the cost of a horrible position. }13.Bc5!? Qc8! { If White takes, the  e5 -pawn will be lost and after }14.Qb4 Rd8 15.f4 { , White has an extra pawn but with }...Rb8 { , ... d4  and ... f6  coming, Black gets too much activity. } )
9. Nc6{ A normal move. Still, we offer White to transpose. }
10. Nxc6{ Taking on  c6  and then trying to fix the weaknesses on the c-file is the only justification that I can think of why White didn't just castle like any sane person! }( { A different move order that leads to the same position is }10.Rc1 Qb6 11.Nxc6 bxc6 { . } )
10. bxc6
11. Rc1{ White might feel clever, choosing this move order that keeps more influence along the c-file. However, there is a reason why castling is important in the opening! Just some small tactics allow Black to get very decent versions of this exchange structure. }( 11.Na4?! { is another typical move to control the c5-square but the uncastled king becomes a problem here as well. }11...Qa5+! { An unpleasant check. White doesn't have too many replies that make sense. }12.Bd2 { Coming with tempo but now the  d4 -pawn is no longer protected by the queen. }12...Qb5 { Black can just continue executing different typical ideas under good circumstances. For example ... Ne4  or ... Nd7  (with the idea to go ... e5 ) will now be with tempo as  d4  is hanging when the  g7 -bishop opens up. }13.O-O Qc4!? { Besides the just mentioned ideas, this is also a very irritating move for White. .... Qxd4  and ... Bc2  are threats while }14.Bc3 Ne4! { wins the bishop pair under good circumstances. } )
11. Qb6{ A nice move, using the fact that White has not castled. Putting pressure on  d4  and  b2  is logical but usually, it runs into  Nc3 - a4  with tempo. But not with White's king on  e1 ! }
12. b3{ This is the best move. }( { Positionally reasonable is }12.Na4? { . However }12...Qb4+!∓ { is just a very annoying check. White has no good way to parry the check without losing  a4 ,  b2  or  d4 ! } )
12. Nd7{ A standard move to prepare ... e5 . Here, we have a good version for Black, because White also has to worry about the hanging  d4 -pawn. }
