6. Bg7{ Our set-up in this line is very easy. We play ... O-O , ... Nc6  and ... Bf5  - usually in this move order.  The main approach for White is to play  Nf3 - e5  and take on  c6 . This creates an obvious imbalance in the pawn structure. But we'll also look at the lines where White keeps the structure symmetrical. }
7. O-O( { We will have this as main move order for White even though most of the positions could also be reached via }7.Nc3 { . }7.Ne5 O-O { has no independent meaning. } )
7. O-O{ Castling, ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 ! That is the typical setup. }
8. Ne5( { This will usually transpose to }8.Nc3 { . }{ Developing the  b1 -knight to a different square than  c3  usually just doesn't work. } )
8. Nc6
9. Nxc6
9. bxc6{ Reaching a typical structure for this chapter. }
10. Nd2{ Bringing the knight to  b3  where it also controls  c5  while keeping the  d4 -pawn protected looks logical but the knight is really not particularly stable on  b3 . }
10. Qb6{ A very annoying move, attacking  d4  while also putting pressure along the b-file. This square is not available if White goes for  Nc3 - a4 ! }
11. Nb3{ The logical follow-up. }
11. a5{ Black can just advance on the queenside. The idea ... a4  makes it hard for White to develop the light-squared bishop. If White's knight jumps to  c5 , we can just exchange it with ... Nd7 . }
