10. Be3{ This slightly weird-looking move has some points to it. White overprotects  d4  which is important in some variations where we leave the  d5 -pawn hanging, hoping to win the  d4 -pawn back after ... Rfd8 . But White also increases the influence over the  c5 -square which is useful if White goes for a postponed  Ne5xc6  ... b7xc6  structure.  Lastly, it is also just a developing move without running into ... h6 /... g5  ideas. }
10. Qb6( { Black is still playing this move. If White plays a slow move like }11.b3 { , Black can just play }11...Rfd8 { and won't ever have any problems with the  d5 -pawn again. } )( { Now, let's look at the three forcing continuations   }11.Nxd5 { , }11.Nxc6 { and }11.Bxd5 { . } )
11. Nxd5{ Black will have no problems regaining the pawn after this move. }
11. Nxd5( { The easiest move. }11...Qxb2!? { does also work. } )
12. Bxd5
12. Rad8( { Creating some tension along the d-file. }12...Nxe5 13.dxe5 Qxb2⇆ { does also make sense to not allow White to take on  c6  and maybe provoke  f2 - f4 . } )
13. Bxc6{ It looks slightly unnatural to give up the light-squared bishop but otherwise Black gets quick counterplay in the center. }( 13.Nxc6 bxc6 { gives }{ Black very easy counterplay with ... Bxd4  next. The activity of the major pieces easily compensates for our slightly weakened structure. } )
13. Bxe5( { The most precise move. After }13...bxc6 14.Qc1⩲ { White does stabilise the extra pawn. There is always some compensation with the bishop pair but overall, White should be happy with this position. } )
14. dxe5
14. Qxc6{ Keeping the queens on the board. White is a pawn up but Black is super active.  White's queen is hanging, ... Bh3  is a threat. }( 14...Rxd1? 15.Bxb6 { will end at least in some extra pawns for White as they are currently bishop and pawn up and we can only take one piece at the time. For example }15...Rxa1 16.Rxa1 axb6 17.Bxb7+- { . } )
15. Qc1{ The only move that covers all the threats. White is trying to exchange queens. }
15. Qb5{ Keeping the queens on the board with pressure against  b2 ,  e2  and  e5 . Without the queens on the board, the opposite-coloured bishops would be a drawish factor but as we are still in the middlegame, they could also be the reason why one side gets checkmated! White's light squares are slightly weak - especially if White gives up the  e2 -pawn - and increasing the tension on the kingside with ... h7 - h5 - h4  is certainly in the air. }
