7. O-O( { We will have this as main move order for White even though most of the positions could also be reached via }7.Nc3 { . }7.Ne5 O-O { has no independent meaning. } )
7. O-O{ Castling, ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 ! That is the typical setup. }
8. Nc3
8. Nc6{ We are still following our development scheme. This position can be seen as main tabiya for the  cxd5  approach within the Fianchetto universe. }
9. Ne5{ This is White's main move. White wants to take on  c6  and create imbalances in the structure. }
9. Bf5{ We absolutely don't care about White's idea to go  Nxc6 . Indeed, we are welcoming this as it creates an imbalance in the pawn structure. }
10. Be3{ This slightly weird-looking move has some points to it. White overprotects  d4  which is important in some variations where we leave the  d5 -pawn hanging, hoping to win the  d4 -pawn back after ... Rfd8 . But White also increases the influence over the  c5 -square which is useful if White goes for a postponed  Ne5xc6  ... b7xc6  structure.  Lastly, it is also just a developing move without running into ... h6 /... g5  ideas. }
10. Qb6( { Black is still playing this move. If White plays a slow move like }11.b3 { , Black can just play }11...Rfd8 { and won't ever have any problems with the  d5 -pawn again. } )( { Now, let's look at the three forcing continuations   }11.Nxd5 { , }11.Nxc6 { and }11.Bxd5 { . } )
11. Nxc6{ This leads to one of the main pawn structures in this line. }
11. bxc6{ Going for the imbalanced structure. Black's pressure against the b-file is a compensating factor and Black will usually easily achieve ... e7 - e5  to strike back in the center. }
12. Na4{ By far the best move. The knight protects  b2 , attacks the queen and takes control over the  c5 -square which is usually a good thing to make sure that the  c6 -pawn remains a weakness. }
12. Qa6{ An interesting square. It might look weird at first glance to allow  Na4 - c5  with tempo but it is not clear if the knight is really better on  c5  and than on  a4 .      a4  is a pretty good square as it also protects  b2  and on  c5 , the knight would be undermined after a potential ... e5 .     Besides this, the queen does a nice job to keep an eye on  e2 . Especially in combination with ... Rfe8  and ... e5 , White might have to deal with the  e2 -pawn at some point. }
13. Re1{ Let's use this as a sample line to illustrate Black's plan as this was played in the most recent and highest-rated correspondence game that I could find with this position. It is just useful to overprotect  e2  for the future. }( 13.Nc5 Qb5 { doesn't change much about Black's plan to go ... Rfe8  and ... e5 . } )
13. Rfe8{ Preparing ... e5  }
14. h3{ In anticipation of ... e5  and ... Ng4 , this looks like a smart move but this pawn move can also be a weakness on the kingside. }
14. h5{ Fixing the g-pawn for now and also gives the ... h5 - h4  idea in the future. }
15. b3{ Let's use this as an explanatory line to illustrate Black's chances on the kingside. }
15. Qc8{ A very nice idea. Black brings the queen away from the queenside and pressurizes the kingside. }
16. Kh2( { This is a mistake but arguable a more logical move to take care of the h-pawn. }16.h4 { is better but Black gets the  g4 -square once again for the knight. }16...e5 17.dxe5 Ng4! { would be a good version of the  last trainable . } )
16. h4{ A very strong response. If Black can just continue with ... hxg3 , we will just be much better because of the advantageous structure. But can't wait just play  17.g4 ? }
17. g4{ Objectively, this makes things worse but it is the critical move. If Black drops back with the bishop, the last moves wouldn't make much sense. }
17. Bxg4{ This is at least winning a really juicy pawn because White's pieces are unable to defend the kingside. The stupid bishop on  e3  makes it especially to bring defenders as it Block's White's e-pawn. }
18. hxg4
18. Nxg4+
19. Kg1
19. Qc7{ Black's queen is coming in to  h2 , followed by ...  h4 - h3 . There is not much White can do about it. Moving the f-pawn loses the  e3 -bishop. }( 20.Kf1 Qh2 { Black will play ... h3  next. Black has potential mates on  h1 ,  g2  and  f2  so all of White's kingside pieces are tied down and Black can just remove some defenders with ... Bh6  or increase the pressure with ... e7 - e5 . } )
