3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. cxd5{ The exchange variation can even be played in the  g3  setups. Even though these symmetrical positions can generally be seen as a little bit drawish, I think I found some nice lines to create imbalances for Black. }
5. cxd5
6. Bg2( { White cannot really play without this move. White can also start with }6.Nc3 { or }6.Ne5 { but  Bg2  will be part of White's setup anyways.  With Black, }{ we just continue with   }6...Bg7 { and }-- 7...O-O { against all moves. } )
6. Bg7{ Our set-up in this line is very easy. We play ... O-O , ... Nc6  and ... Bf5  - usually in this move order.  The main approach for White is to play  Nf3 - e5  and take on  c6 . This creates an obvious imbalance in the pawn structure. But we'll also look at the lines where White keeps the structure symmetrical. }
7. O-O( { We will have this as main move order for White even though most of the positions could also be reached via }7.Nc3 { . }7.Ne5 O-O { has no independent meaning. } )
7. O-O{ Castling, ... Nc6 , ... Bf5 ! That is the typical setup. }
8. Nc3
8. Nc6{ We are still following our development scheme. This position can be seen as main tabiya for the  cxd5  approach within the Fianchetto universe. }
9. Ne5{ This is White's main move. White wants to take on  c6  and create imbalances in the structure. }
9. Bf5{ We absolutely don't care about White's idea to go  Nxc6 . Indeed, we are welcoming this as it creates an imbalance in the pawn structure. }
10. Nxc6{ This is White's most principled follow-up: taking on  c6  before Black can play ... Rc8  and get the option to recapture with the rook. }
10. bxc6
11. Bf4{ This position could also have been reached by a lot of other move orders where White plays  Bc1 - f4  earlier. }
11. Nh5{ I really like this move in this position. Annoying the bishop on  f4  is typical for this repertoire and here Black can combine it with nice dynamic ideas. }( { The standard move }11...Nd7 { is also playable here, preparing }-- ...e5 { . }{ White is slightly more flexible in the current position than in similar positions where we played ... Nd7 .  Qd2 ,  Rfd1 ,  Rac1  is the most popular setup. By delaying  Nc3 - a4  for a bit, Black cannot counter it with the ... Nb6  resource that is often working well against it. } )
12. Be3( { The typical response. }12.Bg5 { has also been played, but then the bishop can be hit with }12...h6! { . After }13.Be3 { , we can continue with }13...c5!? { like after the immediate  12.Be3 , but we can also switch plans and just use the tempo move to continue expanding on the kingside with }13...g5 { . } )
12. c5{ Black is creating a lot of pressure against  d4 . }
13. Nxd5{ This move has been exclusively played in the four games so far with the given position. }( {  A)  }13.dxc5?! d4! { is Black's idea. The fork forced White to at least give up both bishops. }14.Bxd4 ( { ( }14.Bxa8? Qxa8 15.Bxd4-+ { is giving Black many tactical options. }...Bh3 { or }...Rd8 -- ...e5 { are just winning.) } )14...Qxd4 15.Qxd4 Bxd4 16.Bxa8 Rxa8=∞ { . White has two pawns and a rook against two minor pieces but Black's pieces and especially the two bishops are really active. } )( {  B)  After a flexible move, like }13.Rc1 { , Black will follow up with }13...e5! { , }{ forcing White to take on  e5  or  c5  when we will go ... d5 - d4 . }13...Rc8 { to prepare ... e5  without the exchange sacrifice is also possible. } )
13. e6{ This wins back the pawn on  d4 . }
14. Nf4( { The only real square. }14.Nc3? cxd4∓ { wins material. } )
14. cxd4{ Black's idea behind  12...c5  is to sacrifice the exchange. By taking on  d4  first, we win a tempo against the  e3 -bishop, even though White can take on  h5 . }( 14...Nxf4 { is another approach. }15.Bxf4 cxd4! 16.Bxa8 Qxa8 { and Black has sufficient compensation here as well.  ...Bh3  is a threat and }17.f3 e5! { , followed by }-- ...e4 { creates a lot of pressure. } )
15. Nxh5{ White should use the possibility to destroy Black's pawn structure. }
15. gxh5
16. Bxa8( { If White refrains from being greedy, for example with }16.Bd2 { , Black can just save the rook and the strong central pawns should give us an easy game - both after }16...Rc8 { or }16...Rb8 { . } )
16. Qxa8( { Black is threatening   }17...dxe3 { and also }17...Bh3 { . }{ Black is not even forced to regain the exchange at the first possibility but can also increase the pressure against the kingside with ... h4  or ... e5  and ... e4  (after  f2 - f3 ). } )
