1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Qb3{ The move  Qd1 - b3  is often considered White's most ambitious option. White protects  c4  but also creates pressure against  b7  and  d5 .     Rules for this chapter:    - We answer with ... Qb6  and ... Rd8 .     - White usually has no interest in taking on  d5  too early - but if they ever do it, we want to recapture with the knight and - if possible - with the rook. This typically gives us very active pieces    I titled this chapter 'Doubtful Queens' because this constellation with queens on  b3  and  b6  invites the discussion if - and under which circumstances -, one should consider exchanging queens. The side that has its queen captured gets doubled pawns but also the open a-file. There is no rule that fits every time. I heard strong titled players claim that you should pretty much never exchange queens in these situations 'because the doubled pawns barely ever play a role while the a-file sometimes does', on the other hand, you can find plenty of positions where GMs decided to do it and score at least slightly above 50% - an indication that the decision could not have been completely bad.    My practical advice would be:    - Don't exchange queens unnecessarily. If you have no concrete idea how to exploit the changed structure, White's a-file will most likely be the bigger factor.    - If your opponent moves the  a1 -rook, it is a sign that we can consider taking. White will have fewer options on the a-file    - If we can prove that the  b3 -pawn is actually a weakness, we should take. Typically, this means that we have a concrete idea in mind of how we can put pressure on that pawn    - If our opponent provokes us to take, for example with  c4 - c5  or  Nc3 - a4 , it is also not the end of the world. }
