6. Qb3{ By postponing  O-O  , White is theoretically in time to exchange queens and take on  d5  without Black having the option to play ... Nxd5  and ... Rxd5 . Nevertheless, as we will see, this is not something White should do. }
6. O-O
7. Nc3
7. Qb6( { We are still following our setup. If White plays }8.O-O { , we will transpose to the main lines with }8...Rd8 { when Black will always be able to recapture on  d5  with knight and rook. } )
8. Qxb6{ This is barely played and that's not too surprising as Black is very comfortable in the resulting position. }( 8.cxd5 { is similar. Black can either take immediately recapture on  d5  with the knight or does the same after }8...Qxb3 9.axb3 { included.    }{ In both cases, Black remains with the better knight - ours will be developed to  c6  where it actively attacks  d4  while White's knight on  f3  is merely defending a pawn and is also blocking the bishop on  g2 . }{ For example,   }8...Nxd5 { - generally, we are happy to exchange the  f6 -knight against  c3  - }9.Nxd5 cxd5 10.Bd2 ( { ( }10.Qxd5 Nc6 { with pressure against }d4 { and }...Nb4 { ideas is slightly risky for White.) } )10...Nc6 11.Qxb6 axb6 12.e3 Rd8 13.O-O f6 { would be a move order that results in the same position as this trainable. } )
8. axb6
9. cxd5{ One problem of the exchange on  b6  is that White has to deal with the idea ... dxc4  again. }
9. Nxd5{ Typically, it is a good exchange to trade  f6 - against  c3 -knight. Our bishop gets opened up. }
10. Nxd5{ White has nothing better. }
10. cxd5{ This is obviously easy equality and from a practical perspective, we can be happy that our bishop has an open diagonal while White's bishop is still blocked by their knight. A possible continuation could be: }
11. O-O{ White develops. }
11. Nc6{ Black is creating pressure against  d4 . }
12. e3
12. Rd8( { The best square for the rook in these lines as it is always useful to overprotect the d-pawn.The immediate }12...f6!? { is also possible. } )
13. Bd2
13. f6{ With the idea to grab space via ... e5  and potentially ... e4 . Objectively, the position is equal but the imbalances add up and I am sure this position still promises a full-fledged game. }
