9. Bd2{ In some later trainables, you will see that I usually like a setup with ... Be6  to provoke  c4 - c5 . This move is somewhat directed against it. White wants to play an early  Rfc1  to keep the tension in the center. }
9. Bf5( { I recommend this simple developing move here. Our idea }9...Be6 { doesn't work here that well. White can play }10.Na4 Qxb3 11.axb3 { and now }-- 12.Nb6 { is a threat, so Black has to react and White will be in time to protect the  c4 -pawn with }12.Rfc1 { . The  d2 -bishop can often be activated via  b4 . } )
10. Na4{ The main move for White. }( 10.Rfc1 { gives Black a lot of options. they can play }10...h6 { , staying flexible with the idea to transpose after }11.Na4 Qxb3 12.axb3 Nbd7 { but they can also just grab the pawn with }10...dxc4 11.Qxc4 Qxb2 { . } )
10. Qxb3
11. axb3{ Once again, watch out for the  Nb6 -threat! }
11. Nbd7( { I like this move more than }11...Na6 { . Black plans to expand and play actively on the kingside with ... h6  and ... g5 . In those scenarios, it is useful to have the knight not on the rim of the queenside. With the light-squared bishop already developed from  c8 , this move doesn't have the drawback of trapping one of our own pieces. } )
12. Rfc1
12. h6
13. e3
13. g5{ Black can try to take over the initiative on the kingside. See the model game  Osmak - Muzychuk  if you want a possible continuation. }
