9. c5{ We shouldn't be afraid of this kind of structural transition. White provokes us to take on  b3  - and we should do it -, but they also take away the tension from the center. Black will usually get very decent counterplay with ideas like ... e7 - e5 . }
9. Qxb3
10. axb3{ White would love to somewhat use the a-file and combine it with ideas like  b3 - b4 - b5 . Even this wouldn't be the end of the world for Black. However, Black has no reason to allow it. }
10. Na6{ This controls  b4  and stops White's intentions with their b-pawn. }
11. Bf4{ This is White's normal continuation. The bishop controls a lot of vital squares like  c7  but especially  e5 . }
11. Nd7{ The next moves for Black are extremely thematic. It is all about preparing ... e7 - e5 . }
12. Rfd1{ This is the only move that we will have a closer look at. Black's play is pretty straightforward anyway.  Push ... e5  and then expand even further on the kingside.  12.Rfd1  is by far White's main move because it sets up the idea  e2 - e4  in a lot of positions.  If Black plays ... Re8 , plays ... e5  and allows a mass exchange on that square, this does often lead to positions where Black's rook is no longer protecting the back rank. In this scenario,  e2 - e4  might be annoying because Black cannot take it without giving White's rook access. }( { (   }18.e4! { is one example. }{ ) But even without Black playing ... e5 , the rook is often useful in situations when White pushes  e2 - e4 . } )
12. Re8
13. h3
13. h5{ I think, we should stop White from playing  g3 - g4 . This wins space and gives the dark-squared bishop some retreating squares on the powerful long diagonal. White now has plenty of moves.  Let me end the trainable with a motif that you should keep in mind. }
14. Kh2{ This waiting move was played in  Folk Gilsanz - Van Wieringen, ICCF email 2014 . Now Black executed a nice idea. }
14. e5
15. Nxe5
15. Bxe5
16. Bxe5
16. Nxe5
17. dxe5
17. Bf5{ Black doesn't take the pawn right away but just finishes their development first. We will win back the pawn later and will remain with a superior structure. }( 17...Rxe5? { allows the typical motif we talked about earlier. }18.e4! dxe4 19.Rd8+ Kg7 20.Nxe4± { and Black has problems finishing their development. } )
