12. Re8
13. e4{ White's most forcing option. As we have seen, it is useful not to allow Black the ... e5 -break. }
13. dxe4
14. Nxe4{ A double-edged position. White gained a little bit of activity through the  e4 -break, on the other hand, Black does now have an easy plan as  d4  is a backward pawn and the  d5 -square is weak:  Just develop all your pieces towards the control of the  d5 -square. Once the total control is established, regroup your pieces so that they attack the weakness on  d4 . }
14. Nb4{ I will stop the trainable here and show you the next moves, and how Peter Svidler handled this position. }( 15.Bd2 Nd5 16.Nc3 N7f6 17.Ne5 Be6 18.Nc4 Red8 { Phase 1 is completed. Black has full control over  d5 . The next stage is to attack the weak pawn on  d4 . }19.Ne2 Ne8! { The knight was controlling  d5  but it also blocked the bishop on  g7 . Svidler reroutes the knight to a square without this disadvantage. }20.Na5 Rd7 21.Bf3 Rad8 22.Be1 Rb8 { Not an ideal square but  b7  needed protection.    }23.Nc4 { Here, }23...Ndc7 { would have given Black the advantage in  Sakaev -Svidler, Moscow 2007 . The knight is coming to  b5  and }24.Rxa7 Nb5 { wins the d-pawn against the a-pawn which is a pretty good exchange for Black. } )
