8. Rd8{ It makes sense to keep an eye on the  d5 -pawn. White had no direct threat, but this move keeps the tension and doesn't allow White to play  9.Qxb6  and  10.cxd5  with a symmetrical pawn structure longer than absolutely necessary. Black is ready to recapture on  d5  twice with pieces.  In this position, White players played a lot of different moves. One of the reasons why this variation is so popular at the highest level is the existence of many hidden subtleties in different move orders that make it hard for Black to play the next moves on autopilot.  I will give you different ideas on how to play the resulting positions. Guidelines for this repertoire:  - We want to provoke  c4 - c5  in many positions     - often we achieve this by playing ... Be6 . Once we have achieved this goal, the structure is much more defined and the tension in the center is reduced. Black's typical source of counterplay in the resulting structure is the plan to go ... e7 - e5 .     - Besides ... e5 , Black has no clear pawn breaks that are advantageous for him. In closed positions without pawn breaks, we have two ways to improve our position:      1)  Bringing our pieces to better squares.     2)  Winning space with our pawns. If the queens come off, we should keep the plan in mind to expand with our pawns on the kingside. The strength of this plan can be seen in the model game Osmak vs Muzychuk -  see here . }
9. Rd1{ This is White's main move. White simply strengthens their d-pawn. }
9. Be6( { This is a sideline but White players failed to show anything against it. Most players go for }10.c5 { , but this is hardly threatening. } )( 9...Bf5 { is the main line. Black is threatening  ...Qxb3  and  ...Bc2 , so White usually goes for }10.Ne1 { . }{ Here, Black can go for the same plan (just with the knight on  e1  instead of on  f3 ) by playing }10...Be6 { . }{ The plans remain very similar. Overall, the knight looks more passive on  e1  but if it jumps to  d3  and potentially  c5 , things might not be so clear. } )
10. c5{ The most popular move. Even though I don't think that it is particularly critical. }
10. Qxb3( { This is the normal reaction. In some positions, it is possible to keep the queens on with }10...Qa6?! { , but 'playable' is the best-case scenario and often it is just asking for trouble, like here with }11.Bf1! { . } )
11. axb3
11. Nbd7( { A typical move is }11...Na6 { to control the  b4 -square and block the a-file. However, I don't think that we need the knight here and we can instead develop our pieces towards the center and the kingside where we want to start our counterplay. } )
12. b4
12. a6{ The queenside play has stopped for now. In the next moves, we will start our counterplay on the other side of the board. The typical ways to do this are by either preparing ... e7 - e5  or by winning more space with our kingside pawns. }( { A typical way how the game could continue is }13.h3 h6 14.g4 g5 { . So far, both sides have tried their best to win as much space as possible with their pawns. In the next moves, Black coordinates the pieces on the kingside and once their pieces are ideally placed, they will look for the most promising pawn break on the kingside. }15.Nh2 Nf8 16.Nf1 N6h7 17.Ng3 Ng6 18.f3 Nh4 19.Be3 Nf8 20.Na4 f5! { and Black took over the initiative in  Kolehmainen, K. - Delgado Ramirez, N., ICCF email 2019 . } )
