7. b3( { In this chapter we turn our attention to the moves }7.b3 { and }7.Nbd2 { . I put both moves in the same chapter because the variations transpose very easily when White starts with }7.Nbd2 { - }{ the bishop has very few better opportunities to develop than with an early  b2 - b3 .    There are a few harmless independent variations that we'll look at first. Otherwise, against both moves, our counterplay is similar.     Rules:     - We play ... a5  to be able to play with ... a4  on the queenside.     - A good way to develop your pieces is to use the  e4 -square as an outpost. Both ... Ne4  and ... Be4  are moves we will see more often in this chapter.    - When our pawn is on  a4 , both ... a4 - a3  and ... axb3  are important resources in our position. We should not decide too early on one of these two options, but remain flexible, and wait for a good moment to make one of the two moves. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Fianchetto Triple - 7.b3 and 7.Nbd2"]
[Black "7.Nbd2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nbd2( { In my opinion, this is just less flexible than starting with }7.b3 { . }{ In those lines, White is often happy to have the knight on  b1 , for example, to stop Black's a-pawn with  Nb1 - c3 . }{ After }7.Nbd2 { , White has some independent options but they really cannot convince. } )
7. a5( { This will transpose in most cases to  the lines  after   }7.b3 { . } )
8. e3{ This slow move stabilizing the center has been played by some Grandmasters. I guess you can claim that there is no big idea behind the move itself.  However, the fact that White hasn't developed their queenside yet (and it won't become easier once Black has pushed ... a4 ) is often a sign that White wants to ignore the queenside altogether in the next few moves and build up their position on the kingside to its maximum instead.     Typical follow-ups for White in this regard are  Ne5  and  f2 - f4 . If provoked, White might even expand further with  g2 - g4 . This is the reason why I don't recommend ... Bf5  against this sideline - White might be happy to see it if they have aggressive kingside intentions. }( { The immediate }8.Ne5 { is sometimes played with similar intentions. However, this is even less flexible. Both }8...Nbd7 { as well as }8...a4 { followed by }-- 9...Nbd7 { are very much in the spirit of our setup. } )
8. a4{ For now, there is no reason why we should stop our plan of expanding on the queenside. }
9. Qe2( { This is slightly more flexible than the immediate }9.Ne5 { . }{ Nevertheless, with the passive bishop on  c1 , White should look out for a justification soon why they buried this guy alive on the queenside. } )
9. Be6{ Black stays flexible as well. The plan is still to answer  Ne5  with ... Nbd7 . }( { As mentioned, I think }9...Bf5 { might play in White's cards with some potential  g3 - g4  advances. } )
10. h3{ White still tries to make flexible moves. However, they will soon run out. }( 10.Ne5 Nbd7⩱ { is always our reply. } )
10. h6{ A nice move. Black is not unhappy about the waiting game.  Now, they can play ... Nbd7  without being hit with  Ng5 . So very soon, Black will be fully developed and ready to blow up the center with a potential ... c5 . White can always try to limit the dynamics of the position by taking on  d5  but even if Black recaptures with the c-pawn, White's pieces will be weirdly placed for a version of the Exchange structure. }( { And if White plays }11.Ne5 { , we will just answer }11...Nbd7 { and White's only real active piece is about to get exchanged. } )
