7. a5( { This will transpose in most cases to  the lines  after   }7.b3 { . } )
8. e3{ This slow move stabilizing the center has been played by some Grandmasters. I guess you can claim that there is no big idea behind the move itself.  However, the fact that White hasn't developed their queenside yet (and it won't become easier once Black has pushed ... a4 ) is often a sign that White wants to ignore the queenside altogether in the next few moves and build up their position on the kingside to its maximum instead.     Typical follow-ups for White in this regard are  Ne5  and  f2 - f4 . If provoked, White might even expand further with  g2 - g4 . This is the reason why I don't recommend ... Bf5  against this sideline - White might be happy to see it if they have aggressive kingside intentions. }( { The immediate }8.Ne5 { is sometimes played with similar intentions. However, this is even less flexible. Both }8...Nbd7 { as well as }8...a4 { followed by }-- 9...Nbd7 { are very much in the spirit of our setup. } )
8. a4{ For now, there is no reason why we should stop our plan of expanding on the queenside. }
9. Ne5{ A logical follow-up of White's last move but not very flexible. }
9. Nbd7{ This is a simple solution. }( {   }10...Nxe5 11.dxe5 Ng4 { is a legitimate threat and exchanging the knights on  d7  would be horrible after the precious time that White used to bring the knight to the 'active'  e5 -square. } )
10. Ndf3{ The more pieces get exchanged, the more obvious it becomes how horrible the bishop on  c1  is. So we are very happy to just take on  e5 . }
10. Nxe5
11. Nxe5( { Now, Black has several good moves - including the immediate }11...c5 { . However, I find the next moves quite instructive. } )
11. dxc4{ Exchanging the d- for the c-pawn but Black will be able with tempo on the next move and ... c6 - c5  will follow soon, breaking White's solid-looking center. }
12. Nxc4
12. Be6{ Black is fully developed, wins a tempo against the knight and is ready to strike with a quick ... c5 . }
