7. b3
7. a5{ I always liked this early a-pawn push against the  b3 -lines. Black just wins some space and is ready to play ... a4  to soften White's queenside. }
8. Bb2{ This move doesn't stop our a-pawn, so we should keep advancing. }
8. a4
9. cxd5
9. Nxd5{ Not necessary, but I think a good moment to avoid symmetry. Our  g7 -bishop is opened up and we will get active play on the queenside. Especially, if we already have concrete counterplay - like here with our a-pawn on  a4  -, these Grünfeld ideas are often working very nicely. }
10. Na3{ This is the engine's suggestion. White just develops before they decide if  e2 - e4  should be played. }
10. Bf5{ Even though allowing  e2 - e4  is not the end of the world (see  lines  with  10.e4 ), we shouldn't make it easier than necessary. This move is also preparing ... Be4 , a typical move in this variation. }
11. Ne5( {  A)  }11.Nh4 Be6 { is not leading anywhere for White. If White wants to play for  e2-e4 , they should have done it under better circumstances on move 10! } )( {  B) A move like }11.Re1 { just allows }11...Be4 { . } )
11. Nb6{ Avoiding the fork with  e2 - e4 . }
12. e4{ It is hard to recommend something different for White. Usually, Black doesn't mind exchanging some minor pieces with this pawn structure because they have less space. }( { So if White plays it slow with something like }12.Nac4 { , Black will be happy to develop their pieces with a move like }12...N8d7 { . } )
12. Bxe5{ It is an interesting decision to give away the two bishops here. However, Black will remain with the better pawn structure, no matter if White takes on  e5  or  f5 . }
13. exf5{ This move keeps the game in the middlegame. However, Black can keep their dark-squared bishop and won nice control over  d5 . }
13. Bg7
14. fxg6{ Not forced but this pawn was hanging and usually White has no better plan for this plan in any case. }
14. hxg6{ Black's play is pretty straightforward. We will play ... e6  to strengthen control over  d5 , ... N8d7 , something like ... Qe7  and ... Rfd8  and will have good squares for all our pieces while we can also decide when we take on  b3  to open up the queenside. }
