[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25) Fianchetto Triple - 7.b3 and 7.Nbd2"]
[Black "7.b3 & 8.Nc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. b3
7. a5{ I always liked this early a-pawn push against the  b3 -lines. Black just wins some space and is ready to play ... a4  to soften White's queenside. }
8. Nc3{ This is White's most popular reaction. From the  c3 -square, it stops Blacks  a5 - a4  move. }
8. Ne4{ A typical move! Black is ready to exchange the knight on  c3 , which is the defender of the  a4 -square, but Black also fights for control over the  e4 -square. ... Bf5 , ... Nxc3  and ... Be4  is a typical manoeuvre to solve the problem to find a safe square for our dark-squared bishop. }( { In this regard }8...Bf5 { would also fit in our setup but the text move is more forcing as White has to protect  c3 . } )
9. Bb2
9. Bf5{ A nice setup. We want to take on  c3  anyways, but we are in no rush to do so.  Here, White has tested different moves in practice but Black always has very harmonious ways to develop their pieces. }
10. Nh4
10. Nxc3
11. Bxc3
11. Be6{ Usually, we just drop back to  e6  as an answer on  Nh4 . }
12. Qd3{ Once Black has played ... a5 , White can try to take on  d5  and prove that the  b5 -square is a little bit weak. However, it is really not a big deal.  Another idea of  12.Qd3  is the idea to just support the center with  Rad1  and play an early  e2 - e4  to open up the center. }
12. Nd7
13. Rad1{ This move is in the spirit to play in the center with  e2 - e4 . It is nothing to be afraid of but there is no need to allow that. }
13. Nf6{ Now,  e2 - e4  has been stopped and it is questionable why White moves their rook away from the queenside as Black is ready to open it with ... a4  (and potentially ... b5 ). }
