[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. g3
4. g6
5. Bg2
5. Bg7
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. b3
7. a5{ I always liked this early a-pawn push against the  b3 -lines. Black just wins some space and is ready to play ... a4  to soften White's queenside. }
8. Nc3{ This is White's most popular reaction. From the  c3 -square, it stops Blacks  a5 - a4  move. }
8. Ne4{ A typical move! Black is ready to exchange the knight on  c3 , which is the defender of the  a4 -square, but Black also fights for control over the  e4 -square. ... Bf5 , ... Nxc3  and ... Be4  is a typical manoeuvre to solve the problem to find a safe square for our dark-squared bishop. }( { In this regard }8...Bf5 { would also fit in our setup but the text move is more forcing as White has to protect  c3 . } )
9. Bb2
9. Bf5{ A nice setup. We want to take on  c3  anyways, but we are in no rush to do so.  Here, White has tested different moves in practice but Black always has very harmonious ways to develop their pieces. }
10. Ne5{ A clever move. White opens up the bishop on  g2  to make the ... Nxc3  & ... Be4 -maneuver (seemingly) less attractive. Also, White's bishop does now put pressure on  e4  and (if Black takes on  c3 )  d5 . }
10. Nxc3{ I like the idea of still continuing with the ...  Nxc3  & ... Be4  manoeuvre. This looks like a good way to create imbalances. }
11. Bxc3
11. Be4{ A slightly provocative move as White's  10.Ne5  was directed against this idea. In general, there are three potential ways how White can try to 'punish' Black for this cheeky ... Be4 -move.      1.  White can simply take on  e4  and prove that Black's pawn will become weak      2.  White can play  f2 - f3 , Black has to go back with ... Bf5  and White can try to prove something concrete with the two tempi that Black has lost with the bishop. Black, on the other hand, will try to prove that  f2 - f3  is nothing but an ugly positional move.      3.  White can play the tricky  Bh3  move. This threatens  f2 - f3 , winning the  e4 -bishop under pretty good circumstances.  Let's look at these three moves. }( 11...Qb6?! { just drops a pawn. }12.cxd5 cxd5 13.Bxd5±  )
12. f3
12. Bf5{ If White wants to prove the  f3  move rather useful than a liability, it makes sense to combine it with ideas to advance in the center (with  e4 ) or on the kingside (with  g4 , maybe with  f4  at some point).     With this in mind, it is often a useful move to drop back with the bishop to  e6 . This does not only put potential pressure on the  c4 -pawn, but it also avoids moves like  e4  or  g4  with tempo. Besides that, Black has the typical break ... a4  to create counterplay but also ... c5  might be a nice move to create counterplay in the center. }
13. f4{ A logical follow-up. The pawn on  f3  was blocking the  g2 -bishop.  Now, the bishop is free and the f-pawn stabilises the center. Sometimes,  g3 - g4  and  f4 - f5  might be an idea for White. }( { The }13.e4 { idea is very hard to accomplish under good circumstances with the knight on  e5 . }13...Be6 { might be a decent reply as well but strong is the typical response }13...Bxe5! { White can either take on  e5  or  f5 , but in both cases, they will be left with a weakened pawn structure. }14.exf5 ( { ( }14.dxe5 dxe4 { is even worse for White when they might be left with isolated e-pawns with no real attack.) } )14...Bg7 15.fxg6 hxg6 { White's structure feels slightly overextended. } )
13. Be6{ A strong prophylactic move. The bishop is quite useful on  e6  and it cannot be hit with the  g4  tempo.  Black will continue with simple developing moves like ... Nd7 , possibly ... Nf6  and ... Ne4 , but also has the counterplay ideas with ... a4 . }( 14.g4?! { is not particularly powerful when it is not coming with tempo. After }14...f6! { , White has no good follow-up. } )
