8. Ne4{ A typical move! Black is ready to exchange the knight on  c3 , which is the defender of the  a4 -square, but Black also fights for control over the  e4 -square. ... Bf5 , ... Nxc3  and ... Be4  is a typical manoeuvre to solve the problem to find a safe square for our dark-squared bishop. }( { In this regard }8...Bf5 { would also fit in our setup but the text move is more forcing as White has to protect  c3 . } )
9. Bb2
9. Bf5{ A nice setup. We want to take on  c3  anyways, but we are in no rush to do so.  Here, White has tested different moves in practice but Black always has very harmonious ways to develop their pieces. }
10. Ne5{ A clever move. White opens up the bishop on  g2  to make the ... Nxc3  & ... Be4 -maneuver (seemingly) less attractive. Also, White's bishop does now put pressure on  e4  and (if Black takes on  c3 )  d5 . }
10. Nxc3{ I like the idea of still continuing with the ...  Nxc3  & ... Be4  manoeuvre. This looks like a good way to create imbalances. }
11. Bxc3
11. Be4{ A slightly provocative move as White's  10.Ne5  was directed against this idea. In general, there are three potential ways how White can try to 'punish' Black for this cheeky ... Be4 -move.      1.  White can simply take on  e4  and prove that Black's pawn will become weak      2.  White can play  f2 - f3 , Black has to go back with ... Bf5  and White can try to prove something concrete with the two tempi that Black has lost with the bishop. Black, on the other hand, will try to prove that  f2 - f3  is nothing but an ugly positional move.      3.  White can play the tricky  Bh3  move. This threatens  f2 - f3 , winning the  e4 -bishop under pretty good circumstances.  Let's look at these three moves. }( 11...Qb6?! { just drops a pawn. }12.cxd5 cxd5 13.Bxd5±  )
12. Bxe4
12. dxe4{ This line can become quite concrete. Black might be forced to play ... f5  at some point to protect the  e4 -pawn.  (In a lot of cases, it is useful to play it ... f6   Ng4  ... f5  because then everything is coming with tempo.)     In the resulting scenario, the  e5 -knight needs to be exchanged rather sooner than later and often it is the right decision to give away our precious  g7 -bishop! This leaves our king slightly vulnerable but we will be left with no bad pieces and often have nice control over the light squares. }
13. Qc2( { This is the most forcing move to see what I was talking about. White can also start with a move like }13.Rc1 { but the positional ideas remain the same. } )
13. f6{ Winning the tempo. }
14. Ng4
14. f5
15. Ne5( { Here concretely, this is pretty much forced because }15.Ne3 Bxd4! { is indeed a pawn that Black can simply take. But on a more general note, Black might also use the new won control over the  e5 -square to prepare a well-timed ... e7 - e5  break if the knight does not go back to  e5 . } )
15. Bxe5{ An important move. Our king gets a little bit soft on the dark squares but White cannot exploit it immediately and Black will soon be ready for a blockade on the  e6 -square. }( 15...Nd7 16.Nxd7 Qxd7 17.Rad1 { should be slightly better for White. } )
16. dxe5
16. Nd7{ The knight is heading towards  e6 . Let's stop the trainable here, but let's point out that the blockade on  e6  is often even more important than winning the pawn on  e5 . }( { So for example after }17.Rad1 Qc7 { , Black has never the intention to take on  e5  but usually just continues with ... Nc5  and (possibly) ... Ne6 . White, on the other hand, should not hesitate to rather sacrifice the e-pawn with  e5 - e6  as the open diagonal is crucial for White to stay in the game - even though this leads to nothing more than compensation for the pawn. } )
