7. b3
7. a5{ I always liked this early a-pawn push against the  b3 -lines. Black just wins some space and is ready to play ... a4  to soften White's queenside. }
8. Nc3{ This is White's most popular reaction. From the  c3 -square, it stops Blacks  a5 - a4  move. }
8. Ne4{ A typical move! Black is ready to exchange the knight on  c3 , which is the defender of the  a4 -square, but Black also fights for control over the  e4 -square. ... Bf5 , ... Nxc3  and ... Be4  is a typical manoeuvre to solve the problem to find a safe square for our dark-squared bishop. }( { In this regard }8...Bf5 { would also fit in our setup but the text move is more forcing as White has to protect  c3 . } )
9. Bb2
9. Bf5{ A nice setup. We want to take on  c3  anyways, but we are in no rush to do so.  Here, White has tested different moves in practice but Black always has very harmonious ways to develop their pieces. }
10. e3{ This is White's most popular move. White strengthens their center and is preparing  Qd1 - e2  to improve the queen and connect the rooks. }
10. Nxc3{ It is important to take on  c3  at some point. Now, we are able to play ... Be4  but we can also develop our queen to  b6  from where her majesty is controlling some nice squares on the queenside. (With the knight on  c4 , White could always play  Na4  in response.) }( { We can also start with }10...Nd7 { . } )
11. Bxc3
11. Nd7( 11...Be4 { is also a very popular move. I personally prefer to start with }11...Nd7 { , as after the most popular move }12.Qe2 { , }12...Qb6 { is the fastest way to finish development. } )
12. Qe2( { This has been exclusively played in this position. Let's point out that the  ...Qb6  move should only be played with the queen on  e2  because something like }12.Rc1 Qb6?! 13.Nh4 Be6 14.e4 { can be a little bit annoying. }14...dxe4? 15.d5! { would be a problem for Black. } )( { So after }12.Rc1 { , Black should just go for the other standard move }12...Be4! { . } )
12. Qb6{ The logic of Black's setup: Exchange the knight on  c3 , so that ... Qb6  can be played without any problems connected with  Nc3 - a4 . Now, Black has a harmonious setup on the queenside. }
13. Rfc1
13. Rfc8{ The rook will be nicely placed on the c-file in all kinds of situations. In the case of  cxd5   cxd5  , the rook will be on the open file but even if White doesn't take, the rook might be useful to support ... c5 . }( 13...Be4 { is an extremely solid choice. The main drawback is that White can play the typical }14.Bh3! { with the idea to simply play something like }-- 15.Nd2 { and win the bishop under good circumstances. So, Black should continue with }14...Bxf3! 15.Qxf3 e6 { . A similar situation to variations with  e2 - e3  and  Bd3  -  see here . White has the bishop pair but Black has a very solid structure.  Practice has shown that this is a reliable option for Black, however, I don't think that Black has the same dynamics as in the  e3 / Bd3  lines. That's why I choose  13...Rfc8  as the main move in our repertoire. } )
14. Ne1{ This is the engine suggestion if White doesn't want to allow ... Be4 . But all our pieces are on nice squares, so we are not afraid of these kinds of 'subtle' moves. For example, }( 14.h3 Be4 { was played in  Meier,G. -Paehtz,E., Douglas 2016 . Note that  14.h3  took away White's option to go  Bg2 - h3 . In this sense, our 'useful waiting move'  13...Rfc8  was very successful. } )
14. Nf6{ Bringing the knight to better squares.  e4  looks like a nice potential outpost. }
15. Nd3( { Controlling the  e4 -square and potentially preparing  g3-g4  with }15.f3 { is not a bad idea but }15...c5! { is a typical reaction. } )
15. a4{ with counterplay on the queenside. }
