[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "Introduction London System"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4( { I don't have to explain the London system to anyone. 15 years ago it was an opening that was often not taken seriously, but now it's probably the most popular opening in the world, especially at the amateur level.    The opening brings with it a certain simplicity. 'Don't hurt me, I won't hurt you.'    White often enough sets up the simple setup }2.Bf4 { , }-- 3.e3 { , }-- 4.Nf3 { , }-- 5.Bd3 { , }-- 6.Nbd2 { , }-- 7.c3 { , }-- 8.O-O { - although real London experts usually know a lot of subtleties regarding the move order and know when to deviate from the setup. } )( { Typically, there are two different move orders for White:     A)  The modern }2.Bf4 { . }{ One of the reasons why the London System had its renaissance a few years ago was the discoveries of new ideas in variations where White postponed the move  Ng1 - f3  for a bit. }{     B)  The classical }2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 { . After the London System returned to the surface, people found new ideas here as well.    Fortunately, our main line can be played against both move orders!    I have thought for a long time about which variation I should analyze that is most in the spirit of our repertoire.    A natural choice seems to be a setup with }3...g6 { but there are different reasons why I decided against it.     First of all, I was not completely convinced that Black can really equalise in those lines.     Second of all, I talked a lot in this course about the importance of the butcher on  g7  and that it is important to activate it. Playing this setup against the solid pawn formation  c3 ,  d4 ,  e3  makes it definitely harder to achieve this goal.     If Black could achieve ... c5  and ... e5  really soon - and this is indeed one of Black's main ideas in the ... g6  variations-, it would underline this rule perfectly. However, by looking at the positions more concretely, it seems that achieving both breaks under good circumstances is not so easy and White has ways to get an advantage against this simple approach.    The third reason against this setup was that it doesn't promise us easy transpositions anyways. If you remember, usually, we like to answer  Bc1 - f4  in the Slav with ... d5xc4  - this is obviously not possible against the London move order.    In the end, I was looking for a variation that plays with a different idea that we've seen a lot in this course with a bishop on  f4 : Going for the bishop pair ... Nh5 !    And I actually found the perfect variation! Our setup against the London System is }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { and in most of your games, Black will be ready to play ... Nh5  after that. }{    Let me point out one last important thing because you might be wondering how to play ... Nf6 - h5  if White postpones  Ng1 - f3 . }{ Let me explain this with the move order }2.Bf4 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Nd2 c5 5.c3 Nc6 { . Normally, it is important for White to answer the move }-- 6...Bd6 { with }7.Bg3 { , since }7.Bxd6 Qxd6 { usually allows Black a quick ... e6 - e5 . However, the bishop retreat only prevents the e-pawn from advancing if the  e5 -square is controlled once more. Long story short: White should therefore play }{   }6.Ngf3 { , which allows }6...Nh5 { directly and then leads to variations we will discuss via the  2.Nf3  move order. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "2.Bf4 & 4.c4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4{ One of the reasons why the London System had its renaissance a few years ago was the discoveries of new ideas in variations where White postponed the move  Ng1 - f3  for a bit. }( { Luckily for us, in the variations with  ...e6 , White barely has additional options and the main variations will be discussed in the variations via }2.Nf3 Nf6 Bf4 { -  starting here . Here, we will just look at some relatively rare options for White. } )
2. Nf6{ This is the most flexible move in my opinion. }( 2...c5 { usually leads to the same position but it gives White the additional option }3.e4!? { which is a weird Albin Counter Gambit (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 { ) reversed. Not really threatening but if we can cut this option, why not? } )
3. e3( 3.Nc3 { leads to the  Jobava London . } )
3. e6{ The start of our setup as mentioned in the  Introduction . }
4. c4{ Entering Queen's Gambit position with this move is not really in the spirit of most London Players and even objectively it is not particularly good. Black can just play a setup where the early bishop move is not part of White's usual setup. }
4. c5{ This Setup against the Queen's Gambit is often called Semi-Tarrasch. White's critical main response is usually  cxd5  to provoke an isolated pawn after ... exd5  or force the  f6 -knight in the center after ... Nxd5  where it can potentially be hit with  e4 .     As the bishop on  f4  would be immediately attacked if Black recaptures with the knight and White even spent a tempo on  e2 - e3 , this option can be pretty much ruled out as it can only be played under very bad circumstances. }
5. Nf3( { In most games where this position occurs, White accepts the isolated pawn with either }5.Nf3 { or }5.Nc3 { .     A)  }5.Nc3 cxd4 6.exd4 { is very similar. } )( {  B)  }5.cxd5?! Nxd5 { doesn't make much sense. } )( {  C)  }5.dxc5 { is barely played as it leads to Queen's Gambit positions with pretty much a clear tempo down for White. In the line   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 Be7 5.Bf4 O-O 6.e3 c5 7.dxc5 { , White plays this move when Black has already spent a tempo on  ...Be7  - and this is still one of Black's most respected responses! Playing this being a tempo up should be a dream come true for us!   }5...Bxc5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.Nc3 O-O { This is Black's usual developing scheme. }{ Typical ideas are preparing ...  e5  - for example with ... Re8  - but also ... d4  to open up the center.  Especially as we have a well-known variation with extra tempo, we might even look for more aggressive approaches. ... Qa5  or even ... Bb4  with ideas like ... Ne4  can certainly also be taken into consideration. } )
5. cxd4{ This leads to an IQP in most games. }
6. exd4{ It is very typical that White's c-pawn gets exchanged against Black's d-pawn in these positions - mainly because Black takes at some point and then White will have an isolated pawn on  d4 .     In these positions, White rarely puts the bishop on  f4 . Sometimes it gets developed to  e3  to overprotect the  d4 -pawn but the most active square is usually  g5  where the bishop puts some pressure on Black's kingside. White might consider avoiding this structure with  c4 - c5 .     If we can answer this with ... b6  and force White to take the pawn, we usually don't mind.  If White can however strengthen their pawn chain with  b2 - b4  and potentially  a2 - a3 , this might be something to avoid. Our next move does anticipate this scenario. }( { There is no clear refutation to }6.Nxd4 { but White's setup is really awkward. }6...Nbd7 { develops with tempo as  ...e5  is an annoying threat but }6...Bb4+ { is also annoying, starting some threats on the diagonal against White's king. } )
6. Bb4+( { There is not much wrong with }6...Be7 { but White can play  c4 - c5  more easily. With ... Bb4 + we create much more concrete action for now and White literally cannot play  b2 - b4  if they push  c4 - c5  and we respond with .... b6 . } )
7. Nc3
7. O-O{ Black brings the king to safety and now simply plans to develop with ... b6  and ... Bb7 . This solves the problem of our light-squared bishop and we also stop  c4 - c5 .     At some point, we take on  c4  but we usually wait until White has spent a tempo with the bishop on  f1 . }( { Don't blunder with the immediate }7...b6?? 8.Qa4+!+- { . } )( { The only move that anticipates the idea is   }8.a3 { to drive away the bishop. But this tempo loss can be used to create concrete play against White's structure. }8...Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 Qa5!? { Attacking  c3 . The next moves might be ... Nc6 , ... b6 , ... Bb7 , then potentially ... Rac8  or starting with ... dxc4  first. White's pawns are vulnerable. } )
