[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "2.Bf4 & 4.Nd2: Move Order Trickery 6.Bg3 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4{ One of the reasons why the London System had its renaissance a few years ago was the discoveries of new ideas in variations where White postponed the move  Ng1 - f3  for a bit. }( { Luckily for us, in the variations with  ...e6 , White barely has additional options and the main variations will be discussed in the variations via }2.Nf3 Nf6 Bf4 { -  starting here . Here, we will just look at some relatively rare options for White. } )
2. Nf6{ This is the most flexible move in my opinion. }( 2...c5 { usually leads to the same position but it gives White the additional option }3.e4!? { which is a weird Albin Counter Gambit (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 { ) reversed. Not really threatening but if we can cut this option, why not? } )
3. e3( 3.Nc3 { leads to the  Jobava London . } )
3. e6{ The start of our setup as mentioned in the  Introduction . }
4. Nd2( { Besides }4.Nf3 { that leads to our  2.Nf3 -variations -  see here - , this is the most popular move order. } )( 4.c3 { is another move that holds back  Nf3  but we just continue with }4...c5 { and White doesn't really gain anything from this move order. } )
4. c5
5. c3{ Finishing the typical London triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . }
5. Nc6{ An important position!     Most Black players follow up with ... Bd6 . If White exchanges the bishop, Black's queen will replace the bishop and after that, ... e5  will certainly come. }( { So it is usually important for White players to answer   }6...Bd6 { with }7.Bg3 { . However, this does only stop }...e5 { if White has the square once more under their control. } )( { So, most White players will now play }6.Ngf3 { when we finally transpose to  2.Nf3 - variations  and can play our long-awaited }6...Nh5! { . } )
6. Bg3{ If White knows what we are up to, this can be considered a tricky move order. }( { We still cannot play  ...Nh5  and }6...Bd6 7.Ngf3 { leads to one of the  ...e6  main positions that White is most likely ready to play.  Another idea behind this move is to go  f2-f4  and enter a Stonewall setup. Nevertheless, White's move is slow and doesn't do much for the development so Black should have no big problems equalising. } )
6. Be7( { Avoiding the transposition with }6...Bd6 7.Ngf3 { to the variation that we  don't  want to play. } )
7. Bd3{ The most flexible move order. White holds back the development of the knight which stops ... Nh5  and allows  f2 - f4 . }( 7.Ngf3 Nh5 { leads to one of the variations that we are aiming for. } )
7. O-O{ We just continue with our development. }
8. f4{ The independent try but we have a strong response. }
8. b5{ A very nice response. If you cannot exploit White's light-squared holes immediately in the Stonewall - like here -, the plan ... b7 - b5 - b4  is often one of the best options to create strong counterplay before White can build up on the kingside.  Here, we can push the pawn forward without preparation because taking the pawn can lead to problems with White's uncastled king. }
9. Bxb5{ The critical move. }
9. Qb6{ White has some problems on the b-file. If the bishop drops back, we can just take on  b2 . If White exchanges on  c6 , they have sacrificed their most valuable piece and Black is ready to keep White's king in the center with a quick ... Ba6 . }
10. a4{ This is White's best move by far. White stabilizes the bishop. If Black wants to drive it away, we have to play ... a6  which will make it harder for us to continue with ... Ba6 . }( {  A)  }10.Bxc6 Qxc6 { is pretty horrible for White. Black has ... Rb8  to pressurize the  b2 -pawn and ... Ba6  to keep White's king in the center.  If White wants to block the diagonal with  Ne2 , Black gets additional options with ... Ng4 . Black simply has great compensation. } )( {  B)  }10.Ba4 Ba6! { does also keep White's king in the center. } )( {  C)  }10.Qa4 Bd7! { Only makes matters worse for White. Black will not have ... Ba6  after an exchange on  c6  - which is something that Black can force with ... a6  or even ... Rab8  - but Black will recapture with tempo and play ... Bb5 . } )
10. a6
{ White can also drop back with the bishop but Black can just take on  b2 . }11. Bd3
11. Qxb2{ Black has won back the pawn and threatens the  c3 -pawn. }
12. Ne2{ The best move. White develops, protects  c3  and has the idea of  Rb1  which would at least be a repetition for White.  So we have to drop back with our queen. }
12. Qb6{ Escaping from any potential repetition. }
13. O-O
13. Ng4{ A very strong idea. Black attacks  e3  with tempo and plans to close down the kingside with ... f5 . This will stop White's whole kingside initiative and we can safely continue with our queenside play afterwards. }
14. Rf3{ White doesn't really have a better move to protect the pawn. }
14. c4( { This seems to be even more precise than the immediate }14...f5 { . It seems worth it to release the tension to not give White some options to use the  d4 -square with something like }15.Rb1 Qc7 16.dxc5 Bxc5 17.Nd4 { even though this does also look like a very pleasant position for Black. } )
15. Bc2
15. f5{ White has no kingside attack and Black is just better on the queenside. We will have a fight for the b-file after ... Bd7 , ... Rab8  and Black can start to target White's weak pawns with ... Qa5  or ... Be7 - a3 - b2 !? once White's rook has left the a-file. }
