6. Bd3{ If White continues to play without  Nf3 , we can execute our other plan. }( { The same reply would also happen after }6.h3 { for example. } )
6. Bd6
7. dxc5{ A rare move as it loses influence in the center. But it is one way to stop an immediate ... e6 - e5 . }
7. Bxc5( 7...Bxf4 8.exf4 { looks like an interesting pawn sacrifice to weaken White's structure but I don't think that Black does really have something completely convincing to exploit it. } )
8. Ngf3{ White has enough control over  e5  but without a pawn on  d4 , this control can easily be lost. }
8. h6{ A nice multipurpose move. Taking away the  g5 -square for White's bishop is not only useful if we go for ... e6 - e5 , it does also prepare our typical ... Nh5 . }
9. h3{ White can respond with this typical London move to address ... Nh5  - the bishop gets a square on  h2  - but from a practical perspective, the inclusion of h-pawn moves should be helpful for Black as  Bf4 - g5  is never possible. }
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Re8{ Black is threatening ... e6 - e5 - e4 . }
11. e4{ I think this is the most logical reply. White has to strike back in the center at some point and as this move does also stop the fork on ... e6 - e5 - e4  fork, it looks like good timing. }( {  A)  }11.Ne5 { does stop ... e6 - e5  for now but it is barely a stable outpost and Black can pretty much force White to take on  c6  which will increase Black's central influence. }11...Bd6 12.Nxc6 ( { (or }12.Ndf3 Qc7 13.Nxc6 bxc6 { ) } )12...bxc6 13.Bxd6 Qxd6 { Black will play ... e5 , ... Be6 , putting a rook on  b5 , maybe ... a5 - a4 - a3 . Black's central control should give Black an easy game. } )( {  B)  }11.b4 { is not a bad move, it only postpones White’s decision for one move. The bishop can go to any possible square, I would most likely just go }11...Bb6 { to keep as much central influence as possible. } )
11. e5{ That's why we played ... Re8 ! We shouldn't allow White to push  e4 - e5 . }
12. Bg3( 12.Bh2 { is similar even though  g3  looks slightly more active - at least potentially, it could go to  h4 . } )
12. dxe4{ It is always a pity to release the tension in the center but this mass exchange does at least create clear imbalances. Against other moves, we might have to deal with ideas like  b2 - b4 - b5  to undermine the  e5 -pawn. }
13. Nxe4
13. Nxe4{ White's knight attacked our bishop, so it is logical to exchange on  e4 . ... f6  also becomes possible. }
14. Bxe4
14. Qxd1{ Black's plan is to restrict White's kingside pieces with ... f6 . This move does however open up our king quite a bit - the light squares will be extremely weak, so it makes sense to exchange the queens before White can start a mating attack. }
15. Rfxd1
15. f6{ Restricting both the knight on  f3  as well as the bishop on  g3 . I would give White a slight plus in activity as they control the only open file and the bishop on  e4  looks really good but we can quickly fight for the d-file, ... Be6  will pressurize White's queenside and especially the bishop on  g3  is just a very sad piece. }
