[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "2.Bf4 & 4.Nd2: The Flexible 6.Bd3 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4{ One of the reasons why the London System had its renaissance a few years ago was the discoveries of new ideas in variations where White postponed the move  Ng1 - f3  for a bit. }( { Luckily for us, in the variations with  ...e6 , White barely has additional options and the main variations will be discussed in the variations via }2.Nf3 Nf6 Bf4 { -  starting here . Here, we will just look at some relatively rare options for White. } )
2. Nf6{ This is the most flexible move in my opinion. }( 2...c5 { usually leads to the same position but it gives White the additional option }3.e4!? { which is a weird Albin Counter Gambit (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 { ) reversed. Not really threatening but if we can cut this option, why not? } )
3. e3( 3.Nc3 { leads to the  Jobava London . } )
3. e6{ The start of our setup as mentioned in the  Introduction . }
4. Nd2( { Besides }4.Nf3 { that leads to our  2.Nf3 -variations -  see here - , this is the most popular move order. } )( 4.c3 { is another move that holds back  Nf3  but we just continue with }4...c5 { and White doesn't really gain anything from this move order. } )
4. c5
5. c3{ Finishing the typical London triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . }
5. Nc6{ An important position!     Most Black players follow up with ... Bd6 . If White exchanges the bishop, Black's queen will replace the bishop and after that, ... e5  will certainly come. }( { So it is usually important for White players to answer   }6...Bd6 { with }7.Bg3 { . However, this does only stop }...e5 { if White has the square once more under their control. } )( { So, most White players will now play }6.Ngf3 { when we finally transpose to  2.Nf3 - variations  and can play our long-awaited }6...Nh5! { . } )
6. Bd3{ If White continues to play without  Nf3 , we can execute our other plan. }( { The same reply would also happen after }6.h3 { for example. } )
6. Bd6
7. dxc5{ A rare move as it loses influence in the center. But it is one way to stop an immediate ... e6 - e5 . }
7. Bxc5( 7...Bxf4 8.exf4 { looks like an interesting pawn sacrifice to weaken White's structure but I don't think that Black does really have something completely convincing to exploit it. } )
8. Ngf3{ White has enough control over  e5  but without a pawn on  d4 , this control can easily be lost. }
8. h6{ A nice multipurpose move. Taking away the  g5 -square for White's bishop is not only useful if we go for ... e6 - e5 , it does also prepare our typical ... Nh5 . }
9. O-O{ This allows ... Nh5  and - you know me - I am always happy to play it. }
9. Nh5{ Going for the bishop! Let's show some sample lines to illustrate ideas in this position. }
10. Ne5{ White can give the bishop either on  f4  or on  g3 . In this situation, there are some reasons to let Black take on  f4 . Not only does White save a tempo on another bishop move, White also keeps more control over the  e5 -square which makes it harder for Black to advance their central pawns.     If White accepts that Black will grab the bishop on  f4 , White obviously has plenty of moves at their disposal.  10.Ne5  has one extra plus point. The pressure against  c6  makes it tricky to target the pawn on  f4  without running into tricks like  Qa4 . And if Black takes on  e5 , White gets rid of their doubled pawns immediately. }( {  A)  }10.Bg3 Nxg3 11.hxg3 { gives Black more possibilities with their central pawns in the future. We might not push ... e6 - e5  too soon as our king is currently still in the center - and we might even leave the king there for some more moves not to give White any reason to build up a kingside attack. But at some point, ... e5  will certainly be on the agenda. For now, we can also go for other strategic goals: }11...a5!? { Stopping  b2 - b4  and just winning space on the queenside. We might continue with ... a4 . Other useful moves will be ... Bd7 , ... O-O , then we develop the queen - currently, many squares look logical -, then we put our rooks on the central files. } )( {  B)  }10.a3? { This is obviously a horribly slow move but let's just make it to show a strong idea that can be played against all kinds of slow moves. }10...Nxf4 11.exf4 Qf6! { Attacking  f4 . }12.g3 { Now, White's structure looks safe but we have the strong }12...g5! { ⩱ The f-pawn is now hanging and }13.fxg5?! hxg5∓ { is asking for a mating attack on the h-file. } )
10. Nxf4
11. exf4
11. Nxe5{ This does repair White's structure which is a pity but it seems to be the best move. }( {  A)  }11...Qf6 { is typical but }12.Qa4! { protects the pawn and increases the pressure on  c6 . If Black plays }12...Bd7 { , White will happily take this bishop. } )( {  B)  }11...O-O { is possible but the ideas to play ... Qf6  lose some strength because Black cannot follow up as well with ... g5  with the king on the kingside. } )
12. fxe5
12. Bd7{ Eventually, we will castle but for now, it is not clear if our king is really safer on the kingside and we might use the next moves to improve our queenside structure as much as possible before doing it. }
13. Qe2
13. a5{ A useful move, just winning space on the queenside. Our next moves are potentially ... a4 , ... Rc8 , ... Qb6 , at some point we castle. }( { Let's shortly mention that }14.Bb5 { does eliminate our bishop pair but it also exchanges our worst minor piece against their best. }14...O-O { should now be very safe as White doesn't have the attacking piece on  d3  anymore and after the exchange of bishops, Black's dark-squared bishop is stronger than White's knight. } )
