[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4{ One of the reasons why the London System had its renaissance a few years ago was the discoveries of new ideas in variations where White postponed the move  Ng1 - f3  for a bit. }( { Luckily for us, in the variations with  ...e6 , White barely has additional options and the main variations will be discussed in the variations via }2.Nf3 Nf6 Bf4 { -  starting here . Here, we will just look at some relatively rare options for White. } )
2. Nf6{ This is the most flexible move in my opinion. }( 2...c5 { usually leads to the same position but it gives White the additional option }3.e4!? { which is a weird Albin Counter Gambit (   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e5 { ) reversed. Not really threatening but if we can cut this option, why not? } )
3. e3( 3.Nc3 { leads to the  Jobava London . } )
3. e6{ The start of our setup as mentioned in the  Introduction . }
4. Nd2( { Besides }4.Nf3 { that leads to our  2.Nf3 -variations -  see here - , this is the most popular move order. } )( 4.c3 { is another move that holds back  Nf3  but we just continue with }4...c5 { and White doesn't really gain anything from this move order. } )
4. c5
5. c3{ Finishing the typical London triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . }
5. Nc6{ An important position!     Most Black players follow up with ... Bd6 . If White exchanges the bishop, Black's queen will replace the bishop and after that, ... e5  will certainly come. }( { So it is usually important for White players to answer   }6...Bd6 { with }7.Bg3 { . However, this does only stop }...e5 { if White has the square once more under their control. } )( { So, most White players will now play }6.Ngf3 { when we finally transpose to  2.Nf3 - variations  and can play our long-awaited }6...Nh5! { . } )
6. Bd3{ If White continues to play without  Nf3 , we can execute our other plan. }( { The same reply would also happen after }6.h3 { for example. } )
6. Bd6
7. Bxd6( { This is White's main move. }7.Bg3 e5! { is Black's dream. } )
7. Qxd6{ Black is threatening ... e5 . If White wants to stop it, they have to play  f2 - f4  with a Stonewall setup (pawns on  c3 ,  d4 ,  e3  and  f4 ).     Whatever White does, Black's position is really comfortable. }
8. Ngf3{ After this move, Black can easily play ... e5 . }
8. O-O( { The immediate }8...e5 { is also possible, but since White has no way to stop it anyway, we can also start with bringing our king to safety. } )
9. O-O( 9.Bb5 { is a really weird move as White has already played a bishop move to  d3 . It technically stops ... e5  for now but at a high cost. }9...Bd7! { is annoying for White. ... Nxd4  is a serious threat and if White protects the bishop on  b5 , we will be happy to play ... a6 , provoking White to give up their light-squares bishop. }10.O-O? Nxd4! { is tough for White. }11.exd4 Bxb5 { wins a pawn as well as }11.Bxd7 Nxf3+ { .    }11.Nxd4 cxd4! 12.Bxd7 dxe3! { is also a variation that will give Black at least one extra pawn. } )
9. e5{ This position has been reached by a number of strong players from the White side. By looking at the games more closely, I saw that it often happened in casual blitz games and if it happened in classical games, many White players followed it up with a quick draw offer to avoid worse.  So I don't think that this is a serious variation but as it frequently happens that White stumbles into this position, let's quickly talk about White's options. }( { Currently   }10...e4 { is a huge threat. White usually takes either on  c5  or  e5 . } )
10. dxe5
10. Nxe5
11. Nxe5
11. Qxe5{ The engine always gives these kinds of positions as pretty close to equal, but in a practical game, Black scores massively. That's not too surprising, since Black simply has much better control over the center with the  d5  &  c5 -pawns.  Black should play these positions with some patience. Just develop your bishop, put your rooks behind the pawns and very slowly improve the position step by step. Maybe, at some point, advance on the queenside with ... a6  and ... b5 .     A typical mistake at the amateur level is to go play ... d4  too fast because this gives away Black's main advantage - the better central pawns. Instead, it is White who should try to diminish Black's central influence with  e3 - e4  or  c3 - c4 . Anticipating this idea is arguably the main thing we can do in this position. }( { For this reason, the moves }12.Nf3 Qe7 { don't help White. The knight on  d2  is well placed to support  c4  and  e4 . } )
