[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. Nbd2( { This move is less popular than }5.c3 { because Black can play }5...Qb6 { . This is obviously not the end of the world but White players usually like to have }6.Qb3 { available in response. I would recommend giving White the possibility to transpose. } )
5. Nc6( { The same move that we play against  5.c3  and most White players will just transpose to those lines with }6.c3 { . } )
6. Bb5( 6.c3 { is played in 95% of the games and I think this is by far the most logical move.    This }6.Bb5 { idea is sometimes dangerous in other variations if White can create pressure against  c6 . But this doesn't really work against our ... e6 -setup. One thing idea to keep in mind is White's option to play  c2 - c4 . } )
6. Qb6{ This is Black's best scoring reply. Black wants to provoke White to give up the bishops on  c6  immediately. }( {  A)  }6...Bd7 { This is a very solid reply. However, Black can no longer play  ...Bd6  and after }7.O-O a6 { White can just drop back with }8.Be2 { . We can still play our }...Nh5 { idea, now or on move 7, but the positions are not quite the same because White provoked us to spend two of our tempis on early .... Bd7  and ... a6  and White can still play  c2 - c4  in one move. } )( {  B)  The same logic applies to something like }6...a6 7.Bxc6+ bxc6 8.c4 { which could give White a small initiative in the center. } )
7. c4{ This is usually one of White's ideas. Black is completely fine but at least White has the option to play with ideas like  d4xc5 ,  a2 - a3  and  b2 - b4 . This  c4 -resource is the reason why  6.Bb5  is not played after  5.c3 . }( 7.Bxc6+ bxc6 { is not so strong for White.  b2  is hanging and we can develop nicely with ... Ba6 . } )
7. cxd4{ This stops White from taking on  c5  and expanding with  a2 - a3  and  b2 - c4  on the queenside. }
8. exd4
8. dxc4{ This undermines the protection of the  b5 -bishop and gives White an isolated pawn on  d4 . }
9. a4( { This has the same ideas as }9.Qa4 { but there is less pressure against  c6 . Black can just drop back to  d8  with the queen and reach a decent IQP position. } )
9. Nd5{ Coming with tempo and blockading the IQP. }
10. Nxc4
10. Qd8
11. Bd2{ The best square to anticipate ... Bb4 . }
11. Bb4{ With decent blockade over the  d5 -square. }
