[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "Classical London: 5.c3 & 6.Bd3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Bd3{ This move order is relatively often played on amateur level but besides the fact that it is less flexible to commit the bishop to  d3  than the knight to  d2 , there are even more concrete problems with this move order. White has fewer options to react to ... Qb6 . }
6. Nh5{ This move fits best into our repertoire. It is the same move, we will also play against the stronger  6.Nd2 . }
7. Be5{ Not an untypical square for the bishop but Black can play ... f6  under good circumstances in this line. }( { In the lines with   }6.Nbd2 { , White has better options to react to ... Qb6 . } )
7. f6{ Our usual reply when the bishop comes to  e5 . }
8. Bg3( { After discoveries like }8.Nfd2 { Black can just respond with }8...g6 { . } )
8. Qb6{ In these London lines, it is always worth considering including an early ... Qb6 . Black activates the queen with tempo and either provokes the slight weakening in White's pawn structure or provokes White's queen away from the  d1 - h5  diagonal. Also, lines with ... O-O-O  can be possible. }( { Taking on  g3  with }8...Nxg3 9.hxg3 { is }{ possible but White gets immediate pressure against  h7 . } )
9. Qc2{ This move has been played in all four games I found in this position. White protects  b2  and attacks  h7 . On the good side for us, White has no discoveries any longer against the knight on  h5 , so we can wait for a good moment before we take on  g3 . }( { There are other moves for White not to lose the  b2 -pawn such as }9.b3 { but Black's play is similar when it comes to plans.     A)  }9...cxd4 { is still a good move to include.     A1)  }10.cxd4 Nb4 { either wins the bishop or drives it away from the  b1-h7  diagonal.     A2)  }10.exd4 { makes Black's pawn even more impressive after something like ... Nxg3 , . ..Bd7, ... O-O-O  and ... e5 . }{     A3)  }10.Nxd4 { attacks the knight on  h5  but we can just stay calm with }10...g6 { and very soon ... e5  will occupy the center easily. }{     B)  The immediate }9...Bd7!? { with the idea to castle queenside is also both typical and strong but gives White ideas with }Ne5!? { .     C)  }{ A very instructive idea is to take on  g3  and then completely ignore the  h7 -pawn, bring the king to the queenside and claim that White cannot really take the pawn because White gets problems on the h-file. }{   }9...Nxg3!? 10.hxg3 {  h7  is under attack and  Bg6+  is also an idea but Black can just ignore it. }10...Bd7! { Black is getting ready to castle and if White doesn't find something concrete, Black is better without any doubt. We have the bishop pair and the strong plan to go for  ...O-O-O  soon.     C1)  }11.Rxh7 { Taking the pawn is a logical try to punish Black. }11...Rxh7 12.Bg6+! { A tricky in-between move to disturb Black's coordination but it doesn't make a huge difference. }( { ( }12.Bxh7 O-O-O { makes it even easier to get a rook to  h8 .) } )12...Kd8! { The king goes to  c7 . }13.Bxh7 Kc7∓ { followed by ... Bd6  and ... Rh8  with the idea to invade via  h1 . Black will have a huge initiative. }13...f5!? { is also an interesting option to start to isolate White's bishop first.     C2)    }11.Bg6+ Kd8 { is possible for White but at some point, Black can connect rooks with ... Bd6  & ... Kc7  and White's bishop will be hanging. Taking on  h7  then would lead to a worse version and retreating would give Black a decent long-castling position. }{     C3)    }11.Bxh7? O-O-O ! { is the worst option for White. It will just take way too many moves to get out of the pin on the h-file. } )
9. cxd4{ A nice intermediate move. No matter how White recaptures, there are some drawbacks.  Nevertheless, Black does also have other options. }( 9...Bd7!? { to prepare long-castling or even just  ...Rc8  is also not bad. }10.Bxh7? O-O-O ! { would give Black massive compensation because when White's bishop retreats, for example with }11.Bd3 { , we can play }11...Nxg3 { and White has to recapture with the f-pawn with massive compensation. } )
10. Nxd4{ This gives Black very nice central control. }
10. e5{ There is no reason to be modest with the pawns here. }
11. Nxc6
11. bxc6
12. O-O{ It makes sense to develop as fast as possible and maybe keep the option open to play  c3 - c4  and develop the knight to  c3 . Black should be slightly better if we can just develop, take on  g3  and consolidate. Nevertheless, Black can just take on  g3  here without White's rook on  h1 . }( {  A)  }12.Bxh7? { is not working for different reasons. }12...Rxh7 13.Qxh7 Nxg3 14.hxg3 Qxb2-+ { is the most convincing solution as Black just wins material.    However, }12...Kd8! { is also very strong.Stepping out of  13.Bg6  with check and if White does now ever move the bishop, we can just play }-- ...Nxg3 { and destroy White's structure because the h-pawn cannot take. } )( {  B)  }12.Nd2 { is a logical developing move without committing the king too early to the kingside. }12...g6 { Black stops all the tactics against  h7  and can develop with ... Be6 , ... Be7 , ... O-O  and eventually take on  g3 . } )
12. Nxg3{ This doesn't run away but it is very thematic to take the bishop if White's rook has left  h1 . }
13. hxg3{ I think Black has just slightly more options. }( 13...e4 { is possible to close down the diagonal, followed by an aggressive  ...h7-h5-h4 .    }13...Kf7 { is an option.    }13...Rb8 { is a logical move to include. } )
13. Rb8{ A nice inbetween move. Black just wins a tempo against the pawn and also sets a devilish trap. }
14. b4( { The best move according to the engine to solve the problem of the  b2 -pawn but Black's play would be similar after other moves such as }14.b3 { as well. }14.Bxh7? { just loses material because of }14...Rxh7! 15.Qxh7 Qxb2-+ { White has to sacrifice the  b1 -knight to save the rook. } )
14. e4{ Closing the long diagonal. }
15. Be2
15. h5{ Black is ready to play ... h4  and open up the kingside. }
