[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "Classical London: 5.c3 & 6.Bd3 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Bd3{ This move order is relatively often played on amateur level but besides the fact that it is less flexible to commit the bishop to  d3  than the knight to  d2 , there are even more concrete problems with this move order. White has fewer options to react to ... Qb6 . }
6. Nh5{ This move fits best into our repertoire. It is the same move, we will also play against the stronger  6.Nd2 . }
7. Bg5{ Another square to avoid the immediate loss of the bishop pair. }
7. Qb6{ A strong response. If we take on  b2 , we will immediately attack the rook on  a1 . This alone is reason enough that White cannot go for any discoveries against our knight on  h3 . This wins a crucial tempo and gives us the time to play ... h6  and ... g5  to hunt down the bishop on  g5 . }
8. b3{ This is the most popular response to take care of the  b2 -pawn. White slightly weakens their structure but by keeping the queen on  d1 , White at least some tactical discoveries against the knight on  h5 . }( 8.Qc2 { is the second most popular move but here Black can just play }8...h6 9.Bh4 g5 { without any tricks. }10.Bg3 Nxg3 11.hxg3∓ { Black has a great version of our 'bishop grab'. We have to deal with the one-move threat  12.Nxg5  which can be easily dealt with either }11...Bg7 { or }11...g4 { .    White has no real way to prove our kingside vulnerable, our king can castle both sides and White doesn't even have counterplay on the queenside. } )
8. h6{ The typical continuation to hunt the bishop. }
9. Bh4
9. g5
10. Ne5{ The only critical move. By attacking the knight on  h5 , White avoids the easy bishop grab. }( 10.Bg3 Nxg3 11.hxg3 Bg7 { is once again just a dream position (that was cleanly converted) in  Decroix - Saucey, Nimes 2018 . Black has the bishop pair, more space and can decide when to open the position further with }{ ... a7 - a5 - a4  or ... e6 - e5 . } )
10. Nxe5{ The strongest reply. By taking on  e5  first, White's bishop on  g3  will be very limited in its possibilities. }
11. dxe5
11. Ng7{ The knight will be great on  f5  and as we will see, not even  Bd3xf5  stops us! }
12. Bg3
12. Nf5{ A very strong move. If White doesn't take the knight, we can just take on  g3  and reach once again some kind of dream position.  So White is more or less forced to take. But isn't this just losing a pawn? }
13. Bxf5( { The critical test. }13.O-O Nxg3 14.hxg3 Bg7 { is once again very comfortable. Here, White even has a weak  e5 -pawn. }15.f4 { allows the tactical }15...c4!? { but Black can also just play }15...Bd7 { and ...  O-O-O  and start a kingside attack with ... h6 - h5 - h4 . } )
13. exf5
14. Qxd5{ If White doesn't take the pawn, Black will just play ... Be6 , ... Be7 , castle long and either crush White on the kingside or break in the center with ...  d5 - d4 . Black's bishops come to life while White's pieces are extremely limited. }
14. Be6{ Black has sacrificed a pawn but the bishop pair does really come to life. Black can follow up very aggressively. }
15. Qd1{ Sadly, this is the best square. }( 15.Qd3?! { was played in a predecessor game but this does just allow }15...c4! { with tempo. }15.Qf3 { looks like a more active square but Black can castle long if White's queen leaves the d-file. }15...O-O-O 16.O-O c4! { White is completely dominated. }{ Just look at the knight on  b1 !     The position is extremely sharp but Black is definitely for choice. A typical idea is ...  h6 - h5 - h4 , winning some tempi against the bishop on  g3  and opening up the kingside. } )
15. c4{ A typical move. White opens up the position even more for the bishops. }
16. Nd2{ A logical move, developing and keeping the queenside together. }
16. O-O-O{ With a sharp position that should be easier to play for Black. The bishop on  g3  is only a big burden for White and Black can just follow up with ... h5 - h4 . If White stops the h-pawn with  h2 - h4 , Black can just increase the pressure on this pawn with ... Be7 .     Black's attack should be faster than White's. }
