[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Schlechter the London!"]
[Black "Classical London: Mainline c3 & Nbd2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Nbd2{ This is by far White's main move. The knight simply belongs to  d2  without any doubt. }
6. Nh5{ Playing the same kind of idea that we also saw in many Exchange variations. If this works in the Slav, it should definitely also work against the London! }( { If White provokes  ...f6  - which is something they can do both with }7.Bg5 { and }7.Be5 { - }{ it is extremely typical that Black takes on  d4  later on, which might indeed exactly transpose to an Exchange Slav structure (if White recaptures with  cxd4 ). One difference is the knight on  d2 . In the exchange Slav, it is more or less always developed to  c3  instead - and that is certainly the more active square!    Another difference is the early ... e6  here by Black. However, as we saw in different variations of the exchange chapter, ... e6  is a very typical move after Black has won the bishop pair, anyway.  So overall, this position should be absolutely fine. } )
7. Bg3{ As usual, the immediate retreat to  g3  doesn't promise anything for White. }
7. Nxg3{ The typical response. Without ... f6  provoked, Black can just take on  g3 . The kingside is safe enough. }
8. hxg3
8. Qb6{ Black has different moves that fit into the general setup. }( { I think }8...Qb6 { makes equally much sense as }8...Bd7 { which has a crushing 80% score in the database. }{ But as I also give ... Qb6  as the main move with  6.Bd3  instead of  6.Nbd2 , I will also give this move here. Both moves are part of our setup.  Besides these two moves, it usually makes sense to think about a way to deal with the  h7 -pawn if White attacks it with  Qc2  or  Bd3 . (White might not always threaten to take the pawn immediately - for example when a bishop on  h7  can be trapped with ... g6 ) but usually we don't do much wrong if we do something about the pawn.     As a Schlechter player, I prefer the move ... g6  to block the long diagonal. To keep the dark squares protected it makes sense to combine it with ... Bg7 .     In those lines, Black can usually just castle short, the king has an important guard on  g7  and Black can just rely on the bishop pair as a long-term factor.     The alternative is to play ... h6 . In those positions, Black won't develop the bishop to  g7  and short-castling might run into the hook  g4 - g5  eventually. So these setups should often be combined with long-castling instead when the game can sharpen up quickly. I clearly prefer the first option, but if you are a more adventurous player, feel free to choose the second option! } )
9. Qb3{ This move has some nuances that we will see in this trainable. Important:We are not afraid of  Qb3xb6 . The doubled pawns are no problem, we get the open a-file and it just stabilizes our center. }
9. Bd7{ We just continue with our setup. }
10. Bd3{ This is a mistake and the punishment is really typical for this setup with queens on  b3  and  b6  and the bishop on  d3 . }( {  A)  }10.Qxb6 axb6 { This poor exchange was played in the model game  Nabavi - Fedorchuk , Deizisau 2009. Check it out! It is really instructive to see how Black just took space on the kingside with ... f5 , ... g7 - g5 - g4 , then crushed with ... h7 - h5 - h4  and was just winning by move 20. } )( {  B)  A normal move like }10.Be2 { might be best. As White has no attack against  h7 , Black has all sorts of moves such as }10...Be7 { . However, I would recommend the same setup as usual, just }10...g6 { , followed by the fianchetto. } )
10. c4{ A very strong response. White is forced to take on  b6  and in the resulting position, White is not in time to stop ... b6 - b5 - b4 . }
11. Qxb6
11. axb6
12. Bc2{ Black's plan is always the same. }
12. b5{ Black will just play ... b4  and create a very favourable queenside structure. }
