9. Rb1{ We have reached a position from the game  Berkes - Kuzobov, Bucharest 2022 . You can find this game in the model game chapter. It is a really inspiring game to see the merits of Black's setup.  Let's have the following moves of that game as a sample line in this trainable. Black's setup is more or less always the same: ... Bd7 , ... g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O . }( { Very similar is }9.Qc2 { , the most forcing move. White attacks  h7 . Besides the fact that we have to play }9...g6 { here first, we follow the same moves. ...  Bd7 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O . At some point, we open the position and dominate with our bishops. } )
9. Bd7( 9....g6 { is also possible. } )
10. Bd3
10. g6{ Taking care of the  h7 -pawn. }
11. Qe2{ Both sides just make natural moves. }( { The immediate }11.O-O { might be slightly more flexible. We would of course still play }...Bg7 { and castling. } )
11. Bg7
12. O-O
12. O-O{ Black has a harmonious position and the advantage of the two bishops. If White doesn't do something concrete, Black can just win some space on the queenside with ... a7 - a5 - a4  or go the .... e6 - e5  break. }( { In the model game  Berkes - Kuzobov , White played }13.b4 { but Black just closed the position with }13...c4 { and then }-- 14...f5! { which was }{ followed up by a crushing attack with ... g6 - g5 - g4 , ... h7 - h5 - h4 . Chess can be so simple! } )
