1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Nbd2{ This is by far White's main move. The knight simply belongs to  d2  without any doubt. }
6. Nh5{ Playing the same kind of idea that we also saw in many Exchange variations. If this works in the Slav, it should definitely also work against the London! }( { If White provokes  ...f6  - which is something they can do both with }7.Bg5 { and }7.Be5 { - }{ it is extremely typical that Black takes on  d4  later on, which might indeed exactly transpose to an Exchange Slav structure (if White recaptures with  cxd4 ). One difference is the knight on  d2 . In the exchange Slav, it is more or less always developed to  c3  instead - and that is certainly the more active square!    Another difference is the early ... e6  here by Black. However, as we saw in different variations of the exchange chapter, ... e6  is a very typical move after Black has won the bishop pair, anyway.  So overall, this position should be absolutely fine. } )
7. Be5{ White tries to provoke before going back to  g3 . This is more ambitious. }
7. f6{ We don't mind, we just play ... f6  to drive the bishop back. }
8. Bg3( { The best move. Discoveries like }8.Nh4 { just run into }6...g6 { which will prove the knight moves quite pointless. } )
8. cxd4{ With the ... f6  provoked, it makes sense to include the exchange on  d4 .     By playing ... Nh5  and ... f6 , we go for a long-term advantage - the bishop pair. We ignore some short-term goals like quick development and especially the f-pawn move makes our structure more vulnerable.  So White has every reason to play dynamic, open the center and try to punish Black as long as we are not fully coordinated. Ideas like  d4xc5  and  e3 - e4  or  c3 - c4  would be very typical.  By clarifying the structure in the center, White will be more limited in their active possibilities. }
9. cxd4{ This leads to a position that is very similar to  this one  from the Exchange Schlechter. If we play ... g6  - which is one of our options -, we have exactly the same position just that White's knight is on  d2  instead of on  c3 . This comparison can only be good for us. }
9. Bd7{ I like this flexible move. For now, it is not necessary to stabilize the knight on  h5  with ... g6  so we can more or less play the same way as in the sister variation - see for example  here  - but White has the more passive knight and we might save a tempo on ... g6 . I think there is only one trap you need to know. }
10. Bd3{ After other moves, Black can either just develop naturally with ... Be7  and ... O-O  or play aggressive with ... Qb6  - White has no  Nc3 - a4 . }( { However, after }10.Bd3 { , White is threatening }-- 11.Nh4 { because }11....g6 12.Nxg6! { loses material. Typically, threats towards  h7  are the most dangerous thing to look out for.  But here, we have additional options to take care of it. } )
10. Nxg3{ This recapture is very risky with White's knight on  c3  but here we can justify it with a typical response. }( {  A)  }10...Be7?! 11.Nh4!± { for example is asking for trouble.     B)  }10...g6 { is a solid move in the spirit of the same position with the knight on  c3 . } )
11. hxg3{ White is threatening  h7  but... }
11. Qb6{ A typical response in the 'London version' of this structure. White cannot harass the queen with  Nc3 - a4  and so  b6  is a pretty safe square. }( { The main idea is now that taking on  h7  with }12.Bxh7? { , threatening }-- 13.Bg6+ { to win the  h8 -rook can be answered with   }12...O-O-O! { when White will get problems on the h-file. } )( 12.Bg6+ Kd8 { doesn't achieve much. The king is only temporarily in the center as this problem can be resolved with something like ... Rc8  and ... Kc7 - b8 . Also, as  b2  is hanging, White can no longer win a pawn by taking on  h7 .    Black does already have the slightly more comfortable position. } )
