8. cxd4{ With the ... f6  provoked, it makes sense to include the exchange on  d4 .     By playing ... Nh5  and ... f6 , we go for a long-term advantage - the bishop pair. We ignore some short-term goals like quick development and especially the f-pawn move makes our structure more vulnerable.  So White has every reason to play dynamic, open the center and try to punish Black as long as we are not fully coordinated. Ideas like  d4xc5  and  e3 - e4  or  c3 - c4  would be very typical.  By clarifying the structure in the center, White will be more limited in their active possibilities. }
9. exd4{ The main move. Now, we have a very weird version of a Caro-Kann exchange.  White would love to prove that the  e6 -pawn is a weakness. It is on an open file and not protected by other pawns.  However, we have a very convincing plan to solve this: ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... e5 ! }
9. g6{ The bishop will be ideally placed on  g7  to support the advance in the center. }
10. Bb5{ White tries to anticipate Black's idea by fighting for the ... e5 -square. Black gets the additional option to play with ... Qb6 , going for the bishop pair. }
10. Qb6{ Asking White if they still think that the bishop is so well placed on  b5 . }( { Following the standard setup with }10...Bg7 11.O-O O-O { is also fully playable. White can try to anticipate Black's  ...e5  move with }12.c4 { - as with the bishop on  e2  - or with }12.Re1 { .    }12.Ba4!? { is another interesting idea for White to anticipate it and then put the bishop on  b3  with pressure against  d5 . } )
11. c4{ White has different objectively equal options but this is the only move that requires some concrete knowledge as White has more options to open up the center. }( {  A)  }11.Bxc6+ { is exactly what Black wants. In the resulting positions with two bishops versus two knights, Black should always have the much more comfortable game - after both }11...bxc6 { and }11...Qxc6 { . } )( {  B)  }11.a4 a6 12.Bxc6+ { is a better version of the same thing for White because Black's bishop cannot go to  a6  after  ...bxc6  and overall, White's a-pawn move is having more influence on the queenside than Black's. Still, we should be absolutely fine after both recaptures. } )( {  C)  }11.Qb3 { makes sure that  b2  is no longer hanging but - besides other options - Black can also be completely satisfied with the queen trade after }11...a6!? 12.Ba4 Qxb3 { . Once the queens come off, White has much fewer dynamic chances to punish Black for the loose kingside structure. } )( {  D)  }11.Ba4!? { is an interesting pawn sacrifice and Black will be even more behind in development if we capture on  b2 . Usually, this is not my cup of tea - or not my beer as we say in Germany - so I would go with a different setup. }11...Bd7!? { A normal developing move but it also prepares long castling. }12.O-O Nxg3 { At some point, we have to take the bishop - doing it after White castles makes sense. }13.hxg3 O-O-O⇆ { with a very sharp position. Both sides will start a pawn storm against the enemy king.  With Black's bishop pair, I would certainly prefer our side even though the engine gives equal chances here. } )
11. Be7{ An easy move to prepare castling. }( {  A)  }11...Bg7?! 12.Bd6!⩲ { is not so great with the queen on  b6 . } )( {  B)  }11...a6 12.Ba4 { would be a better version of  11.Ba4  as White has played the aggressive  c2 - c4 . } )
12. O-O
12. O-O{ By castling, we unpin the  c6 -knight and attack the  d4 -pawn. }( { If White takes on  c6  or plays }13.cxd5 { , we will be happy with the bishop pair after }13...Qxb5 14.dxc6 Qxc6 { . Eventually, we will take on  g3  and maybe go for the second bishop as well with ... a6 . } )
