4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Nbd2{ This is by far White's main move. The knight simply belongs to  d2  without any doubt. }
6. Nh5{ Playing the same kind of idea that we also saw in many Exchange variations. If this works in the Slav, it should definitely also work against the London! }( { If White provokes  ...f6  - which is something they can do both with }7.Bg5 { and }7.Be5 { - }{ it is extremely typical that Black takes on  d4  later on, which might indeed exactly transpose to an Exchange Slav structure (if White recaptures with  cxd4 ). One difference is the knight on  d2 . In the exchange Slav, it is more or less always developed to  c3  instead - and that is certainly the more active square!    Another difference is the early ... e6  here by Black. However, as we saw in different variations of the exchange chapter, ... e6  is a very typical move after Black has won the bishop pair, anyway.  So overall, this position should be absolutely fine. } )
7. Be5{ White tries to provoke before going back to  g3 . This is more ambitious. }
7. f6{ We don't mind, we just play ... f6  to drive the bishop back. }
8. Bg3( { The best move. Discoveries like }8.Nh4 { just run into }6...g6 { which will prove the knight moves quite pointless. } )
8. cxd4{ With the ... f6  provoked, it makes sense to include the exchange on  d4 .     By playing ... Nh5  and ... f6 , we go for a long-term advantage - the bishop pair. We ignore some short-term goals like quick development and especially the f-pawn move makes our structure more vulnerable.  So White has every reason to play dynamic, open the center and try to punish Black as long as we are not fully coordinated. Ideas like  d4xc5  and  e3 - e4  or  c3 - c4  would be very typical.  By clarifying the structure in the center, White will be more limited in their active possibilities. }
9. exd4{ The main move. Now, we have a very weird version of a Caro-Kann exchange.  White would love to prove that the  e6 -pawn is a weakness. It is on an open file and not protected by other pawns.  However, we have a very convincing plan to solve this: ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... e5 ! }
9. g6{ The bishop will be ideally placed on  g7  to support the advance in the center. }
10. Be2( { This move is very similar to }10.Bd3 { in a sense that there is no concrete idea behind it and White just develops the bishop. This gives Black the opportunity to just execute the main plan behind ... g6 . Objectively, both moves are equally good but masters seem to prefer the bishop on  e2  as it is less vulnerable than on  d3  if Black achieves ... e6 - e5 . }10...Bg7 11.O-O ( { ( }11.Bh4?! Nf4! { doesn't work for White.) } )11...Nxg3!? { Taking on  g3  before White can save the bishop with  12.Bh4 . }12.hxg3 O-O⇆ { Black is ready to go ... e5  with nice counterplay. } )
10. Bg7( { GM Kovalev played }10...Bh6 { twice which controls the  f4 -square and also looks like a nice diagonal. But }10...Bg7 { is more according to our simple plan. } )
11. O-O
11. O-O{ This position has been reached 4 times in practice. Surprisingly, three of the games were played by the same player! }
12. c4{ A logical move to undermine Black's center before we can advance with ... e5 . In return, White slightly weakens their own structure. }( {  A)  }12.Nb3?! { was played in  Le - Erigaisi, Online 2021  and  Le - Perez Gormaz, Online 2022  but Black is just better after }12...e5! { . White tried to destroy Black's center with }13.c4 { but Black just reached a great structure anyway. }13...Nxg3 { Taking the bishop is part of the plan. }14.hxg3 e4! { Grabbing more space. }15.Nfd2 f5! { Black has a massive pawn chain and after }16.cxd5 Ne7!∓ { , we will have a dominant square on  d5 . } )( {  B)  }12.Qb3 { was another move to stop Black from playing ... e5  in  Wang - Le, Ashkabad 2017  by preparing  Rad1  or  Rfd1  which can pose problems with the  d5 -pawn. However, compared to  13.c4  there is less immediate pressure on our center and we can either just play in the same way with ... g5 - g4 , ... Nxg3  and ... f5 / ... h5  but we can also just start with some flexible moves such as }12...Kh8 { or }12...a6 { . } )
12. g5{ It makes a lot of sense to advance f- and g-pawn in the structure because both the bishop on  g3  but also the knight on  f3  - which is an important defender of the  d4 -pawn - can be set under quite some pressure with our pawns. Now, we have the interesting idea to play ... g4  - either to win the  d4 -pawn or to follow up with ... f5  when White's bishop comes under a lot of pressure. }( {  A)  Wesley So played similar after taking on  g3  with }12...Nxg3 13.hxg3 f5 14.Nb3 g5 { which was fine in  Le - So, Online 2019 . However, by exchanging on  g3 , Black exchanged one of White's problem pieces. } )( {  B)  Don't start with }12...f5 { because }13.Be5!⩲ { gives White the nice  e5 -square to occupy. } )
13. cxd5{ The position is more concrete than it might seem at first glance. White doesn't have too many ways to address Black's ... g4  idea. }( {  A)  }13.h3?! { is technically possible but }13...Nxg3 14.fxg3 { ruins White's pawn structure. Black can continue with  ...f5  and  ...Qd6 . } )( {  B)  The immediate }13.Nb3 g4! 14.Ne1 f5!⩱ { gives Black some pressure. If White takes now on  d5 , we can recapture with the queen. }15.cxd5 Qxd5 {  d4  is really weak. } )
13. exd5( 13...Qxd5? 14.Bc4± { is just bad here for Black. } )
14. Nb3{ The most natural move to protect the  d4 -pawn. }
14. Nxg3{ The most straightforward way to play the position. }( {  A)  }14...a6 { is a subtle computer move to continue. The idea behind ... a6  is that it takes away all  Bb5  resources that White can use to fight for the  e5 -square when Black plays ... f5 . Also, Black might claim that White has nothing better than  15.Ne1  anyway when Black can achieve a similar position as in the game but with the g-pawn on  g5  instead of on  g4  which keeps more control over the f-square. For example, }15.Ne1 Nxg3 16.hxg3 f5!? { followed by  ...f4  eventually. } )( {  B)  Going for the forcing }14...g4 15.Ne1 f5!? { does also require extremely precise play from White. The threat  ...f4  is hanging above White like Damokles' sword. }16.Nd3! { is the computer defence that somehow seems to hold with the point that }16...f4 17.Bxg4 fxg3 18.Bxh5 { doesn't lose a piece. } )
15. hxg3
15. g4{ Black keeps pushing on the kingside. }
16. Ne1{ The best square. The knight is heading towards  d3  where it controls many vital squares such as  f4 . }
16. h5{ Black can play on both sides of the board. ... f6 - f5 - f4  or ... h5 - h4  is equally possible as starting by winning some space on the queenside with ... a5 - a4 . Black's king is slightly exposed but White cannot easily get access and the butcher is a truly loyal guard. }
