[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bf4{ This move order with an early  Nf3  is the traditional way of playing the London System, following the old rule to develop knights before bishops. In these lines with the knight already committed to  f3 , we will see the idea ... Nh5  really often. }
3. e6( { Our setup is the same as in the  2.Bf4 -variations. }3...e6 { , }-- 4...c5 { , }-- 5...Nc6 { first. } )
4. e3
4. c5
5. c3{ This is White's main move in this position, building the infamous ultra-solid pawn triangle  c3 - d4 - e3 . This is a typical move against ... c5  in the London. Not only because it overprotects the pawn on  d4  but also because White players like to have the option to answer ... Qb6  with  Qb3 . }
5. Nc6
6. Nbd2{ This is by far White's main move. The knight simply belongs to  d2  without any doubt. }
6. Nh5{ Playing the same kind of idea that we also saw in many Exchange variations. If this works in the Slav, it should definitely also work against the London! }( { If White provokes  ...f6  - which is something they can do both with }7.Bg5 { and }7.Be5 { - }{ it is extremely typical that Black takes on  d4  later on, which might indeed exactly transpose to an Exchange Slav structure (if White recaptures with  cxd4 ). One difference is the knight on  d2 . In the exchange Slav, it is more or less always developed to  c3  instead - and that is certainly the more active square!    Another difference is the early ... e6  here by Black. However, as we saw in different variations of the exchange chapter, ... e6  is a very typical move after Black has won the bishop pair, anyway.  So overall, this position should be absolutely fine. } )
7. Bg5{ This is White's best try. They also provoke ... f6  but the bishop doesn't land on a square where it can be eliminated. }
7. f6( { The typical response.    }7...Qb6 { creates much less of a threat with White's knight already on  d2 . White has different options, the most aggressive being }8.dxc5!? Bxc5 9.b4! { followed by  e3 - e4 , opening up the center while Black is not ideally developed. } )
8. Bh4( { As usual, a discovery like }8.Ne5 { doesn't have a huge effect because of }8...g6 { . } )
8. cxd4{ As mentioned earlier, it is very useful to fix the pawn structure to give White no unnecessary possibilities to open the center in a dynamic way and punish Black before we can finish our development. }( { Nevertheless, it is also possible to start with }8...g6 { and take on  d4  slightly later. } )
9. exd4{ This move is not attractive here for White. Black gets the nice  f4 -square for the knight and if Black starts rolling with ... e5 , we will have a strong pawn mass in the center. }
9. Bd6{ The most active square for the bishop. }
10. Bg3{ This might be White's best move - taking control over the  f4 -square. Black has different ways to proceed. }
10. Nxg3{ Taking the bishop and going for a quick ... e5  looks pretty good. }( {  A)  Staying flexible with }10...O-O { , hoping that White will take on  d6  and leave the  f4 -square unguarded, is also not bad, but White can just ignore Black and complete development. }11.Be2 Nf4 { . If White takes, Black is happy, but White can just ignore the knight with }12.O-O!? { when Black is active, but I think there is no clear path forward. } )( {  B)  }10...Nf4 { has a great score and if White takes the knight, Black will have the easy advantage of the two bishops, but the engine claims that }11.h4!?⇆ { with the idea  h4 - h5  solves White's problem. It looks pretty weird to me and I don't think that many players would play such a move, but I guess there is no point in arguing with the machine. } )
11. hxg3
11. e5{ Black should be slightly better in this position. We have the idea to play ... e5 - e4 - e3  to undermine the pawn on  g3  that we would love to take with check.    If White doesn't find anything concrete against our center, we might also just overprotect our pawns first with ... Be6 , ... Qd7 , ... O-O , rooks on  d8  and  e8 , and enjoy the beauty of having such pawns in the center. }
