10. Be2{ White has different logical moves that they can play in this position. }( 10.Be2 { looks to me like the only one that sets up some kind of trap. With the  f6 -pawn pinned, White does now have the idea to go }-- 11.Ne5 { . } )( {  A)  The immediate }10.Ne5 { is possible but doesn't look too frightened. Black can just unpin with }10...Be7 { and force White to go }11.Nxc6 bxc6 { . }{ In the resulting position, Black is ready to go ... c5 . And if White stops this, we can go for the ... Nh5 - g7 - f5  manoeuvre. } )( {  B)  }10.Bd3 { is a normal square in the London for the bishop. There is nothing in particular that Black can do wrong against this move.  We can not only go }10...Be7 { but also - more active - }10...Bd6 { , followed by ... O-O , ... Bd7  and decent development. }{ In 'The London Attack: An Ambitious Repertoire', our community author IndrekR continues his analysis with }11.O-O O-O 12.Rc1 Bd7 13.g4!? Ng7 14.a3 { . This looks like a suggestion heavily influenced by modern engines which have no problems exposing their king like that and then continue to start completely unrelated counterplay on the other side. From a human perspective, it looks very risky to allow a well-timed }14...e5 { when the  g4 -pawn will be hanging immediately. Black can either play this move right away or play other useful moves such as }14...a5 { or }14...Rc8 { first. } )( {  C)  }10.Rc1 { is Le Quam Liem's recommendation in 'Lifetime Repertoires: London System' but the same logic applies: We get the extra option of playing }10...Bd6 { instead of playing }10...Be7 { that could likely transpose to our main line. } )
