2. Nc3( { As mentioned in the  Introduction , there was a time when anything besides a quick  c2 - c4  was seen as highly innocuous by many players. I can imagine that many of these purists, might go one step further and see the move }2.Nc3 { even as some kind of insult to our sacred game. }{ By blocking the c-pawn, White voluntarily gives one of the two pawn breaks in the center away and the second one -  e2-e4  - is just much harder to accomplish. There is no queen behind the e-pawn to support it and while  f2-f3  is a typical idea in these Veresov lines, it is also much more weakening than for example, in the mirrored structures after   }1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 { the move }c3 { . } )( { Once in a while you can still find players who describe the move  2.Nc3  as 'anti-positional'. Nevertheless, especially with the increasing popularity of the 'Jobava London' with   }3.Bf4 { , all these 'abstract' arguments became much less important and people figured out that chess is a concrete game after all! } )
2. Nf6{ This is an absolute standard response to prevent White from playing  e2 - e4 . }( { One of the reasons why the white opening has gained so much popularity is that White can reach this position not only after   }1...d5 { , but also via the move order }1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 { .    White players thus often have a very narrow repertoire in which they frequently have 'their' positions on the board, while Black players see the position much less frequently. Together with the aggressive nature of the opening, White likes to try to overrun their opponents.    In the past, the move }3.Bg5 { was the typical continuation, the so-called 'Richter-Veresov attack'. White would love to threaten to give away a double pawn on }f6 { to force the opponent to make small concessions.    Well, nowadays we know that   }4.Bxf6 { is anything but a threat, so Black can develop at will, some Black players even provoke this capture with   }3...h6!? { but all in all it's not surprising that  3.Bg5  is hardly ever found nowadays. My recommendation is }3...c6 { which at the same time prepares a game on the queenside. } )( 3.Bf4 { , nowadays usually called 'Jobava-London', is the latest fashion. }{ White develops, sometimes tricks with  Nc3 - b5  are possible, and in the early middlegame White often plays aggressively with his kingside pawns.  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4  are not rarely seen in these variations. Nevertheless, with a little bit of preparation, Black should get good positions. My recommendation }{ is }3...e6 { , which prepares both }-- ...Bb4 { and }...c5 { . } )
