1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3{ As mentioned in the Introduction, there was a time when anything besides a quick  c2 - c4  was seen as highly innocuous by many players. I can imagine that many of these purists might go one step further and even see the move  2.Nc3  as some kind of insult. }( { By blocking the c-pawn, White voluntarily gives one of the two pawn breaks in the center away and the second one -  e2-e4  - is much harder to accomplish. There is no queen behind the e-pawn to support it and while  f2-f3  is a typical idea in these Veresov lines, it is also much more weakening than for example, in the mirrored structures after   }1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 { the move }c3 { . } )( { With the increasing popularity of the 'Jobava London' with   }3.Bf4 { , all these 'abstract' arguments became much less important, even though you still see players who describe the move  2.Nc3  as 'anti-positional' once in a while. } )
2. Nf6{ The most natural move. We simply develop and stop  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bg5( { Before the Jobava London }3.Bf4 { became popular, this was the move that the White players typically chose on move 3 when they played the Veresov. It was never particularly popular but was still once in a while played as a surprise weapon. }{ White plays with the idea to take on  f6  to spoil Black's structure and is often ready to castle long quite early to get a sharp position. }( { Getting in a quick  e2-e4  - sometimes by the means of a pawn sacrifice - is an idea that is often seen.  When I was young, I learned that }3...Nbd7 { is Black's best move to stop the doubled pawns on the f-file while also not allowing  e2-e4 . These days, theory figured out that   }4.Bxf6 { is not even something to be afraid when it creates the doubled pawns and even provoking this with   }3...h6 { is now a respectable answer. I haven't seen  3.Bg5  in a while and I have the feeling, it went pretty much extinct. (At least that is my impression.) }3...Nbd7 { might still be objectively the best move but it is also the most theoretical one.  As this line is so rare these days, I will go with something more practical for the very instances that you'll ever meet this line. } ) )
3. c6{ This is one of Black's easier responses. In lines where White plays  Bxf6  , it is usually a good setup for Black to play ... exf6  and then go for control of the light squares with ... f5 , ... g6 , ... c6 . }( { As Black is often provoking this these days by spending a tempo on }3...h6 { ,  4.Bxf6  is even more unattractive when Black plays a move that's part of this typical setup instead of the tempo loss!    Besides that, Black is also preparing ... Qb6 , since White has no ideal moves to protect  b2 . ... Qa5  and ... b5  might also come in quite handy if White goes for long-castling. }{    Overall, I think }3...c6 { takes away a lot of fun ideas White usually hopes for in this variation. } )
4. Qd3{ A typical aggressive move by White in the Rauzer that both prepares  e2 - e4  as well as  O-O-O . }
4. Qa5{ A typical response. Black stops  e2 - e4  and long-castling does also seem too risky when Black does already build up on the queenside. }
5. Bd2{ This is White's main move to deal with the pin. Nevertheless, White is not really threatening anything by opposing Black's queen.  Let me show you some other moves in the Clickables. }( {  A)  }5.O-O-O ? { is just suicidal. }5...b5! { -+ is nearly decisive. } )( {  B)  }5.f3?! { was played a number of times but White is not even ready to go  e2-e4 . Once again, }5...b5 { is just a strong reply. }5.a3!? { is a flexible move and it also anticipates to answer }5...Ne4 { with }6.b4! { . But I think after normal development such as }6...g6 { with ... Bg7 , ... Nbd7 , ... O-O  and potentially ... e5 , White's setup looks very artificial. } )
5. Na6( { A very unpleasant move for White to face.   }6...Nb4 { is just a big threat. } )
6. Rc1{ White has nothing better to protect  c2 . }( 6.Nd1 { was also played in a few games but just look at White's pieces after }6...Qb6⩱ { . } )
6. g6{ Black is just developing and prepares .... Bg7  but also ... Bf5 . }
7. f3{ Preparing  e2 - e4  is the only active plan White has. }
7. Bg7{ Black just keeps developing. }
8. e4{ White has to develop in a way that ... Nb4  can still be answered with  Qe3 . }( { For example }8.e3? { just loses the  a2 -pawn because of }8...Nb4 9.Qe2 Nxa2 { . With White's queen somewhere different, }10.Ra1 { would win for White. But here, Black could untangle with the counter-attack }10...Nxc3! { . } )
8. Nb4{ This is a good moment to win the tempo as White has to make some concessions not to lose a pawn. }
9. Qe3{ The best square. }( 9.Qe2 { does once again simply lose the  a2 -pawn because of }9...Nxa2 10.Ra1? Nxc3! { -+ . } )
9. dxe4{ Destroying White's center. }
10. Nxe4( 10.fxe4? Ng4! { loses the  d4 -pawn. } )
10. Nfd5( { This protects  b4  and attacks  e3 .   }11...Qxa2 { is also a threat. } )( { White loses a pawn or has to play a slightly worse endgame after }11.Qa3 Qxa3 { . } )
