[White "27) 2.Nc3 - Veresov's Antidote"]
[Black "Jobava 4.e3 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3
2. Nf6{ The most natural move. We simply develop and stop  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bf4{ The Jobava-London. }
3. e6( { The following setup allows very little of what is typically fun for the Jobava-London player. For example,     A)  }3...g6 { can sometimes invite  Qd2  and  Bh6 , but also  h4 - h5 . }{     B)  }3...Bf5 4.f3! { prepares  g4  with tempo.    But the text move is not only defensive. As we will see,   }4...Bb4 { is an insanely annoying idea that White usually addresses with some kind of concession. } )
4. e3{ This normal development move is not so popular anymore. Black can play ... Bb4  and aim for a quick ... c5  when the position might resemble some French Winawers but without White's typical space advantage in the center. }
4. Bb4{ This is pinning the knight and gives White some ideas to create counterplay. ... Ne4  is an immediate idea but also ... c5  and ...  Qa5  can be very annoying.  Potentially ... Bxc3  is an idea to spoil White's structure. }
5. Nge2{ White just overprotects  c3  and is getting ready for  a2 - a3 . }( {  A)  }5.a3?! Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 c5⩱ { is what Black is hoping for. }-- ...Qa5 { is coming with pressure against White's pawns. } )( {  B)  }5.Nf3?! Ne4!⩱ { gives Black strong pressure against  c3 . ... c5  and ... Qa5  are still coming. } )
5. O-O( { Simple development is best. }5...c5?! 6.a3! { is now working well. }6...Bxc3 { does now give up the bishop pair without damaging White's structure. } )
6. a3{ This is White's usual follow-up. }( { Aggressive ideas such as }6.g4 { are typical for the Jobava London and this move has been played by a number of strong players. However, I believe }6...Nxg4! 7.Rg1 { doesn't give White enough compensation. In the game  Omar - Yilmaz , White lost quickly after }7...Nf6 { , followed by a quick ... c5 . } )
6. Be7( { This is considered slightly better than }6...Bd6 { . }{ We have no reason to exchange the  f4 -bishop that is also restricting the  e2 -knight. } )
7. Ng1{ This move is arguably the main line. Played twice by Jobava London expert Hans Niemann and even by Magnus Carlsen! This move somehow underlines how bad the knight on  e2  really is.  White spends two more tempi to bring it to  f3  where it really has some influence in the center.  The second and third most popular move are moves that try to solve the problem of the knight slightly different. Nevertheless, Black's counterplay is always similar and pretty straightforward. }( {  A)  }7.Nc1 c5  )( {  B)  }7.Ng3 c5 {    }{ In both positions, we will just play ... Nc6  next and White does usually take on  c5  so that it is possible to play  Bf1 - d3  without losing the  d4 -pawn - or running into ... c5 - c4 . Nevertheless, with the extra center pawn, Black is doing great and a well-timed ... e5  might activate Black's position even further. } )
7. c5{ The natural pawn break. }
8. Nf3
8. Nh5{ This is certainly a good version of our well-known bishop grab as White lost many tempi in the opening and is in no position to get too much in exchange for the bishop pair. }( { Other moves such as }8...Nc6 { would also be possible. } )
9. dxc5{ This was played by Magnus and in the only Correspondence game that I found with this position. }( {  A)  }9.Bg3 { does give Black the possibility to take on  g3  whenever we want. Both, }9...Nc6 { as well as }9...Nd7 { - with the option to bring the other knight to  f6  to stabilize the kingside -, look like good waiting moves before grabbing the bishop. } )( {  B)  }9.Be5 { is a little bit more tricky. We shouldn't go }9...f6? { because of }10.Bxb8 Rxb8 11.g4! { +- but besides that, we have many good options. }9...Nc6 { or }9...Nd7 { does once again look like strong flexible waiting moves but even the forcing }9...cxd4 10.exd4 f6! { leads to slightly better positions for Black.  Now the trick }11.Bxb8 Rxb8 12.g4 { doesn't work as the knight has the  f4 -square. } )
9. Nxf4{ Grabbing the bishop pair. }
10. exf4
10. Bxc5
11. Bd3{ Bringing the bishop on the attacking diagonal towards  h7 . }
11. Qf6{ Not the only move but a pretty strong one. Black attacks  f4  and simply stabilizes the kingside.  In the next moves, Black can start their own counterplay on the queenside. }( { In  Carlsen - Xiong, Online 2020 , Black got a little nervous about the  h7 -pawn and played }11...g6?! { This gave Magnus the possibility to play }12.h4! { when  h4-h5  became all of a sudden a serious possibility to create an attack. } )
