[Black "Jobava 4.Nb5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3
2. Nf6{ The most natural move. We simply develop and stop  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bf4{ The Jobava-London. }
3. e6( { The following setup allows very little of what is typically fun for the Jobava-London player. For example,     A)  }3...g6 { can sometimes invite  Qd2  and  Bh6 , but also  h4 - h5 . }{     B)  }3...Bf5 4.f3! { prepares  g4  with tempo.    But the text move is not only defensive. As we will see,   }4...Bb4 { is an insanely annoying idea that White usually addresses with some kind of concession. } )
4. Nb5{ This move is the clear mainline nowadays. White stops the pin with ... Bb4 . }
4. Bb4+{ This check looks slightly random but the bishop won't be that bad on  a5 .     In the future, the bishop can go to  c7  where it opposes White's  f4 -bishop, prepares ... e5  and can even become an attacking piece if White cannot exchange it! By provoking  c2 - c3 , White will be forced to retreat with the knight to  a3  where it usually goes the whole way back to  b1  to get developed to the 'normal London square'  d2 . Nevertheless, this is so slow that it shouldn't really worry us. }( 4...Na6 { is the main alternative to protect  c7 . Here, there are also a lot of new territories to explore. As White's knight has the option to return to  c3  later - instead of  a3  - and with Black's knight stuck on the queenside for a while, White has time to build up on the kingside. }{    For example after }5.e3 Be7 { White can play the immediate }6.h4!? { or }6.g4!? { but even a slow build-up on the kingside with  Ng1 - f3 - e5 ,  Bf1 - d3 ,  Qf3  can become dangerous. Nothing horrible but I think the bishop check is easier. } )
5. c3
5. Ba5{ This was the idea. The bishop protects  c7 . }
6. a4{ This move contains a trap but if we are aware of that, there is not much else to know. }
6. a6{ It makes sense to get rid of the knight as soon as possible. }
7. Na3{ This is not really in the spirit of White's last move. Black can go for immediate action to punish White for their uncoordinated setup. }( { Trickier - not necessarily better - is }7.b4 { that we will see in the next trainable. } )
7. Ne4( {   }8...Nxc3 { is now some sort of a threat because Black would love to create the resulting imbalances on the queenside. White could not respond with the clever }9.Qd2?! { because of }9...Nxe2! 10.Qxa5 Nxf4 { . } )
8. e3{ The most natural move. White stops ... Nxc3  by protecting the  f4 -bishop. }( 8.b4 Bb6 9.a5 { fixes the queenside but is still not particularly stable. After }9...Ba7 { ,  c3  is still hanging and Black has also ideas with ... Nc6 , ... Qe7  and a quick ... e5 . } )
8. c5{ By protecting the  a5 -bishop, ... Nxc3  becomes an attractive option. }( 8...Nxc3? { doesn't work here. }9.Qd2! { pins the knight and Black has no good discoveries. } )
9. Nf3( { Developing is the best way to anticipate Black's idea. Something like }9.dxc5 { is only asking for trouble. }9...Nxc3! 10.bxc3 Bxc3+ 11.Ke2 { Black is not forced to take on  a1  immediately, it is also possible to start with }11...e5! { and a strong attack in the center. } )
9. Nxc3{ This was Black's idea behind  7...Ne4 . }
10. bxc3
10. Bxc3+
11. Nd2( 11.Ke2? { is only asking for trouble. }11...Bxa1 12.Qxa1 c4∓ { is an easy way to continue. Black's queenside pawns start rolling. } )
11. cxd4{ Collecting a third pawn for the piece. }
12. exd4
12. Bxd4{ Material is mathematically equal but very imbalanced. White's pieces are still all over the map and Black is ready to play ... e5  with easy development. }
