5. c3
5. Ba5{ This was the idea. The bishop protects  c7 . }
6. e3{ This is White's most popular move - simple development. }
6. a6{ It is usually a good idea to kick the knight back to  a3  as fast as possible. }( 6...O-O { is also possible but for example }6...Qe7?! 7.a4! { is already very annoying. }7...a6 8.b4 Bxb4 9.Nxc7+  )
7. Na3{ Now, White's knight is pretty misplaced and it usually even retreats to  b1 , as  c2  is also a square without future. }
7. O-O( { A flexible move even though we can also start with }7...Qe7 { . The threat of }-- 8...Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 Qxa3 { usually provokes }8.Nb1 { . } )
8. Bd3( { This is the main alternative to }8.Nf3 { . }{ The bishop controls its best diagonal and ... Nh5  is not possible. But the missing control over  e5  has its drawbacks. } )
8. Qe7( { This is the easiest move. Black threatens   }9...Bxc3+ { but is also controlling the vital  e5  and  c5 -squares. } )( { The immediate }8...c5 { is also a very attractive response. White can win the  c5 -pawn one way or the other, but Black will always get good counterplay by getting in ... e6 - e5 . For example: }9.Nf3 { White can just continue development but Black can also here get good counterplay by fighting for the control over the e5-square. }( { (The immediate }9.dxc5 { is similar. For example: }9...Bc7! { Black has the idea ... Bxf4 , followed by ... Qc7 , as well as simply ... e5  to create a huge center. }10.Ne2 e5=∞ { ) } )9...Bc7! 10.O-O Nc6 11.Bxc7 Qxc7 12.dxc5 e5=∞ { Usually, we are the side with the extra pawn in these situations but here I am not sad about reversed roles. White's pieces are not on ideal squares. This should give us very nice counterplay. } )
9. Nb1( { The typical response. }9.Nf3!? { allows }9...Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 Qxa3=∞ { White has compensation with the two bishops but a pawn is a pawn. } )
9. c5{ Black is getting in this pawn break. }
10. Nf3( { This is leading to similar positions as   }8.Nf3 { . } )( {  A)  }10.dxc5?! e5! { does give Black massive counterplay. This pawn move should not be allowed with tempo. } )( {  B) After a neutral developing move such as }10.Nd2 { , we'll go }10...Bc7 { . We are threatening to take on  d4  and  f4  to spoil White's structure. Other than that, we might also achieve ... e6 - e5  very soon. } )
10. Nh5{ Winning the bishop pair! }
11. dxc5{ Let's take this as a sample line. White has different possibilities but nothing that is worrying. }( {  A)  }11.Bg5?! { This is worse than in the next trainable with 8.  Nf3  . The bishop move to  d3  can be not ideal because of ... e6 - e5 - e4  ideas. }11...f6 12.Bh4 { Black has different options on how to continue here but with the bishop on  d3 , all typical motifs seem to work. }12...cxd4 { seems to be the best. If White takes with the knight, we just enjoy our big center. }13.exd4?! g5!? 14.Bg3 e5!? { ∓ is just one of the lines that illustrate the problems of the bishop on  d3 . } )( {  B)  }11.O-O { gives Black different options. }11...Nxf4 12.exf4 cxd4 13.cxd4 { Is a typical structure. White is playing for the fact that the control over the dark squares compensates for the weaker structure. Nevertheless should Black be fine with ... Bd7 , ... Nc6 , then doubling on the c-file. }{ Other moves such as }11...Bb6 { to increase the pressure on  d4  first, followed by ... Nxf4  and ... Qf6  is also possible. } )( {  C)  }11.Bxh7+? { is fancy but it doesn't work. }11...Kxh7 12.Ng5+ Kg6-+ { Protecting the knight and there is no follow-up. } )( {  D)  }11.Bg3 { We don't have to take this bishop right away but we can wait until White castles. }11...cxd4 { This is a good way to start to stop  dxc5  and  b4  ideas. }12.exd4 Nc6⇆ { Whenever White castles, we take on  g3 . }13.Bh4? f6 { makes matters worse for White. }{ Now, ... Nf4  is possible next, but we can also just play for ... e5  or ... g5 . } )
11. Nxf4{ Taking the bishop. }
12. exf4
12. Bc7( { The double-threat of   }13...Bxf4 { and }13...Qxc5 { wins back the pawn. } )
