7. Na3{ Now, White's knight is pretty misplaced and it usually even retreats to  b1 , as  c2  is also a square without future. }
7. O-O( { A flexible move even though we can also start with }7...Qe7 { . The threat of }-- 8...Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 Qxa3 { usually provokes }8.Nb1 { . } )
8. Nf3{ The most natural move, even though putting this knight here allows the following ... Nh5 . }
8. Qe7( { With the threat   }9...Bxc3+ { . }{ As in the last trainable, it is useful to include ... Qe7  and  Nb1 . } )
9. Nb1
9. Nh5{ Going for the bishop pair. }
10. Bg5( {  A)  }10.Be5 f6 11.Bg3 { gives Black plenty of good options. We can play }11...Nxg3 { but we can also play it safe with }11...g6 { . } )( {  B)  }10.Bg3?! { is even worse as Black's kingside is more stable after }10...Nxg3 11.hxg3 { . Now, }11...g6 { secures the kingside and after that, we can play for ... e5  or ... c5 . } )
10. f6
11. Bh4
11. g5{ Once again we use aggressive means to win the bishop pair. }
12. g4{ This was played in the Correspondence game  Cirulis - Nichols, 2021 . But this kind of exchange shouldn't frighten Black. }( {  A)  The natural }12.Bg3 { allows Black dynamic counterplay in the center. }12...Nc6 { Preparing  ...e5 . }13.Nbd2 g4 { Not the only move but misplacing the knight first is a typical idea. }14.Nh4 { and here, we can go for immediate action with }14...e5!? { but it is also possible to start with the more flexible }14...f5 { that protects  g4  and allows still ... e5  but also ... f4  in the future. } )( {  B)  }12.Nfd2 { doesn't achieve anything. }12...Ng7 13.Bg3 Nc6!⩱ { Black is getting ready for ... e5 . } )
12. gxh4
13. gxh5
13. Kh8{ Stepping out of the g-file. In the next moves, we can play ... Nc6 , ... Bd7  and go for ... e5 . It is also possible to go for the h-pawn with ... Qf7 .    With our strong counterplay in the center, White should have other things on their priority list than taking our  h4 -pawn. }
