[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) 1.d4 d5 - Remaining Nonsense"]
[Black "Introduction Queen's Pawn Openings"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5{ The important stuff in the  1.d4   d5  universe is done!     In this chapter, we'll cover the "small stuff" that White can still try in this position. As Grünfeld Slav players we are very spoiled because we could just play against  g2 - g3  or  e2 - e3  setups as if the moves  c2 - c4  and ... c7 - c6  were on the board.     Overall, there is nothing in this chapter that could scare us in any way. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) 1.d4 d5 - Remaining Nonsense"]
[Black "Blackmar Diemer #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. e4{ This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn for the open e- and f-file - that's pretty much it.  I remember playing this gambit quite a bit myself in my youth in casual games but I always had the feeling that Black can play pretty much anything against it and only some really stupid moves need to happen to give White a real initiative. To be honest, looking at this game now with modern engines only solidifies this impression. }
2. dxe4( { If you are a French or Caro-Kann player, you can just play }2...e6 { or }2...c6 { . But taking the pawn is definitely the best move. } )
3. Nc3( { The right move-order. }3.f3 { gives Black the strong additional option }3...e5! { . } )
3. Nf6
4. f3( { This is the white idea. By opening up the f-file, White plays for an initiative in the center and the kingside.    }4.Bg5 { is another move sometimes played in practice, but this so called 'Von Popiel Gambit' is also pretty bad.    As long as the  e4 -pawn stays on the board, White has problems developing. }-- 5.Bxf6 exf6 6.Nxe4 { wins back the pawn but also gives up the bishop pair and should be better for Black, so this is not really a threat.    Similar to my explanation in the  Richter-Veresov , we could claim that even   }4...h6!? { should be pretty good to provoke this exchange. This would be the minimalistic approach.    However, we might even get this exchange under better circumstances. }4...c6 { looks like a nice flexible move here as well, the same move as against the Richter-Veresov. If White plays }5.Bxf6 { , we have pretty much won a full tempo and also if White plays }5.Nge2 { (with the idea  6.Ng3 ), we might then play }5...h6!? 6.Bxf6 exf6 { , once again with the bishop pair and White's knight committed to  e2 .      }5...g6!? { would also fit nicely into our repertoire.    Overall, we are spoilt for choice and White cannot really hope for more than winning back the e4-pawn under a lot of concessions. } )
4. exf3{ Not the only move to stay a pawn up but traditionally the main line. }
5. Nxf3{ The natural way to recapture. White simultaneously develops the knight. }( 5.Qxf3 { has been played in a number of games, hoping that sacrificing a second pawn gives White even more open files and a bigger lead in development. Nevertheless, besides the fact that }5...Qxd4 { is objectively just a two-pawn advantage for very vague compensation, we can also just play the same set-up as after  5.Nxf3 : }5...g6 { , followed by ... Bg7  and ... O-O . } )
5. g6{ More or less any decent developing move is good for Black. I think the following setup has some resemblance to the Schlechter, that's why I chose the fianchetto. }
6. Bf4{ The second most popular plan for White is this move, connected with  Qd2  and long castling.     Kudos to White: Aiming for a position with opposite side castling is practically a good decision if you are a pawn down for very little compensation. At least White creates some chaos.  Nevertheless, a pawn is a pawn. }
6. Bg7
7. Qd2
7. O-O{ We just keep developing. }
8. O-O-O
8. a6{ In positions with kings on opposite sides, it is important to go for the attack. This move prepares ... b5 . }
9. Bh6{ I will use this move as a sample line as it shows one more important idea. White wants to exchange the defender on  g7  and prepares  h2 - h4  without allowing ... h5 . }( { For example: }9.h4 h5! { ∓ does very convincingly stop White's attack. It is not clear if White will get any open files on the kingside soon. } )
9. b5{ Not the only move but part of our plan. }
10. h4{ White would love to play  h4 - h5  and get an attack along the h-file. }( { The move order }10.Bxg7 Kxg7 11.h4 { allows }11...h5∓ { . }{ It's hard for White to break through on the kingside while Black can continue attacking on the queenside but might also just play in the center after something like ... Nbd7 , ... Bb7 , ... c5 . } )
10. Bxh6{ An important exchange. By taking the bishop and playing ... Ng4 , we will still be able to get in ... h5 . }
11. Qxh6
11. Ng4{ Driving the queen away from  h6 . }
12. Qd2{ Just a sample square to show Black's idea. }
12. h5{ White's attack is stopped, we are a pawn up and will just bring our pieces out next with ... Nd7  and ... Bb7 . }
