[White "28) 1.d4 d5 - Remaining Nonsense"]
[Black "Hodgson Attack 2.Bg5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bg5{ This is a pretty odd-looking move as the bishop doesn't really attack anything on  g5  but can be attacked itself with ... h6  or ... f6 . }( { Had Black played   }1...Nf6 { , this bishop move would be the relatively well-respected 'Trompovsky Attack' but in the given position, there is much less purpose to it.    }{ I always knew the bishop move under the name 'Pseudo Trompovsky' but apparently it is also called 'Hodgson Attack' or 'Levitsky Attack'. White typically would love to transpose to the regular Trompovsky if Black plays ... Nf6  - what gives White the option to take the knight.  Besides that, White still wants to develop solidly as in the London System with  e3 ,  Nf3 ,  c3  and just play a game of chess. } )
2. f6{ A few years back, this was quite a shocking response but from the beginning, it scored very well for Black and modern engines simply agree that this is a good move. These days, this is just a well-respected main line for Black.  The lines are pretty forcing and easy to play for Black once you have understood the most important ideas. In many variations, Black will hunt down the dark-squared bishop - very fitting for our repertoire - and sometimes it is also useful to prepare ... e5  with this move.  Note that it is the same move that we play in the Exchange Variation with  4.Bg5  -  see here . You will recognize some similarities! }
3. Bf4{ The bishop is less exposed here than on  h4 . Now, we play a London System where we got the move ... f6  for free. }
3. Nc6{ Black is playing for a quick ... e5 . That is the advantage of having the pawn on  f6 ! }
4. Nf3( { A more passive move like }4.e3 { allows }4...e5 { . } )
4. g5{ A funny move. It is still the same approach as in the  Exchange chapter ! }
5. Bg3
5. g4{ The knight gets driven to the edge of the board where it can be a target. }
6. Nh4{ Despite the problems that we will see, this is the best square. }( {  A)  }6.Nfd2 { gives Black plenty of options. }6...h5 { , }6...e5 { or simply taking the pawn with }6...Nxd4 { are all good. } )( {  B)  }6.Ng1 { looks like White is already planning for the next game. }6...h5! { is threatening }-- ...h4 { and we can still continue aggressively with ... Ng8 - h6 - f5  or ... e5 . } )
6. e5{ Fighting for the initiative in the center. }
7. dxe5{ The main move. }( {  A)  }7.e3? f5! { is the same problem as we have seen in the sister variation of the exchange. }-- 8...f4 { and }8...Be7 { are threats than cannot be parried. } )( {  B)  }7.e4!? { is the engine suggestion. White will have some compensation but Black should still be better after both }7...exd4 { as well as }7...dxe4 { . } )
7. f5( { An interesting move, still playing with the tactical ideas   }8...f4 { as well as }8...Be7 { . White only has one move. } )( 7...fxe5 { is the alternative and about equal after }8.e4! { Striking back! }8...Nf6 9.exd5 Qxd5=  )
8. e4{ White has to play actively to parry the threats. }
8. fxe4{ With a very imbalanced position. The idea to play ... Be7  is usually reason enough that White should play a quick  h2 - h3 . Black can just develop with ... Be6  to secure  d6  and ... Qg5 /... Qd7  and ... O-O-O . A fun position that should objectively give equal chances. }( { Don't go }8...f4? { because of }9.Bxf4! Qxh4 10.exd5!+- { when White has three pawns for the piece but just a massive steamrolling center. } )
