1. d4
1. d5
2. Bg5{ This is a pretty odd-looking move as the bishop doesn't really attack anything on  g5  but can be attacked itself with ... h6  or ... f6 . }( { Had Black played   }1...Nf6 { , this bishop move would be the relatively well-respected 'Trompovsky Attack' but in the given position, there is much less purpose to it.    }{ I always knew the bishop move under the name 'Pseudo Trompovsky' but apparently it is also called 'Hodgson Attack' or 'Levitsky Attack'. White typically would love to transpose to the regular Trompovsky if Black plays ... Nf6  - what gives White the option to take the knight.  Besides that, White still wants to develop solidly as in the London System with  e3 ,  Nf3 ,  c3  and just play a game of chess. } )
2. f6{ A few years back, this was quite a shocking response but from the beginning, it scored very well for Black and modern engines simply agree that this is a good move. These days, this is just a well-respected main line for Black.  The lines are pretty forcing and easy to play for Black once you have understood the most important ideas. In many variations, Black will hunt down the dark-squared bishop - very fitting for our repertoire - and sometimes it is also useful to prepare ... e5  with this move.  Note that it is the same move that we play in the Exchange Variation with  4.Bg5  -  see here . You will recognize some similarities! }
3. Bd2{ This is the main move without the c-pawns but here it has no great reputation. White has a harder time here creating their pawn breaks in the center. }
3. Nc6{ Attacking  d4  while also preparing ... e5 . }
4. e3{ This is White's main move. }( {  A)  }4.Nc3?! { simply loses a pawn here after }4...Nxd4 { . } )( {  B)  }4.Nf3?! { This is just less flexible than  4.e3 . We can just play }4...e5 { when White has nothing better than to still play }5.e3 { . } )
4. e5{ The principled continuation. }
5. Bb5{ The typical move. This creates some pressure against Black's center and the pin against the  c6 -knight might indeed be annoying if Black wants to go for long-castling. }( 5.Nf3?! e4! { is without a doubt a great structure for Black. }{ The knight has to move and we can build a strong center with ... Be6 , ... f5 , ... Bd6 , ... Nf6  where White constantly has to watch out for the ... f5 - f4  break. } )
5. exd4{ A simple solution. In the resulting symmetrical structure, Black can still play aggressive against White's king. }
6. exd4
6. Bf5{ Black will play ... Qd7  and play aggressively on the kingside with ... h7 - h5 - h4 , potentially including the g-pawn. Despite the annoying pin against  c6 , we can consider castling queenside but we can also leave the king in the center for a bit and consider hiding it on  f7 . A sample line: }
7. Ne2
7. Qd7
8. O-O
8. a6{ Asking White what they intend to do with the bishop. }
9. Ba4{ The logical square. Nevertheless, now it is not so easy for White to play  c2 - c4  which would otherwise be one of the more logical attempts to counter a kingside attack. }( 9.Bxc6 Qxc6⩱ { just gives us the bishop pair. } )
9. h5{ The attack starts! }
10. b4{ White typically does the same. }
10. h4{ With a sharp position where I would prefer Black. }( {  ...h4-h3  is a dangerous idea to weaken White's light squares forever and if White plays }11.h3 { themselves, it will be very easy for us to open up the kingside eventually with ... g7 - g5 - g4 . } )
