*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) 1.d4 d5 - Remaining Nonsense"]
[Black "Stonewall Attack #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. e3{ This version of the Colle where White postpones  Ng1 - f3  should usually transpose to its big brother in most cases. The main independent option is a 'Stonewall' setup with  Bf1 - d3 ,  f2 - f4 ,  Ng1 - f3 ,  O-O , and often  c2 - c3 . White tries to create a grip on the dark squares and often tries to go for a kingside attack by using the  e5 -square as an outpost. }
2. g6{ After some thinking, I came to the conclusion that the immediate 2... g6  is a clever move order. If White plays  Ng1 - f3  without  f2 - f4 , we can play .... Ng8 - f6  and transpose to the  normal Colle .      1)  If White plays  c2 - c4 , we transpose to the Grünfeld Slav with ... c7 - c6 .      2) If White however goes for a Stonewall with  f2 - f4 , it is sometimes useful to develop the knight not too early to  f6  just to have the extra option ... Nh6 , which prepares ... Bf5 , allows us to potentially kick a knight out from  e5  with ... f7 - f6  and in the future, Black can often manoeuvre the  h6 -knight via  f5  to  d6  and bring the other knight via  d7  to  f6  when both horsies to a great job of controlling White's weak light squares. }
3. f4( 3.Bd3 { is the move if White wants to stay flexible but as you will see  here , it only leads to transpositions. } )
3. Bg7{ The bishop belongs here anyways. }
4. Nf3
4. c5{ I like to play ... c5  as early as possible against the Stonewall. We never have to worry about this pawn because not only do we usually win back the pawn anyways, it would also give up White's main strategic goal to stay solid on the dark squares. }( 4...Nh6 { also fits in our setup but }5.c4!? { is an additional option for White. }{ With an open center, White doesn't want their pawn on  f4 , however, we also don't like our knight on  h6  in these scenarios. } )
5. c3{ White completes their Stonewall formation  c3 - d4 - e3 - f4 . }
5. Nh6{ Leaving the bishop open, preparing ... Bf5  - after  Bf1 - d3  - and the knight can often end up on  d6  so that the other knight can land on  f6 . Black is trying to take control over White's weak light squares.     Because the Stonewall is such a slow opening - White goes for a solid formation in the center instead of immediate action, it is okay to put some pieces on weird squares in the short term if it allows a very harmonious setup within just some more moves. }
6. Bd3{ The typical square. But Black's following moves can be played against any Stonewall setup. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Qc7{ A flexible move. Black protects  c5  and keeps an eye on  f4  and  c3 . Not really important right now but because White usually wants to respond to ... c5xd4  with  e3xd4 , it makes sense to anticipate Black's pressure against the pawns. }
8. Nbd2( { White can play many moves here. }8.Qe1 { and }8.Qe2 { are the most popular ones just to bring the queen slightly closer to the kingside.  Nevertheless, the following manoeuvre can be played against everything. } )
8. Nf5{ Before we play ... Bf5 , we bring the knight to  d6 . }( 8...Bf5 { makes a lot of sense from a positional standpoint and we would be more than happy if the bishops come off but }9.Be2! { leaves our knight stranded on  h6 . Still a good position for Black but I'd like to have it on  d6  first. } )
9. Qe2{ White has to defend  e3 . }
9. Nd6{ Black's next move is ... Bf5  with the healthier position. }
