[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. e3{ This is the so-called 'Colle System'. It looks strange to imprison the bishop on  c1  voluntarily without any need but Colle specialists have their ideas on how to deal with this. }
3. g6{ An elegant solution when you are ready to play the Schlechter Slav. White has nothing better than to transpose to our  e3  chapters with a quick  c2 - c4 . }( 3...c5!? { is an important move of our setup if White doesn't transpose to the Schlechter. Even though this is the theoretically best move, it allows White to lay out some pitfalls with }4.dxc5!? e6 5.b4 a5 6.c3 { Black is in good theoretical shape if they know their lines - but we have no reason to allow such nonsense. } )
4. Bd3{ White has a lot of moves that don't immediately transpose to the Schlechter. }( { Besides }4.Bd3 { , you could certainly also make cases for }4.Be2 { , }4.Nbd2 { , }4.c3 { or }4.b3 { . Nevertheless, postponing  c2-c4  will only allow it to play  ...c7-c5  for Black when we get our typical Grünfeld activity under even better circumstances than we are used to.  Let's just use }4.Bd3 { as a sample line of how things can develop. } )
4. Bg7{ I think it makes sense to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  against all potential White moves. If White transposes to the Schlechter with  c2 - c4 , we will happily accept it. If White doesn't do it, well, then we can typically play even more active with ... c5 . }
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Nbd2{ This is White's most popular move in the position.  White cannot stop ... c5  with anything besides  b2 - b4  anyways. }( { Even }6.c3 c5! { works for Black. Grabbing the pawn is never really a good option. }7.dxc5 { Here, }7...a5 { is the safe move to make sure that White cannot keep the  c5 -pawn but there are typically different options. }7...Nfd7!? { is another way to do it. }8.b4 a5! { is just creating a ton of pressure against White's queenside pawns and }9.Nd4 e5! { gives Black nice additional pressure in the center. } )
6. c5{ A good moment to strike back in the center. }
7. b3{ I consider this move already very inaccurate. Black can just take on  d4  }
7. cxd4
8. exd4( 8.Nxd4? { gives Black a lot of central influence that can be used immediately with }8...e5! { ∓ . } )
8. Nc6{ The move  b2 - b3  doesn't have a big purpose here. Black has ideas with ... Nb4  and ... Bf5 .     White's structure is very vulnerable here because  c2 - c3  would protect  d4  but would be weak themselves while our pieces can easily put pressure on White's pawns.  If White plays  c2 - c3 , it is indeed a typical idea to prepare for ... e5  to open up the long diagonal and get access to the  c3 -pawn. The big guy on  g7  will be thankful, I promise! }
