3. g3( { With this move, White is typically aiming at Catalan structures but without all the theory that comes with the main move order ( }3.c4 e6 4.g3 { ). } )( { The big drawback of this move order is that Black has much more flexibility:   }3...Bf5 { or }3...Bg4 { are playable as the bishop is not boxed in and also the immediate }3...c5 { can be played without any problems. }{ From our repertoire perspective, the easiest way to deal with this opening in the same way as with the moves  c2-c4  and  ... c7 -c6  included -  see here . We just continue with ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... O-O . If White transposes in the meantime by playing  c2 - c4 , we will happily play the positions from the   4.g3  chapters .     In this chapter, we will only look at the variations where White doesn't play  c2 - c4 . } )
3. g6{ We play  ...g6 ,  ...Bg7  and  ...O-O , giving White the possibility to transpose to  variations with  c2 -c4 . }
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. O-O( { Both sides have played their flexible moves. If White doesn't play }6.c4 { now, it might be Black who takes the initiative in the center with .... c5 . } )
6. c3{ I am pretty sure, I have seen White's piece setup somewhere... White wants to 'schlechter' us themselfes! }
6. a5{ A typical move, trying to eventually gain more space with ... a5 - a4 . }( 6...c5?! 7.dxc5 { is the idea of White's move order. It doesn't look too horrible but White scores nice in practice and the engines also give White a small edge as it is not so easy to regain the pawn. No need to allow that! } )
7. a4{ A standard reply. White stops ... a5 - a4 . }
7. Nbd7{ A flexible move. Black prepares both ... c5  and ... e5 . }
8. Bf4{ White's main move. White controls the  e5 -square and leaves the  b1 -knight the option to go to  a3  if Black plays ... c5 . }( {  A)  }8.Nbd2 c5 { is just very comfortable for Black. White's knight should remain on  b1  so that it is ready to jump quickly to  b5  via  a3 . } )( {  B)  The immediate }8.Na3 { was played in a few games. To me, }8...c6 { looks just like a good answer. } )
8. c6{ Just a solid move that stabilizes the position. We have a very non-forcing line so I don't think that it makes sense to go any deeper.  Typical ideas are ... Re8 , with the idea to prepare ... e5 . For this plan, it is worth considering to play ... Nh5  to get rid of the  f4 -bishop.     Besides that, we can also always consider the ambitious expansion with ... h6  and ... g5  to win more space.  For the more patient players between us, let's just mention that Black can also simply improve their pieces bit by bit. ... Ne4  or ... Qb6  and then maybe ... Nd7 - f6  and ... Bf5  look like ways to continue if you don't feel the need to change the pawn structure anytime soon. }
