2. Nf6
3. g3( { With this move, White is typically aiming at Catalan structures but without all the theory that comes with the main move order ( }3.c4 e6 4.g3 { ). } )( { The big drawback of this move order is that Black has much more flexibility:   }3...Bf5 { or }3...Bg4 { are playable as the bishop is not boxed in and also the immediate }3...c5 { can be played without any problems. }{ From our repertoire perspective, the easiest way to deal with this opening in the same way as with the moves  c2-c4  and  ... c7 -c6  included -  see here . We just continue with ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... O-O . If White transposes in the meantime by playing  c2 - c4 , we will happily play the positions from the   4.g3  chapters .     In this chapter, we will only look at the variations where White doesn't play  c2 - c4 . } )
3. g6{ We play  ...g6 ,  ...Bg7  and  ...O-O , giving White the possibility to transpose to  variations with  c2 -c4 . }
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. O-O( { Both sides have played their flexible moves. If White doesn't play }6.c4 { now, it might be Black who takes the initiative in the center with .... c5 . } )
6. b3( { White goes for a double fianchetto but this is once again just asking for }6...c5 { . } )
6. c5{ Black will end with nice central influence. }
7. Bb2{ This is White's main move but I believe Black is already just better. }( 7.dxc5 Ne4 { With the weakened long diagonal, Black has no problems regaining the pawn with a good position. } )
7. cxd4
8. Nxd4( { The normal way to recapture. }8.Bxd4 { keeps for the moment more control over  e5  but only temporarily. The bishop can be attacked with tempo. }8...Nc6 9.Bb2 Re8 { leads to our trainable. } )
8. Re8{ A strong move. Black wants to play ... e5  and wants to keep the pawn on that square. }( { The immediate }8...e5 9.Nf3 { forces Black to play }9...e4 { when White does at least regain some stability on the dark squares in the center. } )
9. Nf3{ White tries to anticipate Black's ... e5  idea. }
9. Nc6{ Black is once again getting ready for ... e5 . }
10. Ne5{ The typical response. White opens up the  g2 -bishop and just physically blocks ... e7 - e5 . }
10. Qc7{ Forces White to give up the outpost on  e5 . }
11. Nxc6
11. bxc6{ We have a kind of reversed Grünfeld exchange - but one where White has very little pressure against Black's center yet. Simple developing with ... Bf5  and ... Rad8  should ensure that Black's center will always be nicely overprotected and after that, we can either try to play in the center my mobilizing the center pawns or we can go for ... h7 - h5 - h4  to soften up White's kingside. }
