1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. g3( { With this move, White is typically aiming at Catalan structures but without all the theory that comes with the main move order ( }3.c4 e6 4.g3 { ). } )( { The big drawback of this move order is that Black has much more flexibility:   }3...Bf5 { or }3...Bg4 { are playable as the bishop is not boxed in and also the immediate }3...c5 { can be played without any problems. }{ From our repertoire perspective, the easiest way to deal with this opening in the same way as with the moves  c2-c4  and  ... c7 -c6  included -  see here . We just continue with ... g6 , ... Bg7  and ... O-O . If White transposes in the meantime by playing  c2 - c4 , we will happily play the positions from the   4.g3  chapters .     In this chapter, we will only look at the variations where White doesn't play  c2 - c4 . } )
3. g6{ We play  ...g6 ,  ...Bg7  and  ...O-O , giving White the possibility to transpose to  variations with  c2 -c4 . }
4. Bg2
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. O-O( { Both sides have played their flexible moves. If White doesn't play }6.c4 { now, it might be Black who takes the initiative in the center with .... c5 . } )
6. Nbd2( { Besides }6.c4 { , }{ this is White's main move. White keeps options open to still play  c2 - c4  at some point but doesn't commit to anything yet. } )
6. c5{ Black is now attacking White's center and 7... cxd4  would lead to a strong pawn mass in the center. }
7. dxc5( { The only critical move. For example }7.c3 { simply allows }7...cxd4 8.cxd4 { with an Exchange structure where the  d2 -knight is misplaced. } )
7. Qc7{ This threatens to win back the pawn but Black is also preparing ... e5  or ... Rd8  to just build up in the center. }
8. Nb3{ White's main move. White at least try to hang onto the  c5 -pawn. }( {  A)  }8.b4 { is another way to protect the pawn but has never been played in practice. The long diagonal looks menacing. }8...a5 { is the typical response. After }9.c3 { , Black can just play a knight move such as }9...Ne8 { to win back the pawn. }-- 10...Bxc3 { and }10...axb4 { are threats. But we can also go for the more forcing }9...axb4 10.cxb4 Ng4 11.Rb1 Bf5 { which develops with tempo and also wins the  a2 -pawn. } )( {  B)  }8.c4 { leads to a symmetrical structure but Black's pieces seem slightly more active. For example: }8...Qxc5 9.cxd5 Qxd5 { Black will just play ... Qh5 , ... Nc6 , put a rook on the d-file, potentially ... Bh3 . Black's position has some venom. } )
8. Nbd7{ I think this is the easiest move. Black is ready to answer  Bf4  with ... e5  and is simply increasing the pressure on  c5 . }( 8...e5!? { is a nice move as well. Black prevents  Bc1 - f4  and simply builds up a big center.  However, here are more lines where White might indeed keep the extra pawn and Black is forced to play for (good) compensation. }9.Ne1 a5 10.a4 Nc6 11.c3 Be6  )
9. c3{ White's main move. White just makes a flexible move and waits for Black to take on  c5  so that they can play  Bf4 . }
9. e5{ Stopping all  Bf4  ideas. Next, Black might just play ... Re8  to protect  e5  and get ready to take on  c5 . }( 9...Nxc5 10.Bf4 { gives White some pressure because ... e5  is not possible. } )
10. Be3{ White is not forced to protect the pawn on  c5  yet because Black cannot take it without losing the  e5 -pawn. But it's just hard for White to find a different logical developing move! }( 10.e4 { was once played in Correspondence Chess and is a typical idea in similar positions. White forces action in the center even though Black has no particular problems.     A)  }10...Nxe4 11.Qxd5 Nexc5 { looks okay for Black.     B)  }10...dxe4 { might be an even better way to regain the pawn. }11.Ng5 a5! { Black undermines the  b3 -knight first. }12.a4 h6! { As we will see, the  c5 -pawn does not run away and by forcing the issue, Black gets their pieces to very comfortable squares. }13.Nxe4 Nxe4 14.Bxe4 Nf6! 15.Bg2 Be6⇆ { Now, Black is the one who can decide when to play ... Bxb3  and ... Qxc5 . But before we do so, we can get a lot of activity, starting by putting a rook on  d8 . Protecting the  c5 -pawn with  Bc1 - e3  is not really stable as Black can hunt this bishop with ... Ng4  or even ... Nd5 . } )
10. Rd8{ Black just strengthens the center. By putting the rook behind the d-pawn, we might be able to move the  f6 -knight.  ... Ng4  or ... Ne4  might be ideas. }
11. h3{ Trying to get rid of all ... Ng4  ideas but one more tempo that White wastes in the opening. }( {  A)  }11.Qd2?! { for example is already a mistake. }11...a5! { Undermining the  b3 -knight. }12.a4 Ne4! { White has stopped ... a5 - a4  but only at the cost of leaving the  b3 -knight unprotected. This move wins the  c5 -pawn now by force because }13.Qxd5?! Ndxc5! { is asking for trouble. White has to give the queen with }14.Qxd8 { because }14.Qc4 Be6! { is even worse. } )( {  B)  }11.Qc2 { was played in  Mousessian - Meiners, Correspondence 2017 . But besides the fact that Black can just continue the 'standoff' with moves like }11...a5 { or }11...h6 { , that game has shown that even the immediate }11...Ng4 { is good enough. } )
11. b6{ The immediate way to create counterplay. White has spent many tempi securing the  c5 -pawn but besides that, White's pieces are not on particularly great squares. }( { It certainly is also possible to continue waiting here with moves like }11...h6 { or }11...a5 { as well but this pawn sacrifice should give Black nice compensation. } )
12. cxb6
12. Nxb6{ Black is getting a nice queenside initiative. ... a7 - a5 - a4 , ... Bc8 - a6 , ... Na4  or ... Nc4  are coming, .... Rab8 . Black has nice pressure on the queenside. }
