1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. c3{ I don't think I have ever encountered this move in my life and it is such a rare move that I might have ignored it when this wouldn't have been the chosen move order in Le Quang Liem’s 'Lifetime Repertoires: London System'. Against many black setups, White will just play  Bc1 - f4  and reach a 'delayed' London.  But there is a reason why this move is so rarely played: It just takes away a lot of flexibility from White's setup.  Especially  c3 - c4  would now mean the loss of a tempo. }
3. e6( { We are happily inviting White to play }4.Bf4 { and play a normal London kind of position with an unnecessary early  c2 - c3 . For more information, see  this chapter . } )
4. e3{ White's setup looks like a Colle but the given move order allows Black to play a quick ... e5 . }
4. Bd6{ Black will just play for ... e5 . }
5. Bd3{ The most typical response. }
5. Nbd7{ The most direct way to go for the e-pawn break. }
6. Nbd2{ White tries to prepare  e3 - e4  as well. But because White wasted a tempo on  c2 - c3 , we achieve our break first. }
6. O-O{ Bringing the king into safety first is a good way to start. Nevertheless,  the immediate 6...  e5  is also possible. }
7. O-O{ White should accept their fate that Black will get an easy game after ... e5  next. }( { If White plays }7.e4 { themselves, then }7...e5! { is very strong. The center opens up and Black is just slightly better prepared. }8.O-O { is the safest move but after }8...exd4 { , White is forced to play with a non-ideal version of an IQP after     A)  }9.cxd4 dxe4 10.Nxe4 Nxe4 11.Bxe4 { Black gets all pieces to good squares with ... h6 , ... Nf6 , ... Re8 . }{     B)  }9.Nxd4? Nc5! { with an attack against  e4  and  d3  would be bad for White. } )
7. e5( {   }8...e4 { is a threat. Black just gets a nice setup. } )( 8.e4 exd4 { transposes to  7.e4  while }8.dxe5 Nxe5 9.Nxe5 Bxe5 { just gives Black the slightly more active position. } )
