3. e6( { We are happily inviting White to play }4.Bf4 { and play a normal London kind of position with an unnecessary early  c2 - c3 . For more information, see  this chapter . } )
4. Bg5( { The only independent bishop move. }4.Bf4 c5 { will transpose to the London chapter. } )
4. h6{ This move is very much in the spirit of our repertoire. Black wins the bishop pair. }
5. Bxf6{ This does give up the bishops very easily but White typically tries to compensate it with a quick  e2 - e4  in the center. }
5. Qxf6
6. Nbd2{ Staying flexible with the e-pawn.  e2 - e4  is the main idea. }
6. c5{ Black creates some counterplay of their own. Especially if White goes for  e2 - e4 , the  d4 -pawn can become a target. }
7. e4{ The most active response. }( 7.e3 { is playable but doesn't put any pressure on Black. }7...Bd6 { is a good response, followed by ... Nc6 , ... O-O . The position does slightly resemble the  Champion's Choice  chapter with colours reversed. Both sides are looking for good moments to play a pawn break in center but besides that, we will just improve our pieces and eventually try to win space - sometimes on the queenside (... b5  and/or ... a5 ) or even on the kingside (... g5 ). } )
7. cxd4{ This is a rather forcing response to create immediate counterplay in the center. }
8. Nxd4{ White's main move. White goes for some piece activity connected with  Bf1 - b5 + ideas while Black's king is in the center. Nevertheless, this is not scary. }( {  A)  }8.cxd4?! dxe4 { leads to good IQP for Black. Especially because }9.Nxe4 Bb4+⩱ { comes with tempo and forces White to retreat one of their pieces. } )( {  B)  Closing the center with }8.e5 Qd8 { simply kills off White's potential initiative. The structure after }9.Nxd4 { or }9.cxd4 { resembles some Caro-Kanns or Frenchs but with the two bishops, those would be very good versions. } )( {  C)  }8.exd5 { gives Black an isolated pawn but the bishops will easily compensate the slightly weakened structure. }8...exd5 9.Nxd4 Nc6⇆ { There is no concrete pressure against  d5 , so we should be able to simply develop with moves like ... Bd6 , ... Bd7 , ... O-O , then putting the rooks on  e8  and  d8 . } )
8. Bc5{ A strong move. Black is ready to castle but we can also take on  d4 . }
9. N2b3{ This is White's main move to keep the initiative going. }( {  A)  }9.exd5 { does give Black plenty of good options. }9...Qe5+!? { is a funny check to give White an IQP structure. For example }10.Qe2 Bxd4 11.cxd4 Qxd5 { with a decent position for Black in Ballmann - Hübner, Switzerland 2013. } )( {  B)  }9.Bb5+ { is the second most popular move but Black can simply develop. }9...Bd7 10.Qa4 { The main move to create some pressure but there is just not much going on. }( { ( }10.Bxd7+ Nxd7 { is just very comfortable. }11.exd5 Qe5+! { is once again a nice check to recapture on }d5 { with the queen.) } )10...Bxd4! 11.Bxd7+ ( { ( }11.cxd4?! Qg5! { ∓ }{ is surprisingly annoying as White has no harmonious way to save the  g2 -pawn and ... dxe4  would also open the attack against  b5  and force White to take on  d7  and release the tension.) } )11...Nxd7 12.Qxd4 { Sadly forced. }( { ( }12.cxd4?! Qg5∓ { is still annoying.) } )12...Qxd4 13.cxd4 dxe4 14.Nxe4⩱ { with a good endgame for Black because of the  d4 -pawn. } )
9. Bb6{ This is the easy move that has given Black good results. }( 9...Bxd4 10.Nxd4 dxe4 { wins a pawn that White typically sacrifices to get in some tricks with }11.Nb5!? { =∞ }{ This is objectively also good for Black apparently but there is no need to allow this mess. } )
10. Bb5+{ White's most precise move order. They exchange one of Black's bishops before taking on  d5 . }( { After }10.exd5 { , }10...Qe5+ 11.Be2 Qxd5 { is similar to the mainline.    However }10...O-O!? { is a very interesting pawn sacrifice.After }11.dxe6 Bxe6 { , }{ Black has opened up the position for the bishops quite a bit. White cannot take on  e6  as  f2  would be hanging with check. } )
10. Bd7{ This gives up one of our bishops but it is the less active one and the resulting position is very pleasant. }( { Keeping the bishops with }10...Nd7!? { is possible but it is also playing with fire. After }11.exd5 { , our standard manoeuvre     A)  }11...Qe5+?! 12.Qe2 Qxd5 { is risky because of }13.O-O-O ! { → Black's piece setup is asking for trouble. } )( {  B)  }11...exd5 { is the better move to simply play an IQP but White has annoying checks such as }12.Qe2+ { , trying to exchange queens. } )
11. Bxd7+
11. Nxd7
12. exd5
12. Qe5+{ The typical check in this line to win back the pawn. }
13. Qe2
13. Qxd5{ we will castle, play ... Nc5 , and fight for the d-file which is of high importance in this pawn structure as it is the only fully open file. Black can certainly try to grab some space with ... a5 - a4  but as our pawn majority is in the center/the kingside, we should also think about good moments to advance with ... e5  and ... f5 . }
