1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bg5{ Another move order reminiscent of a Trompowsky, but quite unpopular. By inserting ... d7 - d5  and  Ng1 - f3 , White has actually lost many active possibilities. }( { For example, Black can play }3...e6 { without White being able to immediately occupy the center with  e2-e4 .    }3...c5 { is also a good typical move against the Trompowsky.    But I've always found that }3...Ne4 { shows the best the disadvantage of the white move order! } )
3. Ne4{ Activating the knight and attacking the bishop on  g5 . In a normal Trompovsky, White has no knight on  f3  which makes it easier to challenge it and often even play ambitiously with  f2 - f3 . Here, only Black should be happy about the knight on  e4 . }
4. Bh4{ A logical square. }
4. c5{ Black can typically play very ambitiously against White's harmless opening. Black typically follows up with a quick ... Qb6  and pressure against  d4  and  b2 . }
5. dxc5{ This is stopping ... Qb6  and White hopes to win some time by provoking Black's knight out of the center. But in a positional sense, we are quite happy to see White exchanging their d- against our c-pawn. }
5. Nc6{ We are in no hurry to recapture on  c5  and just develop. }
6. e3
6. g6{ Not the only move but it is giving the position a real Grünfeld-Slav touch. With no pawn on  d4 , our butcher will be very happy on that diagonal. }
7. Nbd2{ This move followed by 8.Nb3 is the mainline, but Black's setup is similar anyways. We will just play ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and eventually play ... Nxc5 . }( { If White develops the kingside instead, }7.Be2 Bg7 { - attacking  b2  - }8.c3 O-O 9.O-O Nxc5⇆ { is a logical continuation. Next, we can win some space with ... a5 - a4 . Moves like ... Qb6  or just developing the light-squared bishop are also logical. } )
7. Nxc5{ White provoked us to take the pawn now. }
8. Nb3{ This is the main move, but driving back the knight back to  e4  is no great accomplishment for White. }( 8.Be2 { can lead to positions similar to the ones mentioned on the last move. }{ For example, }8...Bg7 9.c3 O-O 10.O-O a5!?⇆ { is a good way to continue. } )
8. Ne4{ Black has regained the pawn and simply has more influence in the center. We are slightly better. }
