1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3
2. Nf6
3. Bg5{ Another move order reminiscent of a Trompowsky, but quite unpopular. By inserting ... d7 - d5  and  Ng1 - f3 , White has actually lost many active possibilities. }( { For example, Black can play }3...e6 { without White being able to immediately occupy the center with  e2-e4 .    }3...c5 { is also a good typical move against the Trompowsky.    But I've always found that }3...Ne4 { shows the best the disadvantage of the white move order! } )
3. Ne4{ Activating the knight and attacking the bishop on  g5 . In a normal Trompovsky, White has no knight on  f3  which makes it easier to challenge it and often even play ambitiously with  f2 - f3 . Here, only Black should be happy about the knight on  e4 . }
4. Bh4{ A logical square. }
4. c5{ Black can typically play very ambitiously against White's harmless opening. Black typically follows up with a quick ... Qb6  and pressure against  d4  and  b2 . }
5. e3{ Played in the typical solid fashion of many Queen's pawn opening, but White is already under a little bit of pressure after the next move. }( 5.c3 cxd4 6.cxd4 Nc6∓ { is some kind of dream Slav Exchange for Black where our knight reached }e4 { with tempo. }{ To be honest, I am surprised how much better the position is already for Black, but besides the general consideration, Black also has strong dynamic possibilities with ... Qb6  or ... Qa5 +, followed by the ... e5  and ... Bb4  ideas. } )
5. Qb6{ Attacking  b2  and  d4 , but as we will see, the queen can also maneuver along the 6th rank! }
6. Qc1{ By far the main move, but Black can actually refute this move quite convincingly. }( {  A)  }6.Nc3 { is the best move and we will see similar positions in the lines with  4.Bf4 . Typically, there is no reason to believe that having the bishop on  h4  can be advantageous for White as it has less influence in the center For simplicity's sake I would recommend the same continuation. }6...Qa5!? { Pressuring  c3  when we have typical Grünfeld counterplay against  c3 . With precise play, White is not much worse according to the engine, but I would definitely enjoy Black here. } )( {  B)  Taking care of the  b2 -pawn with }6.b3?! { is typically a very weakening move. We can just develop with }6...Nc6 { when White is objectively already in quite a bit of problems.     B1)  }7.Be2 { looks solid, but }7...cxd4 8.exd4 h6!?-+ { i }{ s objectively already just lost for White. We might have ideas along the  a5 - e1  diagonal, but also ... g5 , followed by either ... h5  going for the bishop as well as ... g4 , just winning the  d4 -pawn are extremely convincing ideas. }{     B2)    }7.c3 { runs into }7...cxd4! { . Taking with anything but the c-pawn will leave White with a pawn weakness on that square, but }8.cxd4?! e5!-+ { , followed by  ...Bb4+  is a typical motif that we have seen quite a bit already in the Slav sidelines chapters. Black gets a crushing attack. } )
6. cxd4{ Weakening the d-pawn and also opening the  h6 - c1  diagonal. }
7. exd4
7. g5{ A shot out of the blue. }
8. Bxg5{ Relatively the best move. }( {  A)  }8.Nxg5 Qh6! { is just winning material.  9...f6  is a threat and }9.Qf4 f6 10.Nh3 Bxh3 11.Qxh6 Bxh6 12.gxh3 Bc1!-+ { is also winning material. } )( {  B)  After }8.Bg3 { , we don't even have to win the d-pawn immediately with }8...g4 { , but slightly better is even }8...Bh6!-+ { , making the threat even stronger. White is in too much trouble. } )
8. Nxg5
9. Nxg5
9. Bh6{ Threatening ... f6 , so forcing White's response. }
10. f4
10. Qxd4{ Black has the bishop pair in an open position and White has a lot of holes in their position. }
