3. Bg5{ Another move order reminiscent of a Trompowsky, but quite unpopular. By inserting ... d7 - d5  and  Ng1 - f3 , White has actually lost many active possibilities. }( { For example, Black can play }3...e6 { without White being able to immediately occupy the center with  e2-e4 .    }3...c5 { is also a good typical move against the Trompowsky.    But I've always found that }3...Ne4 { shows the best the disadvantage of the white move order! } )
3. Ne4{ Activating the knight and attacking the bishop on  g5 . In a normal Trompovsky, White has no knight on  f3  which makes it easier to challenge it and often even play ambitiously with  f2 - f3 . Here, only Black should be happy about the knight on  e4 . }
4. Bf4{ The most popular move. Now we have a London Systen with our knight more active on  e4  than on  f6 . }
4. c5{ Once again the best move to immediately undermine the center. }
5. e3{ The main move. }( {  A)  }5.dxc5 { doesn't make as much sense here as with the bishop on  h4 . We can continue in the same style with }5...Nc6 { and sooner or later, the  f4 -bishop can be kicked with  ...e7-e5 . } )( {  B)  After }5.c3 { , I would once again simply go for a dream Slav Exchange with }5...cxd4 6.cxd4 Nc6 { The bishop on  f4  might be better than on  h4  when it comes to defending the queenside, but still, the engine is claiming that the only move that objectively limits Black's advantage to a minimum is }7.Nc3 { when even the simple }7...Nxc3 8.bxc3 g6 { transposes to not the most critical Schlexchange, but we can also play differently.    }7...Qa5 { looks like a move also very consistent with our typical plans. } )
