1. c4
1. c6
2. e4( { When you have reached this chapter, it means that you have completed the }1.d4 d5 { universe. Congratulations! } )( { As I promised in the introduction, you can also aim for the Schlechter Slav against   }1.Nf3 { and }1.c4 { . In most cases, White will sooner or later put his d-pawn on  d4  and transpose to variations we looked at in the previous chapters. Nevertheless, we can't force our opponent to move his d-pawn two squares forward! In many cases, Black will still get positions very similar to the Schlechter Slav.    The biggest exception will be discussed in this and the next chapter: Even though we as Slav players should do our best to get a pawn to  d5  as quickly as possible - and I therefore recommend }1...c6 { against  1.c4  - White has the opportunity here for one move to put his e-pawn in the center undisturbed with }2.e4 { .    This leads to a position mostly achieved via the Caro-Kann Defense in the  1.e4  cosmos   }1.e4 c6 2.c4 { .    }{ Tendentially, few English players have any interest in crossing over into these waters - especially since even  1.e4  players have mostly lost their interest in this variation by now. Neither engines nor statistics are particularly impressed, and Black players now have several reliable setups that have withstood the test of time }{ (and engines) }{ .     So this is definitely nothing that should stop us to play the Slav against  1.c4 . Nevertheless, this variation has been discussed at a high level for decades, White players have tried various setups to put Black under pressure, and - precisely because this variation is so different from much of what we have seen so far - I felt it was important to cover it in some detail. } )
