[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) 1.c4 c6 2.e4 Introduction & Semi-Panov"]
[Black "Introduction Semi-Panov"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { Let's first talk about the kind of positions we get after   }1.c4 c6 2.e4 { . First of all, I still think }2...d5 { is the most principled move. After all, we put our c-pawn after  c6  for this!    Very typical for the whole variation is that White gets an isolani on the d-file, since their c- and e-pawns are exchanged early. In the next chapter, we will talk about }3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { , after which the IQP is still very likely, but the pawn structure is a bit more flexible.    In this chapter we talk about capturing twice on  d5    }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.exd5 { . Why should White do this when the other option is the more flexible one?    In principle, there are two reasons:    - White hopes to keep the  d5 -pawn on the board.    - White hopes that holding back  d2 - d4  will give them additional options. It is typical for the side with the IQP to try to compensate for the pawn weakness through active, often concrete play. And although the move  d2 - d4  fits into the general development scheme, White is sometimes quite happy to have saved this move in order to be able to put direct pressure on the black position with raiding attacks like  Bc4  &  Qb3  or  Bb5 +,  Qa4 ,  Ne5 .    Important: We do not play }4...Qxd5? { because this would only allow White to gain some tempi in the opening. Instead we play }4...Nf6! { in order to be able to take with the knight on  d5 . If White wants to keep the pawn on  d5 , they should then play }5.Bb5+ { or }5.Qa4+ { to force a black piece to  d7 . Especially after the queen's check, White has countless attempts to cling to the pawn on  d5  even though Black should not have major problems with the pawn in any variation.    Rules for the chapter:    - If White allows us to take with the knight on  d5 , we do so. }{    - If White plays }5.Bb5+ { or }5.Qa4+ { , we react with }5...Nbd7 {    }{ - In most cases, we can continue with ... g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O     - Every move should be aimed at winning back the  d5 -pawn } )
