1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Qa4+{ With this check White forces one of Black's minor pieces to the  d7 -square. The queen on  d8  will no longer attack the  d5 -pawn and this gives White the opportunity to protect the pawn on the next move. }
5. Nbd7{ One of the rules you can follow is that you answer both checks ( 5.Qa4+  and 5.  Bb5+ ) with ... Nbd7 . This knight can later land on  b6  to put additional pressure on the  d5 -pawn.     Our bishop on  c8  can become super useful via  b7 . From there, it is also attacking the  d5 -pawn.  Black's plan is pretty clear. ...  g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and then we start to take care of the  d5 -pawn! }
6. Nc3
6. g6{ Following the plan. }
7. g4{ This is an overaggressive move. White prepares  Bg2  and can play  g4 - g5  but this does mainly weaken their own position. }
7. Bg7( { As  g4-g5  is not really a threat, we can just ignore it. Nevertheless, even }7...h6 { has a great score. } )
8. g5
8. Nh5{ White stabilized the  d5 -pawn for now but at what cost? It is still a weakness and White's king will be vulnerable for the whole middle game. Because White's king is so weak, all kinds of pawn sacrifices to open the position are typical and something to look out for.  ... b5 , ... e6  or even ... e5  (with a White pawn on  d4 ) are such moves. }
9. Nge2{ The typical move. }
9. O-O{ Black just develops as fast as possible. }
10. Ng3{ The main move. White puts pressure on  h5  and taking on  g3  would open the h-file. But as we will see, White taking on  h5  is not as dangerous as Black's plan to open up the center. }( 10.d4 { might be objectively better but White won't get any kingside play going and Black can just develop and open up the center. }10...Nb6 11.Qb3 e6 { is an old line that is considered great compensation for Black. But even }11...e5 { or the relative slow }11...Bf5 { , followed by }-- ...Rc8 { seem good.  White just has no play himself while Black builds up their initiative. } )
10. Nb6{ Not the only move but attacking  a4  and  d5  can barely be wrong. }
11. Qe4{ This was played in the only predecessor game by GM Schmittdiel. }( { Increasing the pressure on  h5  with }11.Qh4 { looks logical. However, Black can just take on  d5 . }11...Nxd5 { Black's initiative in the center is just much more valuable than what White can achieve on the kingside. For example }12.Nxh5 gxh5∓ 13.Qxh5? Nb4!-+ { is already lost for White. } )
11. f5{ A nice move that illustrates that all kinds of aggressive ideas are currently possible against White's setup with weak king and full of holes. Let's stop the trainable here but show some ideas. }( 11...e6 { was played in  Schmittdiel - Maki Uuro, Gausdal 1994 . Also a typical idea. } )( { After }11...f5 { , }12.gxf6 Nxf6 { just loses the  d5 -pawn with all problems for White remaining and after   }12.Qf3 f4! 13.Nxh5 gxh5 14.Qxh5 { , Black can break through in the center. }14...Bxc3 { , followed by }-- ...Qxd5 { and invasion on the light squares look really promising. } )
