7. g3{ A pretty rare move. The bishop goes to  g2  to protect the  d5 -pawn. It has been played by some GMs.  We just follow the plan .... Bg7 , ... O-O , then winning the  d5 -pawn! }( 7.Be2 { , followed by  Be2 - f3  is a similar idea. The bishop on  f3  is in comparison more vulnerable, so this version of the idea is even less popular.  ... Ne5  might attack the bishop but even ... Bg4  might be an idea to simply exchange it. I would recommend just playing as against the fianchetto. }7...Bg7 8.Bf3 O-O 9.d4 ( { ( }9.Nge2 Ne5! { would be horrible. ) } )9...Nb6 10.Qb3 10...Bf5 { , followed by ... Bd3  and ... Bc4 . }10...Bg4 { is also possible to exchange the defender from  d5  against a piece that usually needs some tempi to participate in the fight about the  d5 -pawn. } )
