5. Nbd7{ One of the rules you can follow is that you answer both checks ( 5.Qa4+  and 5.  Bb5+ ) with ... Nbd7 . This knight can later land on  b6  to put additional pressure on the  d5 -pawn.     Our bishop on  c8  can become super useful via  b7 . From there, it is also attacking the  d5 -pawn.  Black's plan is pretty clear. ...  g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and then we start to take care of the  d5 -pawn! }
6. Nc3
6. g6{ Following the plan. }
7. Bc4( { This move does usually transpose to }7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Bc4 { -  see here . Other moves can bring White in trouble. } )
7. Bg7
8. d3( { I am not a big fan of this move. This move order only gives more options to Black. From a repertoire perspective, I will go with }8...O-O { which still gives White the possibility to transpose.    Black could also try to punish White with playing }8...a6 { . The point is to go for a quick  ...b5  after something like }9.Nf3 Rb8!? { . } )
8. O-O{ The normal move. Black just finishes development. }
9. Nge2( { It was not too late to transpose with }9.Nf3 { to  these lines . Putting the knight on  e2  is just more passive. } )
9. a6( { Black is threatening   }10...b5 11.Bxb5 Nb6! { what attacks  a4 , protects  a8  and so }-- ...axb5 { will come next. } )
10. Qa3{ More or less exclusively played to address this threat. At some point, White has to move away with this queen anyways because ... b5  will always be looming in the air.  a3  is the best square as White keeps an eye on the  e7 -pawn but also supports  d5 - d6 . }( 10.Be3 { stops it for one move because White could answer }10...b5 { with }11.Bxb5 Nb6 12.Bxb6! { . }10...Ng4 { however is an annoying response. } )
10. b6{ Easy enough. Black just puts the bishop on  b7 . This attacks  d5  one more time but also protects the  a8 -rook so that ... b5  can be played without any  Bxb5  tactics. }
11. O-O
11. Bb7{ Ready for ...  b5  and ... Nb6 . when the  d5 -pawn will fall. }
12. Bg5{ This was played by the strongest player who reached this position. White is ready to take on  f6  to exchange one attacker from  d5 . }( {  A)  After a move like }12.Nf4 { , Black wins back the pawn with }12...b5 13.Bb3 Nb6 { . } )( {  B)  }12.d6 { is a try to keep the pawn but after }12...e6 { , the pawn will not survive for long. It can hardly be protected so Black shouldn't even be in a hurry to pick it up and can just develop naturally: }{ .... Nc5 , ... Rc8 , ... b5 . Once Black picks up the d-pawn, we will just be better. } )
12. b5{ The natural continuation. }
13. Bb3
13. Rc8{ Black prepares ... Nc5  which is also a valid way to win the pawn back- either by taking on  d3  or exchanging on  b3  and then taking  d5 . }( { If White plays }14.d6 { , we can still simply answer with }14...e6 { , but even }14...exd6 15.Qxd6 Nc5! { promises very good compensation. The pawn on  d3  is really weak. } )
