[White "29) 1.c4 c6 2.e4 Introduction & Semi-Panov"]
[Black "5.Qa4+ & 7.Nf3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Qa4+{ With this check White forces one of Black's minor pieces to the  d7 -square. The queen on  d8  will no longer attack the  d5 -pawn and this gives White the opportunity to protect the pawn on the next move. }
5. Nbd7{ One of the rules you can follow is that you answer both checks ( 5.Qa4+  and 5.  Bb5+ ) with ... Nbd7 . This knight can later land on  b6  to put additional pressure on the  d5 -pawn.     Our bishop on  c8  can become super useful via  b7 . From there, it is also attacking the  d5 -pawn.  Black's plan is pretty clear. ...  g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and then we start to take care of the  d5 -pawn! }
6. Nc3
6. g6{ Following the plan. }
7. Nf3{ This is the main line. White just develops with the most logical move. }
7. Bg7{ Just developing. }
8. Bc4( { The normal continuation. }8.Qb3 O-O 9.Bc4 { is the same as  8.Bc4  and  9.Qb3 . } )
8. O-O{ Now, we are ready to go ... Nb6 . This is pretty much a threat. }( 9.O-O? Nb6 10.Qb3 Nxc4 11.Qxc4 b6! { would be horrible for White.    }{ Black will win back the  d5 -pawn after ... Bb7  and will also have the bishop pair in an open position. } )
9. Qb3( { Much rarer than }9.d3 { . }{ White stays flexible with their d-pawn but the queen is not well placed on  b3 . ... Nc5  could come with tempo but the main problem is that Black can open the b-file. } )
9. b5{ A strong pawn sacrifice. White's queen is feeling really uncomfortable on  b3  when the b-file opens up. }
10. Bxb5{ This seems to be slightly better than  10.Nxb5  because the bishop makes slightly more sense on this square than the knight. Nevertheless, both moves run into extremely similar problems. }( {  A)  }10.Nxb5 { gives Black two good moves. We can just continue the same as after  10.Bxb5  with }10...Rb8 { to threaten }-- ...a6 { and continue with }...Nb6 { / ...Nxd5  afterwards but we can also play the immediate }10...Nb6 { . White cannot keep the  d5 -pawn because }11.Nc3? Nxc4 12.Qxc4 { would only give Black the additional plus of the bishop pair. }12...Bb7 { picks up  d5  sufficiently but }12...a5 { with the intention of }-- ...Ba6 { might be even stronger. } )( {  B)  The passive }10.Be2 { just gives Black their dream setup. }10...a6 { , followed by }-- ...Nb6 { is enough to pick up  d5 . } )
10. Rb8{ Pinning the bishop on  b5 . ... a6  is a threat. Here, this is clearly the best move. }( 10...Nb6 { is not so strong here because it doesn't attack the bishop on  c4  and the  d5 -pawn is protected with  Bb5 - c6  tactics. } )
11. Qd1( { White doesn't really has anything better. }11.Qa4 { or }11.Qc4 { allow }11...Nb6 { with tempo. } )
11. Nxd5( { Black has great compensation for the pawn.   }12...Nxc3 { , followed by }-- ...Rxb5 { is a threat. } )( 12.Nxd5 Rxb5 { gives Black the two bishops in an open position and especially Black's unopposed light-squared bishop will be dominating on  b7  or  a6 . Along the b, c and d-file, Black will be able to create a lot of pressure. } )
