6. Nc3
6. g6{ Following the plan. }
7. Nf3{ This is the main line. White just develops with the most logical move. }
7. Bg7{ Just developing. }
8. Bc4( { The normal continuation. }8.Qb3 O-O 9.Bc4 { is the same as  8.Bc4  and  9.Qb3 . } )
8. O-O{ Now, we are ready to go ... Nb6 . This is pretty much a threat. }( 9.O-O? Nb6 10.Qb3 Nxc4 11.Qxc4 b6! { would be horrible for White.    }{ Black will win back the  d5 -pawn after ... Bb7  and will also have the bishop pair in an open position. } )
9. d3{ This is the main move. White protects the  c4 -bishop with a pawn, which makes it much less attractive to take it. }
9. a6( { The threat is   }10...b5 11.Bxb5 Nb6 { which will win a piece. } )
10. Qa3{ The typical reply. ... b5  is addressed and White puts the queen on the square that attacks  e7  and supports  d5 - d6 . }( 10.Be3 { does address the }10...b5 { idea as well - which doesn't work here because of }11.Bxb5 Nb6 12.Bxb6 { . However, }10...Ng4 { is a good move to renew the threat by taking on  e3 . As ... b5  is always in the air, White should move the queen from  a4  rather sooner than later. } )
10. b6{ Black is planning ... Bb7  and then usually ... b5  and ... Nb6 . }
11. O-O
11. Bb7
12. Be3( { Usually, White includes }12.Re1 Re8 { before playing this move -  see here .    }{ In general, the inclusion of these two moves makes sense for White because  Re1  is an active move while ... Re8  is only defensive! The only justification for this move order is the possibility to grab the  e7 -pawn against Black's typical plan ... b5  and ... Nb6 . } )
12. b5{ The fact that White can take the  e7 -pawn in the following sequence is no reason to refrain from our main idea. Black will get great compensation. }
13. Bb3
13. Nb6{ The typical follow-up even though White can take on  b6  and then on  e7 . }
14. Bxb6{ This is White's only justification. }
14. Qxb6
15. Qxe7{ White is now two pawns up but after the next move it will be clear that the  d5 -pawn will be lost. As Black has two great bishops in a position with a completely open center and  d3  is even a very concrete target, this gives Black great compensation. }
15. a5( { Threatening   }16...a4 { which will drive away the bishop from  b3 . This move does also take away the  b4 -square for the queen, so }16...Rae8 { is also a huge threat ( }17.Qa3 b4 { ). } )( 15...b4 { to undermine the  d5 -pawn does not work because }16.Na4 { comes with tempo. } )
16. Qe3{ The best move. White goes for an endgame even though Black has awesome compensation. }( 16.a4?? Rae8 { loses material. }17.Qa3 b4-+  )
16. Qxe3{ Black can easily exchange queens here. }
17. fxe3
17. a4{ Goal achieved.  d5  will fall and White's pawn remain under pressure.      b2 ,  d3 ,  e3  are all weak. }( { Also, the sad move }18.Bd1 { is now a necessity. } )
18. Bc2( { This is a mistake and let's see why.    }18.Bd1 { is the right move but Black can either just play }18...Nxd5 { to regain the pawn immediately but also moves like }18...a3!? { to open up the  a1 - h8  diagonal first gives Black a great game. } )
18. Rfc8( { This is the strongest move to punish White.   }19....b4 { is a huge threat.      }19...a3 { is now also annoying to undermine the protection of the  c3 -knight and even }19...Nxd5 { gets stronger because }20.Nxd5 Rxc2 { allows Black's rook to the second rank. White has no sufficient answer. } )
