5. Nbd7{ One of the rules you can follow is that you answer both checks ( 5.Qa4+  and 5.  Bb5+ ) with ... Nbd7 . This knight can later land on  b6  to put additional pressure on the  d5 -pawn.     Our bishop on  c8  can become super useful via  b7 . From there, it is also attacking the  d5 -pawn.  Black's plan is pretty clear. ...  g6 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and then we start to take care of the  d5 -pawn! }
6. Nc3
6. g6{ Following the plan. }
7. Nf3{ This is the main line. White just develops with the most logical move. }
7. Bg7{ Just developing. }
8. Bc4( { The normal continuation. }8.Qb3 O-O 9.Bc4 { is the same as  8.Bc4  and  9.Qb3 . } )
8. O-O{ Now, we are ready to go ... Nb6 . This is pretty much a threat. }( 9.O-O? Nb6 10.Qb3 Nxc4 11.Qxc4 b6! { would be horrible for White.    }{ Black will win back the  d5 -pawn after ... Bb7  and will also have the bishop pair in an open position. } )
9. d3{ This is the main move. White protects the  c4 -bishop with a pawn, which makes it much less attractive to take it. }
9. a6( { The threat is   }10...b5 11.Bxb5 Nb6 { which will win a piece. } )
10. Qa3{ The typical reply. ... b5  is addressed and White puts the queen on the square that attacks  e7  and supports  d5 - d6 . }( 10.Be3 { does address the }10...b5 { idea as well - which doesn't work here because of }11.Bxb5 Nb6 12.Bxb6 { . However, }10...Ng4 { is a good move to renew the threat by taking on  e3 . As ... b5  is always in the air, White should move the queen from  a4  rather sooner than later. } )
10. b6{ Black is planning ... Bb7  and then usually ... b5  and ... Nb6 . }
11. O-O
11. Bb7
12. Re1{ White is attacking  e7 . }
12. Re8{ Protecting  e7 . }( { Starting with }12...b5 13.Bb3 Re8 { is also possible. However, in some lines it is useful to have White's bishop on  c4  as it can be vulnerable to moves like ... Rc8  or even ... Ne5 . } )
13. Bf4{ White anticipates Black's plan to go ... b5  and ... Nb6  and is preparing the move  d5 - d6  in response. }( { The immediate }13.d6 { is usually answered with }13...e6 { and the pawn on  d6  is even less stable than it was on  d5 . Also ... Bxf3  becomes a serious option. } )
13. Rc8{ Black does not only have the  b6 -square for the  d7 -knight to fight for the  d5 -pawn, it is a motif worth remembering that the knight can also help regain the pawn from  c5 .     In combination with ... b5 , the knight can be used to either collect the  d3 -pawn or just exchange one of the  d5 -defenders - White's light-squared bishop which will then be on  b3 . ... Rc8  makes sure that the knight on  c5  is protected. }( { To be fair, }13...b5 { is not that bad. After }14.Bb3 { , Black can either play }14...Bf8 { to stop White's  d5-d6  move but even 'running into White's idea' with }14...Nb6 15.d6 { is not so clear because }15...Bxf3 { spoils White's kingside structure quite heavily. } )
14. d6{ Still trying to exchange the pawn. }( { A developing move like }14.Rad1 { allows Black main idea. }14...b5! 15.Bb3 Nc5!⩱ { Black will win back the  d5 -pawn and remain with the better pawn structure. } )( 14.Nd4? { was played in two games. But besides the fact that it doesn't stop Black's idea }14...b5 15.Bb3 Nc5 { , Black can even already win material with }15...Qb6 { which threatens }-- ...b4 { and }...Qxd4 { .   }16.Qb4 a5 { didn't help in  Sek - Riazantsev, Moscow 2019 . } )
14. e6{ The typical response. Black is ready to isolate the d-pawn with ... Nc5  from the White queen.  ... Bxf3  and ... b5  are also typical ideas. Soon, Black will win back the  d6 -pawn and is better with the advantageous pawn structure. }
