1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Bb5+{ This move has the same idea as  Qa4 +. White wants to force a minor piece to  d7  and protect  d5  afterwards. But the bishop on  b5  makes it easier to play ... a6  and ... b5  and this approach usually solves all our problems. }
5. Nbd7{ The same move as against  Qa4 +. The knight might later come to  b6  in order to attack  d5 , while the  c8 -bishop would love to go to  b7 . }
6. Nc3
6. a6{ The easiest move. Black just goes for a really quick ... b5 . }
7. Be2( { This move looks pretty innocuous because Black can easily win back the  d5 -pawn. Nevertheless, White's score against the logical }7...Nb6 { is pretty good.  But we have an even better way to regain the  d5 -pawn. } )
7. b5{ This seems even stronger than going for  d5  immediately. Black wins space, prepares  Bb7  and has the idea to play ... b5 - b4  before taking on  d5 . This will misplace White's knight. }( 7...Nb6 { wins back  d5  and is also okay. However, White scores around about 60% so the practice has proven that White has some practical pressure. } )
8. Qb3{ Moves to protect the  d5 -pawn have been played but they are not really effective. Worst case, Black needs one more move before taking on  d5 . }( 8.Bf3 { was also tested a few times to protect the  d5 -pawn, gain the  e5 -square for the knight and threaten some things along the diagonal with  d5 - d6 . }8...Bb7 { is however just an easy response when Black is once again ready for }-- ...b4 { and ... Nxd5 . } )
8. Nc5{ This tempo is too juicy to ignore. White indeed has no better square than  d1 . }
9. Qd1{ This is already some kind of draw offer but Black obviously has other options as well. }( 9.Qa3 e5! { is already slightly annoying for White because }-- ...Nd3+ { is a threat. } )
9. Nxd5{ It looks slightly risky to take the pawn with the  f3 - a8  diagonal open but White has no way to exploit it. }
10. Nxd5{ Forcing the queen to  d5 . Other moves just allow Black easy development with .. .Bb7, ... e6  and so on. }
10. Qxd5{ Black is just completely fine as White has no real tricks along the  f3 - h8  diagonal. }
11. Bf3( { This is a mistake but the only move that really forces Black to find a trick. }11...Ne4? 12.d3 { would now be working for White. } )( 11.d4 { is objectively better but Black's move are easier to find. We just have to put the knight on  e4  and stabilize it as fast as possible. }11...Ne4! { Necessary not to lose material after  Bf3 . }12.Bf3 Bb7 { and Black is ready to unpin the  d5 -knight on the next move. ... Qd7  would be ideal but even other squares come into consideration as all problems along the  f3 - a8  diagonal can in the worst case also be solved with ... Nd6  that protects the  b7 -bishop. } )
11. Nd3+{ The easiest move. White's king is getting into trouble. }( { It is also possible to start with }11...Qd4! { because }12.Bxa8? Nd3+ 13.Ke2 Bf5!-+ { seems to be winning. To me, this looks unnecessarily messy. } )
12. Kf1( 12.Ke2? { is just running into even more trouble. Black has too many ways to save the material here along the long diagonal.     A)  }12...Qc4! { looks easy with the threat of }-- 13...Nxb2+ 14.d3 Qe6 { .     B)  }12...Qe5+ { is also nice because }13.Kxd3? Bf5+ { is leading to mate.     C)  The strongest, however maybe unnecessarily complicated is }12...Qd4 { transposing to the comment from the last move after }13.Bxa8 Bf5! { . } )
12. Qd4{ Avoiding the problems along the diagonal by threatening mate on  f2 . }
13. Qe2( { The only move that stops it without losing material. }13.Nh3 Bxh3 { doesn't help. } )
13. Ra7{ White has no tricks, a bad king and the more restricted pieces. Black is much better. }
