9. e5{ A strong move, played by GM Stukopin. With the king on  f1 , White cannot really open up the center and take en passant on  e6 . And if White doesn't take, well, then ... e5  is just the most aggressive developing move, allowing the  f8 -bishop to come out and play ... e4  potentially. }
10. Nf3{ This is White's best reply, staying active, attacking  e5 . while also preparing  d2 - d4 . }( {  A)  }10.dxe6 Bxe6 { just develops Black's pieces.     A1)  }11.Qxb7?? Bd5! { with a double attack against  g2  and  b7  is a nice tactic. }12.Nxd5 Qd1# { would be mate.     A2)  }11.h3 { is better but Black would even have massive compensation in an endgame after, for example, }11...Qc4+ 12.Qxc4 Bxc4+ 13.Nge2 Bd3! { when White is totally restricted and Black's bishops are just controlling the open board. } )( {  B)  }10.Nge2 { doesn't create a threat so Black can just stop all of White's  d4 -ideas with }10...Bc5! { . White will have a hard time untangling. } )
10. Bc5{ A principled response, not caring too much about the  e5 -pawn. Black just develops their pieces to good squares.  Let's stop the trainable here because we are already on completely new terrain and there is no real forcing continuation for White. }( 10...Bd6 { was played in  Ynojosa Aponte - Stukopin, Dallas 2016 . Black clearly has good compensation here as well. Even the immediate }10...e4!? { is possible.    If White decides to take on  e5  after }10...Bc5 { , Black will also have great compensation in a possible endgame. }11.Nxe5 Qd4! { The double attack against  e5  and  f2  might look winning at first glance but White can keep the game going. }12.Qa4+! { Exchanging queens. }12...Qxa4 13.Nxa4 Ba7 { Even in this endgame, Black has great compensation.  d5  will fall soon and Black's unopposed light-squared bishop will dominate the board. } )
