[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Bb5+{ This move has the same idea as  Qa4 +. White wants to force a minor piece to  d7  and protect  d5  afterwards. But the bishop on  b5  makes it easier to play ... a6  and ... b5  and this approach usually solves all our problems. }
5. Nbd7{ The same move as against  Qa4 +. The knight might later come to  b6  in order to attack  d5 , while the  c8 -bishop would love to go to  b7 . }
6. Nc3
6. a6{ The easiest move. Black just goes for a really quick ... b5 . }
7. Bxd7+( { This capture is much more popular with }7.Qa4 Rb8 { included. Here, Black either wins their pawn back immediately or gets the chance to really destroy White's coordination if they try to be greedy. } )
7. Qxd7{ It is typical to recapture with the queen as we are attacking  d5  immediately. }
8. Nf3{ Simply developing is objectively best but White has to be really precise to keep the balance while Black has easy moves. }
8. Nxd5{ If White gives us the pawn, we take it! }
9. O-O{ This is the most flexible developing move. }( 9.d4 { gives Black different good options. }9...e6 { would most likely just transpose but there is also the unpleasant check }9...Qe6+ { . White has to misplace one of their pieces as }10.Qe2? { would lead to a horrible endgame as Black has the bishop pair and the better structure. } )
9. e6{ Black doesn't have to find any fancy moves. We can just develop.  White is the one who has to come up with something concrete. If White allows Black to just develop and castle, Black is much better with the two bishops and the advantageous structure. }
10. Ne5{ The main move and in the spirit of the position. White tries to go for something concrete.  White hopes to drive Black's queen to an unfortunate square. }( 10.d4 { is also a natural move but it doesn't change the fact that White should soon find a concrete way to annoy Black before they are able to castle to the kingside. Black can play similar to our mainline }10...Nxc3 11.bxc3 Bd6 { to address  Nf3 - e5  and just plan to continue with ... O-O , ... b5 , ... Bb7 . But there is also the option to play }10...f6!? { This slightly weakens the kingside structure but we stop all  Ne5  ideas and will be ready to develop with ... Be7  and ... O-O . } )
10. Nxc3{ A nice in-between move. }( {  A)  }10...Qc7?! { allows White to open up the e-file which promises White enough activity.    }11.Nxd5 exd5 12.Re1 { with some pressure.      }11...Qxe5 12.Nb6 { is also not ideal. } )( {  B)  Keeping the  d5 -knight protected with }10...Qd8?! { allows White to create some weaknesses with }11.Qh5 { or }11.Qf3 { . } )
11. bxc3{ The typical recapture. }( 11.Nxd7 { is not completely unplayable but White has to know what they are doing just to get an equal endgame. }11...Nxd1 12.Nb6! { This move saves White. }12...Rb8 13.d4! { Threatening  Bf4  and also stopping 13... Bc5  so Black cannot save the  d1 -knight. }13...Bd6 14.Rxd1 Bc7 15.Nxc8 Rxc8= { White can get an approximately equal endgame with }16.d5 { , exchanging the weakness.    Arguably even there, Black is just slightly more active. } )
11. Qc7{ Now, we can go to the  c7 -square. If we can get in ... Bd6  and ... O-O , we achieve all our goals. }
12. d4
12. Bd6
13. Ba3{ An important move for White to exchange one of the bishops. }
13. Bxa3
14. Qa4+{ This little trick was what White was playing for. }
14. b5{ A nice move. Blocking the check while also preparing ... Bb7 . }
15. Qxa3
15. Bb7{ Black has a great light-squared bishop and potential pressure against  c3 . ... Qe7  looks like a logical follow-up to bring the king into safety that is currently unable to castle but if you are really adventurous, you can even consider ... f6  and ... Kf7  to bring your  h8 -rook into the game. }
