2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Bb5+{ This move has the same idea as  Qa4 +. White wants to force a minor piece to  d7  and protect  d5  afterwards. But the bishop on  b5  makes it easier to play ... a6  and ... b5  and this approach usually solves all our problems. }
5. Nbd7{ The same move as against  Qa4 +. The knight might later come to  b6  in order to attack  d5 , while the  c8 -bishop would love to go to  b7 . }
6. Nc3
6. a6{ The easiest move. Black just goes for a really quick ... b5 . }
7. Qa4{ This is White's main move. For now, White prevents ... axb5  by pinning the  a6 -pawn.  However, White understands that this is only a short-term strategy. Usually, White combines this move with  Bxd7 + later on.  If White takes right away, Black has no problems. }
7. Rb8{ This forcing move gives Black good results. }
8. Bxd7+( { White claims that - compared to   }7.Bxd7 Qxd7 { - it is slightly harder for Black to regain the  d5 -pawn. As we will see, this is no big deal.  And if the queens come off, that reduces White's dynamic possibilities to compensate for the isolated d-pawn. } )( 8.Be2 { doesn't make much sense. Even without the inclusion of   }7.Qa4 Rb8 { , this retreat is not dangerous.   }{ Here, Black can even play ... b5  with tempo, followed by the same motifs: ... b4  to misplace the knight, attacking and winning the  d5 -pawn, finishing development with either ... g6 , ... Bg7  or ... e6 , ... Be7 . } )
8. Qxd7{ A very easy reply. White is currently a pawn up and thinks that exchanges are good for them.  However, the extra pawn will soon be gone and Black remains with the better structure. }( 8...Bxd7 { is also possible, but to take with the queen is the easy move that leads to a pleasant endgame. } )
9. Qf4{ There have been some tries for White to make this line work without exchanging queens. Not very successful though! White can annoy Black for some moves but at some point,  d5  simply falls and gives Black an easy position.  Here, White is attacking  b8 , hoping that the win of a tempo gives White time to protect  d5 . }( 9.Qb3 { is similar to  7.Bxd7   Qxd7   8.Qb3 . }{ However, the main difference is Black's rook on  b8  instead of on  a8 . This can hardly be bad for Black! We can just answer with the same reply }9...Qg4 { to create some light-squared weaknesses. } )
9. Ra8{ We have to save the rook. }
10. Qd4( { White hangs on to this pawn as long as possible. }10.Nf3 Nxd5 { doesn't pose any problems. } )
10. g6{ Black's play is very straightforward. ... Bg7 , ... O-O , ... Rd8 . There is not much White can do about it. }
11. Nf3
11. Bg7
12. O-O
12. O-O{ , followed by ... Rd8 , winning the  d5 -pawn when Black is just slightly better. }
