1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Nc3{ If White wants to develop naturally instead of going for the defence of the  d5 -pawn, this is the most flexible move. }( { Other moves like }5.Nf3 Nxd5 { should just transpose. } )
5. Nxd5{ Some players like to delay the capture on  d5  to not allow any tempo moves against the  d5 -knight before Black is fully developed. Against the main line Panov - where White has spent a tempo on  d2 - d4  - this works pretty well, but here, White could use this tempo for more concrete ideas to hold on to the  d5 -pawn. }( 5...g6 6.Bc4 Bg7 7.Nf3 O-O 8.Qb3 { is the kind of position to illustrate the point. I am not even 100 % sure if this is the most critical move order, but Black has some problems winning the  d5 -pawn and I am not convinced that Black can really solve all opening problems here. } )
6. Nf3( { The main move, as it is the most flexible one. White cannot really play without it. }6.d4 { transposes to the Panov main line-  see here . } )
6. Nc6{ I chose this for our repertoire because it is the most flexible developing move. }( { I considered }6...g6!? { , as it is also a move that could lead to a position with similarities to other variations from our repertoire. However, I decided against it, because White's main attempts against it can become extremely concrete. }7.Qb3 Nb6 8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Ne5!? { is the main response, but there are also alternatives along the way. I think, in this chapter, we have already seen enough very concrete stuff! } )( { After }6...Nc6 { , there are two independent tries.     1)  The main move is }7.Bb5 { .     2)  A rarer guest is }7.Bc4 { .    The move }7.d4 { would transpose to our main line  Panov chapter . } )
7. Bc4( { With this move, White is inviting Black to play a normal IQP position with }7...e6 { . }{ As we usually only enter IQPs with a bishop on  g7  in this repertoire, I decided to for the other main move in this position. } )
7. Nb6( { The alternative is }7...e6 { which leads to IQP positions with the bishop on  e7  after, for example, }8.O-O Be7 9.d4 O-O { . Black is certainly okay but it doesn't really fit into this repertoire. } )( { Now, after }7...Nb6 { , White usually plays }8.Bb3 { with control over  d5 , looking at  f7 . } )
8. Bb5( { This position now resembles pretty much the positions after   }7.Bb5 { (and I even recommend the same move against both variations: }...g6 { -  see here . The difference is that Black's knight is on  b6  instead of on  d5 .    Cui bono? With the knight on  b6 , White doesn't have the option anymore to go for the  Qa4 -lines to create pressure against  c6 . And even if White plays normal developing moves like  d2 - d4 ,  O-O , etc, it might be Black who is happy that the knight is not on  d5  - the pressure against the  d4 -pawn is just stronger than usual.  So, in what scenario can make use of the knight on  b6 ? Well, the only idea seems to be to take on  c6  - usually not a problem for Black - and claim that in the resulting position the ideal  d5 -outpost is not yet occupied.     Nevertheless, it is quite a stretch to believe that this idea can really give White anything. } )
8. g6{ The same move as against  7.Bb5 . }
9. Ne5{ A concrete move but it doesn't achieve much and White might miss their knight on  f3  as White has less control about  d4 . }
9. Bd7{ After this move, it seems Black is just slightly better. Black unpinning the knight gives White no better option than to take on  c6 . }( 9...Qd6 { is another typical move as we will see in more of the  7.Bb5 -lines and it is also possible here. But concretely, }9...Bd7 { is just extremely attractive as you will see. } )
10. Bxc6{ The attack against  e5  pretty much forces White to take. }( {  A)  }10.Nxc6 Bxc6 { should lead to the same position as White has nothing better than to take on  c6 . Taking the bishop pair makes it hard for White to finish development. } )( {  B)  }10.Nxd7 Qxd7 { Black just gets too much control over the  d4 -square with ... Bg7  and ... Rd8  coming. } )
10. Bxc6
11. Nxc6
11. bxc6{ And here we can see White's problems: They cannot occupy the center. Black will just continue with ... Bg7  and win control over  d4 . }( { If White pushes }12.d4 { , White will have problems with the pawn as }12...Bg7 { already forces }13.Be3 { which gives Black different good options. ... Nc4  can be very annoying but also just increasing the pressure along the d-file can be hard to meet. } )
