9. Bc2{ Keeping the bishops is what many players would do instinctively but here, this is certainly not critical. }
9. g6( { Here, I would just switch back to our fianchetto setup. We will have an improved version of the   }8...g6 { line because White has less options. }{ The  a2 - a4  move is no longer available but usually, there is also the plan to play a quick  d2 - d4 - d5  and answer ... Na5  with surrendering the bishops in exchange for the initiative }{ ( }9.d4 Bg7 10.d5 Na5 11.O-O { ). This is also not an option here. } )
10. d4( { Let's use this as the main move for the trainable. White can also start with }10.O-O { or }10.h3 { . Black's play remains the same. } )
10. Bg7
11. O-O( { All restricting ideas with }11.d5 { won't work any longer. }11...Bxc3+ 12.bxc3 Qxd5∓ { just picks up a pretty important center pawn. } )
11. O-O
12. h3{ Other moves will give Black the extra option to play ... Bg4  after which the  d4 -pawn might be in even more concrete problems. }
12. Be6{ followed by ... Rc8 , potentially ... Re8  to overprotect  e7  and some jumping on the light squares. ... Nac4  looks logical as well as ... Nd5 . However ... Nc6  to attack  d4  might also ask some questions.     If White goes  Be3 , the  b6 -knight could suddenly come to  c4 . }
