6. Nc6{ I chose this for our repertoire because it is the most flexible developing move. }( { I considered }6...g6!? { , as it is also a move that could lead to a position with similarities to other variations from our repertoire. However, I decided against it, because White's main attempts against it can become extremely concrete. }7.Qb3 Nb6 8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Ne5!? { is the main response, but there are also alternatives along the way. I think, in this chapter, we have already seen enough very concrete stuff! } )( { After }6...Nc6 { , there are two independent tries.     1)  The main move is }7.Bb5 { .     2)  A rarer guest is }7.Bc4 { .    The move }7.d4 { would transpose to our main line  Panov chapter . } )
7. Bb5{ White tries to put some pressure on  c6 . Moves like  Qa4  or  Ne5  are very typical to follow it up. These days, there are different good moves that are considered to be very decent for Black. }
7. g6{ A relatively rare move but still approved by many GMs who played it. Black claims that the bishop on  g7  will be very nicely placed - either it attacks White's d-pawn after  d2 - d4  or it simply controls the long diagonal - and doesn't care about White's idea to put pressure on  c6 . }
8. Qb3{ White has to play concrete to give their opening sense. }( { If White plays slow, for example with }8.d4 Bg7 9.O-O O-O { , Black equalises comfortably.   }{ White is the side with a pawn weakness - the d-pawn -, so they have to compensate for it with concrete play. White always has the option to equalize the number of pawn weaknesses by taking on  c6 , but this gives Black the advantage of the two bishops. } )
8. Be6{ This move has given Black great stats. We simply stabilise  d5  and create the idea for future discoveries. }
9. Bc4{ White keeps up the pressure which is in general the only way to ask some questions for Black. To be honest, we don't have any big problems answering them in this line.  But still, in principle this is the correct approach. }( { For example, the move }9.O-O { is natural and does even work tactically - }9...Ne3 10.Nd4! { is at least okay - but Black can play the simple }9...Nb6 { and just play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  next with very easy equality. } )
9. Ndb4( { A strong reply. Black is invading via the  d3 -square. Currently, we are also having the threat   }10...Bxc4 11.Qxc4 Nc2+ { . } )
10. Bxe6( { The best move. }10.O-O ?! Bxc4 11.Qxc4 Qd3!∓ { creates some future problems for White because Black's control over the  d3 -square is hard to break. } )
10. Nd3+{ A very juicy check. }
11. Ke2{ This allows Black to pick up the  e6 -bishop with check but it is still White's best option. }( 11.Kf1? { avoids }{ the  f4 -check but makes it extremely hard for White to ever develop. 11... fxe6  }{ Black's structure is no beauty but White simply doesn't get their pieces out. Black can just play ... Bg7 , ... Rf8 , ... Rc8  and it is absolutely not clear how White can ever untangle.  White can even win a pawn by taking on  e6  but it doesn't change much about their problems. Modern engines already give Black a -+ advantage. } )
11. Nf4+( { Even here Black can play }11...fxe6 { and go for domination in exchange for a weakened structure even though White has much better chances to develop than with the king on  f1 .    }11...Nf4 { is the easy move. } )
12. Kf1{ The best move for the king. Maybe White can play  g3  and  Kg2  at some point. }
12. Nxe6{ Currently material is even and White has the worse structure and a stupid king. Taking the pawn on  b7  is the only way to justify the previous play. }
13. Qxb7{ Taking the pawn and attacking  c6 . }
13. Rc8{ A nice move, protecting  c6  while also bringing the rook into action. Engines evaluate this position as equal and who am I to judge? But nevertheless, in the correspondence game  Varonen - Huuskonen , played in 2019, White couldn't defend this position despite the use of engines.  From a practical perspective, Black's play is much easier. }
