8. Qa4{ This is White's typical follow-up. Increasing the pressure against  c6  is the most principled move after  7.Bb5 . }( 8.Ne5 { is a less ideal version to put pressure on  c6 . After }8...Qd6 { , the counter-threat against  e5  allows Black to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  very soon, which will resolve all the pressure against  c6 . } )
8. Qd6( { Black can also go for the pawn sacrifice }8...Nb6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { . With the bishop pair in a pretty open position and the lead in development, this gives Black great practical compensation. } )( { However, I think Black just equalises with absolutely no problems after }8...Qd6 { and the number of lines to remember should also be smaller. } )
9. Ne4{ This is White’s most aggressive option. Black has to find the right square for the queen. But after that, we shouldn't have any more problems. }( 9.Qd4 { is also a very concrete approach that was played in some blitz games. White is attacking  d5  and  h8 . However, }9...Qe6! { forces White to give up the right to castle and }-- 10...Nf6 { will save the material afterwards. } )
9. Qe6{ An important move to keep everything protected. The queen looks unnatural on  e6 , blocking the  c8 -bishop and being a potential target against future  Re1  or  Nc5 / Ng5  moves.  But Black is only two moves away from castling and after ...  Bg7  and ... O-O , Black's position overall is very solid. }( {  A)  }9...Qc7?! 10.Qd4! { with a double attack against  d5  and  h8  is annoying. } )( {  B)  }9...Qd7?! 10.Ne5! { is also better for White. } )
10. Nfg5{ This move was once played by Kateryna Lagno. White can hunt Black's queen with some knight jumps but they don't really improve White's position and at some point, they stop. }
10. Qd7{ Without the  Nf3 - e5  move, this is a safe square. }
11. Nc5{ After other moves, Black just plays ... Bg7  and castles soon. }
11. Qc7{ Once again, Black is ready to just continue with ... Bg7  and ... O-O . }
12. Qd4( { This double attack would have been problematic had we played  9...Qc7  on move }9. But without the knight on  e4 , we can just answer with12...Nf6 { . } )( 12.O-O Bg7 { happened in  Lagno - Goryachkina, 2016 . White tried to keep the pressure with }13.Bc4?! { to look towards  f7  and answered }13...Qd8 { with }14.Nxb7!? Bxb7 15.Qb5 { However, there are like half a dozen moves to refute this so it's not really worth a trainable. Even if White wins back the piece, Black will have massive compensation for the pawn with their huge lead in development.     A)  Goryachkina won with }15...O-O { which is okay to be slightly better.     B)  }15...Qb6 16.Qxd5 O-O { might be an even better way to give back the piece and even the sequence     C)  }15...Nb6 16.Bxf7 Kf8 17.Ne6+ Kxf7 18.Nxd8 Rhxd8 { is much better for Back as the minor pieces are extremely well coordinated. } )
12. Nf6{ Saving both the knight and the rook. }
13. Qc4{ The only move to stop ... Bg7  for one more move. By attacking  f7 , White provokes 13... e6  and slightly weakens Black on the dark squares. }
13. e6{ Forced. }
14. Qc3{ The only way to continue with the one-move threats. }
14. Bg7( { We use the chance to develop the bishop while also stopping   }15.Qxf6 { . } )
15. Nce4{ Playing for some tricks against  f6  and  g7 . }
15. e5{ A nice response. }( 15...Nh5 { would have been good enough for a perpetual after something like }16.Qc5 Bf8 17.Qc3 Bg7 { but this is obviously not what we want. } )( { In the position after  15...e5 , it is true that White can keep our king in the center with something like }16.Qc5 { . }{ Nevertheless, the rest of our position can be developed harmoniously - ... Nxe4 , ... Be6 , ... Rd8  - so we have still no reason to complain. } )
