1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. cxd5( { If White wants to take twice on  d5 , this is typically White's move order. After }3.exd5 { , Black has the additional option }3...Nf6!? { .    Taking on  c6  is a pawn sacrifice with a good reputation for Black. With an influential white pawn on  e4 , this is not nearly as good. } )
3. cxd5
4. exd5
4. Nf6( { In this position, White has to decide their level of greediness. They have the option to keep the  d5 -pawn alive by the means of }5.Qa4+ { or }5.Bb5+ { but this will place some pieces on weird squares.    With }5.Nc3 { , White gives back the  d5 -pawn immediately and just plays for a normal Isolated Queen's Pawn(IQP) position. } )
5. Nc3{ If White wants to develop naturally instead of going for the defence of the  d5 -pawn, this is the most flexible move. }( { Other moves like }5.Nf3 Nxd5 { should just transpose. } )
5. Nxd5{ Some players like to delay the capture on  d5  to not allow any tempo moves against the  d5 -knight before Black is fully developed. Against the main line Panov - where White has spent a tempo on  d2 - d4  - this works pretty well, but here, White could use this tempo for more concrete ideas to hold on to the  d5 -pawn. }( 5...g6 6.Bc4 Bg7 7.Nf3 O-O 8.Qb3 { is the kind of position to illustrate the point. I am not even 100 % sure if this is the most critical move order, but Black has some problems winning the  d5 -pawn and I am not convinced that Black can really solve all opening problems here. } )
6. Nf3( { The main move, as it is the most flexible one. White cannot really play without it. }6.d4 { transposes to the Panov main line-  see here . } )
6. Nc6{ I chose this for our repertoire because it is the most flexible developing move. }( { I considered }6...g6!? { , as it is also a move that could lead to a position with similarities to other variations from our repertoire. However, I decided against it, because White's main attempts against it can become extremely concrete. }7.Qb3 Nb6 8.Bb5+ Bd7 9.Ne5!? { is the main response, but there are also alternatives along the way. I think, in this chapter, we have already seen enough very concrete stuff! } )( { After }6...Nc6 { , there are two independent tries.     1)  The main move is }7.Bb5 { .     2)  A rarer guest is }7.Bc4 { .    The move }7.d4 { would transpose to our main line  Panov chapter . } )
7. Bb5{ White tries to put some pressure on  c6 . Moves like  Qa4  or  Ne5  are very typical to follow it up. These days, there are different good moves that are considered to be very decent for Black. }
7. g6{ A relatively rare move but still approved by many GMs who played it. Black claims that the bishop on  g7  will be very nicely placed - either it attacks White's d-pawn after  d2 - d4  or it simply controls the long diagonal - and doesn't care about White's idea to put pressure on  c6 . }
8. Qa4{ This is White's typical follow-up. Increasing the pressure against  c6  is the most principled move after  7.Bb5 . }( 8.Ne5 { is a less ideal version to put pressure on  c6 . After }8...Qd6 { , the counter-threat against  e5  allows Black to play ... Bg7  and ... O-O  very soon, which will resolve all the pressure against  c6 . } )
8. Qd6( { Black can also go for the pawn sacrifice }8...Nb6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { . With the bishop pair in a pretty open position and the lead in development, this gives Black great practical compensation. } )( { However, I think Black just equalises with absolutely no problems after }8...Qd6 { and the number of lines to remember should also be smaller. } )
9. Ne4{ This is White’s most aggressive option. Black has to find the right square for the queen. But after that, we shouldn't have any more problems. }( 9.Qd4 { is also a very concrete approach that was played in some blitz games. White is attacking  d5  and  h8 . However, }9...Qe6! { forces White to give up the right to castle and }-- 10...Nf6 { will save the material afterwards. } )
9. Qe6{ An important move to keep everything protected. The queen looks unnatural on  e6 , blocking the  c8 -bishop and being a potential target against future  Re1  or  Nc5 / Ng5  moves.  But Black is only two moves away from castling and after ...  Bg7  and ... O-O , Black's position overall is very solid. }( {  A)  }9...Qc7?! 10.Qd4! { with a double attack against  d5  and  h8  is annoying. } )( {  B)  }9...Qd7?! 10.Ne5! { is also better for White. } )
10. O-O{ Unpinning the  e4 -knight is what most players do here. }( { Another simple developing move that has been played a few times is }10.d3 { but Black can just play in the same way as after }10.O-O { . } )
10. Bg7{ Black can just develop naturally. White doesn't have any particular threats. }
11. Re1( 11.d4 O-O 12.Re1 { is the same. } )
11. O-O
12. d4
12. Rd8{ The ideal square for the rook. With the rook on the d-file, Black is already having ideas with ... Nb6 , followed by taking on  d4 . Black is completely fine. }( 12...Bd7?! 13.Nc5 { with the attack against  e6 ,  d7  and  b7  can be slightly annoying. } )
