9. O-O
9. Bg7{ Black is ready to castle and this usually solves all our problems - if we ever had any. }
10. Re1{ Not an important theoretical move but let's just use it to explain some pretty important aspects of this kind of position and why Black is never afraid if White goes for the  e7 -pawn with their underdeveloped setup. }
10. O-O{ We can just develop naturally. }( 10...Bd7 { is also possible when White usually switches to the }11.Qh4 { plan. }{ The bishop on  d7  is usually most actively placed on  f5  against this approach. } )
11. Nxd5{ This is winning a pawn for White but as we will see, we don't have to be afraid. }( {  A)  Interestingly enough, }11.d4?! { is already a positional mistake. White can no longer go for the  Qh4 -plan and after the strong }11...Bd7! { , White cannot even spoil Black's pawn structure anymore with }12.Bxc6 { . White will just suffer in the resulting middlegame because of the long-term weakness of the  d4 -pawn. } )( {  B)  }11.Bxc6 bxc6 { leads to a typical situation. Both sides have one pawn weakness - White on the d-file, Black on  c6  - but Black has the bishop pair. This alone should be reason enough, why we don't have any problems. Black can just develop with ... Bf5 , put the rooks on the b- and d-file, and has a nice position.  Also an important idea is ... c5  to trade off the two weaknesses.     In the resulting positions, Black is often better, because the bishops will be extremely happy about the fact that the center is now open. } )
11. Qxd5
12. Bxc6{ The principled follow-up. }
12. bxc6{ It is typical to keep the queens on the board. }( { Nevertheless, Black would also have compensation after }12...Qxc6 13.Qxc6 bxc6 14.Rxe7 { . Something like }14...Be6 { to attack  a2  and possibly go ... Bd5 , followed by ... a5 - a4 , ... Rfb8  looks like great compensation in the endgame. } )
13. Rxe7
13. Bf5{ This is one natural way to play for compensation. Black just develops and cuts through the light squares.  ... Be4  looks like a nice potential follow-up. But let's just mention that Black does also have other ways to prove compensation. }( {  A)  }13...c5 { is a good move to keep White restricted by controlling the  d4 -square. (The control over  b4  might also be useful though.) } )( {  B)  }13...a5 { is a typical move to win space on the queenside. Black might continue with developing the light-squared bishop, followed by ... Rfb8 , ... Rb4  and a lot of pressure on the queenside. } )( {  C)  Even }13...g5!? 14.d3 g4 { is approved by the engine. Black misplaces the  f3 -knight and with the lack of development, White has no convincing way to punish Black for this kingside weakness.  So let's just summarize that there are usually all kinds of ways to justify sacrificing the  e7 -pawn - even if is not this exact position. } )
