9. O-O
9. Bg7{ Black is ready to castle and this usually solves all our problems - if we ever had any. }
10. Qh4( { This is the most frequently played move in this position besides }10.Ne4 { . }{ White is hoping for some kingside pressure against  e7  and  h7 . A coffeehouse chess approach would be to follow it up with }{   }11.d4 { , }-- 12.Bh6 { , }-- 13.Ng5 { and eventually mate on  h7 .     The simple problem is that this should never really work! Black can just finish development, centralize the pieces and create some counterplay in the middle of the board. } )( 10.Ne4 Qe6 { transposes to  9.Ne4   Qe6   10.O-O  -  see here . } )
10. O-O{ There is no reason not to castle. White shouldn't be able to create any real threats against our king. }
11. d4( { The natural way to develop.    Let's mention one thing: We are never really afraid of White going for the pawn on  e7  with something like }11.Nxd5 Qxd5 12.Bxc6 Qxc6 13.Qxe7 { . White is way behind in development, we have two massive bishops looking down the board -  e6 ,  f5  and  g4  are all good squares for our light-squared bishop - and our rooks come easily into the game via  c8 ,  d8  and  e8 . If White takes with the queen on  e7 , this is even worse than taking on  e7  with the rook ( Rf1 - e1xe7 ), because ... Re8  will come with tempo. } )
11. Bf5{ The most active square for the bishop. We stop  Nc3 - e4  but we also support other ideas.  ... Ncb4 !? is a typical idea to create some threats on the queenside. The bishop just supports the control over  c2  and  d3  and even ... Bd3  might be an idea.  Exchanging minor pieces is in general a decent idea for Black. Endgames should be favourable for us as White's  d4 -pawn is a long-term weakness. }
12. Bg5{ This was played in the only two games that I could find with this position. White just develops and increases the pressure against  e7 . }( {  A)  As usual, }12.Nxd5 Qxd5 13.Bxc6 bxc6 14.Qxe7 { is not a threat. Black has enough positional compensation. For example, }14...Rfe8 { or }14...Be4 { are good moves. } )( {  B)  }12.Bh6 { is the typical move to go for a mate on  h7  but this doesn't work here.     B1)  }12...Bf6 { is most likely the easiest move. The queen has no good squares and even if it had, we can now exchange any attacking piece that might jump to  g5 .     B2)  }12...Ncb4!? { is a typical move against this  Qh4  setup. The knight is ready to replace the other knight on  d5 , but it might also be useful to attack  a2  or to go to  c2 . } )
12. Ncb4{ Not the only move but I wanted to have this ... Ncb4  resource in one of the trainables. It is indeed not so easy for White to find a convincing continuation. }( { If they play }13.a3 { , we can just go }13...Nc2 { , attacking the rook, but also with ideas like }-- ...Nxc3 bxc3 { and taking on  a3 .     If White ever takes on  d5 , we can now replace it with the  b4 -knight. If White finds nothing concrete, we will just continue with ... Rfc8  and start causing problems on the c-file. } )( 12...e6 { was played in one correspondence game with this position. Black spent a tempo to secure this e-pawn and just continued with ... Rfc8  & ... Bf6  after which White also had no great attack. } )
