1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it.     Rules for this chapter:    - We should still watch out for the stability of our  d5 -pawn.    - White's  d4 -pawn is often our course of counterplay. Even if White doesn't play with an isolated pawn. } )
