[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it. } )
4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. cxd5{ The immediate capture is not particularly flexible. }
6. Nxd5( { If White plays }7.Nf3 { - and that is the main move-, we can just transpose to the mainline with }7...a6 { -  starting here . } )
7. Bc4( { This is White's main independent try. However, Black has different moves to get a good position.  A)  }7.Nf3 a6 { transposes to  6.Nf3 . } )( {  B)  }7.Bb5?! { is a favorite of German IM Max Berchtenbreiter. However, if you don't play against him, you will most likely never face it. }7...g6 { is }{ certainly good enough and leads to the kind of position that we have discussed a little bit in the last chapter already -  like here . As mentioned, all these lines with  Bb5  lose power if White cannot achieve anything concrete against  c6 . Besides this easy solution, }7...Nxc3 8.bxc3 Qd5! { is just a very annoying double attack against  b5  and  g2 . This is objectively even stronger.     Giving up the bishop pair on  c6  is just bad for White and }9.Be2 { , gambiting the pawn and played by Berchtenbreiter in their games, can hardly convince. }9...Qxg2 10.Bf3 Qg6 { Black is a pawn up and White's king will never be safe. } )
7. Be6( { Black just stabilizes the knight on  d5  and is also threatening   }8...Nxc3 9.bxc3 Bxc4 { . } )( 7...Nb6 { is also possible. }8.Bb5 { Forced as not to lose the  d4 -pawn. Now, Black has to do something about the  d4 - d5 -threat. }8...Be6!? { Very likely, we will transpose to positions similar to  this line  after, for example, }9.Nf3 g6 10.O-O Bg7 11.Re1 O-O 12.Bxc6 bxc6 { . }{ Black committed the  c8 -bishop before White played  h2 - h3 . This should be beneficial for White even though it might not be a big deal in this otherwise extremely solid position. } )
8. Bb3{ There is not really anything better. Exchanging on  d5  helps Black as the exchange of minor pieces typically helps the side that plays against the isolated pawn. }( 8.Qb3 { is a logical move. However, }8...Nxd4 { just wins a pawn! There is a reason why White's knight is usually on  f3 ! } )
8. g6{ Black's play is pretty straightforward: Developing with ... Bg7  and ... O-O . ...  h6  might be useful in some cases to stop  Nf3 - g5  or  Bc1 - g5  ideas.  After Black is developed, we can continue with ... Rc8 , ... Na5 - c4  and some queenside play.     How easy things can go wrong can be seen in the model game Gugulashvili - Pantsulaia, 2012 -  see here . }
9. Nf3
9. Bg7{ The pressure against  d4  stops  Nf3 - g5  ideas. }
10. O-O( 10.Ng5? { doesn't work. }10...Nxd4! 11.Nxe6 fxe6∓ { Black has to allow the weakening of their structure because }11...Nxe6 { would hang the  d5 -knight. But we have won a really juicy pawn on  d4  that's definitely worth it! } )
10. O-O
11. Re1{ White has other moves but Black's ideas remain the same. }
11. Rc8{ Black gets typical activity along the c-file. ... Na5  is a typical idea to either take on  b3  or to go to  c4 . ... h6  is useful to stop any White piece to come to  g5 . }( { We need to keep an eye on the  e7 -pawn - for example }12.h3 Na5?! 13.Bxd5 Bxd5 14.Nxd5 Qxd5 15.Rxe7 { is good for White. } )( {   So }12...Re8 { is a move that some players like to play.  It might even be an idea to change the structure by taking on  c3  and start to create counterplay against the  c3 -pawn. } )
