[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 1.c4 c6 2.e4 Panov Mainline"]
[Black "6.Bg5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it. } )
4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Bg5{ This move always had its fanbase. White is playing with the idea to play  Bxf6 . It is not really a threat in a positional sense as the pawn structure after ... exf6  is considered completely fine.  However, concretely the  d5 -pawn is hanging and Black has to decide how to protect it. }
6. Be6{ A typical move. Black simply overprotects the  d5 -pawn. }( {  A)  There is nothing horribly wrong with }6...e6 { but White scores well after }7.Nf3 Be7 8.c5!? { . } )( {  B)  }6...dxc4!? { is theoretical a very decent move but the game can become extremely sharp if White gambits the  d4 -pawn with }7.Bxc4!? { .    Now, switching to regular IQP-positions with }7...e6 { is not really in the spirit of our repertoire and snitching the  d4 -pawn with }7...Qxd4 { or (more precise) }7...h6 8.Bh4 Qxd4 9.Qxd4 Nxd4 10.O-O-O ! { requires precise knowledge from Black. } )
7. Be2{ This is a surprisingly tricky move. The bishop wants to go to  f3 , putting massive pressure on  d5 . There is always a potential pawn fork on  d5  in the position. }
7. Qa5{ A forced response to anticipate  Be2 - f3 . Black is ready to put a rook on  d8  and pin a potential  d5 -pawn appearing on the square. }( 7...g6? 8.Bf3! { is very annoying. White is threatening }-- 9.Bxf6 exf6 10.cxd5 { and }8...dxc4 9.d5 { also doesn't help. } )
8. Bf3{ Now, this move is not so threatening. }
8. Rd8( { The solid response. Now,   }9...dxc4 { is a legitimate threat. } )( { The line }8...dxc4 { is also playable and more forcing. }9.d5 { White has to play this fork. Otherwise, Black has just won a safe extra pawn. }9...O-O-O ! ( { (Better than }9...Rd8 { as Black's king is better on  c8  after the following forcing sequence.) } )10.Bd2! { This unpins the d-pawn. }10...Nxd5 11.Nxd5 { White is currently a piece up and attacking Black's queen. There is one solution though. }11...Rxd5! 12.Bxa5 Rxd1+ 13.Rxd1 Nxa5 { with an approximately equal endgame. Black has two pawns for the exchange. } )
9. Bxf6{ The pressure against White's pawns forces White more or less to clear the situation. }
9. exf6
10. cxd5{ Once again, White doesn't really have a choice to solve the problem with the hanging d-pawn. }( 10.c5 { does allow }10...b6 { and even }10...Bxc5 11.dxc5 d4! { seems to work.    After }12.Qa4 { , Black cannot play }12...dxc3 { because of }13.Bxc6+ { and  14.Qxa5 . However }12...Qxc5 { gives Black a great initiative. }{ White's king is in the center and the combination of ideas with ... Qe5 + and ... d3 - d2  can be really annoying for White. } )
10. Bxd5
11. Bxd5
11. Rxd5{ With a very decent endgame for Black. We will play ... Rd7  at some point as the rook will be hanging once White unpins their knight and we will develop with ... Be7 /... Bb4 , ... O-O , ... Rfd8 . }
