7. Be2{ This is a surprisingly tricky move. The bishop wants to go to  f3 , putting massive pressure on  d5 . There is always a potential pawn fork on  d5  in the position. }
7. Qa5{ A forced response to anticipate  Be2 - f3 . Black is ready to put a rook on  d8  and pin a potential  d5 -pawn appearing on the square. }( 7...g6? 8.Bf3! { is very annoying. White is threatening }-- 9.Bxf6 exf6 10.cxd5 { and }8...dxc4 9.d5 { also doesn't help. } )
8. Nf3{ After this move, Black can just take on  c4 . }
8. dxc4{ Black is now a pawn up, White cannot go for  d4 - d5  and we are ready to play ... Rd8  next to solve all our problems. }
9. O-O{ White has to develop. }( 9.Bxf6 exf6 10.d5?! { doesn't work here. }10...O-O-O ! { ⩱ The idea behind  7...Qa5 . The d-pawn is just weak as White is pinned all over the place. } )
9. Rd8{ Black is rock-solid and now we only have to develop our kingside. A good way is to just play ... h6  next and potentially even ... g5 , then ... Bg7  and ... O-O . }
10. Re1{ This is the trickiest move. White plays for some tricks on the e-file. }( 10.Qc1 { is the engine move but it doesn't really set any problems. White unpins the d-pawn. }10...h6! { is just a good reply. }11.Bxf6 exf6 { is just really pleasant for Black without tricks on the e-file. }{ And if White doesn't take, we might consider ... g5 , ... Bg7 , ... O-O . } )
10. h6{ White taking on  f6  is not even dangerous here even though we have to recapture with the g-pawn. It is true, usually, it is easier to play ... exf6  to keep the kingside safe but our extra pawn is even more important than the weakness of our king. }
11. Bxf6( { The critical move. }11.Be3 g6 { will make it possible to develop the kingside. } )
11. gxf6{ Black is ready to go ... Bg7  and ... O-O . }( 11...exf6?? 12.Bxc4! { doesn't work here. White has not only won their pawn back.   e6  is under pressure and  d4 - d5  is a huge threat. } )
