5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Bg5{ This move always had its fanbase. White is playing with the idea to play  Bxf6 . It is not really a threat in a positional sense as the pawn structure after ... exf6  is considered completely fine.  However, concretely the  d5 -pawn is hanging and Black has to decide how to protect it. }
6. Be6{ A typical move. Black simply overprotects the  d5 -pawn. }( {  A)  There is nothing horribly wrong with }6...e6 { but White scores well after }7.Nf3 Be7 8.c5!? { . } )( {  B)  }6...dxc4!? { is theoretical a very decent move but the game can become extremely sharp if White gambits the  d4 -pawn with }7.Bxc4!? { .    Now, switching to regular IQP-positions with }7...e6 { is not really in the spirit of our repertoire and snitching the  d4 -pawn with }7...Qxd4 { or (more precise) }7...h6 8.Bh4 Qxd4 9.Qxd4 Nxd4 10.O-O-O ! { requires precise knowledge from Black. } )
7. Be2{ This is a surprisingly tricky move. The bishop wants to go to  f3 , putting massive pressure on  d5 . There is always a potential pawn fork on  d5  in the position. }
7. Qa5{ A forced response to anticipate  Be2 - f3 . Black is ready to put a rook on  d8  and pin a potential  d5 -pawn appearing on the square. }( 7...g6? 8.Bf3! { is very annoying. White is threatening }-- 9.Bxf6 exf6 10.cxd5 { and }8...dxc4 9.d5 { also doesn't help. } )
8. c5{ White closes the center - not an untypical idea in this variation. If Black plays a slow move, White can try to prove that the queen on  a5  is misplaced as it allows White to expand with tempo after  a2 - a3  &  b2 - b4 . Luckily, we have a typical Grünfeld-looking move. }
8. Ne4{ This idea to put pressure on  c3  might look familiar from other lines in this course. }
9. Bd2( { This threatens   }10.Nxe4 { and forces Black to take the bishop immediately. } )
9. Nxd2( { Of course, we grab the bishop pair. }9...Nxc3? 10.Bxc3 { followed by  b2 - b4 - b5  would be awesome for White. } )
10. Qxd2
10. g6{ Black has an easy plan. ... Bg7 , ... O-O  and then - when the king is evacuated from the center - a timely ... b6  to break the queenside. If White plays  Nf3 , we also get the option ... Bg4  to create a lot of pressure against  d4 . }
11. Bb5{ The only move really directed against Black's plan. }( 11.Nf3 { is the most popular move. Black can just play }11...Bg4 { , followed by ... Bg7  and a lot of pressure against  d4 . } )
11. Bg7{ Black just develops. }
12. h3{ The best move. White stops ... Bg4 . }( 12.Nf3 Bg4 { will once again create a lot of pressure against the  d4 -pawn. } )
12. O-O{ Black unpins the  c6 -knight and now  d4  is hanging. }
13. Nf3
13. a6{ White's setup looks like taking on  c6  would be part of their plan. However, now White has to show their cards and no matter if White takes on  c6  or not, we can start our own play in the center. }
14. Ba4{ White tries to keep the two bishops. }
14. b5{ Black gives White a protected passed pawn on  c5  which is something that should not be done carelessly. Here, however, Black can just start their own play in the center really quick, so this factor will not be too important in the following middlegame. }
15. Bb3{ White shouldn't take en passant but instead that drop back with the bishop. }( 15.cxb6 Qxb6 { would just be really comfortable for Black. We have a lot of pressure against the pawn on  d4  and on the queenside. } )
15. Rad8{ Black protects the  d5 -pawn which is also useful for the coming plan. Black wants to play ... f6 , ... Bf7  and potentially ... e5 . }
16. O-O
16. f6{ Part of the plan ... Bf7  and ... e5  get prepared. Let's end the trainable with a sample line. }
17. a3{ This is the best move according to the engine. One reason for this move is to take away the ... b5 - b4  move from Black before finally playing ... e5  - this would give White even less counterplay against Black's counterplay.  Also, this move gives the  b3 -bishop a retreat to  a2  so White can prepare  b2 - b4  without moving the bishop from the strong  a2 - g8  diagonal. Black's play would be similar against other moves. }
17. Bf7{ The e-pawn becomes mobile. }
18. Ba2{ White prepares  b2 - b4 . }
18. Qc7{ I think this move is most consistent with our plan. White wanted to play  b2 - b4  anyways and the queen is just much better placed on  c7  if we start playing in the center. }( 18...b4!? { is also possible to create some play on the queenside. } )
19. b4
19. Kh8{ Black moves out of the bishop’s diagonal. If White is not careful, Black can just start to steamroll White with ... e5 - e4 , ...  f5 - f4  and also the g-pawn can join the fray. }( { If White is smart, they anticipate this with a move like }20.Rad1 { to increase pressure on  d5 . After this, we have an interesting standoff. Both sides have currently the plans of the opponent nicely under control.    A long manoeuvring phase might start. }20...e6 { is a good prophylactic move to just overprotect the structure and allow more manoeuvring along the 7th rank.  At some point, we might consider aggressive ideas with ... g5  and ... h5 . To prepare this, we need more pieces looking at the kingside. I really like the idea to bring the queen to  f8  - this might take a while - and prepare ... Bh6 .     After we have won the  c1 - h8  diagonal, we can play ... Bf4 - c7  bringing the bishop to the diagonal towards White's king. Then we assemble our major pieces on  h7 ,  g7  and  g8  and slowly advance on the kingside. } )
