6. Bg5{ This move always had its fanbase. White is playing with the idea to play  Bxf6 . It is not really a threat in a positional sense as the pawn structure after ... exf6  is considered completely fine.  However, concretely the  d5 -pawn is hanging and Black has to decide how to protect it. }
6. Be6{ A typical move. Black simply overprotects the  d5 -pawn. }( {  A)  There is nothing horribly wrong with }6...e6 { but White scores well after }7.Nf3 Be7 8.c5!? { . } )( {  B)  }6...dxc4!? { is theoretical a very decent move but the game can become extremely sharp if White gambits the  d4 -pawn with }7.Bxc4!? { .    Now, switching to regular IQP-positions with }7...e6 { is not really in the spirit of our repertoire and snitching the  d4 -pawn with }7...Qxd4 { or (more precise) }7...h6 8.Bh4 Qxd4 9.Qxd4 Nxd4 10.O-O-O ! { requires precise knowledge from Black. } )
7. Be2{ This is a surprisingly tricky move. The bishop wants to go to  f3 , putting massive pressure on  d5 . There is always a potential pawn fork on  d5  in the position. }
7. Qa5{ A forced response to anticipate  Be2 - f3 . Black is ready to put a rook on  d8  and pin a potential  d5 -pawn appearing on the square. }( 7...g6? 8.Bf3! { is very annoying. White is threatening }-- 9.Bxf6 exf6 10.cxd5 { and }8...dxc4 9.d5 { also doesn't help. } )
8. c5{ White closes the center - not an untypical idea in this variation. If Black plays a slow move, White can try to prove that the queen on  a5  is misplaced as it allows White to expand with tempo after  a2 - a3  &  b2 - b4 . Luckily, we have a typical Grünfeld-looking move. }
8. Ne4{ This idea to put pressure on  c3  might look familiar from other lines in this course. }
9. Nf3{ White simply protects the bishop on  g5  with a developing move. Black has different very playable options. }
9. g6{ I recommend just continue developing and ignoring the bishop on  g5  for now. }( {  A)  Grabbing the bishop pair with }9...Nxg5 { is also possible. But these lines can become messy. After }10.Nxg5 { , White has the idea to take on  e6 . }10...Bf5?! 11.Qb3! { would ask some very concrete questions on the queenside. } )( {  B) Grabbing a pawn as the pawn on  c3  is dangerous with no development. }9...Nxc3?! 10.bxc3 Qxc3+ 11.Bd2 Qa3 { The only square. }12.Qb1!+- { White is threatening to take on  b7  and you also don't really want to castle into White's attack with }12...O-O-O { . } )
10. O-O
10. Bg7( { Now, Black is threatening to play   }11...Nxg5 12.Nxg5 Nxd4 { . White has to spend a tempo to stop this. } )
11. Nxe4
11. dxe4{ This was played in  Atalik - Atakisi, 2018 . The pressure against the d-pawn is too much. }
12. d5{ This was White's idea. This variation is not important from the theoretical perspective but the following sequence is something to remember. }
12. O-O-O{ This move is one of the main resources after ... Qa5 . }( {  A)  In the game, Black played }12...Bxd5?! 13.Qxd5 exf3 14.Bxf3 { which is okay but just equal. } )( {  B)  }12...exf3?! 13.Bxf3 Rd8 { looks like Black has just won a piece but White can untangle with tempo. }14.Bd2! { when White will win back the piece, also with a somewhat equal position. } )
13. Bd2{ This was certainly the move why Black refrained from castling in their game. However, Black has a strong response. }
13. Rxd5{ Now, White can take on  a5  but we can take on  d1 . }
14. Bxa5
14. Rxd1
15. Bxd1( { A sad necessity. After taking with one of the rooks, e.g. }15.Rfxd1 exf3! { comes with tempo against the  e2 -bishop. As the  a5 -bishop is also under attack, Black will just win an additional piece. } )
15. Nxa5{ Black is objectively maybe just winning in this position. White is the exchange up but we have strong bishops that are pointing towards White's queenside,  b2  and  f3  are hanging, ideas with ... Nc4  or ... Bc4  are also possible. }
