1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it. } )
4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Bg5{ This move always had its fanbase. White is playing with the idea to play  Bxf6 . It is not really a threat in a positional sense as the pawn structure after ... exf6  is considered completely fine.  However, concretely the  d5 -pawn is hanging and Black has to decide how to protect it. }
6. Be6{ A typical move. Black simply overprotects the  d5 -pawn. }( {  A)  There is nothing horribly wrong with }6...e6 { but White scores well after }7.Nf3 Be7 8.c5!? { . } )( {  B)  }6...dxc4!? { is theoretical a very decent move but the game can become extremely sharp if White gambits the  d4 -pawn with }7.Bxc4!? { .    Now, switching to regular IQP-positions with }7...e6 { is not really in the spirit of our repertoire and snitching the  d4 -pawn with }7...Qxd4 { or (more precise) }7...h6 8.Bh4 Qxd4 9.Qxd4 Nxd4 10.O-O-O ! { requires precise knowledge from Black. } )
7. Nf3{ The second most popular move but is usually transposes to other lines. }
7. g6( { Still, our normal way to develop as White is not threatening anything. }7...a6!? { is also playable and leads to the variation   }6.Nf3 a6 7.Bg5 Be6 { . } )
8. Be2{ The move to stay flexible without committing to anything. }( {  A)  }8.Bxf6 exf6 { leads to positions from  7.Bxf6 . } )( {  B)  }8.c5 { leads to positions similar to  this one  just with the difference, that White hasn't provoked ... Qa5 . This can only be useful for Black and we can simply keep developing. }8...Bg7 9.Bb5 { The main move. White creates some pressure against  c6  even though there is never really a threat if Black just develops naturally. }9...O-O { , followed by  ...Ne4 . }10.O-O Ne4 { Black is threatening  ...Nxg5 , followed by  ...Nxd4 . }11.Be3 Bg4 { with a lot of pressure against White's center. } )
8. Bg7{ We just keep developing. }
9. O-O
9. O-O{ At some point, White has to decide what to do with their position. At this point, I am already convinced that White can only enter non-ideal versions of other variations. }
10. Rc1{ White tries to be flexible but as we will see, at some point we can just take on  c4 . }( {  A)  }10.cxd5 { Taking on  d5  is just not helping White's position. After both }10...Nxd5 { as well as }10...Bxd5!? { , Black has a very good IQP position. } )( {  B)  }10.c5 Ne4 { is exactly the setup from  this line  with Black not having spent a tempo on ... Qa5 . So here we are even more comfortable. } )
10. dxc4{ For now, this wins a pawn. To get it back, White has to take on  f6  and play  d4 - d5  but after the following forcing variation, only Black can be better. }
11. Bxf6
11. Bxf6
12. d5
12. Bxc3{ A necessary in-between move to get rid of the protection of the  d5 -pawn. }
13. dxe6{ Clearly the piece that White should take. After taking on  c3 , Black could just collect the  d5 -pawn. }( 13.dxc6? Bxb2-+ { is also just horrible with Black's extra pawns, bishop pair and very strong c-passer. } )
13. Bxb2{ A pawn is a pawn. Also, we win a tempo against the rook on  c1 . }
14. exf7+{ An in-between move not to lose another pawn. }
14. Kg7{ Black could have also taken the pawn but it doesn't really run away and the king is safer on  g7 . }
15. Rxc4{ Logical. The rook was attacked. }
15. Qxd1{ Going for an endgame that is unpleasant for White as Black is about to be a pawn up. }
16. Rxd1
16. Bf6{ A safe retreating move to stop all moves like  Rb1  with tempo. Now, White is about to lose the  f7 -pawn.  With best play, White seems to make a draw but only Black can be better of course. }
