4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Bg5{ This move always had its fanbase. White is playing with the idea to play  Bxf6 . It is not really a threat in a positional sense as the pawn structure after ... exf6  is considered completely fine.  However, concretely the  d5 -pawn is hanging and Black has to decide how to protect it. }
6. Be6{ A typical move. Black simply overprotects the  d5 -pawn. }( {  A)  There is nothing horribly wrong with }6...e6 { but White scores well after }7.Nf3 Be7 8.c5!? { . } )( {  B)  }6...dxc4!? { is theoretical a very decent move but the game can become extremely sharp if White gambits the  d4 -pawn with }7.Bxc4!? { .    Now, switching to regular IQP-positions with }7...e6 { is not really in the spirit of our repertoire and snitching the  d4 -pawn with }7...Qxd4 { or (more precise) }7...h6 8.Bh4 Qxd4 9.Qxd4 Nxd4 10.O-O-O ! { requires precise knowledge from Black. } )
7. Bxf6{ Taking on  f6  is a typical idea after 6.  Bg5  . }( { Some White players like to delay it for one move (and start with something like }7.a3 { or }7.Nf3 { ) until Black has committed himself to ... g6  to rule out the option of ... gxf6 .     However, for our repertoire, it doesn't make a difference as we always go .... exf6 . Our king will have a better pawn shelter and - as you will see - having so many pawns on the kingside allows us to expand on the kingside very easily. } )
7. exf6( { There is nothing horribly wrong with }7...gxf6 { but we have to learn the ... exf6  structures anyway so this cuts some workload. And I also simply prefer this pawn structure! } )
8. c5{ This is the typical continuation. After giving up the bishop pair, it makes sense to close the position.  We now have a very original pawn structure. Black's f-pawns are doubled and the d-pawn isolated.  However, it is absolutely not clear if White will ever be able to create a threat against  d5  and the pawn is not on an open file. The doubled pawns can also be useful as Black can advance actively with their pawns on the kingside and always have enough pawns to defend the king left.  The position should be about equal but Black's play is very clear. }
8. g6{ I think this is the best move, with the idea to go ... Bg7  or even ... Bh6  . But even if it is not objectively best, it makes sense to go for this setup here as well. }( { In the variation   }7.a3 g6 8.Bxf6 { or }7.Nf3 g6 8.Bxf6 { , we'll have to play with the same structure. } )
9. Bb5{ This is considered White's most flexible move. In these structures, the  d4 -pawn can become easily a target.  In this regard, many White players postpone  Nf3  so as to not allow ... Bg4 . In a setup with ... Bg7  and ... f5 , the  d4 -pawn can easily drop if White is not careful. Usually, White even continues with  Ng1 - e2  to avoid the ... Bg4  pin. }
9. h5{ I like this move. Against this setup with  Bb5  and no  Nf3 , the pawn on  d4  might not be the greatest target for counterplay.  Instead, we just prepare to grab as much space as possible on the kingside. }
10. Nge2{ The usual follow-up. The White cannot be pinned with ... Bg4  and it can go to  f4  to pressurize  e6  and  d5 . }( 10.Nf3 { is not really in the spirit of this line. The knight has no good follow-up square as long as we don't play ... f5  and give them the  e5 -square }{ . }10...a6!? { A typical move to ask the bishop what it wants to do. }11.Ba4 { Black has different ways to play this position. As we might not want to play  ...f5  anytime soon, I would make a case for }11...Bh6 { instead of  ...Bg7  }{ and Black can even bring their king into safety with ... Ke8 - f8 - g7 .     This way, the rook stays on  h8  in case we want to push forward with our kingside pawns. Not that anything is wrong with simple castling! } )
10. Bh6{ Developing while also stopping  Ne2 - f4 . }
11. O-O( { The normal move. }11.Qa4 { with pressure against  c6  doesn't lead to anything. }11...Qc8 { and }11...Qd7 { are both possible.  Check out the game  Winter Roach - Michalik  where Black very convincingly showed how to operate with the two bishops. } )
11. O-O
12. a3{ Preparing  b2 - b4 . }
12. f5( { Starting our own counterplay on the kingside.    What are the typical ideas? The main thing that Black is already somehow threatening is   }13...f4 { . }{ This would give Black much more active possibilities on the kingside in an instant.  ... f3  becomes an idea, the bishop gets the  f5 -square. } )( { So White should stop this with }13.f4 { .    }{ And then? Well, the move  f2 - f4  created some weaknesses in White's camp that we are not unhappy about.  A typical idea is to play ... h4  and - if possible - ... h3  to soften White's kingside even more. ... Kg7  is a multi-purpose move to stabilise the kingside but there is also the interesting manoeuvre...  Nc6 - e7 - g8 - f6 - e4 .     Pretty slow but  e4  is certainly a juicy square.  We might also consider questioning White's bishop on  b5  with ... a6 . If White takes on  c6 , both are bishops are now unopposed.     All of a sudden, Black can even become active on the queenside because we have the open b-file and we can use the a-pawn to win space.  If White retreats with the bishop to  a4 , we might consider ... b5 !?. This might also be the start to creating counterplay on the queenside. } )
