8. g6{ I think this is the best move, with the idea to go ... Bg7  or even ... Bh6  . But even if it is not objectively best, it makes sense to go for this setup here as well. }( { In the variation   }7.a3 g6 8.Bxf6 { or }7.Nf3 g6 8.Bxf6 { , we'll have to play with the same structure. } )
9. Nf3( { This position does frequently happen after   }7.Nf3 g6 8.Bxf6 { . } )( { Black can just play as I suggest in the variation  9.Bb5  with }9....h5!? { but the main reason why an early  Nf3  is not considered to be flexible is that Black can start to put pressure against  d4 . } )
9. Bg7{ Black's setup does ideally go ... Bg4 , ... f5 , maybe ... Qf6 , taking on  d4 . Your opponent should do something about it. }( 9...h5!? { is still a useful move even though not as concrete. } )
10. Be2{ This move makes ... Bg4  less threatening but it is also pretty passive. }( 10.h3 { has similar intentions but here, Black can also play ... }a6 { with a better version of what we see in this trainable. } )
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. a6{ A simple move but very effective. White will never have the  Bb5  resource anymore and Black can start to storm forwards on the kingside with ... f5 , ... g5  and potentially ... g4 .     The ... f5  push could also be played immediately but it is slightly more risky if White can somehow fight for the  e5 -square with  Bb5 ,  Bxc6 ,  Re1  and  Ne5 .     If you want to see how easy things can go wrong for White, check out the model game Levushkina - Atalik, Bundesliga 2021 -  see here . }
