9. cxd5{ This is the start of a very forcing variation. }( 9.c5 { is the other main move but we already discussed this via the  7.Bxf6   move order . } )
9. Bxd5{ Positionally, Black is doing well. Bishop pair, pressure against the weak pawn on  d4 . Without the following sequence, Black would just prepare castling and be better. }
10. Qe2+{ This is not only a random check but the idea to go  Qe2 - b5  has to be taken seriously. }
10. Ne7{ Forced but good enough. }( 10...Be7? 11.Qb5! { would already be good for White. The bishop on  d5  is attacked twice and has no good squares. }11...Be6 12.d5+- { White's idea behind  11.Qb5  was not to grab the rather unimportant pawn on  b7  but indeed to win a whole piece with this fork. }12...a6 13.Qa4 ( { ( }13.Qe2 { also works.) } )13...Bxd5 14.Rd1 { Winning by pinning! } )
11. Nxd5{ Once again, White has to find something concrete. }( { A move like }11.Nf3 { allows }11...Bh6 { and Black's king can be castled towards the kingside. } )
11. Qxd5
12. Qb5+( { The only forcing follow-up. Once again, }12.Nf3 Bh6 { prepares kingside castling - and when this happens, Black is just better positionally. } )
12. Kd8{ Just one of many good moves. It looks slightly risky to move the king in the center while the queens are still on the board but White really has no attacking pieces and White has no good way to avoid the exchange of queens. }( 12...Qd7 13.Qxd7+ Kxd7 { is the most popular variation and also completely fine. } )
13. Qxd5+{ White really has nothing better. }( { If White keeps the queens on with something like }13.Qa4 { , it is White's king who might come under pressure first. }{ We always have checks on the e-file and ... Bh6 , ... Rc8 , ... Nf5 /... Nc6  really activate Black's pieces fast! } )
13. Nxd5{ with a completely fine endgame for Black. We can continue with ... Bh6  or ... Bg7  and ... f5 . Our rooks can be activated via  c8  and  e8  - or even  d8  if Black's king goes somewhere else.  The knight on  d5  is not a stable outpost so we might consider regrouping it to another square.  e6 ,  c6  or  f5  look decent as we attack the  d4 -pawn. }( 14.Bc4 { doesn't win the  f7 -pawn because of the counterthreat }14...Nf4! 15.g3 Ne6 { . } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 1.c4 c6 2.e4 Panov Mainline"]
[Black "6.Nf3 & 7.Bg5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. e4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. d4( { This is the main position in the Panov-Variation that can be reached via different move orders in the Caro-Kann. Either via   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 { or }1.e4 c6 2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.d4 { .    }{ Luckily for us, here, we don't have to learn variations where White grabs the  d5 -pawn and just tries to protect it. } )
4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Nf3{ This is White's main move. They just develop and stay flexible with the structure in the center.  I tried to avoid a lot of theory by choosing a variation that just became popular recently but has been already approved by strong GMs. }
6. a6{ Not a new move but one that only became popular recently. Black just stops all ideas with  Bf1 - b5  which is one of White's main tries to put pressure on Black's position.  So far, it has given Black very decent results. }( {  A)  }6...g6 { would be logical for our repertoire but White has the very concrete }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 { . Now, }8...e6 { weakens the dark-squares and }8...Nxc3 9.Bc4! { is the start of a heavily debated variation that seems to be slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }6...Bg4 { is holding up nicely theoretically. The main line is a really forcing variation that leads to an endgame where Black still needs to know nuances to hold the balance. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3!? { It is very typical that White has to play concretely to not end in a slightly worse IQP position. }8...Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+! { is a nice in-between check to force Black's king to  e7 . }12...Ke7 13.Qxb5 { with an endgame that Black should hold.    Black has alternatives along the way but those are usually considered at least slightly better for White. } )
7. Bg5{ This looks similar to  6.Bg5 . White is threatening to take on  f6  and then on  d5 .     With the knight already committed to  f3 , we don't have to deal with tricky ideas like  Bf1 - e2 - f3 . In most games, White plays the idea  Bg5xf6  and  c4 - c5  at some point but as we have seen in other lines, the move ... a6  can be pretty useful in these structures to stop  Bf1 - b5 . }
7. Be6{ We use the same reply as against  6.Bg5  to protect  d5 . }
8. c5{ A flexible move. If White wants to take on  f6 , this move does belong in White's setup to close down the position.  But White can also combine this move with a different, strangling approach. }
8. g6{ Our typical setup. }
9. Bd3{ White stops Black's ... Ne4  move. }
9. Bg7{ The natural developing move.  After White's last move - and in anticipation of White's  h2 - h3  -, it is logical to consider putting the bishop on  g4  immediately. It is not a bad move but White can try to use the absence of the bishop on the e-file. }( 9...Bg4 10.Bxf6!? { Opening up the e-file. }10...exf6 11.O-O { Getting ready for a check on  e1 . }11...Bg7 12.Re1+ {     A)  Now, }12...Ne7? 13.Qb3 { with a double attack against  b7  and  d5  is a problem. }{     B)    }12...Kf8 { is the best reply.  While Black's position is solid and the bishops compensate for the weird king and the spoiled structure, this does certainly look like a rather decent version for White compared with similar positions. } )
10. h3{ This is a serious attempt for White. Now, ... Ne4  and ... Bg4  are both stopped - two of our main ideas to activate our pieces.  We should think of a new plan. }( 10.O-O Bg4! { would give Black nice counterplay against White's center. } )
10. Nd7{ With the knight not being able to go to  e4 , it makes sense to free our bishop on  g7  in some other way. Now, the  d4 -pawn is simply hanging and Black is getting ready for ... f6  , potentially followed by a quick ... e5  as well as ... b6 . }
11. Ne2{ If White takes away the pressure against  d5  and blocks the e-file, this is a good sign for us that we can play with a quick ... f6  and ... e5 . }
11. f6
12. Be3
12. Bf7{ There is not much that White can do to stop ... O-O  and ... e5  with a nice advance in the center. }
