11. Bc2{ White keeps the pressure against  d5  and leaves the central files open to make the ... f6  & ... e5  plan as unattractive as possible for Black. But we have other pawn breaks! }
11. h6{ A nice move to include. The bishop has to decide whether to give up the pressure against  e7  or the ability to return to  e3 . }
12. Bf4{ An active square. }( {  A)  }12.Bh4 { is similar but the bishop cannot come back to  e3  anymore which makes }12...b6! 13.cxb6 Qxb6 { even stronger. } )( {  B)  }12.Be3 { is positionally a good square but it allows the typical strike }12...Nxc5! 13.dxc5 d4! { which equalises immediately for Black. } )
12. b6{ A very principled reaction. Black has to break White's bind and this is a typical move to achieve this on the queenside. }( 12...g5 { is a funny move suggested by the engine. The idea is similar to  11...h6  - forcing the bishop to give up some options.     A)  After }13.Bg3 { , we can play }13...b6 { and the bishop can once again not retreat to  e3  to stabilize the pawns.     B)  }13.Be3 Nxc5! { does once again play for the  ...d5-d4  trick. } )( { Nevertheless, I chose }12...b6 { because it equalises without any tricks. } )
13. cxb6
13. Qxb6{ with nice counterplay against  d4  and  b2 . }
