6. a6{ Not a new move but one that only became popular recently. Black just stops all ideas with  Bf1 - b5  which is one of White's main tries to put pressure on Black's position.  So far, it has given Black very decent results. }( {  A)  }6...g6 { would be logical for our repertoire but White has the very concrete }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 { . Now, }8...e6 { weakens the dark-squares and }8...Nxc3 9.Bc4! { is the start of a heavily debated variation that seems to be slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }6...Bg4 { is holding up nicely theoretically. The main line is a really forcing variation that leads to an endgame where Black still needs to know nuances to hold the balance. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3!? { It is very typical that White has to play concretely to not end in a slightly worse IQP position. }8...Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+! { is a nice in-between check to force Black's king to  e7 . }12...Ke7 13.Qxb5 { with an endgame that Black should hold.    Black has alternatives along the way but those are usually considered at least slightly better for White. } )
7. h3{ White usually tries this move to restrict Black.  c4 - c5  and  Bf1 - d3  are usually the plan when Black will have lost the resources ... Ne4  and ... Bg4 . However, there is no reason to let this happen. }( {  A)    }8.Bd3 { first gets answered with }8...dxc4 { and    B)  }8.c5 { will allow us to play }...Ne4 { immediately. } )
7. g6{ For now, we can just continue to develop. }
8. c5{ The critical move. }( {  A)  }8.Bg5 Be6 { is a  7.Bg5 -variation with a weird early  h2-h3 . } )( {  B)  }8.cxd5 Nxd5 9.Bc4 Be6 { is also just a position like the ones after  7.cxd5  where it is not clear why White played this  h2-h3  so early. } )( {  C)  }8.Bd3 dxc4! { Stops all  c4 - c5  restricting ideas and gives Black a very good IQP position. } )
8. Ne4{ I would recommend this move before White can stop it with  Bf1 - d3 . }
9. Bd3{ White increases the pressure on  e4 , trying to force a reaction. After other moves, Black will just continue developing with ... Bg7 . }
9. Bf5{ We protect the  e4 -knight. After this, we just continue with our development ... Bg7  and ... O-O . }( 9...Nxc3?! 10.bxc3 { is what White wants. }{ Black has the pawn breaks ... e5  and ... b6  but it is tough to play them under good circumstances.  The bishop on  c6  also has no ideal square to develop as  f5  and  g4  are both controlled by White. } )
10. O-O
10. Bg7{ Both sides make natural developing moves. Now, White has to decide how to create pressure against Black's setup. }
11. Re1{ This is a logical move. Let's use this as a sample variation to see how Black plays if White has nothing concrete in mind and just develops their pieces naturally. }
11. O-O{ Now that we are fully developed, we have to think about ways to get active. Black's main ways to achieve this are the ... b6  and the ... e5 -pawn break. }( { Right now, we are also threatening   }12...Nxd4 { as White doesn't have the  Qa4+  at the end. } )( {  A)  Don't take the pawn with }11...Nxd4?? 12.Nxd4 Bxd4 13.Qa4+! { +-, winning the bishop. } )( {  B)  }11...Bxd4? 12.Nxd4 Nxd4 { is also too risky. White can just move the  d3 -bishop anywhere and collect the  d5 -pawn afterwards. Be sure before giving up the  g7 -bishop! } )
12. Be3{ A natural move to protect the  d4 -pawn. }
12. Re8{ Staying flexible. Black keeps the ... b6  option open but also supports the e-pawn. }( {  A)  }12...Rc8!? { is a typical move in the same spirit. Preparing the breaks before committing to them. If Black goes ... b7 - b6  and White takes with  c5xb6  , Black has to include ... Ne4xc3   b2xc3  before recapturing on the  b6  is possible.     In the resulting structure, the rook will be ideally placed on  c8 . } )( {  B)  The immediate }12...b6 { is possible but by playing the move immediately, White can anticipate the resulting structures much better. }13.cxb6 Nxc3 14.bxc3 Bxd3 15.Qxd3 Qxb6 16.Rab1⩲ { It is still a typical structure and not the end of the World for Black but White's pieces might be on better squares than strictly necessary. } )
13. Rb1{ A subtle reply. White sees ... Nxc3  coming and places the rook on the ideal half-open b-file. }
13. Nb4{ This knight move to  b4  is really strong. Black would love to take the bishop on  d3  and White might have some problems on the  h7 - b1  diagonal. }
14. Bf1( { Offering an exchange sacrifice. The same could happen after }14.Be2 { .    Giving up the bishop with }14.Bxe4 { is certainly okay for Black. No matter if we play }14...Bxe4 { or }14...dxe4 { . } )
14. e5{ A nice in-between move to activate the pieces before taking the exchange. }( { The immediate }14...Nxc3?! 15.bxc3 Bxb1 16.Qxb1 { wins the exchange but White has great compensation. }16...Nc6 17.Qxb7=∞ { White has one pawn for the exchange, a strong passer on  c5  and the  c6 -knight is under attack. This is annoying for Black. } )
15. Nxe5{ Let's choose this as trainable as this might be the trickiest move. }( 15.dxe5 { allows the same variation as  14...Nxc3?!  on the last move just that Black can recapture on  e5  at the end. }15...Nxc3! 16.bxc3 Bxb1 17.Qxb1 Nc6 18.Qxb7 Nxe5⇆ { White still has compensation for the exchange but it is much less dangerous than before. } )
15. Nxc5{ The right capture. Now, the material is even and Black is ready to jump around with the knights. }( { The best move seems to be the desperado }16.Nxf7!? Kxf7 17.dxc5 { but Black has no problems. Neither after the obvious }17...Bxb1 { nor after the clever }17...Nc2!? { that also wins the exchange but Black won't have to play against the bishop pair. } )( 15...Nxc3 { is tempting but would still give White great compensation. }16.bxc3 Bxb1 17.Qxb1 Nc6 18.Nf3! { A strong response. White doesn't do the favour to take on  c6  and improve our pawn structure.  To be honest, this is not the kind of position where it is completely obvious that White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed material. But once you try to play a move for Black, it becomes extremely tough to create a plan because White has absolutely no targets in this position.    If Black could achieve }...b6 { under decent circumstances, it would be a different story. } )
