6. a6{ Not a new move but one that only became popular recently. Black just stops all ideas with  Bf1 - b5  which is one of White's main tries to put pressure on Black's position.  So far, it has given Black very decent results. }( {  A)  }6...g6 { would be logical for our repertoire but White has the very concrete }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 { . Now, }8...e6 { weakens the dark-squares and }8...Nxc3 9.Bc4! { is the start of a heavily debated variation that seems to be slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }6...Bg4 { is holding up nicely theoretically. The main line is a really forcing variation that leads to an endgame where Black still needs to know nuances to hold the balance. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3!? { It is very typical that White has to play concretely to not end in a slightly worse IQP position. }8...Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+! { is a nice in-between check to force Black's king to  e7 . }12...Ke7 13.Qxb5 { with an endgame that Black should hold.    Black has alternatives along the way but those are usually considered at least slightly better for White. } )
7. c5{ From an objective point of view, this is one of White's best options. However, Black's plan is really easy: Attack  d4  with everything we have!     White is trying to restrict us with their pawns, but this plan gives us a clear target.     We will play ... Bg4 , ... g6 , ... Bg7 , at some point we move the knight from  f6  (and even the route  f6 - g8 - e7 - f5  is possible to increase the pressure on White's d-pawn). }
7. Bg4{ Using the chance to play this move before White can play  h2 - h3 . }( { Nevertheless, we could also start with }7...g6 { and if White plays }8.h3 { , we just transpose to  these trainables . } )
8. Be2{ Because the opening fight is so much about the  d4 -pawn, White puts their bishops pretty much always on  e2  and  e3 . }
8. g6
9. O-O
9. Bg7{ Both sides develop and follow their setups. }
10. Be3( { The most flexible move. }10.h3 { was played in  Blohberger - Donchenko, Bundesliga 2020 . But Black can just continue with }10...Bxf3 11.Bxf3 { and now }11...e6 { , followed by }-- ...Ng8 -- ...Nge7 -- ...Nf5 { . } )
10. e6{ This move is often necessary anyway because Black will take on  f3  at some point (most of the times after  h2 - h3 ) and without this move, it will be impossible to manoeuvre the  f6 -knight to better squares where it doesn't block the  g7 -bishop.     By playing this move before castling, we keep the option open to play the ... Nf6 - g8 - e7 - f5  manoeuvre. }( { Starting with }10...O-O { is also possible and was played in Grandelius - Van Foreest, Malmö 2022. The drawback is that now the  g8 -square is blocked! } )
11. Rb1( { If White plays a slow move like this, the }11...Ng8 { manoeuvre usually works very nicely. } )( { The fact that Black can now also start by taking on  f3  without being provoked with  h2-h3 , should be enough explanation why for example }11.h3 { is not scary. }11...Bxf3 { would just be played under better circumstances. } )
11. Bxf3{ Making sure that White has as few defenders as possible to protect the  d4 -pawn. }( { The immediate }11...Ng8 { is also playable. White can take some strength away from the manoeuvre to  f5  by avoiding the exchange of bishop against knight on  f3  with }12.Ne1!? { . Nevertheless, this doesn't look too frightening, both after }12...Bxe2 { or }12...Bf5 { . } )
12. Bxf3
12. Ng8{ The knight is heading towards the lovely  f5 -square. With the bishop already on  f3 , it makes sense to go the route via  h6  to stop  Bf3 - g4 . White should make sure that this is not possible. }( { Let's look at the two moves }13.Qd2 { and }13.Re1 { in more detail to understand Black's possibilities here. } )
13. Re1{ A subtle way to prevent ... Nh6 . With the rook on  e1 , sacrifices on  d5  are in the air. }
13. h5{ A nice idea to keep in mind. We take away the move  Bf3 - g4  to make sure that our knight lands on  f5 . }( {  A)  }13...Nge7 14.Bg4! { is also about equal according to the engine but here we would have to search for other ways of counterplay. }14...b6!? { would be logical to create some but White can try to create an outpost on  c5  either with the immediate }15.Na4 { or after }15.cxb6 Qxb6 16.Na4 { . } )( {  B)  }13...Nh6? { does just blunder the  d5 -pawn in many ways. }14.Bxh6 Bxh6 15.Nxd5+-  )
14. Na4{ The best move according to the engine and the only one that really asks questions. White has the annoying idea to go to  b6  when our rook is in some trouble. After other moves, we can just play ... Nge7  and go to  f5 .  Tricks against  d5  don't work with the knight still on  g8 . }( { For example }14.Nxd5?? exd5 15.Bg5+ Nge7-+ { and everything is protected. The same applies to   }15.Bh6+ Kf8 { . } )
14. Nge7{ The typical follow-up. }
15. Nb6{ That was the idea behind  14.Na4 . }
15. Rb8{ I cannot resist but give this as the mainline. The rook is still awkward on  b8  but less so than on  a7  in my opinion. }( { The engine is claiming that }15...Ra7!? { is also fine. We get our knight to  f5 . But doesn't }15...Rb8 { lose the exchange? } )
16. Bf4( { If White plays something different, such as }16.Qd2 { , we just continue to ignore the  Bf4 -'threat' and just develop with }16...O-O { . }{ Afterwards, we either continue with ... Nf5  or we use the knight to throw White's knight out with ... Nc8 . } )
16. O-O{ That's the point. We just sacrifice the exchange but we will win the  d4 -pawn in return when our active pieces and strong center gives us plenty of compensation. }( 16...Nxd4? 17.Bxd5! { is the reason why we shouldn't take the pawn with our king still in the center. }17...exd5 18.Bd6 { wins and }17...Nxd5 18.Nxd5 Qxd5 19.Bxb8+- { collects the exchange under much better circumstances. } )
17. Bxb8{ White has no reason to take the exchange immediately as the rook is trapped but this is the only move that forces us to be careful. }( { After other moves such as }17.Qd2 { , we can just play }17...Nf5 { , or }17...Re8 { to never allow the fork on  d7 .    Note that }17...Nxd4 18.Bxb8 { forces us to recapture on  b8  with queen which allows }18...Qxb8 19.Nd7 { . Interestingly enough, Black has still compensation despite being two exchanges down - we can at least spoil White's structure with }...Nxf3 { .    }{ However, overall, I would recommend taking on  d4 , once this fork is no longer possible. White cannot protect  d4  anyway. } )
17. Nxb8{ The last careful move. The next moves are ... Nbc6 , ... Nf5 , taking on  d4 , with very nice compensation. }( 17...Qxb8? 18.Nd7+- { is the trap. } )
