4. Nf6{ The normal move. Black is getting ready to recapture on  d5  with the knight. }
5. Nc3( { This move is pretty much exclusively played and even in those cases where White plays something else, like }5.Nf3 { , it usually transposes ( }5...Nc6 6.Nc3 { ) as there isn't really a setup where White doesn't have their knight on  c3 . } )
5. Nc6{ I chose this move as it fits very nicely to our  lines  against the Semi-Panov where we also develop this knight early to  c6 . }
6. Nf3{ This is White's main move. They just develop and stay flexible with the structure in the center.  I tried to avoid a lot of theory by choosing a variation that just became popular recently but has been already approved by strong GMs. }
6. a6{ Not a new move but one that only became popular recently. Black just stops all ideas with  Bf1 - b5  which is one of White's main tries to put pressure on Black's position.  So far, it has given Black very decent results. }( {  A)  }6...g6 { would be logical for our repertoire but White has the very concrete }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3 { . Now, }8...e6 { weakens the dark-squares and }8...Nxc3 9.Bc4! { is the start of a heavily debated variation that seems to be slightly better for White. } )( {  B)  }6...Bg4 { is holding up nicely theoretically. The main line is a really forcing variation that leads to an endgame where Black still needs to know nuances to hold the balance. }7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Qb3!? { It is very typical that White has to play concretely to not end in a slightly worse IQP position. }8...Bxf3 9.gxf3 e6 10.Qxb7 Nxd4 11.Bb5+ Nxb5 12.Qc6+! { is a nice in-between check to force Black's king to  e7 . }12...Ke7 13.Qxb5 { with an endgame that Black should hold.    Black has alternatives along the way but those are usually considered at least slightly better for White. } )
7. Ne5{ This move has scored well for White in about a dozen games in games by titled players. White doesn't allow ... Bg4  and can think about taking on  c6  in the future but Black has several ways to get a good position. }
7. Nxe5{ This leads to a forcing line that results in an interesting endgame. }( { There is nothing wrong with following our developing scheme with }8...g6 { as well. } )
8. dxe5
8. d4{ Forced so that we don't lose the  d5 -pawn. }
9. exf6
9. dxc3
10. Qxd8+{ Taking away our rights to castle. }
10. Kxd8
11. bxc3{ This was played in the only two games so far with the position. }( 11.fxg7?? Bxg7-+ { is just lost for White. }-- ...cxb2 { is a threat,   }12.Rb1 Bf5 { doesn't help. } )
11. exf6{ This endgame is equal but very imbalanced. Black wants to go ... Bc5 , ... Bf5 , ... Kc7  and bring the rooks to the center. }
12. Be3{ White's best move. If Black gets their bishop to  c5 , there is absolutely nothing to worry about and the engine even prefers Black already. }
12. Bf5{ Stopping  Bf1 - d3  and  Ra1 - b1 ,  Harikrishna - Dreev, Bilbao 2014 . The next move is 13... Kc7  and Black can either just develop the pieces naturally with something like ... Bd6 , ... Rhe8 , ... Rad8  or go for the more concrete ... Re8  with ... Bc5  ideas. }
