5. Bxf6
5. exf6
6. e3{ It is better to take on  f6  without also taking on  d5 . As we have seen, the open c-file is much more useful for Black than creating an IQP is for White. }
6. dxc4{ A simple move, opening the position a little bit for the bishop pair and stopping all of White's ideas to ever create an isolated pawn on  d5 . }
7. bxc4{ This was played in both games I found with this position. White tries to take as much central influence as possible. }( 7.Bxc4 { is developing with tempo but Black can simply develop with ... Bd6 , ... O-O , ... Qe7 , ... Nd7 , ... f5 .     For example, }7...Bd6 8.O-O O-O 9.d4 Qe7 10.Qc2 Nd7 11.Nc3 f5 { Conceptually speaking, White can either try to become active themselves in the center with  e3 - e4  or  d4 - d5  with the risk that this opens up the position for the bishops immediately or wait for Black to finish their development - ... Nf6 , ... Bd7 , ... Rfe8 , ... Rad8  - and then wait to see how Black intends to open the position.     Both options don't look completely convincing. } )
7. f5{ Black is ready to occupy the long diagonal with ... Bg7 . }
8. Nc3{ The most flexible move. }( 8.d4 { allows Black to just play as in the text with }8...Bg7 { but we could also play the immediate }8...f4!? { . Something like }9.exf4 Bb4+ 10.Nbd2 O-O=∞ { with ideas along the e-file but also simply }-- ...Bc3 { to win back the pawn would promise Black great compensation. } )
8. Bg7{ A nice diagonal for the bishop but we might also consider ... Bxc3  to give back the bishop pair in order to destroy White's queenside structure. }
9. Rc1{ This is apparently White's best move to move the rook out of the long diagonal while also stopping ... Bxc3 . }( {  A)  }9.d4 { would allow }9...f4 { but also }9...c5 { in typical Grünfeld fashion is possible. } )( {  B)  }9.Be2?! Bxc3! 10.dxc3 Qxd1+ 11.Rxd1 Na6∓ { would be a horrible endgame for White. } )
9. f4{ A typical pawn sacrifice with the doubled pawns. In exchange, we now ruin White's pawn structure. }
10. exf4{ If White doesn't take, we'll just take on  e3  and get the additional open files for free. }
10. O-O{ Black has nice positional compensation. We can follow up with ... Qd6  which attacks  f4  but also prepares ... Rd8  to fight for the  d4 -square. }( { If White plays }11.d4 { themselves, we can just go }11...Bg4 { and pick up the pawn later on. } )
