7. O-O{ White has different move orders to reach this position.     If we are looking at independent move orders via  1.c4 / 1.Nf3  that don't transpose to our  1.d4 -lines, this is one of White's more serious options.  By leaving the d-pawn on  d2 , Black cannot play the simple ... Bf5  & ... Ne4  manoeuvre that we saw many times in the  7.b3-chapter  - for example  here . Instead, White can put the d-pawn on  d3  which restricts the knight on  f6  and also makes the bishop move to  f5  less attractive.     While other variations in this chapter are more of a 'nice to know', I would definitely recommend studying these variations here in more detail. Black is fine but we shouldn't act carelessly. }( 7.d3 { This move is much less flexible than  7.O-O . It makes sense to keep the d-pawn flexible to discourage Black from preparing  ...e5 . We can certainly simply play }7...a5 { when things will most likely simply transpose to  this variation  but it is also a valid idea to save the tempo on the a-pawn move and start with the immediate }7...Re8 { , followed by ... Nbd7  . } )
7. a5{ Going for the same setup as with White's d-pawn on  d4 . This way, we give White the possibility to transpose. }
8. Nc3
8. Ne4( { An important move. By increasing the pressure on  c3 , we want to provoke White to play }9.d4 { when the game will transpose to positions from the main  g3-lines . } )
9. Na4{ The most critical move. White fights for the control of the long diagonal and wants to claim a small advantage after the exchange of bishops. }( 9.d4 Bf5 { transposes to  these lines . } )
9. b5{ An aggressive move to fight for space on the queenside. }( 9...Bxb2 10.Nxb2⩲ { is not so easy for Black. }{ Black is solid but White has more pieces developed and the more flexible structure.  Especially developing the  c8 -bishop - to a good square - can be tricky. } )
10. Bxg7( 10.cxb5 cxb5 11.Bxg7 Kxg7 { is just a transposition. } )
10. Kxg7
11. Nb2( { This puts less pressure on Black than }11.cxb5 { . White is not doing anything forcing. Nevertheless, with White's lead in development, we have to be careful. } )
11. a4{ A very ambitious move. Black is ready to play ... a4 - a3  with tempo to win a lot of space and fix the pawn on  a2 . }( 11...bxc4!? 12.bxc4 Qd6 { is a safe way to play the position. }{ There are no big imbalances in the pawn structure and Black can develop with ... Nd7 , ... Ba6 , potentially ... e5 . If Black wants to take on  c4 , it makes sense to do it before White can play  d2 - d3 . Otherwise, White would get the extra option of  d3xc4 . } )
12. cxb5{ This was played in the only predecessor that I found in this position. Opening the c-file to invade it later on. }( {  A)  }12.bxa4? bxc4∓ { is just bad for White. } )( {  B)  If White plays a slow move such as }12.Qc2 { , we can play }12...a3! { to fix White's pawn on  a2  and then continue with ... bxc4 , ... Qd6 , ...  Nd7 , ... Ba6 . For example }13.Nd3 bxc4 14.bxc4 Qd6 { A good square where the queen controls all vital dark squares. }15.Rfc1 Nd7⇆ { Black is ready for ... e5  and ... Ba6 . } )
12. a3( { This in-between move is Black's idea. }12...cxb5?! 13.bxa4 { loses a pawn. } )
13. Nd3( 13.Na4 cxb5 14.Nc3 { would be a weird variation to reach a position like  the ones  after  11.cxb5  but with Black's pawn on  a3  instead of on  a5 . To have this extra space and the fixed pawn on  a2  should be rather a better version for Black. Besides that, we can play it pretty much in the same style ( }14...b4! { ). } )
13. cxb5{ White is still ahead in development but the queenside structure gives us decent long-term prospects. }
14. Qc2{ White's most direct plan is invading via the c-file as long as Black is behind in development. }
14. Qd6{ Always a good square for the queen in this line. Black is taking control over many important dark squares such as  e5  and  c5  but also the protection of the  a3 -pawn or the control of  b4  can be factors. }
15. Rfc1
15. Na6{ Stopping the invasion via  c7 . Black only needs two more moves to fight for the c-file with the rooks. For example: }
16. Qc6
16. Qxc6
17. Rxc6
17. Bd7{ , followed by ... Rfc8  gives Black a decent position. }
