7. O-O{ White has different move orders to reach this position.     If we are looking at independent move orders via  1.c4 / 1.Nf3  that don't transpose to our  1.d4 -lines, this is one of White's more serious options.  By leaving the d-pawn on  d2 , Black cannot play the simple ... Bf5  & ... Ne4  manoeuvre that we saw many times in the  7.b3-chapter  - for example  here . Instead, White can put the d-pawn on  d3  which restricts the knight on  f6  and also makes the bishop move to  f5  less attractive.     While other variations in this chapter are more of a 'nice to know', I would definitely recommend studying these variations here in more detail. Black is fine but we shouldn't act carelessly. }( 7.d3 { This move is much less flexible than  7.O-O . It makes sense to keep the d-pawn flexible to discourage Black from preparing  ...e5 . We can certainly simply play }7...a5 { when things will most likely simply transpose to  this variation  but it is also a valid idea to save the tempo on the a-pawn move and start with the immediate }7...Re8 { , followed by ... Nbd7  . } )
7. a5{ Going for the same setup as with White's d-pawn on  d4 . This way, we give White the possibility to transpose. }
8. d3{ This move leaves the diagonal of the  b2 -bishop open. On the other hand, it is not stopping ... a4  and it makes more sense to prepare space-grabbing setups with ... e5  now because it would cost White a tempo if they decide to stop these plays with  d3 - d4 . }( 8.d4 a4 { transposes  here . } )
8. Re8{ Once White has committed their pawn to  d3 , it becomes much more attractive to play this move and prepare ... e5 . }( { It is also possible to simply move further with the a-pawn and it might be even possible to bring the pawn to  a3 . For example }8...a4 9.Nbd2 a3!? 10.Bc3 { has been played a number of times but Black still has to solve the issue of how they bring their remaining pieces into the game.    If Black plays }10...Nbd7 { , }{ they block the  c8 -bishop and there is no good square to follow it up.     Developing the bishop first before the knight might run into tempo moves (... Bg4  in  Nf3 - e5 , ... Bf5  into  e2 - e4 ,  Nf3 - d4  or potentially even  h4 + g4 ). }{    }10...Na6 11.Qc1 { is also just asking for trouble. } )
9. Nbd2{ The most popular move on all levels but not particularly threatening. }
9. Nbd7{ Black is ready to go ... e5 . That would give us the space advantage in the center. }
10. d4{ White can still play this move to stop ... e7 - e5  but Black gets good counterplay. }
10. a4{ With White's pawn on  d4 , this move does once again work nicely. }
11. e3{ This is White's most popular move. As seen in the main chapter with the double fianchetto -  like here , this is just a move to stabilise the center and prepare  Qd1 - e2 . Black's counterplay always looks similar. }( { For example, }11.Qc2 Nb6! { . } )
11. Nb6{ A strong move. Now, with White's d-pawn on  d4 , we can switch to the setup ... Bf5  and ... Ne4  to find good squares.  If White plays  c4 - c5 , White takes all the pressure away from the center and Black can continue preparing ... e5 . So White should rather respond flexibly. }
12. Ne5{ As in the  sister chapter , this move can sometimes be combined with a pawn advance on the kingside. }( { After other moves such as }12.Qe2 { , Black can just develop with }...Bf5 { , followed with ... Ne4 . } )
12. Be6{ Not the only move but a good example to see repeating patterns. As in  this variation , it is a good idea to develop the bishop to  e6  when White plays with  f2 - f4  or  g3 - g4  ideas and follow up with ... Nbd7  next when all pieces are on good squares. }( 12...Bf5?! 13.g4! { , }{ followed by  f2 - f4  is exactly what White wants. } )
