8. Re8{ Once White has committed their pawn to  d3 , it becomes much more attractive to play this move and prepare ... e5 . }( { It is also possible to simply move further with the a-pawn and it might be even possible to bring the pawn to  a3 . For example }8...a4 9.Nbd2 a3!? 10.Bc3 { has been played a number of times but Black still has to solve the issue of how they bring their remaining pieces into the game.    If Black plays }10...Nbd7 { , }{ they block the  c8 -bishop and there is no good square to follow it up.     Developing the bishop first before the knight might run into tempo moves (... Bg4  in  Nf3 - e5 , ... Bf5  into  e2 - e4 ,  Nf3 - d4  or potentially even  h4 + g4 ). }{    }10...Na6 11.Qc1 { is also just asking for trouble. } )
9. Qc2{ The most subtle move. As we have seen in the last trainables, it is a valid idea for White to answer ... e5  by taking on  d5  and building up on the c-file as long as Black is not fully developed.     By playing  9.Qc2 , White keeps the  b1 -knight more flexible and it can be developed via  c3  or  a3  as well when it might jump to  b5 . }
9. Nbd7{ We can still go for the same setup. Nevertheless, we might have to make some small adjustments if White is too quick with their queenside play. }
10. Nc3{ The most popular move on master level. White's knight wants to hop to  b5  after an exchange on  d5 . }
10. e5{ Black should still take the possible space in the center. }
11. cxd5
11. Nxd5{ The right way to recapture. The position resembles a reversed Dragon Sicilian.  In the next moves, we will activate our remaining pieces, for example with ... N7b6  and ... Be6 , ... Qe7 . These structures are pretty flexible, often both sides just manoeuvre with their pieces before deciding on a final plan. I would think that in this given setup, it makes some sense to go ... a5 - a4  eventually but the engine even insists that ... h5 , followed by ... h4  is a valid plan if White allows it!     Interesting stuff. }
