1. Nf3( { We are at the end of the theoretical part of our course. Only those variations remain which start with }1.Nf3 { and }{ do  not  lead to variations already discussed. To be honest, there are not very many of them.     The most important setup is probably the 'King's Indian Attack' in which White sets up with  g3 ,  Bg2 ,  O-O  and  d3 . }{    In fact, against }1.Nf3 { we are quite free in our move order. If you want, you can continue with }1...Nf6 { and postpone the move  ...d7-d5  for the moment. Nevertheless, I have chosen }1...d5 { as my recommendation.    I think for a Slav player there is nothing more natural than putting the d-pawn in the center at the first opportunity! } )
