1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. d3{ A rare move. White might continue in 'King's Indian Attack style' with  g3 ,  Bg2  and  O-O , but it's a very unflexible move order.  The alternative is to play  Nd2  and  e4  immediately and develop the  f1 -bishop to  e2 . But this is considered very passive. So overall, there is not much to learn here. }
2. Nf6{ We just continue logical moves. }
3. Nbd2
3. c5{ Aiming for a setup (and a transposition) to the  KIA lines  via  2.g3 . }( 3...g6 { is also a possible move order but after }4.e4 { , White might think about playing  e4 - e5  on the next move under slightly better circumstances. } )
4. e4
4. Nc6
5. Be2( { The only independent option. White plays an Old-Indian (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 d6 3.Nf3 Nbd7 4.Nc3 e5 { ) with an extra tempo.  However, these days, the opening has no longer a good reputation and the extra tempo doesn't change too much. The main problem of the opening is the inability to create counterplay if the opponent is careful. } )( {  A)  }5.g3 g6 { will transpose to the  KIA lines . } )( {  B)  }5.e5? Nd7 { is pretty much just losing the central pawn. White might exchange it one way or the other but it is still not a good trade if White's only central pawn disappears from the board. } )( {  C)  }5.c3 e5 { will transpose to the text after }6.Be2 { or to the KIA lines as well after }6.g3 { . } )
5. e5( { A good moment to take the center. }5...g6 { is possible but after }6.c3 { , White might have the extra option to play  e4 - e5 , followed by  d3 - d4  next. Let's not allow this. } )
6. O-O
6. Be7{ Not a position that has a lot to do with the Schlechter but Black is objectively already just better. }
7. c3{ The main move. White takes some control over the center and prepares  b2 - b4 . }
7. O-O
8. a3{ The main move to create counterplay on the queenside. }( 8.Re1 { is the alternative but Black can simply keep the tension with }8...Qc7 { or }8...Re8 { but it also looks like a good moment to play }8...d4 { when the rook is pretty useless on  e1 .    In all lines, Black should have the easier game. } )
8. h6{ Just one of many good moves. Black secures the  e6 -square for the bishop without allowing  Ng5  ideas. }
9. b4
9. a6{ A typical position in this line. Black has stopped all counterplay with  b4 - b5  and can eventually even play ... b5  and maybe ... a5  themselves.  Besides that, Black can just improve their pieces first. ... Be6  was one of the reasons why we played ... h6  and ... Qc7  is also a logical move to connect the rooks.  Check out the model game  Bezgodova - Kashlinskaya  to see more of White's struggle. }
