1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. b3{ This move order allows White to take on  f6  and give Black doubled pawns if they go for a Schlechter setup but this is not something that we should be afraid of. The resulting position would be a 'poor man's Trompovsky'. }( { In the Trompovsky (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 { ), }{ White also needs one pawn move until the bishop can be developed to a square where it can take on  f6  but while  d2 - d4  is a very useful move that takes control in the center, the move  b2 - b3  is not only less useful, it can also be a weakening move.  Sometimes, ... Ba3  is possible to disturb the fight for the c-file but also ...  a5 - a4  is a clear hook that can open the position for the side with the bishop pair. } )
2. Nf6{ Against  2.b3 , there is no reason to deviate from our Schlechter setup. }
3. Bb2
3. g6
4. Bxf6{ The only move with independent meaning. }( {  A)  }4.e3 { will be discussed  here . } )( {  B)  }4.g3 { leads to the double fianchetto that can be found  here . } )( {  C)  }4.c4 { can be answered with }4...c6 { which will be discussed via the  1.c4 move order . } )
4. exf6
5. e3
5. Bg7{ Occupying the long diagonal. }
6. d4
6. O-O{ A typical position. White is really vulnerable on the dark squares.  Whenever Nakamura reached this position, he played a quick  g2 - g3 . A smart idea as otherwise ... f6 - f5 - f4  is coming extremely quickly. }( { Nevertheless, the main move is }7.Bd3 { which can only illustrate why  g2 - g3  is so much better. } )
7. Bd3{ This is White's most popular move at the amateur level, but Black's aggressive pawn breaks spoil all the fun for White. }
7. c5( { The most aggressive move. }7...f5 { is similar. }8.O-O c5 { with a lot of pressure against White's center. } )
8. c3{ White should stabilise their structure as much as possible. Opening the long diagonal is just suicide. }( {  A)  }8.dxc5?! f5 9.c3 Nd7∓ { Black will win back the pawn on  c5  and the weakness on  c3  is more concrete than the pressure against  d5 . And, of course, we have the two bishops. }10.b4 a5-+ { only makes it worse. } )( {  B)  }8.O-O { is only giving Black even more ideas. Even the simple }8...cxd4 9.exd4 Bg4 { is better for Black. For example, }10.h3 Bxf3 11.Qxf3 f5 12.c3∓ { is a typical structure. }{ However, the White pawn on  c3  is much more vulnerable than our 'weakness' on  d5  that can simply not be attacked.  We can just play ... Qd6 , ... Nd7 - f6 - e4  and put a rook on the c-file. White is in quite some trouble. } )
8. f5{ Black has an easy set-up. We can go ... Nd7 , ... b6 , ... Bb7 , play ... Qe7  and put the rooks on central files.  With both fianchettoed bishops, White can never really do anything active in the center themselves, as Black's pieces would come even more to life. After that, Black has different slow moves to make progress.  A sample line could be: }
9. O-O
9. Nd7
10. Nbd2
10. b6
11. Qe2{ Hoping for  Be2 - a6  to exchange one of the bishops. }
11. a6{ A nice move to stop White's idea. }
12. Rfd1
12. Bb7{ Now, we go back to our mentioned setup. }
13. Rac1
13. Re8( { A good moment to include this move as   }14...f4 { is now a serious idea. } )
14. Qf1
14. Qe7{ White can't really do anything productive and can only hope that their setup stays solid. Black, on the other hand, has different ideas to improve their position.  We can move forward with ... b5 , or try to win space with ... a5 - a4 . We can regroup our knight,  e4  looks like a nice destination. White is practically in a tough spot. }
