1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. b3{ This move order allows White to take on  f6  and give Black doubled pawns if they go for a Schlechter setup but this is not something that we should be afraid of. The resulting position would be a 'poor man's Trompovsky'. }( { In the Trompovsky (   }1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 { ), }{ White also needs one pawn move until the bishop can be developed to a square where it can take on  f6  but while  d2 - d4  is a very useful move that takes control in the center, the move  b2 - b3  is not only less useful, it can also be a weakening move.  Sometimes, ... Ba3  is possible to disturb the fight for the c-file but also ...  a5 - a4  is a clear hook that can open the position for the side with the bishop pair. } )
2. Nf6{ Against  2.b3 , there is no reason to deviate from our Schlechter setup. }
3. Bb2
3. g6
4. Bxf6{ The only move with independent meaning. }( {  A)  }4.e3 { will be discussed  here . } )( {  B)  }4.g3 { leads to the double fianchetto that can be found  here . } )( {  C)  }4.c4 { can be answered with }4...c6 { which will be discussed via the  1.c4 move order . } )
4. exf6
5. e3
5. Bg7{ Occupying the long diagonal. }
6. d4
6. O-O{ A typical position. White is really vulnerable on the dark squares.  Whenever Nakamura reached this position, he played a quick  g2 - g3 . A smart idea as otherwise ... f6 - f5 - f4  is coming extremely quickly. }( { Nevertheless, the main move is }7.Bd3 { which can only illustrate why  g2 - g3  is so much better. } )
7. g3{ Objectively, the best way to play the position. White keeps the  f4 -square under control and with the bishop on  g2 , White has more pressure against the  d5 -pawn when Black plays ... c5 . }
7. c5{ Even here, it is a good idea to play aggressively against White's center. White's bishop on  g2  puts more pressure on our center, but besides that, our advantages remain.  We will get good pressure against  d4  or along the c-file. }
8. Bg2( { More flexible than the immediate }8.c3 { which has been played in the two games I found with this position - even though the lines can transpose into each other.     A)  For example, }8.c3 b6 9.Bg2 Bg4 { would transpose but Black would get other attractive options as well. }9...Ba6!? { looks like a good way to keep White's king in the center. } )( {  B)  }8.dxc5 { would open up the dark-squared bishop. }8...Qa5+ 9.c3 Qxc5⩱ { The pressure against  c3  is more concrete than White's play against  d5 . We can just play ... f5 , maybe ... Nb8 - d7 - f6 - e4 . } )
8. Bg4{ Increasing the pressure on the  d4 -pawn. If we take on  d4  next, White can no longer recapture with the knight. This would at least keep the d-file half-open. }( { If White doesn't play }9.c3 { , Black will get immediate play in the center. } )
9. c3{ After Black has played ... Bg4 , this looks like a reasonable move to stabilize the  d4 -pawn and get the option to recapture there if needed with the c-pawn. But there are also some drawbacks.  The c-pawn is less flexible than before and the  b1 -knight has problems finding an active role in attacking  d5 . Otherwise, the knight might be developed to  c3  and even be regrouped via  e2  to  f4 . Now, this is not possible. }
9. b6{ Just stabilising the  c5 -pawn. In the next moves, we'll just go ... Nc6 , ... Qd7 , ... Rfd8  and ... Rac8 . Our center is very stable.  Let's show a sample line: }
10. h3{ A reasonable move, trying to win the bishop pair. }
10. Bf5{ Here, there is no reason to give White one of our precious bishops. From  f5 , we might potentially play ... Be4 , a nice outpost so that  d5 -pawn and bishop support each other. True, White might be able to take the bishop then, but if we can go ... dxe4 , we have officially solved the only problem in our position. }
11. O-O
11. Nc6{ Just developing. }
12. Qe2( { Preparing   }13.Rd1 { . } )
12. Qd7( { Part of the setup that I mentioned. With White's rook coming to  d1 , we can also argue that }12...Qe7 { , followed by all the same moves, would also be a very logical choice. } )
13. Rd1
13. Rfd8( { Overprotecting the  d5 -pawn. Let's not get greedy. }13...Bxh3 14.Bxh3 Qxh3 15.dxc5 { wins back the pawn. } )
14. dxc5{ A forcing move, trying to get counterplay against  d5 . Such concrete lines should not be evaluated on general principles only - if it works, it works - but, in general, Black should be happy with these transitions as dynamics in the center will lead to more active bishops. }( 14.Kh2 { allows us to finish our setup with }14...Be4 { or }14...Rac8 { . } )
14. bxc5
15. Ne1{ If White doesn't find a direct way to attack  d5 , their last move would be pretty useless. }
15. d4{ A typical move to open up the position. Black just has the slightly more pleasant position.  Let's not go into the details as this was just a sample line and this concrete position might never appear on the board, but let's point out some instructive points in the Clickables. }( {  A)  The exchange of  d4 -pawn against  h3  is just slightly better for Black. }16.cxd4 Bxh3⩱ { We have no weaknesses anymore and all our pieces are extremely active. } )( {  B)  }16.Bxc6? Qxc6 17.cxd4 cxd4 18.exd4 Bxh3-+ { is similar but much worse for White. Now, both bishops are unopposed, the position is more open and the  d4 -pawn weak. This is simply lost. } )( {  C)  }16.Kh2 { Arguably the best move to protect  h3 . }16...Rac8 { Here, White can actually win a pawn but this is nothing to be afraid of as White has to take on  c6  in order to do so. For example }17.cxd4 cxd4 18.Bxc6? Qxc6 19.exd4 { is just much better for Black.    Concretely, we have the tactic }19...Bxh3! 20.Kxh3 Qh1+ 21.Kg4 h5+ 22.Kf4 Bh6# { but even without this trick, Black would have more than enough compensation for the pawn after a simple move such as }19...h5 { .    In this line, White can often not develop in the most straightforward way possible as they have to make many moves to keep their pawn structure intact. Combined with the factor that Black has the bishop pair, it is a typical factor that Black will be much better if the position opens up early.    A sacrificed pawn is the least of our concerns! } )
