1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. b4( { A very rare move that has some resemblance with the Orang-Utan   }1.b4 { . Black has different good responses against it. } )
2. Nf6( { We can even go for the Schlechter here. If you are not happy with these lines for whatever reason, let me just point out two additional options.     A)  }2...Bg4 { is a good way to create objectively good counter-chances while also creating some imbalances. We are ready to take on  f3  and give White doubled pawns.  The position is a reversed Trompovsky where White has touched their b-pawn for pretty unknown reasons. } )( {  B)  }2...e5 3.Nxe5 Bxb4 { is another typical approach. White has one more additional center pawn but there is no good way to use them to really occupy the center while Black has strong influence and can put pressure along the e-file. } )
3. Bb2
3. g6
4. e3{ The normal way to develop the light-squared bishop in order to gain at least some control with pawns in the center. }( 4.Bxf6?! exf6 { is even worse than with the pawn on  b3  because  b4  is already hanging and Black can use the pawn to open the queenside with ... a5 . } )
4. Bg7{ In the Grünfeld Slav main lines, it is a typical idea for White to push the queenside pawns forward to gain space. Typically, White has all 4 pawns from a to d-file ready to take the space.  With the b-pawn as a lone wolf, it feels more like a target than an improved version. }
5. c4{ A move to get more pawns on the queenside rolling. }
5. c6{ No need to deviate from our typical response. }
6. Be2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. dxc4{ A principled way to play. As in other lines in the course, I think it is a good idea to use White's pawns to fight for the initiative on the queenside. }
8. Bxc4
8. b5{ Pushing the bishop back while also winning space. }
9. Be2( { After }9.Bb3 { , we can see a direct advantage of White not having a pawn on  d4 . After }9...a5 10.bxa5 c5! { , we can pick up the a-pawn later but have already mobilised our queenside pawns. } )
9. a5
10. bxa5
10. Qxa5{ Black will soon be able to play ... c5  with active counterplay. }
