1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way, we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. g3{ The Reti-Opening. White just builds their house on the kingside with  Bg2  and  O-O  and keeps a lot of flexibility.     White can still transpose to the main lines with a quick  c2 - c4  and/or  d2 - d4  but they can also play a reversed King's Indian with  d2 - d3  or even play something completely different such as a double fianchetto with  b3  and  Bb2 . }
2. Nf6( 2...g6 { is a clever variation. This move order has the advantage that }3.Bg2 Bg7 { is now preparing  ...e7-e5 . For many White players, this is reason enough to play }4.d4 { when }4...Nf6 { will lead to positions from our  1.d4 part .    Nevertheless, if White just ignores it and plays   }4.O-O { , I think it is much more consistent with the rest of the repertoire to continue with }4...Nf6 { instead of }4...e5 { . }{ So, the 'threat' of ... e5  would be some kind of bluff.     In this regard, it doesn't make a big difference for us and the move order 2... Nf6  feels more consistent with other lines. } )
3. Bg2
3. g6
4. b3{ If White is aiming for a double fianchetto, they usually play  b2 - b3  before Black's bishop is on  g7 . This stops all kinds of discoveries. }
4. Bg7
5. Bb2
5. O-O{ As in all  g3 -lines, we just start with ... Bg7  and ... O-O . }
6. O-O( { This is the only independent move order. If White plays }6.c4 { , we can transpose with }6...c6 { to  this variation  from the  1.c4  move order. } )
6. c5{ White had their chance to transpose to other lines with an earlier  c2 - c4 , now it is Black who is fighting for extra space in the center. }
7. c4{ This is White's most popular move. White provokes ... d5 - d4  which locks in the bishop on  b2  but White wants to undermine Black's center immediately. }( {  A)  The second most popular move }7.d4 { leads to  this variation . } )( {  B)  If White starts with }7.d3 { , the easiest move is }7...Nc6 { .     B1)  }8.Ne5 { This is a typical move, for example also known from the Queen's Indian, to exchange a pair of knights before Black prevents this with ... Qc7  or even ... d5 - d4 . }8...Nxe5 9.Bxe5 Be6 { , followed by ... Qd7  and ideas like ... Bh3 . Black has a comfortable position. }{     B2)  }8.Nbd2?! { Going for a King's Indian Attack with a bishop on  b2  is good for Black.    Not only can Black eventually play ... d5 - d4  in some positions and shut the bishop down completely, the bishop might even be a target for tactical shots. }8...Qc7!⩱ { Stopping  Ne5  and we can also play ... e7 - e5  next if we want. }9.e4?! { It's hard to find another logical move that makes sense in White's setup, but as we will see, this allows some tactics. }9...dxe4! { Other moves are also comfortable, but here, White is in concrete trouble. }10.dxe4 ( { ( }10.Nxe4?! Nxe4 11.Bxg7 Nxf2!∓ { wins a pawn. }{ ) } )10...Rd8! { Black is threatening ... Nxe4 . But not only because of the pinned  d2 -knight, but also because of the loose  b2 -bishop. }11.Qe2?! ( { (Instead, White has to play a passive queen move like }11.Qc1 { . But White's pieces are just misplaced. Something like }11...a5 { , followed by ... a4  is an easy plan to continue. Black is much better.) } )11...Nxe4! { wins a pawn! }12.Bxg7 Nxd2 { doesn't help White. } )
7. d4{ If Black can consolidate the space advantage, we will be much better. }
8. e3{ A typical move to attack Black's center, but here it is not leading to a lot of pressure. }
8. Nc6{ This overprotects the  d4 -pawn and is also fighting against all kinds of  b3 - b4  ideas. White will get a Benoni position with a misplaced bishop on  b2 . }
9. exd4
9. cxd4{ Black's has different ways of playing this position but an absolute standard plan that has been proven quite successful in practice is ... Nd7 , to open up the bishop and prepare both ... e5  and ... Nc5 .      c5  is an ideal square for the knight as it attacks the  d3 -pawn and also supports breaks with ... e5 - e4  in the future. ... a5  is a standard move to secure the knight on  c5  and after that, we'll go ... Bf5  to create even more pressure against  d3 .     If everything goes according to plan, our space advantage will give us a nice advantage.  I will just show a sample line to illustrate the basic ideas. }
10. d3( { Always part of White's setup. Some players prefer to start with }10.Re1 { to have the additional option to go }-- 11.Ne5 { but as our plan is to go   }10...Nd7 { anyways, this move order doesn't win anything. } )
10. Nd7{ The start of the easy plan. }
11. Re1{ Let's go with this as the sample line. It is a typical move and it is also fighting against Black's plan to bring the knight to  c5 . Both,  Bb2 - a3  as well as  Nb1 - d2 - e4  can be ideas to exchange this knight.  As White has a big space disadvantage, they are happy to exchange minor pieces as it will be easier to find good squares for the pieces afterwards. }( 11.Na3 { is not necessarily bad but it allows Black to attack the  d3 -pawn with tempo. }11...Nc5 12.Nc2 Bf5⩱ { White is forced to spend a passive move defending  d3  or they have to sacrifice it.     Both options are not completely convincing. } )
11. a5{ A nice prophylactic move, securing the  c5 -outpost. }( 11...Nc5 12.Ba3 { is White's idea.  b3 - b4  is an idea but also just exchanging the knight can help White's position. } )
12. Nbd2( { White is ready to answer }12...Nc5 { with }13.Ne4 { . } )
12. Re8{ Just a useful move, preparing ... e5  but also going out of the  a3 - f8  diagonal. We have some kind of standoff.  White wants to answer ... Nc5  with  Ne4  to exchange a pair of knights. However, White cannot play this move earlier, because it would allow Black to play ... f5  with tempo.  As White cannot really do anything active, Black can play patient and just improve their position slowly a little bit with every move. ... h6 , ... e5 , ... Qc7 , maybe ... Ra6  are typical moves to slowly improve.    If you want to see a more fiery way of playing the position check out the model game Enders - Shabalov, Dresden 2018 -  see here  - that illustrates some important concepts better than 1000 words! }
