1. Nf3( { Against }1.Nf3 { , we are pretty free in our move order. As White is not supporting  e2-e4  in any way we can reach the variations in this chapter both via }1...d5 { as well as }1...Nf6 { .    I decided to go with }1...d5 { as the main move order in this chapter as I believe that there is nothing more natural for a Slav player than to put the d-pawn in the center as soon as possible! } )
1. d5
2. g3{ The Reti-Opening. White just builds their house on the kingside with  Bg2  and  O-O  and keeps a lot of flexibility.     White can still transpose to the main lines with a quick  c2 - c4  and/or  d2 - d4  but they can also play a reversed King's Indian with  d2 - d3  or even play something completely different such as a double fianchetto with  b3  and  Bb2 . }
2. Nf6( 2...g6 { is a clever variation. This move order has the advantage that }3.Bg2 Bg7 { is now preparing  ...e7-e5 . For many White players, this is reason enough to play }4.d4 { when }4...Nf6 { will lead to positions from our  1.d4 part .    Nevertheless, if White just ignores it and plays   }4.O-O { , I think it is much more consistent with the rest of the repertoire to continue with }4...Nf6 { instead of }4...e5 { . }{ So, the 'threat' of ... e5  would be some kind of bluff.     In this regard, it doesn't make a big difference for us and the move order 2... Nf6  feels more consistent with other lines. } )
3. Bg2
3. g6
4. O-O{ The most flexible move. }
4. Bg7
5. d3{ This move indicates that White wants to play a 'King's Indian Attack'. They stay flexible with their pawns and prepare either  e2 - e4  or  c2 - c4 . }( { At this point in the course, we have pretty much looked at all other moves via transposition. }5.d4 { transposes to  these lines , }5.c4 c6 { to  those , }5.b3 {  here . } )
5. O-O
6. Nbd2{ In the King's Indian, Black players have tested pretty much every halfway reasonable setup against the fianchetto variation over the decades. Here, White is playing these setups with an extra tempo which gives them even more liberties.  It is impossible to look at all possibilities but let's look at White's most principled way of playing by preparing  e2 - e4 . One factor in this position - and one reason why the fianchetto variation in the King's Indian is so popular - is that it is very easy to play some moves. After ... c5 , ... Nc6 , ... e5 , Black simply has more space and has many moves to improve the position bit by bit (... h6 , ... Qc7 , ... Be6 , putting the rooks on  d8  and  e8 ). }
6. c5{ Grabbing space with the c-pawn is a very principled reaction if White doesn't force us to play ... c6 . I think this option is very much in the spirit of the other lines. }
7. e4{ White's main move, finally putting a pawn in the center. }
7. Nc6{ We just keep developing. }
8. Re1{ White has other moves as well but this is the best move suited against our setup with ... e5 . White wants to create pressure against the  e5 -pawn as soon as possible. }( { Against other moves, such as }8.c3 { , we can also simply play }8...e5 { . } )
8. e5{ Taking as much space in the center as possible. }
9. exd5
9. Nxd5
10. Nc4{ The main move. White attacks  e5 . }
10. f6{ The modern main move to protect the  e5 -pawn. }( 10...Re8 { used to be more popular but }11.Ng5! { is slightly annoying with ideas connected with  Nxf7  and  Qf3 . Black is objectively fine, but we will be provoked to play some ugly moves here as well. } )( { After }10...f6 { , White has achieved the maximum they can hope for in this line.  At least they forced us to spend a tempo with the f-pawn, which is not really a move we would like to play. Nevertheless, Black has a nice space advantage as a long-term factor and White has no easy way to exploit Black's newly created weakness.  In the next few moves, we will simply play ... Be6 , ... Qd7 , ... Rad8  with a nice position. } )
11. Nfd2{ The idea to bring the knight to  e4  as quickly as possible is the most aggressive option. }( { Many games followed up with a slower approach such as }11.c3 Be6 12.a4 Qd7 { when neither side has a clear way to break through but Black is just fine with their space advantage. } )
11. Be6
12. Ne4{ Attacking the pawn on  c5 . On the next move, White wants to go  f2 - f4 . }
12. Qe7( { Stabilising both the  c5 -pawn as well as the  e6 -bishop. }12...b6 { is the alternative but }13.f4 { looks more annoying here. We cannot take because of }13...exf4? 14.Nxc5! bxc5 15.Rxe6+- { . } )
13. f4{ White should follow up aggressively. Otherwise, Black can just make some stabilising moves and eventually kick the knight away with ... f5 . }( { For example, }13.c3 Rad8 14.a4?! h6! { is preparing }-- 15...f5 { when White's knights jumps look pretty counterproductive. } )
13. exf4{ This was played in the game  Venkatesh - Sethuraman  and is the trickiest move for White. }( { The engine very slightly prefers }13...b5!? { but White can simplify the position easily with }14.Ne3 Rfd8 15.Nxd5 Bxd5 16.fxe5 Nxe5 17.Qe2= { which is okay for Black but also doesn't look too problematic for White. } )
14. Ned6( { White has to be precise to keep the balance.    In the just mentioned game, White played }14.gxf4 { and was worse after }14...Rad8 { that stopped White's tricks for the moment. } )( { After }14.Ned6 { , White is threatening }-- 15.Bxd5 { . } )
14. Ne3{ An elegant solution, White has to give up their dark-squared bishop. }
15. Bxe3
15. fxe3
16. Rxe3
16. Ne5{ Blocking the e-file and taking away all ideas with  Bxc6 . White's knights are stepping on each other's toes. Next, we will just unpin with ... Qc7 . }
17. Nxb7( { Taking the pawn looks like the only critical move to me. But not with }17.Bxb7?? Rad8-+ { what simply wins material as  d6  is hanging and  b7  potentially as well. } )
17. Qc7{ Keeping an eye on all retreating squares for the knight. White has different ways to keep the extra pawn but Black will develop nice compensation once we eventually can play ... f5  and open up the  g7 -bishop.  For example: }( {  A)  }18.Nbd6 Rad8 { is already not ideal for White. There are problems on the d-file. There is nothing better than }19.Nxe5 Rxd6 { when Black has different ideas to proceed. }{ White has to retreat with the knight, and we can go ... Qb6 , ... c4 , ... f5  with a lot of pressure on White's position. } )( {  B)  }18.Nba5 Rae8 { Black is ready to go  ...f5 . }19.Nxe5 Qxa5 { This is one of White's safer options. White can reach a position with opposite-coloured bishops and an extra pawn but Black will have enough compensation because our king is much safer and we also have pressure against White's queenside. Both after     B1)  }20.Nc6 Qb6 21.Rxe6 Rxe6 22.Bd5 Kh8 23.Bxe6 Qxc6 { , followed by  ...f5  or     B2)  }20.Nc4 Bxc4 21.Rxe8 Rxe8 22.dxc4 h5!? { Hiding the king on  h7 , we play ... f5  next. } )( {  C)  }18.Nxe5? fxe5-+ { just loses the knight on  b7 . There is no way back! } )( {  D)  If White doesn't retreat the knight immediately, Black can take on  c4  when the  b7 -horsie is stuck. For example: }18.Qe2 Bxc4 19.dxc4 Rab8 { The engine claims that White is okay after }20.Rb3 { but with the dumb knight and ... f5  coming, this should be a fun position for Black. } )
