1. d4{ This game nicely illustrates Black's counter chances in lines where White plays an early  Lc1 - f4  and lets Black take the pawn on  c4 . }( { The game actually began with }1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 c6 3.d4 d5 { . } )
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bf4{ As mentioned in the  introduction , this move is very rare on the titled player level. Black does just have an easy game after grabbing the pawn. }
4. dxc4
5. a4
5. Nd5
6. Bg3
6. Qa5( { Black creates counterplay against White's position. So far, this is what we have seen in  chapter 2 . The best move is actually   }7.e4 Nxc3 8.Qd2! { to force Black to take on  c3  immediately.  White plays a more passive move to protect the knight and this horribly backfires. } )
7. Qc1
7. e5( { A very energetic way that uses the absence of White's dark-squared bishop on the queenside.   }8...Bb4 { is a massive threat besides the simply }8...exd4 { . } )
8. e3( 8.e4 exd4! 9.exd5 cxd5-+ { is also just hopeless. Even if we simply take on  c3  on the next move, we are two pawns up with full control over the center. } )
8. Bb4{ Black has the extra pawn and the initiative. White has to go even more defensive to parry Black's threats. }
9. Nge2
9. exd4{ Opening up the center to make the most of White's fragile setup. }
10. exd4
10. O-O{ It is not easy to recommend a move for White. White is completely tied up and Black's attacking pieces are on very nice outposts.  Note that White's pawn on  a4  makes sure that the  b4 -square is forever in Black's hands. }
11. Qc2( { Preparing   }12.Rc1 { so that the  e2 -knight can finally move. } )
11. Nd7
12. Rc1
12. N7b6{ Black just goes for the  a4 -pawn. Easy enough! }( { I can imagine that other players might have played }13...Re8 { to keep White's pieces tied down. } )
13. Nf4
13. Qxa4{ Black just collects the material and White has still an underdeveloped setup. }
14. Be2
14. Qxc2
15. Rxc2
15. Bf5
16. Rd2{ This loses more material but White is simply completely lost. }( 16.Rc1 { also doesn't help. }16...Rfe8 { and White can't even castle as Black could exchange both knights and then take the bishop. } )
16. Nxc3
