1. d4{ A game similar to the last one. Besides some instructive moves, it also shows the psychological problems of the White side.  After sacrificing the pawn, White often has the feeling that they 'have to do something'. While engines stay objective in these situations and just play the best moves - even if it means accepting a slightly worse position with not much happening in the next 10 moves, a human will very likely try to justify the sacrifice through some concrete ideas - even though they might instinctively know that those might be suicidal. }
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bf4
4. dxc4
5. e3
5. b5
6. a4
6. Qb6{ If we don't have ... Bb4 , this is usually my  recommendation  if White attacks the  b5 -pawn. }
7. axb5{ A very bad move. With the a- and c-pawn gone, Black will no longer have doubled pawns on the c-file and a bishop on  b7  will be very powerful.  Also, now Black's pawn structure is just a very healthy one with no weaknesses and already very far advanced. White's idea is the following move that tries to attack Black's pawns immediately.  But we have similar tactics as in the last game. }
7. cxb5
8. b3{ Consequent but bad. White will be extremely weak on the dark squares on the queenside. How do we exploit it? }
8. e5{ The typical strike. With ... Bb4  coming, White is simply just lost. }
9. dxe5
9. Bb4
10. Rc1
10. Ne4{ Black is increasing the pressure. }
11. Nge2
11. O-O{ Black's main advantage is now his lead in development. The right way to continue is to play as energetic as possible and bring the pieces into the game quickly. }
12. bxc4
12. Rd8{ From here on, the model game deviates from the real game. In that game, it took Black 8 more moves to bring his knight and bishop into the game.  Way too slow and White got chances even though Black prevailed in the end. The right strategy is to strike the iron while it is hot. }( 12...bxc4 { Happened in the game. }13.f3 Nc5 14.Nd4 Qa5 15.Qc2 Ba6 16.Kf2 Rc8 17.Nd5 Nb3 18.Nxb3 Qxd5 19.Nd4 Nd7 20.Qa4 Bd2 21.Rc2 Nc5 22.Qa2 Bb4 23.Be2 Rab8 24.Rd1 Rb6 25.Nf5 Qe6 26.Nd6 Rd8 27.Rd4 Nd3+ 28.Kf1 Bc5 29.Nxc4 Bxd4 30.Nxb6 Qxb6 31.Rd2 Bxe3 { 0 - 1 } )
13. Qc2{ There is nothing better. }( 13.Qb3 Nc5! { and the check on  d3  comes. } )
13. Bf5{ All kinds of discoveries are in the air. }
14. Qa2
14. Na6{ Black's last minor piece joins the attack. White has no defence. }
15. f3
15. Nac5{ This would be a good moment for White to resign. }
16. fxe4
16. Nd3+
17. Kd1
17. Bxc3{ is just one of many easy wins. White cannot recapture because of 18... Nb4 + and some discovery will cost White decisive material anyway. }
