5. Bg7
6. Qb3{ A move that we have seen in several positions throughout this course but here not really effective. The queen doesn't apply too much pressure on our structure. }
6. O-O
7. Be2
7. dxc4{ A very nice decision to create counterplay on the queenside. }( 7...e6 { , followed by ... b6  would lead to positions similar to the Chinese Recipe chapter and is also a very reasonable way to develop naturally without losing the  b7 -pawn. } )
8. Bxc4
8. b5
9. Be2
9. a5
10. O-O
10. Bf5{ A nice move, stopping  e3 - e4 . So far, we are following  this variation  from chapter 3. Why is Black's queenside play here such a good option?      1)  First of all, a lot of moves come with tempo. White's light-squared bishop had already moved before we took on  c4  but even if we decide to advance even further - either with ...  a4  or ... b4 , both these moves would win additional time.      2)  But another important factor can be seen if we think about White's options. I would say, there are two main ideas how White might exploit our last moves.      A)  White can prove that their majority in the center can be used to restrict Black's active's play or (even better) the pawns can be used to steamroll Black in the center.      B)  White can prove that Black's queenside structure is vulnerable. Especially, the  c6 -pawn might come to mind as a backwards pawn that is on an open file. However, neither of these options looks dangerous.  Black's control over the  e4 -square makes it extremely hard to achieve  e3 - e4 , not only but also because  Nf3 - h4  can be answered with ... Be6  and with tempo.     Plan B looks also very far away. The  c3 -knight is blocking the c-file, and the  c1 -bishop is still blocking this square for one of White's rooks. It will take a while before White could ever dream of pressure along the c-file - and in the meantime, Black will have done something with his initiative. }
11. Bd2{ A logical move, developing while also preparing to put a rook on  c1 . }
11. a4{ This is certainly an idea even though I would guess that this tempo move does not run away and we might even use the queen on  b3  to have ... Be6  with tempo when White plays  Nh4 . }( {  A)  }11...Nbd7 { followed by }-- ...Qb8 { looks like a good way to develop flexible and also prepare a quick }-- ...e5 { with counterplay. } )( {  B)  }11...Qd6 { , followed by }-- ...Nbd7 { might be an even more active way to go for the same plan. } )
12. Qd1
12. Nbd7
13. Nh4{ White is trying to break Black's control over the  e4 -square. }( 13.Rc1 { is another flexible move but after }13...Re8 { or }13...Qb8 { , White should most like still go for this move to force the bishop to  e6  before Black can play ...  e5 . } )
13. Be6
14. e4{ A bad mistake. The exchange of  e4 -pawn against  a4 -pawn doesn't end well for White. Black's pieces are just much more active than White's. }( { Objectively, White should already think about offering a repetition with }14.Nf3 { .    }14.Qc2 { , followed by  Rfc1  looks like a better plan if White wants to keep the game going. For the moment, Black can neither play ... c5  nor ... e5 .     Black is doing absolutely fine and for example }14...Qb8 { and ... Rc8  is a good setup to support all queenside pawns while simultaneously still keeping an eye on the ... e5 -break. } )
14. b4
15. Nxa4
15. Qa5{ A nice in-between move to protect the  b4 -pawn before we take on  e4 . }
16. b3( 16.e5 { seems to be slightly better even though still not convincing. }16...Ne4 17.b3 { Here, }17...c5 { is a typical move to just undermine White's position but we can even play }17...Nxe5! 18.dxe5?! Rfd8-+ { to win back the piece. } )
16. Nxe4{ Black's pieces are all centralized while White's knights are on the rim, the bishops on  d2  and  e2  are passive and  d4  is hanging. It is not overexaggerated to speak of a winning position for Black. }
17. Rc1
17. Rfd8{ Black plays for some fancy tactics to activate his pieces. }( 17...Bxd4-+ { should also be simply good. } )
18. Rxc6
18. Ne5{ A fancy move even though not strictly necessary. }( 18...Bxd4 { would also be overwhelmingly for Black. All our pieces are on good squares and White has also problems with the pin along the d-file. } )
19. Rc2( 19.Rxe6 fxe6 { was apparently White's best option even though this is an exchange deficit for not very much. } )
19. Rxd4( { Black is threatening   }20...Nxd2 21.Rxd2 Rxh4 { as well as the simple   }20...Rad8 { .    White finds a way to hang in the game but the game is already lost. } )
20. Nf3
20. Nxf3+
21. Bxf3
21. Bf5{ A logical move to set up some discoveries. }
22. Qc1
22. Nxd2
23. Rxd2
23. Rc8
24. Qd1
24. Qd8{ A strong move. White avoided the loss of material but Black will install his bishop on  d4  from where it will completely dominate White's position.  Especially the knight on  a4  will be stuck. }
25. Rxd4
25. Bxd4{ White has no active moves, ... Rc2  is coming, the bishop can be stabilised with ... e5  and Black can just slowly advance his pawn majority.     Would you believe that Stockfish evaluates this already as minus 7? There is no forcing way to win material but it is quite telling that Black didn't even use another plan than exchanging everything besides the bishop on  d4  and the knight on  e4 . You can either click through the full following 23 moves or just click on the last position to see what happened. }
