8. Qa5{ So far, we are following one of the  main lines  of chapter 4. Now, White already committed a serious inaccuracy. }
9. cxd5{ The idea to combine this move with  Be5  to neutralise the butcher on  g7  is quite typical but here it is not working. White is quite far behind in development and Black will happily use the activity that he gets by taking on  d5 . }
9. Nxd5
10. Be5{ This was White's idea. }
10. Bxe5{ A very pragmatic solution in a rapid game. Black plays for positional pressure. }( 10...Nb4!? 11.Qc1 Bxe5 12.Nxe5 Bf5!? { is an attempt to rely mainly on piece activity but is not better and also makes the game much more complicated. } )
11. Nxe5
11. Qxc5{ Black is already looking at some discoveries against the knight on  e5 . }( {   }12...Nb4 { or }12...Nxe3 { are obvious threats. } )
12. Nc4{ A natural move but not best. }( {  A)  }12.Nf3 Nxc3 { is what White wanted to avoid. White will suffer from a bad structure until the end of the game. For example: }13.Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14.bxc3 Nd7∓  )( {  B)  }12.Nd3 { was the best move. It is a pretty bad square as it blocks the bishop and is just standing in the way on the d-file but at least White wins a tempo and can play }12...Qc6 13.Rc1 { to avoid the doubled pawns. Still, Black can create some pressure for example with }13...Bf5!? { but White avoids clear weaknesses, } )
12. Bf5{ Provoking  e3 - e4 . }( 12...Be6 { Black can also develop without any complications. }13.Be2 Rc8∓ { is also creating quite a lot of pressure along the c-file. } )
13. Qb3{ Now, Black executes an easy positional plan. }( 13.e4 { was the critical move. }13...Nxc3 14.exf5 Nd5 15.fxg6 hxg6 { White's underdeveloped set-up with so many open central files looks indeed quite menacing. The engine claims that }16.O-O-O { ⩱ }{ with the idea to hide the king on  b1  and start a quick counter-attack on the kingside next is reducing Black's advantage but that is obviously a very creative solution to the problems of the position. } )
13. Nxc3
14. Qxc3{ For the moment, White still has avoided all the weaknesses but with the king still in the center, White has to prioritize developing and soon, Black will play ... b5  and ... Qxc3 . }
14. Nc6{ Black develops before playing ... b5 . There is no need to rush. }( { The immediate }14...b5 { is certainly also not bad. }15.Nd2 Qxc3 16.bxc3 a6 { Black has a pleasant endgame even though White can try to play }17.c4! { to exchange the pawn weakness immediately. } )
15. Be2( {  A)  A move like }15.Rc1?! { would ignore all the concrete problems that one side typically has when being underdeveloped. }15...Nb4! { is just a very strong idea to invade via  a2 . } )( {  B)  Unpinning is also not working. }15.Qb3 Nb4! { is still a massive threat with the idea to get in via  c2 . ... Rfd8  and ... Rac8  might prepare even more knight jumps on the central squares. } )
15. Rfd8
16. O-O
16. b5{ Only now that White's king is castled, Black goes for the advantageous endgame. The king on  g1  is certainly not better in an endgame than the king on  e1 . }
17. Na3
17. Qxc3
18. bxc3
18. a6{ This endgame is an absolute nightmare for White even though the rest of the game is still very instructive. }
