12. Rc8{ We have reached this position in the theoretical part of the course -  see here . I found the following game extremely impressive as Black won, well, with black, against a 250 elo points higher-rated opponent.  Black already has a very flexible position with ideal support for both breaks ... e5  and ... c5 , but it is still interesting to see how quickly White came into concrete problems. }
13. Qb3{ White gets out of the c-file and prevents ... c5  by attacking  b7  - but only for one move. }
13. Qc7{ Black protects the pawn and is now ready for ... c5 . }
14. Bd2
14. c5{ White has many options but obviously he has no interest in taking on  c5 . And if Black takes on  d4 , they might have to accept an IQP position with not that many dynamics. The bishop pair would give White compensation for the pawn weakness but, still, Black should be very comfortable. }
15. Nb5
15. Qb8
16. cxd5
16. Nxd5{ White went for two forcing moves but it didn't change anything about the general problems. }
17. Nc3{ This is a pretty weird move. The knight goes back to where it came from. }
17. N5b6{ Black plays a good, solid positional move. We are threatening 18... c4  but taking on  d4  is obviously our typical positional idea. }( 17...cxd4! { was a good tactical move. }18.Nxd5?! ( { ( }18.exd4 Bxd4! { wins a pawn, once again because of some tactics. }19.Nxd5? Nc5 20.Qc4 Bxb2! { a1 and  d5  are hanging while White's other pieces are also awkwardly placed. A messier position than the one in the game, but certainly an extremely good one! ) } )18...Nc5! { is a strong in-between move. Black will take on  d5  next and White has problems protecting  d3  and  d4  simultaneously. } )
18. Bb5{ White tries to annoy Black with some pins. }
18. cxd4{ Black executes his main plan. }
19. exd4
19. Bxd4{ This is a little bit greedy but even though it works out in the game. Moves like 19... a6  or 19... Red8  to get out of the pin are just good positional moves. }
20. Bxd7{ White goes for a continuation that gets Black's dark-squared bishop. In the resulting position, Black has to be careful not to lose control over the dark squares, but in the game, Black is up to the task and slowly kills White's initiative. }( 20.Bh6! { was the best move for White. Black has two hanging pieces on the d-file so }20...Bxc3 { is pretty much forced. After }21.Bxd7! Nxd7 22.Rxd7 { White is slightly better. With  c3  and  b7  hanging, White will regain their pawn and the pressure against  a7  and  f7  promises a slight edge. } )
