11. Bb7{ We have reached a typical position from the  Chinese Recipe chapter  when White plays normal developing moves and doesn't go for anything forcing on the queenside. }
12. cxd5{ This exchange is frequently played in similar positions. White is playing for the fact that Black has a weaker queenside compared to normal Carlsbad structures where Black's b-pawn is on  b7 . Nevertheless, White's minor pieces are not particularly active in this version and I find it impressive how Black simply stabilised their queenside and then slowly but surely starts counterplay on the other side of the board.  The following plans are extremely typical for this variation. }
12. exd5
13. b4{ White takes control over the  c5 -square but is also preparing further advances on the queenside with  a2 - a4 - a4  or  b4 - b5  at the right moment to open up the position. }
13. a6{ A very typical move. Black is stopping  b4 - b5  but it is actually also preparing ... b6 - b5  at the right moment.  Black often closes down the queenside completely in this line. }( 13...Nd7 { is the engine's favourite to begin with as it makes it harder for White to play  Nf3 - e5 . }14.Ne5?! ( { ( }14.a4 a6 15.Ne5 { would be the right move order for White. The pawn on  b6  is slightly more vulnerable which actually makes a difference. }15...Nxe5? ( { ( }15...b5! { would lead to a position similar to the game. ) } )16.dxe5 Qe7 17.f4 f6 18.Bd4± { If the b-pawn falls, Black has problems on the dark-squares. ) } )14...Nxe5 15.dxe5 Qe7 { would be a problem for White. }16.f4 f6⩱  )
14. Ne5{ It is not easy to find a plan without this active move. Black's play is extremely clear:     ... Nd7 , then ... b5  to block the queenside. Eventually, playing ... Nd7 - b6 - c4  or just building up on the kingside with ... Re8 , ... Nd7 - f6 - e4 . Actually, we might regroup both our bishops as neither of them is really participating in the game if we want to play on the kingside. ... Bg7 - f8 - d6  and ... Bb7 - c8  and then potentially going to  f5  looks like an idea.     Black's play looks slow but if White finds no breakthrough on the queenside, Black can just improve his position bit by bit. }
14. Nd7
15. Nd3{ The knight controls a nice number of central squares on  d3 . Nevertheless, White's 'normal-looking moves' allow Black to take over the initiative eventually so it might be worth it to look for alternatives. }( 15.f4!? { might be better even though the resulting weakness on  e3  makes this a very double-edged position. }15...Qe7 { , followed by ... Rae8  looks like a reasonable response. But I think it is also worth noting that the engine recommends the immediate }15...b5!? { , followed by }-- ...Nb6 { - a setup that Black will choose in this game as well. } )
15. Re8
16. a4
16. b5{ A great move. You should definitely remember it! Black has to close the queenside to win enough time to counter on the other side. }
17. Bg4{ A tough decision. This allows Black's knight to come to  b6 . }( 17.a5!? { is Stockfish's suggestion to stop this but now White cannot even open the a-file anymore. }17...Nf6 18.Nc5 Bc8 19.Bd3 Ra7 { , followed by ... Rae7  would be a typical sequence for Black to regroup. The game should objectively be fine for Black but I always have the feeling that Black can improve his pieces much more easily than White. } )
17. Nb6
18. Nc5
18. Bc8{ The bishop on  b7  was extremely passive. It did its job in the opening but - even if it's not attacked - you usually have to regroup it in the middlegame. }
19. Be2{ With so many central pawns on the light-squares, White wants to keep the light-squared bishops on the board. }
19. Ra7{ A typical move. }
20. a5{ Forcing the knight to make a decision but it will happily jump to  c4 . }
20. Nc4
21. Bxc4( 21.e4!? { is a typical move to undermine the knight. Nevertheless, after }21...dxe4 22.Bxc4 bxc4 { and ... Qd5 , Black is extremely solid on the light squares and should be slightly better. } )
21. bxc4
22. Qf3( 22.e4! { was actually the best move to transpose to  21.e4 . Now, Black can take over the initiative. } )
22. Bf8( { The immediate }22...f5! { was strong to prevent White from playing  e3 - e4 . } )
23. Rfe1( { This was the last chance to play }23.e4 { . }23...dxe4 24.Nxe4 Bf5 { , followed by ... Qd5  is very comfortable for Black but not more. } )
23. f5{ Now, White really has no counterplay and Black can freely prepare an attack on the kingside. }
24. Qg3
24. Bd6{ From now on, Black simply improves his kingside. }( { Even the aggressive }24...g5!? { was already possible. White really can't do anything active. } )
25. f4
