35. Be7{ The bishop can come to  h4  but it also prepares ... g5 . With Black being so active, White is pretty much lost. Unfortunately, Black chose the wrong moment to strike with ... g5 . }
36. Ke2
36. Bf6( 36...g5! { would have been a strong move. }37.fxg5 f4! { Black sacrifices two pawns for now but our light-squared bishop joins the game, the  c3 -pawn can advance and White is still tied down. For example, }38.exf4 c3 39.Bc1 Bxc5 40.bxc5 Bf5-+ { with ideas like ... Re8 + , ... Be4  or ... Bd3 . White can't do anything. } )
37. Kd1
37. R8h4( 37...g5! { was still strong. }38.fxg5 Be7-+ { The bishop will go to  d6 , Black will win the  h2 -pawn and White's weakness on  g5  will also fall sooner or later. } )
38. Be1{ Now, White's bishop will come to  g3  when the kingside is stabilised. }
38. Rg4
39. Bg3
39. g5{ Too late. White is able to create a blockade on the  f4 -square. }
40. Rf1{ Now, it is actually impossible for Black to break through and the game ended in a draw after a long fight. }
