11. Ne8{ We have reached this position in the  theoretical part  of the course. Black's last move is a nice manoeuvre to bring the knight to  d6  and have more options to get rid of the  e5 -knight.  We can play ... f6  but we also have better options of exchanging it. }
12. b4{ A typical move. White plays as in the last game  Wang - Bu . }
12. Nd7{ We are challenging the knight on  e5 . }
13. Nxd7( 13.f4!? { is a typical move to strengthen the knight. Nevertheless. }13...Nxe5 14.fxe5 f6⇆ { is promising nice counterplay as White's structure gets destroyed. } )
13. Qxd7
14. b5{ Here, White achieves the  b5 -break. Interestingly enough, the game shows that it is still not clear if this transition is really advisable for White. }
14. Nd6{ A good square for the knight. Potentially it can go to  e4  or  c4 . }
15. Qb3{ Now, it is Black who takes over the initiative in the center. The most obvious way to avoid what will happen in the game is the exchange on  c6 . }( 15.bxc6 Bxc6 { Let's just point out that Black won't start a checkmating attack here anytime soon but despite Black having more pawn islands than White, there are still good reasons to find Black's structure very appealing. We have a nice queenside majority and with moves like ... Rfc8 , ... b5  and ... Nc4  , Black gets active play on that side of the board. } )
15. c5{ A good moment to strike. Black has pressure against the  d4 -pawn. White has nothing better than to take on  c5 . }
16. dxc5
16. bxc5{ In the rest of the game, we will see the dynamics that the hanging pawns on  d5  and  c5  can potentially create. The pawns are nicely supported and our bishops are just waiting to get activated. }
17. Rfd1( 17.Nxd5? { loses to both }17...c4 { as well as - even stronger - }17...Ne4! { . } )
17. d4{ Just a few moves ago, the position looked pretty calm. Now, the center is exploding and Black takes over the initiative. }
18. exd4( 18.Na4 c4! { was Black's idea. }19.Qb4 d3 { should give Black a very pleasant position even though things are obviously very complicated. }19.Bxc4? Nxc4 20.Qxc4 Qg4! { is an annoying little move. White at least has to give back a pawn under bad circumstances to avoid the immediate loss. }21.Qf1? dxe3 22.Bxe3 Qxa4-+ { would lose the knight. } )
18. Bxd4{ This is pretty successful in the game. Still, let's mention that objectively }( 18...cxd4 { is stronger. For example, }19.Na4 Ne4∓ { Black still has the more active pieces but the d-pawn is also much better than a pawn on  c5 . } )
19. Be3{ This natural move is actually a mistake. White wants to create counterplay along the d-file. }( 19.Bf1 { It was better to defend passively for now. Black has several active moves like 19... Qf5  but White should be able to defend everything with best play. } )
19. Qe7{ Increasing the pressure on  e3  while also getting out of the d-file. }
20. Bf1{ This is losing the  e3 -pawn without any compensation but the position was already critical. }( {  A)  }20.Bxd4? cxd4 21.Rxd4 Qg5-+ { with a double attack against  g2  and  c1  is painful. } )( {  B)  }20.Na4 { was the best move to protect  e3  but Black remains much better after }20...Nf5-+ { . } )
20. Bxe3
