8. a4{ White is playing one of the most critical lines against the  Chinese Recipe . }
8. a5( { In the course I recommend   }8...Ne4 { -  see here . Nevertheless, the reaction }8...a5 { is extremely typical for these positions. }{ Black stops  a4 - a5  but also takes control over the  b4 -square.  As we will see, this won't last long. } )
9. cxd5( { Magnus goes for a symmetrical structure. The inclusion of   }8.a4 a5 { creates some holes on the queenside and White is the first one to exploit those. } )
9. cxd5
10. b3{ The bishop will go to  a3 . }
10. Ne4{ You know, this is a typical move but after the following sequence, Black's position will just have even more holes! }( 10...Nc6 { looks natural but after }11.Ba3⩲ { , Black has problems using the  b4 -square while White can occupy  b5  with either bishop or knight. Black is solid but there is not much counterplay. } )
11. Nxe4
11. dxe4
12. Nd2{  e4  is hanging and the knight can come to  c4  where it is extremely stable and is controlling a lot of vital squares - as we will see. }
12. Bb7{ It would be typical to strike back in the center with ... e5  after the exchange on  e4 , but here it simply doesn't work. }( 12...e5? 13.d5! { is a strong response. Not the only one to be honest. }13...Qxd5 { What else? }14.Ba3 Rd8 ( { ( }14...Re8 15.Bc4 Qb7 16.Nxe4! { , followed by }-- 17.Bd5 { or }17.Nd6 { is not better. ) } )15.Nxe4! { is horrible. } )
13. Ba3
13. f5{ Mamedyarov goes for some kind of activity on the kingside but White is just so much faster on the queenside/center. }
14. Rc1
14. Kh8
15. Nc4
15. Nd7
16. d5{ White is ready to break through in the center with  d5 - d6 . }
16. Rc8
17. d6
17. e6{ Black is trying to keep files closed but Carlsen gives no time to coordinate. }
18. b4{ Strong and simple. White just opens the whole queenside with this and the next moves. }
18. axb4
19. Bxb4
19. Bd5
20. a5{ A typical Magnus approach. Other players might have looked for solutions that kept some queenside pawns on the board - to win them later on - but Magnus is not afraid of simplifications.  The piece activity combined with the strong pawn on  d6  is enough for him to win the game. }
20. bxa5
21. Bxa5
21. Qe8
22. Qa4{ White has opened as many files as possible and now he is simply trying to invade with his pieces. }
22. Bc6
23. Qb4
23. Rb8
24. Nb6{ Once again, Magnus is not afraid of simplification. The knight on  d7  was passive but it was also a very reliable 'stopper' of the  d6 -pawn. }
24. Ne5( 24...Nxb6 25.Bxb6 { might have been objectively better but Black has no counterplay and White has three open files on the queenside to invade into Black's camp. Not a position that Mamedyarov is interested in. } )
25. Qc5( { Magnus prepares   }26.Bc3 { . After that, the dark squares will be even more vulnerable. } )
25. Ba8{ This allows a concrete finish but Black was lost anyway. }
26. Bc3
26. Nd7
27. Bxg7+
27. Kxg7
28. Nxd7
28. Qxd7
29. Qe5+{ White's rook will invade on  c7 . A nice lecture about the topic 'simplifications' and how to use them as a weapon! }
