7. Rc1{ White plays a rare sideline against our Grünfeld Slav. }
7. Ne4{ A nice move to grab the bishop pair and open up the  g7 -bishop. }
8. Bd3( { White develops naturally even though we could in hindsight claim that White should take the dynamics out of the center with }8.cxd5 { Black could recapture on  d5  immediately or on  d2  first. But at the very least, Black doesn't get the option of ... dxc4  that we will see later in the game. } )( 8.Nxe4? dxe4 { is just horrible for White. Black can play ... e5  next no matter what. } )
8. Bf5{ Nothing wrong with natural development. }( 8...Nxd2!? { immediately and still playing in the same style as the game is certainly also possible. } )( { Now,   }9...Nxf2 { is a threat. } )
9. Qc2
9. Nxd2{ Creating the imbalance bishop vs. knight. }
10. Nxd2( 10.Qxd2 { might be better in hindsight to keep more control over  e5 . Still, Black has different attractive options. }10...Bg4!? { with the idea to spoil White's structure looks like the best. } )
10. Bxd3{ This gives up the bishop pair but Black could follow it up with a quick ... e5  after which the  g7 -bishop will be the strongest minor piece on the board. }
11. Qxd3
11. dxc4{ Black opens the center as much as possible. }
12. Nxc4( 12.Qxc4 { is preferred by the engine to put the knight on  f3 . Still, Black is slightly for choice after }12...Nd7 13.Nf3 e5⩱ { . } )
12. e5{ The typical break! }
13. Rd1{ White cannot take on  e5  as the  d4 -pawn is pinned. }
13. exd4{ Creating the typical weakness on  d4 . }
14. exd4
14. Na6{ Just one of many good moves. Playing ... Nb4  to occupy the  d5 -square with tempo is a very typical idea. }
15. O-O
15. Nb4
16. Qf3{ White wants to be able to give Black an isolated pawn on  d5  as well if they continue with ... Nd5 . But Black has something even stronger now. }
