12. a3
12. a5{ We reached this position in the theoretical section -  see here . This game does nicely illustrate some of the key ideas in this Benoni position. }
13. Nbd2
13. Nc5{ This is usually considered the ideal square for the knight. It attacks  d3  and also supports the ... e7 - e5 - e4  break that we will also see in this game. }
14. Ne4{ The typical response. White has less space and would love to exchange a pair of minor pieces. }
14. Na6{ If you haven't seen the idea before, it might look like a pretty ridiculous move. In the last moves, Black spent 3 tempi with this knight and now it is on  a6 ? But there is some logic behind it.  We avoid the exchange of knights and the white knight on  e4  is so vulnerable to ... f7 - f5  - a move that fits nicely in the plan of playing with ... e7 - e5 - e4  eventually. Often, the  e4 -knight has no better square than  d2  available so White will have two lost tempi as well. }
15. h4{ A very commital move. White wants to stabilise the  g5 -square I suppose but it is also very weakening. }
15. h6{ A simple move to take the  g5 -square under control as well. }
16. Nh2{ With the space disadvantage, it is often not easy to create counterplay and often White has to work with a lot of hidden tactics to create dynamic counter chances. This move is just too passive. }( 16.b4!? { is a typical move to at least create some open files and diagonals. After }16...axb4 17.axb4 Ncxb4 18.Ba3 Nc6 { White has some compensation for the sacrificed pawn. } )
16. f5{ Now, Black takes over the initiative. }
17. Nd2
17. Nc5{ The knight return to the ideal square on  c5  ,attacking  d3 . }
18. Bf1{ Another very passive move. }{ I am not sure why White didn't protect the pawn with a more natural move such as }( 18.Qc2 { . After }18...e5∓ { , Black is much better as well but it looks better than in the game. } )
18. e5{ The e-pawn is coming! }
19. Qf3{ If White's idea was to build a blockade on the  e4 -square, the next move must have come as a shocker. }
19. e4{ This is the typical breakthrough in these Benoni positions. }
20. dxe4
20. Ne5{ Black's pieces are just way too active. Next, a knight will land on  d3 . }
21. Qe2
21. Ned3{ White is actually just totally lost. }
22. Qxd3{ White found nothing better than sacrificing the queen but just two minor pieces are obviously not nearly enough material in exchange. }( 22.Reb1 Nxb2 23.Rxb2 d3-+ { wins the rook on  b2 . } )
